	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08/05--A Momentum Notice</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/+Worth1.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth1.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08/05--A Momentum Notice</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>Momentum investing looks splendid on paper. But individual investors should be cautious.</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Friday's big market move confirmed the predictions of sources quoted in last week's "Market Week Ahead." Namely, that the market was likely to have firm support at the bottom and trade up. The only question was how high. <p>
Steve Chronowitz mentioned that the laggard performance of the Dow transportation and utility indexes had made him somewhat
cautious. I checked in with him on Friday, after those subindices had caught up with the rest of the market, and the New York Financial Index had also hit a record high.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
"If you consistently chase stocks that did well in the previous six months, you will realize superior returns."<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Chronowitz expects the market to race back to its all-time highs--and soon. The S&P 500 hit a record high of 681 in May, and that's the level to watch this week. If the market breaks that level decisively, it could go above 700, he says. He also notes that Friday brought us within 100 points of an all-time closing high in the Dow. "If we get through the high--and I think we will--it looks like we'll march quickly to 6000 plus possibly as high as 6150 to 6200." <p>
But he cautions that if the market moves too quickly up, it will be overbought by midweek, and a near-term correction could last a week or two before it continues on. <p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>Some technicians predict a Dow of 10,000.</font></b><p><p>
If anything, Chronowitz is cautious and conservative compared to other technicians. Ralph J. Acampora, technical analyst at Prudential Securities, released a report last week outlining the case for a Dow of 7000. And Friday afternoon, some commentators were predicting a Dow of 10,000. But this progress won't be the straight ride up we saw last year. "Over the next couple of months, I expect a very choppy market replete with wide swings in the leading averages," Acampora observed.<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>A new study shows that momentum investing consistently beats the market.</font></b><p><p>
A rising tide lifts all boats, but some get more lift than others. Three financial economists from the University of Illinois recently demonstrated that momentum investing strategies can consistently beat the market. "If you consistently chase stocks that did well in the previous six months, this strategy will lead to superior returns," says Professor Josef Lakonishok. Some momentum investors look at earnings performance, some look at stock price performance. Lakonishok and his colleagues Louis Bhan and Narasimhan Jegadeesh found that both strategies outperform the market.<p>
The study looked at all domestic stocks listed on the New York, American and NASDAQ exchanges from 1977 to 1993. Ranking stocks according to their stock price performance over the previous six month period, the researchers divided them into 10 groups. The stocks with the highest prior six month returns outperformed the stocks with the lowest by 8.8 percent over the next six months and 15.4 percent over the next year. Ranking them on earnings, the researchers found more modest spreads of 7.7 percent over the next six months and 9.7 percent over the next year.<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>The momentum strategy looks splendid on paper. But individual investors should beware.</font></b><p><p>
The paper blows another hole in the so-called "efficient market" hypothesis. A market is defined as efficient when all available information about a company is quickly priced into the stock. "The results suggest a market that responds only slowly to new information," Lakonishok told me. "The market is suspicious, and does not take big improvements very seriously."<p>
Individual investors trying to implement the strategy will find it difficult, though. It's a trading-intensive approach, and portfolio turnover could be 100 percent a year. That means that commissions will likely take a big bite out of returns. Diversification is also important, because sometimes momentum carries stocks, even whole sectors, too far to fast.<p>
Lakonishok offers the following advice: "If you implement momentum strategies, you must be careful how you trade. Use discount brokers, put in limit orders, and remember that if your portfolio is not large enough, there's no way to benefit because you want to be diversified. As splendid as it looks on paper it is difficult to implement unless you have a sizable portfolio of at least a million dollars."<p>
<p><a name="SUB4"><b><font size=+1>Investors use the momentum strategy other ways.</font></b><p><p>
Investors without the resources to construct their own portfolios
can play the momentum game at the margin, by considering the
stock's recent performance with an eye towards its momentum. 
There are also mutual funds that specialize in momentum investing--but as the Wall Street Journal reported last week, recent market volatility has taken its toll on them.<p>
Next week, we'll take a look at another study by Lakonishok, on value investing. This approach is somewhat more suitable to the individual.<p>
[Post your comments on the market on the "Market Week Ahead" message board in the "Let's Talk Stocks" folder.]

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

