<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/07/29--Scared Bears</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/+Worth1.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth1.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/07/29--Scared Bears</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>The recent bad news in the market may not be so bad as some pundits have painted it</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Notwithstanding the much reported forecasts of a crash, it was a quiet Friday afternoon on the floor of the Chicago Board Option Exchange. "Summers used to be like this all the time," reminisced Kevin Berninger, a CBOE floor trader with plenty of time to jaw on the phone, even though the market was open.<p>
When the CBOE is quiet, of course, you can assume that it's quiet almost everywhere. Nowadays, there aren't distinct stock, bond, options, and futures markets. There's just one big market with several visible exchanges. So you can take the big market's temperature by sticking a thermometer in almost anywhere. By Friday, the fever had broken.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
"It's going to continue like this for a couple days then there'll be another selloff," says one CBOE trader.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
After a big drop, a rally back, and another drop, the market's crisis had passed. Volatility had come down, options premiums were lower, and people thought it was safe to put their toes in the water again. "People are coming in, and buying stocks," Berninger noted. "I think they're wrong. It's going to continue like this for a couple days then there'll be another selloff."<p>
Berninger said the market fell not because people were desperate to sell, but because buyers had simply stepped away from high prices. Once prices move up a bit, there are many big pension and mutual funds looking to take profits.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>Traders say buyers are willing to come in at the right price. That's what scares the bears.</font></b><p><p>
The same analysis was offered by a trader on the equity desk of a major New York bank. "We see customers picking their spots," he said, "When the market goes down it's because buyers walk away, but they come back at certain levels. Right now, order flow is better to the buy side."<p>
If buyers are willing to come in at the right price, it means that the recent bad news in the market may not be so bad as some pundits have painted it. That's what scares the bears.<p>
Ben Kopin manages the short-selling Lynx fund in Chicago. He returned his investors a negative 6 percent performance until the beginning of June. From June until the present, he has given them a positive 24 percent, thanks to big short positions in technology and health care. But he's skeptical about the prospects for a really momentous decline. "If we go into a 1987 type crash, I will be very happy," he says. "But I've pulled in my horns a little so if we have a significant rally I won't get beat up too bad." That is, he's taken some profits on his short positions rather than adding to them.<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Last week's S&P low was an important support level.</font></b><p><p>
The outlook for a market with a fairly firm bottom and a pretty distinct top was more precisely defined by Steve Chronowitz. Formerly the director of futures research for Smith Barney, Chronowitz has been trading on his own account for the past five years. He has quite a reputation among professional traders, and regular readers of this column will understand why he seems to deserve it. When I last interviewed Chronowitz for the March 4 "Market Week Ahead," he predicted that the S&P 500 would go no higher than 680. In May, it hit 681, then fell back.<p>
I checked in with Chronowitz on Friday to see how he read this market. "A lot of cross currents," he said. "After the spike low we had, a majority of traders dumped most of their so-called hot stocks.  Now the market is going through a period of consolidation, with the possibility that we can get a substantial rebound." He sees last week's low of 616.50 as an important support area for the S&P. The NASDAQ index should likewise find support around the 30300 to 30500 level.<p>
"Those levels are important to me," he explained, "As long as we can hold above them short term it looks like the market overall can continue to rebound. But my oscillators show the market bouncing between oversold and overbought very quickly, so that means big up and big down days." <p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>For the time being, it's a stock picker's market.</font></b><p><p>
A rebound doesn't necessarily mean a new bull market. Chronowitz is watching the Dow utility and transportation indices closely. "These are currently lagging the rally and I need them to join in order to adopt a much more positive outlook," he notes. But even if they joined, it would not guarantee new highs on other averages. For the time being, Chronowitz sees a stock picker's market.<p>
The July 16 drop in the Dow brought forth a flood of dire forecasts by famous market timers. Season their words with rock salt, dear reader. The market is doing what markets usually do, namely moving up and down as buyers and sellers both try to make money.<p>
That said, this week will be a rocky ride. July 30 is the release date for the employment cost index and wage data. On August 1, the National Association of Purchasing Management (NAPM) releases its report. Then on August 2, the employment results come out. Strong numbers will boost expectations for a Fed rate hike, send interest rates up, and probably move stock prices down at least short term.<p>
Post your questions and comments for columnist Gregory Millman on the "Market Week Ahead" bulletin board in the "Let's Talk Stocks" folder.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

