<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/07/22--Bumpy Ride to Nowhere</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/+Worth1.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth1.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/07/22--Bumpy Ride to Nowhere</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br> By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>Is this a rally or a dive? Either way, smart stock pickers can reap rewards.</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Traders are debating whether last week's big fall was the beginning of a correction, or the beginning of a bear market. Some contrarians still hold out hope for a big summer rally, but they are scarce.<p>
"It's certainly not Pamplona, that's for sure," says John Roque, a technical analyst at Lehman Brothers. He expects the market to test last week's lows again--but not right away. "We think the averages have made good temporary lows. Next week will probably be OK."  <p>
<wam-pullquote>We have either embarked on a bumpy ride to nowhere, or a lurching rally. No one is sure, quite yet, which it is.</wam-pulluote><p>
Meanwhile, he and his colleagues at Lehman expect bank stocks to do well relative to the rest of the market. In a faxed report to institutional clients last week, they noted that the Philadelphia Bank Index held fast and firm during the big selloff. The report named Northern Trust, Boatmen's, Citicorp and Bankamerica as "some of our favorites." <p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>"On any spikes up, I'd be selling."</font></b><p><p>
It takes a lot of confidence to buy in a market like this one. "I really don't know what's going to happen but I'm nervous about this market and on any spikes up, I'd be selling," said one big New York trader as the market closed Friday. "It may go up before the end of the year. But for the short term I would be fleet of foot." He notes that short interest fell last week for the first time in months. When there are a lot of shorts in the market, they can hold prices up. <p>
Shorts are investors who have sold borrowed stock, expecting prices to fall. When prices do fall they buy back the stock, "covering" their shorts, and make a profit. So shorts have a good reason to buy as prices fall--and their demand can keep prices from falling too far, too fast. <p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>At these prices, investors can find bargains.</font></b><p><p>
But at Bankers Trust Company, chief trader Anthony Conroy says that it's a stock pickers' market. "Wednesday saw some stocks at crash levels. A lot of companies have been cut in half. <a name="NYSE:ANN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14959"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ann Taylor Stores</b></a> traded at $23, and is down to $11. In technology and the OTC arena, some stocks are just decimated," he says. He doesn't expect a major recovery anytime soon, and looks to see the Dow trade in a range between 5200-5600. <p>
But at these prices, investors can find bargains. Melissa Brown, quantitative analyst at Prudential Securities, expects positive earnings surprises from six small-cap companies this week: <a name="NASD:AMMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12702"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AMRESCO INC.</b></a>, <a name="NASD:ASFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16617"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Astoria Financial</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:COG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10592"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cabot Oil & Gas</b></a>, <a name="NASD:DYTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13249"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dynatech Corp.</b></a>, <a name="NASD:IVCR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13827"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Invacare Corp.</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:MNTR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14077"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Mentor Corp.</b></a> One measure of their quality is the fact that their prices have held rather firm when others were falling. Bargains, of course, can come in many different forms. <p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>Two numbers make the case for a short-term market rally.</font></b><p><p>
Can a case be made for a major market rally in the short term? Yes, says Michael Oyster of the Investment Research Institute in Cincinnatti. "We're still pretty positive even after today's pullback," he said Friday. "There's a big opportunity for investors to benefit from the recovery." Oyster's favorite numbers are the volatility index at the Chicago Board Options Exchange, and the put-call ratio.<p>
The volatility index, or VIX, is a measure of how turbulent prices are. It closed above 20 on July 16 and 17, then dropped down again. "Historically, that has preceded pretty strong rallies in the short term," Oyster explains. Since 1986, the earliest year for which the VIX is calculated, this pattern of closing above 20 and dropping back has only occurred 50 times. This is what happened on average to the S&P 100 OEX index in the weeks following such a peak and fallback in volatility:
<b>
<pre>
5 days after peak-fall, up (on average) 0.7%
10 days after, up 1.3%
15 days after, up 1.6%
20 days after, up 1.7% 
25 days after, up 1.9%
</pre></b><p>
Oyster also sees a bullish signal in the put/call ratio, which hit 0.86 last week. This is the ratio of individual equity put options to individual equity call options. Since investors buy put options on stocks in order to protect themselves against, or profit from, a drop in the stock price, a high put/call ratio means lots of pessimism in the market. That is a positive sign for contrarian investors. Oyster says the put/call ratio hasn't been close to this level since October 11, 1990, when it hit 0.85. Here's what happened to the S&P 100 OEX index:
<b>
<pre>
 5 days later, up 3.7%
10 days later, up 5.5%
15 days later, up 4.5%
20 days later, up 4.3%
25 days later, up 7.6%
</pre></b><p>
If that historical pattern repeats itself, the Dow would be around 5800 in a month.<p>
Oyster cautions that there are some differences between 1990 and the present. For example, in 1990, the Fed was lowering interest rates to drag the country out of recession. Now, all debate is over the question of whether the Fed will raise interest rates, and by how much. But he does believe that these indicators point to a big rally just ahead.<p>
<p><a name="SUB4"><b><font size=+1>Confusion is what makes a market.</font></b><p><p>
The data is mixed, though. While the put/call ratio on individual equities is high, the put/call ratio of options on the OEX itself is not particularly high. That is what keeps some analysts from joining Oyster in his bullish mood. "My reading tells me that people are unsure about individual equities, but they're not buying puts on the OEX. So I don't  think the put/call numbers say we're going to move one way or another," Lehman's John Roque said.<p>
This kind of confusion and disagreement is what makes a market, of course. We have either embarked on a bumpy ride to nowhere, or a lurching rally. No one is sure, quite yet, which it is. In the meantime, stock pickers can reap rewards--provided they can tell the difference between a bargain stock and a broken one. <p>
[Post your questions and comments for columnist Gregory Millman on the "Market Week Ahead" message board in the "Let's Talk Stocks" folder.]<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
