<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/07-15--The Puzzle</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/+Worth1.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth1.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/07-15--The Puzzle</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>This week could be the critical moment for the market.</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Over the past two weeks, we've seen shocks that ought to have made things very clear. So why are the experts so puzzled?<p>
Back in February, when almost everyone else in the market thought the economy was in recession, one man told me another story. Paul DaRosa, president of Eastbridge Capital in New York, said what looked like a recession was really a mid-cycle slowdown, and the economy  was about to roar back, and interest rates would be going up instead of down. <p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
"People waiting for a slowdown sound like they're waiting for a repeat of the Virgin Birth."<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Events proved him correct. DaRosa trades bonds. Though this has been a so-so year for bonds, it's been a good year for his firm. <p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>What is supporting the market?</font></b><p><p>
I decided to check back with him because of the strange way the bond market has been acting. Bond traders, not the Fed, are primarily responsible for determining interest rates. Interest rates of course affect the stock market, the mortgage market, the currency market, in short, everything and everybody. The data on jobs and wages, combined with the Fed's decision to do nothing at its last meeting, ought to have sent bonds down much farther than they've gone. What is supporting the market?<p>
DaRosa says that bond traders are now split into two camps. One camp says the economy is already slowing down, partly because interest rates have been rising since February. If they're right, the Fed won't need to hike rates in August, and we can look forward to falling interest rates in the second half of the year.<p>
The second camp says that the interest rate rises we've seen so far can't slow the economy down. Interest rates have gone up simply because demand for money has gone up. They're a second-hand consequence of economic growth, and won't of themselves cause a slowdown. Only the Fed can do that.<p>
And what does Darosa think? "I'm a little skeptical about seeing a spontaneous weakening," he says, "People waiting for a slowdown sound like they're waiting for a repeat of the Virgin Birth."<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Greenspan is spending one of his credibility chips.</font></b><p><p>
A lot of bond investors were uncomfortable about Alan Greenspan's decision not to raise rates at the July FOMC meeting. "He has a lot of credibility chips in his pile, but he's clearly spending one now," DaRosa notes. <p>
Greenspan of course testifies before Congress on Thursday of this week, and somewhere in his Delphic pronunciamentos there may be a murky clue to what he thinks. For his part, though, DaRosa expects to see the Fed raise interest rates a modest 25 basis points in August.  (Note: A basis point is one-hundredth of a percent.) <p>
What will that mean for stocks? It will probably be good for the market. "Stocks have displayed a real allergy to inflation," DaRosa says. When inflation is up, the market goes down. The three worst stock market years of recent memory were 1972-'73, 1979-'80, and 1987-'88.  All inflationary years.<p>
Nick Sargen, an economist with JP Morgan's private client group, says that his group is offering clients three pieces of advice about the current market: 1) look for pockets of opportunity, 2) buy protection, and 3) consider the benefits of international diversification.<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>The pickup in the economy is not necessarily good for corporate earnings.</font></b><p><p>
It's not altogether clear that last week's tech stock carnage will spread to the overall market. Sargen notes that the Dow and the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index are still only about 4 percent to 5 percent below their peaks for the year. <p>
But the bad news from Hewlett-Packard and Motorola Inc. showed that the pickup in the economy is not necessarily good for corporate earnings. Intel's earnings release this week, and Microsoft's next week, could either confirm or contradict that picture.<p>
Technicians point out that the market is getting closer to it's 200 day moving average. Crossing that line signals that the price trend has reversed from rising to falling -- and that the market is correcting.  <p>
In sum, this week could be the critical moment for the market.<p>
[Post questions and comments for columnist Gregory Millman on the "Market Week Ahead" message board in the "Let's Talk Stocks" folder.]<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

