<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/07/08--It's Not Over Yet</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/+Worth1.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth1.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/07/08--It's Not Over Yet</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>No one was expecting bad news last Friday when the payroll numbers came in.</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Friday was not a good day for bad news. The New York Stock Exchange had planned for a light, half-day of trading before an early afternoon close on a day of no news. <p>
If there were going to be news, it was reasonable to expect it would have come before the holiday. The real event of the week, after all, had been the Fed meeting on Tuesday and Wednesday. But the Fed had surprised no one by doing nothing. That was no news. The market had already decided long before that the Fed would not need to raise interest rates. Even before the Fed had finished doing nothing on Wednesday, people were taking off for four-day weekends at mountains and beaches. <p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
"The economy is moving too fast for the Fed's comfort," says a trader on the NYSE floor who predicted the Dow's dive.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
So no one was expecting news on Friday. Especially not this news.<p>
When the payroll numbers hit desks early Friday morning, there was no doubt that the market would move down. One trader called me a few minutes after the report was out to predict a Dow down one hundred points at the opening bell. "The economy is moving too fast for the Fed's comfort," he said, "People are even  talking about the Fed raising interest rates in an intermediate move, before the August meeting." His prediction was only slightly off. In the first few minutes of trading, the Dow was down 50, and it finished the short day down 114. 88.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>By tomorrow the impact of Friday's report will become clear.</font></b><p><p>
But that's not the end of the story. Because so many portfolio managers were away for the long weekend, sources on the NYSE floor said that the real shakeout would come on Monday and Tuesday of this week. The real impact of the Friday report won't be clear until midweek. But it's a safe bet that stocks won't be surging up and only a slightly less safe bet that they'll be heading farther south.<p>
Expectations of interest rate hikes tend to be self-fulfilling. Whether the Fed raises short term rates or not, the bond traders will demand higher interest rates to protect themselves against inflation risk on long-term bonds. Those higher market rates will be a drag on the stock market, at the very least. Many investors will prefer a high guaranteed return on a bond to a somewhat riskier return on stocks, and move their money from stocks to bonds. Lower demand for stocks means lower stock prices. Traders will anticipate all of this well before the money moves, so prices will be adjusting today and tomorrow.<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Pacific Scientific is one stock that was pushed too high and fell too low.</font></b><p><p>
Here's the silver lining to a cloudy market. As the cold wind of rational expectations blows, it strips the rosy fog off the prospects of hot speculative stocks. In some cases it strips off more fog than there really is.<p>
Consider the case of <a name="NYSE:PSX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11146"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pacific Scientific</b></a> (PSX), a stock that ran up to $27 before tumbling recently to around $12. Excessive optimism about a new product, a dimmer for fluorescent lights, sent it up. But the company ran into some problems bringing the new product to market. Now the pessimism is almost as excessive as the optimism was. "If this goes to $11, it's time to mortgage your house and buy," one knowledgeable source, not a broker, not an employee, told me last week. "Between $12 and $13 you've got value, but it's the value of the company, not the froth."<p>
I don't make stock recommendations, but PSX seems to be a good example of a stock pushed too high that then fell too low. When the price fell to $12 1/8 on Wednesday, Richard V. Plat, the company's CFO, bought some more to add to his personal holdings of about a quarter-million shares. "The book value of the stock is $8.90, and if we make 5 percent just on our base business of $300 million, it's $15 million. We have 12.5 million shares out, that's $1.20 per share. I'm not making a prediction but we should be able to do better than 5 percent," he told me. <p>
Broken stocks like PSX can offer bargains--but don't rush to buy. Check the numbers carefully, and watch this market shake out first. <p>
[Post your questions and comments for columnist Gregory Millman on the "Market Week Ahead" message board in the "Let's Talk Stocks" folder.]<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

