<DOCHDR>
http://www.worth.com:80/articles/D0701M.html 204.141.48.165 19970209074440 text/html 7394
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 09 Feb 1997 07:45:31 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.0
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=2061014855474331725; path=/
</DOCHDR>
<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/07/01--The Fed Looks East</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.worth.com/departments/newsletter.html+Worth.gif+>
<img src="/ads/Worth.gif" border=3 width=374 height=45 alt="Worth - Financial Intelligence"></a>

		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/07/01--The Fed Looks East</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>Will the Fed follow Japan's lead in a decision not to raise interest rates? Who cares?</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Mark your calendars. This is an important week--a historic week, even. For this is the week that the Fed's monetary policy mavens will deliberate and pronounce on the interest rate question. The prospect of this week has been the single most important force in the stock market for months. Fears of an interest rate hike cowed bulls, baited bears, and became the default explanation for every market move.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
The very week of traders' nightmares is upon us. The week the Fed deliberates and pronounces on the interest rate question.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Were prices up? Fears of the Fed had eased. Down? The market feared a rate increase in July--at this week's meeting.<p>
Now that the very week of traders' nightmares is upon us, do they wring their hands anxiously, and bemoan this fateful moment? Nay, nay, dear reader. For the anxious market has turned its fickle eyes to other terrors. As to the Fed meeting--who cares? Not Anthony Conroy, managing director and head trader at Bankers Trust. "The market is expecting a non-event," he says, "If they do anything, it's going to be light."<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>After Japan's decision not to raise interest rates, traders are expecting the Fed to keep any increases low.</font></b><p><p>
The market has found encouragement in the East. "If anyplace at all had an incentive to raise rates," says Conroy, "it was Japan, and they did nothing." Japan's decision not to tighten has an immediate impact on the Fed's decision making. In a global market, capital seeks the most attractive returns. If the Japanese had raised rates, the Fed would have had some leeway to move. But the Japanese did not raise rates. So the Fed has less elbow room. The market has built in expectations of the Fed staying in bounds, with a rate increase of 25 basis points or less. "Fifty or more would be bad for stocks," says Conroy. But 25 is a non-event.<p>
Of course, the Fed only controls short-term rates, and it's long-term rates that matter most for stocks. As long-term rates have risen, Conroy has noticed some outflow of funds from stocks into bonds, and from the speculative technology stocks into big, well established names. <p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Globally, U.S. stocks are attractive.</font></b><p><p>
However, in the global capital market, U.S. stocks still look very attractive compared to Europe and Japan. Ian Scott, European Strategist with  Lehman Brothers in London, says, "The U.S. market no longer looks as cheap as at the start of this year, and bonds have gone up, but we still maintain an overweight position in the U.S."<p>
Lehman's model portfolio is underweight on Europe and neutral onJapan. Lehman's pricing model takes the trailing dividend yield and divides it by the bond yield in each country. The resulting number gives a sense of the relationship between stock and bond prices. "European markets are trading on relatively low yields which in the past have been associated with low returns going forward," he explains.<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>In Japan. share prices have been stimulated by the highest first-quarter GDP in two decades.</font></b><p><p>
Meanwhile, in Japan, the market has been pleasantly stimulated by the highest first-quarter GDP growth numbers seen in more than 20 years. "Theoretically, higher GDP growth means good news and bad news for the stock market at the same time," says Nikko's Hideyuki Omakawa in Tokyo. "Increased corporate profits would be welcomed while a likely interest rate hike is definitely a negative. But share prices seem to have taken the news as positive this time."<p>
However, no one doubts that an interest rate hike will be in the cards in the not too distant future. As long as there was some doubt about Japan's recovery from recession and deflation, the government could pressure the Bank of Japan to keep interest rates low. <p>
Reason: Japan's high deficits mean that the government can't do much to stimulate the economy through fiscal means. The high GDP figures show that there's no need now for any stimulus. But both the Bank of Japan and the government have been busily reassuring the country that no monetary policy change is necessary at this time.<p>
Bottom line: Savvy investors in the U.S. markets will watch Japan for some clues to possible Fed action.<p>
[What do you think will happen to U.S. interest rates? Post your comments and opinions on the "Market Week Ahead" message board in the "Let's Talk Stocks" folder.]<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

