	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06/24--Time To Buy?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06/24--Time To Buy?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						What a week it was! The market action is confusing even the most experienced traders. "Everybody was afraid of the Fed raising interest rates in July, now they're saying there won't be any rate increase in July, but maybe August, or maybe not at all," says one old hand, a trader for a major New York bank. The seasonal summer slowdown in volume could be a problem, he says. "We haven't been busy, and low volume is like slow death, stocks can just unwind."<p>
Nonetheless he expects a rally that will push the market up a couple of hundred points over the next two or three weeks. "This market wants to move up," he says.<p>
Bob Rack, research director for the Investment Research Institute, saw strongly bullish signals in the put-call ratio--the ratio of put options to call options. (Puts are the right to sell a stock, calls the right to buy one.) "We just registered a put-call ratio of 0.94. That means there are almost as many puts as calls," Rack says.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
The market action is confusing even the most experienced traders.  But some see good news in the bad news.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
"Historically when that has happened, the market has gone up on average 2 percent over the next 20 days, almost double the usual market return," he explains. Usually, there are far fewer puts than calls. When the volume of puts goes up, Rack says it's a contrarian indicator. "It means we have excessive fear in the market as people think this is the end of a run and rush out to buy puts. When fear reaches that level it's a good buying opportunity," he notes. (For more from the Investment Research Institute, check out their <a href="http://www.options-iri.com">Web page</a>.)<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>There's good news in the bad news.</font></b><p><p>
John L. Manley Jr., equity strategist at <a name="AMEX:SBT"></a><b>Smith Barney</b>, also sees good news in the bad news. "The problems we're all aware of, such as high values and deterioration of earnings, will cause a correction but not for a while. Why not? Because we're all aware of them, they're not things we need to deal with now. Values are high but could stay high for 10 years. We are seeing small stocks come down sharply. That says we haven't reached the sustained peak and excesses that usually mark the top of a bull market, so we'll probably do well between now and the election. In this century, there's never been a bad market in the U.S. in the six months going into an election." <p>
Manley recommends conservative sector bets, health stocks and tobacco for example. He also likes <a name="NYSE:CAG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10388"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Conagra</b></a>, which has recently restructured and is trying to get back to a 14 percent growth rate. His stance is based on the expectation of a slowing economy over the next six to twelve months. <p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Recession? Not until the next millennium.</font></b><p><p>
A recent report from Lehman Brothers says the economic expansion could continue until after the millennium. "I expect this expansion has better than a 50-50 shot of lasting three to five more years," says David Kelly, a senior economist at the firm. "If we get five more years then it's the middle of 2001 before we hit a recession."<p>
Kelly's analysis shows that the economy of the 1990's is more stable than those of the '70's or '80's. There are three reasons why. Thanks to deregulation of banks and interest rates, the housing market is no longer governed by a boom-bust cycle. Meanwhile, information technology has helped corporations learn to manage their inventories better. Finally, different parts of the economy that used to move together now move independently. <p>
So instead of getting a simultaneous crash in housing, inventories and autos, we get separate little busts in each sector. The economy works more like a diversified investment portfolio. And speaking of investment portfolios, if Kelly is right it means very good news for cyclical stocks. "If the business cycle is less significant now than in the past, then cyclical stocks are less risky than in the past. But often, cyclical stock prices incorporate an expectation that earnings will go down when recession hits. If a recession is less likely maybe those stocks are undervalued," Kelly explains.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
