<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06/17--Short Stuff</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06/17--Short Stuff</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						There's no time like the present for a quick refresher course on shorting.<p>
"People are nervous about the whole market, and watching rates like a hawk," says one veteran New York trader. So there's no time like the present for a quick refresher course on shorting, with some nice prospective shorts to consider.<p>
Shorting means selling something you don't have but promise to deliver in the future. Shorts expect prices to fall. They sell at today's prices and buy at tomorrow's, hopefully lower, prices. In the stock market, shorting usually means borrowing shares from one investor to sell them to another, but with the obligation to deliver equivalent shares to the lender at some future time.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
Shorting is getting more attractive to individual investors as a way of profitably investing in the downside of markets.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Shorting is getting more attractive to individual investors, both as a way of protecting their portfolio and as a way of profitably investing in the downside of markets. Short investors in semiconductor stocks have been reaping rich rewards over the past week. Goldman Sachs helped send Micron farther south by cutting the earnings estimate. Meanwhile, the book to bills numbers for the sector came out last week and showed orders continuing below last quarter's level. This means that these companies will show slowing earnings.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>How to identify good shorts.</font></b><p><p>
Among the tech stock shorts was Christopher May of TLB Partners in New York City. May uses shorts as a leg of a strategy that helped him deliver over 100 percent returns to his investors in 1995. His approach is unusual if not unique. He doesn't particularly care about the overall market outlook, or about the fundamental business in which companies are involved. He uses chaos and fractal analysis to identify non-random price movements in securities. If the stock prices are moving up in a mathematically persistent pattern, he buys, and if down, he sells or shorts. <p>
On Friday, May shorted <a name="NASD:KMAG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13912"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>KOMAG (KMAG)</b></a> and <a name="NASD:CUBE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17270"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>C-Cube Microsystems (CUBE)</b></a>. "They hit a statistical trigger, prices were going down and the Hurst was going up, so the time series was becoming persistent, the system was becoming less random, therefore more predictable and the direction of prediction was down," he explains.<p>
Of course, that's not the only way to identify good investments on the short side. At the <a name="FUND:HRSMX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/HRSMX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Heartland Small Cap Contrarian Fund</b></a>, trader Kevin Clark outlined more conventional reasons for shorting these retailers: <a name="NASD:FEET"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17144"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Just For Feet (FEET)</b></a> and the <a name="NASD:DLTR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dollar Tree Stores (DLTR)</b></a>. "Just For Feet trades at 64.9 times 1997 estimated earnings. For a retailer we think it's ridiculous. Granted, the company is growing fast. But  one hiccup and it will come apart," he explains. And Dollar Tree? "Insiders have been selling a lot. And at 43 times trailing twelve month earnings, we think it's rich." <p>
Clark says the fund tries to pair shorts with longs. The longs corresponding to these shorts are <a name="NASD:UNIV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10055"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chicos FAS Inc. (CHCS)</wamco> and <wam-co NASD:UNIV>Universal International (UNIV)</b></a>.<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>How to short the market.</font></b><p><p>
You don't have to short individual stocks to make money or hedge. If you expect the overall market to go down, you can short SPDRS at the American Stock Exchange. These are shares in a trust that owns the S&P 500 stocks and moves with that index. SPDRS are one convenient way for individual investors to cover their bets when the market actually begins to slide. SEC rules forbid shorting most stocks  as they are falling, but SPDRS are exempt from this rule. "You can short SPDRS in a free falling market," says Jay Baker, managing director of derivative securities at the AMEX.<p>
Meanwhile, several score of options products traded at the CBOE and AMEX allow investors to short not only individual stocks and the overall market but also sectors like technology and health care. More on those in future columns.<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>On the international front, copper goes south.</font></b><p><p>
Fraud and skullduggery shook the international financial markets last week. A bond theft scandal in the Russian financial markets left Western investors with $100 million in losses. That news paled beside the sudden exposure of $1.8 billion of losses hidden by a Sumitomo copper trader in London. Regulators, bankers and investors are huddling to avert a global meltdown in the copper market.<p>
Apparently Sumitomo's trader, Yasuo Hamanaka, had single-handedly propped up the international copper price through his long positions. Now that the news of his unsustainable losses is out, the copper price has only one way to go--down. The news can only delight investors in the Quantum and Tiger hedge funds. Those funds, run by George Soros and Julian Robertson respectively, had shorted copper in a mano a mano duel with Hamanaka. 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
