<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06/10--Look Out Below!</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06/10--Look Out Below!</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The market is paying more attention to bad news than good.<p>
Consider the roller coaster the market rode Friday. Good news about jobs implied bad news to come about interest rates and sent the Dow down 87 points by lunchtime. As everyone knows though, the Dow regained all that lost ground to close up almost 30 points for the day, or a little over half a percentage point. What comes next?<p>
Consider Friday's volatile trading a warning. That's the word from Edgar Peters, a portfolio manager at Panagora Asset Management in Boston and author of several books on using the mathematics of chaos and fractals to analyze the financial markets. Peters is expecting the market to become more sensitive to bad news, more volatile, and likelier to fall than rise in the next few weeks. "This usually happens when long-term investors become uncertain and stop playing the game," he says. "When the market is in this state it means it is susceptible to shocks from bad news." Peters says that volume is down considerably. So with fewer players in the market, and those players edgy, the market is paying more attention to bad news than good.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
Fridays yo-yo Dow is one indication that no one knows what will be good news and what will be bad news in this market.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Consider what sent the market down Friday morning. News that job growth had been better than anyone expected means two things: 1) earnings will probably be better than anyone expected, and 2) interest rates will probably go up, and certainly won't go down. Now, there are lots of fundamental economic analyses of relationships between earnings, interest rates, and stock prices and they're not unimportant. But in a day-to-day trading situation, the market is purely a psychological game. Traders are trying to figure out how other traders are going to react.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>There will be near-term trouble for investors who are long in this market.</font></b><p><p>
Friday's yo-yo Dow is one indication that no one really knows what will be good news and what will be bad news in this market.<p>
This uncertainty means near-term trouble for people who are long in this market. "We'll probably have some sort of blowoff," Peters says. "I don't anticipate it will be a bear market, certainly not a crash, but at this point even if we had a 10 percent correction it's almost 600 points on the Dow."<p>
Harry Roth, an options strategist at Cowan and Company in New York, also expects the market to fall. Why? Put options, which represent the right to sell stocks and are a way to go short, have been running about 30 to 35 percent of the volume of calls. That's low. It means there are too few bears in the market. "When people aren't interested in buying puts, it means the market is too high and there's too much complacency," he says. Like a good contrarian, Roth thinks the market will go down over the next two weeks.<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>If the market goes down, here are four stocks to short.</font></b><p><p>
If the market does go down, shorts will make money. I asked David Tice, manager of The <a name="FUND:BEARX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BEARX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Prudent Bear fund</b></a>, for his favorite shorts. In terms of sectors, he thinks money can be made by shorting high technology and consumer credit stocks. <p>
According to Tice, specific stocks to short are: <a name="NYSE:MU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Micron Technologies</b></a>, on grounds that the memory market is collapsing; <a name="NASD:KLIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13915"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kulicke and Soffa</b></a>, a maker of semiconductor manufacturing equipment, on grounds that the semiconductor industry already has a capacity glut; <a name="NYSE:FUS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15687"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First USA</b></a>, the consumer credit card company, on grounds explained in great detail in my article in the current issue of Worth; and <a name="NASD:IOMG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13832"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Iomega</b></a>, on grounds that it is ridiculously overvalued. For more details on Tice's short picks and The Prudent Bear fund, check out his <a href="http://www.tice.com">Web page</a>.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


<font size=+1><b>Table of Contents</b><p>
</font>						<img src="/imgs/wee-page.gif" align=left>
						<a href="#SUB1">There will be near-term trouble for investors who are long in this market.</a><p>
						<img src="/imgs/wee-page.gif" align=left>
						<a href="#SUB2">If the market goes down, here are four stocks to short.</a><p>
					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:MU">Micron Technology, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:KLIC">Kulicke and Soffa Industries, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:FUS">First USA, Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:IOMG">Iomega Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:BEARX">Prudent Bear fund</a><br>

