<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06/03--Bull Trap</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06/03--Bull Trap</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The S&P hit an all time high just a week ago. Then it dropped back slightly. So where is it going from here?<p>
Jack Schwager heads up the futures research area at Prudential Securities. He says that last week's trading action looks like a classic bull trap. In a bull trap, the market sets a new high then moves to another even higher high. Then, instead of continuing up, it falls back down. <p>
As Schwager reads the charts, last Monday's high can't be sustained. After hitting it, the market spent several days without going up or down decisively, trading sideways, but edging a little lower each day. That's bad news for bulls. "For now, I would be bearish," Schwager says, "I would take an even money bet the market will gap lower Monday."<p>
The drop could be merely a short term retreat that lasts a week or two. On the other hand, it might be more significant--perhaps the beginning of the major market correction that professionals have been predicting, expecting, and fearing for months. For now, Schwager says he's comfortable being long--but not too comfortable.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
Are we headed for a short-term retreat, or the start of the major market correction the pros have been predicting?<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
At Lehman Brothers, technical analyst Stephen Shobin thinks
the bull market still has a long way to run. Among other factors, he likes the fact that when the S&P hit its new high, bellwether stock <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Electric (GE)</b></a> also reached an all time high. "If GE had failed to reach an all time high, that would be a suggestion that something was awry," he explains. A bellwether is a stock that analysts watch to double-check their conclusions about the market. In order for conclusions to be solid, the market and the bellwether must both send the same signals. For now, they are.<p>
Watch out for interest rates, though. If the long bond yield gets much above 7 percent, it will mean trouble for stocks. There's a fundamental explanation for this: When investors can get a high risk-free return in treasuries, they take money out of stock and put it in bonds. But the fundamental economics are secondary. In fact, higher interest rates will be a problem for the market simply because every analyst, trader, and investor expects them to be. If the long bond tests the 7.25 percent level, people will sell stocks because they fear that others are about to sell stocks. And stocks will go down.<p>
What does all of this mean to you, as you blink at your screen?<p>
For young investors in the market for the long haul, it makes
sense to simply ride out the storm. The market could take years to recover from a sharp drop, but if you can wait years, that's no problem. For older investors, close to retirement, hedge your bets on the U.S. stock market. <a name="NYSE:JPM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10812"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>JP Morgan</b></a> is advising private clients to either hedge or take 5 to 10 percent of their funds out of the stock market. Then what? Either keep it in cash money market instruments or invest it in international stocks, particularly European and emerging market equities. The bond market is simply too risky now. 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:GE">General Electric Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:JPM">J.P. Morgan & Co. Incorporated</a><br>

