<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05/28--Lets Retire the Dow</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05/28--Lets Retire the Dow</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						One hundred years ago today, a Wall Street news sheet began to publish the average stock price of several railroad and industrial stocks. The computation was perfectly suited to an age that had barely seen the invention of the hand-cranked adding machine, let alone the computer. Anyone with a pencil and paper could figure the average by adding up the prices of the stocks at the end of each trading day and dividing.<p>
Charles Dow, who invented this market indicator, believed that investors who paid careful attention to price movements could "beat the market" by timing their investment decisions correctly. Dow's successors devised a whole theory of investing based on fluctuations of the Dow Jones Average, popularly known as "Dow Theory."<p>
A century later, many things have changed. Dow's news sheet has evolved into The Wall Street Journal. The stock markets are much bigger and more complex. Nobel prizes have been awarded to economists for proving that price changes in stocks are random and unpredictable, so that beating the market as Dow suggested is all but impossible. Dow theory is no more than a historical curiosity.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
The Dow Jones average stubbornly endures,  even though it no longer provides much information about the stock market.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Yet the Dow Jones average stubbornly endures. Even though it is no longer as easy to calculate. Even though it is no longer a simple average. Even though it  no longer provides much information about the stock market.<p>
"The day-to-day fluctuation in the Dow is meaningless. It's random. Yet every night on the news they tell you the Dow, like this is something you can judge things by," says Mark Cunningham, a money manager with <a name="NYSE:OCC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41946"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oppenheimer</b></a> in New York.<p>
Consider this. The Dow Jones Industrial Average now contains only 30 stocks out of the more than 7,000 traded on various exchanges in the United States. What's more, it gives the most weight to the highest priced stocks, not the most highly capitalized. So the daily moves in the Dow not only don't tell us much about the overall market, but also, what they do tell us may have nothing to do with the overall market.<p>
For example, last week, news from Iraq sent oil prices up, and oil company stock prices with them. The 30 stocks in the Dow include three oil stocks. The jump in oil stock prices alone was enough to send the Dow up to a new record high. On Thursday, as the Financial Times reported, good news for <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a> sent that stock up far enough to trim the Dow's 50 point loss to a mere 16 points.<p>
The Dow is eccentric, to say the least. In fact, the Dow often moves in opposite directions from broader indexes.  <p>
No wonder that professional investors are reluctant to put their money on the Dow. Robert Waid, a senior associate with the Santa Monica based financial consulting firm Wilshire Associates says "Many people who only get their financial information from the news media think the Dow is important, but I don't know any people who've hired managers for performance fees to beat the Dow. For every other index, there's somebody being paid on a performance basis to beat it--but not the Dow." <p>
Despite the Dow's shortcomings, it has established such a firm position in the popular imagination that it's unlikely to go away soon. And as long as we keep a few facts in mind, there's no reason why it should.   <p>
Fact one: With the Dow above 5700, a 50 point drop or rise isn't what it used to be. So think in percentage terms, not in point terms.<p>
Fact two: The Dow is an entertaining anachronism, irrelevant for most investment purposes. Investing to "Beat the Dow" is silly.<p>
Fact three: Broad market indexes like the S&P, the Wilshire 5000, and the Russell 2000 are the numbers to watch for real information about the stock market.<p>
Anyway, happy birthday, Dow.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:OCC">Oppenheimer Capital L.P.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:MO">Philip Morris Companies Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

