<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05/20--Low Pain, High Gain?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05/20--Low Pain, High Gain?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4>Low Pain, High Gain?</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Last week, the American Stock Exchange began to trade call warrants on a group of technology stocks. Buyers of the warrants get a piece of the action if this basket of stocks goes up in value during the next two years. If history is any guide, there will surely be more such warrants trading soon at the AMEX and other exchanges. So, how do they work?<p>
Warrants are similar to options. An option is the right to buy or sell something at a fixed price during some set period of time. Call options give the holder the right to buy, put options the right to sell. These rights are bought and sold. For ordinary purposes, the option gives an investor the chance to profit whether stocks go up or down. <p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
The new AMEX call warrants allow investors to make a risk-controlled play on the tech sectors future.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Suppose you buy a call option that gives you the right to buy a
stock for a dollar, and the stock then goes up to two dollars, you should be able to sell that right for something close to two dollars. If on the other hand you have a put option that gives you the right to sell a stock for two dollars, and the market price of the stock falls to one dollar, you should be able to sell the put option for something close to two dollars. <p>
So you have all of the gains of actually buying or shorting stocks, but the option price is much lower than the stock price. And if the stock moves the wrong way, the investor's loss is limited to the price of the option. So the option allows investors to capture profits whether a stock moves up or down while limiting losses.<p>
The new warrants at the AMEX are call warrants on the Lehman Select Technology Stock Index. This Index includes 23 stocks from the following technology sectors: software, semiconductor, computer, electronic equipment, telecom equipment, and office equipment. At introduction, the value of the index was set at 100. On May 15, 1998, the value of the index will be calculated. It's not a complicated calculation. Each stock accounts for approximately 4.3 percent of the index. Adding and subtracting the price change on each stock in the two years the warrants have been in force will give a number that will be greater or less than 100. Each warrant holder will receive a payment equal to 1/4 the increase in value of the index. (The stocks in the index are listed at the end of this column.)<p>
By the way, don't rush to buy these or any other warrants on issue. Unless you have a PhD in math from MIT and a Sun workstation or two to run pricing programs. The mathematics of pricing options and warrants is what brought hundreds of nuclear physicists and astronomers to Wall Street over the past decade. It's not simple. As a rule, ordinary Joe investors should wait until these instruments have been trading for a few weeks. By then, professionals will have arbitraged away the most extreme pricing inefficiencies and anomalies and you'll get what you're after--a risk-controlled play on the tech sector's future.<p>
On other subjects, interest rates have been the talk of the markets in the U.S. and in Japan over the past week. In the U.S., the debate continues over whether the economy is overheating or merely doing well. However the debate at the moment seems to favor the unalarmed. Low to moderately low inflation forecasts dominate, and that's good for interest rates.<p>
In Japan, a fall in yen interest rates sent the stock market up. The fall in rates puzzled some, because Japanese central bank officials have been making public statements about the desirability of higher rates. But Hideyuki Omakawa of Nikko Securities in Tokyo explains, "Money traders aren't stupid. After following Mr. Matsushita's wobbling steps in the last several weeks, they finally started to think that BOJ is only playing a game with the market, and has little intention of raising interest rates soon."<p>
Appendix: Lehman Select Technology Stock Index<br>
<br>
<a name="NASD:ADCT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12487"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>ADC Telecommunications, Inc. (ADCT)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:ADPT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12515"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Adaptec, Inc. (ADPT)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online, Inc. (AMER)</b><br>
<a name="NASD:CSCO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13494"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Cisco Systems, Inc. (CSCO)</b></a><br>
<a name="NYSE:CA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10383"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Computer Associates International, Inc. (CA)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:DELL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13193"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Dell Computer Corporation (DELL)</b></a><br>
<a name="NYSE:DEC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10462"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Digital Equipment Corporation (DEC)</b></a><br>
<a name="NYSE:FDC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14441"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>First Data Corporation (FDC)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:GATE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16706"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gateway 2000, Inc. (GATE)</b></a><br>
<a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett Packard Company (HWP)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:IFMX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13768"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Informix Corporation (IFMX)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel Corporation (INTC)</b></a><br>
<a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>International Business Machines Corp. (IBM)</b></a><br>
<a name="NYSE:LSI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13932"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LSI Logic Corporation (LSI)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft Corporation (MSFT)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:ORCL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14337"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Oracle Corporation (ORCL)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:QCOM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11436"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>QUALCOMM Incorporated (QCOM)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:SUNW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14833"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sun Microsystems, Inc. (SUNW)</b></a><br>
<a name="NASD:TNCR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16153"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tencor Instruments (TNCR)</b></a><br>
<a name="NYSE:TXN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11462"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Texas Instruments Incorporated (TXN)</b></a><br>
<a name="NYSE:VSH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11587"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Vishay Intertechnology, Inc. (VSH)</b></a><br>
