<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05/13--Wrong Way for Rates</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05/13--Wrong Way for Rates</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The interest rate window is closed. In fact, it never really opened. Regular readers remember the hopeful window scenario outlined by our economic sources two weeks ago. To recap briefly, the weak May jobs report would convince the bond market that the economy wasn't growing as fast as traders feared. Consequently bond prices would rise, interest rates fall.<p>
Lower interest rates would answer the prayers of mortgage borrowers and would probably help the stock market too. <p>
Well, the jobs report came in weaker than anyone expected, showing a net gain of only two thousand jobs last month. The market all but ignored the favorable news, focusing instead on a very slight rise in hourly raises (six-tenths of one percent) and on the May 2 GDP report that showed the economy growing at a sizzling 2.8 percent in the first quarter. Instead of falling, interest rates rose, and the stock market began to slide.<p>
Interest rates matter to all investors of course. But they matter to mortgage borrowers especially. What should they do now? Economists who follow the mortgage market are split on the interest rate outlook, but they offer remarkably similar advice to borrowers. <p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
Experts who follows the mortgage market are split on the interest rate outlook but offer remarkably similar advice.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Eileen Neely, senior economist at Fannie Mae, expects interest rates to fall slightly later in the year, winding up at 7.6 to 7.7 percent by year end. David Lereah, chief economist at the Mortgage Bankers Association, is more pessimistic. "My outlook for near term is upward pressure on rates. I expect the Fed to come in and tighten, raising short term rates in the July meeting," he says. Lereah also sees rates falling slightly after that, ending the year at about 8 percent.<p>
So what should home buyers do? The answer depends on the length of time they plan to own the house, and on their tolerance for risk. Buyers who plan to stay in their homes for awhile have nothing to lose if they lock in at current rates. The lows we saw in February aren't likely to return, but current rates are still low by historical standards. Moreover, refinancing is cheap and easy, just in case interest rates surprise everyone by falling steeply.<p>
Lereah recommends that borrowers with a shorter horizon look at a "three-one" mortgage. These offer rates about a quarter of a percentage point below a 30 year mortgage. They lock in a rate for the first three years, then change to a floating rate mortgage. Both Neely and Lereah say that the annually adjusted floating rate mortgages are risky propositions at present.<p>
What does the interest rate outlook mean for the stock market? Low rates and expectations of Fed ease in the first quarter helped stock prices up in December, January, and February. When interest rate expectations shifted, stocks took a dive. Now the market is pricing in expectations of a Fed tightening in July. Near term, expect a tug of war between the hopes implicit in a high growth economy, and fear of the Fed. 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
					<p>
					
