<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/05/05--Stop Paying for Performance</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05/05--Stop Paying for Performance</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Are you getting what you pay for from your mutual fund? Probably not, according to a recent study.<p>
One big reason investors buy mutual funds is to get the benefit of professional management. But the average professional money manager under performs the market, according to a new study by Martin Gruber, chairman of the finance department at New York University's Stern School of Business.<p>
Gruber found that professional management on average does more harm than good. He started out trying to determine why mutual funds, especially actively managed funds, have grown so rapidly when their performance on average lags behind index funds. (Index funds don't try to beat the market, they just try to track the market by buying a representative sample of securities in an index--like the S&P, the Morgan Stanley EAFE, or the Wilshire 5000--and holding them.)<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
According to a new mutual fund study,  the worst performers charged the highest management fees.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Along the way, Gruber turned up some surprising facts. Most important is his discovery that past performance can indeed predict future results. So investors who put money in funds that performed well in the past can beat the market. <p>
But handle this insight with caution. "It doesn't mean that investors should buy the fund that did well last in the past," Gruber emphasizes. "What I found is that a group of firms that do well one year are more likely to do well than poorly in the future. But buying the top fund doesn't guarantee you'll get the best performance next year."<p>
A small group of sophisticated investors apparently understands this already. They invest in funds actively--moving their money often in search of the best performance. And they make money at the game. In fact, Gruber found that sophisticated investors can even beat index funds.<p>
But not by much--on average, the strategy of actively investing in top performing funds only yields a quarter to a half percent a year more than mere indexing. Moreover, the active strategy is risky, and the passive is virtually risk free. Is a third of a percentage point worth the risk? "There's no answer," says Gruber. "It depends on the individual."<p>
Interestingly, Gruber also found that investors who pay extra for professional management not only don't get what they pay for, but sometimes get the opposite. Investors in load funds do worse than investors in no-load funds. And of the 270 funds he studied, the worst performers charged the highest management fees.<p>
Index fund investors also have to watch fees carefully. They can pay as little as 0.17 percent or as much as 1.25 percent. Since index funds merely track the market, investors who pay high fees get no more for their money than investors who pay low fees.<p>
Gruber's study, entitled "Another Puzzle: The Growth in Actively Managed Mutual Funds," will be published in the "Journal of Finance" in July.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
					<p>
					
<font size=+1><b>Related Message Board</b><p></font><img src="/imgs/smpin.gif" align=left>
<a href="/forums/talkfunds/friday/worthboard.html">	Mutual Fund Friday	</a>
 <p>

</td>
	</tr>
