<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04/29--A Break On Mortgage Rates</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04/29--A Break On Mortgage Rates</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						A window of opportunity for mortgage borrowers may begin to open later this week. Some economists expect the April jobs report, due out on Friday, to show weaker job growth and a slower economy than the February and March reports indicated. "That will rally the bond market and the bond market rally in turn will lower mortgage rates," says Evelina Tainer, chief economist at Indosuez Carr Futures in Chicago.<p>
Eileen Neely, an economist with the mortgage finance agency Fannie Mae in Washington, also expects mortgages rates to go lower. She  says that rates on 30 year fixed rate mortgages are unlikely to reach February's bottom of 6.94 percent, but she expects to see long term fixed mortgages available at 7.50 percent by mid summer. That's considerably better than the 8.05 percent we saw in the second week of April. In fact, rates have already begun to descend. They had eased down to 7.95 percent by the third week of April.<p>
Since questions about mortgages rates come up frequently on the "Market Week Ahead" message board, it's worth looking a little more closely at the factors that have been pushing rates up lately.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
Home buyers and refinancers have little to lose if they commit to a mortgage rate.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Through the final months of 1995 and into January 1996, monthly job reports and other economic data showed the economy growing slowly. Bond traders expected the Fed to continue lowering interest rates until the economy picked up steam. That was good news for bond holders because when interest rates slip lower, higher interest rate bonds get scarcer and more valuable. <p>
The bond market is closely related to the mortgage market. In fact, through a process called securitisation, many mortgages end up being bought and sold just like bonds. Bonds and mortgages went at low interest rates to reflect the weak economic outlook.<p>
In February and March, the bond market got a couple of rude shocks. The jobs reports showed the economy growing much faster than anyone had thought. The bond traders no longer had any reason to expect lower interest rates. In fact, they began to fear inflation and the Fed's sovereign remedy for it: higher interest rates. These fears were heightened by price reports that showed dramatic jumps in commodity prices.<p>
Hopes and fears showed up quickly in bond prices. Interest rates surged. But economists like Tainer and Neely believe the market overreacted to the February and March reports. They say that the government shutdown in December, the blizzard of the century in January, and a strike at <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GM</b></a> all played havoc with the employment data. "In the first quarter we had such a slew of special factors that even looking at three months' job data  doesn't give you a good assessment of the economy," Tainer says.<p>
Evidence is now emerging to show that the economy is not in fact growing all that fast. A report on durable goods orders that came out last Thursday showed an increase of 1.4 percent. That would ordinarily indicate economic growth. But Neely says, "All of that was in transportation and defense. If somebody orders three jets from <a name="NYSE:BA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10221"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boeing</b></a>, it can skew the numbers. But if you look at non-defense capital goods, the report was unchanged in March after being down both in January and February."<p>
The bottom line is that, as usual in the market, no one is really sure what is going on. But home buyers and mortgage refinancers have little to lose if they wait for Friday's job report before they commit to a mortgage rate. 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:GM">General Motors Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:BA">The Boeing Company</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
					<p>
					
