<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04/22--Will Washington Move the Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04/22--Will Washington Move the Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Not since bull-shaped Jupiter abducted Europa to Crete has a horny bovine covered so much ground so fast.<p>
From Amsterdam to Zurich, almost every market in the world was up last week. German interest rate cuts performed CPR on a blue-lipped economy and the Frankfurt market twitched encouragingly. Rate cuts in Amsterdam lifted the Dutch bourse, and the mere expectation of lower interest rates in Spain sent Madrid's market to a high for the year. Meanwhile, in the Far East, Seoul's stock market hit new highs despite North Korean troop movements and war threats. <p>
But the most important news comes from Tokyo. Domestic Japanese insurance companies and pension funds have finally started to put their money into the Japanese stock market. "In the short term, Japanese stocks continue to be a good buy," says Hideyuki Omakawa of Nikko in Tokyo. "The only concern, which I point out over and over, is the possibility that the Japanese economy may lose its momentum in the latter half of this fiscal year."<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
The good news is that even if the solons fail to put together a budget agreement, their failure wont hurt the market.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Two factors could take the wind out of Japan's economic sails. The government's economic stimulus package, which has driven the economic recovery, will largely be spent by mid-year. Moreover, private consumption could be dampened by a plan already approved by legislators to raise the consumption tax rate to 5 percent from the current 3 percent in April 1997.<p>
Meanwhile, in the United States, the jobs report that so shocked the market earlier this month has been fully priced in. No major reports are due for a while, and if Washington has any short-term effect on the market, it's likely to be for the better. <p>
That's not entirely good news though.<p>
This week, Republican legislators will be meeting to decide what to do about the budget. The biggest question on their minds: if a deal is struck, who will get the credit? If it looks as if the President will get credit for meeting Republicans more than halfway and resolving the budget debate in a statesmanlike fashion, don't expect the Republicans to agree to a deal. Especially if all they come away with, politically speaking, is the blame for cuts in popular programs.<p>
The good news is that even if the solons fail to put together a budget agreement, their failure won't hurt the market. The market is on the whole level headed and realistic about these things. It has already priced their failure into stocks and bonds.<p>
Suppose, on the other hand, they're able to put aside petty partisan squabbles and work together for the good of the country? "The market will act extremely favorably because that will be a surprise," says Kim Wallace, a senior political analyst with Lehman Brothers in Washington.<p>
Perhaps not coincidentally, a puzzling event in the currency markets last Thursday was noted by Miek Ballow, an analyst with Indosuez Carr Futures in Chicago. On the day that Germany's Bundesbank announced lower interest rates, the dollar fell slightly. Ordinarily, the dollar should rise if interest rates go down elsewhere. "I didn't see a good explanation for it, so I'd be nervous about being long on the dollar," he says.<p>
Here's one possible explanation: Politicians of both parties convinced the electorate and investors that the budget was a critical imperative. Then they failed to do anything about it.<p>
Investor attention has been focused on other things, notably the economic outlook. Now that the budget is coming back into focus, investors are already worrying about inflation and debating the need for Fed tightening. <p>
Well, either Fed tightening or inflation will be the only possible outcome if Congress and the President aren't able or willing to grapple with the budget. If fiscal authorities do nothing, then discipline over inflation must be exercised by monetary authorities -- the Fed -- or not at all.<p>
I'd be a little careful about the dollar, too.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
