<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04/15--Is Inflation Back?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04/15--Is Inflation Back?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Is inflation back? That's the focus of fear for the markets now. To recap briefly, oil futures prices surged to five-year highs last week. Also, the Commodities Research Bureau index, published by Knight Ridder, was at eight year highs. Bond and stock prices fell as traders worried that the consumer price data to be released Friday would show surprising jumps in prices.<p>
The surprise Friday was that while prices were up, they weren't shockingly high. Meanwhile, Fed chairman Greenspan suggested fears were of an overheating economy were overblown. Bond prices and stock prices lifted slightly.<p>
The gods must be crazy.<p>
As recently as two weeks ago, investors could make a case that February's job statistics were an anomaly, goosed up by one-of-a-kind quirks like the furloughed bureaucrats slouching back to their cubicles after the December government shutdown and all the temporary jobs created by snow removal opportunities.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
Two weeks ago, investors could make a case that Februarys job statistics were an anomaly.  No one is saying that now.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
But no one is making that argument anymore, at least not in public. Last week the frightful question was: when will the Fed raise interest rates to stem this inflationary boom?<p>
When I spoke with an equity strategist at one big European bank last week, he described his outlook with a word that no one has used since the mid-'70s -- stagflation. Roughly speaking, stagflation occurs when lots of people are out of work and everything gets more expensive. He pointed out that oil prices have gone from $13 per barrel to almost $25. Wheat and corn are also high. "I think commodities as an asset class are going to come back," he concluded.<p>
No one would be happier about this prospect than Grant Schaumburg, president of Mount Lucas Management, a commodity trading firm based in Princeton, N.J. "I would love to see it," he said. "But I can't imagine we are going to see anything like the '70s. We don't have the fundamental monetary factors, the major inflation, nor do we have the fundamental shortages we had then."<p>
The grain price increases are easily explained by the fact that government stockpiles are down, and there's a drought in the Midwest. Oil prices are tougher to account for, Schaumburg said. <p>
But Nick Sargen of <a name="NYSE:JPM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10812"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>JP Morgans</b></a> private client group pointed out that while oil prices are high, the forward market is backward. That is, the price of oil for future delivery is lower than the price of oil for delivery today. This means that oil traders are expecting prices to fall, not rise. <p>
"I'm willing to say that if the U.S. is picking up and if that sleeping giant, Japan, is picking up then there's potential for further increases in commodity prices," Sargen said. "But how realistic is the threat of inflation? My conclusion is it's overdone."<p>
The question of inflation nonetheless will set the tone of the coming week's trading.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

