<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04/08--New Ways to Play the Market</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04/08--New Ways to Play the Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						There's a new way to play the international markets game--and it couldn't be timelier.<p>
On March 11, Morgan Stanley and the American Stock Exchange, launched "WEBS." They were inspired by "SPDRs" (pronounced, "spiders"), which were introduced in January of 1993.<p>
Arachnophobes, fear not, SPDRs and WEBS are simply securities that allow an individual investor to buy and sell whole stock markets, instead of simply buying and selling individual stocks.<p>
They're like shares in an index fund. SPDRs--Standard & Poor's Depositary Shares--are domestic, based on the S&P stock index. WEBS--World Equity Benchmark Shares--are based on the Morgan Stanley Capital Index, and are much more interesting than SPDRs.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
Eyeing emerging Asia, but dont trust China in 1997?  Now you can buy Singapore and Malaysia, and short Hong Kong.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Why? WEBS enable individual investors to do something that can't be done any other way: buy and sell countries. Seventeen countries, to be precise. And buy and sell them at market prices.<p>
When big institutions spread their money around the world, they often do so by buying a basket of stock that stands as proxy for a country's stock market. Instead of picking a few German stocks, in the hopes of beating the market, they buy the whole market on an indexed basis.<p>
That's not easy for individual investors to do. Most international mutual funds own the securities of several countries. Specialized open-end funds are rare. Moreover, when you buy or sell mutual fund shares, your transaction is priced as of the end of the trading day. So if the market happens to be declining when you decide to sell, you get the low end, not the high.<p>
Of course, closed-end funds allow you to buy into particular countries, some of them well off the beaten track, but they're usually not indexed. That means that when you buy, you get the manager's picks, for better or worse.<p>
WEBS expand your opportunity set by giving you a quick, easy way to buy or sell the following countries: Australia, Austria, Belgium, Canada, France, Germany, Hong Kong, Italy, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico, Netherlands, Singapore, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, United Kingdom.<p>
Suppose you like the prospects for emerging Asia, but don't trust China in 1997? You can buy Singapore and Malaysia, and short the Hong Kong WEBS.<p>
Though I'm no market timer, it's nice to have these new securities around now. Emerging markets stock prices ran up toward the end of last year, but since early February they've pulled back hard. The explanation: as this year opened, most investors bet their money on continued Fed easing. Low U.S. interest rates give investors a reason to look for high returns elsewhere. <p>
But the Fed didn't continue to ease. Investors who'd bought the emerging markets expecting a quick turn have sold off. That means there are good opportunities for longer term investors.<p>
Not every country is a good buy. Maryam Mansoury, emerging
market strategist at Lehman Brothers, says that there are new signs of healthy growth in Latin America. "In most countries it's not consumer led growth but infrastructure and investment led growth," she says. <p>
In Mexico, she expects falling inflation and economic recovery to brighten the fortunes of the financial and cyclical sectors. Argentina and Brazil are fundamentally attractive, but some investors might balk at political risks to recent economic reforms. "We're selective on approach, and we still think Asia will outperform Latin America in the near term," Mansoury notes.<p>
Now, thanks to WEBS, you can be selective too.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
					<p>
					
<font size=+1><b>Related Message Board</b><p></font><img src="/imgs/smpin.gif" align=left>
<a href="/forums/talkstocks/week/worthboard.html">	Market Week Ahead	</a>
 <p>

</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
