<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/04/01--Sucker-Cash High?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04/01--Sucker-Cash High?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Remember all the talk about the liquidity-driven bull market? You know, the theory that stock prices were being pushed ever higher by baby boomers pouring money into mutual funds?<p>
You couldn't have missed it. Why, the Wall Street Journal even did a front page story a few weeks back where they went coast to coast interviewing all kinds of ignoramuses, schlemiels, chowderheads, dunces, dopes, suckers, and dupes who had the bald effrontery to just keep pouring cash into equity mutual funds no matter what. Even though the market was way, way too high -- so high, only amateurs could buy at those levels. People who had never been in the market before! Can you imagine?<p>
Flash to subtext: easy come, easy go.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
If its not sucker cash in a speculative frenzy,  what is pushing this market to unprecedented highs?<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
The professional investor's nightmare: households yanking savings out of the market at the first sign of a correction, turning the correction into a crash.<p>
No wonder the savviest mutual fund managers were sitting on cash, refusing to put it in the market. And missing the rise. And proving once again that Josh Billings was right. It's better to know nothing than to know what ain't so.<p>
The liquidity-driven bull market is one of those things we know that just ain't so.<p>
In fact, according to recently released Fed data, households sold more stock than they bought last year. In fact, on balance, they took $80 billion out of the market. Yet the market was up 38 percent. <p>
Think about that. How can household money pouring into mutual funds drive a speculative frenzy when in fact households are taking more out of the market than they are putting in?<p>
People own stocks two ways. They buy them through a broker, and own them directly, or they buy them through mutual funds, and own them indirectly.<p>
A lot has been written about the inflows into mutual funds being at historic highs, making a lot of people nervous. But now we know that households haven't been pouring new money into the market at unprecedented rates. They've been yanking their savings out of the market for a year by selling off stocks they owned directly. Yet the market keeps going up anyway.<p>
Well, if it's not sucker cash in a spec frenzy, what is pushing this market to unprecedented highs?<p>
Lehman analyst Jeffrey Applegate suggests there's only one possible explanation -- the fundamentals, earnings and interest rates. "Embedded in this worry about households causing a crash is the view that households are jittery, naive, and fairly stupid," he says. But households know enough to buy on the dips.<p>
Where does that leave us for the near term? Well, we're well into the time when companies preannounce earnings disappointments. Except for a few garish red smears (<a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple</b></a> for example), there's not much being preannounced.<p>
"I'm not worried about a bad quarter," says Prudential's Melissa Brown. She expects that the earnings growth in this market will shift from cyclicals to stable growers, like consumer staples and health care.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NASD:AAPL">Apple Computer, Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
					<p>
					
<font size=+1><b>Related Message Board</b><p></font><img src="/imgs/smpin.gif" align=left>
<a href="/forums/talkstocks/week/worthboard.html">	Market Week Ahead	</a>
 <p>

</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
