<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03/25--Tobacco Stocks: Smoke Screen</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03/25--Tobacco Stocks: Smoke Screen</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Do you expect tobacco companies to be out of business in the United States in two years? If not, buy their stock.<p>
A recent report by Sanford Bernstein analyst Gary Black shows just how badly publicity has burned the coffin nail makers. The current price of <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a> stock makes sense only if you expect the domestic tobacco business to last two years. If you expect it to last longer, it's a bargain.<p>
A realistic price for Philip Morris (NYSE: MO), according to Black's calculations, is around $104.35. The stock now trades at around $86.75.  <a name="NYSE:RN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13122"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>RJR Nabisco Holdings (NYSE: RN)</b></a> is trading at $30, but should be about $38.73. Black's advice -- "Hold your nose and buy on weakness."<p>
The current market prices wildly overstate the likelihood of damage from the pending lawsuits. Black expects the suits to be dead ends. Moreover, scientists who say that tobacco companies manipulate nicotine levels are merely stating the obvious. A cancer stick is a manufactured product. One pack of Marlboros tastes pretty much like the next. But there's a big difference between Marlboros and Merits. The difference is the recipe. Yes, a recipe, where every ingredient is measured and controlled.<p>
<wam-pullquote> The current prices of  <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a> stock makes sense only if you expect the domestic tobacco business to last two years.</wam-pullquote><p>
To make a Marlboro, you need 16 milligrams of tar and 1.1 milligrams of nicotine. A Merit has 1 milligram of tar and 0.1 milligrams of nicotine. Says Black, "They have to be able to vary the level of nicotine by choosing various blends of tobacco. But nobody in the industry takes existing blends and shoots nicotine in to keep people addicted." <p>
JUNK BONDS: Other smoke in the news -- Illinois incinerators burned high yield investors. The incinerators were originally intended to burn trash, generate electricity, and (by selling the electricity) pay the $484.2 million in bonds that financed their construction. Problem -- these projects weren't economically viable without a state subsidy. On March 15, the governor signed a bill withdrawing the subsidy. Now the market fears a default on the debt -- which was, in all fairness, unrated and high risk from the get go. <p>
Lesson -- it's unwise to invest in any project that can't stand on its own economic feet.<p>
MARKET OUTLOOK: We warned you to hang on for a bumpy ride this year. And sure enough, it's white-knuckle time. If your heart is in your throat, take comfort in these words: "It's perfectly normal to have markets move like this. Nothing weird is happening," says Bluford Putnam, chief market strategist for <a name="NYSE:BT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bankers Trust Company</b></a>. <p>
INDICATORS: A cryptic message posted on the Market Week Ahead bulletin board last week said that utility stocks were the key to predicting interest rate moves.<p>
Well, not quite. Utility stocks used to be pretty good indicators. But deregulation and competitive pressure have ruined them for that purpose. Investors looking for the key to interest rates might consider, instead, the New York Financial Index. "A breakdown in the bond market probably will be ephemeral if it's not accompanied by a similar breakdown in the New York Financial Index, and a move to a new high unconfirmed by the New York Financial Index will lack tenure," says Steve Shobin, a technical analyst at Lehman. 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
