<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03/11--Dont Believe the Bad News</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03/11--Dont Believe the Bad News</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						I'm writing this column at 5:30 a.m. EST on Monday morning.<p>
Of course, the question on everyone's mind this morning--is this the big one?<p>
Already I've heard half a dozen broadcasters repeat that Friday's 171 point drop in the Dow was the market's third biggest fall ever.<p>
Don't believe it. In fact, the Dow hardly slipped at all on Friday.<p>
Perspective is everything. The Dow's 171.24 fall brought it down just a shade over 3 percent. Since the turn of the century, the Dow has fallen by 3 percent more than 302 times.<p>
Far from being the third worst loss in market history, Friday's tumble doesn't even rank among the top 100.<p>
Friday's drop was no surprise to regular readers of Market Week Ahead. Two weeks ago I predicted that market would trade in a very volatile manner and close about 2 percent lower. Friday's move puts us right where we said we'd be--not exactly 2 percent, but close enough.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
The Dows Friday tumble is far from being the third worst loss in market history.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
Now what?<p>
The U.S. stock market will fall farther this week, then climb back. As Nick Sargen of JP Morgan's private client group says, "This is not the end of the bull market, but a temporary correction, maximum 5 to 10 percent."<p>
It would take one of two things to turn the equity bull into a bear--a threat of Fed tightening, or clear evidence of looming recession. And neither is likely.<p>
Inflation is under control, so there's no need for a Fed tightening. And Friday's panic was over an employment report that said more people were working. So it's clear we're not in recession.<p>
But that's just stocks. What about bonds?<p>
The bond bull is dead.<p>
Almost everyone in the bond market had taken for granted that the economy was moving into recession and March would bring another Fed easing. (For newbies, that means that the Fed would lower interest rates. When interest rates go lower, the price of bonds goes
higher.)<p>
Because this view was so widely held, bonds were already trading close to the prices at which they'd be trading after the Fed's expected easing in March.<p>
We offered readers a contrarian view: Paul DaRosa, president of Eastbridge Capital. DaRosa said in this column that the economy was not in recession, but in a mid-cycle slowdown, and would likely roar back.<p>
I called him Friday in the middle of the panic to check in. He wasn't ready to take full credit for being right--yet. "All the facts tell you now is that you're not in a recession," DaRosa says. "They don't say anything about a boom."<p>
He expects that bond prices will fall even more. Big pension funds, insurance companies, banks, and other institutions own a lot of bonds. "People who run these funds are going to meet with economists, give it the big think, and probably sell more on
Monday," he says.<p>
A wild card in the deck is China. China's face-off with Taiwan--a face-off that has included firing missiles, and brought in U.S. warships--could push Asian investors toward a safe haven. A fresh flow of dollars from Asia to North America could buoy U.S. markets and ease the recent pain.<p>
Money that leaves Asia has to go somewhere. Some will go to gold. Some will go to U.S. stocks and bonds.<p>
Added to the money American investors are already pouring into mutual funds at history-making levels, flight capital from Taiwan and Hong Kong will be like a shot of adrenaline to a hyperactive kid.<p>
In fact, this move could already be starting. The Tokyo and Hong Kong markets both sold off today. Hong Kong was down 7.3 percent.<p>
Early news reports blamed the selloff on Friday's fall in New York and Japan's budget impasse.<p>
But a late Reuters report said that China's saber rattling had unnerved Hong Kong investors. Investors there are speculating that China might seize one of Taiwan's outlying islands if the wrong man wins Taiwan's presidential elections.<p>
Watch the China-Taiwan conflict. It will matter to the markets here.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
