<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03/04--Techs Orderly Tumble</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03/04--Techs Orderly Tumble</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Friday, 15 minutes after the close, I was on the phone with Jesse Stamer. "My head's just spinning after today," said Stamer, a primary dealer for options on several technology companies at the Chicago Board Options Exchange (CBOE).<p>
By now you know that tech stocks flew south on Friday. What a cold spring:  <a name="NYSE:CPQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10381"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Compaq</b></a> and  <a name="NYSE:LSI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13932"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LSI</b></a> and  <a name="NASD:INTU"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16001"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intuit</b></a> announced lower earnings, a research firm lowered its rating on  <a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel</b></a>, and, boom, selloff--the TXX, an index of 30 technology stocks at the CBOE went down 6 percent.<p>
You know that they fell. But the key is how they fell. "It was like going down stairs, very orderly, no panic," Stamer says. "I usually like to see people panic. That means a top or a bottom." <p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
Tech stocks are descending in an orderly manner,  meaning the worst isnt over yet.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
That orderly progress means the worst isn't over yet. Stamer expects the TXX index to drop as much as 10 percent farther this week. A lot of funds and institutional investors are still heavily invested in technology stocks. On Friday, these institutional investors were buying lots of "put" options. (A "put" option is the right to sell stock for a certain price within a certain period of time. As stock prices fall, "put" option prices tend to rise because the option's owner has locked in a selling price. They're like insurance policies.)<p>
Two weeks ago, Paul Kandel, senior sector manager for technology and telecommunications at the Dreyfus Corporation made a prediction in this column. He said that he expected consumer technology to falter this year. But he was bullish on business-to-business technology stocks.<p>
Despite Friday's action, he hasn't changed his view.<p>
But Intuit took a hard hit. In addition to its direct consumer sales of personal finance software, Intuit sells software through banks. Isn't that business to business?<p>
No, says Kandel. The ultimate user of Intuit's software is the computer-banking bank customer. So Intuit's software sales to banks are consumer sales after all. "Nothing we've heard has changed our thesis," Kandel concludes.<p>
Tech stocks aside, most traders I talked with Friday think that the long bull market in stocks will continue. Anthony Conroy heads global investment management and trading for <a name="NYSE:BT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bankers Trust Company</b></a>. He summed up the sentiment: "Could we see the Dow at 6000 by the end of the year? Absolutely. I just don't see where else to put your money right now." <p>
But 6000 isn't what it used to be. It's less than a 10 percent rise from the roughly 5500 level where the Dow now stands. This is not the stuff that dreams are made of.<p>
Last year it was hard not to make money on stocks. Everything was going in one direction--up. This year is different. Fits and starts.<p>
"You have to be very adept, willing to swing on a dime when markets move so quickly back and forth," says Steve Chronowitz, a technician who trades futures on his own account from New York.<p>
Chronowitz sees a support level for the S&P index at around 630. If it falls to that level, it will move up again. He expects the market to run back towards its recent high of 667. If it breaks through that level, it could move as far as 680 this year.<p>
That's less than 10 percent.<p>
Great Expectations? Not.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:CPQ">Compaq Computer Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:LSI">LSI Logic Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:INTU">Intuit Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:INTC">Intel Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:BT">Bankers Trust New York Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
					<p>
					
<font size=+1><b>Related Message Board</b><p></font><img src="/imgs/smpin.gif" align=left>
<a href="/forums/talkstocks/week/worthboard.html">	Market Week Ahead	</a>
 <p>

</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
