<DOCNO>WT14-B06-23</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA088-000636-B029-376</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.worth.com:80/articles/D0226M.html 204.141.48.165 19970209074928 text/html 5852
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Date: Sun, 09 Feb 1997 07:50:19 GMT
Server: Apache/1.1.0
Content-type: text/html
Set-Cookie: Apache=2061010855474619592; path=/
</DOCHDR>
<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02/26--Hang on for a Wild Ride</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02/26--Hang on for a Wild Ride</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						What's next for this market? Over the next 12 days, expect the Dow to go down about 2 percent, then to start moving back up very bumpily, but not very far. It probably won't crash before the year ends, but volatility is here to stay. Get used to seeing the Dow up or down 50 to 100 points in a day.<p>
I feel pretty confident in that prediction. It has the weight of history behind it. <p>
Last week's market action was so chaotic that instead of calling my usual round of contacts on Friday, I phoned just one man. One man with an incredible machine.<p>
His name is Michael Carr, and he's an analyst with Logical Information Machines in Chicago. The company makes a database and software package called Market Information Machine (MIM).<p>
But that doesn't do it justice. The MIM holds decades, and decades of historical price information on virtually every market. MIM can answer almost any statistical question about the markets within seconds. It costs about $3,000 a month to use this package, so most users trade for big banks and hedge funds. <p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
Last weeks market action was so chaotic that I phoned just one man.  One man with an incredible machine.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
I apologize in advance for the clutter of numbers that follows. Unfortunately, the only language MIM talks is numbers. And what the MIM has to say is too important to ignore. <p>
For example, have you noticed the oddly uncoordinated movement of the stock and bond markets lately? The bond market has fallen about 5 percent in the past month, while the stock market is up about 8.5 percent. I asked Carr if that had ever happened before, and what it means.<p>
He fed the query into the MIM and a few seconds later, out popped the answer. The markets have only behaved that way once before in history. The date was August 14, 1980. We decided to see where the market was a random 44 days later. It was up 6.75 percent--but it didn't go straight to get there. "It was an extremely volatile time," Carr says, "It didn't finish either tremendously up or tremendously down, but it went up and down a lot, in a very choppy sideways pattern." That pattern continued for about a year, and then the market fell sharply.<p>
Carr fed a few more queries into the MIM. They all pointed to volatility. For example, between February 13 and February 16, the Dow Industrials were down about 100 points, but the Dow Transportation index was up. The MIM told us that has happened 19 times since 1933. On average, three volatile months later, the market was up 7.29 percent.<p>
But don't take my word for it. Check this out. On Friday, February 23, some unusual events lined up together. The three day move in the Dow Industrials had been greater than 2.25 percent. The three day move in the Dow Transportation Index was over 3.5 percent. Treasury futures had moved less than .75 percent in three days. That has happened only 17 times since 1980. Sixteen of those times, the market moved lower over the next week and a half. On average, it lost a little over 2 percent.<p>
Watch the market this week and next to see if history will repeat itself.<p>
Now, just like the New York Times, I have a correction to make. My apologies to Paul Kandel, senior sector manager with the Dreyfus Corporation. In last week's column, I said he was with another fund management company. The column has been corrected in the archives.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
