<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02/20--The Intranet: Tech Boom 96?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02/20--The Intranet: Tech Boom 96?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Happy New Year. On February 19, the Year of the Rat began. It will be the Year of the Box for technology investors, though. After a couple of years of not spending much on technology, businesses are upgrading at last.<p>
What does it take to succeed in technology stocks this year? I asked Greg Smith, chief investment strategist at Prudential Securities. He said, "You have to be in parts of the technology sector that sell to businesses, not consumers." Smith likes <a name="NASD:FORE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42045"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fore Systems</b></a>, a leader in automatic teller machine equipment and software, <a name="NYSE:SGI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11735"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Silicon Graphics</b></a> for its "pretty strong business-to-business sales," and <a name="NYSE:CA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10383"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Computer Associates International</b></a>. <p>
Paul Kandel, senior sector manager, technology and communications, with The Dreyfus Corporation in New York, sees the same trend. He calls it the "intranet" boom. There's no doubt about the need for businesses to improve internal communications and data transfer--that's what the "intra" in "intranet" means.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
The year of the Box begins.  Heres what to expect in tech stocks.<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
The intranet will be good news for the stocks of traditional, heavy iron companies like IBM, DEC, Hewlett Packard, and Sun Microsystems, Kandel says. Also poised to benefit are server and router companies. Kandel likes Auspex Systems, which makes high speed data transfer servers. Cisco and Bay Networks are also poised to benefit. Though their stocks already look pricey by some standards, Kandel isn't deterred. "They're certainly not overvalued. There's still a lot left in both stocks. They appear rich on PE basis but the fundamentals remain very strong," he says.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>Should I cash my CD's and invest in stocks?</font></b><p><p>
This question appeared on the Market Week Ahead message board last week. On Friday, I put it to Derek Sasveld, a financial consultant with Ibbotson Associates in Chicago. "Of course, it depends on what the money is for," he said, "But if it's for some fifteen or twenty year retirement horizon, get it invested in the market." <p>
Sasveld reasons that CD rates are slow to go up, quick to go down, and probably won't even pay enough to protect you against inflation. Long term investors should be in stocks and shouldn't worry about the market falling. "I understand the nervousness of investors when we've had great returns over the past 18 months. But for long term investors, there is no bad time to invest," he says.<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Japan watch: Loose lips sink ships</font></b><p><p>
Two items of good news last week. A report in an economic journal said that Japanese companies had increased capital investment in 1995. Moreover, department store sales were up for the first time in 47 months.<p>
So why didn't the market jump for joy? Some blame Finance Minister Kubo. He told a Diet session that pensioners were suffering from low interest rates and said something should be done. The market heard this as a warning that the Ministry of Finance intended to raise interest rates. Result--a sell off of stocks and bonds.<p>
The Japanese markets are also wary of some big geopolitical developments. The food and energy crisis in North Korea is so severe that Kim Jong Il's own wife has reportedly fled the country. A total collapse of order in North Korea is possible. <p>
This would mean waves of refugees pouring into South Korea, and possibly even Japan. As if that weren't bad enough, Korea and Japan have been trading hard words over a barren island both claim. Stir into this mix China's threats of military force against Taiwan. This week's lunar New Year's vacation may be the last spot of quiet for a while.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


