<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02/12--World Case of the Jitters</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02/12--World Case of the Jitters</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						First, the good news. If you've been kicking yourself for not refinancing your mortgage in 1993, when you could get 30 year fixed rate loans at 6.5 percent and no points, put your feet back on the ground. Paul Ullman, a vice president with Alliance Capital in New York expects another burst of mortgage refinancing to kick in over the next three to four months.<p>
Ullman manages mortgage securities portfolios. He says the fixed, 30 year mortgage rate "is almost down to 1993 levels. Right now it's 7 percent without any points." Moreover, advances in online technology even since 1993 have made the paperwork side of refinancing faster, easier and cheaper. So, brace yourself for a spate of dinnertime phone calls from telemarketers pushing cheap money. <p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
Does the present economy mean were on our way to recession, or is it just catching its breath?<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
But the good news for home owners isn't good news for investors in mortgage securities.<p>
When interest rates fall, old, higher interest treasury and corporate bonds gain in value. But when homeowners retire their old mortgages and take out new ones at lower rates, investors in mortgage securities get their principal back. They have to reinvest at lower rates. The result, says Ullman: mortgage funds will eat dust if the bond market races for glory.<p>
But that's a big if.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>This year's bond market looks a lot like 1986's--and 1976's, for that matter.</font></b><p><p>
"It's not a good time to buy bonds. That would be my advice," says Paul DaRosa, president of Eastbridge Capital in New York, an extraordinarily honest man. "I would probably have said the same thing last summer and you would have lost your shirt listening to my advice," he volunteered when we spoke Friday after the close.<p>
DaRosa has a sense of history, and what he sees going on now, in 1996, reminds him of what went on in 1986, and for that matter in 1976. In fact, in the middle of every business cycle since World War II, there's been a little slowdown. It lasted one to three quarters, and then the economy roared back along with the inflation rate.<p>
Does the present slow economy mean we're on our way to recession, or is the economy just catching its breath? The answer to that question is what divides the bond market into buyers and sellers. "I read the situation as a midcourse slowdown, but I'm probably in the minority," DaRosa says.<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Stocks are "expensive enough," but there are some cheapies. Buyer beware.</font></b><p><p>
What about that stock market? Well, as everyone knows by now, a seat on the New York Stock Exchange sold for a record price of one and a quarter million dollars last week. The previous record price was paid about a month before the 1987 crash. Hmmm. No wonder the professionals are nervous.<p>
"I don't think stocks are too expensive now, but I think they're expensive enough," says Melissa Brown of Prudential Securities in New York. A heavy duty number cruncher, or "quant" in the market argot, Brown says there are pockets of cheapness in a generally expensive market. <p>
Beware of them. They're cheap for a reason.<p>
For example, stock prices of companies in basic industries--paper, chemicals, aluminum, steel, and so-called consumer cyclicals like cars --are low in relation to their earnings. What does this mean? The market doesn't expect those earnings to hold up. In order for the stock prices to surge up, there will have to be dramatic improvements in earnings. "I think that's going to be tough
to find," she says.<p>
She's not alone. "We're looking for ways to hedge against a dramatic correction in the market. A 500 point correction shouldn't be out of the question," says Arnie Staalof of Bloom-Staalof, a Philadelphia-based broker dealer. Specifically, Staalof is considering put options either on individual stocks or groups of stocks.<p>
A put option is a low-risk way to benefit from a fall in stock prices. Investors who already own stocks often use put options as a sort of insurance policy. If the market collapses, they lose money on their stocks, but they gain on their put options. It's a little like getting a check from the insurance company when your house burns down. Better it doesn't burn down, but if it does, much better to have the check.<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>The Japanese are getting emotional over the "jusen" crisis.</font></b><p><p>
Meanwhile, in Japan. The debate over the "jusen" crisis is gathering steam. "Jusen" is the Japanese version of America's S&L crisis. Hideyuki Omakawa of Nikko Securities in Tokyo says that all of the major TV networks there have run long special reports on the problem within the past week.<p>
"More people are now interested in the issue, but they are emotionally involved," he sighs. Japanese voters don't want their tax money to bail out S&L crooks, but the government claims that
a bailout is critical to the stability of the financial system.<p>
"In the stock market, the only buyers are non-Japanese investors, like US pension funds," Omakawa says, "Japanese institutions are selling."<p>
He thinks the buyers are a little optimistic. If the bailout bill fails to clear the Diet, he expects a big fall in stock prices.<p>
On the other hand, the rule of thumb in the Japanese market is that the foreigners make the big money. So stay tuned.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


<font size=+1><b>Table of Contents</b><p>
</font>						<img src="/imgs/wee-page.gif" align=left>
						<a href="#SUB1">This year's bond market looks a lot like 1986's--and 1976's, for that matter.</a><p>
						<img src="/imgs/wee-page.gif" align=left>
						<a href="#SUB2">Stocks are "expensive enough," but there are some cheapies. Buyer beware.</a><p>
						<img src="/imgs/wee-page.gif" align=left>
						<a href="#SUB3">The Japanese are getting emotional over the "jusen" crisis.</a><p>
					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
					<p>
					
<font size=+1><b>Related Message Board</b><p></font><img src="/imgs/smpin.gif" align=left>
<a href="/forums/talkstocks/week/worthboard.html">	Market Week Ahead	</a>
 <p>

</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
