<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02/05--Market Rut or Slowdown</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02/05--Market Rut or Slowdown</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Welcome to the first Market Week Ahead column. Look for me every Monday with insider market intelligence.<p>
Nervous about this market? So are investors from New York to Tokyo.<p>
The U.S. stock market is nervous, and confused, after Friday's menacing employment report, which showed that two hundred thousand jobs or so disappeared in January, the worst drop in ten years.<p>
<wam-pullquote>Is Fridays employment report a spectral finger pointing towards an economic slowdown?</wam-pullqoute><p>
Did a lot of people stay home from work because they were snowed in? Or was Friday's employment report a spectral finger pointing towards an economic slowdown? President Clinton's best and brightest say that the economy is strong. If it hadn't been for the snow, more people would have been at work.<p>
That's what bond investors are afraid of. Economic growth and inflation lead to higher interest rates. On Friday, it looked as if bondholders were trying to get out while the getting was good. Bond prices fell because sellers were more eager than buyers.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>A metal shows its mettle--but is it an accurate reflection of inflation's direction?</font></b><p><p>
Meanwhile, gold prices are acting as if the economy is booming toward inflation. Inflation makes cash worth less, so investors fled to gold, sending up its price both Thursday and Friday.<p>
Economic growth? Inflation? Logically, stock prices should have gone up too--but they didn't. In fact, they fell on Friday despite the fact that the Fed cut interest rates earlier in the week. The fall had more to do with the job report than the Fed's interest-rate cuts, suggesting the market thinks the economy is cooling off and that the Fed may have more cutting to do.<p>
So what if the bond and gold markets are wrong about inflation? What if the employment numbers mean that employment is really down? Then the economy is slowing, and corporate earnings will be down. That could take some steam out of stocks. The market's fall on Friday may be a preview of next week's coming attractions.<p>
Nicholas Sargen plots investment strategy for <wam-co NYSE:JPM>JP Morgans<wam-co> richest clients. "Uncertainty about earnings is the new dimension we're dealing with," he said on Friday afternoon, after the close. <p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Low interest rates on bonds and money market accounts are helping stocks defy gravity.</font></b><p><p>
This market has been funny, though. It keeps defying gravity. Stock prices don't seem to have any relation to earnings at all. They're just being pushed up by all the new money flowing into equity mutual funds.<p>
How long can it last? As long as interest rates on bonds and money market accounts are so low, they give people sticker shock. "This is the same kind of situation that fueled Japanese equity markets in the 1980s" says David Diamond, who manages small capitalization stocks for The Boston Company. "Regardless of earnings, stocks went up and continued to go up for ten years."<p>
Then they crashed when the Japanese central bank raised interest rates.<p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>Japanese investors are keeping close tabs on politics at home and here.</font></b><p><p>
Friday evening, I talked to Hideyuki Omakawa, who manages the international capital markets desk for Nikko--Japan's third largest brokerage. He said that next week could be the turning point for the Japanese market.<p>
The Diet, Japan's Parliament, is the key. Lawmakers are considering a plan to solve Japan's "S&L" crisis, a $60 billion (6.14 trillion yen) millstone around the market, through a taxpayer-financed bailout. "The political debate is now at its height," Omakawa says. He predicts that if the Diet can agree on a plan, the Japanese stock market will rise. If not, it will fall. <p>
The U.S. presidential race is also on the minds of Japanese investors. The recent strength of the dollar has been good news for Japanese exporters, but not so good for big U.S. companies. Some U.S. corporations are said to be discreetly pointing this out to people in Washington. In a very politically sensitive year, they might find someone there who shares their pain.<p>
Gregory J. Millman is author of "The Vandals' Crown, How Rebel Currency Traders Overthrew the World's Central Banks," now available in nine languages.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
