<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01/27--AOL's Good/Bad News</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Daily%20Exclusives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01/27--AOL's Good/Bad News</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						On Friday, New York attorney general Dennis Vacco threatened to sue AOL for fraud. His announcement, which gave AOL five days to show why he shouldn't proceed, followed Thursday's meeting by 20 states' attorneys general concerning possible fraud actions against AOL.<p>
Apparently this is one of those good news/bad news situations. The good news is that AOL's new  pricing plan, a flat rate of $19.95 per month, is popular--the service signed up half a million new subscribers in December. <p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
It's worth noting that shortly before this controversy hit, Salomon Brothers touted AOL as a "buy."<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
<p>
The bad news is that people who sign up for the new pricing plan have actually been trying to use the service. And they can't. Unless listening to a busy signal counts as use. Advertising and taking money for a service that people can't use counts as fraud in Mr. Vacco's book. Other states are considering suing, too. Moreover, according to the Financial Times, five civil class action suits have already been filed by angry subscribers.  <p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>Is there a pattern of deception?</font></b><p><p>
Golly, fraud is serious. Vacco says that AOL had used "persistently and repeatedly deceptive business practices." That could almost be read as an underhanded reference to AOL's erstwhile accounting practices. Is it deceptive to count sales expenses as assets and thereby report high earnings even while cash flew out the door?<p>
But that was last year's news, and AOL solved it by taking a little adjustment to the books, pace all you unfortunate buyers of AOL stock at its pre-adjustment highs. Hmm. <p>
Could there be a pattern here? Buyers of stock don't get what they expect, and buyers of the service don't get what they expect, either.  No, that would be wrong. In fact, I read in the Financial Times that Mr. Stephen Case said in a message to subscribers that AOL was "working night and day" to add capacity and make it possible for people who pay for the service to get what they paid for. Maybe I could have read this message online, but then, it's been pretty tough getting on the system lately.  <p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>There are parallels between Apple's plight and AOL's.</font></b><p><p>
It's worth noting that shortly before this controversy hit, Salomon Brothers touted AOL as a "buy." There's been no immediate reaction by analysts to the fraud suit threats. Watch this space for updates.<p>
It is hard, given all of the recent talk of Apple Computer, not to see some parallels between Apple's plight and AOL's. Both companies were more about a vision of changing the world than about the boring humdrum of numbers. Let us hope that parallels go no farther.<p>
Lehman Brothers analyst Kimberly Alexy has downgraded Apple again, to "neutral" from "outperform." In July, she had generously elevated Apple in the expectation of a financial turnaround. "We simply cannot feel confident about Apple's ability to deliver even conservative revenue expectations," she writes. The company's announcement of a first-quarter revenue shortfall of $300 million led her to lower her fiscal 1997 estimate of a positive 0.67 EPS to a loss of $1.90 per share. The NeXT O/S is at least a year away, and Apple clone makers like Power Computing and Umax are seducing customers.  <p>
<p><a name="SUB3"><b><font size=+1>What do you think of Apple's long-term prospects?</font></b><p><p>
Meanwhile, at Merrill Lynch, analysts Lucianne Painter and Leslie Thornbury "question Apple's long term viability as both a PC hardware and software provider." They have further lowered their expectations of the company's prospects in fiscal 1997 and now expect a loss of $3.25 per share.  <p>
Why? "Essentially our revised financial outlook reflects our opinion that demand for the Macintosh platform (rather than specific products) is waning substantially, and that once-loyal Mac customers are abandoning the platform," they write.<p>
What do you think?  Post your opinions on the <a href="/forums/talkstocks/week/worthboard.html">"Market Week Ahead"</a> message board.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
