<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01/20--Focus on Financials</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Daily%20Exclusives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01/20--Focus on Financials</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>Financial stocks both here and abroad had a bang-up year.
</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Opportunity continues to knock in the financial sector. Global consolidation of the financial industry, and lowering interest rates make the banking and insurance industry look like good bets in 1997. <p>
A Salomon Brothers report on international bank stocks, published January 15, notes that bank stocks beat the market worldwide during the second half of 1996. In almost every stock market except Japan's, bank stocks turned in better performance numbers than the market as a whole--and the markets generally did pretty well themselves.  <p>
**Overseas bank stocks reported eye-popping increases.**<p>
The report notes that the best performers (in local-currency terms) were FPB Bank in Hong Kong, which more than doubled. Sweden's Nordbanken came in second. Citicorp was up over 53 percent for the year. But Spain's Banco Bilbao Vizcaya surged 60.4 percent.<p>
Other bank stocks up more than 60 percent include Argentina's Bansud, up 61 percent in U.S. dollar terms; Brazil's Unibanco and Itau, up 78.1 percent and 61.5 percent respectively in local currency term.   <p>
In this company, Mexico's Banacci and Bancomer both look like laggards. They "only" climbed 24.7 percent and 44.5 percent respectively last year. Salomon nonetheless rates both a "buy."<p>
**U.S. banking and financial favorites.**<p>
Back in the USA, Merrill Lynch analysts pulled together a short list of banking and financial favorites for 1997. They include: <a name="NYSE:NOB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11095"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Norwest Corp. (NYSE: NOB)</b></a>; <a name="NYSE:EWB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16079"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>E.W. Blanch Holdings Inc. (NYSE: EWB)</b></a>; Conseco; <a name="NYSE:TIG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16065"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TIG Holdings Inc. (NYSE: TIG)</b></a>; <a name="NYSE:FTR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13523"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Frontier Insurance Group Inc. (NYSE: FTR)</b></a>; <a name="NASD:PHBK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14405"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Peoples Heritage Financial Group (Nasdaq: PHBK)</b></a>; and <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan (NYSE: CMB)</b></a>.  <p>
Why should bank and financials stocks continue to do well globally? Consolidation and restructuring, privatization and deregulation are going on everywhere. Moreover, global interest rates are falling. That means of course that banks can get their raw material (money) at a lower price.<p>
**Authorities in Asian and Latin America are helping banks and similar institutions develop.**<p>
In the emerging markets of Latin America and Asia, there are additional forces favoring banks.<p>
To wit: you can't have a modern economy without phones and electricity. So in order to meet their development targets, the countries in these regions have to build, rebuild or expand their telecommunications and power grids. <p>
In Asia, power needs alone are estimated to require a trillion dollars of investment over the next decade. To date, most countries have relied on foreign investors to provide the lion's share of the capital they require. But there's a limit to what foreigners can and will invest. So authorities recognize that they have to develop banking, insurance, and similar institutions. The job of these institutions is to pool and invest domestic savings in order to finance growth.<p>
It's nice to be needed. This, of course, is good news for financial stocks.  <p>
**Tax and budget measures in Japan may have a depressing effect on bank stocks.**<p>
Egregiously immunized against the general epidemic of good news is Japan. There, the average bank lost a quarter of its share price value in second-half 1996. The Japanese banks still haven't recovered from the hangover of the 1980s. There are plenty of bad loans still on the books. <p>
Nor does it look as if they'll manage to grow their way out of the problems in the near future. Taxes are going up in 1997, while government spending is going down. This is an excellent combination for slowing an economy down, but not a great combination for booming bank business. <p>
Merrill Lynch Japan analysts Bijal Shah and Trevor Greetham suggest that the Bank of Japan may cut interest rates to offset the depressing effect of the tax and budget measures. This could give stock prices a shot in the arm. But increasing the supply of yen would likely lower the price of yen relative to the dollar. So what foreign investors make on the stock they could lose on the currency. <p>
[Post your questions and comments for Gregory Millman on the "Market Week Ahead" message board in the "Let's Talk Stocks" folder.]<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

