<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01/06--Dollar Driven Bull?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Daily%20Exclusives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>

				<img src="/imgs/c-MWA.gif">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01/06--Dollar Driven Bull?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4><br>By Gregory J. Millman</font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i>Dow 7000 in '97? Sure, says a prominent Wall Street strategist.</i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Maybe the skeptics are wrong. Maybe the rules have changed. A close perusal of a stack of year end research reports by key Wall Street strategists leaves one with a strange sense of the debate. Maybe the stock market will continue to climb forever. Or maybe the bull only has another year to run.  <p>
At Prudential, technical analyst Ralph Acampora predicts the Dow will hit 7,000 in 1997. That's a year earlier than he had previously predicted. Meanwhile, at the same firm, equity strategist Greg Smith sees the dollar's strength drawing more foreign money to the U.S. markets. "Of course, the point when foreign investors flock to U.S. markets en masse might be considered an early-warning sign of an approaching peak, but it could also be very profitable for investors here first!", Smith writes.<p>
<p><hr noshade size=1>
<center><font size=+1><i><b>
"Foreign investors flocking to U.S. markets en masse might be considered an early warning sign of an approaching peak."<br>
</font></i></b></center>
<hr noshade size=1><p>
 <p>
As Smith sees the world, European investors will be drawn to the U.S. because of the European Monetary Union (EMU). Europeans have been trying to pull their currencies into tighter alignment for years, with the ultimate but usually unspoken objective being a single currency. The so-called "speculative attack" on the European currencies in 1992 briefly delayed the program. Bureaucrats are trying to put it together again by 1999.<p>
<p><a name="SUB1"><b><font size=+1>Foreigners aren't investing much in the U.S. market.</font></b><p><p>
The nations of Europe have all engaged in greater or lesser degrees of number fudging in order to meet the strict criteria of EMU. So there's every reason in the world to expect currency instability in 1997 and 1998. "As Europeans become less certain of the value of their strong currencies, the dollar looks better and better," notes Smith. Smith also sees a strong possibility that Japan's financial institutions will pour money into U.S. markets, too. They need high yielding investments to patch the holes in their asset base.  <p>
Interestingly, as Smith points out, U.S. Treasury data show that foreigners aren't investing much in the U.S. financial markets. Smith reads this optimistically -- it means there is room for foreigners to put a lot more capital in the U.S.<p>
<p><a name="SUB2"><b><font size=+1>Advice for investors: Watch the dollar.</font></b><p><p>
But other sources indicate that  Europeans believe the U.S. market is absurdly overvalued and the Japanese, having been stung before, are more cautious, and also a lot poorer than they used to be.  <p>
The dollar's effect on the stock market is never simple. A strengthening dollar certainly makes U.S. investments even more profitable to foreign holders who translate their dollar holdings into local currencies. But the same strengthening dollar can make dollar-based U.S. companies less competitive, and less profitable.<p>
Best advice for investors -- do watch the dollar. Currency instability in Europe coupled with a strong dollar will at the very least help big money center and investment bank earnings. These institutions have not been very active in the foreign exchange markets lately, but that will change if currencies get more volatile. <p>
[Post your questions and comments on the <a href="/forums/talkstocks/week/worthboard.html">"Market Week Ahead"</a> message board.]

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

