				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01S-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Welcome to Worth's 1997 Investing Guide. This is the second year we have produced this special issue, a free bonus to our subscribers. Once again, it's our way of saying thanks for your support, including the encouraging and often helpful comments so many of you passed on to us during the past year. Your feedback is appreciated.<p>
The coming year promises an array of challenges and opportunities for investors. The market will, as it has for some time, continue to test our optimism. From a historical perspective, stocks are anything but cheap. Yet attractive alternatives to equities -- even at their current levels -- remain few and far between. More than ever, investors need to choose wisely, as our senior financial editor, Jim Jubak, explains in this issue's lead article, "What Comes Next." For specific tips, check out the stock selections from our regular panel of top mutual-fund managers and newsletter writers ("<a HREF="http://www.worth.com/articles/Z9700F07.html">Top Picks for 1997</A>").<p>
Washington, meanwhile, has vowed to address Medicare, Social Security, and capital-gains taxes in the coming year -- all areas of considerable interest to our readers. Morey Stettner provides further details in "Against All Odds."<p>
Elsewhere, Todd G. Buchholz, who writes regularly about overseas markets for Worth, identifies the major global trends for 1997. Staff writer Paul Davies offers select advice from some of America's best financial planners. And Nick Ravo, a regular contributor on real-estate issues, explains why the outlook for the housing market is finally starting to look up.<p>
Throughout this special issue, you'll encounter the witty and often striking photography of Geof Kern. Geof, who lives in Dallas, is one of the most celebrated professionals in our business. He has won virtually every award that can be bestowed on a photographer, and we are delighted to have this opportunity to showcase his work.<p>
As always, I welcome your comments and suggestions about Worth. You can write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022, or you can send me a fax at 212-980-4307. My E-mail address is: <A HREF="mailto:john_koten@worth.com">john_koten@worth.com</A>.<p>

