<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Forward Thinking </title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Forward Thinking </b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						What do the rest of us think about our charity, or lack thereof?<p>
By John Koten<p>
Early a year ago, contributing editor Richard Todd got the assignment to explore the nature of charitable giving. We asked him to consider a few questions, such as why do some people give money away and others not? Is charity learned or innate? Is money given out of guilt or hope of heavenly reward? Are philanthropists better people than the rest of us?<p>
**What is the motivation behind giving?**<p>
To report the story, which begins on page 69, Dick went to different parts of the country and into the homes and offices of experts and thoughtful people of all kinds -- philanthropists, tax lawyers, sociologists, fund-raisers, and philosophers. He found that there is no monolithic thinking on the subject -- the motives for giving are mixed. But the result of giving money became manifestly clear. As one philanthropist explained, "An enormous sense of abundance came over me. You would think you would feel depleted, but no, it's just the opposite."<p>
This election year is an apt time to think about philanthropy because the debate over whether the country needs less government or more -- and even more basically, over what government is for -- concerns the charitable impulses of the nation as a whole. Programs for the arts and the poor have been under considerable attack. But who should fund the arts? The government? Private individuals exclusively? Who will help the poor if the government will not? The rich?<p>
**Carnegie intended charity as a means to help the less-fortunate outside the marketplace.**<p>
The robber barons of the past sought through enormous acts of charity to place "ladders on which the aspiring can rise," as Andrew Carnegie put it. If neither the wealthy nor the government will build these ladders, are we as a society happy to tolerate a world that is left entirely to the marketplace?<p>
It's not big news that many of the very rich have been disappointments to philanthropic and nonprofit organizations. The question is, what do the rest of us think about our charity, or lack thereof? The answer should tell us much about whether we are truly rich or poor.<p>
As always, I welcome your comments and suggestions about how we might be able to serve you better at Worth. You can write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY, 10022, or send me a fax at 212-980-4307. My E-mail address is: <A HREF="mailto:john_koten@worth.com.">john_koten@worth.com.</A><p>
KEYWORDS:Philanthropy, philanthropist, charity, donation, charities, gift

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

