<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						This tale is about how things work -- or don't work -- in this land of ours<p>
By John Koten<p>
I have been an Andrew Tobias fan for a long time. Few magazine writers can bring Andy's level of intelligence and wit to the telling of a story. So naturally I was pleased when last year he agreed to sign on as a Worth contributing editor. It also happened that I had a specific story in mind that I hoped he would write -- a first-person account of his efforts to fix our nation's auto-insurance mess.<p>
I got more than I bargained for. Andy's tale, which appears in this issue, is about car insurance. But it is also a story about Ralph Nader, trial lawyers, big business, grassroots politics, and the American voter. It's a story about how things really work -- or don't work -- in this land of ours.<p>
With the possible exception of Michigan, virtually every state in the U.S. has an auto-insurance system that costs far too much and provides little in the way of benefits to people who are seriously injured. There's nothing new about this. Consumer advocates have been saying so -- loudly -- for a long time. Yet almost every effort to bring about reform has either failed or been sabotaged. Why?
Well, for one thing, because a very powerful group of people (trial lawyers) likes the way things are now just fine. They make a lot of money.<p>
Another reason is that the solution to the auto-insurance mess (adopting true, as opposed to fake, no-fault auto insurance) runs counter to a concept that has become ingrained in our culture -- the appealing notion that when anything bad happens someone else must be to blame and made to pay. The problem is most accidents are just that -- accidents.<p>
True no-fault systems haven't been able to find a place in our blame-based society. They apparently have no place even in the worldview of a liberal thinker like Ralph Nader -- perhaps because he's staked a career on fingering "the bad guys." Yet as Andy's story so eloquently demonstrates, we are all worse off as a result.<p>
As always, you can write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022, or send me a fax at 212-980-4307. My E-mailaddress is: john_koten@worth.com.<p>
John Koten, Editor
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
