	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By John Koten<p>Rich communities don't always conform to popular stereotypes about wealth. Take No. 209 on our list of America's 300 richest towns: North Barrington, Illinois -- a distant suburb northwest of Chicago. I happen to know this place fairly well; it's where I spent much of my childhood.<p>North Barrington was, and is, a nice place, with rolling hills, a couple of golf courses, pleasant homes, and well-tended yards. There are basketball hoops in the driveways and barbecues in the backyards. The residents are mostly hardworking and family oriented. They include doctors, lawyers, business executives, airline pilots, and architects.<p>North Barrington, however, hardly resembles anything you'd see on Lifestyles of the Rich and Famous. It's certainly not a Palm Beach or a Beverly Hills. It doesn't have butlers, or chauffeurs, or long-term guests living in pool houses. <p>It isn't even as showy as nearby Barrington Hills (No. 95 on our list) or South Barrington (No. 52). Barrington Hills has a prestigious country club, horse trails, and five-acre zoning. South Barrington, a relatively new community, is dotted with huge baronial houses, many of which look as if they were mail-ordered from Neiman Marcus. Walter Payton, the former star running back for the Chicago Bears, lives there. No one of comparable fame lives in North Barrington, as far as I know.<p>In North Barrington, success buys refuge and conformity, not status and ostentation. This is undoubtedly true of many of the towns on our list of 300 (including No. 1 Rolling Hills, California, with its one-story, identically painted homes). It also may be a reason it isn't always easy to spot some of the pockets of wealth in this country: Some people actually prefer to use their money to live relatively normal, quiet, and anonymous lives.<p>A note to the more than 35,000 entrants of the first Worth stock-picking contest: We'll announce the winner in the September issue.
As always, I'm interested in your thoughts about Worth. You can write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022, or send me a fax at 212-980-4307. My E-mail address: John_Koten@Worth.com.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

