	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/05-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Forward Thinking  <p> FORWARD THINKING  <p> By John Koten  <p> Life would be simpler if investing in the stock market was just about the numbers. Do your homework. Buy low. Sell high. Ride a nice cycle of profits and losses, with emphasis on the profits. But life's not that simple, of course. As two quite different stories in this issue show, investing is as much about hopes and dreams and power as it is about figures.   <p> A lot of hopes are riding on the amazing stock market of 1996. Baby boomers, for one, are hoping that it will bail them out of all their difficulties, pay for their children's education, help them start new businesses, and provide for retirement ina style that won't be embarrassing. It's a whole new world for a generation that once eschewed capitalism. So far, it's paying off in spades.   <p> But, as Jim Jubak asks in his cover story, will it last?  <p> That may depend as much on the character of investors as on anything. Will boomers panic if prices fall? Will they cash out of their 401(k) plans and flee to Canada? Or will they stay put and hope for the best? I think it will be the last of these. Say what you will about baby boomers, but they aren't fickle. This is a generation that still listens to the Rolling Stones and even thinks it still looks good in blue jeans. It will take more than a correction to pry these folks loose from the marketand from the chance to fulfill their dreams.  <p> "The Master Passion," by William Green, is the story of another kind of stock-market investor: a miser. Orville Wood was not a famous misernot a Hetty Green or a Silas Marnerbut he had the miser's love of money and an overwhelming, passionate fear of sharing it, even with those closest to him. Wood was fascinated by the stock market. He read investment newsletters, took correspondence courses in economics, and, for most of his 102 years, kept meticulous records of his trades. He was proud of his investments and never let his family forget how he had suffered and saved. What he did forget, or never admitted, was that he owed his success mostly to a stock market that kept going up.  <p> As always, I am interested in your thoughts on Worth. Call me at 212-223-3100, fax me at 212-980-4307, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.   <p> <p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
