					<font size=4>
						April 1996  <p>Worth magazine/Forward Thinking  <p> FORWARD THINKING  <p> By John Koten  <p> "Interactive" is a word in search of a definition at most magazines. That's because the only motivation they have for incarnating themselves on-line is that everyone else is doing it. But at Worth, we have a different perspective on cyber-space.  <p> As this month's two cover stories make all too clear, the financial markets are less well policed than ever, and no oversight institution can ensure the safety of your investments. That, increasingly, is up to you. To do it, however, you need information about market trends, companies, CEOs, the global economy and cyber-space, being infinite, is a marvelous medium for getting all of it to you, whenever you need it.  <p> Worth recently launched the second upgrade of Worth OnLine, which we provide via <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b>. Designed by our cyber-guru, Lewis Schiff, with editorial direction by Worth general editor Peter Edidin, this version provides enhanced graphics, expanded bulletin boards, and daily features about the markets, stocks, and mutual funds. Readers can also subscribe to our new E-mail newsletter.  <p> This is a part of Worth's continuing commitment to help our readers be the best-informed and most effective investors they can be. Please check it out, if you haven't already. To subscribe to America Online, call 800-827-6364, extension 0341.  <p> In another variation on the theme of interactivity, I am pleased to report that we have received more than 20,000 entries for our stock-picking contest, which was announced in our February issue. The deadline for entries will have passed by the time you read this, but we are planning to hold another such contest within the next few months. We'll let you know the winner.  <p> I am also pleased to note that Worth columnist Susan Lee's "Hands Off: Why the Government Is a Menace to Economic Health" (Simon& Schuster) will be published this month. Lee, an economist, makes a lively argument that government attempts to control or fine-tune the economy are doomed to fail, sometimes disastrously. <p> As always, I'm interested in your thoughts on Worth. Call meat 212-223-3100, fax me at 212-980-4307, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
