	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Forward Thinking<p>FORWARD THINKING<p>W. Randall Jones <p>Words have a way of losing their meaning when they're repeated carelessly. Before kids took to tossing it around as a synonym for "good," "awesome" sparked the imagination. "Counterintuitive" conjured images of brave and original thinkers until investors began attaching it to virtually every half-baked stock-market play imaginable. And now that we're about to enter yet another campaign season, the meaning of one of my favorite words is surely about to be drained: "values."<p>Those who follow my column know that my wife and I have spent the last two years renovating our home in a suburb just outside of New York City. It hasn't been easy. A couple of times I felt that I had surely changed places with the Cary Grant character in the movie Mr. Blandings Builds His Dream House. I wondered how Connie and I and our three boys were going to outlast the ongoing invasions of workmen, the blizzards of dust, and the early-morning serenades of the circular saw. <p>But the headaches and the heartaches have finally paid off. No, not in any financial sense, because we'll probably never get as much money out of this house as we've now put into it. But how do you place a dollar value on the place where your children grow into adults? How do you run a profit-and-loss analysis on sitting with your family in a place that's exactly as you'd hoped it would be? You simply don't.<p>A home is a sanctuary. It's where you build the relationships that make life's journey worthwhile. It's where you know everything's place. It's where memories carve themselves into the walls.
From an investment standpoint, I view my newly finished home the same way I'd view art. If it appreciates in value, I'll consider myself lucky. But the return I'm shooting for from this investment is the pleasure I derive from it. That pleasure, and the even greater gratification I receive from watching my family enjoy the house, are things I value deeply.<p>Speaking of value, our goal at Worth is to offer you more with each new issue__sharpening our focus, improving our presentation, and seeking new sources of information to bring you the best financial intelligence around. I hope you feel your investment in Worth is living up to this goal__and providing the value you expect.<p>As always, I'm interested in how you think we're doing. You can reach me by phone at 212-223-3100, send me a fax at 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
