<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth Magazine/Forward Thinking  <p> FORWARD THINKING <p>Join me in Vienna for a conference on the hottest global investments <p> By W. Randall Jones   <p> I like to think of it as the "smush scenario." The lines in our lives are blurring. Consider that 60 million Americans now work out of their homes and that folks now go into bookstores to relax on comfortable couches, read magazines, and sip cappuccino as if sitting in their own living rooms. Redefinition is everywhere. <p> The next category for an overhaul, in my mind, is the vacation.The grand old concept of an indulgent three-week sprawl is a19th-century notion. The new concept is the learning vacation, an elegant blend of business and pleasure.   <p> My wife, Connie, and I are planning such a venture in June, and we're inviting you along. The occasion is a seminar on global investing called "Seeking Safe Harbors: How to Profit From Global Diversification." Sponsored by Worth and Investments SeminarsInc., it's in Vienna, Austria, June 3 to 9, 1996.  <p> I'll be speaking about Worth's views on where the hottest global investments are and why we're so bullish on them. But I'll also be listening to 20 of the world's leading experts on global investing. Among them will be Worth's own global economist Walter Russell Mead; Paul Melton, editor of The Outside Analyst; Mark Skousen, editor of Forecasts and Strategies; and Allen Keyte, editor of World Affairs Review.  <p> I've always thought of Worth as a collaboration among all of us who share a passion for the tangible and intangible world of finance. This investment summit will give us a chance to meet many of us for the first time. More than 30 workshops are planned think of it as a stimulating investment salon. In Vienna, we can nod to Freud, psychoanalyze the global markets, and put the world's economy on the couch. If you'd like to join us, please call 800-226-0323, or if you harbor any thoughts about Worth you'd like to share, I'm at 212-223-3100; fax, 212-223-1597. My address is 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry, International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
