				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01S-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						January 1996--Special Issue <p>Worth magazine/Forward Thinking  <p> FORWARD THINKING  <p> By W. Randall Jones and John Koten  <p> Welcome to worth's 1996 investing Guide a special bonus issue that provides an advance view of the financial landscape for the year ahead.  <p> Why a bonus issue? It seemed like a good way to say thank you for helping us make this one of the most successful new magazines in years. Since our launch in February 1992, Worth has surpassed every target we've set for it whether the measure is subscription sales, newsstand purchases, or advertising revenue. In 1995, our total paid circulation surpassed the 500,000 mark. We have been adding readers at a faster rate than any other major financial publication.   <p> The contents of this special outlook issue cover a broad spectrum from the complexities of investing in an election year to the outlook for collectible wines and colored diamonds. We're especially pleased with the story "Top Picks for 1996," which is essentially an expanded version of our regular What They're Buying Now and What They're Recommending features. This time, we asked our 12 eminent panelists to name their top two stock picks for 1996 as well as to explain their outlook for the market as a whole (the story begins on page 53). Keep in mind that these folksare not the stock touts you see in other money and business publications, but highly successful fund managers and newsletter writers who put their mouths where their money is for Worth's audience.  <p> We also asked ten highly respected financial planners to tell us the single most important strategy or tactic they will advise their clients to adopt in the upcoming year. Their insightful responses begin on page 74. Elsewhere, Todd G. Buchholz, whoregularly writes about overseas markets for the Need to Know section, takes on the task of identifying the major global trends for 1996 (page 42). Elizabeth Macdonald, our tireless monitor of all things involving taxes, brings together the smartest ideas for approaching April 15 (page 87). Nick Ravo stays closer to home, writing about the outlook for the U.S. housing market (page98).  <p> Regular readers know that we are anything but market cheerleaders, but as you read this issue, you'll discover we're pretty optimistic about the future. As we researched the prospects for the year ahead a task that included surveying 20 key U.S. industries (see page 66) we concluded that the outlook isn't nearly as gloomy as some prognosticators would want us to believe. The U.S. economy is a dynamic and vital enterprise it rarely pays to underestimate its vigor.  <p> We hope the same can be said of our magazine. As always, we're delighted when we hear from you about how Worth is doing. You can reach us by phone at 212-223-3100 or by fax at 212-223-1597,or you can write to us at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY10022.  <p> 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
