		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>
Worth magazine/Forward Thinking  <p>
 FORWARD THINKING <p>
Our next issue will feature expanded coverage of investing and personal business  <p>
 By W. Randall Jones and John Koten  <p>
 Close readers of this magazine will notice some new names in our pages this month, including Jim Rogers and Susan Lee. Peter Lynch, meanwhile, is taking the month off after completing features for our last two issues. Peter will be back next month.  <p>
 Change is important to a magazine. It helps keep the contentslively and fresh. But readers also appreciate familiarity. Part of our job at Worth is to find the right balance between the two. Our approach is to simply try to make each issue better than the last, constantly building on the things that you, the readers, tell us you like.  <p>
 Last year, we put months of effort into contructing the methodology--and computer spreadsheets--we used for selecting our top mutual fund picks for 1994. This year, we spent another two months refining and building on that system. The result is an even better fund package--a 28-page guide that begins on page 105.   <p>
 Nevertheless, not all change can be gradual and evolutionary. Sometimes a leap forward is called for after a long period of development and planning. We intend to take just such a leap in our next issue. The December Worth will feature expanded investing and personal-business coverage--located in two new sections in the back of the magazine. We'll also be launching a refined cover design, adjusting the size of the magazine slightly to make it easier to read, and doubling the size of the popular What They're Buying Now feature in our Need to Know section.  <p>
 These changes are possible, in part, because of the success of our magazine to date, as our paid circulation climbs past the 500,000 mark. And they are intended to expand on the things that helped us to achieve this remarkable progress.   <p>
 From the beginning, a dialog with our readers has been critical both to our growth as a business and our "growing up" as a mature publication. We want to do everything we can to continue this conversation, so please keep sharing your thoughts with us. You can reach us by phone at 212-223-3100, by fax at 212-223-1597, or you can write to us at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY.10022.  
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

