	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995   <p>Worth magazine/Forward Thinking  <p> FORWARD THINKING  <p> By John Koten  <p> I got my first credit card at the age of 15. I didn't ask for it. It just came in the mail a product of the great credit card wars of the late 1960s and early 1970s. At the time, banks were scrambling to sign up customers for this new form of money, and many were throwing caution to the wind. They sent cards to convicts, babies, and even folks who were long deceased.  <p> My first charge card arrived courtesy of the First National Bank of Chicago, which I later learned had mailed out more than 2 million unsolicited cards in a single postal fusillade. I was honored to be so trusted by such an important financial institution and proud to have something so adult as a credit card in my wallet as I boarded the school bus each day.  <p> But I hardly qualified for the $1,500 credit limit that came with my card. Between mowing the neighbor's lawn and caddying at the local golf course, I barely earned $30 a week. I was certainly in no position to be making monthly payments and paying 18 percent interest. The First National Bank never lost money on me, because I didn't use the card until years later. But the bank was forced to write off millions of dollars of bad debt that resulted from its overeager marketing.  <p> I mention this because I suspect we may be due for another big wave of this sort of folly as banks stampede to sell their brands of another new type of money. The imminent arrival of digital cash (also known as electronic cash, or E-money) poses many of the same challenges credit cards did more than 20 years ago.  <p> This time the stakes may be even higher. As Alan Deutschman points out in his profile of digital-money guru David Chaum, which begins on page 94, there is widespread disagreement among financial institutions and other experts about how this new form of money should work. Privacy issues loom especially large. Whatever else, I think it's safe to anticipate a few bloopers by financial institutions and wise to keep a close eye on your teenager. As always, I'm eager to hear your thoughts about how Worth is doing.Call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.  <p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
