<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Forward Thinking<p>FORWARD THINKING
We need to slow down, and some of us are beginning to do just that.<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>Americans live in what may be the world's fastest-paced society. It makes sense that it would be this way--given that most (but not all) of us are descendants of folks who willingly transported themselves halfway around the globe in search of a better life.<p>Moving fast comes naturally to us. It feels good--whether we are blasting down the highway, racing downfield with a football, or charging up the corporate ladder. This trait, of course, has also helped the U.S. become the most industrious and powerful nation on earth. But life in the fast lane takes its toll. Sometimes we move too fast for our own good or for the good of those around us. Caught up in a footrace through life, we scamper past the signals that are there to tell us what we need to do for ourselves or what our spouses, children, or friends need from us.<p>Psychologists know that manic behavior is often an avoidance tactic--a way of escaping our problems and the pain that accompanies them. To a manic, the stimulus of frenetic activity provides a protective shield from pain. We all know people who are like this to varying degrees, because we live in a manic society.
To be more in touch with real life, we need to slow down. Some of us are beginning to do just that. The trend is called downshifting--and it is chronicled by John Brant in a feature this month. <p>Downshifting isn't necessarily an easy thing to do. The more a fast-paced life is motivated by the desire to escape problems and pain, the more discomfort is likely to bubble to the surface when the fast pace disappears.<p>Nevertheless, a new survey by the Merck Family Fund found that 87 percent of the people who chose to downshift described themselves as happy with the resulting change in their life. Think about it: How many alterations have you made in your life that offered such high odds of success?<p>As always, I'm eager to hear your thoughts about how Worth is doing. Call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.<p>
KEYWORDS: Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
