<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By W. Randall Jones  <p> The American middle class has always looked to the very well-off as a source of inspiration for its dreams. After all, it's not enough just to want to be rich; it's also nice to know what you're going to do if you ever get there. Imitating the behavior of the wealthy, even without the appropriate bank account, is common. It's as if there's a need to practice up, just in case.  <p> Nevertheless, what's good for the rich isn't always what's best for the rest of us. Take the subject of inherited wealth, the focus of this month's cover story. Until quite recently, the practice of leaving something grand enough to be called an estate was pretty much confined to the wealthy. Middle-class inheritances consisted of the family homestead, perhaps a business or a farm, and a few heirlooms but little in the way of invested assets or cash, and certainly nothing requiring complicated estate planning. <p> But the postWorld War II economic boom began to change all that. As more and more people began to accumulate wealth, accountants, lawyers, and financial-services companies began marketing trusts and other estate-planning tools to an ever wider clientele. The passing of the baby boomers into middle age, and their parents into their senior years, has brought the whole thing to a fever pitch. Today, it's practically conventional wisdom that inheritance is for everyone but the poor.  <p> Does this make sense? Is leaving an inheritance really the best way to handle what's left after a lifetime of earnings? Will you really get more enjoyment out of your money after you're dead than while you're alive?  <p> At Worth, we believe that raising such questions is a fundamental part of our mission. We know our readers make up their own minds about how to handle their money and their lives, that's why we don't tell you month in and month out what to do with your money now, as some magazines do. But we believe it's important that everyone understand the assumptions underlying financial trends, and the consequences of following along.  <p> As always, I welcome your comments. Call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.  <p> <p>
KEYWORDS: Estate Planning, Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
