	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Forward Thinking  <p> FORWARD THINKING <p>Why in the world would any company want to list its shares on Nasdaq?  <p> By W. Randall Jones  <p> This month, Gretchen Morgenson, Worth's executive editor, takes on the National Association of Securities Dealers for its shoddy oversight of the Nasdaq stock exchange. After finishing her compelling story, some readers may wonder: Why in the world would any company want to list its shares on Nasdaq?  <p> For some companies, the answer is simple: There's no choice. Because of its lesser listing requirements, Nasdaq is the only place certain small, untried companies can get on the map. To these folks, listing on the New York or American exchange is a goal for the future.   <p> But many larger, well-heeled companies also list on Nasdaq, even though they could easily move to the NYSE or AMEX. This is puzzling to investors who rightly believe that a company's CEO should be interested in the well-being of its shareholders. <p> Nasdaq would say that companies choose to list with it because its multiple-dealer market provides greater liquidity more cash to go chasing after stock. But there are some other reasons, as well.  <p> <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI Communications</b></a> could easily move to the NYSE, yet it has a very cozy relationship with Nasdaq. Perhaps that's because in 1993, the telecommunications giant won a $150 million multi-year contract to run Nasdaq's phone operations. What's more, Bert C. Roberts of MCI sits on the Nasdaq board, while Gordon Macklin of the NASD is an MCI director.  <p> MCI may be an unusual case. A more common reason companies stick with Nasdaq is that a number of major market-maker firms, eager to profit on the high spreads in a Nasdaq stock, sometimes work behind the scenes to increase a stock's profile among investors by getting research reports published on the stock. This can raise a company's profile fast.  <p> Chief executives who are concerned about their shareholders and the prices they pay to buy and sell stock should have cause for concern when they've finished with Morgenson's piece. If they don't well, that in itself is cause for concern.  <p> As always, I'm eager to hear your thoughts about how we're doing. Call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
