	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Forward Thinking<p>FORWARD THINKING<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>In February's issue, we identified Alan Greenspan as the person investors should watch most carefully in 1995. The Federal Reserve chairman is arguably the most powerful figure in the global economy. His decisions directly affect our financial lives in a way no other public figure can match.<p>Yet information about the man himself, his beliefs, and his actions inside the Fed can be hard to come by. To give our readers more insight, we asked Michael Lewis to delve behind the scenes and produce an in-depth profile of the Fed chairman. The resulting feature, which begins on page 58, is one of the most fascinating financial stories I've ever read. <p>Alan Greenspan is clearly on a mission--a mission many of his supporters don't fully appreciate or understand. Certainly he has played an important role in stabilizing the U.S. economy and increasing the confidence levels of the business and investment communities. But at the same time, Greenspan has moved to insulate himself and the Fed from answering to any other authority.<p>I don't know about you, but when I see a man taping meetings without some participants' knowledge, withholding information from Congress, and running public policy as a personal fief, I start to worry. History is replete with stories of leaders who thought they knew better than everyone else. That has usually been their downfall. I'm wary of anyone who tries to place himself beyond accountability, especially a man who influences my financial destiny.<p>Here at Worth, I'm the one who's accountable--to you, our readers. Because of that, I'd like to raise an issue you may have read about lately: ethics in personal-finance journalism. I'm not interested in airing other magazines' dirty laundry, but I do want you to know our own conflict-of-interest policy. It's simple, it's rigorously enforced, and we think it's the strictest in the business. In short: No one who works for Worth may benefit from advance knowledge of what we plan to publish. This applies to staff members, consultants, contributors, vendors ... anyone who earns a buck from the magazine. We believe such a policy is a prerequisite for credible advice. As always, I'm eager to hear your thoughts. Call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
