<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/04-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/04-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1995 
Worth magazine/Forward Thinking<p>FORWARD THINKING
Our problems are large, but to the rest of the world, the U.S. still looks good<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>Compared to what? it's a critical question when it comes to assessing the prospects for U.S. markets. Especially right now. In a global economy, everything is relative and perspective is key.<p>Say you live in Des Moines, Iowa. The outlook for the U.S. economy might not appear so bright from where you sit. President Clinton seems reasonably well-meaning, but is he an effective leader? Not really. Will the Gingrich-led Republicans really make our government leaner and more effective? It's hard to tell. Meanwhile, the cost of your adjustable-rate home mortgage just spiked up another few bucks, you know several folks who have been looking for work for quite a while, and your farmer friends are scared to death about impending cuts in agricultural price supports. You keep hearing that inflation may be just around the corner, but you also wonder if all these interest-rate increases could actually end up causing a recession.<p>Are these reasons to be concerned? The answer is yes. Is our country faced with major economic and social challenges? Again, the answer is yes.<p>Yet increasingly, an even more important matter that people need to consider__at least as investors and perhaps as citizens, as well__is, How does our country look compared with the rest of the world? How big are our problems compared with those of Mexico? Or Japan? Or Cuba?<p>I'm not highlighting these questions because I think Americans are spoiled and ought to spend more time counting their blessings. I point them out because these days investment dollars increasingly flow to areas of relative strength in world markets.<p>The outlook for U.S. stocks depends not only on how our economy is performing, but also on how it is performing relative to the economies of other nations. At the moment, as this month's cover story explains in greater detail, the relative outlook is actually pretty good.<p>It's the sort of perspective you can count on Worth to provide. We'll leave it to others to miss the forest for the trees. As always, I'm happy to hear your thoughts about how we're doing. Call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Internatonal Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
