<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Forward Thinking  <p> FORWARD THINKING <p>Maybe Newt should give the IRS a tax credit to go out and buy new computers  <p> By W. Randall Jones  <p> As sound bite-thirsty gop conservatives try to close on their "devolutionary" Contract With America, the arguments on Capitol Hill have focused on how much of their self-proclaimed revolution the party of Gingrich will be able to accomplish, and how much is worth accomplishing.  <p> This is fine grist for the pundits, who can now wonder out loud whether Newt's notion (later retracted) of giving every man, woman, and child in America a government credit to go out and buy laptop computers is responsible social and economic policy. Term limits, gun control, welfare, and health reform are important issues. But what if government can't even collect the money it requires to administer this society, much less change it?   <p> To get the trillion or so dollars a year it needs each year, government relies almost totally on one institution: the Internal Revenue Service. (Tariffs and other fees provide a few bucks as well.) But the service, once held in something like superstitious awe by taxpayers, has had a hard time of late. Antitax sentiment throughout the country has undermined the legitimacy of its mission, and the ongoing transformation of our economy has complicated the job of revenue collection.  <p> Electronic cash and commercial transactions, the decline of large corporations and the rise of small entrepreneurial ventures, for which "headquarters" can be wherever one of Newt's laptops is present--all this is making life tougher for the IRS, which can barely keep its own crumbling computer system up and running.  <p> For the first time, responsible voices are questioning whether the IRS and the present tax system are about to be rendered obsolescent by an electorate that doesn't want them around anymore, and whether advances in technology will make it easy for many of us by the year 2000 to hide the money we earn from the IRS's once omnipresent gaze.  <p> Our cover story takes readers beyond the day's headlines to investigate a crisis that could change the way our government and our society operates. It's a story that matters, a story for Worth. As always, I'm happy to hear your thoughts about how we are doing. Call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.  <p><p>
<p>KEYWORDS:  Taxation, Government 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

