		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Forward Thinking  <p> FORWARD THINKING <p>The markets are about far more than money--as our list of market movers proves  <p> By W. Randall Jones  <p> It proved somewhat humbling, trying to identify the 50 people with the most influence on the U.S. markets. Wall Street is a place where virtually every facet of American life intersects in one way or another. Toss in the effects of developments in other countries--whether economic or political--and the range of activity mirrored in the daily percolation of the markets begins to seem almost boundless.  <p> Here's one piece of evidence: Fewer than half the people who made our final list are involved directly in an investment activity. Among others, our list includes judges, politicians, industry titans, media representatives, and economists. Wall Street is well represented, but so are Tokyo, Baghdad, and Omaha, Nebraska. <p> To cynics, stocks, bonds, and other investments are only about greed, power, and money. Yet to anyone who cares to look past the dollar signs, there is far more to see--a wide panorama of human endeavor and social evolution. Ideas. Laws. Technology. Psychology. Nature. They all play a role. Each can rise to dominate at any given moment. Yet over the sweep of time, none is necessarily most powerful.  <p> The range and depth of the markets ultimately is what makes them so interesting to observe. It's also why our definition of market mover involves more than the ability to make the Dow jump on a given day.  <p> The inevitable lesson of this package is that informed investing requires more than just a sharp eye on the ticker tape. The economy doesn't tell the whole story. And neither does the rise and fall of stocks. In the worst market, there are always still some winners. In the best market, there are always some losers.   <p> The best investors share this with the people on our list: They keep their eyes open and never stop learning. Part of our job at Worth is to help with this never-ending task. It's one reason the range of subjects we cover in each issue is broader than that found in other personal-finance magazines. As always, I'm happy to hear your thoughts about how we are doing. Call me at212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022. If you'd like, wish us a happy birthday. It's our third--a happy day I'm told 95 percent of all new magazines never see.  <p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Market Trends
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

