	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Forward Thinking<p>FORWARD THINKING
But enough about us. Here's some impressive research about you, the readers.<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>Magazines normally reserve this space for hearty self-congratulations. It is here we boast of our latest accomplishments and heroic acts in the face of tight deadlines, et cetera, et cetera.<p>I'll get around to my share of this in a moment. But first, I want to break with tradition and offer congratulations to another group--to you, our readers. Why? Because I just finished reading the 1994 Mendelsohn Affluent Survey, which reports on the reader demographics of the major national magazines. Each year the Mendelsohn organization surveys thousands of citizens to find out who peruses what. Within our industry, this research is widely considered the most accurate tabulation of its kind. It can be scary, as well:  A competitor of ours in the personal-finance category refuses to participate, presumably for fear of the results.<p>This year, the findings divulged some fascinating things about the readers of Worth. First, Mendelsohn told us that you are an exceptionally smart audience. In fact, a larger percentage of you attended college than the readers of any other periodical published in the U.S. More than the audiences of magazines like The New Yorker, The Atlantic, Forbes, Business Week, and Fortune. More also than the readers of the Wall Street Journal and Barron's. <p>The survey also told us that you folks are doing quite well financially. Worth's audience beat every other major U.S.-based publication in average household income. In fact, we learned that as a group you are even more well-heeled than our 1993 readership, which also finished first in the survey. I won't be crass and invade your privacy by publishing any figures here. You already know how successful you are. What you might not have known, however, is what good company you are in as readers of this magazine.<p>So congratulations for all your success. I wish even greater accomplishment for you in the future.<p>Now it's time for me to blow our horn, too. After all, we're the ones who attracted you smart, successful types. What's more, our circulation rose 49 percent during the 12 months between the last two Mendelsohn surveys. I'm also very pleased to report that an increasing share of our new readers are women.<p>We intend to keep doing the things that have helped us attract the best magazine audience around. If you know of any way we can improve on this mission, please drop me a line at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022. My fax number is 212-223-1597, or you can call me at 212-223-3100. One of the advantages of having a smart audience is the quality of the feedback we get.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
