<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Departments<p>FORWARD THINKING
Be the boss when it comes to your money. The best advisors are more effective with a knowledgeable client.<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>Our readers ask us a lot of questions. which stocks should I buy? What's a good way to pick a mutual fund? Do I really have to pay all those taxes? How much of my portfolio should I invest overseas?<p>We do our best to respond to these questions and concerns, not only individually but in the stories we run in the magazine. Such is the case with this month's feature on America's best financial advisors. Wherever we go, it seems, people want to know: How can I find an expert who can help me get my personal finances in order?<p>Our answer to this question begins on page 60, in "A Skeptical Guide to Financial Advisors." <p>We approached the subject, as the title of the story suggests, with a certain ambivalence. We understand why some people might need an advisor to help them with their finances. Planning for the future, restructuring investment portfolios, establishing trusts, developing tax strategies--these are crucial issues, and we believe in expert help. But when it comes to issues involving money and investments, we also believe strongly in self-reliance.<p>Why? Partly because we think it's the only way anyone can be sure his or her personal finances are getting the full attention they deserve. Advisor or no advisor, you still have to be the boss when it comes to your money. And a boss who is absent or doesn't understand the issues is asking for big trouble. That's why even the best financial advisors operate more effectively with a knowledgeable client.<p>Making good decisions about money can certainly be a headache. It also requires a lot of time and energy--commodities not always in abundant supply. But these aren't reasons to turn full responsibility for your personal economic affairs over to a stranger. We suggest that you use a financial advisor as a kind of partner. Don't let the buck stop somewhere else.<p>Of course, we should acknowledge a certain conflict of interest. After all, this magazine is in the advice business, too. So we're writing about the competition here.<p>But which would you rather read: a list of top financial advisors compiled by an industry booster, or one compiled by grudging skeptics? We hope your answer is the latter, because that's what we're all about.<p>As always, I am happy to hear from readers about any aspect of the magazine. Call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
