	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
It's impossible to be a well-informed citizen without some knowledge of economic policy<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>In this issue, we're pleased to feature a story adapted from Joseph Nocera's The Sunny Side of the Street, to be published this fall by Simon & Schuster. The book dramatizes what Nocera calls the "the money revolution," a profound set of changes that has turned the U.S. from a nation of savers into a nation of investors. As revolutions go, this one hasn't been violent, but it has had an epic sweep. Nocera shows us the visionaries and savants who have introduced a progressively more anxious nation to credit cards, mutual funds, and discount brokers. <p>Many of the changes of the money revolution, Nocera argues, can be traced to the inflationary period of the 1970s, a time when Americans had to become financially nimble in ways they never had been before. Both economically and socially, the age of inflation etched its impact on America every bit as sharply as the Great Depression did 40 years earlier. Inflation can certainly be ruinous, especially for those who live on fixed incomes. Yet to the extent that the age of inflation forced us to raise our awareness about economics and personal finance, it was a good thing, too.<p>Today, it's impossible to be a well-informed citizen without at least some knowledge of how government economic policy can affect our ability to earn a living and provide for our own future. A global economy will reward nations that manage their finances well, and it will punish those that don't. Voters will have to know how to elect leaders who can get the job done.<p>As individuals, we also now hold more responsibility for our personal economic affairs. Few of us will want to count on the government to take care of us when we retire. So it is up to us to manage our money effectively amid a changing economic landscape.<p>This message is especially timely right now. Many economists believe that in five years we may look back on 1994 as the year that inflation returned as a menace to the economy. Federal Reserve Board chairman Alan Greenspan is in the midst of an aggressive campaign to stop inflation before it can gain any kind of foothold at all. His remedy--higher interest rates--has been painful and has stopped both the stock and bond markets in their tracks.<p>Will Greenspan's strategy work? Only time will tell. To date, history has shown that the only thing that halts inflation is a jarring recession. Whatever happens, investors will need all the navigational help they can get. And that's a big part of our job here at Worth. As always, I'm happy to hear your thoughts on how we're doing. Call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Economy<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

