	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>Imagine you're at a fashionable dinner party, chatting with someone you've just met. Within a half hour, you've already touched on your difficult relationship with your parents, debated sexual ethics, and explored your problems with organized religion. This is what passes for small talk in our liberated age. Then, without thinking about it, you ask your new friend how much he or she makes. <p>You've never seen a conversation come to an end faster. <p>This, of course, would never happen.  Money, as contributing editor Donald Katz wrote in a cover story for Worth last June, is "the last taboo," a subject so full of fear and loathing that we keep our financial anxieties hidden away in a sort of emotional safe-deposit box. A line from that story is the inspiration for the cover story in this issue. "The rise of a money culture every bit as rich as a culture of sexuality," Katz wrote, "has been attended by no Kinsey Report." <p>As a magazine, we've always tried to stress the personal dimension of personal finance, so it seemed clear that we needed to answer Katz's implied challenge. Teaming up with Roper/Starch Worldwide, one of the country's top market-research organizations, we sent a legion of pollsters across the country to help us draw a road map of America's financial psyche. The results are eye-opening. As a nation, we are still struggling with the legacy of the '80s and the realities of the '90s. We see money as touched with magic but also as the back door to sin. <p>The report also proves a hunch that we've always had: that successfully managing money is as much a matter of psychological makeup as intelligence or education. Thanks to some high-powered analytical techniques, Roper's statisticians were able to prove that some of us are virtually coded to accumulate money, while others are emotionally disabled when it comes to staying in the black. <p>Of course, the ability to manage money effortlessly is no guarantee of happiness. In fact, the drive to accumulate can be just as damaging as the compulsion to spend wildly. What's important is to understand why you treat money the way you do--and, in some cases, to change attitudes and behavior.<p>Not that we recommend going around asking strangers how much they're worth--it might be a few decades before that's acceptable--but we do think it's healthy to bring these issues out into the open. Reticence about financial matters often hides deeper and more troubling emotional issues. As always, I'd love to hear what you're thinking--and feeling--about the subject. Feel free to call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
