<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Financial decisions may be influenced as much by emotional considerations as rational ones<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>Sometimes good story ideas leap from personal experience. Last year, before moving to New York, our editor, John Koten, spent 26 weeks commuting between his home in Chicago and our magazine offices. At the time, he recalls, the reaction he got from most people wasn't "Gosh, that must be a tough grind," but rather, "Wow, think about all the frequent-flier miles you'll rack up." Such is the current passion over airline promotions.<p>Yet when his weekly commutes ended, the outcome was hardly a bonanza of free junkets to Maui. Six months of flying had yielded exactly one ticket free and clear. (The statement showed his frequent-flier account was still 500 miles short of his second bonus award.) "I admit I didn't do all the tricks for building mileage that some people do--like taking flights with a lot of stopovers--but still, one free ticket didn't seem like much of a discount for all those hours in the air," Koten says. "It made me want to ask: What's an airline mile really worth anyway?"<p>The answer to that question begins on page 60. <p>Our cover story about frequent-flier programs certainly isn't typical of what you might find in a personal-finance magazine. Then again, neither is our tale about John Sculley's embarrassing career move, our look at fashion in the workplace, or our recounting of the murder of a stockbroker at the hands of one of his clients. <p>These stories reflect our view that there is more to covering the world of money that just picking stocks or reporting the latest mood swing on Wall Street. Money issues touch virtually every area of our personal lives, and financial decisions are often influenced as much by emotional considerations as rational ones. That's why we aren't interested in being just another copycat magazine in the field. There are enough of those already. <p>Our mission is to try to provide our readers with a deeper level of understanding through thorough reporting and compelling storytelling. There's nothing wrong with giving instructions on how to play the frequent-flier game. But the first step is to ask how valuable these promotions are to begin with. The results are surprising.<p>We also welcome your ideas, as always, and with this issue we are making it even easier to get in touch with us. On page 18, we've published a list of addresses that people with personal computers can use to reach us on any of the major on-line services. You can also call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or drop a line to 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022. <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
