	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>In this issue, we turn once again to electronic investing--a topic to which we also devoted a feature story last month. Why so much coverage of a single subject? Because it's clear to us that computers are rapidly becoming a tool few serious investors can do without. We've said repeatedly that successful investing requires thorough homework using timely and unbiased information. As the pros on Wall Street have known for years, computers help to do this better. Now the boost is available to amateurs too, through improvements in financial software. <p>Last month, we looked at ways for investors to use computer networks such as the Internet to research companies and swap tips. This time, we present a nitty-gritty guide for readers who want to use their home computers to help them invest better. If you're a beginner, we tell you what equipment and software you need to get started. Next, we explain how to research a stock or evaluate a mutual fund on your own. More advanced users will find tips to expand their repertoire. To prepare this package, our staff conducted hands-on reviews of more than 100 top financial software programs. A listing of our favorites begins on page 91, along with explanations of what the programs do and how to use them.<p>Worth is committed to covering electronic investing better than any other magazine. We'll keep you up to date on new software and services, including the growing array of programs that write checks, manage the family budget, and help taxpayers complete their 1040s. For computer-using readers, we're also committed to providing the best on-line service. Worth was one of the first national publications to make its contents available on America Online, the fastest growing of the major on-line networks. America Online customers can read Worth stories, get answers to common financial questions, and send messages to our staff. Have a problem with a broker, insurance company, real estate agent, or tax advisor? Send a message on-line to the Worth Advocate (a.k.a. senior writer Andrew Gluck), and he'll try to help solve it. In coming months we plan to expand our on-line services dramatically, in response to the hundreds of suggestions we've received.<p>Of course I'm always happy to hear from our readers by more conventional means, too. You can call me at 212-223-3100, send a fax to 212-223-1597, or drop a line to 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022. This issue also contains a reader-response card on which you can return your comments postage-free. I promise to read every one. How's that for interactivity?<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
