<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>From the start, worth's mission has been a straightforward one: Revolutionize the journalism of personal finance. Take a subject that previously looked drab and breathe some life into it. We knew we could accomplish this partly through crisper writing and partly by focusing more deeply on the human dimension behind our stories.<p>But an equally important aspect of this task is to bring greater sophistication and intelligence to the job. Just jazzing up the copy won't do. We want you, our readers, to regard Worth as a truly helpful ally in your lives.<p>The way we report and write about publicly traded securities is a good example. Before any stock gets mentioned in Worth, in either a positive or negative context, we do thorough background research on the company and its performance history. We keep a sharp eye out for factors that could influence future performance, even if they have nothing to do with why we chose to write about the stock in the first place. Each selection must also clear several editing hurdles before it gets into the magazine.<p>In this regard, we're fortunate to have a group of highly talented editors with backgrounds in both financial journalism and professional stock trading. Our ace in the hole, of course, is Peter Lynch, perhaps the most highly regarded stock picker ever. I recently checked the record of the ten stocks that Peter mentioned in his inaugural column for us back in August 1992. A portfolio with an equal number of shares in each stock--all in the savings-and-loan industry--would have been up 39 percent as of mid-January this year. Not too shabby for just 18 months.<p>We also have a good record so far with the "Ten Stocks to Avoid" feature we launched in the October issue of Worth. As of December 30, the October list had underperformed the market by 9.4 percentage points, the November list by 4.3 percentage points, and the December list by 0.5 percentage points. (As you might expect, the underperformance is greater for the earlier periods, because the stocks have had more time to move.)<p>This isn't to say that we'll be right short-term with every stock. Our December/January issue, for instance, carried a story on the promising outlook for CompUSA. At the time we wrote this, the stock was at $27 a share. It rose for a short period but then fell to $18 by the middle of January. <p>Although we won't hesitate to point out unique opportunities for our readers, we generally take a long-term stance toward stocks, basing our views on fundamental analysis. I welcome your feedback about our stock coverage or any other aspects of Worth. I can be reached at 212-223-3100, fax 212-223-1597. Or write me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
