				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
 <p>By W. Randall Jones<p>We at worth are especially proud of this issue of the magazine. With it, we enter our third year of publishing--a considerable achievement in a difficult time for our industry. Yet Worth has done more than just survive; it has prospered in a way that has exceeded even our most optimistic expectations. <p>By September of this year, our circulation will surpass 400,000 paid subscribers, making Worth one of the fastest-growing magazines around. We also recently began broadcasting the Worth approach to personal finance on CNBC. We appear every Wednesday night at 7:30 eastern time on the Money Talk program. These accomplishments have helped confirm our belief that a magazine that brought a fresh approach to writing about money and finance would find an enthusiastic audience. <p>We're particularly proud of our February issue simply because it is our best yet. With each passing month, we've listened carefully to you, our readers, and instituted improvements to better address your needs. We've sharpened our writing, introduced new columns and features, and refined our design. We've also added more talent to our staff. I hope you'll agree that these efforts have produced an even more striking, innovative, and intelligent financial magazine.<p>We certainly have no intention of becoming complacent. Our basic format and design won't change, but we will continue with other improvements as we proceed into our third year. At its best, a magazine is like a good friend. It's there when you need wise counsel, smart advice, and even entertainment. Friends need to grow, but they also need to do so in a way that deepens their relationship.<p>Our mission at Worth is to transcend the didactic and formulaic approaches that historically have dominated the craft of financial journalism. We seek to add a more human dimension, one that recognizes the importance of financial success but that also recognizes other values in life--values that run deeper than the size of a person's bank account.<p>This approach is certainly reflected in the mix of features we chose for this issue. Our cover story, by Gretchen Morgenson, looks behind the current momentum-investing fad on Wall Street and challenges its wisdom. "A Farmer's Battle," by Donovan Webster, tells the story of a true American hero: an Iowa farmer battling to save 3,200 acres in the wake of the Mississippi flood. This is financial journalism at its best--the only kind you'll find in Worth.<p>As always, I'm interested in your thoughts about the magazine. Readers can write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022, or call 212-223-3100. My fax number is 212-223-1597.<p> <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
