	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Family Plan: Bringing charity closer to home<p>By W.Randall Jones<p>Most of my friends are very charitable, giving people. For the most part, though, it's checkbook charity. I have to admit that I'm no exception. It's a way to assuage the guilt of being financially comfortable when so many Americans aren't. Plus, it's easy and time-efficient. No muss, no fuss.<p>But it's not enough. True charity isn't just about charity balls and checks to worthy foundations. So my family and I decided to try something different for the holidays. Our plan: To help a less fortunate family celebrate Christmas this year. <p>The first step for the Jones family was to discuss the idea together. We all agreed that this was something we wanted to do. Chance, our four-year-old son, suggested we set up a charity bank in the family room. Cole, who's ten, said that he and Chance would each place 50 percent of their allowance in the bank every week until Christmas. My wife and I agreed to make an equal contribution for Chip (he's only six months old, so an allowance is a bit premature). We also said we'd put in double the total for the three boys each week. The money would go toward gifts for the family that we would "adopt" for Christmas.<p>We found this family by contacting a social-service agency in Georgia, where we spend Christmas with our relatives. (No national groups I know of offer this as a service, and it takes some digging to find local organizations that do. One place to start might be with your church.)<p>We've already talked with our adopted family on the phone to get to know them better. In the process, a remarkable thing happened. Suddenly, instead of watching the commercials during Saturday-morning cartoons and saying, "I want that," my kids are saying, "I wonder if Dave would like that G.I. Joe?" They are actually more excited about going to buy gifts for our "Christmas family" than they are about their own wishes. <p>I learned a life lesson in this small act of charity. Kids are natural givers; they just need the encouragement and help to do it. I think this just may be the best gift I'll give them this Christmas. <p>Here's wishing you the happiest of holiday seasons. As always, I'm interested in what you think about Worth. I can be reached at 212-223-3100, fax 212-223-1597. Or write to me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

