	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The Deeper Meaning of Money<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>Maybe it's because I publish this magazine. Or maybe it's because I'm getting older. But I find myself increasingly aware of the way money attaches itself to almost every deep emotional issue in life: love, acceptance, freedom, expectation, control, you name it. And I'm learning that when conflicts arise over money, there is almost always a deep-seated emotional issue involved. It is a signal that something significant is amiss--and needs to be addressed.<p>During our 13 years of marriage, my wife, Connie, and I have renovated several homes. Despite the fact that we are two strong-willed people, these projects always have gone quite smoothly. The old saying"Build a house, tear down a marriage" seemed like folly to us. But that was before our latest project. Suffice it to say that this time harmony in our household was a little harder to come by. Our poor architect must have thought we'd lost our minds because we kept revising our instructions. And we weren't sure why either of us were behaving this way.<p>Finally, Connie and I decided a good heart-to-heart talk might help. Sure enough, in the course of our discussion, it turned out some important issues between us had been neglected. She was upset because we were relying more heavily on her money to pay for the renovations. Giving up a major portion of her savings threatened her sense of freedom and independence, she said. I was angry because I felt my contribution toward paying for the house in the first place wasn't being given enough weight. Why it was so easy to view my income as "our" money, but not her income? Was there even such as thing as "our" money? <p>I am sure we are far from the first couple to have such a discussion. The important thing was that just sharing these feelings made a big difference. Eventually, we devised a new plan. We're now splitting the cost of the renovation, and I'm happy to report our dream house is proceeding on schedule.<p>The broader role of money in our lives is a major focus for this magazine, and something that sets us apart from our competitors. As always, I'm interested in hearing how you think we are doing at Worth. I can be reached at 212-223-3100, fax 212-223-1597. Or write me at 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

