	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Forward Thinking</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Forward Thinking</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Cybertalk: What is interactivity really about?<p>By W. Randall Jones<p>Last month worth wrote about investment opportunities in the new interactive age. The interest was astounding and understandably so. It's a sexy and potentially profitable subject, and few sophisticated people truly understand the intricacies of this technology revolution. We know we'll be able to shop directly from home and to call up Casablanca any time we feel like hearing Rick say, "Louie, this could be the beginning of a beautiful friendship. "But I've been thinking--is this what interactivity is all about? <p>When you laugh out loud at The Catcher in the Rye or cry at Madame Bovary, that's interactivity. When you get so mad or so touched that you sit down and write a letter to the editor, that's interactivity. When you can't get a Chopin nocturne out of your mind--or a ballad by Elvis, for that matter--that's interactivity. <p>To me, buying a pair of cubic-zirconium earrings seems pretty passive in comparison. I think genuine interactivity is feeling the heft of David McCullough's biography of Harry Truman. And what about a truly great conversation with an old friend? You can't have a relationship like that with an 800 number.<p>The problem with the interactive future foreseen by communications gurus is that it isn't interpersonal. We need to interact with the big issues that define our future. We need to hurl philosophy back and forth at each other and not accept predigested information that passes for insight.<p>I've experienced the computer bulletin boards and the two-way dialogue that goes on between people who communicate via invented names and passwords but never really know each other. It's intentional. It's high-tech armor. To me, that's a technological cop-out for a lack of courage--the courage to put yourself on the line and accept responsibility. I get nervous when we celebrate technology for depersonalizing the individual. Don't get me wrong; I couldn't live without my Macintosh PowerBook, and I've been seduced by the new Newton personal digital assistant as well. But I'm hooked on these technologies only because they make me more productive and give me more time for real interaction with my family, friends, and other things, like a great novel. Or a great magazine. I'd love to hear how Worth is measuring up to your standards of interactivity. I can be reached at (212) 223-3100, fax (212) 223-1597. Or write to 575 Lexington Avenue, New York, NY 10022.<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
