	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Well Suited</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Well Suited</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Options  <p> WELL SUITED  <p> By Tish Durkin  <p> Assuming that clothes make the man, the ultimate wardrobe coup must be a suit made expressly for the man (starting in the posh neighborhood of $1,400). The secrets of sartorial splendor: <p> Total fabrication. Even the finest men's retailers can carry only so many patterns and fabrics in so many styles. Custom tailors, on the other hand, are apt to boast hundreds of patterns, in an equally dizzying array of fabrics.   <p> A wearable lightness that's freeing. To appreciate the difference between a technologically "engineered" suit and one made by hand, you needn't notice that the collar is perfectly laid in or the shoulder stitching superbly spaced. Just breathe. "It feels like you're wearing a shirt--light, comfortable, zero restriction," says Skip Cuddy, a consultant at clothier Louis, Boston.   <p> The invisible army. Quiet but relentless needle-and-thread brigades preserve man's right to things like button holes that never fray and lapels that don't lie flat but roll. "We didn't like the thread for our handmade button holes; two-ply was too limp, four-ply too coarse," says Joseph Barrato, CEO of Brioni USA, which seconded a force of tailors to remove the problem ply.  <p> Only you. Say the word, and Nancy Hilton/Dormeuil (800-506-4400), a recently established alliance of French finery and American service-with-a-smile, will appear at your office (or at an airport during a layover). "Do you like to look dark and stately? Corporate but cool?" asks company president Nancy Hilton. Describe your ideal self, and six weeks from now you'll be putting on his trousers. <p> 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

