<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Tap Lessons</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Tap Lessons</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Tap Lessons</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Options  <p> TAP LESSONS <p>On-site breweries provide all you need to make beer  <p> By Robert Sullivan  <p> I have always been interested in brewing beer at home, on account of my close relationship with the end result. But I'm leery of the various processes, not to mention the necessary subcultural interests. ("Open Fermentation: It's OK to Leave the Lid Up," a recent article in the home-brewing journal Zymurgy, says, "The debate about open vs. closed fermentation will no doubt continue as long as there are interested brewers to debate.") I come from the school that believes weekends are intended for higher purposes than boiling kettles of greenish wort on the kitchen stove. Recently, however, I discovered an interactive brew-your-own alternative so new that it has yet to pick up a compellingly trendy name. At this point it is called on-site brewing.  <p> On-site brewing is to beer what Kinko's is to copying; the on-site brewer supplies you with everything you need, from hops to malt to the big copper kettles. You brew, go home for two weeks while the soon-to-be beer ferments, and return to carbonate and bottle your private label. It appears to have originated in 1986 in Ontario--where today there are about 140 on-site brewing facilities--as a response to the high cost of Canadian beer--a six-pack of Molson can run six bucks. Recently, Cask Brewing Systems, a Canadian firm, has sold on-site brewing systems in St. Louis, Chicago, not to mention Perth and Melbourne, Australia.  <p> I did my first on-site work at  the Glisan Street Brewhaus in Portland, Oregon. The Brewhaus is the first of its kind in Portland, which has been called the microbrew capital of America by the country's leading beer writer, Michael Jackson (no relation). I brought along my friend Mark, who is a passionate home brewer and even a sometime reader of Zymurgy. Naturally, Mark was skeptical about the on-site concept.  <p> When we arrived at the Brewhaus, we were given a few minutes to sample some of the 90 recipes we might choose from. We settled on a pale ale, not unlike Bass Ale (the recipe list includes brand-name flavor analogies for neophyte brewers like me). We began the process, and Mark raised a red flag, concerned about my not witnessing the entire pitching, the part in which they east consumes the fermentable sugars in the corn syrup. "You're missing a really critical part,'' he said.  <p> We next prepared chocolate malts and roasted barley, in accordance with our easy-to-follow recipe sheet. We then chose our hops, each batch sporting elysian names like Willamette, Irish Moss, and Ringwood. Doug Steele, the co-owner of the Brewhaus, shuttled us along, never allowing us to miss a step in the procedure. Eventually, Mark found a few nice things to say about the Brewhaus's sterilization. Sterilization is a huge part of home brewing.  <p> About an hour after arriving at the Brewhaus, we dropped our grains into a cheese cloth sack--a kind of beer tea bag--which we then lowered into the copper kettle. Every few minutes, we stirred the hopped mixture, called the wort. Feeling expert, I leaned over the kettle to inhale what would soon be my beer. <p> And then something happened that assured me of the rightness of on-site brewing (the rightness for me, anyway): I overheard Mark in conversation with another home brewer. They were talking about bad batches. Vile smells. Friends who had become violently ill. Here were home brewing's dirty little secrets. As it turnedout, the guy that Mark was talking to had come to the more sterile on-site brewing environment on the recommendation of his doctor. His doctor!  <p> After storing the beer in the Brewhaus's refrigerated room, we went away for two weeks while the yeast did its work. When we returned, our beer was carbonated mechanically. Home brewers tend to let the yeast do the fermenting, adding a little extra for the months or so between capping and consuming, so mechanized carbonation was another sore point with Mark. But he was brought around again by the quality of our product, which was smooth, copper-colored, 5 percent alcohol, and, as billed, "100% chemical free.'' It was also very good. It took an hour to bottle 12 gallons of pale ale, and we could have shaved 15 minutes off that if we hadn't stopped so many times to sip and congratulate ourselves. <p> In the end, Mark said the only thing he really missed was the smell of beer on the days he brewed as it wafted through all the rooms of his home. I would not miss sterilizing pots, and the smell of my beer in the Brewhaus was enough for me, not to mention my family. But when we were finished and split the bottles, Mark and I found common ground on the matter of quantity. Suddenly,12 gallons of such a fine, smooth ale didn't seem like enough.- <p> BEER BASICS  <p> At these on-site breweries, expect to pay about $100 for five cases of beer if you bring your own bottles; add $30 if you don't. <p> The Beer Store, Boulder, Colorado (303-494-7000); Brew City, San Francisco (415-929-2255); Brewworks, Hermosa Beach, California(310-376-0406); Custom Brew Haus, St. Louis (314-726-2739); Glisan Street Brewhaus, Portland, Oregon (503-223-9566).  <p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
