				<font size=5><b>Shutterbugs</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Shutterbugs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Options  <p> SHUTTERBUGS  <p> By Lauren Goldstein  <p> Mary Ellen Mark and Bruce Weber each own one; Annie Leibovitz has three. Contax expected professional photographers to snapup their point-and-shoot titanium cameras with precision Carl Zeiss lenses. But the Contax T series has attracted a large following among non-professionals as well, and the reason is its retro good looks.   <p> The success of the line--launched in the early '80s--has focused other makers, including the more affordable Ricoh and Pentax, on the growing market for compact retro-styled cameras. Nikon's new Ti cameras were influenced by the styles of the '50s and'60s and include one feature that perhaps should have never been discontinued in the first place--the analog display panel for a perture, focus, and exposure readings. "People feel better about analog displays," says Frank Fennell, a Nikon marketing manager. "It is emotionally pleasing to be able to see all the controls at once." Late last year, at the urging of professional photographers, Contax introduced the G1--the first compact with "auto-everything" and interchangeable lenses. Retro cameras like the G1, Konica's Hexar Rhodium, and Nikon's 35Ti combine all the ease of a point-and-shoot with the quality of a single-lens-reflex camera. "The average person on vacation" wouldn't notice the differences between a picture shot with a conventional point-and-shoot and one shot with a single-lens-reflex camera, says Fennell. "The Ti is for those who can."  <p>  

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
