	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Let it Rain</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Let it Rain</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Options  <p> LET IT RAIN  <p> By Dean Robinson  <p> Big and bright umbrellas aren't just for the golf course anymore. For good reasons, too: The colors are enough to lighten the darkest rainy-day blues, and anything designed to keep caddie, player, and bag all dry at once is ready for the streets.  <p> Size, though, can have its drawbacks. "Golf umbrellas are not something we recommend," says Mark Murray, the owner of Seattle's Weather or Not. "You can't know where other people are." Of course Murray still sells golf or jumbo umbrellas, along with opera umbrellas, waxed-cotton brollies from Scotland, V-shafted "double brellas," and a slew of designer bumbershoots. "Umbrellas are a strange mix of personality and need," says Murray. "They let you persevere, but you can do so with style."  <p> Designers are helping the humble umbrella overcome its gray history--Nicole Miller and Moschino are two of the more prominent figures unfurling colorful, witty patterns--but the issue of etiquette remains muddy: Who gives way when umbrella carriers cross paths? "It seems to be the law of the jungle," says Murray. Even at the genteel Swaine Adeney Brigg, holder of the royal umbrella warrant for the Queen Mother in England, there's no clear answer. "I don't know," says Marc Russell, a deputy manager at the company's London store. "But I think if it's a lady coming, you lift yours up."  <p>  

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
