<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Courage 101</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Courage 101</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Courage 101</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Options  <p> COURAGE 101  <p> By Christina Frank  <p> I once lopped an entire week off a two-week vacation by taking the train round-trip from New York to San Francisco. I Amtraked it not to save money, not to take in the scenery, but because I was convinced that to fly is to die. Then I learned that people like me could be helped. I enrolled in a crash course for the aerophobic.  <p> Saturday, 8 a.m.: I arrive at a Holiday Inn near Newark Airport for American Airlines' weekend AAirborn seminar. I meet 13 other fearful fliers who are sitting in a circle along with Sandra Brown, a counselor who leads the group, and Michael McKenzie, a pilot with American. Brown asks each of us to tell the group why we need the course. Two people knew someone who died in a plane crash. One woman said her kids kept wondering why their friends get to vacation at Disneyland while they go to cities like Trenton, New Jersey, and Wilmington, Delaware. The AAirborn approach is to train us to think about flying as logical, rational people. Brown starts by offering us some comforting statistics. We learn that the chances of dying in a domestic plane crash are 1 in 11 million, but those of being killed while walking are 1 in 26,000, and while driving, 1 in 5,000.  <p> Then McKenzie's on. Believing that knowledge is power, he presents an extensive slide show and lecture, giving us more facts about the mechanics of flying, pilot training, and the rigorous FAA standards than we ever wanted to know. Turbulence, he stresses repeatedly, "is not a safety issue; it's a comfort issue." Later, he takes us on board a stationary aircraft, explains all the controls in the cockpit, and introduces us to "George," the autopilot. Brown teaches us numerous relaxation exercises involving deep breathing and positive imaging. She then gives us each a rubber band, which we are to wrap around our hands and snap violently if a catastrophic thought (such as "Isn't it so obvious that a planeload of fearful fliers is going to crash tomorrow?") enters our heads. At 6 p.m., our fretful minds somewhat soothed, our palms sporting enormous welts, we go home to do things--like eat (1,200 deaths per year)--that are much riskier than flying. <p> Sunday, 8 a.m.: In three and a half hours we're scheduled to take an hour-long flight to Raleigh/Durham. Two classmates decide they're not ready to get airborne. The rest of us talk about how we're feeling. I'm tense. Brown gets on the plane to talk us through our anxieties, while McKenzie quizzes us: "What's that noise?" To which we respond in unison, "That's the landing gear retracting."   <p> Once on the ground, we all admit that the flight wasn't so bad. One woman claims to be completely cured. The rest of us are still anxious, but significantly less so. We are given a diploma, a hug, and a pin. The return flight is even easier, with more chatting and less snapping and breathing than before. When we land, I, as always, feel tremendous relief. But armed with loads of statistics, exercises, and my trusty rubber band, I know that the next time I plan to travel long distance, I won't be calling Amtrak.  <p>  <p>WHAT IT COSTS: $495.  <p> WHAT YOU GET: An abbreviated course in aerodynamics and FAA regulations; a stress gauge; a round-trip flight to a nearby city; two continental breakfasts and one lunch.  <p> WHAT YOU MIGHT BUY INSTEAD:   <p> * A round-trip ticket to St. Thomas and a six-week supply of Xanax. <p>* 83 Bloody Marys. <p>* 2-1/2 round-trip tickets from New York to Los Angeles on a Greyhound bus. <p>* A rental car for nine days.  <p> BOTTOM LINE: Don't expect miracles, but do expect to improve. Most major airlines offer seminars. For information on this one, call 800-451-5106.  <p>  <p> <p>
KEYWORDS:  Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
