	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-The Toast of South Africa</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Toast of South Africa</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-The Toast of South Africa</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Options<p>THE TOAST OF SOUTH AFRICA
Americans take up the cause of Cape-grown wines<p>By Karen MacNeil<p>Most restaurant diners have never scanned a wine list with the hope of finding something delicious from South Africa. That's beginning to change. In 1994 U.S. importers brought in an estimated 80,000 cases of South African wine, representing more than 200 different labels. While that's peanuts compared with a winery like Robert Mondavi, which alone sells more than a million cases a year, it's amazing considering that five years ago the number of South African wines sold here was zero.<p>South Africa is one of the oldest and most prominent wine regions in the New World, with a wine-making tradition that is three centuries old, yet the wines have remained largely unknown here because of trade sanctions imposed in response to South African apartheid. In the last year, thanks to the sales muscle of about a dozen determined American importers and an extremely weak South African rand, South African wines have begun to turn up throughout the United States, both in wine shops and in top restaurants like New York City's Lespinasse and the Dining Room of the Ritz-Carlton in San Francisco. "South Africa has the makings of the next California or Australia," says Ronn Wiegand, publisher of the journal Restaurant Wine.<p>When the first advertisement for the Cape Wine of the Month Club appeared in the Wine Spectator last August, the telephone rang off the hook for weeks, according to club president John Gorman. The club evaluates and rates all commercially available South African wines and then sells them, usually at discounted prices. They retail for between $6 and $20 a bottle. "At those prices, the best Cape wines stand shoulder to shoulder with the best wines in the world," says Gorman.<p>Cape Classics, one of the earliest importers and marketers of South African wines in the United States, brings in nine Cape wines from small estates. When Andre Shearer (a white South African) and Jabulani Ntshangase (a black South African) founded the company in 1992, apartheid was still an open wound. Yet at a time when the very words "South Africa" could make people edgy, Shearer and Ntshangase could already imagine hip dinner parties at which guests sipped Glen Carlou chardonnay or Pierre Jourdan Brut, a sparkling wine from the Cape's Franschoek Valley.<p>Cape wine makers are both geographically and climatically blessed. The Cape of South Africa is the only wine region in the world that is tucked between two oceans. Cool breezes off the Atlantic and Indian oceans moderate the generally hot climate. Most important, the best vineyard areas are situated on cool, high slopes, so the grapes mature slowly and evenly--a virtual prerequisite for wines of depth and character.<p>The top wine districts are Stellenbosch, Paarl, Constantia, Durbanville, and Franschoek (area of origin is generally listed on the label). In South Africa, as in the United States, wines are named for the grape varietal from which they are made. The most popular South African white wine is chenin blanc, locally called steen. The leading red grape is cinsaut (cinsault in French), which in France is a meaty component in many southern and Rhne wines. In 1926, Cape cinsaut was genetically crossed with pinot noir in a South African laboratory. The result was pinotage--a wine varietal not grown anywhere else in the world.<p>In most wine regions, one or two grape types always seem to produce the best wine: the riesling grape in the Mosel, for example, pinot noir in Burgundy, sangiovese in Tuscany, cabernet sauvignon in the Napa Valley. In South Africa, the star is sauvignon blanc. Madeline Triffon, sommelier of Detroit's Rattlesnake Club restaurant, praises South African sauvignon blanc for its fresh, grapefruity flavor. "While we make very good cabernet and chardonnay," says Peter Koff, founder of Fairest Cape Importing, another importer of small, prestigious Cape estate wines, "South Africa makes the most extraordinary sauvignon blanc in the world. We can easily rival New Zealand, which is renowned for that grape."<p>South African wines have also had their critics. New York Times wine reporter Frank J. Prial, for example, found "too much oak" in many South African wines, particularly the chardonnays. In 1993, the journal The New York Wine Cellar found "far too many" Cape wines to be "watery" and said that some revealed "flaws typically displayed by wines from producers with limited experience." Koff diplomatically suggests that some Americans have grown accustomed to what he calls the "bouncy, up-front fruitiness of California and Australian wines." South African wines, he says, are much more lean and taut, like European wines. He pauses. "Maybe that's bad wine making. Or maybe that's adhering to centuries of tradition."<p>
CAPE GRAPES<p>For American consumers who use California wine as their benchmark, Cape wines will come as something of a shock. These wines have their own distinct personality--a personality that takes some getting used to. South Africa's wildly herbal, razor-sharp sauvignon blanc, for example, makes California sauvignon look positively tame. As for Cape chardonnays, expect big, heavy-handed wines with the full-throttle sweetness that comes from lots of toasted oak. With Cape red wines, an unusual smokey/bacony aroma and flavor are often present. The cabernets and pinotages are usually lean wines, with more pronounced tannin than generous fruit. Here are some suggestions:<p>* Zonnebloem Sauvignon Blanc ($10)
* Villiera Estate Sauvignon Blanc ($9)
* Thelema Mountain Sauvignon Blanc ($13)
* Glen Carlou Chardonnay ($17)
* Louisvale Chardonnay ($15)
* Meerlust Rubicon ($16)
* La Motte Estate Millennium ($11)
* Villiera Estate Cru Monro ($15)
* Rozendal Farm ($16)
* Blaauwklippen Zinfandel ($15)
* Middelvlei Estate Pinotage ($9.50)<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
