	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Power Seating</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Power Seating</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Power Seating</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Options<p>POWER SEATING<p>By Lauren Goldstein<p>Those ceremonial office chairs once found in the executive suite are being retired. Modern executives need seating better suited to long days at the computer. According to Ergonomic Living by Gordon Inkeles and Iris Schencke (Fireside Books, $16), that extra foot at the back of older chairs "conveys a regal impression at the expense of the executive's health. A high backed chair pushes the upper back forward while forcing the lower back to bend backwards." <p>These aren't idle concerns. The Occupational Safety and Health Administration plans to propose mandatory standards for ergonomically correct workplaces this year, including recommendations for desk chairs. The most important is that an office chair be easily adjusted. "The body was made to move," says Barbara Silverstein, special assistant for ergonomic programs at OSHA. The Picto from Wilkhahn automatically adjusts the angle of its seat and backrest to the weight, posture, and movements of the user. Another consideration is lower-back support. The Sapper chair, from the Knoll Group, is being reissued with additional lumbar support and cushioning. Herman Miller's radical new Aeron chair is made of a meshlike fabric covering a frame that distributes weight evenly on the seat. It's so unusual that the Museum of Modern Art in New York City acquired one for its permanent collection. "It's got an unsettling and mechanistic aesthetic that is perfectly suited to these times," says Paola Antonelli, associate design curator at MoMA. "It's also the most comfortable chair you can dream of."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
