<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Platonic Relationships</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Platonic Relationships</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Platonic Relationships</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Options<p>PLATONIC RELATIONSHIPS
Still have some things to learn about life? Try a tutor.<p>By John Marchese<p>Not long ago, Bill Tonelli decided to talk to someone one day a week about life and what it all means.<p>"I figured everyone else in New York had their therapist," says Tonelli. But the weekly sessions he arranged were a bit different. For one thing, he didn't go to a plush, paneled office with overstuffed furniture but to a tavern just off the campus of Columbia University.<p>And instead of talking about himself, he discussed Plato and Nietzsche and Bertrand Russell. Across the table was a Columbia Ph.D. candidate in philosophy, whom Tonelli had hired to guide him through a reading list in Western philosophy--a subject he had overlooked in college. He paid his tutor $25 an hour and bought the beer.<p>"I figured this was kind of like therapy for people who are ill-suited to it," says Tonelli, a magazine editor. "Supposedly, the point of philosophy is to teach us how to live, which is also the point of therapy."<p>Over the past few decades adult education has become a major growth industry. It has filled college classroom seats during a drought of traditional students and has helped adults get credentials or socialize. But for someone who wants to learn a subject for the sheer joy of it, tutoring might be the best way to go about it.<p>For years, University of Chicago president Robert Maynard Hutchins and his colleague Mortimer Adler taught the great books in Socratic style to titans of Chicago industry, in what became aptly dubbed the Fat Man's course. A few years ago, then media wunderkind Chris Whittle hired three different Harvard professors to tutor him in preparation for a possible political life in his home state of Tennessee until business pressures forced him to stop the sessions. Lately, Hollywood lawyer Bert Fields has been throwing monthly history dinners with a former history graduate student and radio talk-show host leading the discussion.<p>But you needn't be wealthy to be tutored. Pricewise, it's a practical way to learn. A three-credit course in Columbia's School of General Studies (which caters to older students) would cost about $1,600. A dozen sessions with a $25-an-hour tutor comes to $300.<p>The best place to look for a tutor is at a local university. (Don't bother calling the tutoring companies that advertise in the Yellow Pages. They're geared to high school students.) Call the chairman of the department you think is most appropriate for your subject and ask if there are tutors available. If you're having trouble figuring out which department to approach, try the college's public-relations department. Most keep lists of faculty experts on various topics. But don't expect to a get a senior professor from a prestigious university--unless you're willing to pay rich man's prices.<p>"If I were to tutor a student, they'd have to prove they were really serious, and I'd probably charge what it would cost to take a course--maybe $250 a shot," says one Ivy League professor and former department chairman. He means per session, which is steeper than most psychiatrists. "But," the professor added, "my graduate students would be delighted to supplement their income."<p>Michelle Heaps, a student who works in the tutoring department at the University of California at Berkeley, says the going local rate for a graduate-student tutor is $15 or $20 an hour, which often buys plenty of enthusiasm. "There are people here who just can't stop talking about the subject they are studying," she says.<p>But it's not just hungry graduate students who would be good and willing tutors. Some professional practitioners need extra money. Want help writing that novel? Most cities have writers' organizations that can recommend teachers, or you could call a novelist for lessons. In Philadelphia, Rachel Simon (author of the well-reviewed novel The Magic Touch) used to teach writing at several universities but has recently redirected her efforts toward finding private students. She charges $60 a week for a writing lesson and critique. When she tutors students, she says, "I feel they're getting a real education, and I'm able to be a real teacher."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Education Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
