<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Movie Magic</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Movie Magic</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Movie Magic</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Options<p>MOVIE MAGIC<p>By Dean Robinson<p>Coming to a theater near you is . . . well, a new kind of theater. Not since the 1950s, when moviegoers were reeled in by such innovations as 70-millimeter film and CinemaScope, has the competition to sell tickets been so technological. Virtual reality, 3-D headsets, moving seats, even computers that let viewers determine the plot, are some of the lures that theaters are using to fill seats.<p>Sony's eight-story-high Imax screen in New York City grossed more than any other single commercial screen in North America over one weekend shortly after opening last fall. And that was before it had Hollywood features to exhibit. This spring the theater premieres Wings of Courage, directed by Oscar winner Jean-Jacques Annaud and starring Val Kilmer and Elizabeth McGovern.<p>Imax, Iwerks, and Showscan are the movers and shakers in another type of theater experience: ride films, in which movable seats are synchronized with onscreen motion. Examples include RoboCop: The Ride and Back to the Future: The Ride (see Options, July/August 1994). Last summer Showscan signed an agreement with United Artists Theater Circuit to bring the technology to multiplexes around the country.<p>Interfilm offers yet another theater experience: audience control of the action. This interactive approach involves lots of shouting and pressing of buttons on specially outfitted armrests. At various moments during a program audience members press one of three buttons, shaping the material into a 20-minute film (the price of admission includes three viewings). The company's first interactive feature, Mr. Payback, starring Christopher Lloyd and written by Bob Gale, the screenwriter of the Back to the Future movies, opens this month at about 50 theaters.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

