	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Cigar Chic</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Cigar Chic</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Options<p>CIGAR CHIC<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Jack Nicholson, David Letterman, and Madonna aren't the only ones puffing on cigars with insouciance. The premium-cigar industry, with sales up 30 percent last year, is growing faster than you can ask, "Mind if I smoke?" Restaurants acknowledge the trend, too: New York City's Tatou recently opened an upscale cigar lounge. To get a good table, you'd better smoke the best. Here's how to choose:<p>Is it fresh? Like fine wine, premium cigars must be pampered. A reputable cigar retailer like Wally's in West Los Angeles houses its finest in humidors. You gauge freshness by gently pinching the cigar's middle: It should give a bit and feel slightly oily. <p>Check for craftsmanship. A quality cigar is never predrilled for inhaling. Each has a flap of tobacco at the rounded end; you slice it off before lighting up. The wrapper should consist of one whole leaf with visible veins.<p>Size matters. "Many women opt for the thinner cigarillo," says Craig Nelson, founder of the Cigar of the Month Club (800-700-7661). But it's not all image: Size and shape affect taste too. A thick cigar delivers cooler smoke and fuller flavor.<p>Easy does it. Most Dominican and Jamaican cigars make for mild beginner smokes. An Ashton ($4$11.50), an Anniversario No. 2 ($15), or a Nat Sherman's VIP ($4$5) offers mellow taste. Later, try the Honduran Zino Mouton Cadet ($4$6). As for the fabled Cuban cigar, you'll have to wait for Fidel's fall or buy abroad. Black market Cubans are often poor-quality counterfeits.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
