	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-A Better Whey</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Better Whey</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-A Better Whey</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Options<p>A BETTER WHEY
The country's finest restaurants say "Cheese"<p>By John Mariani<p>If you've recently noticed an odd but familiar odor wafting through the air of the better restaurants in your city, you are probably sniffing one of the more blatant--and delectable--examples of an ongoing backlash against the nutritional terrorism of the past decade. After years when the idea of serving fat-rich, cholesterol-laden Camembert, Stilton, or Gorgonzola at the end of a meal was regarded as the height of coronary folly, many of the best restaurants in America are now offering an array of superb cheeses.<p>"American chefs are coming out of the closet now with cheeses," says cheese maker Jonathan White of the Egg Farm Dairy in Peekskill, New York, which supplies top New York City restaurants like Chanterelle, Le Bernardin, and Aureole. "I think the last straw for people was the study showing that margarine is as bad or worse for you than butter. That broke the back of Americans' guilt over fat, and with more and more terrific cheeses now available, people are willing to sample them at fine restaurants. The interest is exploding nationally."<p>"The demand is definitely growing every year," says Chantal Plasse, an expert on French cheese at La Ferme Imports in San Francisco who has trained restaurant staffs on how best to handle, serve, and promote fine cheeses. "Four years ago when I talked to chefs about cheese, it was like speaking Chinese. There was just no demand. But I'd get them to buy just one good cheese and promote it as a special item, and it sold. Now cheese is becoming very important to many of the best chefs in America."<p>At mad.61, a vast restaurant and retail shop in the basement of New York City's uptown Barney's department store, more than 40 cheeses are on display, including a wide range of rarely seen Italian imports like Toma di Carmagnola and Brezzi, English classics like farmhouse Appleby Cheshire and Keen's Somerset Cheddar, French regional cheeses like Vacherin Mont d'Or from the Jura, and superb American types like Coach Farm Chevre, Vella Dry Jack, and Teleme. Since many diners are reluctant to add an additional course to their meal, chef Marta Pulini suggests trying cheese as the main course. The menu lists eight separate cheese plates to help them choose.<p>Americans still only eat about half as much cheese per capita as the French, Italians, and Greeks do, although we are eating 30 percent more than we did ten years ago--mostly as pizza toppings. But restaurateurs are finding that once their customers sample a good cheese, they become hooked on the idea. At Chicago's new Zinfandel, chef-partner Susan Goss serves a farmhouse sampler consisting of three American cheeses, like Yerba Santa Alpine Chevre from California, Granville Cheddar from Massachusetts, Chicory Farms Catahoula from Louisiana, and Loomis Great Lakes Cheshire from Michigan, together with marinated greens and grilled country bread. To encourage diners to try them, Goss offers cheese as an appetizer. "The attitude that European cheeses are always better is changing because of some very dedicated American cheese makers," she says.<p>Tom Colicchio of New York City's hottest new restaurant, Gramercy Tavern, agrees. Each evening he offers 15 cheeses in three-, five-, and seven-variety tastings. Set on a beautiful serving tray in full view of diners as they enter and accompanied by a terrific array of dessert wines, beers, and ciders, the selection of cheeses changes nightly. Many of them are American, like Indiana's Capriole Banon goat cheese aged in chestnut leaves. "I'm a big fan of American cheeses," says Colicchio. "I think American cheese making is where wine making was 25 years ago in this country, and I want to serve the very best we can find."<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
