<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-The Wheel World</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Wheel World</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-The Wheel World</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>
THE WHEEL WORLD
Perks -- not big savings -- are driving buyers to take delivery of new cars in Europe.<p>
By Stephan Wilkinson<p>
Anybody old enough to recall only the good things about MG TDs, Porsche 356s, and Fiat Topolinos also remembers the golden age of buying a car in Europe -- with a dollar so strong an American could save as much as 25 percent by purchasing an auto on foreign soil. The downside, however, was the risky, time-consuming work involved: haggling with a Gauloise-smoking European car salesman, finding a seedy shipping agent, delivering the car to a pier in Rotterdam, and venturing to deepest Brooklyn to retrieve it.<p>
Times have changed. Today, European "tourist delivery plans" are easy-on, easy-off. Dealers do much of the legwork. Buyers can save as much as 12 percent off the list price of the identical car bought domestically. But the most compelling allure may be having a new car ready and waiting in Europe for your next vacation. This provides the opportunity to take your new roadster for a spin on the autobahns and Alpine passes for which it was designed. Here's a rundown of the major programs:<p>
BMW (800-932-0831) As with most European-delivery programs, you should order your car two or three months ahead of time and pay in full five weeks before pickup. You can save as much as 10 percent, and the purchase price includes a month's insurance, paperwork, shipping, and delivery (from 18 European drop-off points between Madrid and Oslo) to your local dealer in the United States.<p>
MERCEDES-BENZ (800-367-6372) Savings on a new Benz generally run about 6 percent in this, one of the oldest and easily the most popular tourist programs. "The company makes less money," says Fred Heiler of Mercedes-Benz North America, "but we do it because people who go to the plant, see cars exactly like theirs being made, and drive away in one -- we think that instills really strong long-term customer loyalty."<p>
PORSCHE (702-348-3000) Pickup and drop-off are available free solely at the factory in Stuttgart, Germany. Run-of-the-mill customers, if the term applies to any Porsche pilots, get a factory tour and lunch, but three times a year -- during April, June, and September in 1995 -- Porsche Cars North America organizes special tours that include two days of wining and dining, a visit to Porsche's R&D center, and test-track rides with factory test drivers.<p>
SAAB (800-582-7222) You don't have to go to the factory to pick up your new Saab; there are 11 other delivery locations in Europe and the U.K. But if you do make the trek to Trollhattan, Sweden, Saab will send a limo to pick you up, and you'll be fed and bunked in a lovely manor house overnight and sent on your way (usually after a factory tour) with savings of about 10 percent, maps, itinerary, and good Swedish cheer. <p>
VOLVO (800-631-1667) Save 8 to 12 percent over U.S. list, plus an extra $510 if you retrieve your car at any of ten East and West Coast ports. "But oddly enough, we have a pocket of people in Minneapolis, some of our best customers, who use this program year after year," says Nancy Nelle, manager of overseas delivery. Volvo has three free drop-off points in Europe (Antwerp, Belgium; Bremerhaven, Germany; and Goteborg, Sweden) plus another 22 that will accept the car for shipment at slight extra cost.<p>
FERRARI (201-816-2600) The simplest program of all. You don't save a single lira. "But we'll tailor the arrangements however the customer wants," says Ferrari North America's Michael Jacklin, "and I have yet to meet a person who didn't wax rhapsodical about the factory tour, lunch at Cavallino [the Ferrari "house restaurant"] across the street from the factory, and the Italian roads. It truly inspires people." Cost of the lunch? A minimum of $120,050 for an entry-level Ferrari 355. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
