<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Something Wild</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Something Wild</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Something Wild</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>SOMETHING WILD
Americans flock to game birds, an alternative to turkey.<p>By Susan Kuchinskas<p>It's not your forefathers' thanksgiving. Interest in fowl like quail, pheasant, and guinea hen has risen over the last few years. The USDA reports its inspections of game birds have increased 65-fold since 1983. The turkey may not be in danger of losing its status as a holiday icon, but it's clear that consumers are searching for tasty, exotic alternatives.<p>Nutrition is one reason people are reconsidering their Butterballs: Game birds tend to have less fat and more protein. The muscovy duck, for example, which nests in trees, doesn't need body fat to keep warm and has well-developed breast muscles, making it lean and meaty. Size is another factor in the alternative fowl's popularity. Forget turkey soup and turkey sandwiches. Two quail, with an average weight of about six ounces each, serve a single eater; a goose, at eight to twelve pounds, makes a very nice meal for four.<p>Ariane Daguin, co-owner of D'Artagnan, a New Jersey wild-game importer, reports that her sales of game poultry are up 30 percent over the last few years. She credits top restaurant chefs with encouraging American eaters to be adventurous and teaching them that gamy flavors are not a negative. "A real game bird is not going to be anything like a domesticated bird," says Thomas Keller, chef-owner of the French Laundry in Yountville, California. "It's going to have that rich, almost liver-type flavor to it." Keller regularly puts squab on his menu. Its subtle flavor appeals to cautious palates -- compared to wild pigeon or grouse, it's positively tame.<p>The taste of wild game changes throughout the year as the birds' diets change, but they are at their flavor peak around the holidays. "Fall is the best season, because they've eaten all the different berries and seeds," says Daniel Boulud, owner of Restaurant Daniel in Manhattan. "Some eat a lot of juniper, and that flavors the meat in a nice way." <p>A wide variety of game birds is now available by mail from the sources below. Though prices vary according to purveyor and season, expect to pay around $2.50 per bird for quail and $5.50 per pound for pheasant. The ultimate indulgence is to have poultry jetted in from Scotland; prices start at around $6.95 each for wood pigeons, which weigh less than a pound, and reach $15 for pheasants, which usually weigh in at two pounds. Count on additional charges for express shipping.<p>D'ARTAGNAN (800-327-8246) Wild game from Scotland; free-range chicken, turkey, game birds, and game meats; sausages, terrines, and foie gras specialties.<p>DURHAM NIGHT BIRD (800-225-7457) Domestic free-range game and poultry; pates, terrines, pancettas, and sausages.<p>FOGGY RIDGE GAME BIRD FARM (207-273-2357) Free-range pheasant, quail, partridge, wild turkey, geese, and ducks.<p>POLERICA GAME EXCHANGE (800-426-3872) Domestic free-range game birds, including guinea, partridge, quail, squab, and poussin. <p>WILD GAME (312-278-1661) Wild Scottish partridge, wild American turkey, wood pigeon, venison; natural free-range Amish chicken and turkey; poussin.<p>WYLIE HILL FARM (802-586-2887) "Farm-raised" natural free-range pheasant, quail, partridge, and guinea hens; quail eggs.<p><p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
