	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Habla Mexico City?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Habla Mexico City?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Habla Mexico City?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>HABLA MEXICO CITY?
Navigating a trip to Latin America's hottest business center.<p>By Susan Enfield<p>HOTELS: CHECKING OUT WHAT'S IN<p>$
---------------
The HOTEL IMPERIAL (705-4911 -- all phone numbers in 525 area code; doubles from $120) is a 1904 landmark that subsequently housed Mexican president Venustiano Carranza and the U.S. embassy (not at the same time). Newly renovated, it's a popular  base for those working with government or banking headquarters in the nearby historical center.<p>Studio-apartment-like rooms with kitchenettes and a location on one of the Zona Rosa's poshest promenades make the MARCO POLO (511-1839; doubles from $165) a favorite with travelers in creative fields.<p>$$
---------------
Pink and blue postmodern on the outside, luxuriously ersatz art deco on the inside, the HOTEL MARQUIS REFORMA (211-3600; doubles from $205) is riding the NAFTA wave. Rooms are fully booked two weeks in advance by those who can't survive without the  services of a bilingual secretary or a dedicated fax line.<p>The CAMINO REAL (203-2121; doubles from $200) is no longer the capital's most technologically up-to-the-minute hotel, but its funky, distinctly Mexican atmosphere makes it hands down the most fun. Among its charming idiosyncrasies are the city's  best outdoor swimming pool and an endlessly meandering roof garden.<p>$$$
---------------
Built around a parklike inner courtyard, the newly opened FOUR SEASONS HOTEL MEXICO CITY (800-332-3442; doubles from $225), with its elegant Spanish colonial-style exterior, is the perfect refuge for Wall Street types to recuperate after a long day  in the world's smoggiest metropolis. <p>The CASA VIEJA (282-0067; doubles from $250) is so impeccably decorated that it recently made the cover of Mexico's leading architectural magazine. This exclusive hideaway shelters a hotel-phobic elite including Virgin Atlantic's Richard Branson.  Designed for longer-term stays, ten apartments boast more than the comforts of home: VCRs, CD players -- and pre-Columbian artifacts.<p>
RESTAURANTS: PLATS DU JOUR<p>$
---------------
Ceiling-rattling serenades by a mariachi band make late dinners at the candlelit hot spot LA CIRCUNSTANCIA (529-4140; dinner for two, about $50) feel like a fiesta. Cordon Bleu-trained chef-owner Roberto Santibanez renders traditional dishes  practically unrecognizable: Try the blackberry-based mole sauce and vol-au-vent of huitlacoche (a black corn fungus prized by the Aztecs).<p>An urbane, Chanel-suited crowd and a bar serving 16 different tequilas "macho style" -- in a chili-powder-rimmed shot glass with a spicy O.J. chaser -- make LOS ALCATRACES (281-4909; dinner for two, about $50) popular with local yuppies. Bring a  dictionary to translate the menu, which is a flowery paean to Alta Cocina Mexicana, the current rage for updating Mexican standards with exotic ingredients.<p>$$
---------------
With a chef from the original location in New York, REMI (282-0062; dinner for two, about $85) manages to replicate the food, including Venetian risottos and ravioli, in the most sophisticated room in town, overlooking Chapultepec Park. <p>With sister restaurants in Merida and Ticul, LOS ALMENDROS (531-6646; dinner for two, about $65), an upscale Yucatan cuisine purveyor, serves up hearty exotica like venison fajitas, jalabi (wild pig), and pork pibil (slow roasted in a banana leaf)  in a breezy, patiolike setting.<p>$$$
---------------
The just-opened branch of Spago may receive its stiffest competition from LA GALVIA (281-2310; dinner for two about $100). The food, from gravlax to shellfish chile relleno, is a favorite with the business elite. The menu changes seasonally, greens  are organic, and desserts are made to order. One of very few top restaurants confident enough to dispense with traditional coat and tie requirements.<p>At CICERO CENTENARIO (521-2934; dinner for two, about $100), step through the lace-curtained doors of a 300-year-old hacienda and experience the pleasures of life as a pre-revolutionary patron. Who cares if some of the Mexican and continental  specialties seem a tad old-fashioned? <p>
SHOPPING<p>Skip the cavernous new Centro Comercial Sante Fe and the shops on Mazaryk Street; the boutiques there sell the same designer merchandise you can buy at home. Focus instead on handmade wares. Tucked away in a courtyard in fashionable Polanco, LAS ARTESANIAS (Oscar Wilde No. 29) is a one-stop source of expertly selected, top-quality regional handicrafts: talavera, or traditional ceramic ware, from Puebla and Guanajuato; painted wooden animals and black pottery from Oaxaca; copperware from  Michoacan; and woven rebozos, or shawls, from San Luis Potosi. Prices are better than at FONART, the government-owned store.<p>Ask any local where to buy silver, and you're likely to get the same answer: TANE (Campos Elisios No. 218). The imposing vaultlike boutique doesn't exactly shout "bargain," but savvy Districto Federale matrons insist the handmade jewelry and  flatware is not only heavier and purer here, but often competitively priced.<p>A no-frills showroom on a Zona Rosa side street, TEMOAYA (Hamburgo No. 235) is the place to find all-wool tepates, or traditional Mexican rugs. Handwoven with 140,000 knots per square meter, the colorful, indigenous patterned rugs are somewhat cheaper than fine Orientals.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

