	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Basic Black Tie</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Basic Black Tie</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>BASIC BLACK TIE
With a tuxedo in your closet, looking good is a mere formality.<p>By Tish Durkin<p>If clothes make the man, the tuxedo makes the gentleman. The perfect gentleman -- if you know the rules. Which, incidentally, are:<p>BLACK IS BEAUTIFUL. For an Oscar acceptance the rainbow's the limit. Otherwise, the only color is no color at all. Your tuxedo must blend to perfection at formal-wear free-for-alls and in corporate cultures where chalk stripe is a crime. (Whenever you've gotta be you, just go crazy with a colorful cummerbund.)<p>SIZZLE, DON'T SHINE. Spend $400-plus on a fine, lightweight wool -- or $1,500-plus on the finest. Skimp with a reflective, polyester-enhanced number, and they'll give you a drink order.<p>CHERISH YOUR CHOICES. Peak, shawl, or notched lapel? According to Kevin Lonergan, Brooks Brothers formal-wear buyer: The top-selling notch is safe; the peak is a notch higher up on the lapel; and the rounded shawl is "fashion-forward" and tuxedo-specific -- but they're all correct. Vents or no vents? "Never vents! Too sportif!" growls Werner Baldessarini, head designer for Hugo Boss. Trouser pleats or no trouser pleats? These days pleats are in.<p>TWIST AND SHOUT. Or at least stand and sit in your prospective garment. "Men do more in a tuxedo than other suits," says Richard Cohen, president of the menswear maker Zegna, so though a tux should fit like any suit, it should feel even better. For purposes of the smooth move, think twice about that dramatic double-breasted model: it "sort of crumbles when you sit down," says Harvey Weinstein, chairman of Lord West, America's largest manufacturer of formal wear. A single looks good open or closed.<p>RELAX. So long as you get a size that fits in a form that flatters, any tuxedo is guaranteed to make you look much more handsome than you really are. So just clap on a tie, slap on the Aramis, and go get Ginger Rogers. You, after all, have turned into Fred Astaire. <p><p><p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
