		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Ancient Chinese Secrets</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Ancient Chinese Secrets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>ANCIENT CHINESE SECRETS
Using art and design to attract luck and prosperity.<p>By Myriam Weisang Misrach<p>Every deal that the company tried to complete died, but it wasn't the management team's fault. No, the problem was the conference room. It was shaped like a coffin. Then there was the case of the entertainment executive who feared he was about to suffer the fate of his predecessor, who was forced out because of extravagant spending. Solution: Install a planted window box to keep money from flying out of his office window.<p>These stories are told by Sarah Rossbach, a New York-based expert in feng shui (pronounced fung shway), the complex Chinese system of architecture and design used to bring about good luck and prosperity. Rossbach's full consulting calendar is proof that the latest dabbler in ancient Chinese philosophy is perhaps the least likely: corporate America. She has brought feng shui, a blend of Buddhism, Taoism, astrology, numerology, and common sense, to employees at <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley</b></a>, Ogilvy & Mather, Grey Advertising, and Peregrine Capital Management. <p>Rossbach recommends how and where walls, windows, and even buildings should be placed, but sometimes the feng shui solution is merely a matter of furniture placement: Make sure the door to your office opens fully, or it may block your career. <p>Because feng shui often involves little time and expense, it's quite easy to practice. Rossbach's latest book, "Living Color: Master Lin Yun's Guide to Feng Shui and the Art of Color" (Kodansha, $18), is just reaching bookstores. Who knows? Perhaps it's not the weak dollar or the unpredictable stock market that's thwarting you after all. Maybe it's just the direction your chair is facing.<p><p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
