<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Warming to Cashmere</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Warming to Cashmere</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Warming to Cashmere</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>WARMING TO CASHMERE
What to look for when buying something warm and fuzzy.<p>By Tish Durkin<p>Cashmere, the champagne of cloth, has never come cheap, but this fall it will be even more of an extravagance as unprecedented demand sends the price of raw materials skyward. Here's what separates the cream from the crop: <p>A MONGOLIAN BIRTH CERTIFICATE. Long before it's spun into sweaters, cashmere gets its start as the thermal underwear of Kel goats, from -- you guessed it -- Kashmir. Though lushly lingeried goats can be found in a number of freezing, arid places, the best do their shivering in Inner Mongolia.<p>THE RIGHT FLUFF. The hand, or feel, of a good cashmere is soft. But soft is a theme with variations. The same tight weave that gives cashmere remarkable warmth for its weight also gives it a firmness of feel. How firm is up to you -- but the fabric should be far from flimsy. In the store, "it should look even and flat; the fibers should run in one direction," advises Pier Luigi Guerci, president of cashmere manufacturer Loro Piana USA, which wouldn't let a substandard strand near its warehouse.<p>PERFECT PURITY. Though good things can come from blending cashmere with silk or wool, the same can't be said of blending it with paper pulp or cat's hair. A 100 percent cashmere label should reassure you, but not if it's accompanied by a suspiciously low price. "If I saw 100 percent cashmere for $100," says Luigi Leonardi, executive vice president of Maniffature Associate Cashmere USA, "I'd bet my last dollar that it's not pure."<p>AN UNIMPEACHABLE SOURCE. Don't assume that great designers have great taste in textiles -- if you want fine as well as famous, ask whose cloth Donna or Calvin cut from. Ballantyne or Loro Piana are among the very best answers. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

