		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Salad Days</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Salad Days</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>SALAD DAYS
A New York restaurant's recipe for lasting success.<p>By John House<p>Ever since it opened its doors in 1959 on the ground floor of Manhattan's landmark Seagram building, the Four Seasons has been serving up more than just meals. It's there that many diners first learned that not all American wines are sold by Gallo or the gallon; it's there that health-conscious dishes came to be known as spa cuisine (owners Tom Margittai and Paul Kovi registered the term as a trademark); and it's there that the first official "power lunch" was confidently consumed.<p>So it's no surprise that innovation is a prominent theme in John Mariani's "The Four Seasons: The History of America's Premier Restaurant" (Crown, $35), written with Four Seasons general manager Alex von Bidder and published this month. Undeniably, the book is in one sense a valentine, an extra-large tip from media magnate Si Newhouse (who owns Crown) to the people who usually feed him at midday -- along with many of his higher-placed employees. But Mariani's research makes his effort something else as well. In telling the story of architect Philip Johnson's only restaurant commission, a place designed to serve as an expression of "power, money, modernism, sophistication, eccentricity, and iconoclasm," Mariani provides an overview of American eating habits in this century and a sociological gloss on New York since the 1950s, those innocent days when fish was still cooked all the way through and the greens preferred by educated palates were Bibb and oak-leaf lettuce.<p>Given the restaurant's long standing as a stage for displays of wealth and business might, Mariani (a regular contributor to Worth) had no shortage of scenes to recount, such as the original owners' wrangling with Mark Rothko over a series of paintings for the private dining room and the celebrity-stocked party for John F. Kennedy's 45th birthday. There are also a number of revealing observations -- for instance, the fact that the $4.5 million price tag for the Four Seasons (which at one point was in danger of being named Season-o-Rama or Season-Go-Round) was $1.5 million more than the cost of the Guggenheim Museum, which opened the same year. And what would a book like this be without recipes? Try to tackle the curried swordfish and pickled vegetables or a cappuccino souffle, and revel in how powerful it makes you feel<p>--------------------------------------<p>Bite Map: 
A Cross-Country Guide to Eating Lunch<p>By Jason Nixon<p>The power lunch may have been invented at the Four Seasons in New York City, but it's being eaten around the country.<p>ATLANTA. Downtown, the City Grill (50 Hurt Plaza, Suite 200; 404-524-2489) is popular with politicians and the financial crowd. Ted Turner has been known to take his lunch there, too. A hipper, less clubby choice is the Buckhead Diner (3073 Piedmont Road; 404-262-3336), where Elton John, Halle Berry, Whitney Houston, and top executives from nearby Coca-Cola dig into grilled salmon BLT's.<p>BOSTON. Locke-Ober (3-4 Winter Place; 617-542-1340), over 100 years old and still in its prime, continues to pack in the Brahmins and those who wish they were. Aujourd'Hui at the Four Seasons hotel (200 Boylston Street; 617-451-1392) and Lydia Shire's Biba (272 Boylston Street; 617-426-7878) are also big draws.<p>CHICAGO. In the River North area, locals flock to Gordon (500 North Clark; 312-467-9780), where chef Mark Dorian, formerly of Manhattan's Union Square Cafe, lures the power-hungry with artichoke fritters and roasted-vegetable sandwiches. Catch 35 (35 West Wacker Drive; 312-346-3500) and Nick's Fishmarket (1 First National Plaza; 312-621-0200) are other contenders.<p>DALLAS. At lunch, most of the power is wielded at private clubs like the Tower Club or the Crescent Club. Nonmembers prefer the Mansion on Turtle Creek (2821 Turtle Creek Boulevard; 214-559-2100) for red jalapeno Caesar salad with shrimp diablo "tamale."<p>DETROIT. The Rattlesnake Club (300 River Place; 313-567-4400) brings executives from the adjacent Stroh Brewery for Lake Erie pickerel and, if they are feeling indulgent, white chocolate ravioli. Detroit mayor Dennis Archer prefers the more opulent Opus 1 (565 East Larned Street; 313-961-7766).<p>LOS ANGELES. Robert Shapiro and Alan Dershowitz have strategized at the Grill on the Alley (9560 Dayton Way; 310-276-0615), the Beverly Hills boite modeled after San Francisco's famous Tadich Grill. Mortons (8764 Melrose Avenue; 310-276-5205) was strictly an evening spot until it recently changed locations. Now Sharon Stone, Bill Block of ICM, and Lili Zanuck can be seen munching on Thai chicken salad at lunch.<p>SAN FRANCISCO. Wolfgang Puck's L.A.-based Spago is as famous for its celebrity clientele as its California pizzas; Postrio (545 Post Street; 415-776-7825) imports Puck's winning formula to the Bay Area. <p>WASHINGTON, D.C. It's strictly surf and turf for the capital's powerful lunchers. Perhaps the hottest seat in town right now is "Rosty's Rotunda": Dan Rostenkowski's table at Morton's of Chicago (3251 Prospect Street NW; 202-342-6258). <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
