	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Psychic Forecasting</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Psychic Forecasting</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Psychic Forecasting</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>PSYCHIC FORECASTING<p>By Ellen Tien<p>You are not a particularly mystical person -- the only crystals you own are affixed to Swiss precision timepieces. So when a friend recounts an experience with a psychic reader, you're naturally skeptical. Recently, I had my first mental online experience with the other world. My personal accessor: Mary T. Browne, a Manhattan psychic and author. Her client list, she says, is long and includes corporate CEOs, presidents of countries, a slew of muckety-mucks in finance and publishing, and an Oscar-winning actor. <p>HOW IT WORKED: We met in the living room of her modest apartment, where she kindly offered me a spot of tea. Then she got straight to business. For roughly 60 minutes, I frantically scribbled notes as she gazed to her left and, without any clues or prompting from me, recited a dazzling array of info-bites about my life. After this mind-bending performance, she urged me to make inquiries. I asked if she had anything stronger than tea. <p>THE REALLY UNCANNY PART: She was disconcertingly accurate. She named the exact location of an apartment I was thinking of buying and warned me of plumbing problems that were later confirmed. She supplied (true) information about friends and relatives -- facts I hadn't previously known. She offered shrewd career and personal advice. <p>NET EFFECT: What the. . . ? The cynical New York brain doesn't really track stuff like this. Still, once I stopped searching for trick mirrors and strings, the session was highly enjoyable. My reading focused on the present with some forays into the past and a few projections into the foreseeable (for her, anyway) future. Browne does not dispense financial tips, nor will she issue direct orders. Rather, as with a doctor or lawyer, you're paying for expertise. She gives you her professional opinion; you do with it what you will. Granted, this is an inexact science. Then again, so is meteorology, and no one seems to be storming the Weather Channel, shrieking fraud. <p>THE UPSIDE: You leave with a clearer overview of yourself. A good reading is a self-affirming experience -- it untangles some of the bigger snarls in day-to-day life. Although the experience is not entirely unlike psychotherapy, a therapist concentrates on why it is, while a psychic identifies what it is. Also, a shrink makes you hunt for answers, whereas a psychic does the hard labor for you. <p>HOW TO MAXIMIZE THE UPSIDE: Don't play coy. When a doctor asks you where it hurts, you don't reply, "Maybe my shoulder, maybe not -- you tell me." <p>THE DOWNSIDE: You may not like what you hear. What's more, there are plenty of charlatans out there, so you have to choose wisely and well. <p>HOW TO MINIMIZE THE DOWNSIDE: Get referrals. In Browne's words, "This 1-800 stuff has got to stop! Forget fortune tellers in the yellow pages -- go to a metaphysical bookstore and do some homework." <p>WHEN TO GO: Most clients schedule appointments when they have an important decision to make. "If you need emotional help, see a psychologist," Browne advises. "But if you want some insight into the gift of prophecy, see a psychic -- seriously, respectfully, and with a sense of humor." <p>IS IT WORTH IT? In my case, yes indeedy. <p><p>WHAT IT COSTS:
-> $200 a session.<p>WHAT YOU MIGHT BUY INSTEAD:
-> One 50-minute personal prediction from a live psychic on the Psychic Hotline. 
-> Three sessions with a psychotherapist.
-> Twenty-five Magic 8 Balls. <p>BOTTOM LINE:
-> If you don't have a decade to spare on psychoanalysis (and you're not searching for your inner anything), a psychic reading can be the tonic for life's big decisions (Mary T. Browne, 212-242-6080).<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

