<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-No Man's Land</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>No Man's Land</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-No Man's Land</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>NO MAN'S LAND
The emerging cosmetics market for the other 49 percent.<p>By Gully Wells <p>If nature abhors a vacuum, then there is nothing more challenging to capitalism than a market in desperate need of saturation. When the guys in Atlanta who run <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a> look at a map of the world and see China, I think we all know what runs through their minds. And when the giant cosmetics companies look at the male half of the human race, a similar thought process takes place. There are literally millions of men out there who have yet to be converted to the true faith. Many men have been persuaded to buy aftershave and cologne, but apart from that, they are pretty basic animals: shampoo, deodorant, and shaving stuff.<p>Why are men such pitiful consumers when it comes to grooming products? Maybe they don't care what they look like (obviously untrue). Or perhaps they are less credulous than women are when it comes to advertising (c'mon). Since men are every bit as vain and deluded as women in other aspects of life, there must be some other explanation. I suspect the secret lies in borrowing: The reason men don't shop for cosmetics is that they use their significant others'. I'll admit to a bit of borrowing in my time. Somebody else's nice new razor is always useful, a firm toothbrush works wonders on mascara-clogged eyelashes, and Eau Sauvage has long been my perfume of choice. But it only recently occurred to me that this borrowing could be a two-way street (a concept that has not escaped marketing genius Calvin Klein, who launches CK One, a unisex fragrance, this month). After a few weeks of entirely random research among some of the men I'm acquainted with, here's what I discovered.<p>However much men care about their looks, they are mostly unwilling to spend more than a few minutes on a basic grooming routine. "How long is this going to take?" was the question I heard most often. When it comes to the newest wonders of the cosmetics business, alphahydroxy fruit acids, the answer is anything up to two months. These are the main components in Estee Lauder's skin treatment, Fruition, described by the company as a "megaleap into the future of skin care. . . a stratospheric fusion of nature and science only glimpsed in dreams." Unfortunately, it was only glimpsed on my husband's face for two consecutive nights, and the promised "42 percent increase in evenness of skin tone" sadly never materialized. The truth is that men crave instant gratification (no news to most women, I realize), so products that work in seconds, not months, seem to be the answer (by the way, Fruition does make an excellent shave cream). <p>Foaming cleansers that can be used in the shower while shaving -- like those made by Clarins, Shiseido, and Borghese -- were a big hit with the men I surveyed. The addition of a shaving brush brings back atavistic memories of old-fashioned barbershops. My initial polling showed that 86 percent of men have been known to borrow a moisturizer from a woman in their life. And when they are temporarily and inexplicably without a woman, they will actually go out and buy a moisturizer for themselves -- an encouraging sign. What they like is something light that also includes some sun protection, like Clarins Fluide Multi-Confort SPF 15. The other brand that seemed to work for men was Chanel, which probably has to do with the packaging. I suspect that most men go for outward appearance (another big surprise) and that Chanel and Prescriptives (plain gray and white) look better on the shelf than the gilt-encrusted packages of the more extravagant women's lines. <p>One area of men's faces that deserves attention is the eyes, which are always the first to go. Too little sleep, too much alcohol and smoke, and just too many years: It all adds up. But Clarins's Eye Contour Gel claims that it will "help reduce the appearance of puffiness and dark circles." The operative words are help and appearance, which is why my guinea pig, his tiny tube finished, threw in the towel and said he thought he'd rather start saving for the knife.<p>Which brings us abruptly back to reality. Men may be easing their way into the beauty business through women's products, but they will never be ideal customers. Impatient, craving the instant high (and, incidentally, horrified by what women are willing to spend on magic potions), they are not in this for the long haul. They are essentially '90s consumers: the basics, preferably of good quality, and then get me out of here. Looking at that map of the world, I think I'd put my money on Coke in China.<p><p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
