<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Chips off the Old Block</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Chips off the Old Block</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Chips off the Old Block</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>CHIPS OFF THE OLD BLOCK
Reissues of classic furnishings are affordable, but not as collectible.<p>By Susan Kuchinskas<p>Everything old is new again, literally, in the world of 20th-century furnishings. Since auction prices have soared and collectors have picked flea markets and antique stores clean of vintage pieces designed by masters like Stickley, Wright, and Eames, manufacturers are meeting consumer demand by making more. <p>Reproductions are good news for those who simply wish to curl up on an icon of modern design. But for collectors of vintage furnishings, this trend makes things a little trickier, calling into question the whole concept of an "original" piece. For the novice collector it's often difficult to tell the difference. When shopping, be sure to find out whether the piece is a knockoff or an officially sanctioned reproduction that bears the designer's imprimatur.<p>The past five years have brought reissues of Mission Oak furniture designed by Gustav and Leopold Stickley, silver tableware designed by William Spratling, and licensed reproductions of furniture, textiles, and accessories by Frank Lloyd Wright. Last January, Herman Miller reintroduced designs from the '40s and '50s by Charles and Ray Eames and George Nelson. <p>A recently made piece may cost more than a vintage one, according to Lisa Light of the Manhattan-based home-furnishings emporium Zona, because the cost of labor is higher today. But at least, as one collector says, it doesn't take longer to furnish your house than it does for your children to grow up. Want a Frank Lloyd Wright Husser House dining table with eight barrel chairs? No problem: You can order them for around $13,500 by calling the manufacturer. Compare this with the $442,500 Christie's got at auction for the original set in June 1993.<p>What's the difference between buying an Eames folding screen made in 1954 and the same screen made in 1994? The facile answer is about $2,700 (more for the vintage piece). But while the appearance may be identical except for signs of wear, variations in construction make repros unacceptable to the collecting purist. <p>Frank Lloyd Wright furniture is made by Cassina in the "aesthetic spirit" of his work, rather than as replicas, using fully contemporary construction methods and cherry wood. Arkitektura/In-Situ has produced Eero Saarinen-designed seating for several restaurants and adjusted the pitches of the chair backs for greater comfort. Modern glues and connections make them sturdier than the originals.<p>Construction of the 11-piece Heywood-Wakefield reproduction collection is a blend of old and new methods. While door hinges come from the original supplier, some designs are adapted, like increasing table sizes and adding a personal-computer option to a desk. "We're not aiming at the collectibles market," says Leonard Riforgiato of Heywood-Wakefield. Herman Miller is using a manmade fiber for the joints of the Eames folding screen and a different method of bonding the shock mount for the molded plywood chairs. Details like these should make it easier to tell the new products from the vintage. On the other hand, production of Spratling silver place settings and tableware remains practically unchanged from the '30s and '40s. Many of the original artisans still work in Spratling's Taxco, Mexico, factory. <p>Then there are the items that never went off the market. Alvar Aalto's Scroll Chair for ICF has been in continuous production in Finland since the '30s, made from trees in the same birch forest outside Helsinki, although the clear finish now has a different formula. Yet the chairs from the '30s and '40s are highly prized by serious collectors, even though they typically sell for less than new ones. <p>To ensure that buyers know what they're getting, some companies, like Stickley and Spratling, date each piece. The Frank Lloyd Wright Foundation's stamp clearly marks pieces as reproductions. But the distinction is not always so clear. The revived Heywood-Wakefield line is stamped with a mark very similar to the original. As it is, vintage collectors can be incredibly picky when trying to date things. "Some of our collectors are very detailed, very anal," says Dominic Longacre, owner of AD/50 in San Francisco. "Labels, colors, wood, glides, even the screw rubber mount, all those things make a chair worth more or less."<p>"This is a continuing problem in the business," says antiques dealer John Sikorski. "An educated collector might know the difference, but most people who are buying these collectibles are not necessarily aware of the fact that they changed the spring, or the color of the mark is different. The industry could make it much easier if there were a bold mark, but [some of] these outfits are trying to capitalize on a trendy situation." Sikorski, who hosts a radio show on WUFT-FM in Gainesville, Florida, often breaks the bad news to callers who are sure they've got a valuable original.<p>Of course, to the serious collector, becoming an expert on screw mounts or joints is half the fun. These die-hards spurn anything that wasn't produced in the era of its designer, and that should keep prices of the originals steady. In fact, the spate of reproductions is a good sign for collectors, according to Nancy McClelland, a vice president at Christie's auction house in New York City. "This should be encouraging to the marketplace, not threatening," she says. "I think it's a clear indication that the style is broadly recognized and appreciated and that it is here to stay."<p>Reissues of classic specimens may bolster the market for collectibles by increasing awareness and demand for the designs. Dealers hope sophisticated consumers will come to crave the level of workmanship shown in these archetypes. While true believers hold out for the patina factor, buyers more concerned with style than provenance might opt for the reintroductions, which, according to Riforgiato, may "stabilize some of the wackiness in the collectibles market."<p>Dealers say reproductions will probably never have the collectible value of the originals. Acquire them because you love them. It's also reassuring to know your furniture is replaceable. Go ahead, put your feet up.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

