	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Back to Glamour</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Back to Glamour</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Back to Glamour</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>BACK TO GLAMOUR
Diamonds become fashionable again.<p>By Giselle Benatar<p>Diamonds could be the first artifact of the flashy '80s to successfully shed the stigma of excess and become a signature of genuine style and authentic hipness. In today's glamour-obsessed fashion climate, the lustrous stones are again very much of the moment. <p>The blue-chip French fashion house Chanel recently launched an extravagant collection of fine jewelry based on original designs worn by its famous founder. The pieces will be sold in jewelry boutiques adjacent to the company's clothing stores at up to $500,000 (for an exotic diamond camellia necklace). "Chanel loved diamonds because they represent the highest value in the smallest volume," says spokeswoman Arlette Thebault.<p>A more casual approach to diamond classics comes from maverick American designer Marc Jacobs, the same man who turned grunge into a fashion statement. Jacobs's new line of diamond jewelry, available at Neiman Marcus, consists of delicate diamond clusters -- dazzling sprays of stars and moons or Arabic numerals. "The attitude here is very different from what I call those precious old-fashioned diamonds," says Jacobs. "I wanted to take this classic material and treat it in a way that's very mundane and looks almost thrown away." Jacobs even suggests women might use the cluster pins to advertise their telephone numbers, and at its June menswear collection, the cheeky Italian design team Dolce & Gabbana showed its controversial Mafioso-style men's suits with flashy diamond chokers (suggesting that diamonds may also be a man's best friend). <p>The new diamond jewelry might be fun to flaunt and beautiful to admire, but there's no guarantee it will make an equally alluring investment. Unlike "timeless" diamond pieces, the latest fashion-driven settings and stones may not retain their value over time. "If it's a fashion piece, you should buy it today because you want to wear it today," says Tom Heyman of the New York jeweler Oscar Heyman and Brothers. "With that type of piece there's no way to tell whether it's a lasting fashion or a flash in the pan." Given the temporary nature of fashion, in other words, even the eternal stones aren't necessarily forever.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
