<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Training Wheels</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Training Wheels</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
A new class of urban bikers is hitting the road -- but not, mind you, before going back to school.<p>By John Marchese<p>I was a mild one. I drove a sensible four-door foreign car, with the tires properly inflated and my seat belt buckled. High-altitude elevator riding was the closest I came to excitement in transport.<p>But lately, each time I noticed a gray hair or that another pair of pants had really shrunk, I got bike thoughts. For the first time, I caught myself staring at motorcycles as they passed -- not just cursing their noise but looking and longing and thinking: That could be me. It wasn't long before I met Paula.<p>"I have this romantic vision," said Paula Petrella, who works in the business-affairs department of a film-distribution company in Manhattan and was playing hooky for a day in order to learn how to ride a motorcycle. "You know, the whole fantasy -- the wind in my hair, the open road, all of it."<p>She didn't have to tell me. I was in class with her, another eager student taking a cram course in fantasy.<p>We were seated in plain brown metal folding chairs in the back room of Trama's Auto School in Queens, New York, listening to brief lectures and watching videotapes on the joys of motorcycling. It was the first of three grueling days of instruction offered by Trama and approved by the Motorcycle Safety Foundation.<p>Among my classmates were lawyers (including one who happily announced one morning that he'd been out the night before with clients who looked like the cast of The Godfather, Part IV), city bureaucrats, and composers. Not the sort of people who fit the image. But Marlon Brando's bad boy in The Wild One never was quite true, and in recent years the snarling face of biking has changed even more.<p>According to information compiled by <a name="NYSE:HDI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10706"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Harley-Davidson</b></a>, the average rider buying a bike is 38 years old and has a median income near $53,000. In big cities, upscale biker gangs with names like the Rolex Riders in Los Angeles and the Gotham City Riders in Manhattan have become common. The Gotham City Riders are Wall Street types who do such antisocial stuff as volunteering at a soup kitchen and roaring out to Kennedy Airport once a year to meet the first shipment of Beaujolais Nouveau.<p>In New York, the person to see to get the riding skills to join such a dastardly bunch is Gasper Trama (pronounced like trauma, which, he admits good-naturedly, is an unfortunate name for someone in his line of work)<p>Trama has been teaching motorcycle skills since 1966 and is licensed by the MSF. His three-day beginner course costs $350. (For information, call 718-847-2015.) He supplies the bikes and helmets; no special clothing is required, though leather is always appropriate. In 50 states around the country, courses like these are offered in affiliation with the state, and usually prices are lower, averaging around $150, according to an MSF spokeswoman. The foundation has a hotline number (800-447-4700) to refer prospective riders to a local course. Also, Discover Today's Motorcycling (800-833-3995) will send booklets on purchasing, insuring, financing, and learning to ride a motorcycle.<p>Gasper Trama is a small, perky New Yorker with the bouncy personality of a Catskills comedian. He's also got about as many corny jokes, most of which pertain to what will happen to you if you do something stupid while riding a motorcycle. Trama has become something of a motorcycle instructor to the stars, having taught Alan Alda, Scott Baio, and Sonia Braga for film roles. Other students for his private lessons (which cost $45 an hour) have included Rolling Stone publisher Jann Wenner and a member of the Forbes family, whose patriarch turned motorcycling into a form of business and self-promotion.<p>A few years ago, before she was planning to leave for a trip around the world on a motorcycle with investor and author Jim Rogers, Tabitha Estabrook took Trama's course (see sidebar "Tour de World" below). She'd never driven a bike before and was about to embark on a 65,000-mile journey that would get her into the Guinness Book of World Records. "If you're going to do it," she says, of learning to ride a motorcycle generally, not necessarily for long distances, "make sure you take this course. There's no other way to learn these things, except by lots of errors on the road. And I think it's always better to have more trial and less error."<p>Three days with Trama on an old coast guard airfield in Brooklyn taught me that riding a motorcycle can be trying, mostly because riding is paradoxical. It is both easier and harder than you would think. The thing that at first seems difficult is actually pretty easy -- keeping the motorcycle up. As long as there's power from the throttle, the bike wants to stand. The hardest thing is keeping that power under control. Working the throttle, the clutch, the brakes, and the shift takes coordination of both hands and feet -- like playing the drums. <p>"Is it challenging to ride a motorcycle?" Trama asks. "Every second!"<p>I estimated that during Trama's course, I spent 57,600 seconds on a bike -- a full 16 hours. The MSF requires its course providers to supply a total of at least 15 hours (class and riding) of instruction. Trama takes it up to about 24 hours. He builds skills like a kid playing with blocks. We started on the the bikes by pushing one another around and coasting. And we spent what seemed at first like an inordinate amount of time learning the proper sequence to turn the bike on and off. There was a lot of riding around in circles, just to get the feel of easy turning. We spent hours learning to stop correctly.<p>But by the third day of the course, when we were speeding through turns and veering quickly to avoid simulated obstacles, the need for such simple skills became obvious. When the complexity of the riding situations increases, instinct must take over. If you've learned the correct way right from the beginning, you're way ahead. I can't imagine that people ride without a course like this. Tabitha Estabrook said she'd been riding every day for a year when she encountered an unexpected hairpin turn in an Australian beach town. One of Trama's drills came back to her, taking her safely through the corner.<p>A few weeks have gone by since I learned to ride, and my fantasies these days focus on the classified pages, where I'm searching for a certain BMW cycle for a good price. Now if I could just find someone to teach me how not to turn gray.<p>Sidebar:
Tour de World
---------------
"Whenever I travel," writes Jim Rogers, "because of who I am, I notice promising investment opportunities."<p>In 1990, at the age of 47, Rogers decided to really do some traveling -- scooting on his BMW motorcycle across Europe, Asia, Africa, Australia, and South America, and back home to the Upper West Side of Manhattan. He rode with a tall, leggy blonde half his age named Tabitha Estabrook and with a world view formed by a small-town southern boyhood, education at Yale and Oxford, and years of driving himself to success on Wall Street.<p>The result of this two-year, 65,000-mile journey is "Investment Biker: On the Road With Jim Rogers" (Random House, $25). The book is part adventure story, part travelogue, part love story, and part primer on world markets. What Rogers lacks in skills as a close observer and a writer he makes up for in his feel for the intersecting lines of culture, history, geography, and economics. And the book is propelled by the sheer preposterousness of his journey.<p>Whether dodging bureaucrats in China, land mines in Angola, civil war in Central America, or traffic jams in Philadelphia, Rogers, like many travel writers before him, was ultimately looking for an epiphany: "I wanted to scrap my old life completely and start a new one. If I could just find the right road. . . "<p>He didn't quite get an epiphany, but he picked up a few useful things. Rogers, who is frequently seen discussing the markets on CNBC, now has money in a number of countries he biked through.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
