	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Timeless Watches</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Timeless Watches</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>TIMELESS OPTIONS
Here's what to look for when buying a mechanical timepiece.<p>By Tish Durkin<p>Quartz watches are tellers of time, but mechanical watches, like handblown glass in a paper-cup world, are pieces of history, works of art -- and, of course, symbols of status. Here's what makes them tick:<p>BATTERIES NOT INCLUDED. Mechanical watches pack their power in a mainspring, wound either manually or automatically -- by handshaking, wrist-flipping, or finger-pointing.<p>WHEELS IN MOTION. Mechanical watches keep time via a positively Pentagonian maze of wheels, gears, and gadgets -- at least 130 of them, not including "complications" (chronograph, perpetual calendar, minute repeater ... ). <p>HUMAN HANDS. Quality of workmanship doesn't define the mechanical watch -- but it certainly distinguishes it from a quartz one. All high-end mechanical watches are finished with painstaking care by highly trained, surgeon's-handed watchmakers, not too different -- in spirit at least -- from the Swiss cabinotiers of the 18th century.<p>A KING'S RANSOM. A Patek Philipe gentleman's watch starts around $7,800 and can run to $400,000. And that's not counting the cost of cleaning it every few years -- up to $2,000. "The more you pay for a watch," says David Marold, general manager of UTAC America, distributor of such luminaries as Bertolucci and Breguet, "the more it costs to maintain it."<p>AN ILLUSTRIOUS PAST. There is something deeply right about a watch that has kept time in essentially the same way for hundreds of years. "A mechanical watch," says veteran clock watcher Mort Gershman, is "a true watch, a watch in its purest form."<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
