	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Right Under Our Noses</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Right Under Our Noses</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Right Under Our Noses</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>RIGHT UNDER OUR NOSES
Soured by wine speculating, savvy buyers are sniffing out bargains that are selling (surprise!) at retail.<p>By John Mariani <p>Back in the woozy, high-flying days of the 1980s, wines appreciated like just about everything else. Then, like just about everything else, they didn't.<p>And those who bought wine futures -- wines not yet released, purchased in advance at the wine store on the assumption they will cost much more upon release and later on -- found themselves holding on to cases of wines that never grew in value. "The futures market has gone bust," says Peter D. Meltzer, writer for Wine Enthusiast. "The last three vintages in Bordeaux -- 1991, 1992, and 1993 -- all turned out below expectations in terms of quality, so there's no point in shelling out dollars now in the belief that such wines will go up in price. There's just too much wine around right now."<p>In an ironic twist, this slump in the futures market has sent savvy oenophiles into wine shops in search of bargains on less hyped wines that offer not just splendid drinking for the long term but prices you may not see again in the future. "There's a lot of good wines from unfashionable vintages that have developed well," insists Darrell Corti of Corti Brothers in Sacramento, California, "and it's our job as wine sellers to find such wines. The '86 Burgundies were not fashionable when they came out, but many of them have matured into wonderful wines."<p>Corti is currently selling Rene Engel's '86 Echezeaux and Clos de Vougeot for about $40 -- below what they cost when they first came out in most wine stores. "Even the much-criticized '84 vintage in Bordeaux has turned up wines like Chateau Talbot and Gruaud-Larose that were hard, mean, and nasty when they were released but are now coming around beautifully."<p>Since the wines of Bordeaux have for so long been the benchmark for wine collectors, that is where many of the bargains lie in today's saturated wine market. Robert Parker, publisher of the immensely influential newsletter the Wine Advocate, notes that there are still large stocks of 1988 Bordeaux out there just ripe for the grabbing. <p>"They were not at the level of the '89s or '90s, so they were dumped to raise cash," Parker says. "Now they are very reasonably priced, especially those from the northern Medoc and Pomerol. It's a classic vintage, and they'll easily go on for another ten years."<p>Wine merchant Michael Aaron, chairman of Manhattan's prestigious Sherry-Lehmann, feels this is a great time to stock up on bargains from Bordeaux. "If you're looking for good wines to drink now and lay down for the future and aren't interested in investment, there are some fabulous wines out there," he says. "I'd buy the '83 Talbot at $25 a bottle and Ducru-Beaucaillou for $35. Even the highly regarded '85 Talbot is now just $23, Ducru is $40, and Duhart-Milon is $25. These wines will very soon disappear from the market, so now's the time to get them." Last year the retail list prices for the same '85 vintages were, respectively, $35, $51, and $34.<p>For the wine lover willing to make the calls and snoop around in reputable shops, there are now some remarkable old wines that may sell for even less than more recent vintages.<p>"Buying futures is stupid unless you can buy them inexpensively," says Corti. "And the rare, expensive, much-hyped wines of the past always find their way back into the trade. Right now you can find wines like Richebourg '61 for $3,000 a case and La Tache '59 for $4,200. That may sound expensive, but it's actually less money than the '89s are currently selling for."<p>And what of wines from countries other than France, including those from America's own backyard? Most wine experts shrug and say that California wines are made to be sold and drunk at the time they are released and are not for putting away. "California whites should have a pull date on them," jokes Parker, who thinks the best bargains out of California right now are '90 and '91 zinfandels (though he'd avoid the '89 and '88 vintages). "The so-called 'Rhone Rangers' [California wines made in the style of France's Rhone Valley with the same grapes, such as Syrah, Mourvedre, and Grenache] are usually made by maverick producers and the wines have less prestige than cabernet sauvignons, so they're selling cheaply, for $8 to $15."<p>There are also a number of beautifully crafted Italian wines now priced to sell in an oversupplied market. Old Brunello di Montalcino used to cost $40, $50, and up until more modern wineries started to produce lighter, fruitier versions, so that now an '88 Brunello from a fine producer like Altesino, at $26, is a steal for a wine that will get better and better through the next decade.<p>Since Italy's DOCG (Denominazione di Origine Controllata e Garantita) laws prohibit producers from labeling wines like Brunello, Barolo, or Chianti Classico if they don't meet certain quality standards in certain vintages, a great deal of good wine from the top producers' very best vineyards must be sold off under inexpensive, secondary labels. "People were calling 1992 a disastrous vintage" in Tuscany, says Corti. "So a great Chianti producer like Antinori puts his best wines under his lesser 'Santa Cristina' label because he can't sell them as 'Chianti Classico.' Believe me, at about $9 a bottle, these will be terrific buys and make for good drinking for years to come." <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
