	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Blues Power</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Blues Power</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>BLUES POWER
From postage stamps to restaurants, the blues is becoming big business.<p>By David Hochman<p>Suddenly, millions of Americans are getting the blues. This month, the U.S. Postal Service is issuing eight 29-cent stamps honoring legendary blues musicians like Muddy Waters, Howlin' Wolf, and Billie Holiday. <p>The first-class tribute arrives just as the blues is becoming big business across the country. Hohner USA, the world's largest maker of harmonicas -- so closely associated with the wail of the blues -- has almost doubled its sales since the mid-'80s. The Blues Foundation in Memphis, Tennessee, reports that since 1990, attendance at blues festivals has increased more than 1,000 percent, while the number of blues albums being released annually is up more than 50 percent. <p>"We're witnessing an extraordinary return to roots music right now," says Hard Rock Cafe founder Isaac Tigrett, whose House of Blues clubs in New Orleans, Los Angeles, and Cambridge, Massachusetts, are helping thirtysomething music lovers recover from a decade-long barrage of techno music, fluffy pop patter, and hip-hop. "When MTV came along, it cut off the baby-booming market," says Tigrett, whose partner in the venture is Blues Brother Dan Aykroyd. "Now people are desperate for something that's real, has depth, history, and emotion. That's why they turn to the blues." House of Blues showcases both local talent and legends. <p>Blues guitarist B. B. King also recognizes the selling power of the blues. After the success of his Blues Club and Restaurant in Memphis and Universal City Walk in Los Angeles, King's partner, Tommy Peters, says they will open clubs across the country. "We're not out to change the world," he says. "We just know that listening to the blues does something wonderful to people, and we'd like to spread that around." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
