<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Well Mannered</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Well Mannered</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
London's townhouse hotels are in a class by themselves.<p>By Randall Fuller<p>With room rates often beginning well above $300 a night, London's premium hotels are enough to give anyone a stiff upper lip. Fortunately, there is a new class of small, stylish hotel that offers the same bespoke British service and more charm -- for about a third less cost. Dubbed townhouse hotels, these newcomers attract traveling cognoscenti such as Kevin Costner, Bette Midler, and Ralph Lauren. Discreet from the outside -- often a bronze plaque is all that distinguishes them from their Victorian neighbors -- their rooms are the perfect setting for sumptuous, Anglo-style pampering.<p>After visiting more than 25 of the London upstarts, we chose 8 of the best, including the one generally credited with starting it all, Blakes (44-71-370-6701; doubles about $187). Opened by fashion designer Anouska Hempel (Lady Weinberg) in 1983, this South Kensington mansion is still the benchmark by which others are judged. The compact lobby -- a tropical fantasy of rattan furniture -- sets the tone for each of the 50 rooms, which Hempel has treated as 50 theater sets for her active imagination. The results have attracted the fashion aristocracy (Gianni Versace and Issey Miyake are regulars) and those they dress.<p>The Pelham (44-71-589-8288; doubles from $216) is just a short walk away from Royal Albert Hall. Upon entering, you immediately notice the umbrellas lined up in anticipation of blustery English weather. Dozens of such comforting details grace the 37 rooms here: The drawing room, paneled in 18th-century pine, is redolent of apples; a complimentary leather bookmark accompanies the wide selection of books on your nightstand; and the mahogany-trimmed bathtub with heated towel racks is perfectly designed to soak away your jet lag.<p>One of the newest townhouse hotels is the Franklin (800-473-9487; doubles about $202), an impressive three-house establishment just around the corner from fashionable Brompton Cross. David Naylor-Leyland and Alasdair Hadden-Paton, who also own Egerton House down the street, have outfitted the Franklin with the kind of period detail Yanks have come to expect in a Merchant-Ivory production. Secretarial services are also available, making it easy to conduct business in Edwardian style. Request room No. 11 for its French windows overlooking the lovely enclosed Egerton Garden.<p>The 25-room Draycott (44-71-730-6466; doubles about $225) has a light-filled lounge for sipping drinks and junior suites that feel like guest bedrooms in a country manor. Guests have included actresses Uma Thurman and Penelope Ann Miller and photographer Annie Leibowitz. Visitors will appreciate complimentary memberships to a health club and the tony Vanderbilt Tennis Club, as well as nanny service.<p>Around the corner, on the site of what was once the Chelsea Cricket Grounds, is Eleven Cadogan Gardens (44-71-730-3426; doubles about $198). Housed in four red-brick mansions, the hotel's 60 rooms attract film stars and diplomats. Perhaps it's the ineffable atmosphere of a private ancestral home: Eleven Cadogan Gardens is crammed with overstuffed chairs, imperious grandfather clocks, and oil paintings of dour grande dames perched above the wainscoting. Unlike such homes, however, this one provides a chauffeured Rolls-Royce to guests running late to the theater; just call room service.<p>The Beaufort (44-71-584-5252; doubles about $238), located in a leafy cul-de-sac less than 100 yards from Harrods, has carved out a niche for itself as a haven for business travelers, especially women. The Beaufort's billing system is unique to the townhouse category: A single rate includes all drinks (including champagne), breakfast, and health club. The hotel also employs the almost unheard-of practice of billing telephone calls at cost.<p>Chelsea is still London's nexus of money and fashion, so it's not surprising that two of the most imaginative hotels are located here. The whimsical Sloane Hotel (44-71-581-5757; doubles about $180), whose postmodern lobby (picture a leopard-skin sofa, stacks of antique Vuitton luggage, and a Napoleonic uniform hanging opposite the marble fireplace) is but a harbinger for the ten highly variegated rooms. The owner, Sue Rogers, has handpicked the hundreds of antiques throughout the hotel, but for enough money you can acquire her impeccable taste: Every stick of furniture in the hotel can be purchased and shipped home.<p>Finally, there is the muy trendy Sydney House (44-71-376-7711; doubles about $165). Try room No. 11, a tongue-in-cheek take on British imperialism, with cane furniture, tiger-skin pillows, and prints of Victorian-era Egypt composed as though in a fashion shoot. There's a room in the basement dining area set up for business meetings, and "deep cleansing and stress-reduction treatments" for hair can be arranged through a nearby salon. Be sure to request a room away from noisy Sydney Street.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

