<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Top To Bottom</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Top To Bottom</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The lowdown on five invigorating new convertibles.<p>By Stephan Wilkinson<p>In a world filled with soap-bar sedans and can't-tell-'em-apart sport utility vehicles, a convertible can put playfulness and distinction into what might otherwise be just another rolling appliance. It's why ragtop drivers often wave to each other, a revival of the rite in which 1950s sports-car owners indulged as they declared their individuality.<p>Your hand won't get very tired: Only about 1.8 percent -- 155,000 -- of the cars sold in the United States last year were convertibles, so you'll be a member of an exclusive club. Still, not counting aftermarket customizations or such six-digit anomalies as the $269,000 Rolls-Royce Corniche, there are 20 production convertibles available to domestic car shoppers this summer, up from nearly zero in the mid-1970s, when manufacturers' fears of sweeping regulations on rollover safety stampeded them into discontinuing drop-top development. Here are five worth owning.<p>
MAZDA MIATA - base price $17,000<p>Mazda's biggest challenge with this latter-day classic is how to renew it annually without infringing on what is already a near-perfect two-seat roadster design. For this, the Miata's fifth year, the company has added an invisible 200cc to the engine displacement, which ups the horsepower and torque some 10 percent, but nobody has messed with the stunningly clean styling or simple interior. In some cars, you can go 90 and think you're doing 60; the Miata's strength is that 60 feels like 90, with your elbow inches from the yellow line and your butt back near the rear wheels. Still, the Miata is a toy car. Unless you're in high school, you won't consider it a primary or even a secondary vehicle, since the trunk is big enough for only a backpack and there's barely room in the cockpit for two seats. If you have teenage kids, buy it for them so you can borrow it once in a while.<p>
VOLKSWAGEN CABRIO - base price $19,975<p>When convertibles slowly returned to the market in the late 1970s, the Volkswagen Rabbit soft top, destined to be the valley girl's chosen mount, was the first modern one. The new-for-'95 VW Cabrio -- a convertible Golf -- inherits that original Rabbit's spunk, style, practicality, and value. You'll never mistake its tall, chunky bulk and psychedelic seat fabrics for a domestic or Japanese product -- the Cabrio is decidedly Euro-brash -- but it's an honest four-seater. It offers the security of a relatively unobtrusive roll bar and is suffused with a delightful lightness of touch, steering, and handling. While its four-cylinder, 115-horsepower engine hardly makes it a high-performance car, agile responsiveness and supple handling make the VW Cabrio far more fun to drive than it deserves to be.<p>
BMW 325i - base price $38,800<p>The current three-series BMW is the best-handling production car in the world, so finely sized, tuned, and balanced that it redefines four-wheel precision. The six-cylinder engine is a jewel, virtually a turbine with pistons, and the lined cabriolet top is Germanic in fit and operation. Twist a single release handle, push a button, and the windows partially retract while the top slides automatically into its metal-lidded boot. Pedestrians will applaud, but if 40 grand seems a stiff initiation fee, BMW recently introduced the identically bodied 318i convertible for a base price of $29,900 with a 1.8-liter four-cylinder engine and manual top.<p>
PORSCHE 911 CARRERA CABRIOLET - base price $68,200<p>Porsche's rear-engine, air-cooled staple, the 911, reengineered and restyled for the 1995 model year, is two machines: a sober, tractable around-town car at ordinary speeds, and a crazed race car when pushed anywhere in the direction of the rather extreme limits of its performance. If the BMW is a scalpel, the Carrera can be a Glock 9mm. Don't fool around with it if you don't know what you're doing. As a convertible, the Carrera provides a top-down driving experience close to what you'd have gotten at Le Mans or Sebring in the good old days -- but in a car you can also drive to the mall.<p>
JAGUAR XJS - base price $79,950<p>The XJS is less the inheritor of classic Jag roadsters' genes than it is a modern-day Duesenberg: the most mass, metal, and hood length that can be set aside for the ostentatious carriage of two individuals. (The vestigial back '"seats'" are good only for parcels and Yorkies.) In ordinary driving conditions, it quickly becomes apparent that this is a big car, with reason to require the torque of a six-liter, 278-horsepower V12 engine, redesigned for '94. At 55 mph, the XJS has all the panache and best qualities of a '60s Caddy convertible. Urge it anywhere toward triple-digit speeds on an empty two-lane, however, and you'll experience the quality that makes Jaguars so special: the sinuous, silky handling and supple road holding that turns a two-and-a-quarter-ton boulevard boar into the ride of a lifetime.<p><p>When convertible fever strikes, it's time to get a grip. The perceived need to drive around in an automobile that can be reopened with a steak knife in order to take fullest advantage of melanoma opportunities and engage in face-to-face repartee with squeegee men has created a considerable fleet of ragtops that, after the first 3,000 miles, are never again driven alfresco. "A convertible is the perfect rental car,'" my all-too-practical wife insists. '"You drive around Miami with the top down for two days, turn it in at the airport on Monday morning, and you're all done."<p>That's not bad advice: Consider renting a convertible -- any convertible -- for a weekend before you take the plunge. You might find that not being able to hear the radio, re-erecting the top every time you park at the mall, and driving with the sun in your eyes half the time gets old fast. Then again, you might not.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
