<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-The Virtual Roller Coaster</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-The Virtual Roller Coaster</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Laurence Hooper<p>Used to be I was scared of roller coasters -- made so by my mother, who warned once that screaming curves and sickening drops were a sure way to trigger hidden heart defects. Only on pain of teen ridicule did I finally break with her advice. I recall it as I recall other first times: excruciating in buildup, exhilarating in release, and over far too soon. As my car slowed to a halt, I knew my mother was wrong. Roller coasters are about life, not death.<p>No wonder my heart fluttered, then, upon learning about a new type of roller coaster, Back to the Future: The Ride. The high-tech coaster fuses a movie with a flight simulator to immerse passengers in a make-believe world -- virtual reality, in a way, but without the goofy goggles. Speed and thrills are still the drug. But participants never actually move: They "ride" through a movie that streams around them as their car is jolted by a moving platform. The hurtling sensation is so convincing that some may retch with motion sickness. Not even a real heart defect could stop me from trying this.<p>Such futuristic rides are popping up all over -- in theme parks, obviously, but also in casinos. Steven Spielberg will unveil a Jurassic Park ride before long, taking the form to new heights. Right now, however, the quintessential version is the Back to the Future ride, the main draw at the Universal Studios theme parks in Orlando, Florida, and Hollywood. For me, it was the sole reason to visit Universal Studios. That meant I would pay $29.95 and stand in line for 90 minutes, all for a ride that lasted just about 5 minutes.<p>Back to the Future begins entertaining riders while they're still in line. Televisions go behind the scenes of the eponymous hit movie and its two sequels and also set up the ride's premise -- that riders are 21st-century volunteers in a time-travel experiment. Amusing signs deconstruct 21st-century gadgets, including the time-traveling DeLorean car used in the ride. One snag: If the wait is more than 40 minutes or so, the line snakes beyond this waiting area. On my first visit, this meant my friends and I had to kill almost an hour doing some low-tech chatting.<p>Once inside the waiting area, though, things go quickly. Somehow the line never stops moving, and the patter from the TVs is soothing and sometimes funny. The last 20 minutes or so are spent inside the main pavilion where the ride's plot unfolds: Biff Tannen, the heavy from the movies, is running amok in the building. As ride time approaches, eight "volunteers" are ushered into an intimidating staging area where their task becomes clear: They must chase Biff and his stolen DeLorean through time and bring him (you guessed it) back to the future.<p>Anyone who's seen the movies will remember that the DeLorean is rigged so it can fly. This makes for a truly thrilling ride. Imagine a darker, scarier version of the famous IMAX movie To Fly, but with viewers physically thrown around by each bone-juddering turn, lurching dip, and terrifying crash. The feeling of motion is utterly convincing. When the DeLorean "brakes," riders are thrown forward just as in a car that has been speeding. When it plummets from the sky, they instinctively brace just as in a plunging roller coaster. Some effects are a tad cheesy, but the overall feel is exactly as intended: Riders are inside a movie, participating in the chase scene. By ride's end, I felt drained by an experience like none I'd ever had before. And I was ready for more.<p>WHAT YOU GET: The best roller coaster ride of your life and a glimpse into entertainment's future. Also, entrance to everything else at Universal Studios.<p>EXTRAS: Souvenir T-shirt, $14.95; "acid hat" from the second Back to the Future movie, $19.95; toy remote-control DeLorean, $49.95. <p>WHAT YOU MIGHT BUY INSTEAD: Entry to Six Flags Magic Mountain park for Batman the Ride, a state-of-the-art "real" coaster, plus a small snack. Two thirds of a copy of <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>'s Flight Simulator computer game. Nine rentals of the Top Gun video, plus popcorn. Twenty-three miles in a New York City cab.<p>BOTTOM LINE: If you've never done it before, it's worth every penny. But a second visit reveals that the experience doesn't have the repeat power of either of its components, a roller coaster or a blockbuster movie. Wait instead for Jurassic Park: The Ride.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

