<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Simply Devine</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Simply Devine</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
By Francis Gasparini<p>It's said that everything comes back in style if you wait long enough. Monks and nuns have waited several hundred years to become au courant again, but from clothes to music to leisure time, the contemplative life (or at least the contemplative lifestyle) is finally making a comeback.<p>The revival was first seen on fashion runways, with loose flowing garb based on monastery wear created by designers like Donna Karan, Geoffrey Beene, and Calvin Klein. The interest has also fueled the resurgence of medieval plainsong: <a name="NYSE:SNE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sony</b></a> Classical, Erato, and Angel Records have all released Gregorian chant albums; Angel's offering, Chant, has sold over a million copies and reached the top ten on the Billboard pop chart.<p>The new monasticism is not solely a Catholic or even a Christian phenomenon. In the mountains of California's Ventana Wilderness, the Soto Zen Buddhist monastery Tassajara (408-659-2229) offers restorative hot springs as well as an introduction to non-Western methods of meditation. Rooms at Tassajara range from spartan wooden cabins to antique-furnished stone rooms whose patios offer sweeping views. Guests can participate in workshops on yoga and vegetarian cooking or simply relax and enjoy the setting. "We get lots of high-powered executive types who are escaping their cellular phones," says Jim Jordan, Tassajara's treasurer.<p>In Darien, Connecticut, the Catholic Sisters of Saint Brigitta run the Vikingsborg Guest House (203-655-1068) as a sort of blessed bed and breakfast for the world-weary. Like many apostolic retreats, Vikingsborg offers few diversions besides optional masses. Vikingsborg and Tassajara are also ideal for reflecting on the significance of monk mania. Does it signal a reawakening of spirituality, or is it merely another fad?<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

