	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Not Garden Variety</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Not Garden Variety</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1994
Worth magazine/Options<p>NOT GARDEN VARIETY
How do vegetable chips taste? We rate the crop.<p>By Lauren Picker<p>Colorful chips made from vegetables are mushrooming in popularity, snagging gourmet market shelf space, and gracing the plates of many trendy restaurants. While the latest snack-food fad commands only a few million dollars in annual revenue so far -- peanuts compared to the $4.4 billion potato-chip market -- veggie chips are quickly "establishing a niche in the market," says Al Rickard of the Snack Food Association. With an unearned healthful image and the aesthetic appeal (and sometimes the taste) of potpourri, veggie chips offer a new frontier for snackers who don't mind the bite of high prices. A taste test, from yuca to just plain yuck:<p>TERRA CHIPS (*****) Founded by a pair of New York City caterers who offered veggie chips in lieu of crudites, this brand boasts sales that are doubling yearly. No wonder: Its award-winning batata, parsnip, taro, and yuca chips ($4.79 for six ounces) are crisp, crunchy, and not too salty -- pleasing to the eye and the palate. A new flavor, spiced sweet potato ($2.99 for six ounces), has real zing.<p>BARBARA'S (****) Way ahead of the curve with visually striking sweet-potato chips a decade ago, Barbara's chips ($1.99 to $2.49 for five ounces) remain a mixed bag. The sweet-potato chips are yammy but hardly yummy, while tortilla chips made with corn, brown rice, and beans are unremarkable. Still, Barbara's True Blue potato chips are truly delicious, and the crunchy taro flavor, sold under the Ray's brand, is an all-round pip of a chip.<p>ROUTE 11 (****) This small fry's mixed-vegetable chips ($9 to $12 for a decorative six-ounce tin) are a tad less crisp and a touch more greasy than those of its nationally distributed competitors. Still, the manufacturer from Middletown, Virginia, holds its own.<p>PEDDLERS OFFBEAT ORIGINALS, sold as Harry's Garden Vegetable Chips on the East Coast (***) Sturdy but light, these veggie-flavored tortilla chips are great chips to dip. But the truth about these "incredibly hip chips" ($1.99 to $2.39 for eight ounces) is that some are hipper than others. Carrot caraway, for example, is way tasty -- even though it is mostly corn. But the pea-soup-colored mixed veggie is a dud. And of the mild bean, one taster said, "Yes, I can eat just one."<p>SARATOGA (** 1/2) Packaged in a shiny foil wrapper, these chips (about $4.50 for six ounces of mixed veggie; $3.25 for sweet potato) are a pale imitator of Terra Chips. Chewing them requires some serious jaw action -- and what exactly is a malanga, anyway?<p>MAINE COAST SEA VEGETABLES (*) These so-called sea chips ($1.98 for six ounces) are made from tortillas flavored with dulse and kelp seaweed. About as appetizing as they sound. Strictly for the hard-core health nut; all others snack at their own risk.<p>VEG OUT (*) The only good thing about these chips ($4.95 for 5.5 ounces), which include carrots, squash, and green beans, is that 0.5 percent of sales are donated to the National Foundation for Teaching Entrepreneurship. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

