	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Lobster Tale</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Lobster Tale</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Tish Durkin<p>Brittany's may be more delicate, and Australia's may have more spine, but when it comes to lobster this summer, if it's not from Maine, it's treason. Here's how to sink your claws (and teeth) into the ultimate Homarus americanus:<p>SHAKE THAT SHELLFISH. The lobster hunter's first task, says Eric Ripert, executive chef at New York's Le Bernardin, is to "check if it is alive" -- and literally kicking, a sure sign that it has eaten off the ocean floor in the not-too-distant past. Always pick your prospect up. The angrier it gets, the fresher it'll taste.<p>CHECK THE ANTENNAE. After about a month in the pen, lobsters start eating each other alive. They regenerate lost parts, but as Augusta Seafood's Florence Benedict says, "it's nice to know they have everything." Long antennae indicate that the owner hasn't been locked up forever.<p>HIT ON THE HAIRY-LEGGED WOMAN. Crustacean connoisseurs worship the lobster goddess for her roe, or coral, which turns red when cooked. You can tell it's a female by the hairs on the tiny paddle fins under her tail end. (Male lobsters are relatively bald.)<p>TAKE IT HARD. Hard-shell lobsters generally have more meat than the oft-shedding soft. To get a particularly hearty one, feel the first ring of the belly. "If it's firm and bumpy," says Ripert, "it's full of meat."<p>BEWARE OF THE FEATURE CREATURE. When you're hungry, a giant can be tempting. But before throwing money at that uber-crustacean, remember: quality before quantity. With lobsters over three pounds, the meat tends to be tough. Besides, you have to fit it in the pot.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
