<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Toying With Summer</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Toying With Summer</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
All you need for outdoor fun in the coming season <p>By Elizabeth Royte<p>SAILBOAT:
Racing with the wind
In 1992, William Koch and Buddy Melges successfully defended the America's Cup with their radical America3, a $5 million, 75-foot boat. Now ordinary yachtsmen can sail like a high-rolling consortium of investors and naval architects in the Melges 24, a racing sailboat with many of the innovations of the America3 but at one third the length and 1/130th the price. The Melges 24 has been clocked at more than 20 knots downwind, an impressive speed for a boat its size and shape. It handles with the responsiveness of a smaller boat, thanks to the 624-pound bulb at the end of its keel, which lowers the center of gravity and gives greater stability. The mast, keel fin, rudder, and tiller are made of carbon composites--lighter than metal but remarkably strong. It also has a kelp cutter, a steel blade that runs along 
the front of the keel and slices through accumulated aquatic debris, stuff that might, heaven forbid, slow you down. Melges Boatworks: 414-248-6621; $38,500.<p>
In-Line Skates
Protect the innocent<p>In-line skating is the fastest-growing sport in the country. Problem is, few of the newest devotees know how to stop. Rollerblade's new Active Braking Technology, available on five models, promises to take the terror out of terminating. It works like this: Instead of lifting the toes to activate the heel brake--the old method--the skater simply slides her braking foot forward. The change in foot angle puts pressure on the skate cuff, which lowers a braking device to the ground. The brake height adjusts to match skill level and skating style. Bladers already confident of their stopping skills will find ABT gives them better speed control on hills, a development that ought to please the world of innocent bystanders. Rollerblade: 800-232-7655; $149-$339.<p>
Bicycle
The shape of things that have almost come<p>For almost a year, cyclists have waited as if for the Second Coming for the radical new Cannondale V 4000. Finally, it's almost here. Available in August, the V 4000 may just be the lightest mountain bike in the world with both front and rear suspension. Alex Pong, the bike's iconoclastic designer, compares his creation to a modern jet. Here's why: Not at all tubular, the frame of the V 4000 is more like a fuselage, made of aluminum machined away on the inside to leave only ribs and skin. The result weighs just over 20 pounds (compared with about 27 pounds for a conventional bike). The frame comprises four panels, so if you dump, it's easy to replace parts. It's also easy to install them; almost the entire bike uses identical screws, which means you need only one wrench. Among other ways this bike is visibly different from anything else in the shops today: The identical front and back wheels mount to the frame on one side only. Cannondale: 800-245-3872; $5,000-$7,000.<p>
Golf clubs
The new Iron Age<p>In 1991, <a name="NASD:CLWY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11387"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Callaway</b></a> golf introduced its oversize big Bertha metal woods, and the earth moved under the feet of duffers 'round the world. Now, with much hype and fanfare, Callaway presents two lines of Big Bertha irons. Other companies offer oversize irons, but Callaway is betting that its will provide more consistent hitting over different parts of the club head. "It's too soon to tell whether Big Bertha irons will be as effective as the woods," says Golf Digest equipment editor Ed Weathers, "but expectations are high and retailers have ordered a lot." Callaway calls Big Bertha a "distance weapon" in keeping with the militaristic theme: Big Bertha was a World War I cannon alleged to have fired cannonballs 94 miles with a fair degree of accuracy--longer than any fairway golfers will encounter. Callaway: 800-228-2767; $125 and $170 per club.<p>
Tennis Racket
Head strong<p>The wilson sledge hammer 3.8si may be the weirdest-looking racket on the court, but it's also--at 9.2 ounces--the lightest. In fact, it's the lightest performance racket ever made. Wilson whittled mass from the handle and shifted it to the head, a move that brings power and control to the player's swing. With the head wider at the top than the bottom and strings that splay out in a fan shape--two more design innovations--the sweet spot gets moved up about an inch and a half on the racket face, which is good news for average players. Wilson: 800-946-6060; $320.<p>
Biodegradable Backpack
The greenest way to carry granola<p>When James Cox, a former product designer at the North Face, communes with nature, he doesn't want petrochemical products to mar the experience. Looking for an alternative to synthetic outdoor gear, he designed a day pack constructed of undyed, untreated, organically grown hemp, wool-felt shoulder straps, linen webbing, and staghorn closures. The end result, says Cox, is "bomber"--strong as Cordura nylon, comfortable to wear, and water-resistant, too. When the pack has reached the end of its natural life, you can mail the brass hardware back and get a 20 percent discount on future purchases. Then return the hemp to the nitrogen cycle: It will compost nicely in your backyard. TerraPax cost more than conventional day packs, but then again, says Cox, "they're not subsidized by the environment--by oil spills like Valdez." TerraPax: 800-308-3772; $130.<p>
Kayak
Bring the family<p>Little kids and big kayaks don't always mix. Children get tired of pushing around 16 feet of boat. They get discouraged, and they start to whine. Aquaterra has improved the dynamics of family paddling with the new Umiak designed for smaller and lighter paddlers. It weighs only 35 pounds, compared with at least 50 pounds for a typical adult model. The integral skeg--a small rear fin--gives sure tracking; the low absolute profile means the boat handles well in rough weather. The Umiak comes with bungee deck rigging fore and aft, grab loops, reflective tape, and foam walls to aid flotation. The makers of the small Umiak are also thinking big about the future of kayaking: They'll recycle any old kayak you send them, grinding it down to make parts, and will even pick up the freight charges. Aquaterra: 800-845-0762; $479.<p>
sleeping system
Fed approved<p>You don't need a bad suit, mirrored shades, and a high-level security clearance to play federal agent. The FBI tested Envirogear's Cocoon, and this high-tech sleeping system passed. Backpacker magazine's equipment editor also gives it thumbs up. The Cocoon is a sleeping bag, tent, sleeping pad, and ground cloth in one. Filled with down, it has two inflatable chambers: one a four-inch mattress, the other a blanket whose warmth increases as you pump in air. Unlike conventional bags, the Cocoon's insulation never gets compressed; also unlike conventional bags, the Cocoon is designed to be comfortable in a wide range of temperatures--as cold as 45 degrees below zero and as warm as 70 above. When wrestled into its stuff sack, it measures 9 by 17 inches, and it weighs just eight and a half pounds--a far cry from the accumulated weight of everything the system replaces. Envirogear: 607-753-8801; $395.<p>
Fishing Rod
A proprietary resin system runs through it<p>Thanks to the fall of the Berlin wall, americans will make longer and more accurate casts this summer. G. Loomis, looking for a lighter graphite for its already famously light fly rods, persuaded a defense contractor feeling the peacetime pinch to supply a fiber that shaves 25 percent off the lightest rod on the water. Assembled as Loomis's GLX Anti-Gravity line, these rods transfer more energy from the casting stroke to the fly line, have the highest strain rate in fishdom, and come out of a bend with alacrity, so vibration is damped and casts are smoother. Loomis claims the GLX casts as responsively at 15 feet as at 50. "With the GLX, a mediocre caster will be much better," says an enthusiastic company spokesman, quickly adding, "Well, he'll look better." G. Loomis: 800-662-8818; $440-$535.<p>
Surfboard
In the older, fatter green room<p>Imagine you're a little heavy and, perhaps, a little out of shape for cranking speed out of your ultrathin short board. But you're too cool to make the leap to the conservative long board. David Parmenter's remedy, the Stubb Vector, is a dignified compromise, a slight variation on standard hybrid boards with an emphasis on speed and carving. The Vector is about the same width as a hybrid (21 inches), the same or shorter in length (from 6 feet 5 inches to 7 feet), but less thick, making it more responsive. "It's the perfect board for aging surfers," says Surfer magazine editor Ben Marcus. "You know, guys in their 30s." Available at Moondoggies: 805-541-1995; $350.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
