	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Chuck Yeager Training</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Suzanne Costas<p>As Cole Porter observed, some get their kicks in a plane. But with air travel a lot like going Greyhound these days, it takes more than a ride in a commercial jet to keep spirits soaring. Thrill seekers can now experience what it's like to be a fighter pilot firsthand. Actor Alan Thicke, <a name="NYSE:ODP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14308"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Office Depot</b></a> president Mark Begelman, and motivational guru Anthony Robbins have all climbed into the cockpits of real fighter planes to engage in mock combat maneuvers. For $35,000, Hammacher Schlemmer even flies you to Moscow to put you on board a MiG.<p>What started in Fullerton, California, in 1989 with a company called Air Combat USA has mushroomed nationwide. American T-34-A Mentor and SF-260 SIAI Marchetti fighters don't break the sound barrier like the Russian MiGs do, but the price isn't as lofty: only about $750 per person for one hour in the air. After a preflight briefing (no experience required; veteran pilots do most of the actual flying), you get airborne, pressed into the seat by a force of up to six Gs.<p>Basic maneuvers like high and low yo-yos and gunsight tracking are all part of the fun. Laser-beam gun systems, billowing smoke (a valid kill sends a cloud out the back of the target plane), and in some cases explosive sound effects all simulate aerial combat. Don't forget the Dramamine: Assuming your stomach holds out, you'll attempt the intensively competitive dogfighting flyboys call "the knife fight in a phone booth." <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
