<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-The Ultimate Place Setting</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-The Ultimate Place Setting</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Eating at your hotel is no longer a last resort<p>By John Mariani<p>It used to be the conventional wisdom that the food at a resort didn't need to be very good, because no one went to a resort to dine in the grand manner. But with the increased competition for leisure-time dollars, a fine dining room on premises has become one of those amenities sophisticated travelers demand, and resorts have finally responded by paying the same attention to their cuisine as they do to their golf greens. Instead of hiring over-the-hill banquet chefs with names like Franz und Hans, resorts are making an effort to attract real talent.<p>For those who believe that no vacation is complete without a great meal at the end of the day, here's a guide to some of America's finest restaurants--which happen to be in some of America's finest resorts.<p>AUBERGE DU SOLEIL. There are few more beautiful views in America than the one from the veranda of this Napa Valley retreat. You look out over the rolling hillsides and gardens of the 33-acre property and watch the sun set over the vineyards. The air is fresh with the smell of grapes. You watch a hawk arching downward through the pines while sipping on a chardonnay produced within miles of where you sit. Because this is in the middle of wine country, the people who come here bring a very sophisticated appetite with them. Chef David Hale's Californian cuisine includes original dishes like sun-dried-cherry-stuffed quail served on wild-rice gnocchi in a bourbon pan sauce, grilled double venison chops with smoked potato hash and an apple-bacon sage sauce, and apricot-pine nut tart (707-963-1211; dinner for two, about $75).<p>RANCHO BERNARDO INN. The first thing you notice as you enter this resort just outside San Diego in the San Pasqual Mountains is the inebriating smell of oak burning in the fireplace. Your appetite will be racing. Head straight for El Bizcocho, a dining room with adobe walls framed in limed wood, dotted with some exquisite antiques and artwork. Settle in behind a wide, candle-lit table, and wait to be approached by the sommelier to discuss the 650-label wine list, and then be served a superb meal by chef Thomas Dowling. The menu here has a distinct international cast. The sauteed prawns with tomato concasse and ginger beurre blanc, the lobster bisque with Armagnac, and the roast rack of lamb with fresh herbs show the classic range of this fine dining room (303-920-6330; dinner for two, about $80).<p>THE BOULDERS. Many guests to this Arizona resort are drawn by the golf course--one of only 17 in the United States to receive a gold-medal award from Golf magazine. The landscape is breathtaking, eerily quiet except for the sound of coyotes howling at dawn. And at the resort's two dining rooms, the starkly elegant Latilla room and the more casual Palo Verde, chef Chuck Wiley has proved himself one of the most inventive cuisiniers in the West. He loves working with the flavors of the Southwest at Palo Verde, with bright dishes like achiote-chile-basted veal chop with pumpkin-seed cream and red pepper orzo, and Southwestern-style "bouillabaisse" made with grilled nopal cactus. At Latilla, he works magic with local game like pan-seared buffalo loin with vegetable potato hash and juniper-berry sauce. At twilight, from the window of Latilla, you may see the family of bobcats that lives in the towering rocks above you (602-488-9009; dinner for two, about $90 at Latilla, $75 at Palo Verde).<p>THE LITTLE NELL. Aspen is lovely enough in the winter, but I much prefer it in the summer, when the entire valley is dotted with wildflowers and the mountains are not so forbidding for exploration. The dining room at the Little Nell is set within full view of the majestic Aspen Mountain. Here chef George Mahaffey (formerly of the Bel-Air Hotel) turns out cuisine as spectacular as the scenery itself, drawing on the traditions of Colorado cookery while marrying it to the finesse of a classic European dining experience. Mahaffey's menus offer dishes like grilled golden trout with seasonal greens, corn spoonbread and green onion-morel mushroom compote, blackbuck antelope osso buco braised in mole with cilantro-vegetable rice, and blueberry and almond tea cakes with vanilla-buttermilk sorbet and mixed-berry sauce (303-920-6330; dinner for two, about $80)<p>GRAND WAILEA. There are places on earth so rich in natural beauty that fine restaurants seem rather beside the point. The island of Maui is a stunning case in point, for one doesn't go there expecting to find any gastronomic experience to match the sunrise over Haleakala Crater. Yet increasingly Maui is home to some of Hawaii's most inventive restaurants, led by Kincha at this lavish resort. The $22 million restaurant has tatami rooms and a serene rock garden set with 800 tons of stones brought from Mount Fuji. The best way to sample chef Tsuyoshi Yoshida's artistry is to have him create a multicourse kaiseki dinner composed of dishes like deep-fried sea urchin and broiled corn with shoyu flour, lobster broiled in an earthenware hibachi, and steamed abalone with vinegar sauce (808-875-1234; dinner for two, from about $150).<p>THE GRAND BAY HOTEL. If you seek respite from the glitz of Miami Beach, check in to this Coconut Grove resort. At the Grand Bay Cafe, the chef is Pascal Oudin, who worked with Michelin stars Roger Verge, Michel Rostang, and Alain Ducasse. Oudin's training shows in his marvelous melding of native Floridian ingredients into simple but revelatory dishes like plantain-wrapped baked pompano with a chartreuse of scallops and eggplant with champagne-caviar sauce, Florida lobster ravioli flavored with sea urchin and American caviar, and crisp striped sea bass with crushed black pepper and a red wine reduction (305-858-9600; dinner for two, about $85). <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

