	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Storybook Marketing</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Storybook Marketing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
By Will Dana<p>This month William Wegman's ABC (Hyperion Books for Children, $17.95), the fanciful dog photographer's third picture book for children, is published. Wegman's trademark weimaraners pose across glossy pages, dolefully contorted into the letters of the alphabet. Is it art? Or whimsy? Or, perhaps, very clever marketing? ABC, like Wegman's sly retellings of the Little Red Riding Hood and Cinderella tales, is at the forefront of a new wave in children's publishing: books that appeal as much to the adults who buy them as to the kids they are bought for. "Children see Wegman on Sesame Street," says Howard Reeves, an editor at Hyperion, "and the grown-ups see his work at the Whitney."<p>Fine-art children's books are taking off now for two reasons. First, children are becoming harder to please. "TV has educated kids so that when they see illustration, they aren't content with something superficial," says Emily Andrews, a collector of original children's-book art in Portland, Oregon. "They want content and detail." For their part, parents want to buy books that reflect their own view of the world; hence many of these books rely heavily on a postmodern cultivation of willed naivete; they are silly and fun but also knowing and droll. Take, for example, Henrik Drescher's Pat the Beastie, an arch, spiky parody of Pat the Bunny.<p>Original art from these books is also gaining status among adults, spawning a new field of collection. In Los Angeles, Every Picture Tells a Story..., an art gallery and bookstore, sells the art from children's books to customers such as Robin Williams, Harrison Ford, Tim Allen, and Phil Collins. Until the gallery was founded in 1989, there was little market for this work. Today, pieces by contemporary illustrators like William Joyce and Tim Burton fetch between $500 and $16,000, and vintage work can be far more expensive. One of Ludwig Bemelmans' original illustrations for his Madeline books brought $30,000.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Education, Publishing, Art Industry, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

