	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Shaded Glory</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Glenn Helmers<p>When speed skater Dan Jansen finally raced to Olympic victory this winter, he did it in Oakley sunglasses. His shades were as streamlined as the hooded racing skin he wore. While these new specs may already be the frames of choice among the athletic set - Nike head honcho Phil Knight wears Oakleys just about every day - they certainly aren't the only game in town. This season, vintage styles are also coming on strong.<p>Even L.A. Eyeworks, known for its avant-garde designs, is looking backward for a change: The current collection boasts a series of totally modern interpretations of vintage shapes, such as the Felix, an anodized version of a 1950s tortoiseshell staple. But the '90s are about basics, and plain metal sunglasses like those worn in the military have never looked so good. Recast in metals such as silver, pewter, even nickel, often in brushed raw finishes, they are the benchmark of cool for shielding the eyes.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
