<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-The Company Men</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-The Company Men</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
In the trenches with a top <a name="NYSE:XRX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11657"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Xerox</b></a> sales team.<p>By John House<p>Anyone who's been on the receiving end of a skillful sales pitch knows that "the coitus of commerce," as author David Dorsey calls it, can seem an awful lot like date rape. Even the most practiced seducers sometimes confess to seeing it that way and will own up to pangs - however fleeting - of remorse. So why, apart from the obvious need to make a living somehow, would anyone keep at it year after year? And what, after typically sacrificing marital harmony, self-respect, and a healthy stomach, are salespeople getting in return?<p>One of Dorsey's aims in The Force (Random House, $23) is to offer a glimpse at some individual answers. For a year, he lived among a group of top salespeople in the Cleveland office of Xerox, sitting in on the pep-rally staff meetings, tagging along on plaintive sales calls, listening to incessant interoffice harangues. More important, he got to follow some of his subjects home, giving him the chance to see how the triumphs and dissatisfactions of their workaday lives played out around the kitchen table. The result is a kind of de-Mametized Glengarry Glen Ross - a mercantile drama without the misanthropy and the expletives, featuring sales manager Fred Thomas as the flawed but essentially decent but dogged hero. "All along," Dorsey writes of one especially trying encounter with a potential customer, "Fred played the puppy dog, warm and ingratiating. When he got outside onto the sidewalk, though, Fred wanted to smash something, possibly some portion of Salter's facial anatomy. Fred had learned his share of boyhood lessons. He didn't need Salter's advice on maturity and patience. He needed the man's signature."<p>What keeps the Cleveland office humming is a combustible mix of ambition, anxiety, loyalty, and shame, and Dorsey vividly conveys the taste of each. He shows exactly what Fred's "force" is all about: both a canny sales squad and the willpower to push each deal to a profitable close. But Fred depends on the force in another sense as well, and for this his Yoda is Frank Pacetta, the district manager. Though Dorsey describes him as a "corporate puppet" and a bit of a martinet, Frank manages to inspire his staff, whether by gathering everyone into a huddle at yet another raucous company-paid outing or by grabbing a sales rep in a jubilant headlock, all the while spouting quotations from Dylan and the Band. Fred doesn't miss the deep insincerity in his boss's noisy cheerleading, but something about it nourishes him all the same.<p>On the whole, Dorsey is far better at sketching the Cleveland contingent's tics and totems (like the troll doll that sits each month on the desk of the manager with the worst results) than he is at articulating the moral he keeps stretching to find. His effort to weave a church sermon based on the Parsifal story into his own theme of the salesman's quest falls particularly flat. "It sounded so simple," he writes. "Just ask a single question every day, like a ceaseless prayer: What is your sorrow? Don't put it into words. Put it into action.... What if Fred were to do exactly that with his customers? Wasn't that supposed to be the way things worked?"<p>For the most part, though, the platitudes can be overlooked amid the numerous telling vignettes, as when Fred asks his wife to dance at a corporate outing: "This is what she wants - a dance, a genuine touch. This modest gesture, without ambiguity, without any multiple layers of meaning and intent, means more to her than any of Fred's words at dinner.... Fred has quit talking and started doing something." Seeing the Thomases try to puzzle out their future serves as counterweight not only to most of Fred and Frank's bombast, but to some of Dorsey's as well.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

