		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-A Bicycle Tour</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-A Bicycle Tour</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Tish Durkin<p>Mountain bikes attack the earth, and touring cycles roam it, but hybrids just want to have fun. Here's why a hybrid - part road bike, part off-roader - is the best bike for most riders.<p>Your aching back. Unless you have a race to win, there's no reason to crouch over drop handlebars (which are good for aerodynamics, but tough on the back). Flat handlebars let you sit up comfortably and take in the scenery. The shifters sit right next to your hands.<p>Tireless tires. Hybrid tires are stout (at least 32 mm in width, with a good tread), so you can hop curbs and ride trails. But they're fast and smooth enough for short road rides. <p>All due speed. Triple chain rings up front give you enough gears for hill, dale, and dusty trail.<p>Not rock bottom. Narrow, firm seats are strictly for Tour de France types. A hybrid's gel saddle is easy on  the, um, pressure points.<p>Multiple personalities. Most hybrids come with braze-ons for the attachment of racks and bottle holders. Add a lighting system and fenders (not cool, but crucial in rain), and you're set. As soon as you get your helmet, that is.<p>Cheap thrills. Although the best hybrid will cost the moon ($5,000), a fine one can be had for a song (about $250).<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
