	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-The $2,595 Back Rub</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-The $2,595 Back Rub</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Carla Koehl<p>It's becoming as easy to get a massage these days as it is to get a meal at <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a> - and at roughly the same price. So as more and more storefront services such as the Great American BackRub offer $9.95 rubdowns, why would anyone want to drop thousands of dollars on a massage chair? To find out, I sank into the top-of-the-line chair, the Get-a-Way Chair Premiere II ($2,595) from HWE.<p>Like the best traditional body massages, the rollers and vibrators of a Premiere II actively exercise the muscles they contact, reviving them in a way that's akin to a meditation session - and leave you feeling as if you've been through a form of mild hypnosis. The sensation is of someone rolling a huge, firm rubber ball from your lower back all the way up to your neck, focusing on the spots you choose and vibrating on command. The overwhelming urge, of course, is to drop everything you'd planned to do for the next half hour, sit back, and wait for your eyes to glaze over. <p>True, it takes just two hands to give a great traditional massage, but re-creating the stimulating effects of one is slightly more complex. "It was like making a car," says HWE vice president of marketing Mark Wollman of the chair's development. From original concept to final product took almost three years and about $2 million in research and development, a half-billion-dollar factory in Japan, and a design team of six. The chairs are so comforting that American Airlines and Air France furnish several of their airport lounges with them to help passengers ease the back pain associated with long flights. <p>The streamlined Premiere II has the added advantage of being a piece of furniture you can stand to look at. And once you've fought the kids for the chair, sat down, turned on the massage mechanism, and flipped to The McLaughlin Group, you'll have no trouble remembering why you bought it.<p><p>The $2,595 Back Rub: What You Get <p>-> Cassette player installed in the chair's left arm and speakers hidden inside the headrest <p>-> Leg rest that vibrates on command<p>-> Option of reclining to sleeping position <p>Extras <p>-> $150 for the optional three-year warranty<p>-> About $18 a year (more or less) added to your electricity bill, assuming one hour of use per day <p>What you might buy instead<p>-> 324 rubdowns at the Great American BackRub in New York City <p>-> 98 reflexology treatments at Ten Thousand Waves in Santa Fe<p>-> 43 full-body massages at Georgette Klinger's salons nationwide <p>-> Two leather Barcalounger chairs from Bloomingdale's <p>Bottom line <p>No matter how much these things cost to make or buy, and no matter how high-tech they become, no one's going to give up their weekly Swedish body massages to own one. That's because nothing compares to the human touch. Still, giving up just a year's worth of spa treatments will pay for a Premiere II - a device that's expected to last at least ten years and ultimately is best used to fill the gaps between visits to a masseuse. The Premiere II is available only at the <a name="NASD:SHRP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14704"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sharper Image</b></a> (800-344-4444).<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
