<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-The Dish on Satellite TV</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-The Dish on Satellite TV</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
It's getting better and cheaper. Sorry, cable slaves.<p>By Stephan Wilkinson<p>The future, they tell us, holds 500 channels of television for every zombied man, woman, and child.<p>With a ten-foot satellite dish in my backyard, I tell them, I'm already two thirds of the way there. Each week, Satellite TVWeek, the size and thickness of Rolling Stone, clogs my mailbox, its pages plump with the offerings of some 330 channels of video. <p>Superstations. HBO. Pay-per-view movies summoned from 24,000 miles away by simply keying in a phone number. Nonstop sports, some as arcane as female bodybuilding and kick boxing. Porn channels. The Arab Network of America. An Inuit channel. Mexican vaudeville. News in Japanese. Home shopping. A whine of infomercials. And that favorite of satellite geeks everywhere, live prebroadcast feeds of network news. <p>Granted, the big black dish makes our lawn look like a NASA launch pad. But by May, you'll be able to see much of what's available to owners of gargantuan C-band dishes via a new and much more compact DBS (direct-broadcast satellite) system built and launched last December by Hughes Communications. The DBS satellites transmit on the Ku-band (pronounced "kay-you") to rooftop or even windowsill dishes only 18 inches in diameter.<p>I'm not about to trade in my big dish, but others will have reason to weigh the relative strengths of the two technologies. The little DBS dish will start at $1,000 installed, which is about a quarter of the price of the best big systems. On the other hand, monthly programming costs will run nearly twice the cost of equivalent C-band program packages. And at a time when C-band will be creeping steadily toward that couch-potato nirvana of 500 channels, DBS will be offering about 150. Finally, it's predicted that competition from DBS could cut as much as $1,000 from the price of more expensive C-band setups by year end.<p>As for transmission quality, DBS marketing has touted the "laser disc-sharp" pictures and CD sound available through that brand-new system's digital transmission technology. Big-dish C-band pictures and sound currently are conventional analog transmissions, though the C-band spectrum will be shifting increasingly to digital transmissions by the end of this year. But unless you have a studio-quality TV monitor or a rare HDTV (high-definition TV) set rather than a conventional 525-line screen, it's debatable whether you'll be able to tell the difference. "I've seen analog, digital, and laser disc pictures side-by-side on conventional screens, and they all looked pretty much the same to me," says Satellite TV Week editor James Scott. Nobody is sure yet what an actual DBS transmission will look like, for it depends in part upon how much "digital compression" the broadcasters choose to use: More compression means more channels but less sharpness. Knowledgeable industry observers predict the image will be more like good VHS videocassette displays than of true laser disc quality. <p>Some satellite-industry observers compare the coming of DBS to an earlier revolution in radio. "When FM first came out, a few manufacturers introduced FM-only sets," says Greg Gudorf, director of marketing for the leading decoder manufacturer, GI Communications. "Those quickly died out, because consumers wanted not just good music but the AM option for news, traffic, and sports. Analog C-band satellite delivery is today's AM, and the new Ku-band stuff is equivalent to FM. With digital transmission coming to C-band in late '94, I think what we have is the new guys launching the equivalent of FM only, while C-band will give you the choice of both AM and FM."<p>Your options? Frankly, the channels that will be available on DBS--about 35 cable and major networks, 50 to 60 channels of pay-per-view films, about 30 each of special interest and sports--will be varied enough to make the best of conventional cable TV seem painfully limited. And there's no denying that an 18-inch dish on the roof sure beats planting something on your lawn that looks as though it ought to be talking to a fleet of AWACS jets. <p>Still, for the first year and a half or so, RCA will be the sole source of antennas and decoders, and there is a limited choice of programming from two broadcasting packagers, DirecTv and USSB. The world of C-band, on the other hand, is wide-open and competitive: more than a dozen manufacturers of receivers, half a dozen choices of major dish builders, and more than 26 different program packagers. If you like to be in control, C-band retains a lot of appeal. <p>For the true TV maven, nothing beats a big dish. If you want everything that's broadcast, you need a cumbersome, expensive, C-band frequency dish. Depending on where you live, that means a diameter of anywhere from 5 to 12 feet; the farther you are from Kansas, the bigger the dish, since the TV satellites consider ground zero to be Middle America. Assuming you already have a television set, you'll also need to spend from $1,700 to $3,000 for a good satellite system (the antenna and associated electronics, a receiver that also decodes scrambled pay-TV signals, and installation) and up to $4,000 for a superb one. Nor does it stop there. Trust me, you'll be shopping for professional monitors, projection TVs, and five-speaker home-theater setups within hours of seeing your first satellite signal.<p>Though some channels are still unscrambled, you'll also pay monthly or annual charges just as you would for cable. But there are advantages. Those charges often are as much as 50 percent less than cable fees, and while cable subscribers get only a single HBO channel, you'll have a choice of five (plus three Cinemax and three Showtime options). Another plus is that you're free of your local cable company's quirks, outages, and monopolistic attitude.<p>The downside: It isn't cheap; zoning regulations or housing-association rules sometimes forbid big, ugly dishes; and the dish site has to have an unobstructed view of the southern sky for the antenna to "see" the satellites (even foliage will block the signals from space). <p>Nonetheless, for the complete video-equipment junkie, there's one killer reason to get a dish, whether it's a big C-band microwave funnel or a pizza-pan DBS platter: Those of us who have been fighting zoning boards and worrying about foliage will be getting HDTV years before cable TV supplies it to the rest of the country. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry, Technology Industry, Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
