	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Roll Over Again, Beethoven</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Roll Over Again, Beethoven</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The sounds are classical, but the marketing is MTV <p>By Dean Robinson<p>The scene in the film Philadelphia in which Denzel Washington and Tom Hanks listen to Maria Callas has struck a surprising chord with audiences. And it's sent them out to music stores to buy. To capitalize on the rush, the classical-music department of a New York City HMV record store even posted a sign above a display of Maria Callas Opera Arias CDs: "As featured in the new movie Philadelphia."<p>Record stores, like the rest of the classical-music industry, will take whatever help they can get--the age of the sound bite has been rough for highbrow music. Concertgoing has declined, magazines have folded, and over the last two decades the number of commercial radio stations playing classical has been reduced by half. It's increasingly difficult for people interested in classical music to learn about what they like--unless they hear it on TV or in the movies.<p>Record labels are also singing a new tune. "We're promoting classical music much like rock and movies--using MTV marketing," says Rob Enslin, one of the creators of a CD line called Counter Culture, which includes a Beethoven sampler titled What Does a Deaf Guy Hear? Other classical labels have been releasing CDs that repackage and rearrange the core classical repertoire in progressive ways. These range from Deutsche Grammophon's Mad About series to Angel/EMI's Heavy Classix compilations and its interactive line The Key to Classics. Most of the individual discs have the famous parts from well-known works. Mad About Tchaikovsky, for example, includes the 1812 Overture and pieces from Swan Lake and The Nutrcracker. Heavy Classix rumbles with a Sturm und Drang snippet from Wagner's The Valkyrie. Even the cover graphics on these CDs are a bold departure from the expected: Sensual Classics and Sensual Classics II resemble the jackets of steamy romance novels.<p>Stores are also catering successfully to those unfamiliar with classical music. At HMV, where the Philadelphia display was a success, there are plans to install a large movielike marquee that will tell customers how to find other classical music they hear in films. The main branch of Rose Records in Chicago has not only a film-music section but also a beginners' section, with many selections determined by the number of novice requests the staff receives.<p>Despite fears by some within the industry, customers seem to be biting. A spokesman for Deutsche Grammophon claims that the entire Mad About series has sold close to a million copies. And, according to Enslin, "Symphonies are contacting us and saying, 'Hey, can we have a Counter Culture night?'" Sandra Hyslop, editor of Symphony magazine, acknowledges the efforts orchestras are making. "It's such a period of change and exploration," she says. "There's a willingness to look at imaginative ways to get an audience to come in and listen to music." She could just as easily be talking about the entire classical-music industry. Not bad for a bunch of stodgy folks. <p><p>Sound Advice:
The experts choose some essential building blocks to start a classical-music collection. 
--D.R.<p>Wynton Marsalis, trumpeter:
-- Bach: Cello Suites
-- Haydn: Trumpet Concerto
-- Beethoven: Symphony No. 6 "The Pastoral" 
-- Schubert: Trout Quintet
-- Wagner: Tristan und Isolde
-- Mussorgsky--Ravel: Pictures at an Exhibition
-- Rimsky-Korsakov: Capriccio Espagnol
-- Ravel: La Valse
-- Bartok: Concerto for Orchestra
-- Stravinsky: Petrushka<p>James Galway, flutist:
--A baroque brass collection
--Vivaldi: Four Seasons
--Handel: The Messiah
--Mozart: Symphony No. 41 "Jupiter," Piano Concerto No. 21 "Elvira Madigan" 
--Beethoven: Symphony No. 9 "Choral"
--Tchaikovsky: The Nutcracker, Swan Lake
--Chopin: Nocturnes, Etudes
--Strauss : Waltzes
--Puccini: La Boheme
--Gershwin: Rhapsody in Blue<p>Peter Schickele, composer:
--Praetorius: Dances from "Terpsichore"
--Bach: Brandenburg Concertos 
--Haydn: String Quartet in D "The Lark"
--Mozart: Don Giovanni
--Beethoven: Piano Sonata No. 21 "Waldstein" 
--Schubert: Quintet in C 
--Brahms: Variations on a Theme by Haydn
--Debussy: Nocturnes, for Orchestra and Chorus
--Stravinsky: Symphony in Three Movements
--Prokofiev: Violin Concerto No. 1 in D <p>Itzhak Perlman, violinist
--Vivaldi: Four Seasons
--Bach: Brandenburg Concertos
--Mozart: Late symphonies
--Beethoven: Symphonies Nos. 5, 7, 9
--Schubert: Lieder 
--Mendelssohn: A Midsummer Night's Dream
--Tchaikovsky: Symphonies Nos. 4, 5
--Mahler: Symphony No. 1 "Titan"
--Stravinsky: The Rite of Spring
--Shostakovich: Symphony No. 5<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry, Art Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
