	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Mastering the Wine List</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Mastering the Wine List</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Alexis Bespaloff<p>Even someone with only a casual interest in wine must occasionally deal with a wine list when entertaining friends or business associates, and the finer the restaurant, the longer the list. Here's how to make some good choices.<p>Arrive early. Try to get to the restaurant a few minutes before your guests, choose a red and white wine within your budget, and confirm with the sommelier that the wines are actually in stock. That way, you won't be poring over the list just when you should be paying attention to your dinner companions.<p>Don't overlook the bubbly. You may find a decent sparkler from California or the Loire that's actually less expensive than the best chardonnay, and nothing creates a festive mood at the start of an evening more effectively than a glass of sparkling wine.<p>Think American. Generally, the California selections on any wine list will be less expensive than those from France. Bordeaux and Burgundy may range from $35 to $60 and up, while some good California labels will be available at $25 to $35. And the California selections are more dependable because there is less vintage variation.<p>Experiment. When your guests order an assortment of dishes, sauvignon blanc, with its assertive taste, might be closer to an all-purpose white than the more popular chardonnay. (The French equivalents are Sancerre and Pouilly-Fume, from the Loire.) And young cabernet sauvignon can be quite tannic and puckerish, whereas a softer pinot noir is easier to drink.<p>Don't underpay. Muscadet, Beaujolais, Soave, and Valpolicella are likely to be the least expensive wines. Although the wholesale cost of most brands of these four popular wines is about the same--$6 or so--the price on a wine list may be as high as $20. If you pay $1 or $2 more, you're likely to get a wine whose price more accurately reflects its cost and is thus a better buy. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
