	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Digging It</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Digging It</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Glenn Helmers <p>Today, gardening enthusiasts are as prevalent as dandelions and crabgrass. Gardening is the most popular leisure activity in America, according to American Demographics, with 61 million people rooting around in the dirt for fun.<p>But fun with seedlings, pests, and other earthly delights requires more than a green thumb. A thorough manual is a must (suggested reading: The American Horticultural Society Encyclopedia of Gardening, Dorling Kindersley, $59.95), as are good tools.<p>The basic trousseau of tools--spade, fork, rake, trowel, watering can, hat, sturdy pair of gloves--has not changed much since doyennes of the field like Gertrude Jekyll worked her garden in Victorian England. But necessities for the well-heeled gardener are now practically luxury items, crafted to exacting standards and packaged with as much romance as French perfume. Take the Catamount Cart, marketed as the Rolls Royce of garden wagons, which is hand-built by a New England cabinetmaker, or Smith & Hawken's grass clippers, designed in 1730 for shearing sheep, that sing when you snip.<p>Perhaps the most alluring thing about forged-steel spades, moss-covered pots, rubber Wellies, and the like is that they make even amateurs feel--and look--like old hands to the task. A few calluses and you're all set. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
