<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-The $1,380 Berlitz-Krieg</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-The $1,380 Berlitz-Krieg</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Marshall Sella<p>The global marketplace is shrinking. The odd part is that, no matter how small it gets, every corner still has its own language--a by-product of that pesky force known as human history. Before an important journey, it is sometimes wise to acquaint yourself with (or, God willing, actually learn) the language of the land. The best-known method is that of Berlitz International, which runs 350 schools around the globe. But what can you expect from one of these kwik-stop lingo shops? I decided to find out.<p>Day zero: During an initial consultation, I present my goal to a Berlitz representative: to become fluent in Russian in one week. His advice: "Re-incarnate." I opt instead to sign up for Berlitz's five-day crash course--four and a half hours per day of intensive, one-on-one training with a native Russian. Total cost: $1,380. <p>Day one: My first lesson is spent repeating questions and answers that all seem to involve notebooks and pencils. Given the alien sound of the language, I'm little more than a parrot with an American Express card. The second half starts 15 minutes late when a different teacher shambles in, irritated to learn that I don't already read Cyrillic. For the next two hours, he proceeds to scribble down words and pound them with his finger, as if the clamor will awaken the Russian poet that is doubtless hiding deep within me. It does not. At day's end, I pop by the main desk to ask that I never see this man again. The request is politely granted. <p>Progress: I've already surpassed most tourists by being able to pluck what and where out of the dim netherworld of spoken Russian. <p>Day two: Evgenije, a wry, rather Bohemian coach, replaces King Cyril; more Q&A drills. I learn much about a family called the Petrovs and stare at colorful pictures of them engaged in cheery daily activities. Accommodatingly, Evgenije spices up the conversation by endowing the family with unsavory traits. We decide, for instance, that Mr. Petrov is a philanderer, while little Tanya is unmasked (in simple Russian) as a half-wit. <p>Progress: I'm amazed at how much of Evgenije's commentary I can follow. If Muscovites confine themselves to questions such as "Is the pen red?" I shall be the most celebrated visitor to Russia since Armand Hammer.<p>Day three: Bad news. Russian verbs have different tenses. <p>Progress: I pick up a vague notion of the past and future. <p>Day four: Evgenije is fascinated by the late-night talk show wars and can steer any linguistic drill toward an analysis of David Letterman: "Please, what do you think of Letterman?" and "Is it true that Dave lives in Connecticut but works in Manhattan?" <p>Progress: By sunset I can manage a crude version of "Madam, do you want Paul Shaffer to purchase a new piano?" <p>Day five: Evgenije winds up the course with some useful travel expressions: "What does that sign mean?" "Got a smoke?" and "Fortunately, Grandmother will be asleep when the Letterman show begins." <p>Progress: I marvel that the guttural noises Evgenije is making are real sentences to me. I go home to polish my accent but fall asleep during Letterman.<p>
What you get:
--Five days (22.5 hours) of personalized coaching by Berlitz-trained native speakers<p>Extras:
--Set of 24 audiocassettes with 480-page Russian/English textbook called Ruski Jezik: $300 
--Paper cup of coffee: 25 cents<p>What you might buy instead:
--Three round-trip air tickets to Moscow
--Four weeks' intensive coaching by a non-Berlitz teacher
--Almost one Russian wolfhound
--89 bottles of Stolichnaya vodka 
--14 months' worth of the average Russian worker's wages<p>Bottom line:
Berlitz's method relies on conversation: Classes are conducted entirely in the foreign tongue. Most teachers are top-notch, and they tailor the class to your needs and abilities. You'll be astonished at how much you can absorb, especially if you do your homework. For information, call 800-257-9449.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

