<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-A Cut Above the Rest</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-A Cut Above the Rest</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Steak houses are sizzling as Americans rediscover beef <p>By John Mariani<p>If there is any way to gauge how Americans feel about their guilty pleasures in the middle of the '90s, the proliferation of steak houses over the past three years would seem to indicate that a certain segment of society is feeling no pain. For despite health warnings about cholesterol and fat, the steady decline in overall consumption of beef--from a high of 94.5 pounds per person in 1976--has finally leveled off; Americans consumed 66.5 pounds of beef per person in both 1991 and 1992. <p>And not only have people stopped avoiding red meat, they're eating the best beef they can find. They seem willing to pay top dollar for the richest, fattest, tastiest beef available. Steak houses have been doing banner business across the country recently, with chains like Morton's of Chicago, Ruth's Chris Steak House, and Palm Restaurant pushing the number of their locations into double digits and many haute chefs getting back to basic beef. Richard Chamberlain, for example, after years of cooking up lighter fare at the Little Nell in Aspen, Colorado, recently opened up Chamberlain's Prime Chop House in Dallas.<p>True excellence is a relative thing, and beef graded prime (the highest USDA grading) can vary in quality at even the best steak houses and restaurants. While demand for prime has risen over the past decade, there is still only a finite amount of such top-grade beef available--currently about 2 percent of total beef production. "It's getting tougher all the time to find a consistently good product," says Alfred Thimm, COO for the New York-based Palm chain, which set the mold for the New York steak house genre when the first Palm opened back in 1926. And Marilyn Spiera, president of Brooklyn's Peter Luger Steak House, insists, "The beef the government now grades prime wouldn't even have made choice 35 years ago."<p>Prime beef is for the most part a genetic accident, dependent on how intramuscular fat, called marbling, is distributed throughout the best cuts of a steer carcass. There's just no way to get that rich beefy flavor from a steak if it isn't highly marbleized: The more fat throughout the beef, the more flavorful it will be, and the most marbleized of all is stamped usda prime. Ranchers can't simply overfeed a steer to produce such marbling, because it would be prohibitively expensive and might produce more external than internal fat.<p>The taste of a steak also has a good deal to do with how the beef is packed and shipped to meat markets. Prime beef comes principally from three meatpackers--IBP in Nebraska, Monfort in Colorado, and Excel in Kansas--and is shipped in airtight Cryovac bags to local markets, where it is then selected by the steak house operators. Most of the big steak houses swear that "dry aging," whereby the meat is removed from its Cryovac bag and aged for several weeks in cold, dry lockers, is better than "wet aging," in which the meat ages in the bag while sitting in its own juices.<p>It has long been true that New York gets the best prime beef, because the competition among steak houses like Palm, Gallagher's Steak House, Smith & Wollensky, and Peter Luger in that city demands extremely high quality, and operators pay top dollar for their meat. In fact, many people in other U.S. cities balk at paying upwards of $30 for a sirloin and often complain prime meat tastes too rich and beefy to their liking. Until recently, the best restaurants in this country served only top choice (the next grade down from prime) to their customers.<p>The prospects of getting a good steak, therefore, are very good at any of the national chains serving prime meat, but the odds of getting a great steak increase measurably if you eat in New York. As one operator says, "We guarantee our steaks will be the best you'll find in any city we're in. But to be perfectly honest, the ones we and our competitors serve in our New York restaurant are going to be even better."<p>Palm Restaurants runs its own purchasing company. Gallagher's (opened 1927) dry ages its meat in its own lockers for three weeks (you can see them in the window of the restaurant). Peter Luger, dating back to 1887 and best known for its porterhouse, refuses to buy any boxed or Cryovac-wrapped meat at all, and trims off half a pound of exterior fat to get half a pound of perfect beef. And at New York's Old Homestead (1868), a specialty is Japanese kobe (or wagyu) beef, which is fed on beer and grain and hand-massaged daily, resulting in an incredibly tender steak that sells for $100 a pound in the restaurant.<p>"We know it's a big challenge for us to try to crack the New York market," says Ruth Fertel, chairman of the board and founder of Ruth's Chris, "but customers who love our steaks in New Orleans or Washington or Orlando will love them just as much when they go to New York." <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
