<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Crowning Achievement</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Crowning Achievement</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
A new catalog banks on a royal connection<p>By Jennifer Pierce<p>Since her engagement to prince Charles in 1981, Princess Diana has been on the cover of People magazine 56 times, more than any other celebrity--ever. There's no doubt about it: Royalty sells. This fact has not escaped the notice of a few shrewd marketers who have taken creative license using a regal-looking coat of arms to distinguish themselves among the already crowded list of more than 10,000 mail-order catalogs in existence.<p>This month, The House of Windsor Collection, the brainchild of the Eclectic American Catalogue Co., debuts with 160 specially commissioned and indubitably British products. Included among them are a $135 sterling silver Skinner & Co. key ring ("an elegant accessory for all who like to live their lives with style"), a $115 set of four lead-crystal Windsor tumblers with an etched silhouette of Windsor castle ("hold history in your hand"), and $110-a-pair Queen Victoria wineglasses (available with or without the House of Windsor Collection crest).<p>Cynics might point out that the only member of the royal family directly involved in the venture is the Queen's distant cousin Prince Michael of Kent, who is paid to sit on the Eclectic American board of directors. ("He's got to earn a living," says a Buckingham Palace spokesman.) Nonetheless, all manufacturers whose goods appear in the catalog have earned warrant status in Great Britain, a distinction bestowed exclusively by the Queen, the Queen Mother, the Duke of Edinburgh, and the Prince of Wales to honor royal patronage. The catalog's creators are counting on this royal connection to sell their private line of "quintessentially English" goods on the other side of the Atlantic. <p>The House of Windsor Collection is hoping that by selling hand-painted Weymss ceramic-cat collectibles and bottle goblets with inscriptions like "Wine gives courage and makes men apt for passion," it can cash in on the success of other companies like Laura Ashley, Victoria's Secret, and Crabtree & Evelyn that market an English lifestyle. One promising indicator: When the Queen opened Buckingham Palace last summer, in just two months visitors spent about $1.2 million in the souvenir shop. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
