<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Catch the Wave</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Catch the Wave</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
World-band radios keep media junkies connected<p>By Robert Sullivan<p>Almost invariably, when i mention to someone that I enjoy spending time with my shortwave radio, I have to talk them down from a mental picture of me in which I am wearing a headset down in a basement somewhere, surrounded by transistors, old wires, knobs, and maps--possibly coming to the aid of some Portuguese merchant-marine vessel in distress off the Maine coast. In fact, my shortwave radio is a sleek little number made by <a name="NYSE:SNE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sony</b></a>, about the size of a small hardback book; technically, it is known as the ICF-7601, and if I feel like hamming it up at all, it has a nifty little extension antenna that rolls out like a tape measure and makes the rest of the world sound that much clearer.<p>The other invariable that comes when I am spreading the word of shortwave is the recitation of my very first shortwave experience, which involved a BBC report from Wales about the closing of a mine. The person who is not meant to be a shortwave listener generally interrupts me to say that I could have had the same experience with less audio interference had I gotten a cable subscription that included CNN. But I say no. First of all, television makes the world seem smaller: No matter how many channels we will one day wind up with, all TV news will always seem to take place within the space of a land mass the size of Pennsylvania. Second, with shortwave, the static is the thing. That night, the miners just talked and talked and one wept, and in those faraway silences, in the wash of white noise out of which they told their story, I could hear all the Atlantic's waves.<p>My shortwave ended up serving me well during the Gulf War--I heard Radio Damascus, Radio Iraq International, and for a while Radio Kuwait--but the war hurt shortwave in general. Initially, it caused shortwave sales to boom by almost 80 percent overnight. But few radio-manufacturing companies were able to keep up, and the gap was filled mostly by fly-by-night operations. "The people who do Ginsu knives were doing these things," says Lawrence Magne, editor in chief of Passport to World Band Radio, a shortwave guide, "and the problem is these things just don't work. So we had a half-million people who bought these junkers and turned them on and thought, 'This is what shortwave radio is all about?' So we lost them." Sales soon flattened out, and although they are now on a more gradual rise, Magne estimates the industry lost a year's worth of growth because of the war. At the same time, shortwave's image suffered: The newspaper stories tended to pigeonhole the average shortwave listener into either the grandfatherly ham-operator category or the techno-nerd, when the actual average user, by Magne's own survey's account, has only a slight technological sophistication and is just looking for information with perspective.<p>I listen primarily to news on my shortwave. The BBC itself is worth the price of the thing; it has the best newscast in the world. Monitor Radio from Boston covers North America in particular better than the BBC, though it lacks the BBC's overall scope, and then there is Deutsche Welle's European Journal, a great news show broadcast in English from Germany. Once a week the news is even read in Latin on Radio Finland.<p>But there are all kinds of entertainment programs on shortwave, too. On Sundays on the BBC you can hear Letter From America, a short weekly report from Alistair Cooke, who was a British correspondent from the U.S. long before he stumped for Masterpiece Theater, and there are a lot of nifty quiz shows (David Letterman has said he is a BBC quiz-show fan). The selection is absolutely endless.<p>In my time, I have heard a report on National Hugging Week in Britain and lots of great jazz on Radio Havana Cuba. Once, on a Radio Nederland show called East of Edam, I heard long talks on the history of various cheeses and then the following exchange between the host and a listener on the telephone from the U.S.: "I've got a photograph of you here, Theresa," the host said. "Would you like to tell us what's different about you?" A cheery woman responded, "Well, I'm three foot five inches, and I used to have a perm. Basically, I'm just like everyone else except I'm a little shorter. And my hobby is listening to shortwave radio!" The host then hit her with a few questions about dwarf throwing and then moved on to a guy with a question for the Dutch Allergy Board, which I didn't catch. I was too busy thinking what a crazy world it is out there, and then I just kept moving along the shortwave bands. <p>
Tuning In<p>Before you even think about buying a shortwave radio, you should buy Passport to World Band Radio (International Broadcasting Services, $17.95), the best and biggest shortwave guidebook. Aside from listing all the shortwave radio shows in the world, it rates the performance of most of the different kinds of radios anyone would want to buy.<p>You will probably want to start with a radio that has a digital frequency readout, as tuning otherwise can be tedious. The Sony ICF-SW30 ($130) is a good bet, and the Realistic DX-375 ($100) is almost as good. The Grundig Yacht Boy ($249) was a favorite this year of the panelists who rate shortwaves for Passport. The radio they choose year after year is the Sony ICF-2010, a kind of classic, which, at about $430, is as good for the obsessive beginner as it is for the long-time low-rent fan waiting to move up: It has 32 preset buttons, an alarm, and a world time clock, which comes in handy if you don't naturally think in terms of the shortwave standard, Greenwich Mean Time. Whatever you buy, you'll soon find that part of the romance of shortwave is that the radio, thanks to the mercurial workings of the ionosphere, works better at night. <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:SNE">Sony Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
