<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Auction Savvy</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Auction Savvy</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Tish Durkin<p>Barbra streisand may be a person who needs people, but her 1927 Cartier clock she can apparently do without. It--along with the rest of Funny Girl's art nouveau and art deco collection--hits the block at Christie's this month. But without a basic grounding in the auction game, don't even think about picking up a bidder's paddle.<p>Take your time. Subscribe to Antiques and the Arts Weekly, the auction bible regularly devoured by those in the know. Then get your paddle wet in a low-price setting, such as a <a name="NYSE:BID"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12331"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sotheby</b></a>'s Arcade Auction, where a lot (an object or group of objects offered together) can go for less than $1000.<p>See it all. "Buy with a notebook, not your checkbook," counsels Kathleen Guzman of Christie's. Always attend the preview before an auction, and don't confuse it with a wander through the Met: You are not here to "ooh" and "aah" but to assess. If it's a painting you're thinking about buying, ask to see the back of it. If it's a bureau, open the drawers. <p>Control yourself. House appraisers publicly set estimates, low and high, between which a lot can be expected to sell--Barbra's clock, for instance, should fetch from $100,000 to $150,000. But in the frenzy of bidding, anything can happen. Set your limit and stick to it.<p>Know your values. Several factors determine the worth of an object: its rarity, condition, quality, desirability in the market of the moment. Perhaps most intriguing, though, is provenance. What will the highest bidder pay for the fact that a Tiffany lamp spent time in Streisand's sunroom? No telling--but in a society of people who read People, 'twont be peanuts. "I don't know what your driver's license is worth," says Guzman, "but I sold Liberace's for $4,000." <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:BID">Sotheby's Holdings, Inc.</a><br>

