<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-The Art of the Meal</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-The Art of the Meal</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Randall Fuller<p>How does a hotel room get to be $800 a night? To find out, we visited Twin Farms, the Vermont property that author Sinclair Lewis gave his wife as a wedding present in 1928. Back then, Lewis paid $10,000 for the 300-acre farm; today, you can have run of the entire spread for a mere $8,000--a day. Once the setting of bohemian literary parties, the upscale, rustic hotel is now more likely to have its guest book signed by Southampton, New York, socialites. And no wonder: With tax and the 15 percent service fee added, a night's stay in the least expensive room tallies up to $869.40, including meals.<p>At Twin Farms the dizzying price is reflected in the smallest details: Wedgwood bone china (in case you develop a sudden thirst for tea) and unbleached 310-count Egyptian cotton sheets in the room, Wegman photographs in the gym. We had a supper of lobster bisque, goat-cheese salad, caviar sorbet, roast quail, and tarte tartin--a menu built around a wine we had selected earlier in the day. <p>Our activities manager drew up a route for us to go mountain biking along a country road. As soon as we finished, the kitchen outfitted us with a rucksack lunch and we made the hour-long hike to Turtle Mountain, where we picnicked on smoked-salmon sandwiches and locally brewed hickory-smoked beer. When we weren't being expensively athletic, there was time to browse through Lewis first editions in the library.<p>Had the author lived to see the transformation of Twin Farms, he undoubtedly would have made the same discovery we did: The farm is simply too expensive to stay for as long as you'd like. After all, until the success of Main Street, Lewis's advances were only $2,000--barely enough to cover a weekend at the hotel.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
