	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Pens with Flair</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Pens with Flair</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Bill Marsano<p>What a blessing obsolescence can be. The Newton is an executive tool, but a pen is executive jewelry, a personal scepter: symbol of power. But not just any pen. Stock clerks use felt tips and messengers use ball points, so whether you're making a deal or making history, use a fountain pen.<p>You say it's totally impractical? Exactly. With their handmade gold nibs and bellies full of liquid ink, fountain pens have gone from utility (machine made by the millions, sold for pocket change) to indulgence (made by hand, priced like fine wines).<p>The symbolism is power and image. "Success used to be measured by the secretary-typed letter," says Wayne Kingsland of the pen maker Montblanc. "Today, it's receiving a letter that has been handwritten." Executives use fountain pens because they control their own time and because they don't sign million-dollar contracts with 50-cent ballpoints.<p>A fountain pen turns signing into ceremony: Slide the pen from your pocket, admire it, slowly unscrew the top. Scan the document a final time and adjust the pen in your hand. Then, you sign.<p>These days, men don't have much jewelry left except fountain pens and watches. Executive women are using fountain pens more, too. They treat them like another accessory. Men aren't as good at accessorizing with pens, "but some men become fascinated," says Steven Wiederlight, whose Fountain Pen Hospital in New York City has "some men collecting vintage pens, and others ordering every new model shipped sight unseen."<p>Fountain pens may draw the line between class and clunk, but not much else. Still, for what it's worth, consider this: Ollie North and Princess Diana own Sheaffers; Prince Charles and Colin Powell wield Parkers.   -<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
