	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Hello, World</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Hello, World</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>Here's how to prepare for a summer full of international soccer. That's right, soccer.<p>By Jim Harmon<p>How did a country of such renowned indifference to international soccer end up as host of the 15th World Cup? Simple: We asked for it. Back in 1987, the only other serious contender for the 1994 tournament was Morocco. So the Federation Internationale de Football Association (FIFA) swallowed hard and chose the United States.<p>Immediately there were howls in the European and South American press. The game is neither understood nor appreciated in America, they said. The cup will be bastardized and commercialized into something unrecognizable, they fretted.<p>Commercial it may be, but this World Cup won't be ignored. The first-round games in several of the nine host cities sold out within hours last spring, and World Cup USA94, the organizing body, now hopes that this will be the first Mondial ever to sell out all 52 tournament games. Take that, Eurosnobs. So what if we have a trademarked cartoon canine mascot named Striker?<p>The tournament starts on June 17, with defending champion Germany playing Bolivia in Chicago, and concludes with the final on July 17 in Los Angeles. Americans had what they thought was their last shot at seats by way of lotteries last fall, but there are still ways to find seats. Sponsors will be returning tickets; they'll be resold through TicketMaster. Or consider the numerous multigame ticket packages, which range in price from $425 (one seat for every game in Detroit) to $10,000 (one seat and VIP perks for any ten games, including the opener, one semifinal, and the final). Call 800-793-1994 for information.   <p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Sports Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
