<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Buy and Hold</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Buy and Hold</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>Sometimes it pays to keep antiques in the family <p>By Carla Koehl<p>Things lead lives like people do," writes Thatcher Freund in Objects of Desire (Pantheon, $24), a biography of three pieces of fine antique American furniture. "And they prosper, like some people, on the strength of their character."<p>Whether they also prosper as investments depends on how long one can afford to hang on to them (see above). "People are not buying a liquid investment when they buy antiques," says preeminent American antiques dealer Harold Sack, who figures prominently in Freund's book. "It's like good real estate; it takes time to liquidate. You're not going to call a broker tomorrow and sell the highboy to put a kid through college." <p>So, if antiques are the ultimate long-term investment, could antique funds be the ultimate long-term portfolio-diversity move? Fred Giampietro, one of the dealers featured in Objects, thinks so. His $2 million private limited partnership, Artvest LT I, has owned 250 American antiques for four years and has just begun to liquidate--so far, at a profit. <p>Most of the fund's 35 investors, who paid $50,000 a unit to be part of Artvest, are friends and associates of Giampietro and his partner, Allan Katz, and based their investment on the two partners' successes, rather than on their own often-limited knowledge of or interest in antiques. It's a good thing, too, since most of Artvest's 18th- and 19th-century Americana is sitting in a bank vault in Hartford. <p>Shareholders, therefore, aren't in it for artistic fulfillment, and they won't start to see any cash until later this year. But the upside, says Giampietro, is considerable: He and Katz paid dealer prices to increase profit potential, and they're not accepting management fees, only commissions.<p>Freund, however, reminds his readers of the risks inherent in seeing antiques only as things that might become worth more money to someone else. As he writes about the 1759 Willing Chippendale card table: "It was valuable because someplace a market existed for it and because out in the world of American furniture--where dealers fought and lied and stole things from their friends--some people could tell a great card table from a good one."   <p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
