<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Shopping By Design</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Shopping By Design</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Museum stores are drawing crowds these days with some of the season's best gift ideas<p>By Glenn Helmers<p>With museums long known as scholarly arbiters of taste and enduring style, perhaps it was only a matter of time before their shops would be turned into full-blown specialty boutiques--filled with objects as tempting as the exhibitions that spawned them. Museums have been forced to cash in on this cultural cachet, "marketing the word museum and everything it stands for," as Beverly J. Barsook, executive director of the Museum Store Association, puts it. Government funding and support from the private sector have waned in the last 15 years, and income from endowments has dropped because of lower interest rates. "The dollars are simply drying up," says Susan R. Laudeman, shop manager for the Historic New Orleans Collection, a museum and research center dedicated to preserving the history and culture of Louisiana and the Gulf South. "The only tax-free income museums are able to generate is through related business activity, which is why museum shops have exploded."<p>The criteria for choosing merchandise vary from shop to shop, depending upon the museum's mission, but the driving force behind the offerings is to educate. As Robin Cramer, museum-shop director for the Jewish Museum in New York City, explains: "We try to reinforce the permanent collection and the special exhibits in our product line." At the Renwick Gallery in Washington, D.C., that means anything handcrafted in America. At the Museum of Modern Art Design Store in New York City, the relationship between the items for sale and the museum's vaunted design collection is more direct: All the furniture is reviewed by curators, objects of consumer interest in the collection that are currently in production are stocked, and there are reproductions of selected pieces from the collection.<p>Boosting the educational nature of museum-shop merchandise are information or provenance cards that accompany most items. These tell about the history and significance of the product, whether it's a miniature Model T from the Henry Ford Museum in Dearborn, Michigan, a rubber dinosaur from the Peabody Museum of Natural History's Dinostore for kids in New Haven, Connecticut, or sterling silver Jesuit sugar tongs from the Historic New Orleans Collection.<p>Some shops are doing more than selling museum reproductions and adaptations and the usual fare of related books, videos, and stationery. Like galleries, these innovative shops seek to foster relationships between contemporary artists and the community or consumer. In Los Angeles, the Museum of Contemporary Art asked sculptor Robert Graham to produce a limited-production bronze torso for sale in the gift shop. Some of his seven apprentices are former gang members, and the proceeds go to benefit the museum's community-outreach program. The Jewish Museum's store, which features one-of-a-kind and limited-edition pieces of contemporary Judaica, recently launched a monthly program that showcases the work of an artist or craftsperson. Shoppers have the opportunity to meet the artist on a particular day and to learn more about his or her work.<p>If the idea of supporting a cultural institution while taking care of your holiday shopping fills you with cheer, remember that almost all larger museums, including the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston and Delaware's Winterthur Museum, Gardens, and Library, have catalogs that let your fingers do the walking. Museum members generally get a 10 percent discount on all purchases, whether ordering by phone or in person, so joining may be worth the cost, even if you live far away.<p>Shoppers who aren't avid culture buffs may also rejoice that some museums, like the Art Institute of Chicago, New York's Museum of American Folk Art, and the Toledo Museum of Art, have off-site stores located in other parts of their cities. New York City's Metropolitan Museum of Art has the most far-reaching store network of any museum: 11 to date, including two on the West Coast for the bicoastal crowd, with plans on the drawing board for venues outside the United States. But don't confuse these satellite shops with commercial ventures like the Museum Company, which buys much of its merchandise wholesale from museums. The difference, of course, is that the store, not the museum, pockets the profits.<p>
The Artful Shopper<p>Art Institute of Chicago 312-443-3600
Gene Autry Western Heritage Museum 213-667-2000
Henry Ford Museum 313-271-1620
Historic New Orleans Collection 504-523-4662
Jewish Museum  212-423-3200
Metropolitan Museum of Art 212-879-5500
Musee des Arts Decoratifs  33-1-42-60-32-14
Museum of American Folk Art 212-977-7298
Museum of Contemporary Art 213-621-2766
Museum of Fine Arts, Boston 617-267-9300
Museum of Modern Art 212-708-9888
National Museum of American History 202-357-2700
National Postal Museum 202-357-1300
Peabody Museum of Natural History 203-432-5050
Phillips Collection 202-387-2151
Renwick Gallery 202-357-2700
Solomon R. Guggenheim Museum 212-423-3500
Textile Museum 202-483-0983
Toledo Museum of Art 419-255-8000
Whitney Museum's Store Next Door 212-606-0200
Winterthur Museum, Gardens, and Library 800-448-3883<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

