<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Nevermind</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Nevermind</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Reaching for nirvana, CD-ROM software has a long way to go<p>By Will Dana<p>Pardon me if i'm hopelessly stuck in the 20th century, but I've spent the last few weeks taking the future for a spin, and I just don't have time for it.<p>This particular future, interactive multimedia CD-ROM, is the computer industry's latest attempt to convince consumers that they absolutely need a personal computer at home. It's long been axiomatic that just the right combination of hardware, software, and marketing will release America's inner nerd, making the home computer as essential to our daily lives as sliced bread. But Silicon Valley is more out of touch with mainstream American tastes than even the so-called cultural elite.<p>CD-ROM stands for compact disc-read only memory. A CD-ROM looks just like a music CD. But in addition to mere music it can hold text and "real time" video. The idea, essentially, is that hooking up a specialized CD player to a computer will turn that computer into everything that your television is not; that is, it will make it interactive. While the big companies like IBM, Apple, and Microsoft--as well as scores of smaller developers--labor to figure out exactly what they mean by "information superhighways" and "500-channel digital interactive cable systems," they are pushing CD-ROM as if their lives depended on it. With some 7 million CD-ROM drives sitting on America's desktops and 15 million expected by 1994, "CD-ROM is the next evolutionary step in computing," says Tim Boyle of the San Francisco Multimedia Development Group. <p>The great advantage of CD-ROM is that the discs are cheap and offer a quantum improvement in storage space over floppy discs. Manufacturers salivate over the fact that for about one dollar per unit, a CD has a 600-megabyte capacity; that's nearly ten times more than the average hard drive. But the disc is only a storage medium. Most personal computers don't have the speed and power to efficiently deliver sound, video, and text all at once. There is simply too much information. It's like trying to manage a ten-story warehouse with just one forklift. "It's a compromised form," says Homer Flynn, one of the owners of the Cryptic Corp., which represents the Residents, a San Francisco-based group of multimedia artists who are working on a new interactive disc. "The information flow is so slow that you can only get a small window on-screen with full motion."<p>That's not to say CD-ROMs are useless. CDs are great for storing data--government records, back issues of newspapers, stock information, and dictionaries, for instance, exactly the type of data you want to get away from when you're trying to get excited about the future. The discs I sampled, sci-fi games such as Iron Helix and a travel book, From Alice to Ocean, adapted to multimedia, were stunning in their graphics and easy to use but slow. So slow in fact that I interacted with them by turning off my computer. I had high hopes for ICOM Simulations' Sherlock Holmes, Consulting Detective game, but when I booted it up, I discovered it wasn't much more than a cross between the game of Clue and a cheesy period movie, complete with bad accents. And these are the cutting-edge products. There are hundreds of other discs derisively known as shovelware.<p>The promoters of the new technology, while not quite ready to admit that it's not all its cracked up to be, seem to be under no illusions that they have to do better. They don't tell you to stay away from CD-ROM; they just talk about the future, hoping, in effect, that someone else figures out how to get the home-computer consumer excited. "My imagination is too linear to be aware of what the breakthrough product might be," says Tim Boyle. Victor Harwood of American Expositions, a company that runs computer expos, is no less sure where the industry is going: "We are just entering the period where creators are figuring things out," he says. <p>Whether or not interactive CD-ROM finally becomes the system that puts computers in every home will probably stand or fall on whether the music industry can figure out a way to excite consumers with it. Young consumers who are hooked on MTV, that is. Ty Roberts, who runs Ion, a multimedia production company in San Francisco, has positioned himself to become something like the Phil Spector of interactive music-video discs. He has one disc under his belt--an interactive version of David Bowie's latest video--has signed a $5 million deal with Bertelsmann, the West German media conglomerate, and is looking for the band with which he can make an "interactive Sgt. Pepper." All he has to do is find the right band, a band big enough to send 18-to-25-year-olds out to spend as much as $1,500 on a multimedia system. But that's in the future, a future the computer industry is more comfortable talking about than actually delivering on. For now, my inner nerd will slumber on.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
