<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Getting the Big Picture</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Getting the Big Picture</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Tish Durkin<p>God may be in the details, but for photographer Macduff Everton, who was shooting the ruins of ancient Uxmal, the picture wasn't. "I could get wonderful detail shots with my regular 35 mm," he says, "but no sense of the overall site, of what it was like to be there." He's been carrying a panoramic camera ever since.<p>Panoramic cameras aren't new, and their appeal is not hard to grasp: They stand out because they are more than twice as wide as they are high. But panoramics have never been more popular--or profuse--than they are right now. <a name="NYSE:EK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10500"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kodak</b></a>, Fuji, Nikon, Pentax, Olympus, and Minolta have all weighed in with wide-eyed models; price tags range from $13 for a cute disposable to $15,000-plus for a tripod technofeat. The overview, so to speak, is dizzying. Several different features can achieve panoramic photos--a fixed wide-angle lens, a lens that rotates, or a camera that itself rotates. Everton's own first panoramic was a Widelux ($1,200). "It looks like a crummy old camera," he recalls fondly, still faintly amazed that he could hang the Widelux around his neck and, almost never putting eye to viewfinder, just hold the lens parallel to the horizon and shoot. But the Widelux was "temperamental," erratic in the quality of image it produced and requiring constant servicing. Everton is now happily married to a sharp and stable Noblex ($2,250). For those who snap pictures on the side, though, a few thousand dollars, no matter how well spent, is too much. <p>As the wide-photo craze kicks in, beware of models that sound more panoramic than they shoot. The Nikon 600 ($300) has a lens that switches obligingly between panoramic and regular formats--which has zero effect on the picture you take. "It just crops the top and bottom," says Everton. "You are not getting a wider angle of view." The same goes for Pentax, Olympus, and Minolta. His sole "Eureka!": The dirt-cheap disposable. Kodak and Fuji panoramics cover an area of 100 degrees, doubling the vision of a normal 50-mm lens and yielding 3.5-by-10-inch prints instead of the standard 3.5-by-5-inch. (Agfa's disposable, with a 17-mm lens that will provide an extremely wide shot, should be available next year). Though hardly in the Noblex league, "the optics are surprisingly good," Everton says. "For what you pay, they're great."<p>The final image, of course, comes not from the camera but from the person using it. "You must rethink how you normally shoot," says Everton. Unlike the family snapshot, a pleasing panorama requires more than keeping the dog or the happy couple centered in the viewfinder. Edges matter. "It is like life, where we often get caught up in the details and don't notice the overall patterns," says the lensman. "In order to convey the big picture, you need to see the big picture."<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
