<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Field of Dreams</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Field of Dreams</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Surveying the world with a wide-angle view, photographers revive the panoramic format <p>By Vicki Goldberg<p>In 1845, just six years after the invention of photography, the first panoramic camera was devised; its field of vision was 150 degrees. Staring straight ahead, our eyes can do better than that--almost 180 degrees--but nothing is very sharp at the sides. Panoramic photographs always come up with more than mere human vision can imagine; every inch is miraculously detailed. The cameras have no peripheral vision: Everything they see is dead ahead.<p>Nineteenth-century panoramic cameras were hopelessly expensive and cumbersome. In 1890, an Englishman reported that a panoramic camera he had first seen in 1861 was still in perfect condition 28 years later, probably because it had only been used once. Its plates, cleaning board, dark slide, and printing frame were all curved. "Fancy the expense and trouble attending to this apparatus," he said. Nonetheless, photographers, enchanted by the ultrawide view, took some awesome pictures. The Bisson brothers in France surveyed the Alps, the English photographer Samuel Bourne looked over the sprawl of Calcutta, and George N. Barnard registered the terrain that General Sherman marched through in the South.<p>Landscape and cityscape were the subjects of choice, for the cameras could not record moving figures. There was a breadth of ambition as well as of proportion in these photographs--they meant to encompass in a single frame the expansive grandeur of nature and human accomplishment. To some extent this could be accomplished with a wide-angle lens or even with a standard camera that was rotated after each shot and the pictures then carefully aligned and pasted together. In 1878, Eadweard Muybridge depicted San Francisco in this fashion in a series of 13 plates.<p>Then, in 1900, <a name="NYSE:EK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10500"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kodak</b></a> marketed a handheld camera that used roll film, and amateurs got into the game. In some panoramic cameras the film sits still on a curved plane while the lens and a narrow-slit shutter sweep past it; the camera only focuses on one small area at a time. In others, like the well-known Cirkut camera, the lens stands still but the camera body rotates mechanically and the film goes with it, again making exposures successively through a narrow slit. When the rotation is a full 360 degrees, we have the science-fiction like ability to see, without moving, what we never could have seen without turning around.<p>The lasting popularity of panoramic photographs in America depended for a long time on commercial photographers who took pictures of the members of the Elks Club, factory workers, or entire graduating classes. A few art photographers kept up the extended photograph throughout the century. Josef Sudek, a Czech who could find poetry in simple circumstances, rehabilitated an old panoramic camera after World War II and took pictures of streets and garden walks that seemed to curve or even bulge out toward us in ways no self-respecting rules of perspective would permit.<p>This is one of the seductions of panorama, that it can subvert the eye's experience, presenting an unfamiliar world in brilliant detail. In the last two or three decades, more and more photographers have tried this. Kenneth Snelson's color photographs seem to propose a physics of curved space. The streets of Paris and Venice go off at unlikely angles, single buildings may repeat themselves at the edges of the frame, urban geometry runs a fever and goes slightly loopy.<p>Other recent work depends more on the lure of views that take time to traverse. Art Sinsabaugh's pictures suggest the infinite reach of the Midwestern farmlands by cutting a narrow slice through the landscape; Stuart D. Klipper records the harsh, bold emptiness of Antarctica. In Lois Conner's eloquent platinum prints of China and Turkey, the landscape calmly unfurls like a scroll opened out for viewing. Mark Klett has rephotographed San Francisco in 13 images as Muybridge once did; when the two sets of images are shown together, they deliver an instant lesson in American history. <p>The recent revival of panoramic pictures was sparked by cameras produced by Russian and Japanese manufacturers around 1959, as well as by such easy-to-operate versions as the Widelux 150, introduced in 1973. The '60s and '70s were a time of renewed interest in landscape photography and rampant experimentation in photography in general; the odd, elongated format posed a challenge photographers took on eagerly. Now the panorama has really arrived: In 1984, the International Association of Panoramic Photographers was founded in Hampton, Virginia, and is now based in Orlando, Florida. Most of its members come from the United States but some from as far as Bangladesh, Finland, and Australia--a veritable panorama of the world.<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
