<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Wash, Wash, Wash, and Wear</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Wash, Wash, Wash, and Wear</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
We go in search of the indestructible button <p>By Carla Koehl<p>Faster than you can say "cheap offshore labor," the buttons on most new men's dress shirts will have already started chipping, cracking, breaking, dangling, falling off--and generally rendering millions of otherwise resourceful men utterly helpless. So it should come as a relief to learn that Coors Ceramicon Designs, a division of Adolph Coors, has recently developed new, Chinese-laundry-resistant buttons: Diamond Zs, which, according to Coors Ceramicon, can withstand just about any daily abuse short of being left in the path of a falling anvil.<p>Wondering how they'd hold up to everyday use, we decided to test these newfangled fasteners--and the shirts to which they're sewn--to see just how strong both shirt and button really were. Four all-cotton broadcloths were sent to the laundry, including a Perry Ellis Portfolio with ordinary plastic buttons ($42.50), a Sulka with high-end mother-of-pearl buttons ($115), and two shirts--an Ike Behar ($72.50) and a Nordstrom's private label ($52.50)--that have exclusive rights to Diamond Zs through the end of this month. <p>The results: After 25 times through the wash, nine times in a machine presser, and 16 rounds of hand ironing at a rather hostile neighborhood laundry, the pricier new Diamond Zs (eight to ten cents each for a shirtmaker to buy) had darkened at the edges, looking a little tired next to their cheap plastic rivals (less than a penny each).<p>Though the strength of the ubiquitous plastic button wasn't news to anyone at the Chinese laundry, it was news to us. That's because Coors Ceramicon--which makes such life-saving impermeables as bullet-proof vests--has made a fairly big deal of the fact that its Diamond Z buttons are even stronger than plastic, being made, as they are, out of sand that has been transformed into zirconia (yes, as in simulated diamonds), then fired at 3,200 degrees.<p>Unfortunately, buttons this strong are of little use when they come out of the wash considerably darker than the white shirts to which they're attached. After the first nine washings and machine pressings, the Diamond Zs were still in one piece, but surprisingly, they'd turned charcoal colored around the white-coated edges. After another 16 washings and, this time, hand ironings, they looked even worse. Coors Ceramicon brand manager Kristin Michas says the Diamond Zs can discolor if they meet with an old washing machine or iron. Since the rock-hard zirconia won't give way to pressure the way plastic does, she says, the resulting friction can cause rust or dirt to rub off onto them.<p>Despite the darkening, the Diamond Zs came out in much better shape than Sulka's mother-of-pearl buttons, which were chipped, scratched, and discolored. The plastic buttons on the Perry Ellis shirt came out with hardly a scratch. <p>The unfortunate part about our findings is that the strongest buttons are available on the cheapest, weakest shirtings, and the weakest buttons are available on the most expensive shirts. Both the Perry Ellis and Nordstrom's shirts, for example, went yellow at the collar and cuffs after being washed and ironed 25 times. Ike Behar's stitching ceded a button and odd threads after just 11 washings. Sulka's shirt stayed perfectly intact. <p>Our recommendation? Buy plastic buttons on the finest shirts available within your budget. Or buy one of the shirts now made with Diamond Zs and be sure that whoever launders them has brand-new equipment.<p>And don't bother bribing Sulka to put plastic buttons on a $115 shirt. We've already tried.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

