<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Time Traveler</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Time Traveler</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Platinum designs are popular again<p>By Lauren Goldstein<p>Platinum traders were bartering on the floor of the New York Mercantile Exchange, but they weren't establishing the cost of a troy ounce of metal. Instead, the mock trading session was held to fix the price of the newest collectible Swatch, the platinum Tresor Magique. The limited-edition piece sold for about $1,500.<p>Swatch is helping to usher in a platinum-watch renaissance. The metal was most popular in the late '40s, when use surged after a wartime ban. During World War II the government stockpiled platinum for military use, including the manufacture of explosives. The jewelry industry developed white gold as a replacement, and platinum subsequently fell out of favor. Until now.<p>Seven years ago only 1,000 platinum watches were produced worldwide. Last year about 11,000 were. Platinum's growing popularity seems to be a reaction against the gaudy, gold-swathed, Trumpesque 1980s, says Laurie Hudson, president of the Platinum Guild International U.S.A.: "People are tired of ostentation and want a metal with a more refined character." <p>Ebel began offering Americans platinum options in the early 1990s but keeps fewer than 50 on hand in its New York store at any given time. Gucci introduced its first-ever platinum watch, a version of the 700M Skel ($4,000), a few months ago. Most of the 50 made available were headed for Japan, which consumes 90 percent of all the platinum jewelry produced in the world.<p>Although the popularity of platinum has not yet reached postwar-era levels, manufacturers hoping to capitalize on the metal's return to vogue have looked to the past for inspiration. Cartier has introduced the Platinum Tonneau ($10,600), inspired by a model created in 1906. The best-selling Chanel platinum watch, the Mademoiselle ($5,300), pays homage to Coco Chanel and the style of the 1930s she helped define.

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


