	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Simple Pleasures</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Simple Pleasures</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
A new book series shows you how to streamline with style<p>By Sarah Schoen<p>The '80s were the decade of (among other things) style as concept. We bought our looks lock, stock, and barrel, dressing our homes in Santa Fe, Swedish, or French Country and ourselves head to toe in Armani or Ralph Lauren. Wardrobes were easily retooled when fashion moved on, but when in the blink of an eye Spanish tiles went out and Italian marble came in, the only choice was to redecorate. <p>Times have changed, and so has our sense of style. The Chic Simple series--published by Knopf and described by the publisher as "practical primers for living stylishly with less"--addresses style in the '90s. The books are part catalog, part manual, and part mantra. Their mission is to streamline style and deconstruct design.<p>The series launched last May with Clothes and Home. The newest titles are Scents, Scarves, Bath, and Shirt and Tie. These four-by-five mini manuals sell for $12.50 and are truer to the concept than the first two larger and more expensive books. While Clothes covers everything from creating five different outfits with one navy suitto recycling classics like your old motorcycle jacket, the new books concentrate on the essentials. In Shirt and Tie it's fabric, fit, and feel (Gatsby's shirts made Daisy cry). Bath devotes a chapter to each of the four basic elements of cleansing: water, soap, scrub, and towel.<p>There may still be some '80s types around who would take issue with the Chic Simple premise, but what the '90s are about style-wise can be summed up by the aboriginal saying that begins each book: "The more you know, the less you need."<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
