<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Red, White, and Affordable</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Red, White, and Affordable</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
400 percent markups are out as restaurant wine prices become easier to swallow<p>By John Mariani<p>"Wine," wrote Ernest Hemingway, "is one of the most civilized things in the world." And the best thing about it is that it's getting more affordable all the time. Like everything else, wine must obey the laws of supply and demand, and everyone involved in selling the stuff--from French vignerons to restaurant sommeliers--is trying to make it easier to enjoy a good bottle with a meal, mostly by dropping prices to levels Americans haven't seen in years. The greedy upward spiral of prices for top Bordeaux in the 1980s has flattened out, the $50 cabernets out of California's Napa Valley have become anachronisms, and wine futures are no longer the sure-shot investments they once seemed. "For a while there, wines like Chassagne-Montrachet from the '85 and '88 vintages were up to $35 to $40 a bottle," says Jim Gordon, managing editor of the Wine Spectator, a magazine taken as gospel by many oenophiles. "But today you see the same wines from the '90 and '91 vintage going for $25 to $30." Even wine from the preeminent Burgundy estate of them all, Romanee-Conti, was found recently on the gray market at lower prices than the estate's contracted distributors were charging.<p>Restaurateurs who once routinely marked wines up 400 percent above retail are now sitting on large stocks of aging and unsold grand cru. These days wine stewards are becoming more user-friendly, and the intimidation factor once used by sommeliers who blatantly coerced a host to pop for a $200 bottle of Opus One has been replaced by a caring rapport that offers exciting wines at easy-to-swallow prices. Indeed, the last vestige of 1980s gourmandism is the conceit that a cheap wine must be a bad wine. Sirio Maccioni, owner of the haute deluxe Manhattan restaurant Le Cirque, whose international clientele would seem to be able to afford any wine it wants from the restaurant's 50,000-bottle cellar, says, "I have scores of wines on my list for under $30. If I didn't want my customers to order these wines, I wouldn't have bought them in the first place. I tell my staff to promote them because I want young people to come to Le Cirque and not be put off by the feeling they have to spend a lot of money to dine here. That's why Ihave a $29 lunch and offer wine specials each week at reasonable prices." Le Cirque also charges only $5.50 for a glass of excellent house wine--far less than many low-rent bistros charge for plonk.<p>"People drink more wine if the prices are low," says Jean-Georges Vongerichten of Vong, one of the toughest reservations to get in Manhattan right now. "A table for four is more likely to order two bottles instead of one. But you'd still be surprised at how many people avoid a wine under $15, because they can't believe it's any good. Sometimes we've raised the price on a wine that's not moving at all, then, bang! It begins to sell like crazy."<p>"You've got to take the customer by the hand--gently--and tell them, 'Listen, this is a great wine at a great price,'" says Jimmy Brennan, an owner of Brennan's in New Orleans, which offers, in addition to many inexpensive wines on a massive list, some extraordinary buys on great rarities like Lafite-Rothschild '61 at $415, Cheval Blanc '53 at $360, and Romanee-Conti '47 at $500--prices you could never get at a wine store.<p>Gone are the days when a naive or ignorant chef-owner simply bought whatever popular wines the local distributor told him to buy. Now more knowledgeable restaurateurs hold tastings, travel extensively, and seek out wines from many distributors and regions as disparate as Apulia in Italy, the Willamette Valley in Oregon, the Maipo Valley in Chile, and the PenedEs in Spain. Also, people are realizing that many of the lighter, inexpensive regional wines go well with modern cuisine. And they allow the host to flex his connoisseurship by saying things like "This wine is from the best producer in the Barossa Valley, where you don't usually get the best out of the Shiraz grape."<p>With the savory bistro foods at Atlanta's Resto des Amis, chef-co-owner Guenther Seeger looks for sturdy wines from the RhOne valley and southwest France for under $25. Instead of listing inappropriate massive, tannic Bordeaux and burgundies, Vongerichten features unusual regional wines between $20 and $30 to go with his spicy Thai-French cuisine at Vong. If you can snag a table at the hot new NOLA in New Orleans's French Quarter, you'll find a wide range of wines set in price categories, the highest being $42. When Glen and Michael Cordua debuted Americas in Houston as a restaurant featuring cuisines of North, South, and Central America, they decided to rotate their wine list every six weeks in order to find the best bargains in the market and to feature well-priced Spanish and South American wines that go well with their food. In addition, you can order every wine on the list by the glass. In San Francisco, the namesake chef-owner Alain Rondelli offers every wine on his list by the bottle, glass, and even half glass so that you can taste a wine to see if you like it.<p>Markups, which once might have been 200 percent, 300 percent, or more above retail, have dropped to saner levels (see "Best Cellars"). At the Century Cafe in New York City, the formula is wholesale plus one dollar on a choice of over 60 wines ordered after 8:00 p.m. And the wine list at Richmond, Virginia's best new restaurant, the Frog and the Redneck, offers 75 out of 100 wines for under $35. In New York one of the Broadway hits of the season has been a theater-district trattoria named Becco, whose lusty, low-priced Italian food is accompanied by wonderful wines, every one going for $15 a bottle--most from excellent small vineyards like Batasiolo and Rocco delle Macie, whose Dolcetto d'Alba and Chianti Classico, respectively, are much better, more distinctive wines than the same varieties made by better-known, high-volume producers.<p>Restaurateurs have initiated all sorts of convivial lures to attract customers. At Zoe in New York's Soho, the wine list reprints remarks and numerical ratings under individual bottlings from the Wine Spectator. Some worry, however, that a restaurant that gives only the numbers rating will tend to make people order only the highest-rated bottlings on the list and ignore some perfectly good, interesting, lesser-rated wines.<p>Wine dinners, at which diners pay a special price for a multicourse meal built around a particular producer's wines, have become extremely popular at places like New York's "21" Club, Charlie Trotter's in Chicago, the Highlands Inn in Carmel, California, and Fournou's Ovens in San Francisco. At such dinners one can dine splendiferously with wines at every course--many of them special bottlings never released to the general public and otherwise unaffordable. So drink up. Like interest rates and inflation, you may never see wine prices this low again or fine restaurateurs so willing to part with the treasures in their cellars. <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
