<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Move Over, Eiffel Tower</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Move Over, Eiffel Tower</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The Conran Shop is the Paris attraction drawing crowds<p>By Charla Carter<p>Banish any preconceptions you may have about the name. British design guru Sir Terence Conran is the same guy who was once behind the eponymous home-furnishings store chain that blankets America, but that's a thing of the past--Conran's is now owned by former Bloomingdale's executive Marvin Traub. Ever since 1987, when Conran inaugurated his design emporium, the Conran Shop in the grand Michelin Building on London's Fulham Road, Conran has been synonymous with upscale chic.<p>And now there's a Conran Shop in Paris (117 rue de Bac; 33-1-42-84-10-01). Sprawled over 16,000 square feet of an erstwhile entrepot (whose 19th-century iron structure is signed by Gustave Eiffel), the Conran Shop has become to connoisseurs of style what the Louvre is to art lovers. Here, Eames chaise longues, Noguchi tables, and Alessi kitchenware mingle with Cutler and Gross sunglasses and vials of Neal's Yard foaming bath. Whimsical wrought-iron birdcages from India jostle baskets of wood-handled gardening tools; children's toys both beautiful and educational share shelf space with packets of fresh-ground Faguais coffee and bottles of pungent Maussane olive oil. Sixty-one-year-old Conran likes to think of the store as an attraction, a place where "clients can wander around like tourists," he says.<p>Paris's Conran Shop not only showcases classics of contemporary design (including a few Terence Conran-signed pieces) and irresistibly British and French items like shortbread biscuits and woven baguette baskets, but also kilim rugs from Turkey and Morocco, jewel-toned glassware from Iran, carved wooden doors from Rajastahn, and Indonesian straw mats.<p>The Conran Shop's sources may be third world, but it remains unabashedly elitist. "It's out of the question to situate the Conran Shop on the mass market," Conran commented on his Paris shop's opening. "We will remain on the top of the pyramid, targeting a clientele who may have shopped at Habitat [the mass-market store chain also owned by Conran] before but whose tastes have evolved towards more striking design." The merchandise is so unusual, in fact, that when designer Peter Marino, known for his interiors for Giorgio Armani, Christopher Whittle, and Calvin Klein, decided on the furnishings for New York City's lavish new Barney's flagship store, the only stock piece he used was a wicker-and-chrome bistro chair from Conran's Paris store. <p>Conran's style doesn't come cheap. Though the Conran Shop likes to boast that its prices start at about $2.50 for a glass-and-chrome salt shaker, a circular oak-and-wrought-iron shelf unit designed by Conran himself carries a $1,650 price tag, and a streamlined canvas-covered couch weighs in at a hefty $5,700. So even if you leave your credit card at the hotel (sound advice for budget travelers), Paris's Conran Shop merits a visit if only for the pure visual gratification. It is rapidly becoming what Conran predicted: a cultural attraction.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


