<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Fire on the Mountain</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>   </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Fire on the Mountain</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Whether you slalom or shred, there's a slope for you<p>By Lauren Goldstein<p>Like it or not, snowboarding is the downhill winter sport of the future. Boarders bought 16 percent more lift tickets last season than the season before, and 9.4 percent of all lift tickets sold. A whole generation is growing up boarding instead of skiing: 77 percent of all boarders are under the age of 25. And it doesn't stop there: "We're seeing a lot of dads willing to take up the sport to keep up with their sons," says Lee Rogers, snowboard director of Snow Summit resort in Big Bear Lake, California. Ski legend Jean-Claude Killy, whose son is an avid boarder, is among them; the 1968 Olympic triple gold medalist is now actively campaigning to make snowboarding an Olympic event.<p>The spirit of boarding owes more to surfing and skateboarding culture than to skiing, so it's not unusual for boarders to ride over trees, picnic tables, and other obstacles on the mountain to catch air. Skiing purists who find them an annoyance are having trouble escaping them, since nearly 90 percent of American ski areas allow boarding. Snowboard-only parks have begun to spring up and are expected to multiply. Try these areas for an isolationist's experience.<p>
Board-free:
-Silver Mountain at Bear Mountain in California
-Aspen Mountain and Keystone in Colorado
-Taos Ski Valley in New Mexico
-Alta, Deer Valley, and Solitude in Utah<p>Ski-free:
-Big Air Green Valley in California
-Raging Buffalo in Illinois<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
