	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Triple-A Investing</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Triple-A Investing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
In the minor leagues, you don't have to be a millionaire to afford a diamond<p>By Emanuel Howard<p>As minor-league baseball heads to the showers for 1993, club owners are suiting up for a different kind of action: October is prime time for selling a minor-league franchise.<p>Unlike big-league ball, this isn't a moguls-only game. In fact, franchise buyers often are regular folks who convince their friends and family to form an investor group.<p>A triple-A club costs at least $5 million; double-A clubs go for $3 million and up. But buying a minority stake takes little more than a love of baseball--and about $100,000 to invest not so wisely.<p>In return, well-heeled fans can live out fantasies that will never be fulfilled by a mutual fund.<p>"We can't promise you double-digit returns," admits Dave Hersh, general partner of the double-A Memphis Chicks. "But we can promise you the things you dreamed of: spring training, tickets to the World Series, a road trip with the team."<p>Hersh says a small stake in his club costs $150,000, putting investors in league with co-owners including TV host Maury Povich and moviemaker Ron Howard. The relatively low entry point is a lure for unfulfilled fans. In 1985, Lee Anne Pagliai worked for <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>. Now she's a partner in the High Desert Mavericks, a single-A team out of Adelanto, California. "I figured if I was selling, I might as well sell baseball," she says.<p>Big-league clubs manage all their affiliated teams, so minor-league owners don't have those hassles. "You can hang around the batting cage and not have to think, 'I gave this guy a $50,000 pay cut,'" says Bobby Brett, who recently bought the triple-A Indians in Portland, Oregon. Brett's partners:His three brothers, including Royals slugger George, and his high school basketball coach. <p>An investor's main role is to ensure that the club runs smoothly--and to keep 25 million Americans returning to minor-league parks every year. This isn't easy:Players move so quickly through the leagues that fans rarely see a consistent lineup. Feisty mascots and fireworks are the real draw for many clubs.<p>"Our tickets cost the same as a movie," says bond trader Frank Bolton, an owner of the single-A Blue Rocks in Wilmington, Delaware. "We compete against Sleepless in Seattle."<p>Even in franchises that do well, earning about 10 percent profit, owners often end up reinvesting their income--or diluting their ownership by offering extra shares to fund improved facilities.<p>Says Bob Richmond of Baseball Opportunities, a broker for many club sales: "People get into baseball because they want to get into baseball--not because of the returns."<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Sports Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

