	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-The Three Scrooges</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-The Three Scrooges</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
When it comes to bashing their rivals, tightwads are generous to a fault<p>By Andrew Feinberg<p>The nation's top penny-pinchers may be tight with a buck, but they're certainly not tight with each other. In fact, cheap shots are now common currency among the self-appointed gurus who've made frugality a lucrative profession.<p>"I was retching" while reading a recent issue of the industry-leading Tightwad Gazette, snipes Mary Hunt, editor of the rival Cheapskate Monthly--one of two dozen such newsletters now being published. The reason for Hunt's nausea:Tightwad stories on reusing feminine pads and identifying edible food in dumpsters.<p>But bad taste is only the beginning. This homely little industry is abuzz with accusations about everything from inflated circulation figures to espionage.<p>The most bitter rivalry pits Ron and Melodie Moore, editors of the Skinflint News, against queen piker Amy Dacyczyn--she of the dumpster diving. Dacyczyn (pronounced "decision") is convinced the Moores are exaggerating their newsletter's popularity.<p>In part, she bases her argument on penny-pinching. If the Skinflint News really has 45,000 subscribers as claimed, she says, the Moores should be using zip-plus-four mailing codes:"They'd save hundreds of dollars a month. And they'd save $2,000 a month if they did what I did" and bought special postal machines.<p>To clinch it, Dacyczyn cites a recent price drop at the Skinflint News, which advocates draining fried food on grocery bags instead of wasting "expensive" paper towels. "Who gives away $100,000 in annual profits?" she wonders.<p>Melodie Moore replies, "We negotiated a better printing deal and passed that on." But the Moores won't document their circulation claims. "We don't have anything to prove," Melodie Moore snaps, hanging up.<p>Dacyczyn says she has records to verify her claimed circulation of 55,000. But that doesn't get her off the hook with the Moores.<p>In June, Ron Moore spent an hour bad-mouthing Dacyczyn to Worth. Among other things, he griped that Dacyczyn sent employees to Florida to spy on him --perhaps to steal ideas, perhaps to prove the Moores aren't as cheap as they claim.<p>Tightwad employee Ellie Ring admits she tried to see the Moores' setup while visiting a nearby home in Florida but says it was her own idea. Ron Moore refused to let Ring in, and now he won't even discuss the rivalry.<p>"I wish you wouldn't print something like that," Moore sighs, fresh from appearing on a magazine cover and the Home television show. "I don't want any negative publicity."<p>The stakes in this dogfight are hardly penny-ante. Besides newsletter sales, there's a bundle to be made by successful books:Dacyczyn's best-selling Tightwad Gazette has 300,000 copies in print. Hunt's The Best of the Cheapskate Monthly--replete with tips such as rinsing coffee filters for reuse--counts 100,000 copies, while the Moores' Smart Cents tallies more than 75,000.<p>And in an industry that trades heavily on its friendly, homespun image, the misers' backbiting may carry a price.<p>Says Dacyczyn, who advocates cutting wide rubber bands in half lengthwise, thereby doubling their number:"This kind of talk makes us all look petty."<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
