<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Safe at Home</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Safe at Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
The Jays feathered their nests with their World Series cash<p>By James Buckley Jr.<p>In 1949, a thrilled Jerry Coleman of the Yankees took his World Series check for $5,400 and ran to buy his first-ever car. The traditional Series bonus has grown a lot, but it won't hold such primal joy for the well-paid players who become world champions this month--at least, not if last year's winners are any indicator.<p>For most of the Toronto Blue Jays, the 1992 Series bonus of $114,962.16 was just another paycheck. In fact, most of the Jays we asked couldn't say exactly where their share of the loot went. <p>Only a few Jays--mostly rookies and staff--did any more than hand their bonus to a business manager after knocking off the Atlanta Braves in six games. And even the big spenders spent conservatively. A Jay's idea of splurging, in two words:Real estate.<p>The players' award pool, which is split between 12 teams, is created with 60 percent of the gate receipts from the first four games of both the league championships and the World Series. The remaining 40 percent, and the entire gate from any extra best-of-seven games, is split between Major League Baseball and the owners of the two Series clubs. (That explains why Marge Schott groused when her underdog Cincinnati Reds swept the 1990 Series in four games.)<p>Once the winning team's share of the pool is determined, the 25-man Series roster decides how to split it. Partial-season players might get less, as might trainers and other club personnel. After last year's Series, 35 members of the Blue Jays organization were handed full-share checks. Nineteen got partial shares, and the club gave cash grants to 14 more people. For most recipients, security came before indulgence.<p>Mark Eichhorn, pitcher
"I paid off the mortgage on my new house in Santa Cruz, California. Two acres and lots of trees--and the ocean is only a 78-mile-an-hour fastball away."<p>Ed Sprague, third baseman
The rookie pinch-hit a homer that won Game Two. He used his check to finish building a dream home in Stockton, California. But no pool for wife Kristen Babb-Sprague, an Olympic gold-medal winner in synchronized swimming: "I'd have never gotten her out of it."<p>Pat Hentgen, pitcher
The Series bonus more than doubled his income. His reaction would warm any parent's heart: "I put a down payment on a house in Macomb County, Michigan, 15 minutes from where I grew up."<p>Tommy Craig, trainer
When the Jays won the AL Eastern Division title in 1985, he used his bonus to buy a new house in Tarpon Springs, Florida. After the Series last year, he refurbished it. "I've got a pool and an exercise room, and everything looks like new."<p>Duane Ward, pitcher
The stolid reliever has banked his bonus for now but may change his mind. "I'm always looking for things to add to my collection of baseball memorabilia, like uniforms, baseballs, and cards. I might use the money for that."<p>Devon White, outfielder
Then there's Devo. Found near the batting cage before a recent game, he would only smile mysteriously:"Oh, believe me, it went to a worthy cause."<p>Maybe, just maybe, there's one old-time player left in Toronto.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Sports Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

