	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Rebuilt for Speed</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Rebuilt for Speed</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Father and son rescue a cheesy cartoon, retooling it for success in the MTV age<p>By Thomas E. Weber<p>When a father starts tinkering under the hood of a classic sports car, it's only natural for him to ask his son to lend a hand.<p>That's what John Rocknowski figured when he set about tuning up the old Speed Racer cartoon for a comeback. And by putting son Jim, 34, in charge of U.S. licensing for Speed Racer Enterprises, Rocknowski gained more than a helpmate--he got an unabashed fan of the cheesy Japanese serial.<p>"I used to come and whip on the TV" to watchSpeed Racer, says Jim Rocknowski. "Being in tune with fans helps me figure out what to do here." Speed Racer, about a brash teenager and his fantastic car, was a staple for millions of children in the '60s. Now that its comeback is accelerating, the Rocknowskis think a new generation is ready for Speed. John Rocknowski, 62, has sunk about $6 million into the property since he snapped up rights in 1991. Together with Jim, he's jump-started a show that had languished for years.<p>The break came when MTV --like most cable channels, hungry for programming--granted Speed a regular time slot. Jim Rocknowski scored the coup with a free trial, allowing MTVto air Speed reruns at no charge. When viewership of the slot jumped as much as 50 percent from the previous offering, MTVbit and the Rocknowskis rejoiced: Speed is now a six-times-a-week supplement to the station's music videos.<p>MTV's heavy rotation is a partial solution to the Rocknowskis' number-one dilemma:how to ease the cartoon away from nostalgic baby busters and toward the gold mine of 1990s kiddie markets. With that aim, the elder Rocknowski, a veteran marketer of other cartoons, has more deals in motion. Speed merchandise is now on store shelves, for example, and a video game is in the works. A cartoon movie has been cobbled together from several old episodes.<p>Most important, though, is The New Adventures of Speed Racer, an updated TVshow that hits syndication this month. New Speed got major body work to ensure it appeals to kids; even the sleek design of the Mach Vcar was altered.<p>"With all due respect to the nostalgic aspects, [baby busters] are not our target audience," says producer Fred Wolf. "We're sensitive to the legacy, but we have to compete with newer shows."<p>So far, the Rocknowskis have seen little returnfrom their investment. And with new Speed episodes costing about $250,000 each, it'll be a while before they cash in on Speed's new hipness. "I don't think we'll hit the peak until 1996 or 1997," says John.<p>Neither he nor Jim fully understands Speed's staying power. "It was a weird, cutting-edge show," says Jim. "It's old enough to be new again.
 <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
