<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Crazed Like a Fox</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Crazed Like a Fox</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
The only certainties for Alex Gabor are debt and taxes, and he won't pay either<p>By Carla Koehl<p>Maybe you saw the ad in Esquire. Or Premiere.<p>Maybe you were intrigued enough to consider ordering a book called Confessions of a Sex-Crazed Money Man.<p>Maybe you're lucky you didn't. You'd have taken your chances with the author--admitted sex addict, polygamy advocate, and master debtor Alex S. Gabor.<p>Gabor admits that some customers who bought his book were overcharged by more than $100. What's more, he admits stiffing about a dozen magazines for at least $150,000 worth of ad space for Confessions.<p>The Hungarian-born Gabor also has peeved more than 20 other businesses and individuals, mostly around Seattle, who claim he owes them a total of more than $100,000 for schemes ranging from real estate deals to rave parties gone awry.<p>Gabor, 37, acknowledges many of these debts. He says he owes about $300,000 and that he'll pay it all. Eventually. After the Internal Revenue Service is eliminated.<p>"When the IRS no longer exists," Gabor reads aloud from Confessions, "I will pay off all of my creditors 100 percent on the dollar."<p>Plus interest?<p>"Sure. Plus interest."<p>To Alex Gabor, a.k.a. Gabriel Acs, a.k.a. Gabriel Alexander, a.k.a. Gabriel O. Di Safeyette, a.k.a. Gabor Sandor Acs--"it's only 30 bucks to change your name"--the tax system is the root of all evil. Don't understand? Read the book, he says.<p>Confessions details Gabor's sexual and financial exploits in a rambling diary-cum-political critique. At the end of a chapter titled "The Tuna Highway," he grandly forgives himself "for all offenses I may have committed . . .  while a member of this planet's social order."<p>Others aren't as generous. Worth spoke to 50 people, including a few Gabor told us would vouch for his good character.<p>Only one did. A more typical response:"I think he's clinically insane," says David Meinert, a Seattle music agent who says Gabor owes him money. "I don't know anyone who hasn't been scammed by him."<p>And he was one of Gabor's handpicked references.<p>Two people who helped Gabor sell Confessions say buyers were relieved of considerable sums when zeros were added to their $11.95 credit card bills--and one worker says buyers were also billed $100 extra if they ordered another author's book. Gabor says the overcharges were the fault of an incompetent employee he declines to identify, and that he intends to refund the money.<p>For his blizzard of ads, Gabor is in the hole to magazines across the country:Esquire says it's out $50,000, Premiere $58,000. "I'm looking for him, too," says Ed Gonzaga, a Seattle licensing inspector. Gabor owes the city taxes for various events he produced during the last year.<p>Lots of people would love to sue Gabor. But finding him isn't easy:Worth made more than 70 phone calls to track him down, finally finding him in Seattle at the Center for Applied Metapsychology, where he says he's recovering from an addiction to pot.<p>"I'm not hiding out,"insists Gabor, who can be reached only by leaving a message on phone mail. "I'm busy writing a script." He claims he's sold another script to an unnamed actor for $300,000.<p>Also on his agenda are two more books. "My goal," he confides, "is to sell a million copies . . .  and use the proceeds to abolish the IRS. And make some money for myself."<p>But so far, he's sold just 2,000 copies of Confessions--grossing, well, at least $23,900.<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
