<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-A Killer Auction</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-A Killer Auction</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Uncle Sam wants to sell Jerry Lee Lewis's childhood piano<p>By Tara McKelvey<p>At this rate, the Internal Revenue Service will be opening its own branch of the Hard Rock Cafe.<p>The latest addition to the agency's revolving collection of confiscated music memorabilia:Jerry Lee Lewis's childhood piano. The upright is due to be sold at public auction, following in the tradition of Sammy Davis Jr.'s tap shoes and Willie Nelson's grand piano.<p>First, however, the IRS must prove it's the true owner of the instrument, now moldering in the Delta auction house in Memphis. This month Kerrie Lewis, the Killer's sixth wife, will argue in court that she has a better claim on the piano:She bought it after Jerry Lee's 1988 bankruptcy, she says, so the IRS can't use it to pay her husband's back taxes.<p>The piano itself is no prize. Half the ivory is falling off the keys, the paint is chipped, and it has been "kind of pasted together to keep from falling to the floor," says a Delta employee. Still, the auctioneers think it'll fetch "in the thousands"--a start toward paying off Lewis's debt of about $3.7 million in taxes, penalties, and interest.<p>Despite its condition, the Starck piano has a priceless history. As a youngster in Ferriday, Louisiana, Lewis pounded out his first chords on it. He learned to play alongside cousins Jimmy Swaggart--later to gain fame as a defiled minister--and Mickey Gilley, who would become known for running the Texas honky-tonk featured in Urban Cowboy.<p>The piano was the most notable item seized by the IRS when it cleaned out Lewis's home in Nesbit, Mississippi, in May. Lewis had previously removed other valuable keepsakes, including gold records he received for such songs as "Whole Lotta Shakin' Goin' On" and "Great Balls of Fire."<p>Nonetheless, the IRS spent a day filling three 24-foot trucks with more than 350 items. Included in the haul:A plaque from a Jerry Lee Lewis fan club in Holland, an exercise video, and ten Duraflame logs.<p>"They even got the shower curtain,"says David Monypeny, an attorney in Memphis who represents Lewis.<p>While this was going on, Lewis was traveling  with Kerrie and their son, Lee; shortly afterward, the family decided to settle awhile in Ireland. A spokesman says Lewis isn't evading the IRS; it must simply be coincidence that Irish tax laws exempt income from artistic efforts. Either way, Lewis, now 58, traveled light. An IRS official in Jackson, Mississippi, says the agency took everything in Lewis's house except young Lee's toys.<p>Lewis, who popped up as a guest at a Bruce Springsteen concert soon after his arrival in Dublin, has traded wits with the feds since the 1970s. He still owes taxes for 11 years and ducked a criminal rap by proving he was too uneducated to understand the tax code.<p>Lewis even dedicated a song to the IRS in 1979. Called "Milk Cow Blues," it's a sweet, bluesy tune about a man whose woman has left him. The IRS won't see any money from it, though: His label never released the record.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Entertainment Industry, Government Adgency 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
