<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-The Other Kitchen Cabinet</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-The Other Kitchen Cabinet</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Washington chefs are ushering in changes faster than the Clinton administration<p>By Randall Fuller<p>Forget health-care reform and middle-class tax breaks. The politics of change currently sweeping Washington is in the kitchen. Less than six months after Bill Clinton called on government to engage in "bold, persistent experimentation," nearly a dozen innovative restaurants have opened in the nation's capital. Chefs from around the country have migrated to the city and quickly transformed eating habits that until recently had seemed trapped between the Eisenhower and Nixon administrations. Says Washington Post food critic Phyllis C. Richman, "Suddenly, and somewhat unexpectedly, Washington's become an outlandishly hot place to eat." <p>Inquire about this sudden interest in food, and you may get a reply that sounds like reheated campaign rhetoric. "Three or four years ago, this town was too ensconced in formal French cooking to even consider opening a restaurant," says Mark Miller, who started the trend of new restaurants a year and a half ago with his wildly successful Red Sage, on 14th Street. "What happened? I think the status quo finally gave way." Indeed, in less time than it takes to push a budget bill through Congress, the new administration has permanently altered the dining culture of Washington. New and stylish cafes have replaced Republican power haunts as the places to lunch, and even old take-out joints no longer receive most-favored-trade status (while Bush and Reagan staffers were content to order from Domino's, young Democrats prefer Listrani's upscale "Mediterranean" pizzas--Horwood Gdid I do the Mdash correctly. chicken and broccoli with feta and fontina cheeses). One sip of a double decaf iced cappuccino at Georgetown's brand-new Dean & DeLuca market--which unlike its New York City counterpart offers Bill and Hillary gingerbread cookies and Arkansas peppered ham--and you quickly catch the flavor of the Clinton era. <p>Palladin, the latest eponymous restaurant from Jean-Louis Palladin, is a perfect example of the kind of dinner place that is flourishing under the new administration. Set below the Watergate Hotel, the restaurant is a sophisticated but less expensive version of the much-heralded Jean-Louis. The food--continental technique applied to local American ingredients--seems custom-made for a small-town Ozark boy educated at Oxford. So far, however, the commander in chief has yet to try the sublime milk-fed Virginia leg of lamb with ragout of flageolets or raviolis of Maine scallops.<p>Fiscal responsibility also plays a role at Gerard's Place, the 65-seat coral-colored bistro within jogging distance of the White House, on 15th Street NW. A two-star chef in Paris before leaving to work at the Ritz-Carlton in Pentagon City, Gerard Pangaud opened the restaurant a month and a half after Clinton took office. "I wanted to create something smart and sophisticated," he says, "but not too snobbish or expensive." The result--populism with a French accent--has already attracted at least one powerful FOB: National Economic Council chief Robert Rubin is regularly spotted there at lunch. <p>Of course, part of the capital's booming restaurant scene can be attributed to the second most powerful group in Washington: Hollywood. Citronelle, the chic Georgetown restaurant set inside the Latham Hotel and run by L.A. chef Michel Richard, has been mobbed nearly every night since Janet Reno and Barbra Streisand met for the culinary equivalent of Camp David. Billy Crystal and Sam Waterston have stopped in on their way from the White House, as has political heavyweight Henry "the Fonz" Winkler. According to some old Washington hands, the commotion around a recent visit by William Baldwin brought back memories of the days when JFK and the Rat Pack dined at the then-new Sans Souci. (As for Washington's real celebrities: Warren Christopher is a regular at Citronelle, as are media heavy hitters Art Buchwald and David Brinkley.)<p>Still, Washington has always molded itself to the image of its leader, which helps explain the recent influx of food from below the Mason-Dixon line. The trend began with Vidalia, Jeffrey Buben's slick Southern eatery on M Street. Buben started work on the new restaurant as soon as he left his job at the Republican-favored Occidental Grill--the day after the inauguration, as it turned out. Lawyers and lobbyists crowd Vidalia for lunch, but dinner, featuring wild mushroom ragout with Virginia ham, cream gravy over a rosemary biscuit, and plenty of fresh cornbread, is when Buben's talents really sparkle. Next came the down-home Dixie Grill, located across the street from Ford's Theater. A hangout for Bubba wanna-bes and agents from the nearby FBI building, the place debuted soon after Chris Zarpas, former president of Island Pictures and co-owner of the restaurant with his brother Stephen, returned from a road trip to Little Rock just before the election. People come for the pool table and jukebox as well as the corn-fried catfish, french-fried sweet potatoes, and gumbo pie. Finally, there's Georgia Brown's Fine Southern Cuisine, on 15th Street NW, which opened in July with a host of low-country dishes, including Cape Fear River clams and crab cakes with collard greens. <p>As if to remind us that no government can afford to focus entirely on domestic policy, three international restaurants opened within the administration's first 100 days. Cafe Milano is a trendy Italian trattoria in Georgetown, while Jaleo, a Spanish tapas bar brightened by a mural of a flamenco dancer, is located in the newly booming downtown area. Most interesting of all is Mimmetta, on Eye Street, which was opened in March by Sicilian cookbook author Mimmetta Lo Monte. Workers from the nearby World Bank and IMF offices stop by for the beef with chocolate sauce and snails with mint, garlic, and bread crumbs. "But," admits Lo Monte, "I'm still waiting for Clinton and Gore to try my gelati."<p>Indeed, in a town where power is not only an aphrodisiac but a surefire way to keep a place booked, restaurateurs are clamoring to attract influential Democrats. The John Hay Room at the Hay-Adams Hotel, a traditional spot for power breakfasts directly across from the White House, recently hired chef Patrick Clark for a three-year contract rumored at $250,000 a year in an effort to lure the Clinton administration. The president instead has ventured to Restaurant Nora, the 14-year-old restaurant whose reputation for political correctness was oddly enhanced when George Stephanopoulos reportedly broke up with his girlfriend there. About the menu, full of heartfelt assurances that "animals are raised in a stress-free environment, fed highly nutritional ingredients with no pesticides or antibiotics, and butchered at the peak of their strength," Clinton was moved to comment: "The food is good, but I couldn't understand the menu."<p>Still, the most popular restaurant with the administration continues to be Red Sage. A multimillion-dollar cowboy fantasy, it remains the wittiest restaurant in D.C.: A cloud over the chili bar flickers with simulated heat lightning, and margaritas are made with passion fruit and served with a plastic barbed wire stirrer. Bill took Hillary there for Valentine's Day (the first couple's first dinner out in Washington), and on a busy night you're liable to see Les Aspin, Warren Christopher, Janet Reno, and even Tipper Gore. All of which is why Miller, who also owns Santa Fe's Coyote Cafe, is developing another restaurant for the capital--this time using cuisines from the Pacific Rim. <p>True, not all has changed in the capital. Clinton and Bob Dole chose the clubbish Duke Zeibert's for a recent dinner date, and Sam Donaldson continues to pay for drinks at the Jefferson after taping Prime Time. But to paraphrase another young Democratic president, there hasn't been such an intense appreciation of food in one place since Thomas Jefferson dined alone in the White House.<p>
RECOMMENDED RESTAURANTS<p>Prices are average for a three-course dinner per couple; drinks, tax, and tip not included. The area code for Washington, D.C., is 202.<p>Cafe Milano, 3251 Prospect St. NW; 333-6183. $50.<p>Citronelle, 3000 M St. NW; 625-2150. $79.<p>Dean & DeLuca, 3276 M St. NW; 342-2500. Double cappuccino, $2.80.<p>Dixie Grill, 518 10th St. NW; 628-4800. $33.<p>Georgia Brown's, 950 15th St. NW; 393-4499. $50.<p>Girard's Place, 915 15th St. NW; 737-4445. $75.<p>John Hay Room, 1 Lafayette Square; 638-6600. $81.<p>Jaleo, 480 7th St. NW; 628-7949. $48.<p>Mimmetta, 1919 Eye St. NW; 659-4447. $54.<p>Palladin, 2650 Virginia Ave. NW; 298-4455. $56.<p>Red Sage, 605 14th St. NW; 638-4444. $75.<p>Restaurant Nora, 2132 Florida Ave. NW; 462-5143. $71.<p>Vidalia, 1990 M St. NW; 659-1990. $58.<p>
ARE YOU WHAT YOU EAT?<p>We polled several Washington restaurants with political followings and discovered that listening to a voice count on Bill Clinton's budget package isn't the only way to tell the left from the right. There is some common ground between the two parties. Nearly every restaurant said that liberals and conservatives alike have cut down on hard liquor. (A notable exception was Red Sage, which manager Don Senich wishfully characterizes as "an oasis of political bipartisanship": 2,000 margaritas are sold there each week.) Duke Zeibert's strawberry cheesecake cuts across party lines as do crab cakes from the Monocle. <p>Democrat Dinner<p>Chardonnay, Citronelle. Margarita, Red Sage. Crispy shrimp, Citronelle. Eggplant steak, Restaurant Nora. Mushroom risotto, Restaurant Nora. Crab cakes, the Monocle. Fresh blueberry pie, Restaurant Nora. Strawberry cheesecake, Duke Zeibert's. <p>Republican Dinner<p>Beer, Red, Hot & Blue. Margaritas, Red Sage. Onion-ring loaf, Red, Hot & Blue. Grilled Black Angus strip steak, Occidental Grill. Tennessee Triple (barbecued beef, pork, and chicken), Red, Hot & Blue. Crab cakes, the Monocle. Mocha mousse torte, Occidental Grill. Strawberry cheesecake, Duke Zeibert's. <p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/6pages.gif"><br>About 6 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
