		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Mondo Miami</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Mondo Miami</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
There's much more than South Beach on humorist Dave Barry's personal tour<p>By Carla Koehl<p>In 1986, syndicated columnist Dave Barry moved to Florida from Glen Mills, Pennsylvania ("It's exactly like Miami without the machine-gun fire"). It was then that he realized insects, not humans, were the dominant species. "I've seen grasshoppers all my life, but these things block your path," he says. "The animal life is much closer here. It's in your bathroom."<p>When Out-of-Towners Arrive: "We offer them a toothbrush and tell them to go to the Grand Bay Hotel [2669 S. Bayshore Drive; 305-858-9600] in Coconut Grove. It's elegant, fun, and has a nice Florida feel."<p>Favorite Restaurant: "At Coco Walk in Coconut Grove, there's Cafe Tu Tu Tango [3015 Grand Avenue; 305-529-2222], which has a really elaborate, complicated menu--mostly Caribbean food--with tons of hors d'oeuvres. I always order about ten of them and imported beer, which is very important."<p>Favorite Dive Bar: "The Taurus Steakhouse [3540 Main Highway; 305-448-0633]. It's an old, eccentric little bar where the bartender always dresses up. In August he's come in as Santa Claus. The Taurus also has a ring-toss game. It's low-tech, but hey--it still works when the power's out in a hurricane."<p>Getting to a Miami Heat Game: "You go to the 1800 Club [1800 N. Bayshore Drive; 305-373-1093], which is right near the Miami Herald, and buy tickets from a scalper. Then get on the trolley that the bar hires, drink in hand, go see the game, and come back to the 1800 Club to eat."<p>Favorite Live-Music Spot: "Tobacco Road [626 S. Miami Avenue; 305-374-1198]. It's the oldest, first licensed bar in Miami. Sort of hidden away. They serve a yuppie crowd at lunch. But at night it's just a good, good bar, with mostly blues bands."<p>What Not to Do: "Go on an airboat ride in the Everglades. I had this vision of the Everglades being like the Brazilian rain forest. But it's swamp, endless grass, and muck. Theoretically, there are all kinds of rare and exotic creatures, but the airboat, which is designed to be louder than a hydrogen-bomb test, makes all the animals disappear."<p>How to Pass for a Local: "No native here uses traffic signals. In fact, anyone who obeys traffic laws at all is generally assumed to be from Iowa and is usually robbed for it."
 <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
