<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Help Wanted</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Help Wanted</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Personal digital assistants put efficiency in your palm<p>By Thomas E. Weber<p>Pocket organizers have been around for years, logging appointments and remembering telephone numbers, but tiny rows of keys were a poor substitute for putting pen to paper inside a Filofax. Now manufacturers are getting the point--pens are easy to use, and computers aren't. New pen-based computers, known as personal digital assistants, are doing away with rigid software, which often requires the patience only Wizardheads--gadget freaks named after the Sharp organizer--can muster. A PDA will let you scribble and jot using a stylus on a touch-sensitive screen, and with the help of some fancy programming, it will try to read your mind a bit, too. "Intelligent assistant" software helps route your scrawl to the right location--calendar, address book, to-do list--without specific instructions from you. The introductory hype for PDAs has created high expectations: A television commercial for the <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> EO unit shows a relaxed executive sending a fax from the beach (ever try to clean sand out of a computer?). Here's a look at some of the major players:<p>Newton MessagePad
Manufacturer: <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple Computer</b></a>
Street price: $699
Size: 4.5 in. x 7.25 in. x 0.75 in.
Weight: 14 ounces
Battery life: Two weeks of normal use
Most useful feature: Intelligent-assistant software
Most useless feature: Acts as an autodialer when held up to the phone
Gee-whiz feature: A puff of animated smoke appears when you delete a note<p>Despite some bad buzz before its introduction, Newton delivers. While other pen-based units have evolved from laptops or organizers, Apple designed Newton from scratch (see "Newton's Core") to be an all-encompassing technology for information management, with the MessagePad serving as the doorway. A few examples: Apple is launching a Newton electronic mail service that users can access with a pocket-size modem. For those who tote the kind of pager that can receive brief text messages, a plug-in card for the MessagePad will replace it.<p>Apple advises users to think of it as "an endless roll of notepaper." Write whatever you want, and Newton's intelligent-assistant software will guess what to do with it, based on preprogrammed knowledge and observation of your habits. Newton would look at a note stating "lunch with Lisa tomorrow" and surmise that it should add the date to tomorrow's calendar. If you have more than one Lisa in your address book, Newton suggests the Lisa whose name appears most often.<p>It can store a sketch in its original form, or it can clean up doodles, replacing them with straight lines and perfect circles. When using the optional modem (a Newton-modem bundle costs $100 more than the MessagePad alone), tapping your location on a world map tells MessagePad where you are, letting it dial and fax shrewdly, omitting area codes.<p>These features make Newton simple and intuitive for technophobes. For those who have mastered their personal computer, Newton's friendly style may seem disorderly and perplexing at first. And the idea of giving up some control to Newton's smart software can be disquieting. But Apple has definitely done its homework by sketching a thoroughly new framework for computing and filling in the details. Newton won't just replace paper organizers; it will supersede them.<p>Zoomer<p>Manufacturer: Casio, <a name="NYSE:TAN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11441"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tandy</b></a>
Street price: $699
Size: 4.2 in. x 6.8 in. x 1 in.
Weight: 16 ounces
Battery life: 100 hours
Most useful feature: Built-in versions of  popular software
Most useless feature: Built-in solitaire game
Gee-whiz feature: 26-language translator<p>Zoomer is ideal for personal computer users who don't want to lug around a notebook or spend time recharging batteries on the road. Two of its best features have been transferred straight from PCs: Pocket Quicken and <a name="NASD:AMER"></a><b>America Online</b>. Pocket Quicken is a streamlined version of Intuit's personal-finance software. A special version of America Online lets Zoomer users plug in a modem and access online services--electronic mail, stock quotes, news, and airline reservations. You can even send a fax by routing it through America Online.<p>Handwriting recognition, turning your scrawled notes into neatly typed text, is a bit slow on Zoomer. It's fine for quick notes, but lengthy letters may be frustrating. Also, the screen is a bit dim and may require some experimentation to find the optimum viewing angle. For experienced PC users, though, Zoomer's Windows-like software makes it a good option.<p>AT&T EO 440<p>Manufacturer: EO Inc.
Street price: $1,999
Size: 7.1 in. x 10.8 in. x 0.9 in.
Weight: 35 ounces
Battery life: 4 hours
Most useful feature: Large, sharp screen
Most useless feature: Short battery life
Gee-whiz feature: Lets you record voice notes<p>EO is positioned as a "personal communicator." It's not a pocket-size assistant, and it's not a laptop computer either. In fact, the base model would be a poor substitute for either. But with the addition of an internal modem ($500) and a cellular-phone module ($799), EO is transformed into a hybrid of computer, phone, and fax machine at the size and price of a high-end laptop.<p>A powerful chip called Hobbit drives the EO and helps the machine do a speedy job of handwriting recognition. With its cellular-phone module, EO can then fax those notes. Want to phone instead? Tap the appropriate entry in EO's address book, and it will even dial for you.<p>EO, like Newton, also includes intelligent software. For instance, writing "call Bob" in EO's calendar causes the device to display a note alerting the user if Bob isn't listed in the address book.<p>Despite these impressive capabilities, EO is relatively large and heavy for a pen-based device. After all, one advantage to getting rid of traditional keyboards is making portable computers slimmer. EO is best for users, such as businessmen often on the road, who want to make full use of its modem and cellular-phone add-ons and don't mind carrying them around. Otherwise, consider a laptop for computing power or a pocket organizer for portability.<p>Wizard OZ-9600II<p>Manufacturer: Sharp Electronics 
Street price: $499
Size: 4.1 in. x 7.1 in. x 1 in.
Weight: 15 ounces
Battery life: 80 hours
Most useful feature: Beaming memos straight to a printer
Most useless feature: Beaming doodles to another Wizard
Gee-whiz feature: Has actual keyboard  buttons<p>Wizard bridges the gap between simple electronic organizers and pen-based devices. Unlike Zoomer, Newton, and EO, Wizard can't translate handwriting into computer text. Instead, it stores pictures of what's been written and drawn on its touch screen. For all but the most rudimentary uses, text must be entered using a miniature keyboard. For users who plan on writing memos on the move, that's not necessarily bad. Wizard's keys, while smaller and more difficult to type on than a standard keyboard, allow text entry at a much faster rate than units dependent on handwriting recognition. The touch screen is available for entering drawings.<p>Wizard provides the basics: an address book and a calendar. It also offers a nicely thought-out to-do list which tracks completed tasks in a "done entries" section. Wizard's common-sense interface doesn't offer intelligent assistance, but controls are clearly marked, and calendars, notepads, and to-do lists look like their paper analogues. Like the completely pen-based units, Wizard can be hooked up to a PC (with additional software) to transfer information.<p>If you enter a lot of text, Wizard may be the PDA for you. It may not have the glamour of the pen-based Newton or Zoomer, but sometimes glamour is no substitute for a keyboard.<p>
NEWTON'S CORE<p>How did apple computer fulfill a promise to introduce groundbreaking technology in five months? Simple. They locked a team of high-tech wizards in a square, windowless room and prayed for a miracle. "Basically, these guys were told to come up with the next cool thing," says photojournalist Doug Menuez, who was granted complete access by Apple to chronicle the Newton project for the new book Horwood Gthis might be a November book Defying Gravity: The Making of Newton (Beyond Words Publishing, $29.95). Regarding John Sculley's January 1992 announcement that Apple would unveil its PDA technology in May of that year, Menuez confirms that the ex-CEO fired a blank. "That was an absolute screamer because they were not ready at all."<p>To fine-tune Newton's software and hardware, 65 engineers hacked around the clock for more than a year, breaking only to play fiercely competitive games of basketball and Ping-Pong or to nap for three or four hours a day. Kids, visiting their parents at dinnertime, shot arrows at busy engineers and scribbled on scientific data marked do not erase. The project mantra was "The absurd has become routine." <p>As pressure mounted, absurdity met tragedy. One team member committed suicide, engineers cracked up, and personal lives dissolved. "The stresses and strains of this project definitely took their toll," says Menuez. With Newton completed and its evolution recorded in the book Menuez describes as "Soul of a New Machine meets Day in the Life," will Apple's finest relax? "There's a  says Menuez, "but a lot of them plan to go right back to work."      <p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
