		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/10-Field & Street</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/10-Field & Street</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Fishing Vests Are the New Urban Style Craze<p>By Paul Schneider<p>Andy Carlson is reasonably certain that the man who was caught shoplifting at the Manhattan store of the fly-fishing outfitter Orvis a few months ago was not looking for a fishing vest for sporting reasons. "He had five of our Super Tac-L-Pak vests stuffed into a bag," says Carlson, an Orvis manager. "If he were going fishing, he would only need one." The $74 vests, he explains, have become a very fashionable thing for urban males to own. "The guy was definitely planning to sell them on the street."<p>Fishing vests are turning up on the street, and not just on the shoulders of German tourists, Associated Press photographers, and urban teens. Businessmen are wearing them in layers under jackets and over sweaters. Ralph Lauren pioneered the look as the first major designer to realize the wider fashion potential of the multi-pocketed vests; he has been selling them since the early '80s. The style really took off when rappers--among them Heavy D and the Boyz, Das Efx, the Pharcyde, Grand Puba Maxwell, and Brand Nubian--adopted the vests as part of their street wear. Donna Karan, a designer who often looks to the streets for inspiration, introduced a stylized $115 fishing vest into her DKNY men's line last spring. It was so popular she reinterpreted it for fall in a down-filled version (above). A $105 linen fishing vest was one of the hottest-selling items in Joseph Abboud's J.O.E summer collection. This season Abboud completes the garment's divorce from its angling origins with a loose, patch-pocketed vest made out of nubuck (at around $300, it costs as much as any real fisherman would spend on a fly rod). <p>Abboud's vest has only four pockets, while any fishing-worthy vest has at least ten. The mid-priced Super Tac-L-Pak, the most popular vest at Orvis among nonfishing customers, has an astounding 33 pockets: one for the cellular phone, one for the personal digital assistant, one for taxi receipts, one for subway tokens, and 29 for looks. The top of the line vest, Carlson says, can be automatically inflated for use as a life preserver. "And that," he says, "is a bit more of a fashion statement than people want."
 <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

