<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Outfront: More Moguls in Vermont</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Outfront: More Moguls in Vermont</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Nick Ravo<p>
"People call us the Switzerland of the U. S. because of our initiative," says Robert Miller, head of financial-services development for the state of Vermont. <p>
Vermont? Home to Socialist congressman Bernie Sanders and lefty dessert dons Ben & Jerry? A haven for money managers?<p>
Yes, Vermont. Last summer, the aptly named Green Mountain State adopted an ambitious plan to lure financial managers. The biggest incentive (besides the ski slopes) is a 75 percent tax credit on state income taxes for Vermont-based investment firms. Right now, Vermont has the fifth-highest marginal tax rate.<p>
About 178 firms have inquired about the Vermont plan, and 3 companies have already relocated to cow country. "The state has gone from being hostile to business to being receptive," says Arnold Barton, president of Blackford Securities of New York, which recently opened an office in Vermont. Anticipating a boom, the state has launched Vermont Securities Institute at Champlain College in Burlington to train residents for the 1,000 or so jobs that may develop over the next five years.<p>
Those who know their history won't be surprised by the state's new economic ambience. Vermont's most famous native son is Calvin Coolidge, the 30th president and Yankee cheapskate who urged Americans to invest in the stock market of the Roaring Twenties.<p>
KEYWORDS:
New England, northeast

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
