<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Outfront: Banker Blues </title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Outfront: Banker Blues </b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By William Green<p>
Like Bruce Springsteen, Nick Binkley bemoans the working life. But you will not hear about factory shifts and dirt pay in the songs of this musician. Binkley, a venture capitalist and former banker, croons of Wall Street drudgery and white-collar angst. <p>
"It's my antidote to the burnout," explains the 51-year-old Binkley, who, until a couple of years ago, had to sing on the sly. During the day, he worked as vice-chairman of the board at BankAmerica. But once the whistle blew, Binkley grabbed his guitar and headed out to local clubs. "I was gigging all over L.A.," he says. "It never filtered up to the top of the bank. I think they'd have been a little surprised."<p>
Anxious for an out, Binkley resigned from BankAmerica in 1993 and co-founded Forrest Binkley & Brown, a venture-capital firm in Newport Beach, California. He and his two partners currently manage $110 million in assets for such clients as Texas billionaires Sid and Lee Bass. Binkley, however, remains devoted to his parallel career as a musician.<p>
Months ago, he released his debut album, Pin Stripe Brain. He financed it himself, and though he hasn't broken even on his $50,000 investment, the CD has sold 4,000 copies. Nearly 50 radio stations around the country have played it.<p>
Pin Stripe Brain, a collection of 15 folk and rock songs, kicks off with a Willie Lomanesque lament. On the title track, Binkley muses, "Grazing 'cross the fields / Of high profitability yields / Is the man / With the pinstripe brain / Summertime seersucker / Wall Street prisoner / Is the man with the pinstripe brain... / Bottom-line hypnotized / On a jet commuter red-eye / Is the man with the pinstripe brain."<p>
Already, Binkley has a follow-up album in the works. And he is still brooding over the corporate grind. One of his new songs, "Wooden Indians," recalls his experiences at Chase Manhattan Bank, where he once worked as an assistant treasurer. Recalling the floor where hundreds of fellow Chase bankers crunched numbers, Binkley sings, "Broken minds, lost in time / Twist and turn like rusted signs in the wind."<p>
Decades ago, Binkley tried to escape such decay. At 29, he dropped out of Chase, spent two years writing songs and studying guitar, and tried to nail down a record deal. "I really was hoping it would develop into an alternative to banking," he explains. "But I got back so many rejections." A music-industry veteran, who played guitar on Paul Simon's albums, finally told him, "You can make more money as a singing banker." <p>
Binkley still believes he's got a shot at the big time, especially if he can persuade a major record label to back his upcoming album. But as a venture capitalist, he knows the odds are daunting. "It's not an inexpensive thing to take on a new act," he says. "And the statistics are not good: Eighty-six percent of the 7,300 albums that were released in 1995 from the major labels sold fewer than 10,000 copies." What's more, most record companies, according to Binkley, "look at someone who's 50 and say, 'This isn't going to work.'" <p>
Not surprisingly, bankers really dig Binkley. He counts among his fans the chief financial officer of Credit Suisse First Boston and the chairman of Bankers Trust. He even appeared as a surprise performer at a conference for senior executives from BankAmerica. At the start of the show, Binkley says, "there were a lot of stunned faces, jaws dropping six inches."<p>
Binkley will not look back in anger if musical success eludes him. "This is something I do for my heart," he says. "The reason I write music is that, if I didn't, I would probably kill myself."<p>
KEYWORDS:
musician, novelty, record
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
