<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Melissa Jeffries<p>
REAL-ESTATE PEAK. Rocky Mountain High ain't just a knee-slappin' John Denver tune. Houses in the Rocky Mountain states (ranging from Montana to New Mexico) have risen in value 44.2 percent over the past five years, according to the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight. That's nearly double the growth of any other area. Stanley Duobinis, economist at the National Association of Home Builders, credits the spurt to a thriving job market and an influx of Californians. But prices should plateau as more new homes are built in this region.<p>
DOLLY PARTON ON RYE. Who says the Hard Rock Cafe isn't inspirational? Since 1990, Ecklein Communications reports, 18 new theme-restaurant chains have come on the scene. Our favorite? Country Star restaurant.<p>
PSYCHIC-PETS NETWORK. The American Veterinary Medical Association recently approved new guidelines that include alternative medicine -- such as acupuncture and massage therapy -- for pets. <p>
GUILT-FREE FUNDS. The politically correct craze continues. According to Lipper Analytical Services, since 1991 the number of socially conscious mutual funds -- those investing in companies that benefit social and environmental causes -- has soared 243 percent to 48. <p>
ACCLIMATION INCENTIVE. Sure, moving can be traumatic. But if it's a corporate transfer, adjust or pay. According to research firm Runzheimer International, since 1990, 25.9 percent more companies demand that transferees repay moving expenses if they leave the company within six months to a year. <p>
WHAT A DOLL. Feminism seems to be lost in the toy department. According to the most recent figures from Mattel, the maker of Barbie dolls, worldwide sales of the blond bombshell have soared 40 percent since 1993. Not bad for a 37-year-old icon who's definitely getting better with age -- her 35th anniversary prompted a bevy of collector's editions. Wal-Mart reports that it sells a Barbie every two seconds. <p>
LIQUID ASSETS. Aerobics addicts and status junkies aren't the only folks chugging designer water. The International Bottled Water Association estimates that Americans drink 2.7 billion gallons of bottled water a year, up 151 percent from 1985. Experts say a fear of polluted resources is driving the trend, which has boosted annual bottled-water sales to over $3 billion. <p>
TIME-OUT. A recent study by Boston-based research firm Dalbar reveals that investors who use financial advisers spend four hours per month managing their money, while do-it-yourself types devote nine hours. <p>
MY BOSS, MY BROKER. Where to invest that bonus? Ask the person who signs the check. According to a study by benefits consultants William M. Mercer of New York, 75 percent of companies (up from 44 percent in 1993) now offer basic investing seminars to employees.  <p>
YOU CHARGE, THEY CHARGE. Don't sit on that credit-card bill; the coming trend among issuers is to punish the tardy. Citicorp and Capital One have already upped their cards' $15 penalty fees for late payments to $18 and $20, respectively. But there's more bad news. Expect grace periods to shorten to just 1 day from 5 to 15 days, says Bank Card Holders of America, a nonprofit consumer agency that tracks the credit industry.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
