	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-The Terrible Two</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Tom Vinciguerra<p>
Twenty years after its much-ballyhooed bicentennial reissue, the two-dollar bill is back. The Federal Reserve, having let its stock dwindle to a two-month supply, has printed up and begun circulating another $153.6 million worth -- enough for five years. The Fed hopes the deuce can finally shake its reputation as the bill of choice at the two-dollar window. "The two-dollar bill has often been associated with gambling," explains Tom Bower, a numismatist at the Smithsonian. "Putting a two-dollar bill in the collection plate at church on Sunday indicated that you'd been gambling Saturday night." Fed spokesman Robert Moore has his own use for the tender, which could catch on. "A lot of times," he says, "I'll just go and get a bunch of two-dollar bills because they're good for tips." Especially the ones from your bookie.
KEYWORD:
currency, collecting

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
