	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Swinging for the Fences</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Swinging for the Fences</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Monica Corcoran<p>
"God, did I want to be a ballplayer," says Barry Halper. Instead, the 57-year-old New Jerseyan spent nearly five decades amassing the world's largest private baseball-memorabilia collection, now worth $42 million. "The collection is like a child to me," says Halper, who's anxious to sell the lot, which includes Lou Gehrig's first mitt, Babe Ruth's will, and 30,000 baseball cards, "I don't want it split up." To keep his treasure together, Halper has taken a novel approach to unloading it: He's hired investment bank Lazard Freres to broker a deal. "I know Lazard's a blue-chip company. They sold Viacom," he says. Lazard managing director Peter Ezersky admits the firm has never done this before. "It's an unusual inquiry," says Ezersky, who's courting companies capable of housing the collection in a hotel, casino, or theme park/restaurant. "Someone like Ted Turner could buy it, too," adds Halper. "But the people who really want it can't afford it."<p>
KEYWORDS:
sports, auction

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
