	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Mouthing Off for the Media</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Mouthing Off for the Media</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ken Kurson<p>
What do economic seers predict for the coming year? Perhaps a rash of free publicity, if they stray far enough from the crowd. And that, says Owen Lamont, an assistant professor of finance at the University of Chicago, appears to be the agenda of many economic forecasters this time of year. <p>
Lamont analyzed the year-end BusinessWeek forecasts going back more than two decades and drew some controversial conclusions. Accuracy grows significantly worse as forecasters become older and more established, he says. And these forecasters, along with those who have their own firms, make wilder calls. <p>
"I cannot prove why," Lamont says. "I think it's because they're making a name for themselves." Lamont points out that there's plenty of incentive to play Chicken Little. While forecasters who make correct predictions are often publicly lauded, those who err rarely suffer censure. <p>
A. Gary Shilling, former chief economist at Merrill Lynch, disputes Lamont's theories. "As forecasters grow their reputations, they are more willing to speak their minds," he says. Shilling, who is cited in Lamont's study as one of the attention grabbers, now heads his own money-management firm in New Jersey. "Those who never stray from the crowd never develop a reputation," adds Shilling, "so they're not in BusinessWeek."<p>
KEYWORDS: 
progosticate

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
