<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Money Angles</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Money Angles</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Andrew Tobias<p>
AMAZING MATH: WINE BY THE CASE. Saving money is often the best "investment" anyone can make. No alternative yields as much with so little risk. One of the examples I use to illustrate this point has evolved over the years. The first time I told it was in 1978, on The Tonight Show. It went like this: Say you bought a $10 bottle of wine for dinner every Saturday night, but could instead get a 10 percent discount if you bought by the case. You'd "make" 10 percent on the extra money you tied up. And you'd make it in just 12 weeks, which works out to better than a 40 percent annual return. Where else can you earn 40 percent tax-free? (Uncle Sam doesn't tax you for smart shopping.)<p>
As the years passed, I found that some people were having trouble understanding this example. Why is it 40 percent if I just got a 10 percent discount? So I tried explaining it in more detail -- only to discover that I had badly underestimated the payoff. What really happens is that instead of going to the store and spending $10 for one bottle you are spending $108 for 12 bottles -- $120 minus the 10 percent discount. Which means you are laying out $98 more than the $10 you otherwise would have spent that weekend. That extra $98 is your "investment." The $1 a week ($52 a year) that you save on wine is your "return." And "earning" $52 a year on an investment of $98 is equal to a 53 percent return, tax-free.<p>
This revised example confused people even more. That first $98 is gone, they would tell me, and now you have to come up with a new $98 to buy your next case of wine. My response: not really. If you were someone who planned to spend $10 every week on wine -- $520 a year -- and who would have loved to save 10 percent buying by the case but just couldn't scrape up the dough to do it, how much would you need to borrow? Would you have to go to a bank and ask for a $520 line of credit to be able to change your buying habits? No, you would need only a $98 credit line -- and even that you would fully draw down only the first week. In the ensuing 11 weeks, you would replenish it by $10 a week (the $10 you previously used to spend on wine by the bottle). Result? After 12 weeks -- when you'd finished that first case and needed to buy another -- you would not only have replenished the full $98; you'd actually have an extra $12 in your pocket (the money you saved buying by the case). So now you'd have to draw down only $86 of your $98 credit line.<p>
I know this example can glaze the eyeballs, especially if you've had a glass or two of the wine (it's a nice merlot, contemplative but not haughty). So now that you see where I'm headed, let me drive the point home.<p>
* To finance this change in habits, from by-the-bottle to buy-the-case, you'd need a loan, that first day, of $98. <p>
* Soon -- within 10 weeks -- you'd have paid the loan down to zero (because of the $10 a week you'd have spent otherwise, the old way).<p>
* Then, to buy the next case, you'd have to run your loan balance back up only to $86 in the 13th week, which would require even less time to pay down at $10 a week.<p>
* And so on.<p>
Over the course of the year, you're drawing on far less than the full $98 credit line, on average, to finance this change in buying habits. So the return on your decision to tie up that $98 at first, and then gradually less money, is actually much greater than 40 percent or 53 percent.<p>
If my friend who keyed all this into his Hewlett-Packard financial calculator is right -- and I've never known him to err -- it works out to an annualized 177 percent rate of return. It's still only $52 you're earning -- $1 a week by getting the 10 percent discount. But if you do all your shopping this way, it can mount up. (Now try explaining that in 40 seconds on The Tonight Show.)<p>
INVESTING IN AIRLINE TICKETS. Have you noticed that "nonrefundable" tickets are, in fact, refundable -- in that you can apply them toward other tickets? <p>
There's a $50 charge, yes, but that $50 can constitute an excellent investment. Take your best guess now on your next five round-trips. Suppose two of them come to pass. You're now left with three tickets you'll need to exchange. The cost: $150. The gain: fares that you can get only through advance planning, such as $300 transcontinental round-trips instead of the full-fare $1,400. Got your spring-break ticket yet? You should. And if you're not sure whether you'll be spending it in Denver or Daytona, buy your super-savers to both. Forfeit $50 for having the privilege of deciding what you want to do right up to the last minute.<p>
THE MARKET FOR CAVES. Have you seen what's happened to the prices of caves in southern Spain lately? A perfectly adequate two-bedroom cave that sold for about $150 ten years ago now fetches nearly $8,000, according to the newsletter International Living.<p>
Apparently, there are quite a few middle-class Andalusians living in caves that are complete with all the modern cave-veniences, including phone and fax. It kills me that I didn't think of this ten years ago, of course. For $200,000, I could have all but cornered the cave market. It's still intriguing, if only because these caves have a year-round temperature of around 60 degrees (perfect for storing your aforementioned case of wine). To see how you like it, the newsletter suggests blowing $500 to rent a nice two- to four-bedroom cave for a week. For more information, contact the Spanish Government Tourist Office at 666 Fifth Avenue, New York, NY 10022.<p>
GIVE UP ON RUSSIA? NYET YET.I continue to think that Russia, while speculative, represents a great opportunity. If the Templeton Russia Fund (TRF) should tank one of these days, I think I'd pick up a few more shares. It's risky, but not imprudent if it represents a small portion of the funds you earmark for long shots.<p>
Andrew Tobias is the author of The OnlyInvestment Guide You'll Ever Need. He writes a daily Internet commentary that appears at <A HREF="http://www.ceres.com">www.ceres.com</A>, portions of which have been adapted for use in this column.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
