<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-The Exchanges Trade Blows</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-The Exchanges Trade Blows</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Paul Davies<p>
We all know about the ducking and jabbing that goes on in Wall Street's trading pits. But the three major stock exchanges -- Nasdaq, the New York, and the American -- don't pull any punches either. Not when it comes to courting companies as potential listings.<p>
The three-cornered ring is primed for sparring right now, due to the Securities and Exchange Commission's recent crackdown on Nasdaq's large trading spreads. A record number of companies have defected from that exchange, including <a name="NYSE:AOL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15558"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>America Online</b></a> (which moved to the Big Board) and <a name="AMEX:FIZ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13947"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>National Beverage</b></a> (which went to the American Stock Exchange). At the same time, Nasdaq has managed to steal 12 companies from the ASE.<p>
Brian Wilson, a Nasdaq vice president, downplays the inter-exchange rivalry. "We're not beating down the doors," insists Wilson. "Many companies approach us." The 204-year-old New York Stock Exchange, home to <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, <a name="NASD:COKE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13014"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>, offers a similar line. "Eighty-five percent of the companies eligible to list here are already here," says NYSE spokesman Raymond Pellecchia, implying that the noble exchange needn't stoop to such measures.<p>
But those kid gloves may be padded with quarters; industry insiders claim that both the NYSE and Nasdaq employ "switch teams" of salespeople who woo companies listed with the enemy. "Sucking up to issuers is rampant," says a former Nasdaq employee, who refused to be named.<p>
American Stock Exchange chairman Richard F. Syron calls the NYSE "the toughest of street fighters" and talks freely about the scrapping among the exchanges. "Anyone who says they are not out there competing is living in a different world," says Syron, who admits to being an underdog in the war. With just 794 listings, the ASE struggles to compete with the NYSE (2,809 listings) and Nasdaq (5,430 listings). <p>
The American Stock Exchange also suffers an economic handicap. Golf outings and expensive meals often figure into the mating ritual. At the ASE, says a spokeswoman, sighing, "we don't even have Knicks tickets."<p>
KEYWORDS:stock, stock exchanges, NASD

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

