<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Adult Themes</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Adult Themes</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Nick Ravo<p>
When Bob Pittman was a child, he thought as a child. In 1981, at 27 years old, he founded MTV. "I've always made a nice living off of understanding the baby boomers," says Pittman.<p>
In fact, he's never taken his finger off the yuppie jugular, though he's marketed products as diverse as amusement parks, movies, and real estate. And now, he says, America's largest generation wants to figure out this Internet thing. That's why he's flitted yet again: to <a name="NYSE:AOL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15558"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Online</b></a>, to head up the company's new division, AOL Networks.<p>
Many Net watchers scratched their heads over the hiring of a marketer for this job rather than someone more technologically adept. Pittman says this misses the point. "A lot of the people who cover AOL don't know who I am because they are technology people," he says. "But AOL is more like a media company than a tech company." What this service needs, in other words, is to be peddled to the right people in the right way.<p>
For someone who dropped out of college four times and never graduated, Pittman has an argot and rsum that would do a Harvard MBA proud. After selling MTV to <a name="AMEX:VIA"></a><b>Viacom</b> in 1987, Pittman founded Quantum Media. Two years later he became chief executive officer of <a name="NYSE:TWX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11482"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Time Warner Enterprises</b></a>, where he resuscitated Six Flags Theme Parks. Before jumping to America Online, Pittman devoted just 19 months to Century 21 as CEO of the mammoth real-estate company. "I'm a junkie for a good turnaround," he says with a slight Mississippi drawl.<p>
Perhaps that was the problem at Century 21: The company was huge and healthy; there were no crises to solve. AOL, on the other hand, appears to need a savior. The day the company announced the hiring of Pittman, it also announced that it was taking a $385 million charge to write down outstanding expenses. AOL's stock closed that day at less than $26 a share -- a crushing $45 a share below its 1996 high. Increasingly, AOL is seen, especially by young people, as a starter kit for Internet users -- something to be used just until cyberspace becomes comfortable. Some 10 percent of AOL's seven million subscribers give up on the service every month.<p>
That's where Pittman comes in. His chief role at America Online is to increase and hold on to the service's subscriber base. "This gives me a real buzz, one that I haven't had since MTV," he says. He notes that TV viewing has plateaued for the first time in his lifetime and that on-line services appear to be the next big thing.<p>
Pittman is quick to dismiss the doomsayers, particularly those who scoff at AOL's reliance on its proprietary content. "AOL will do whatever makes AOL the best service," he says. He's clearly ready for a fight. "AOL's already got great growth potential," he says. "We just have to pour gasoline on the fire." He also lauds his new co-workers. "I've been on the AOL board for a while," he explains. "I like the people. They are creative." In short, according to Pittman, "AOL is number one."<p>
Pittman's Music Man enthusiasm may affect Main Street, but Wall Street thinks that there's trouble in River City. "AOL's a house of cards," says David Rocker of Rocker Partners, a New York money-management firm and short-seller of AOL's stock. "The paradigm has shifted. The name of the game is content, and the content is moving off AOL."<p>
Pittman, however, likens AOL to MTV, circa 1983. "There was a time when people said the same about MTV," he responds. "They claimed that there were only so many cable subscribers, so we wouldn't be able to make more money. What they didn't foresee was how advertising took off." Pittman expects to expand AOL's user base by marketing the service heavily. If he can get people his own age to subscribe, and stick around, it will be a lot less important if the newest MTV generation thinks AOL is uncool.<p>
As for his brief tenure at Century 21, Pittman insists he never planned to get too cozy in real estate -- he says he did what he intended to do and moved on. Fair enough. Who could expect the man who's responsible for corrupting attention spans worldwide to sit still?
KEYWORDS:
technology, Music Television, Internet, World Wide Web

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
