				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By John Fried<p>
With big business infiltrating the ivory tower, higher learning sometimes sounds more like learning for hire. Here's a sampling of university posts, with their more corporate than collegiate endowments, sure to evoke snickers in the faculty lounge:<p>
McLamoreBurger King Chair in Marketing, University of Miami: $1.5 million.<p>
<a name="NYSE:ALL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16182"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Allstate</b></a> Chair in Finance and Insurance, UCLA: $500,000.<p>
Lego Professor of Learning Research, MIT: $1.5 million.<p>
<a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears Roebuck</b></a> Professorship in Economics & Financial Services, University of Chicago: $1 million.<p>
K-Mart Professor of Marketing, Wayne State University: $2 million.<p>
General Mills Land Grant Chair in Cereal Chemistry and Technology, University of Minnesota: $1.6 million.<p>
KEYWORDS: 
college

					</font>
