	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Melissa Jeffries<p>
IT'S ALL AN ACT. Who really gives a whoop if Whoopi Goldberg calls her friends and family via MCI? Not consumers, according to research company Video Storyboard Tests. A recent poll reveals that the public's approval of the use of celebrities as product spokespersons has fallen 39 percent since 1993. <p>
POLL VAULTING. What's on America's mind? The Gallup Organization reports that more folks are following public-opinion polls, up 34 percent from 1985. Unfortunately, Gallup is not sure what's behind this trend -- nobody asked.<p>
BUYING THE FARM. Who can afford to die these days? The National Funeral Directors Association estimates that the average cost of a funeral has soared 23.6 percent, to $4,624, since 1991. As a result, the sales of prepaid funeral packages are up 50 percent, and wholesale caskets are now appearing on the market. "Preplanning can save people 30 to 40 percent," says spokesman Michael Kubasak. "We plan for every other aspect of life. But we avoid the inevitable." <p>
HOME SAFE HOME. White picket fences may be quaint, but these days folks prefer a more secure barrier. Studies estimate that four million Americans now live in gated communities, and home-security-system sales are up 20 percent since 1991, according to the Electronic Industries Association.<p>
WILD CARDS. The number of debit-card users has soared 251 percent since 1992.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
