<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/11-Seeing Red</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Seeing Red</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>
They say Texans make the worst enemies. If that's so, Senators Al D'Amato, Christopher Dodd, and Phil Gramm had better watch out for Karen Evans. "Investors are often victims without recourse," says the 48-year-old Dallas divorcee. "And lately, Congress has been absolutely no help." <p>
Evans believes she knows why. From her home office, she tracks political contributions made by the financial industry to members of Congress. A few pecks at her computer keyboard summon more than ten years' worth of data. For instance, from 1985 through 1995, D'Amato, Dodd, and Gramm received nearly $3.5 million(40 percent of their campaign funding) in financial-sector contributions. The deepest pockets include <a name="NYSE:CCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10345"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Citicorp</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, and the American Council of Life Insurance. Evans believes that money appears to have had its say.<p>
In 1994 Gramm helped kill a bill that would have required giving investors more background information on their investment advisers and their advisers' compensation. D'Amato, as head of the Senate Banking Committee, endorsed a law that exempts companies from liability based upon their projections of future earnings. "Do I see a connection?" asks Evans. "Absolutely." <p>
**Evans aims to educate constituents of their politicians' stances on issues.**<p>
Evans wants the public to be aware of their politicians' stances on investor issues. She works toward this end by sending her research to watchdog agencies and news outlets. "Evans is uncovering a real problem," says Gerri Detweiler, spokeswoman for the National Council of Individual Investors. "The securities industry wields a lot of influence on Congress. The individual investor's voice is often drowned out."<p>
Evans became an activist after a close friend, M. K. Peterson, ultimately lost $5 million, in investments and legal fees, after his broker ignored his demands to sell stock in 1987. An NASD proceeding failed to hold the broker accountable. When Peterson died nearly broke, in 1993, his case drew Evans's anger out like wildfire. That ire keeps Evans, who works without pay and owns no investments, obsessed. "I've become somewhat of a recluse," she sighs.<p>
And not a very popular one. Gramm's press secretary calls Evans's theory linking contributions with votes a "gross distortion." Dodd's spokesman calls her charges "outrageous." But a recent confidential fund-raising letter from the Securities Litigation Reform Coalition, a group that represents financial companies, calls upon industry insiders to contribute to Dodd's re-election effort as thanks for his recent support of a bill that critics say undermines investor-oriented reform. "Senator Chris Dodd stood as the Senate's foremost supporter of the bill," the letter says. "Now he needs our help." When Dodd gets that help, Evans will know about it.<p>
KEYWORDS:
watchdog, politics, contributions

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
