				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/11-Motor Home</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Your neighbors are boors, and deafening traffic rattles the bedroom windows. But, hey, what do you expect if you live in a condo overlooking the Charlotte Motor Speedway? When built in 1984, the 40 units were priced at $95,000 each. They hardly budged. David Letterman even roasted the flagging venture by sneering, "Are you going to let your kids walk across the street?" <p>
Today, however, stock-car racing appeals to the Southern polo set; those same two-bedroom abodes are valued at anywhere from $350,000 to $800,000 apiece. And the real-estate race is on. Georgia already boasts a trackside condominium development at its Atlanta Motor Speedway, replete with a swimming pool, ballroom, and complimentary race tickets. <p>
Early next year, the Texas International Raceway outside Fort Worth will unveil its own horsepower housing. According to spokesman Jack Lenhart, most of the two-bedroom condos are already taken. And for $450,000 a pop, you better love the smell of Valvoline in the morning.<p>
KEYWORDS:racing, real estate, house
					</font>
