<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/10-Southern Rock</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-Southern Rock</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Peter Aronson<p>
Pack up that cooler, darlin', we're heading to Crater of Diamonds State Park to mine precious gems! Located in southwest Arkansas, Crater charges just four dollars for a day of jewel hunting in the United States' largest diamond deposit. And there really are carats in them hills. The Uncle Sam Diamond, the biggest sparkler ever found in North America at 40.23 carats uncut, was unearthed in Crater by a mining company in 1924. In 1975, W. W. Johnson of Amarillo, Texas, found in Crater what became known as the Amarillo Starlight, valued at $100,000. According to the park's superintendent, Michael Hall, an average of 16 diamonds weighing over a carat each are discovered in Crater each year. What do triumphant prospectors do with their quarry? Hall recalls one man who just took his stone home and traded it for a pickup truck. Yee-ha! 
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
