				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/10-One Suite Deal</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Cash can come in handy when you break the law or your leg. At California's Huntington Beach jail, a pen that offers housing to pay-to-stay offenders, convicts pony up $100 (for the first night; it's $65 a night thereafter) for better food and bigger cells. City jails in nearby Fullerton and Seal Beach have similar programs. Meanwhile, the ailing affluent can go for broke. Johns Hopkins Hospital in Baltimore has private suiteswith personal safes, fax machines, CD players, and catered mealsfor an additional $650 per night. New York's Columbia-Presbyterian Medical Center serves high tea with live piano music and shrimp cocktail to those who pay an extra $250 per night to stay in its McKeen Pavilion.
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
