	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> TREND SPOTTER  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> *401(k) UPDATE. Good news for the retirement-obsessed. According to Hewitt Associates, a management-consulting firm, 52 percent of American companies now offer daily valuations of 401(k) accounts over the phone, up from 18 percent five years ago. Just punch in your PIN. Investment choices are up, too--to six options from four.  <p> *WHO, ME RETIRE? Keyport Life Insurance, in a recent survey, found that 46 percent of those employed expect to work after retiring. That would constitute a real change in the economy: Only 13 percent of current retirees collect a pay check.  <p> *THE END OF AN ERA. Could this be the end of shopping as we know it? Procter & Gamble has begun phasing out cents-off coupons, because the number redeemed has been dropping--by 6 percent last year alone. In their absence, check your mailbox for more samples, which, according to the firm Target Marketing, 92 percent of us prefer over coupons.  <p> *TEEN GREEN. Off to the mall, son? Pick up a job while you're there. Since 1993, the number of high- school students whose main source of income is a job (their own, that is) has risen almost 10 percent, according to the National Endowment for Financial Education. The number of high schoolers dependent on an allowance, meanwhile, has fallen nearly 10 percent.  <p> *DOWNWARDLY MOBILE. The Dohring Company, an automotive research firm, reports that 49 percent of consumers--the highest percentage Dohring has recorded--would rather save money and buy a two-to three-year-old car than pay for a new one. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement, Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
