				<font size=6><b>96/04-No Cookies</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> NO COOKIES  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> For Chris Gross, charity meant "giving to public television and buying Girl Scout cookies"--until the bombing in Oklahoma City last April.  <p> After the disaster, the 27-year-old California financial analyst donated a year's salary of $53,874 to seed a college-scholarship fund for kids who lost a parent in the blast. His employer, Applied Materials, and other firms also chipped in. About $700,000 has been raised, still short of Gross's goal of $1 million.  <p> During his year without pay, Gross says, he "ate a lot of cereal and pasta." Anticipating his first paycheck, Gross, a wind surfer, says, "I'm buying a new sail--and I won't feel a bit guilty." Send donations to:Children of Oklahoma City Scholarship Fund,c/o Oklahoma City Community Foundation, P.O. Box 1146, Oklahoma City, OK 73101 (405-235-5603).  

					</font>
