		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Buffett with a Bullet</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-The Buffett with a Bullet</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> THE BUFFETT WITH A BULLET  <p> By Ken Kurson  <p> What do you do when your father's fame practically marries your last name to his career? Well, you can run for president with the money your dad made. Or you can find something you love to do--and do it.  <p> Peter Buffett, 37, is Warren Buffett's third and youngest child, and a man refreshingly unoppressed by his genetic link to wealth and fame. For the past 18 years, he has quietly collected a string of credentials as a composer, arranger, and producer that impresse seven those who've never heard of value investing.  <p> "I went to public school in Omaha. Dad had a Volkswagen--not a lot of sitting around eating bonbons," says Buffett, who dropped out of college and, with an eight-track recorder in his San Francisco apartment, created his Independent Sound studio business.  <p> Then, perhaps showing something of his father's eye for opportunity, Buffett saw that "in the early 1980s electronic music was coming into its own. It was popular and cheaper and easier to do. I got into it."  <p> After recording and playing on some minor-league disco hits, in 1987 Buffett composed, produced, and played many of the instruments on his debut album, The Waiting. He followed that up in 1989 with One by One, which reflected his interest in the American West and Native Americans.   <p> Next, Buffett made his own break by calling in favors from friends of friends to get a copy of One by One to Kevin Costner, who had begun work on the movie Dances With Wolves. Buffett wound up scoring the music in the film's pre-dance scene and went onto score last year's eight-hour CBS documentary 500 Nations for Costner's production company. Buffett also scored several scenes for the 1995 version of The Scarlet Letter ("It was a lot of fun, but man, what a bomb").  <p> As for how the prudent billionaire viewed his son's decision to enter the hit-or-miss music profession, the younger Buffett says, "For as long as I can remember, he thought all three of us should do what made us happy. He was great that way." Buffett isn't surprised that his father has retained his down-to-earth reputation. "He is, essentially, the same guy he was 30 years ago. He'll ask me, What do you get paid for something like The Scarlet Letter?' Well, I got this or that,' and he'll be like, Wow, that's a lot of money!'"  <p> In 1989, Buffett moved back to the Midwest, to Milwaukee, where he built Independent Sound into a state-of-the-art studio, with clients including CNN, <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, and Cadillac.  <p> So what does this Buffett do with his money? "I don't have enough to sit back and figure that out," Peter says. "I plow what I've got back into what I'm doing."  <p> Buffett has a new album, Spirit Dance, arriving this spring. He's also touring on the strength of the 500 Nations sound track. "You should see it," he says, "20 people onstage and Douglas Spotted Eagle plays the flute."  <p> Incidentally, Buffett long ago sold all his shares in <a name="NYSE:BRK.A"></a><b>Berkshire Hathaway</b>, his dad's company, to fund his business. They "would be worth 20 million bucks" today, he says blithely. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Business, Small Business Ownership

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

