	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Blue-Chip Books</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Blue-Chip Books</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> BLUE-CHIP BOOKS -- A SELLER'S MARKET  <p> By John Kearney  <p> Books about money are supposed to impart financial wisdom, but some provide a financial windfall as well. In 1994, for instance, R. G. Klein of Wall Street Books in Los Angeles sold a 1934 first edition of the investment to me Security Analysis for $7,500. <p> Robert Rubin, an antiquarian bookseller in Brookline, Massachusetts, says that, increasingly, investors are "buying blue-chip books and want them to perform as blue-chip stocks." He notes that in 1954 first editions of Adam Smith's Wealth of Nations sold for $250 to $500, but today fetch $20,000 to $40,000. A firstedition of Thomas Robert Malthus's An Essay on the Principle of Population sold in 1980 for $12,815; in 1991, a comparable copy went for $52,500. And David Ricardo's On the Principles of Political Economy and Taxation, published in 1817, cost around $3,000 in the late 1970s, but is now worth $10,000. Even the first edition of Das Kapital ($300 in the 1970s) today runs up to $19,000.  <p> "The economic classics are an excellent investment," says Judith Lowry of Argosy Books in Manhattan. "There will never be a time when Adam Smith is a lesser author."<p>
KEYWORDS: Financial Product Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
