	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Biz-School Brawl</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/04-Biz-School Brawl</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> BIZ-SCHOOL BRAWL  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> The nation's elite business schools reached their lofty status because their degrees are seen as tickets to a high-paying job. So what's a school to do if its recent grads aren't doing so hot?  <p> Massage the employment statistics, claims Alice McCarty Baxter, a former employee of Dartmouth College's Amos Tuck School of Business Administration. In a recently led lawsuit, Baxter says that in 1995 Tuck fired her for refusing to boost the number of graduates with job offers. <p>Roland Adams, a Dartmouth spokesman, calls Baxter's allegations"baseless" and motivated by greed. "Our gures are veriable,"he says.  <p> "She got fired for doing the right thing," counters Susanna Robinson, Baxter's attorney, who's seeking $500,000 in damages. "Those are damn important numbers."  <p> They are indeed. For example, in U.S. News & World Report's annual issue "America's Best Graduate Schools," published in March, job placement accounts for 35 percent of B-school rankings."There's a long history of schools' puffing data," says Robert Morse, research director for the issue. "None of the academic data is accredited."  <p> One way to inflate figures, says Andrew Adams, placement director at the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton School of Business, is to count only the students registered in the placement office. "C'mon, this is not brain surgery," says Adams, who bases his claims on Wharton's entire graduating class. "But everyone seems to have a complicated method for getting their figures."  <p> At MIT's Sloan School of Management, career-development director Ilse Evans says, "A business school falsifying data is like a company misstating its quarterly revenue numbers. That's bad news."

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
