<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-No Quarter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-No Quarter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>Executive-compensation expert Graef Crystal calls her the woman who put corporate governance on the map. 
Warren Buffett says, "Sarah is hard to say no to." Sarah Teslik may not be a household name, but she's well known (if not well liked) where it counts -- in the boardroom. Teslik, 42, is the executive director of the Washington, D.C. based Council of Institutional Investors, a group formed by 20 pension funds back in 1985 to agitate for change at major corporations in which the funds owned stock. Today, the council represents 100 pension funds with $1-trillion-plus in combined assets, and Teslik still scrutinizes every company expenditure as if it came out of her own pocket. This Methodist minister's daughter, originally from Walla Walla, Washington, specializes in corporate exorcisms, too. When the stock of Westinghouse began a devastating tumble in the early 1990s -- the company's losses topped $5 billion by 1993 -- Teslik was instrumental in persuading <a name="NYSE:WX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11627"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Westinghouse</b></a>'s board to remove CEO Paul Lego. She also had a hand in the ousting of CEOs at <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>.<p>As if that weren't enough to earn her powerful enemies, she also speaks her mind -- with very little editing. Here is the shrewd and scrappy Teslik on what she's seen and learned in 11 years of fighting power with power.<p>On the new noblesse: "There is a star cult about CEOs that I find disappointing. They are a very sheltered group. They have lackeys who do their laundry, who arrange their corporate jets, who do their every little personal chore. Today's CEOs need lessons in courage and the nature of fiduciary obligations."<p>On those six-, seven-, and eight-figure salaries: "If you took the excesses of corporate perks, executive compensation, and personal rapaciousness out of their context and put them into another, you would find violations that border on the criminal."<p>On what goes on behind closed oak doors: "The only contact CEOs have with the outside world is when their boards meet with analysts and investment bankers. They'll ask the CEO questions to determine where the stock price will be tomorrow, but not where the company should be in 20 years."<p>On corporate DNA: "Genetic defects caused by inbreeding are nature's way of voting for big gene pools. The independent board is the corporate equivalent. Chairman clones on the board won't see problems the chairman doesn't."<p>On the most incestuous board: "<a name="NYSE:ADM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10124"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Archer Daniels Midland</b></a>. Of the 16 members, 3 are related to the chairman by blood, and most of the others have financial or business ties to him. It is outrageous, immoral, and bad management to put one's family members on any board or entangle a board member with a financial connection."<p>On why she took the job: "Back in the mid-'80s, shareholders were getting screwed. Hostile takeovers were common. Customers have contract rights, employers have contract rights, bondholders have contract rights, and taxpayers have voting rights. But shareholders had no rights. Back then, few public or union pension funds had ever filed shareholder proposals."<p>On why she hasn't sold out: "This is people's grocery money and jobs we're fighting for. Once, pension funds were asleep at the switch. Now we use the power of our purse to raise issues and embarrass corporations in the media. It is just plain wrong to take $100 million from a company in salary and lay off a hundred workers."<p>On watching her back: "We have terrifically large enemies with a lot of clout who are watching us to make a misstep. For example, I was told that <a name="NYSE:TWX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11482"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Time Warner</b></a>'s chairman, Gerald Levin, 'wants to get me.' What's he going to do, have me killed?" (A spokesman for Levin says, "Her comment is totally off the wall, absurd, and ridiculous.")<p>On why she has made such a powerful enemy: "They're too arrogant at Time Warner. They're not careful enough with their money. They reserve 17 percent of the whole company for employee stock-based compensation."<p>On whom she identifies with, as a survivor: "Yasser Arafat, because he is famous for taking on the state of Israel for 20 years and for being able to say no to people, as I do with big corporate executives. 
Yet he's still alive. That's extraordinary."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:WX">Westinghouse Electric Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:AXP">American Express Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:IBM">International Business Machines Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:ADM">Archer-Daniels-Midland Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:TWX">Time Warner Inc.</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
