	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/09-Hollywood Shuffle</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Hollywood Shuffle</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Robert Bentley<p>In Hollywood, where you're only as good as your last deal, folks are always pawing through their Rolodexes. Especially those who are locked into a pyramid scheme that has spread faster than a Joe Eszterhas script.<p>The scheme, dubbed Friends Helping Friends, has spawned countless others and become the buzz in entertainment circles. The fact that soliciting money for so-called endless chains is illegal hasn't deterred interest. Chardonnay-and-canap parties, held in Hollywood Hills mansions, have become venues for anyone willing to join in. Entry fees range from $100 to $5,000. Either way, the same rules apply: Each player must recruit other participants to move up to the next slot. The process repeats until that player reaches the pinnacle and collects the big prize, which can be as much as $40,000.<p>Pyramid pushing on the job has become a heated issue. After an in-house investigation, one <a name="NYSE:SNE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41885"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sony Pictures Entertainment</b></a> employee was red recently and another resigned for pyramid networking on company time, and a memo warning all studio workers to steer clear of the scheme followed. A similar missive circulated at CBS's Television City.<p><a name="NYSE:TWX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11482"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Warner Bros.</b></a> has had pyramid problems, too. Allegedly, jobs on the studio's hit TV series ER went to extras who joined the scheme. Warner execs denied the claims, and the Screen Actors Guild nosed around (it found "no evidence of widespread abuse," according to a SAG spokeswoman). Nevertheless, Warner Bros. quickly issued a memo threatening to terminate Friends Helping Friends players.<p>The Los Angeles City Attorney's Office has convicted eight people involved in Friends Helping Friends schemes; all eight have received 90-day jail sentences. "It's a nice title," says prosecutor Don Kass, "but somebody always gets screwed." Just like in a Joe Eszterhas script.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
