	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/09-Handle With Care</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jim Melloan<p>Relocating employees can be a bear, especially when it comes to creature comforts. According to a nationwide survey by the research firm Runzheimer International, the corporate policy on pets knows no limits. And Michael Jackson isn't the only wacko, with his llama farm and pet chimp. Along with dogs of every size and description, companies have transferred a live gorilla, a pack of mink, a dolphin, a pair of alligators, 50 cats belonging to one family, and a 500-gallon aquarium. One executive even persuaded his company to relocate a huge rock -- it was his dog's favorite pit stop. "If it's not illegal and not unethical, we'll move it," says Betsy Roche of Connecticut-based PHH Relocation. Yeah, but what if it bites?<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
