<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Wise Guy</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Wise Guy</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						In 1926, a man could get a good suit for $50 and a seat on the New York Stock Exchange for $133,000. David Granger, then 22 years old, bought both.<p>"I'm the senior member," Granger simply says of his 
70-year tenure on Wall Street, where he's the longest-serving
current member of the NYSE. At 93, Granger still puts in at least six hours a day at the investment firm Ingalls & Snyder, where he manages nearly 100 accounts for clients, some of whom have been with him for 40 years or more.<p>Not a bad run for someone who claims he "was propelled" into making Wall Street a permanent address. After graduating from Yale in 1924, Granger did his postgraduate work at Cambridge University. There he studied under John Maynard Keynes, whom he refers to as his mentor. When Granger returned to New York, his father put up the stake money for him to join his two older brothers on Wall Street. Together, the siblings founded Granger & Co., and as the youngest, David was sent to trade on the floor. "It was a different world then," Granger says. "Today, far more of the traders are ex-clerks, and there's a mad scramble for profits. Back then, we'd sit around for days and do maybe a few hundred shares."<p>Granger recounts his first brush with a blue chip. "One day I was asked to lunch by an <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a> board member," he says. "It had to be around 1930. He told me that IBM was not going to expand its plant in upstate New York. So I bought some, because of his wonderfully conservative stick-to-our-knitting story. Obviously, I bought it for all the wrong reasons." Nonetheless, he still made a tenfold gain when he sold his shares.<p>These days, Granger seldom visits the trading floor, and his seat is leased to a whippersnapper of the scrambling variety. But he remains passionately protective of his clients, whom he calls "friends," and takes pride in staying abreast of news that may affect their holdings. "I'm not an analyst," he says, "but I read a great deal about the companies I follow. A lot of investing is spontaneous, emotional."<p>Retirement has yet to cross his mind. Granger says he is determined to continue "investing for my friends and increasing their capital." His 70th anniversary with the stock exchange came and went last February with no acknowledgment from the NYSE. "They used to hand out 25-year and 50-year certificates," he says. "People now are too busy. They should think of it, but they don't." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:IBM">International Business Machines Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
