	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-What's Sex Got To Do With It?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Melissa Jeffries<p>The price ain't right at most hair salons and dry cleaners -- at least not for women, who usually pay more than men do for like services. The vendors say this is justified: Female tresses take more time to cut; women's shirts don't fit on the presses and must be ironed by hand. But that argument doesn't fly in California, where a new law requires that comparable unisex services (including manicures, which often cost up to $10 more for men) be priced the same. A similar bill is being considered in New York, and its supporters hope to bring it before the legislatures of every state. Expect Adam and Eve to face off. "I only get 10 to 15 women's shirts a month. I'm not buying a $6,000 press just for that," snaps Ishves Naik of Atlanta's Esquire Cleaners, which charges women up to $2.10 more a shirt. Manicure, Ishves? <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
