	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Monica Corcoran<p>CHARGE DU JOUR. Booked a reservation at that fancy French bistro but didn't show? Prepare to say "Au revoir" to as much as $25 per head if you gave up your <a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a> card number to hold the table. Amex and selected restaurants recently tested the new no-show penalty, and more eateries could soon adopt the policy.<p>DOUBLE OR NOTHING. That's the cry of consumers looking for a real sale these days. America's Research Group reports that shoppers now expect a 38.7 percent price cut, compared with 21.8 percent in 1990. Apparently, discount diamonds are a girl's best friend -- 63 percent of jewelry buyers demand about 50 percent off retail. <p>HOUR TRIPPER. Expect fewer drivers wreaking highway havoc 
to get the rented four-door back in time. Last year, Value Rent-a-Car wheeled out hourly rates, ranging from 99 cents to $2.49 in most areas, and now some independent companies are following suit. <p>WHO'S J.? Georgetown Publishing House reinvents the trend in personalized marketing with an overly friendly approach. Hawking a $297 book titled American Speaker, the firm mass mailed ads that 
were affixed with a handwritten endorsement (right) signed by "J." Deceptive and annoying, sure. But not illegal, says Lesley Fair of the Federal Trade Commission's Division of Advertising Practices, which recently stopped the same company from endorsing the pricey tome with an ad that looked like a book review. Maybe J. wrote that, too.<p>MTV FINANCE. Generation-Xers are more than twice as likely to play the lottery as to invest, says a recent poll.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:AXP">American Express Company</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
