	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/08-Trading Places</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/08-Trading Places</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Louis Jacobson<p>Until we were out of the woods, it was surrealistic," recounts futures trader Thomas McMahon. "We didn't know what to expect. After the first bombs went off, the adrenaline came up at a fever pitch."<p>No, not a typical day of trading on the New York Mercantile Exchange. Recently, McMahon and 21 fellow traders headed off to Quantico, Virginia, to find out what it means to be one of the few, the proud, a Marine. The weekend was an even swap for an event late last year, when Marines visited the exchange to sample the trader's brand of split-second decision making. After testing their reflexes in the pit, the soldiers invited the traders to the trenches. And Marines take payback time very seriously.<p>At 0500 hours, a leather-lunged drill instructor roused the underwear-clad traders from their bunks by barking orders. "That was fun," recalls silver trader Andrew Stanton. "But only because you knew it was going to end." Next, the camouflage contingency marched to a field-command center, where Marine communications specialists re-enacted a battlefield scenario on a computer. The traders relaxed and felt right at home amid the hand signals and squealing radios.<p>Hours later, however, the real battle began. Face-painted, M-16-toting Marines briefed the traders on their next mission: Backing up the jarheads while they knocked out an enemy post. Bullets whizzed by as Marine gunners strafed the practice range with authentic machine-gun fire. Grenades shook the trenches. Not surprisingly, the traders took a highly conservative approach to combat. Not a one strayed from his safe spot.<p>But the chance to fire machine guns at abandoned tanks brought out the GI Joe in all of them. "They did outstanding," says First Lieutenant Christopher Lewis. "But I don't think any of them would trade their jobs for Marine green."<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

