				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Peter Aronson<p>Come August 16, the start of "Death Week," Elvisphiles head off to 
Memphis, Tennessee, to commemorate the King's passing. Folks in Fort Smith, Arkansas, hope to get their share of tourists, too. Elementary-school students there are raising money for "Blue Suede Cut Economics," a campaign to preserve Fort Chaffee's Building 133, where Elvis lost his pompadour to the U.S. Army in 1958. "I cannot believe I lived in this town for five years before I knew Elvis got his hair cut here," says schoolteacher Jan Honeycutt, who's also rallying to have the original two barber chairs reinstalled in Building 133. A small fee would be charged at the door. But no ELVIS SAT HERE sign will grace either throne. Alas, nobody knows for sure which chair bore the King. <p><p><p>

					</font>
