				<font size=6><b>96/08-A Game for Losers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Monica Corcoran<p>You won't see a toothy blond caressing a refrigerator. Or hear about those lovely prizes. This is Debt, a new TV game show airing on cable's Lifetime Television, where the contestants want to lose. "They play against their debt," says Michael Davies, who developed the show because everyone he knows is in hock. "So the winner takes home nothing." Three contestants are matched by their fiscal woes -- ranging from credit-card burdens and student loans to mortgages -- and battle one another to be the first to wipe out their debt by correctly answering pop-culture questions. Losers get an apt parting gift: a savings bond. And plenty of empathy. "I have a beautiful home that's mortgaged, and I lease two cars," says Debt host Wink Martindale, who has given away many a dinette set in his time. "I know debt, too." <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
