	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Trend Spotter</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Trend Spotter</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Monica Corcoran<p>A STAR IS BOUGHT. As the cost of making movies continues to rise, so does the price of Hollywood immortality. Recently, the cost of installing a star on the Hollywood Walk of Fame rose 50 percent, from $5,000 to $7,500. <p>WRONG NUMBERS. Apparently, the long-distance heavies--<a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a>, <a name="NASD:MCIC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13996"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>MCI</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:FON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11560"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sprint</b></a>--are reaching out and picking our pockets. Consumer Action, a San Francisco not-for-profit watchdog agency, reports that basic rates among the three carriers have jumped 12 to 17 percent in the past five years; a sampling of four long-distance calls made with Sprint--which upped its rates the most--increased from $19.56 in 1991 to $22.96 this year. Somebody better call Candice Bergen.<p>"LIKE, UM, FORE?" Teenage girls are totally teeing off. The number of girls aged 18 and under on the green has increased 73 percent since 1988. She-teens now make up  the most rapidly growing group among the female fairway set, reports the Ladies Professional Golf Association. <p>FREEDOM OF CHOICE. Feeling fickle about your 401(k) plan? Perhaps you can switch right away. A recent survey reveals that 35 percent of companies, up from 4 percent in 1989, allow their employees to change their investment choices on a daily basis. <p>REWIND THIS. Maybe it's those pesky late charges. Research firm Alexander & Associates says that video sales climbed almost 18 percent last year, while video rentals dropped nearly 9 percent. Plus, the average video rental fee increased to $2.61 from $2.50.<p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Telecommunications Industry, Entertainment Industry, Retirement

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
