	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Finally, Plumbing to Match the Plane</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By William Green<p>As status symbols go, it's hard to beat a Learjet. But until now, your typical plutocrat's chariot had an Achilles' heel, or perhaps head: A trip to the john on the Learjet 35 meant arranging some plastic panels around a spartan facility at the front of the cabin. In 1995, however, Learjet Inc. of Wichita, Kansas, unveiled the $6.7 million, 512-mph Learjet 45, its first totally new plane in over 30 years. And the toilet is glorious.<p>Kip Harkness, who designed the jet's interior, waxes lyrical about the loo's "harmonious feel," "biomorphic flowing shapes," and calfskin-covered cabinet with "a hardwood trim that dances around the border." About $20,000 more buys 24-karat gold-plated sinks and fixtures. The rest room can even seat a passenger when the eight swivel chairs in the cabin are full. "Not somebody's first choice," says Jeff Miller, Learjet's PR director, "but it's probably not that unpleasant as long as no one else needs the lavatory." <p><p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
