				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Lick Here</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ken Kurson<p>Americans bemoan the ubiquity of advertising, but we're mere babes in the woods. Great Britain, for example, sells ads on its postal cancellations, hawking everything from Nestle's Kit Kat bar to a radio station. New Zealand once put ads on the glue side of stamps. But you won't soon see the Pepsi logo on U.S. mail, says the New York Philatelic Foundation. Only not-for-profit companies, such as Easter Seals, have appeared on mail here. "In 1981, the U.S. considered it, with Barry Goldwater championing the idea," says the foundation's William Crowe. But Congress vetoed the proposal, dooming that attempt to lick the budget deficit. <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
