<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Grand Old Money</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Grand Old Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Elizabeth Macdonald<p>Ready money" is the most reliable friend in American politics, said Senator Phil Gramm at the start of his failed campaign for the Republican presidential nomination.<p>He's right. Whatever else a candidate needs these days, money--lots of money--is first on the list. How else to pay for months of TV attack ads?<p>In fact, the two major political parties are, among other things, permanent fund-raising operations, laboring to keep the coffers filled so that candidates around the country can be financed. <p>Getting hold of voters' cash is a crude business, as described in an article in Roll Call, a twice-weekly Capitol Hill newspaper. The article showed how the Republican National Committee squeezes contributions from senior citizens (average age 54). The GOP depends on this group for much of the $9 million it raises annually over the phone, says the RNC's press secretary, Mary Crawford.<p>"Don't let the donors ramble on and on about their bills, sick spouse, or problems with the government. Move carefully and purposefully, keeping the subject of the conversation on money." These and other helpful hints are part of the RNC's handbook for telemarketers, which adds, "You deserve their attention, not complaints about invasion of privacy."<p>RNC fund-raisers must make at least three demands for money during a call, and they are exhorted to "think big and ask for a lot." Indeed, they must pull in at least $250 per hour, or they get the boot. That's a tough benchmark: The RNC's average contribution is $43.<p>One former RNC telemarketer, Andrew Beadle, 27, told Worth that he quit last March because "the RNC was exerting way too much pressure on senior citizens. It made me feel kind of slimy."<p>The American Association of Retired Persons and the Gray Panthers are unaware of any complaints (political fund-raising outfits are not federally regulated). But Gray Panthers executive director Dixie Horning says, "If that was their mother, they would probably get angry and tell her to hang up."<p><p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
