<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-College Kickbacks</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-College Kickbacks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Monica Corcoran<p>"Twenty years of schoolin' and they put you on the day shift," Bob Dylan sang in the 1960s, but it's today's reality for many college students, whose diplomas may be worth a lot less than they cost. <p>This is making it tougher for many schools to fill their classes. "There are about 1,600 private four-year colleges," says Morton Schapiro, economics professor at the University of Southern California and co-author of Keeping College Affordable. "How many have lines of high-quality, affluent students waiting to get in? A generous answer is 50." <p>Some schools are using marketing to help bring in good applicants. St. John Fisher College in Rochester, New York, for example, is offering a kind of money-back guarantee on its four-year $40,000 tuition. If students sign up for the "Fisher Commitment" and can't find a job within six months of graduation, the college will pay them $400 per month--up to a maximum of $5,000. The fine print: Students must graduate with a 2.75 grade-point average or better, have developed a career plan with their counselors, and do a job-related internship. <p>"We decided to put our money where our mouth is," says William Pickett, president of the college. <p>Fisher isn't alone. At Clark University in Massachusetts, undergraduates with at least a 3.25 GPA are entitled to a year's free tuition toward a master's degree. "That could be a savings of up to $50,000 [on] the cost of an advanced degree," says provost Roger Kasperson. Pennsylvania's Lehigh University has a similar program. <p>"Private colleges have to be more creative about attracting students," says Russell Edgerton, president of the American Association for Higher Education. "We're going to see a lot of ingenious marketing, given the current competitive climate."<p>This fall, Ohio's Muskingum College is slashing its tuition 29 percent to $9,850, and North Carolina Wesleyan College's tuition will fall 23 percent to $11,650. Drake University of Iowa guarantees tuition increases won't exceed the consumer price index, or 3 percent.<p>Not everyone thinks these deals will work. "People get the sense that this is the school's last gasp," remarks David Breneman, author of Liberal Arts Colleges: Thriving, Surviving, or Endangered? and dean of the Curry School of Education at the University of Virginia. <p>By contrast, he says, "some folks would mortgage their grandmother if they could get their kid into Harvard." Even Harvard, though, at $28,896 a year, kept the 1996 tuition rise to 4.8 percent, the lowest since 1969. <p>So competition is coming to campus. Can frequent-flier miles and free cable TV be far behind? <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Education<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
