<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/06-Go for the Gold</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/06-Go for the Gold</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						And you thought the tickets to the Olympics were expensive<p>By Tom Nawrocki<p>Sure, you can buy a program or sweatshirt, but how can you really show your allegiance to the Summer Games in Atlanta? By plunking down 50 grand for a set of five commemorative pins.<p>Each pin is 18-karat gold and slathered in diamonds, emeralds, sapphires, and/or rubies. Each reflects a different aspect of this summer's centennial games. Balfour, the pins' manufacturer, made only ten sets, and nine are still available: Former Atlantan and 1984 Olympic boxing medalist Evander Holyfield was the first to snap one up. The remainder are for sale at <a name="NYSE:SKS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=40406"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Saks Fifth Avenue</b></a> in Atlanta.<p>If $50,000 seems a little much, the pins are available individually for $10,000. But if $50,000 seems like petty cash, there's also a very limited edition set (one made) of platinum pins. The price tag: a cool million.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
