	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Used Car</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Used Car</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Used Car</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>USED CAR<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Don't bother asking for a test-drive. This used car, the Bugatti Type 41 Royale Binder Coupe de Ville, is one of only six of its kind in existence, three of which are in museums. "We wouldn't accept an offer of anything less than $15 million," says Don Williams, a partner in the Barrett-Jackson Classic Car Auction. <p>In January, the 7,000-pound, 20-foot sedan went on sale in a silent auction at Barrett-Jackson in Scottsdale, Arizona. No payment plans allowed. Williams says, "There are only ten people in the world I can think of with the desire and the wherewithal to buy this Mona Lisa of a car."<p>Legend has it that this model, which was built in the early 1930s by designer Ettore Bugatti, earned its noble title by default. The cars were presented to royalty, including, it is said, King Carol II of Romania, because even the profligate refused to pay $42,000 for a car originally built with no headlights. "Call it an early Edsel," says Andy Rheault, secretary and registrar of the American Bugatti Club. "It's not very practical." <p>And though a Sunday drive with the family might be snug in a cab that seats just two, those bulletproof rear and side windows are a nice touch, and the Royale's eight-cylinder, 300-horsepower engine will take you up to 125 miles per hour in top (third) gear. As for mileage, don't ask.<p>Of course, a fender bender would cost you a second mortgage. "C'mon, you wouldn't dare drive that car anywhere but in your own driveway," says William H. Smith, executive director of the Antique Automobile Club of America.<p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
