<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-How Lizzie Got her Carriage</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>How Lizzie Got her Carriage</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-How Lizzie Got her Carriage</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>HOW LIZZIE GOT HER CARRIAGE<p>By Carol A. Schatz<p>In 1892, Lizzie Borden, as every child knows, gave her mother 40 whacks (and her father 41) in Fall River, Massachusetts. Following a trial at which the defense argued that Lizzie was the innocent and upper-class victim of overeager Irish cops, Borden was acquitted of the ax murders in less than an hour. However, history, like the popular nursery rhyme, has rendered a different verdict: that she was, in fact, a parricide.<p>Why, then, did she do it? A compelling new documentary by filmmaker Immy Humes, who was nominated for an Academy Award for A Little Vicious, her 1991 film about a dog on death row, suggests one straightforward motive: money. "This is a story about her getting hers," says Humes.<p>To make Lizzie Borden Hash & Rehash, Humes interviewed dozens of crime experts and Borden buffs. Among other things, she discovered that Lizzie had a stingy father, Andrew, and believed that her stepmother was out to steal her inheritance. <p>Andrew was a poor relation in a rich family but eventually made himself into one of Fall River's wealthiest men, first as an undertaker and later as a real-estate investor. It seems, however, that he never overcame his experience of poverty; for though Lizzie was given a genteel education and socialized with her wealthy cousins, she lived in a house without plumbing in a shabby part of town__and she had no carriage. Thirty-two years old at the time of the murders, "she was living below her means," says Humes, "and got sick of it."<p>Of course, there are other theories to explain why Lizzie chopped her way into history, says Humes. Andrew could be violent (he once decapitated his daughter's pigeons after neighborhood kids tried to steal them), and the doors of the Borden house were often locked and bolted, leading some to suggest the possibility of abuse or incest. <p>Happily for murder connoisseurs, no theory is ever likely to provide conclusive proof. As for Humes, she reserves her greatest distaste for the many people who believe that Borden was guilty and yet are still understanding. "What I think is suspect," says Humes, "is how sympathetic most people are to [her], as if there's something criminal in her father being a miser."<p>In the end, free of her father's parsimony and also in control of his fortune, Borden bought a mansion in the nice part of town__complete with four bathrooms, two servants, and a car and chauffeur. <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
