<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-Economics in the 'Hood</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-Economics in the 'Hood</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Ken Kurson <p>As he surveyed the sea of black faces at last fall's Million Man March, the only color Kelvin Boston saw was green. "It's time," he says, "for blacks to take a good look at ourselves and the whole enterprise system."<p>The 41-year-old Boston, author of the recently published Smart Money Moves for African Americans (G. P. Putnam) and host of the cable-television show The Color of Money, is a star in the booming business of providing financial advice to America's 32.5 million blacks. The work is also something of a crusade__a 1990s-style civil-rights movement for a man who exemplifies its potential.<p>Boston was born in the projects of Wilmington, Delaware. He remembers that "others had more things__beautiful cars and lovely homes. Most blacks were told in church that money is the root of all evil, but I didn't believe that God intended for all blacks to be poor."<p>After graduating from predominantly black Lincoln University outside Philadelphia, with a B.A. in English literature, Boston landed a job as the liaison between the Wilmington mayor's office and the city's community groups. Working with the black poor, he saw that "the civil-rights leaders were talking about economic priorities [as] a class issue. But I realized it's an individual issue. We needed to reach heads of families, not heads of rallies."<p>Eight months later, in 1980, Boston headed for Toledo, Ohio, and enrolled in IDS/<a name="NYSE:AXP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10085"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Express</b></a>'s financial-planning program. Though "intimidated by finance and my classmates," he completed the course and by 1985 rose to become the company's Midwest manager for financial planning.<p>Boston counseled hundreds of families (most of them black) in Toledo, and discovered that, along with his race, his facility with numbers and knack for punctuating financial advice with biblical quotations helped him reach people mistrustful of the largely white financial-services industry. In 1988, Boston moved to Detroit, a city that was bleeding services and expertise as whites fled to the suburbs. There he created Financial Insight, a cable-access program for black investors that combined Boston's relaxed manner with tough talk about the importance of investing. Rechristened The Color of Money, it won the backing of the Detroit PBS station and the Black Entertainment Television cable network. Today, it airs on more than a hundred PBS affiliates and reaches more than 53 million people. <p>Boston's eponymous Boston Media Inc. produces and syndicates The Color of Money, and he owns 50 percent of Corporate Detroit, publisher of Corporate Detroit magazine. He will launch The Color of Money Journal, a "wealth-building magazine for people of color," early in 1996, and has signed with Bloomberg Business News to produce the Bloomberg Color of Money Business Index, which will track black-owned firms.<p>On television and in his book, Boston offers a general primer on personal finance and takes on some sensitive issues. For example, he writes of the inferiority felt by many black entrepreneurs in the presence of whites. He calls it the "white man's ice is always colder" syndrome and says African-Americans must free themselves of this "utter nonsense" or fail.<p>Young blacks, he says, are increasingly aware of the importance of finance. "You go into the black sororities, clubs__black wealth is what's on their minds. They want their chunk of the American dream. The economic-rights movement is what people are talking about in the 'hood."<p>Still, while median income for black families is about half that of white families, their net worth is just 10 percent that of white families. To erase this disparity, Boston preaches "the Power of Ten. Take 10 percent of your income and invest it in instruments likely to produce 10 percent returns and make a commitment to do so for ten years."<p>Boston adds that there is a growing number of black-owned or -affiliated companies. "A lot of Americans have made money with black companies and black-owned mutual funds," he says. "Unfortunately, most of those Americans aren't black."<p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:AXP">American Express Company</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
