<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/03-The (Really) Big Board Game</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The (Really) Big Board Game</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/03-The (Really) Big Board Game</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1996
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>THE (REALLY) BIG BOARD GAME<p>By Nick Ravo<p>In real estate, everything is location, location, location. No surprise, then, that Monopoly can now be found on both CD-ROM and the Internet, the hottest piece of real (albeit virtual) estate on the planet.The Monopoly Web site is open to all, but to play on-line you need the Monopoly CD-ROM__distributed by Virgin Interactive
Entertainment ($39.95)__which was introduced last fall in a match among players at cyber cafs in Los Angeles, San Francisco, New York, and London. Players log on at http://www.monopoly.com to schedule games in the Monopoly Boardroom. Off-line, the CD-ROM lets groups play via a local area network (LAN), at a  single PC terminal, or against a computer opponent. There are more than 800 animations and a score with tunes from the 1930s, when the game was invented.<p>On-line Monopoly is available in English, French, and German; the Web site converts currencies and translates property names. For example, when a player in Manhattan sells Boardwalk and Park Place to an opponent in London, they become Mayfair and Park Lane. You need Windows 3.1 or higher and a 486/33 MHz computer with eight megabytes of memory; a quad-speed CD-ROM drive is recommended. Direct Internet and World Wide Web access through SLIP and TCP/IP connections is required.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
