	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Music to Get Lucky by</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Music to Get Lucky by</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Music to Get Lucky by</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> MUSIC TO GET LUCKY BY  <p> By Gretchen Reynolds  <p> Of all the new music acts coming to Las Vegas, Dave Zabriskie's is probably the one that people will want to hear most. As a composer for WMS Gaming, a slot-machine manufacturer in Chicago, Zabriskie creates the melodies of jackpots.  <p> "In the old days, slot machines just kerplunked and pinged," Zabriskie explains. "It was dull, dull."  <p> Now the one-armed bandits toot, blare, and even talk. Take WMS Gaming's Western-themed slot, Jackpot Stampede. Players hear pounding hooves, braying horses, and cowboys yelling "Yee-haw." It's all set to a rollicking musical background that evokes, to the untrained ear, "Oklahoma." (Zabriskie says it's evocative of Aaron Copland.) The serenade sounds with every quarter a player drops into the machine, reaching its crescendo when someone hits the jackpot. Then lights flash and extra horns toot.  "It's sensational," Zabriskie explains, "but tasteful. You don't want to scare away the little old ladies."  <p> Of course, when it comes to a casino, "tasteful" covers a lot of territory. One of the company's other slot machines is Lucky Ladies, which is decorated with drawings of voluptuous 1940s sweater girls. The musical score is Glenn Miller's familiar "In the Mood." When three "Miss Firecrackers" or "Peek a Boo Sues" line up, the big-band sound bursts forth. For that, Zabriskie says, WMS did its own arrangement. "It's a really big big-band sound," he adds proudly.  <p> Zabriskie's serenading slots have proved popular in Atlantic City and also in the Midwest, but until late last year, WMS did not have a license to operate its machines in Las Vegas. James Jackson, senior vice president of gaming operations at WMS, is confident that the company's slots can make it in the big leagues."We give people fun," Jackson says. "If they don't hit the jackpot, well, then they get to hear some good-quality music. That's a fair trade, we think."  <p> Zabriskie has been with WMS for ten years now, ever since completing his doctorate in music composition at Northwestern University. In his spare time, he also composes classical symphonies for the Evanston Symphony in suburban Chicago.   <p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Small Business Ownership

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
