	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-Microsoft Alumni</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Microsoft Alumni: A Wealth of Options</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-Microsoft Alumni</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Need To Know  <p> MICROSOFT ALUMNI:  A WEALTH OF OPTIONS <p>You know the two billionaires:  here's what's become of the other nine  <p> By Jane Birnbaum  <p> Long before  Bill Gates began hobnobbing with Warren Buffett and guest-starring on David Letterman, the now mighty  <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft Corp. </b></a>consisted of a ragtag group working away in Albuquerque, New Mexico. In 1978, just before the company moved to the Seattle suburbs, the staff gathered for the company photo that appears on the following page. Of the 11 faces in the photograph, 2 are familiar: Gates, who is famously wealthy, and Paul Allen, the company co-founder, who is nearly as rich and famous as Gates. As for the rest? Almost all of them cashed in on those celebrated Microsoft stock options. But listening to them, you discover that money didn't drive these folks then, and  it doesn't now. <p> Marla Wood says, "I kind of kick myself for having left Microsoft before it went public, but staying wouldn't have been worth it. There was so much tension." Wood, 40, was originally enlisted to do part-time filing; later she became office manager. Today she lives outside Seattle with her husband, Stephen. She's a "professional volunteer," a full-time mom of two, and leader of Girl Scout troop No. 163. She uses a computer constantly, finding it especially helpful for keeping track of her troop's badge requirements.  <p> Stephen Wood, 43, left Microsoft in 1980, long before workers received a stock option plan, but he did start buying and selling shares in 1985. Originally a programmer, Wood moved on to jobs at Asymetrix and Starwave, two of Paul Allen's companies. In1994, he founded his own company, Notable Technologies, which will soon produce a pager-like device to notify stock traders of portfolio changes and price and volume alerts. Wood says he's followed Microsoft's example by hiring high-energy people and giving them stock options. "A start-up is very high risk," he says, "and the way you motivate people who are very bright and capable is to give them a piece of it."  <p> Programmer Marc McDonald, 39, was Microsoft's first permanent employee, in 1976. He left in 1984 because of a "corporate attitude that sucks people dry and throws away the husk," he says. As for the stock options, "you take a look at how much people were offered for the work they'd done. It was a joke," says McDonald, who works as a programmer for another Seattle start-up. Still, the options made him financially comfortable he has courtside seats for the Seattle Supersonics ("my biggest splurge," he says). They have also enabled him to speak his mind. "That's one thing I got out of Microsoft. I can say what I mean."  <p> Former Microsoft technical writer Andrea Lewis, 47, says, "Working with Bill and Paul was great because you always knew where you stood with them. You had to move fast, but you always knew where you stood." She left Microsoft in 1983 and exercised about two years' worth of stock options. Now living with her hydrologist husband in Seattle, she's at work on short stories and a novel."I have enough money so that I can go on calling myself a novelist for a couple more years."  <p> Programmer Bob Wallace, 46, left Microsoft in 1983 and exercised exactly one stock option, worth 450 shares. "I managed not to sell it, even when I was desperately in debt," says Wallace. Now that stock is worth $1.5 million. Wallace's latest venture is Mind Books, a direct-mail company in Sebastopol, California, that offers scholarly titles about psychedelic drug use.  "I knew in the 1960s that personal computers would become extremely important," he says. "And now these psychedelic compounds are the beginning of something that will be very useful."  <p> Robert O'Rear is a bona fide Microsoft millionaire. "I was fortunate to get the options and keep the options and exercise them overtime," he says, "and too busy to ever bother selling stock until it had accumulated a fair amount." Unlike most of the original team, O'Rear, 55, rode out the changes at Microsoft and retired two years ago. He now plans to spend more time with his brother on the cattle ranch they operate in their native Texas. "I'd hate to ever call ranching a business," he says. "It has its own category, I think."  <p> Freelance contract software engineer James Lane lives on secluded Seattle acreage, soon to include a dance hall, where he'll indulge his passion for the tango. When the 42-year-old programmer works, it's as a hired gun for start-ups. "There's an enthusiasm in the best of small companies that you rarely see in large companies,"he observes. "We had that at Microsoft at the beginning, and they beat it out of me." When he left in 1985 ("I wasn't happy with Microsoft, and they weren't happy with me") Lane exercised three years' worth of stock options. He says he's held on to his stock, and can quote the daily closing price down to an eighth.  <p> Bill Gates, 40, remains chairman and CEO of Microsoft.  <p> James Gordon Letwin, 44, rose at Microsoft to become an "architect," one of its high priests of programming. Three years ago he took an indefinite leave of absence to kick back with his wife in Seattle. "There's a dessert place here that sells a T-shirt that reads: life is uncertain; eat dessert first," he says. "We decided it was time to eat some dessert." Still friendly with Gates, he is advising on the construction of electronic systems for Gates's new house. Says Letwin: "Bill offered me money. But I thought taking it would be churlish, considering what we've been through."  <p> The day Robert Greenberg, 41, left his programming job at Microsoft in 1981, he received seven job offers. Some companies wanted to hire him "only to compete against Microsoft, but I didn't want to live my life for revenge." Greenberg, whose grandfather founded Coleco, later developed Intelligent Tee-Time Manager, software for golf courses. Years ago he taught computers to fellow students at Harvard, where he met Bill Gates.  <p> Paul Allen, 43, retired from Microsoft in 1983. Among his businesses: Asymetrix and Starwave.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
