	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Little Valentine to Hartz</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-A Little Valentine to Hartz</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> A LITTLE VALENTINE TO HARTZ  <p> Jim O'Gorman sent one of his valentines a little early this year. In this case, the valentine was a $10,000 ad in The Wall Street Journal in which he thanked his former employer, Leonard Stern, for 22 great years at the Hartz Mountain Corp.  <p> O'Gorman, who retired in late September from his job as a regional sales manager at Hartz, thought the ad would be a nice way of showing his appreciation to the company's owner. "I know Leonard is a billionaire," O'Gorman explains. "And what can you do for a billionaire?"  <p> Stern says the ad came as a complete surprise. His first reaction when he opened the Journal and saw An Open Letter to Leonard Stern' was negative. "I figured it was going to be an ugly complaint," he admits.  <p> Hardly. In the ad, which appeared late last year, O'Gorman praised Stern for "caring acts of kindness" and "concern for people." The boss was especially attentive when O'Gorman was diagnosed with kidney problems in March 1991. "Leonard called and said,Don't do anything until you get a second opinion,'" O'Gorman remembers. Stern flew O'Gorman from Atlanta to New York to see a specialist. A few months later, O'Gorman underwent heart surgery, and Stern telephoned several times to check on him.  <p> Upon his retirement, O'Gorman and his wife took a vacation, visiting Montana, Wyoming, and the Dakotas. "Now I've seen all 50 states," he says. He hasn't yet figured out everything he wants to do with his free time. "But I'm not going to sit around and watch Matlock," he says. "You know he's always going to win in the end, so that's a waste." <p>
KEYWORDS: Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
