	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-By Order of Kernel Lugar</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>By Order of Kernel Lugar</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-By Order of Kernel Lugar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> BY ORDER OF KERNEL LUGAR  <p> By Louis Jacobson  <p> Like many Republicans, Senator Richard G. Lugar of Indiana says he favors shrinking the federal government except when it comes to popcorn. Lugar, currently running for president, is the force behind the Popcorn Promotion, Research, and Consumer Information Act, a Senate bill introduced in late 1995. Under the bill, the government would levy an assessment on popcorn processors to fund a  Popcorn Board, which would  be overseen by the Agriculture Department and charged with managing an "effective, continuous, and coordinated program of promotion, research, [and] consumer information" on popcorn (much like programs for beef and eggs). <p> Should the government be sticking an invisible hand into the nation's snack foods? Sure, if you believe the bill's claim that "the production and processing of popcorn plays a significant role in the economy of the United States." (Oh, it's not just a snack food anymore, either. In the stately legislative prose of the bill, "popcorn is an important food that is a valuable part of the human diet.")  <p> Lugar declined to comment on the bill for this story. But Andy Fisher, press secretary for the Senate's Agriculture, Nutrition, and Forestry Committee, cautions against underestimating the power of popcorn. "It adds value in rural areas, so it benefits rural development in popcorn-growing regions," Fisher says. They include Indiana, Lugar's home state, and Iowa. Hmmm, isn't there a caucus or something in Iowa soon?  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Legislation, Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
