<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/02-A Rubens? Hot Dog!</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Rubens? Hot Dog!</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/02-A Rubens? Hot Dog!</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> A RUBENS?  HOT DOG!  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> As disputes in the art world go, this one's quite meaty. George Hormel II, the 67-year-old heir to the Spam fortune, claims he was tricked into buying some fake paintings. And the man he's accusing, Robert Peters, is no stranger to processed-meat products; he made his millions peddling Peters Wieners in the Midwest. <p> The feud, expected to go to trial later this year, dates back to July 1993. That's when Hormel and Peters, both living in Arizona, first met to talk about art. Hormel wanted to expand his collection. Peters had more than 200 paintings and sculptures to sell includingtwo paintings purportedly by Peter Paul Rubens and two by Maurice Utrillo. But there was a hitch, according to the complaint Hormel filed with the Superior Court of the State of Arizona: Hormel says he wasn't permitted to remove the four paintings from Peters's plush home to have them authenticated. In fact, he says he wasn't allowed any access to the art without buying Peters's house as well. Even so, after several viewings, Hormel and his wife agreed to buy the house and the art for $2.2 million.  <p> Now Hormel says he didn't get the Grade-A prime artwork he paid for. When he was finally able to have Sotheby's and Christie's evaluate the Rubenses and Utrillos, according to court filings, they turned out to be fakes. The Peters camp, however, says the works were sold as is. "Hormel's case is groundless," says Michael Gallagher, the attorney representing Peters. "The paperwork specifically had a disclaimer that said there was no guarantee of the art's authenticity."  <p> Neither Hormel nor his attorney will discuss the case, but Hormel's personal financial adviser, Allan Winter, says his client hopes to settle out of court. For now, the beef continues.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing, Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
