	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Wall Street Loves a Party</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Wall Street Loves a Party</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> WALL STREET LOVES A PARTY  <p> By Christina Ohly  <p> It's time to deck the halls of Wall Street again. Whatever the state  of the markets, and despite a Scrooge here and a Grinch there, most folks in the financial world will have at least one thing to celebrate this holiday season: a party. Here's a survey of the ghosts of Christmas parties past and present:  <p> <a name="NYSE:BSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10191"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BEAR STEARNS</b></a> Chairman Alan C. ("Ace") Greenberg hosts a magic show for employees and their children at the company's Park Avenue offices. Greenberg performs tricks with eggs, peanut butter, and jelly. "A three-year-old once told me it was the best magic act he'd ever seen," says Greenberg.  <p> Over five December nights in its Wall Street atrium, J.P. MORGAN holds fancy cocktail parties--food from around the world, including French wines, sushi, and Russian caviar--for different groups of employees.  <p> When the DREYFUS CORP. was acquired by Mellon Bank last year, the holiday dinner-dance at the Waldorf-Astoria's Grand Ballroom was one of the first things to go. "The days of wine and roses are clearly over at Dreyfus," says one staffer.  <p> Neither LAZARD FRERES nor <a name="NYSE:LEH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41936"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LEHMAN BROTHERS</b></a> throws a party--whether employees are naughty or nice.  <p> Chicago-based brokerage firm WILLIAM BLAIR & CO. celebrates with cocktails at the Mid-Day Club. Music is provided by William Blair's in-house band.  <p> Last year some CITICORP employees partied at the Cowgirl Hall of Fame in New York City. An awards ceremony featured the Orange County Award (for the biggest municipal-bond deal) and the Longest Deal (the winner received a sterling silver ruler from Tiffany). <p> At T. ROWE PRICE in Baltimore, pot luck departmental celebrations take place in one of the firm's conference rooms.  <p> PIPER JAFFRAY, in Minneapolis, offers its 2,800 or so employees a choice: 21-pound tom turkeys or 11-pound hen turkeys.  <p> FIDELITY INVESTMENTS throws a party for thousands at Boston's World Trade Center. The company provides food and entertainment; employees provide the laughs by performing skits in the "Fidelity Follies." At the various regional office bashes, attractions in past years have included karaoke and arcade games.  <p> FIRST INTERSTATE BANK in Los Angeles allocates $10 to $15 per employee; employees arrange themselves into groups, and then each group spends its holiday money as it wishes.  <p> SALOMON BROTHERS employees traditionally gather at Bridgewaters, a Manhattan restaurant. The Chicago office, after last year's soiree at Michael Jordan's restaurant, plans a sports-themed party again this year.  <p> Denver-based JANUS FUNDS hosts a dressy dinner that includes casino games. No money is wagered, but participants can win $50 gift certificates to such local establishments as Blockbuster Video, Chili's restaurants, and King Soopers grocery stores.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
