	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-A Son's Debt to His Mother</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-A Son's Debt to His Mother</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By William Green  <p> In the 1960s, the Joyce Chen Restaurant in Cambridge, Massachusetts, grew into a spectacular success. Local luminaries such as Julia Child and John Kenneth Galbraith were regulars, and Chen herself became a celebrity. As the host of her own Chinese cooking show on PBS, Chen introduced the American public to Peking duck, moo-shi pork, and other exotic delights.  <p> Her son, Stephen, was her dutiful assistant. At 13, he began packing take-out orders. At 16, he started driving the restaurant's employees home in the family's van each night. When his mother traveled to Hong Kong and Taiwan in search of new recipes, he left school and accompanied her for months on end. In those days, Joyce Chen's business flourished.  <p> Now 43, Stephen Chen is struggling to save his mother's business from a mess that he created. The trouble began in the mid-1980s, when Joyce Chen developed Alzheimer's disease. "One by one, things wouldn't get done," remembers Stephen Chen. "My mother would get lost driving home." When she acted irrationally, he would try to humor her: "She'd wake up at 5 a.m. and say, 'We've gotto go the restaurant.' I'd say, 'Okay,' and we'd go."  <p> When his mother's condition worsened, Stephen Chen assumed control of the business. He decided to set up a second Joyce Chen Restaurant, selected a site in Boston, and secured $1.85 million in loans by pledging his home and the restaurant in Cambridge as collateral. <p> If his mother had known what he was doing, says Chen, "she would have said I was crazy to spend so much money." But the Boston economy was booming and Chen thought he could profit from the area's revitalization. The project also appealed to him on a personal level: For the first time, he says, there was a "sense that maybe I could do something, too.... It felt good."   <p> His venture quickly hit the skids. Construction delays proved expensive; the Wang Center exhibition hall next door closed for repairs, depriving the fledgling restaurant of patrons; and Boston sank into the throes of recession. By 1991, the restaurant was $116,000 behind on rent and other payments. In 1994, Chen received an eviction notice. The restaurant was closed, and the property was converted into a microbrewery cum restaurant called Brew Moon. A few months later, Joyce Chen died at the age of 76, unaware that her business was near bankruptcy.  <p> Stephen Chen took the failure hard. "It was really a blow," he says. "When something like that happens, you realize how vulnerable you are." Worst of all, he adds, is a sense that he has let down his family. "I feel a little shameful," he says.  <p> The Cambridge restaurant is still serving customers, but Chen says the business is $1.5 million in debt. Part of him just wants to forget the debacle and move on. "To me, spiritually, I think I've paid enough," he says. Yet he still feels obligated to keep the restaurant open. "The idea," he says, "is not to let people forget Joyce Chen."  <p> Chen says he has come to believe that he devoted too much of his life to his mother's business. Now he's pursuing some of his own interests. He recently learned to ski and ride a motorcycle. And he's starting a family of his own. Two years ago, he married a woman he met through a dating agency, and they are about to adopt a baby girl from China. The baby's name is Mingxue, which means "bright snow." <p>
KEYWORDS: Family Business, Small Business Ownership

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

