<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Something in My Stocking Sure Smells Good</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Something in My Stocking Sure Smells Good</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 By Ralph Gardner Jr.  <p>
 I was eager to meet David Salz, president and CEO of western-hemisphere operations for Alfred Dunhill of London, the venerable English tobacconist and tailor. Dunhill makes the hearty, masculine aftershave that I use and my father used before me. (Dad's still around. But when Dunhill upped its prices a few years back, my father started diluting the fragrance with rubbing alcohol--even when he received it from me as a Christmas gift. He finally abandoned it completely.)  <p>
 I envisioned Salz as a Prince Philip type with impeccably tailored double-breasted suits, bushy eyebrows, and a wry, British sense of humor. I was frankly disappointed when I found him in shirtsleeves in his modest office above the company's Park Avenue store. He was on the phone, trying to sell a private locker in Dunhill's humidor to some guy from Goldman, Sachs. "Sign up before we run out," he was saying.  <p>
 When he got off the phone, Salz reluctantly admitted he doesn't use aftershave. "I have very, very sensitive skin," he said. <p>
 However, he did assure me that he shared my respect for the product--at least from the perspective of the company's balance sheet. "I find it fascinating that we can do $1.5 million in fragrance sales [at $37 for a 100-milliliter bottle] in ten stores when we don't promote this at all," he says. "It tells you there is huge brand loyalty."  <p>
 Dunhill sells two lines of its aftershave and cologne. There's the Classic, devotees of which include myself and Jerry Lewis. The comedian apparently applies the stuff liberally and is known to plug it on TV talk shows when interviewers question him about his aroma. Personally, I usually splash it on and then shower, a procedure that helps to mute its appealing but assertive scent. <p>
 There's also the newer, zippier Edition aftershave, which comes in a frosted bottle and has a fruity smell. Women are said to use it as well, and it accounts for a majority of Dunhill's fragrance sales.  <p>
 At the moment, the aftershaves are sold only at Dunhill stores and at a smattering of duty-free airport shops. But Salz thinks sales could expand dramatically with proper marketing. Among other things, that will require wholesaling the aftershave to retailers--for instance, Saks Fifth Avenue. "I would hope," Salz told me, "that a year from now when you and I meet, our fragrance business would be very much different than it is today, in terms of the seriousness with which we approach it."  <p>
 I kept my mouth shut. But I doubted that going wholesale was the right approach. I thought of the horror of walking through a department store and being ambushed with my own aftershave by one of those spritzing sales associates.  <p>
 Brand loyalty be damned. That'll be the day I switch to rubbing alcohol too.   
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

