<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Some Random Thoughts</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Some Random Thoughts</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Some Random Thoughts</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> SOME RANDOM THOUGHTS  <p> By Jack Egan  <p> In the new, sixth edition of his investment classic A Random Walk Down Wall Street, Princeton University economist Burton Malkiel argues once again that it's nearly impossible to beat the market. But for those who want to try anyway, we asked Malkiel--who has consistently outperformed the market over the past few years with his own private portfolio--for his thoughts on what's hot and what's not. Among his observations: There's a Warren Buffett bubble puffing up <a name="NYSE:BRK.A"></a><b>Berkshire Hathaway</b>'s stock. Malkiel also thinks <a name="FUND:FMAGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/FMAGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fidelity's Magellan Fund</b></a> is "highly risky," having binged on tech stocks. So what does he like? Malkiel, a contrarian, favors down trodden real estate investment trusts, recuperating Japanese shares, and AAA-rated tax-free municipal bonds. "There's an assumption built into the municipal market that we'll have a flat tax, which is not necessarily true," he says. For devoted Random Walk fans who want to stick with index funds, Malkiel warns that the popularity of Standard & Poor's 500 funds may have inflated their value. He likes funds based on the broader Wilshire 5000.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:BRK.A">Berkshire Hathaway</a><br>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:FMAGX">Fidelity's Magellan Fund</a><br>

