<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 96/01-Should This Man Be Fired?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Should This Man Be Fired?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Should This Man Be Fired?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> SHOULD THIS MAN BE FIRED?  <p> By Jane Birnbaum  <p> Okay, so the perks aren't too shabby. Members of the Council of Economic Advisers get to dine in the White House mess, hang out with the Commander in Chief, and take an occasional jaunton Air Force One. So who can blame Joseph Stiglitz for shuttering his office at Stanford University in 1993 and accepting Bill Clinton's invitation to join the council?  <p> Indeed, reports Stiglitz, the food at the White House mess puts the Stanford faculty club to shame. And there's nothing quite like a flight on the president's plane, where there are no nagging flight attendants to interrupt high-level chats about the latest gross domestic product numbers. "The first trip, we were working as the plane was taking off," says Stiglitz, the council's chairman. "People were standing at a 45-degree angle and holding their meeting."  <p> Alas, those fabulous fringe benefits would all come to an end if House Republicans have their way. Keeping the three-member council in business costs $3.4 million annually. The House Appropriations Committee deleted those funds from the proposed budget, arguing that the White House could make do with economic advice from other agencies. That move has put the council's future in limbo, though it appears likely that an effort by Republicans in the Senate to help the White House save the council will succeed. <p> If the council is sacrificed in the name of austerity, Stiglitz will get by. No matter how good the White House chefs are, produce in Washington, D.C., just doesn't compare to northern California. And frankly, the pay of a presidential advisor doesn't measure up. Stiglitz's CEA salary is around $130,000--about half his Stanford salary and forgone consulting fees. There's no cushy expense account making up the difference, either. "When we have guests from abroad or bring somebody into the mess to discuss an issue, we pay for them ourselves," Stiglitz says.  <p> The council just can't seem to get respect. Part of the White House since the Truman administration, the CEA consists of economists on leave from the nation's top universities. They stand ready to give the president analysis on all things economic, ranging from the meaning of economic indicators to the potential impact of a proposed tariff. And since they aren't entrenched Washington insiders, it is hoped they can offer the president unbiased opinions. <p> But most people don't find that very exciting. Herbert Stein, who chaired the council during the Nixon administration, remembers people asking him whether it was even a full-time job. (It is.) "Many members of Congress are not aware of how the CEA works, and there's a negative attitude now about intellectuals of any kind," says Stein. "They say, 'Who needs them,' like the CEA is the National Endowment for the Arts engaging in pornographic activity."  <p> And how does the average American feel about the council? Brian Cox, a beekeeper from Ojai, California, favors killing it off because, he says, Clinton "has it in for bee keepers" by opposing subsidies that help them cope with cheap Chinese honey flooding the country.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
