	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Miss America Talks About Investing</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>96/01-Miss America Talks...Investing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						December/January 1996 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> MISS AMERICA TALKS ABOUT INVESTING  <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> Shawntel Smith, a 24-year-old Oklahoman, was recently crowned Miss America, a title she'll hold for a year. After that, she'll return to Oklahoma City University, where she's pursuing a master's of business administration degree. We decided to test her poise yet again by asking her about money, investing, and nondurable goods.  <p> Do you have any investments?  <p>No, I sure don't. But that will be something to consider in the future.   <p> Will you make more money now that you're Miss America?  <p>Yes, I will. I could make $250,000 over the next year. I will want to invest that money and put it in places where it could grow.  <p> If you did invest, where would you put your money?  <p>Well, we have some wonderful sponsors of the Miss America Organization: <a name="NYSE:FTL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11960"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Fruit of the Loom</b></a>, Konica, <a name="NASD:WATFZ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42015"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Waterford Wedgwood</b></a>, and Clairol. As far as learning anything from the Miss America Organization on investing, those are companies that I would strongly consider investing in. Also, I've grown up with <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a> stores in my area, and they stand behind their products. I might invest in Wal-Mart.   <p> What else have you won?  <p>I also won $12,000 by winning the Miss Oklahoma title. I've competed in Miss America for six years and it's paid for my entire education. I foresee my scholarships paying for my M.B.A. and, after that, my Ph.D.  <p> Have you spent a lot of money on pageants?  <p>I've bought a dress here and there, but I never spent a whole lot of money. But I competed in the pageants to get the scholarship money, so I wouldn't shoot myself in the foot by buying an expensive gown. And of course, my family wouldn't allow it because that would mean I wasn't competing for the right reasons.  <p> What did your family teach you about money?  <p>My dad owned a small furniture business, so we always had to work hard for money. We never made money a big priority in our lives.  <p> What have your pageant experiences taught you about money? <p>Don't abuse it, don't spend too much, and save it. I've also learned that I should invest for a secure future and my retirement. Now that I'll be making more money, I'll definitely learn more about investing.  <p> Do you think the current state of the economy is good or bad? <p>I know that in my community in Oklahoma, we're doing pretty good. There's people purchasing durable and nondurable goods in Oklahoma. And as far as the nation, we're doing okay.  <p> Is there anything you want to buy with the money you'll receive? <p>Later on, I will buy my dream sports car: a red <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> Mustang with a tan interior. Definitely a convertible.  <p> Do you think Americans care too much about money?  <p>Unfortunately, some people place too much importance on money. That's too bad, because money can't make you happy.   <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
