	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Son of Spam</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Son of Spam</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Son of Spam</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> SON OF SPAM  <p> By Dean Robinson  <p> Axel Boldt likes Spam  if it's a cold dish in a Monty Python sketch. But when it's a force-fed diet of advertisements blasted over the Internet--a process nicknamed "spamming" by denizens of the Net--Boldt gags. So to fight back against overeager entrepreneurs in cyberspace, Boldt created his own World Wide Web page, which he calls the Blacklist of Internet Advertisers.  <p> Boldt says he was inspired by Larry Canter and Martha Siegel, two Arizona lawyers who earned notoriety last year for spamming the Internet's discussion groups with ads for their services. "I was in a bookstore, and I saw their book, How to Make a Fortune on the Information Superhighway," Boldt says. "I thought, I've got to do something about these guys."  <p> For Boldt, a 29-year-old student from Germany working on a Ph.D. in math at the University of California's Santa Barbara campus, that something turned out to be the Blacklist, a roster of the worst offenders of Internet etiquette. Attorneys Canter and Siegel were the first named to this hall of shame, and more than 50 others have since joined them.  <p> Simply advertising on the Internet isn't enough to draw Boldt's wrath; he isn't a purist trying to keep cyberspace commerce-free. Instead he's railing against advertising that is intrusive and indiscriminate. Sending unsolicited ads through electronic mailis one of his pet peeves. Another is burdening Internet bulletin-board discussion areas, called newsgroups, with ads for products or services that have nothing to do with the discussion's topic. For instance, take the person who sent an ad for credit card information to an animal-rights discussion. Or the folks at the Sound Healing Center: They spammed 61 newsgroups in order to sell "what Jesus Christ, Buddha, Shiva, and Pythagoras knew."(Price: $3.00.)  <p> Boldt says he doesn't advocate retaliatory spamming or other sorts of digital mayhem. "I'm not so much into punishing these guys," he says. Instead, Boldt encourages simply boycotting the businesses. That said, though, the Blacklist (located on theWeb at http://math-www.uni-paderborn.de/~axel/BL/blacklist.html) pointedly provides the names, telephone numbers, and computer addresses of offenders.  <p> Boldt plans to return to Germany after completing his dissertation,"The Position of Uniserial Modules in the Auslander-Reiten Quiver of Finite Dimensional Algebras," but he doesn't expect to escape the spammers, even though most of those on the Blacklist are based in the U.S. "It's much easier for a business or for a private person to get Internet access in the States," says Boldt. "But this will change, and we will start to see more non-American asses."  <p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
