<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-The Right Way to Stiff</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Right Way to Stiff</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-The Right Way to Stiff</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> THE RIGHT WAY TO STIFF  <p> By Carol A. Schatz  <p> All hell broke loose just as the diners were about to tuck into their wild striped bass. The problem, it seems, was the bottle of 1994 Rioja. "This wine is undrinkable, and we can't have it with our dinner!" shouted one guest, shattering the genteel atmosphere of Solera, a stylish Spanish restaurant in midtown Manhattan. Another, examining the label with disdain, exclaimed, "What kind of grape is this?"  <p> Fortunately, this was only a test, not an actual food emergency. The indignant patrons were practicing how not to return spoiled wine as part of a workshop on obtaining better restaurant service. Twenty-five passionate diners--from a Wall Street futures salesman who called eating out his hobby to a physician who described herself as a "professional foodie"--paid $85 each for a three-course dinner with wine and well-seasoned advice from New York City service consultant Eric Weiss.  <p> Weiss, 45, has been in the restaurant business in one way or another since the age of 16. He normally runs service classes for the trade but recently decided to offer his expertise to the general public. The enthusiastic response didn't surprisehim. "I think I've hit a nerve," he says.  <p> And indeed, the assembled guests at Solera seemed in need of therapy for traumatic experiences had while dining out. Their litany of woes from various restaurants included dead flies on the sorbet, horse meat substituted for steak, and waiting-for-Godotstyle service. After Weiss invited the group to share memorable experiences, a young man recalled the time a runaway dessert cart plowed down his table as he dived for cover. The group sighed with sympathy."I'm afraid I've had more bad experiences than good, and that's why I'm here tonight," said one member.  <p> Unfazed, Weiss worked the group like a food-obsessed Phil Donahue, describing problematic restaurant scenarios and asking for possible solutions. "I used to get good service by using doctor' when I reserved," offered a wine consultant. "It worked. But then it backfired when somebody had a heart attack and they called me over." A real doctor dismissed that as no problem, saying that all one needs to do when that happens is to recommend calling an ambulance. "That's all I do," he said, "and then you usually get a free meal or a bottle of wine."  <p> That incited more recollections from the increasingly chatty crowd, forcing Weiss to quiet them all in order to get back to addressing their biggest complaints, such as enduring a surly waiter while trying to send a dish back to the kitchen. Weiss advised being honest, specific, immediate, firm, and gracious while returning food.  <p> Some of Weiss's other suggestions for dining bliss: get the name of the person who takes your reservation; total up the items on your check--waiters make both honest and not-so-honest mistakes; and send a thank-you note to a chef or manager if you've had a great meal. Practices to avoid, Weiss said, are forgetting to cancel a reservation; offering a gratuity to the maitre d' beforehand (most aren't comfortable being bribed); and antagonizing servers by snapping your fingers, calling their names, or tugging at their sleeves. And if you must return wine, do so graciously, and keep in mind that when it comes to very expensive bottles--or what one diner called "show-off" wines--it's caveat emptor. <p> The key to better service, Weiss concluded, is to act as if you were a guest in someone's home--a tipping guest, of course."If someone has been rude, I have no problem stiffing," he said."But you must tell the person in charge--the owner or the maitre d'--why."  <p> That posed no obstacle for a seemingly demure woman from Virginia. "Food matters so tremendously to me that after breakfast I start thinking about lunch," she said. "After lunch, then dinner. So if I go to a restaurant and things aren't good, I'm not quiet at all." 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
