	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Re: Pilgrim's Progress</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Diane Goldner  <p>
 A lot can happen in just under 400 years. Which is why Alicia Williams has some perspective on immigration to these United States.  <p>
 "It's fine with us," says Williams, a Katharine Gibbs graduate and genealogist who traces her own lineage back to those legendary immigrants, the Mayflower pilgrims. "The old idea about the melting pot of America, that you have to become homogeneous, it's changed now to the idea of a goulash: The gravy is the Americanization that keeps us together. But diversity is great. We aren't throwing ourselves across the portal.S If you travel across this country, you will realize there's plenty of room left."  <p>
 Williams, 48, was born on the army base at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas. Today she makes her home in Hingham, Massachusetts, living with her parents in their ranch-style house. Hingham is about 30 miles from Duxbury, where Williams's forebear John Alden settled after arriving in Plymouth on the Mayflower. Alden was awarded 600 acres in the colony's land grant. But the land is long since gone--divided up and sold off piece by piece. "If we had 600 acres, we'd all be very rich," says Williams. "I only wish. It's a distinguished lineage, not distinguished money. There's a big difference." 
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
