	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Basking in the Hall of Fame</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Basking in the Hall of Fame</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> BASKING IN THE HALL OF FAME  <p> By Ralph Gardner, Jr.  <p> Miss Hall's, a prestigious private school for girls in Pittsfield, Massachusetts, will deploy a not-so-secret weapon in its $10 million fund-raising campaign this fall: Trudy E. Hall, the school's head. Hall, 40, has a loquacious personality, a solid educational track record, and a jar of M&Ms that she forces on visitors. But when it comes to persuading alumnae to open their wallets, her most convincing quality may be the last name she shares with Mira Hinsdale Hall, who founded the academy back in 1898.  <p> The two women aren't related as far as Trudy Hall can tell, but many of the school's graduates don't know that. Alumnae--some of them old enough to remember the original Miss Hall, who worked at the school until her death in 1937--tend to approach her at school functions with enchanted expressions, Hall reports. Then they'll gush about how wonderful it is to have "Miss Hall" back at the old school again. "The assumption is that I must have the same standards she had for the school," Hall says.  <p> There were actually two Miss Halls prior to Trudy: Miss Mira, as she was known, and her niece, Miss Margaret, who took over the school when her aunt died. The latest Miss Hall assures us that she never tries to pass herself off as a blood relative:"My disclaimer is usually, Oh, but I wish I were!' "  <p> But Hall is leaving the genealogical door open just a crack. Trudy is of Scottish descent, as were her predecessors at the school, and Trudy's dad recently discovered some old family portraits that bear a striking resemblance to Mira and Margaret. Does Trudy share an ancestor with Mira somewhere back in history? The issue could be settled shortly; the Berkshire Historical Society, which Miss Margaret founded after her retirement from the school, isusing a recent grant to dust off and catalog the old Hall family arcana in its files.  <p> Useful as it may be drumming up endowment dollars, the Hall name does have some drawbacks. Particularly when Trudy Hall is checking into a hotel late at night and a smart-alecky front-desk clerk, looking at the address that she's written on the register, can't help pointing out that she resides at a school that bears her name. "At 11 o'clock at night when that happens to you, you're about ready to throttle the person," Hall says. 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
