	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-Defending Sweet Cheeks</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Defending Sweet Cheeks</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-Defending Sweet Cheeks</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> DEFENDING SWEET CHEEKS  <p> By Sharon Churcher  <p> Wags in Texas have suggested that when the inevitable TV movie is made about Anna Nicole Smith's fight for a chunk of her late husband's fortune, it might well be titled The Bimbo and the Brain.  <p> The brain in this case is Diana Marshall, Smith's Houston lawyer. A tough-talking redhead, Marshall, 47, was once named among the nation's top women litigators in a Time magazine poll. Until now she was best known for corporate work on behalf of such button-downclients as Tenneco and Texas Commerce Bank--hardly the obvious candidate to represent a former Playboy centerfold. But Marshall says she leapt at the chance to take Smith's case.  <p> "Anna has been treated without any regard at all for her rights, and I consider that to be an affront to wives, women, and spouses anywhere," Marshall declares. "I find her an attractive person to represent because she only wants what is fair."  <p> What's fair depends on what you think about Smith's marriage last year to oil mogul J. Howard Marshall II (no relation to Diana). When the wedding took place, he was wheelchair-boundand 89; she was 26. "I don't believe that Anna Nicole married Howard for his money," says Diana Marshall. "But even if she did, I can't think of any way that it would be relevant to her legal rights. Whether or not you love your spouse is not relevant to what you get when he dies."  <p> The question of Smith's legal rights is complicated. At stake is a potential share in the estate's big prize--a family trust valued between $480 million and $3.2 billion. Smith was essentially excluded from the trust by documents Howard Marshall signed two weeks after the marriage. Smith has alleged in court filings that Howard's son, E. Pierce Marshall, used "fraud" or "undue influence" to get his father to sign those papers. In an alleged attempt to keep his father away from Smith, Pierce eventually went to court and had his father declared mentally incapacitated. <p> Diana Marshall has no doubts as to Howard's capacity. "We will prove that Howard Marshall was a man who truly demonstrated never a moment of senility," she says. "He was a man who had a legendary love for beautiful women."  <p> And that's why he fell for a woman who might be cast as the bimbo? "I do not consider her to be that at all," snaps the lawyer."Anna is very strong in some ways, and in others she's quite vulnerable and unsophisticated. In some ways, she is, shall we say naive.<p> There's no question that Diana Marshall feels sympathy for Smith--may be even a certain kinship. Like Smith, Diana grew up in Texas. She was raised in the oil camps near Odessa, where her father was a $100-a-week pumper. After working her way through school, she became one of the first women to make partner at Baker & Botts, family firm of former secretary of state James Baker. Unlike Smith, Marshall has never appeared at a strip club or assumeda stage name like "Sweet Cheeks." But she does perform in public, playing the banjo and harmonica in a country and western band called the Texas Barflies.  <p> Even if Marshall does share some traits with Smith, it would be a mistake to view her as naive or vulnerable. Once, when a judge condescendingly referred to her as "lady" while addressing her male adversary as "counselor," Marshall sweetly informed the judge, "You can call him lady, too."  <p> Courtroom viewers can expect to see this no-nonsense attitude when Smith's case goes to trial. Pierce Marshall's lawyers are likely to portray Smith as a callous predator; in court papers they've accused her of carrying on "adulterous" affairs behind her elderly husband's back. Diana Marshall maintains that her client's character has nothing to do with her rights as J. Howard Marshall's widow. "I can't think of anything they could say about Anna that would be relevant in court," she says smoothly.   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

