	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>CPA: Certified Party Animal?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-CPA: Certified Party Animal?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> CPA: CERTIFIED PARTY ANIMAL?  <p> By Lauren Goldstein  <p> Surely, at some point, you've thought, My accountant is a nerd. And that's exactly the kind of attitude that causes CPAs to want to throw off their green eyeshades and break a No. 2 pencil in half. Now the American Institute of CPAs is fighting back witha $3 million ad campaign it feels will pump up the image of CPAs and get clients to think of them as financial planners, not number-crunchers. But will it? Here's a sample: "The CPA. Never underestimate the value." In other words, don't expect to see ads with your favorite accountant wearing a milk mustache or imploring you to "just do it." When Accounting Today polled readers, most favored the plan, but a hint of the CPA's true nature crept into one response: "Don't make it look like those Calvin Klein ads."  

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

