<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/11-A Grave Issue for Investors</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Grave Issue for Investors</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/11-A Grave Issue for Investors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> A GRAVE ISSUE FOR INVESTORS  <p> By Jack Egan  <p> When Republican Congressman Jack Fields was growing up in the tiny oil town of Humble, Texas--now subsumed by the sprawling suburbs north of Houston that make up his district--he was paid 25 cents an hour to dig cemetery graves for his father's funeral business.  <p> Today he stands accused by foes of trying to bury investors' rights. Fields, the chairman of the House Telecommunications and Finance Subcommittee, recently introduced the Capital Markets Deregulation and Liberalization Act of 1995. If passed, the measure would constitute the most dramatic revision of America's securities laws since they were put on the books following the crash of1929.  <p> "Everything is on the table," Fields says--from easing corporate takeover rules to giving brokers the benefit of the doubt when dealing with big-buck investors. Under Fields's bill the federal government would even gut the role of state securities regulators, who typically deal with penny-stock frauds that are too small to draw the notice of the Securities and Exchange Commission. <p> Hearings were set to begin in October. Needless to say, state regulators strenuously oppose the bill. "This measure would take the cops off the beat across America and leave small investors on their own," says the North American Securities Administrators Association, a group representing state regulators. Also crying foul is Representative Edward Markey, Fields's predecessor as chairman of the subcommittee. Markey, a Massachusetts Democrat, calls the bill an "ideologically driven assault" and "a solution in search of a problem."  <p> Texas-tall and boyish looking at 43, Fields scoffs at such accusations."Any time you review something that hasn't been looked at for 60 years, it's going to shake some people up," says Fields at the desk of his spacious House office. None of the changes, he says, "would compromise investor protection in any way."  <p> Beyond that, though, Fields offers few specific assurances as to why little-guy investors shouldn't be worried. The bill is more likely to please the brokerage community, which for years has been a significant source of campaign contributions for the eight-term congressman. (From 1985 to 1994, Fields received $660,000 in contributions from political action committees representing securities and finance interests.) But Fields--a long-time champion of free-market views--says he's convinced that both individuals and publicly owned companies can benefit from the lifting of some existing regulations.  <p> One example, Fields says, is the rules governing dissemination of information to investors. He fixes on those bulky prospectuses, which investors are supposed to review before they buy shares in a new offering but which few are able to comprehend.   <p> "As Jack Citizen, if I want to buy shares in <a name="NYSE:XON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10537"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Exxon</b></a>, why shouldn't I just be able to go online with them and ask them to answer a few pertinent questions?" he asks.  <p> Among other reforms, Fields would also like to see the number of SEC commissioners cut to three from five. He'd also like to see the SEC's budget trimmed. And he's for privatizing the SEC's electronic records system, known as EDGAR. Especially in the area of technology, he says, the market and not the government can do things "better, faster, and at a lower cost."  <p> Will the bill make it? Legislation making it much tougher to sue publicly owned companies for misleading individual investors sailed through the House and Senate this summer, and only small differences remain to be hammered out. With pro-business sentiment strong in Congress, Fields's deregulation proposal could very well pass.  <p> When he's not plotting the future of finance, Fields focuses on the other half of his subcommittee's beat, the telecommunications industry. Earlier this year he won high marks inside the Beltway for steering an overhaul of communications regulations through all-but-final passage. Under that bill, cable television companies would be permitted to offer telephone service, while phone companies would be allowed to deliver movies to homes--potentially revolutionizing the entertainment industry.  <p> For Fields, entertainment mainly amounts to catching old movies on late-night cable. "My favorite actors," he says, "are Errol Flynn, John Wayne, and Gary Cooper."  <p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Legislation, Technology Industry<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


