<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Sister Activists</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Sister Activists</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Sister Activists</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth Magazine/Outfront  <p> SISTER ACTIVISTS  <p> By Laura Goldstein  <p> Fictional nuns go off to Africa to visit leper colonies or hangout with Bing Crosby in failing Catholic schools. Real nuns keepan eye on their investments. Sister Marie Lucey, who monitors the retirement fund for the Sisters of St. Francis of Philadelphia, is in charge of making sure her convent keeps its conscienceclean while it pursues a decent dividend. That means scrutinizing portfolios managed by Mellon Bank and Smith Barney and generally making a nuisance of herself to corporate chieftains such as John Smale, chairman of <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>, and Jack Welch, chairman of <a name="NYSE:GE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10634"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Electric</b></a>.  <p> It may be awkward to argue with a nun, but the chairmen try. When Sister Marie Lucey chastised Smale at this year's annual stockholders meeting over the company's involvement in foreign military sales, he didn't hesitate to invoke GM's new time limits designed to silence perennial rabble-rousers. In fact, Smalecut the nun off twice. "The rules were not clear," she says."I thought it was rather foolish. I was not ranting and raving. I fully expected to have my say."  <p> GE's Welch, an Irish Catholic, is less sanguine about messing with the church. Sister Marie Lucey fondly remembers the time in 1992 he helicoptered in to the order's mother house in Aston, Pennsylvania, 20 miles south of Philadelphia, for a chat. The nun wanted GE to phase out weapons production for more Christian pursuits. "It was very exciting," she says. "That he agreed to the meeting acknowledged the influence we have." That fall, GE announced that it would sell its defense business. Says a spokesman:"We sold the division because of market conditions ... not because of any protest group."  <p> Whatever.  <p> The 60-year-old nun has been applying the ruler to corporate knuckles for 17 years now. Standing about five feet tall, with smartly cropped gray hair and wearing a conservatively long white skirt topped by a blue blouse (accessorized only by a cross), she works from a cramped office at a small convent in Philadelphia, tracking the stocks selected for the portfolios by the pros at Mellon and Smith Barney and sniffing out such problematic activities as discrimination or environmental transgressions. Then she writes to the companies, follows up with phone calls, arranges meetings with executives, and attends shareholder gatherings. Occasionally, Sister Marie Lucey will instruct the investment managers to divest a stock on ethical grounds, though she might opt to keep a small number of shares in the portfolio just so she can continue to give the company a hard time. (<a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a> was the latest to receive this treatment.)  <p> This fall, Sister Marie Lucey will retire from her job with the Sisters of St. Francis fund and take up work as an employment coordinator for Project H.O.M.E., a Philadelphia organization that works with homeless people who are addicted or mentally ill. In her new role, Sister Marie Lucey won't need to attend shareholder meetings. That development seems likely to please the regular contingent of agitators who can be a bit competitive about the spotlight. Evelyn Davis, a notorious annual-meeting gadfly, said she wouldn't miss the nun at all because she didn't know who she was. Then, reminded that Sister Marie Lucey had been squelched at this year's GM gathering, Davis said, "I was the main story there. I was cut off too."   <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
