	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Proof of Money Trees</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Proof that Money Grows on Trees</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Proof of Money Trees</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> PROOF THAT MONEY GROWS ON TREES  <p> By Laura Goldstein  <p> It may be inadvisable to accept a wooden nickel, but Mats Lijemark hopes folks won't be similarly spooked by a wooden credit card. The 29-year-old Swede and his father, Bengt, have developed a thin birch wafer they think is well suited for charging purchases of blond modular furniture, aquavit, and the like.  <p> The pair created the EcoCard as a test for Telia, the Swedish national phone company. Telia under pressure from environmentalists in Sweden wanted an alternative to its plastic phone cards. The Lijemarks hope to branch out from wooden phone cards to key cards for hotels and eventually to full-fledged credit cards.  <p> The younger Lijemark believes wooden cards won't present any knotty problems for consumers. Asked whether card carriers need worry about splinters, he replies, "No, not at all." Is the EcoCard suitable for whittling? No. But it can be imprinted with raised letters and numbers, just like a plastic credit card. Will the EcoCard burn? Well, yes.  <p> To Lijemark, wood is ideal for credit cards, and Sweden is an ideal place to make them. "Trees," he points out, "are not a problem in Scandinavia." <p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
