<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-The Next Warren Buffett?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Is This the Next Warren Buffett?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-The Next Warren Buffett?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> IS THIS THE NEXT WARREN BUFFETT?  <p> By Jane Birnbaum  <p> As hawk on American Gladiators, self-described "in-shape big guy" Lee Reherman was in New York City last year to help drum up investors for a live version of the televised athletic clash. At dinner one night, he sat beside a stockbroker in his early 20s. "Suddenly he starts pitching himself as a great retail broker and wants to open an account for me," Reherman recalls. "When you're on TV, everyone thinks you're a billionaire and wants to sell you something. He thought I was a meathead Gladiator." <p> Carrying 245 pounds on a six-foot-four-inch frame, Reherman is muscular, but not steroidally so. And with his beefy brown-red skin and a blond buzz cut, he does look a bit like your average meathead. So he let the broker natter on before delivering the death blow. "I asked whether he preferred the capital-asset pricing model or the arbitrage pricing theory. The kid had no idea what I was talking about. He was just shocked. I felt bad for him and bought him a few beers."  <p> Clearly, this is one gladiator who knows his puts from his calls. Reherman, a 29-year-old native of Louisville, Kentucky, has already earned an M.B.A. from the Anderson Graduate School of Management at UCLA. Now he's working on a Ph.D. in economics at Anderson while putting in time as a business think-tank researcher.  <p> His jock credentials are in order, too. During his undergraduate days at Cornell, Reherman was an offensive lineman on the Big Red football squad. After college he took his shot at pro football but was cut from the Miami Dolphins' roster during preseason training. He then spent three years in sports marketing before turning to graduate school. And it was there, while working out one day at the weight room, that he was discovered by a talent agent. Soon Reherman was firing tennis balls at Spandex-suited contestants in the Gladiators arena.  <p> It has proved to be a steady gig. Reherman was recently renewed for his third Gladiators season. "He's not only a great athlete, but a big personality," says Adam Jordan, coordinating producer for the program. "Sometimes he gets a little too wild and we say, Calm Hawk down.' " (The producers dubbed him Hawk because of his expansiveness and because his hair fringe flies out like wings when ungelled.)  <p> Reherman's verbal skills are highly prized on the show. "Whenever we need a good one-liner, he always has something witty to say," Jordan says. His financial savvy is also valued. Fellow gladiators often ask for Hawk's counsel. He won't recommend specific stocks, but he is willing to listen to people talk out their problems and to discuss the risks and benefits of various courses of action. "If they ask what investments I'm in, I'll tell them," Reherman says. "But I always give a disclaimer."  <p> Now Reherman is looking to the big screen. He recently completed his first starring role as an Austrian ski instructor in a family movie called Downhill Willy. Later, he figures a financial-services career awaits. Will his days as Hawk be an asset in the investment world? "It might be tough for people who watched the show as teenagers when ten years from now I'm dealing with them in a business relationship,"he says. "Say I'm a portfolio manager. Would you let Hawk manage your money?"  <p> But Reherman wouldn't be Hawk without his confidence in himself and the future: "Somebody may also look at the fact I accomplished a lot athletically and respect my diversity," he says. "I have no idea how it will play out, nor do I worry."  <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
