<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-MIT's Late-Night Pizza King</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-MIT's Late-Night Pizza King</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jim Melloan  <p> Pizza joints in Cambridge, Massachusetts, take note: If late-night business falls off this year, blame Andrew W. Lo. The boyish finance professor at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology has created a trading-room simulator destined to become the new hip hangout among budding M.B.A.s.  <p> Indeed, Lo sees his simulator becoming a regular campus hot spot, with students loitering into the wee hours to catch the latest prices from stock exchanges on the other side of the world. "Students should be getting good sleep," Lo says. "But I suspect we're going to have some people staying here."  <p> The simulator (officially, the Laboratory for Financial Engineering) opens for business this fall, and it promises to be the first of its kind a true simulation of a brokerage trading room. Students can choose to work with live data from the financial markets or try their hand at coping with such mocked-up disasters as a sudden plunge in the dollar.   <p> Not that Lo will be training the brainy students at MIT's Sloan School of Management to be mere traders. "We're in the business of producing sophisticated financial engineers," he says. In other words, high-paid Wall Street wizards who cook up new derivatives and decide how to price them.  <p> Lo, 35, seems a fittingly wired choice to direct the lab. Boasting a bachelor's degree in economics from Yale and a Ph.D. from Harvard, he believes that most kinds of trading done by people today can be automated. "What you need humans for is to understand the motivation for trading, to come up with the ideas, to take the ideas from the blackboard to the trader," he says. "The technology we're now developing will automate the easy trades and allow the traders to really focus, using human judgment and intuition on the more difficult ones."  <p> Would anyone dispute him on this? "Yes," he says. "The current installed base of traders would argue with me."  <p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Market Trends, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
