<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Remember Your First Time</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>You Always Remember Your First Time</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Remember Your First Time</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> YOU ALWAYS REMEMBER YOUR FIRST TIME  <p> By Christina Ohly  <p> Michael Minikes <p>Treasurer, <a name="NYSE:BSC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10191"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bear Stearns & Co.</b></a> <p>" I bought my very first stock for all the wrong reasons. My girlfriend at the time Cheryl, now my wife of 30 years, worked at a small brokerage firm and gave me a hot tip. The stock was in a company called Commonwealth Oil Refining, and I can't quite remember how it performed. My first important stock buy, however,was in a company called Felmont Oil, which is no longer in existence. It was recommended by a broker friend at Bear Stearns. That buy made me enough money for my wife to redo the kitchen in our apartmentin grand style. And she was going to redo it anyway, so that stock was a very good thing. "  <p> Evelyn Lauder <p>Senior corporate vice president, <a name="NYSE:EL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=40148"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Estee Lauder Companies</b></a> <p>" My first shares were in Pacific Southwest Airlines. My husband, Leonard, and I flew the airline on our honeymoon in July of 1959. We  traveled out west, and it was so enjoyable that I decided to buy stock in the company. "  <p> Floyd Abrams <p>First Amendment lawyer <p>" My first stock purchase was 200 shares of Penn Central railroadback in the '60s. It soared and soared and rose from $20 a share to $200. Unfortunately, I held on to that stock until Penn Central's bankruptcy at $1 a share.... I bought it on the recommendation of a very intelligent person. Unfortunately, he didn't tell me exactly when to sell. I've learned since that it's much easier to lose money than to make it in the stock market.  "  <p> Ken SEIff <p>Founder and CEO, Pivot Rules Co. <p>" I picked my first stock in 1986 after I received a phone bill from a call I made on spring break in Mexico. The call lasted ten minutes and cost something like $75. I was so floored by the size of that bill that I decided to look further into Telefonos de Mexico. I borrowed $10,000 and bought a number of shares at nine cents each. I held on for a year and a half and bought more. I cashed out in the fall of '87, three weeks before the market crashed. When I sold the stock, I made about $50,000 which I used to start my company.  "  <p> Ben Cohen <p>Cofounder, <a name="NASD:BJICA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12763"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ben & Jerry's Homemade</b></a>  <p>" My first stock investment was my 50 percent stake in Ben & Jerry's, which started out at zero value. When the company went public several years later, though, it was worth real money. Later, I invested in a Vermont company marketing a vegetarian chili called Chili 2000. They were committed to eliminating hunger by the year 2000. I lost all of my money there. "  <p> Ellin Saltzman <p>Vice president and fashion director, <a name="NYSE:LTD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11471"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>The Limited</b></a>  <p>" I bought my first grown up stock as a 22-year-old newlywed. It was an oil stock Asamera Oil and it was about $1 or $2 a share. I bought under $1,000 worth on a hot tip from a friend. My husband went crazy at me for gambling with so much money. I ended up doubling my money on that investment, however. "<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies

					</font>
