<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-Don't Tax Her Patience</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-Don't Tax Her Patience</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> Lee Sheppard is one cranky lady. In her weekly column for TaxNotes, an insider D.C. newsletter read by 4,000 lawyers, accountants, journalists, and other tax junkies nationwide, Sheppard routinely vents her spleen over apparent abuses of the tax system.  <p> And she gets personal: Among those who have crossed her sights are Speaker of the House Newt Gingrich, ex-White House chief of staff John Sununu, and former Virginia governor Douglas Wilder. A recent target was Bob Dole, whom she savaged for setting up a think tank with tax-free status. Sheppard saw it instead as a campaign organization in disguise or, as she put it, "a haven for former Bushies." The day after her story appeared, Dole announced he was disbanding the organization.  <p> At Tax Notes, Sheppard, 38, has earned a reputation as a thorough reporter. But one suspects that her readers savor her column for its biting prose as much as for its Beltway insights. On the doomed Clinton health care reform bill, she wrote: "It is difficult to believe that 500 educated people labored six months over this ill-conceived package. It is more likely that the scheme sat in White House Senior Policy Advisor Ira Magaziner's head until he found time to commit it to paper."  <p> The sharp words just come naturally, it seems. "I hate phony images and hypocrisy," she says. "I like to break down the tax-law-abiding faade that anybody puts on. I shouldn't take this stuff so personally.I'm going to blow a gasket one of these days."  <p> Perhaps. It's certain that her subjects explode from time to time. When Sheppard recently seared corporate tax lawyers, lobbyist Tim McCormally fired off a letter accusing her of a "calumnious" smear campaign. The only things missing from her piece, McCormally wrote, were comparisons between tax lawyers and "white males, members of the Michigan Militia, or disciples of the Religious Right."  <p> But Sheppard gets her share of fan letters, too. Senator Bill Bradley is an avid reader. Other admirers include tax-minded staffers at the Treasury, Congress, and Washington think tanks. Says Henry Aaron, a tax expert at the Brookings Institute: "She's fun to read."  <p> "Fun" isn't how Sheppard characterizes her early exposure to the world of taxes. After graduating from Northwestern University's School of Law in 1981, she took a job at a Chicago law firm and soon found herself helping rich guys find loopholes. So she sent her rsum to the editors of Tax Notes, and a tax muckracker was born. After putting in seven years in Washington, she moved to New York in 1991. "I like the vibe, speed, and impatience of New York because it matches my personality," she says. "It's the only place where aggressive, tough women are completely welcome." <p> Inside Sheppard's Manhattan apartment, the floor is cluttered with stacks of paper two feet high. There she pores over tax-related documents eight hours a day, perching on a smoker's chair while tunes by Black Sabbath and Led Zeppelin play in the background. <p> These days, with Washington mired in tax-reform debate, there's plenty for her to read and to write about. And believe it or not, beneath that cranky exterior, Sheppard favors sticking with the income tax. She says alternative approaches, such as a value-added tax, aren't practical. "My dream is for [House Ways and Means chairman Bill] Archer to move up here to New York and ask the pizza sellers how much cheese they bought to figure out how much of a value-added tax to collect," Sheppard says. "Forcing taxpayers to comply under a VAT ain't no day at the beach."   <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
