	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/10-A Basket of Cash,</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>A Basket of Cash, E-I-E-I-O</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/10-A Basket of Cash,</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1995  <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> A BASKET OF CASH, E-I-E-I-O  <p> By Raplh Gardner Jr.  <p> Among the tourist attractions in the Berkshire hills of Massachusetts are the Tanglewood Music Festival, the Norman Rockwell Museum, and the wicker cash basket at the Rawson Brook goat farm. "People do come just to look at the money box," says Susan Sellew, who, along with her husband, Wayne Dunlop, operates the idyllic little farm in Monterey and produces some of the most delicious and delicate goat cheese around.  <p> The renowned money box sits inside Sellew and Dunlop's unattended farm stand, where customers help themselves to plastic containers of cheese from the milking room's sparkling refrigerator. For payment, they leave money in the basket, making change out of the cash already there if necessary. Many of the visitors are weekenders from less placid locales, and the sight of unguarded cash frankly weirds them out.  <p> "Customers come and tell me, I'm nervous would you please empty the box,' " Sellew says. It fills up fast, especially on weekends, when tourists stock up on Rawson Brook's flavorful Monterey Chvre with chives and garlic and the ever-popular peppered log. The cheeses sell for $8.75 a pound.  <p> When edgy customers can't find anybody to witness their purchases if, say, Sellew and Dunlop are off making replacement shingles for their barn or home-schooling their eight-year-old daughter, Tarsi some will nonetheless announce that they're depositing money in the basket. Occasionally, Dunlop will overhear these shouted bulletins while working behind the barn. "They'll say, I got a pound of chives and two of wild thyme,' " Dunlop says. "They walk youth rough it in case someone's listening."  <p> Sellew attributes the couple's willingness to employ the honor system to their fundamental belief in the goodness of human nature, to the fact that the farm happens to be down a little-traveled dirt road, and to what she describes as "the specific vibe" of the farm. "Somebody would have to be pretty hard off to rip off poor farmers," she says.  <p> Unfortunately, somebody apparently was last year. "We did have our first dip in the basket," says Sellew. The damage was about $25, plus a pound of cheese. She suspects a local teenager rather than a larcenous weekender. The couple contemplated beefing up security, albeit not very seriously. "A fake camera was the first thing my husband thought of," Sellew says.  <p> In any case, the money in the cash box represents only a small portion of Rawson Brook Farm's revenues. The farm produces about 350 pounds of cheese each week, selling it throughout the Berkshires and at stores such as Zabar's in New York City and Bread & Circus in Boston.  <p> The problem, Dunlop says, is keeping up with demand. The farm is profitable enough, but expanding would mean a new barn and new equipment. It would also mean adding some full-time employees including, presumably, replacing the old money box with a cash register manned by some local teen with a problem complexion. Dunlop flatly rejects that idea. "We'd just be like all the rest," he says.  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Business, Small Business Ownership<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
