	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Tips for Rich Boors</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Tips for Rich Boors</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Tips for Rich Boors</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>TIPS FOR RICH BOORS<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Gracious! money, it seems, is finally a topic fit for discussion in The Amy Vanderbilt Complete Book of Etiquette. There's no way of knowing what Amy herself might say about this, since she passed away in 1974. Instead, credit for this modern attitude must go to Nancy Dunnan, author (with Nancy Tuckerman) of the new, completely rewritten etiquette guide.<p>And who better to advise the courtesy-conscious? Dunnan is a 50-year-old veteran personal-finance writer and the author of 27 books, including The Dun & Bradstreet Guide to Your Investments. <p>Dunnan sees the decision to include money matters in this latest edition as logical. "Money was never discussed in prior editions because it was taboo to talk about it," she says. "But these days, a lot of people are inheriting more money. And a lot of people are declaring personal bankruptcy."<p>Her approach is thoroughly modern. "I am not prim and proper," she says. "But I am polite and pragmatic."<p>One example: In dealing with your poorer friends, "You can either change your style of entertainment...or you can treat.... Probably you will end up doing a little of both."<p>Even in this more enlightened age, money is still a topic best skirted if possible. "Difficult as it may be, try to avoid talking about money more than absolutely necessary," the guide advises. "It becomes boring and can be offensive."<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


