<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Stock Tips, Next Exit</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Stock Tips, Next Exit</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Stock Tips, Next Exit</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>STOCK TIPS, NEXT EXIT<p>By Laurie DeLater Weeks <p>When the latest edition of JAG Notes reels out of a subscriber's fax machine in the morning, the look is amateurish: plain type, plenty of underlining, and lots of capital letters. At the top, computer-generated calligraphy proclaims the daily newsletter's name; below that is its motto: "Don't Settle for Rumors, Get the Fax!"<p>In short, JAG Notes looks like a bunch of guys in New Jersey are slapping it together every day. Guess what: They are. JAG stands for Jeff, Anthony, and Gary--that is, Jeff Goss, Anthony Salandra, and Gary Valinoti, three stockbrokers in their 30s. Every morning, from a small office in Linden, New Jersey, they, along with partner Barry Belzer and Valinoti's wife, Cathy, pirate the hottest stock market tips from Wall Street's top brokerages, compile them into three pages, and fax them out to subscribers.<p>These subscribers are hoping for a window into a Wall Street ritual known as the morning call. Every day, members of a brokerage firm's sales force arrive at their desks at sunrise to listen to a conference call in which analysts from the firm's research staff share their newest investment ideas--which stocks are ripe for purchase and, less frequently, which should be sold. The brokers then share the information with their top clients before the opening bell.<p>JAG Notes' three pages may be short on details, but they do offer a gloss on what a lot of the firms are saying, not just one. More important, they get the news out early; in the stock market, whoever gets the information first wins. Around 7:30 a.m., the 15-line phones at JAG Notes' headquarters start ringing as sources at brokerages phone in tips fresh from their morning calls. Cathy Valinoti types up the remarks, then, at 8:30, starts faxing them to clients. "We do have typos at times," Goss says. "But if there's a mistake, someone will call and we'll put out a retraction."<p>Goss, Salandra, and Valinoti launched JAG Notes five years ago. Back then, all three were brokers at Jesup Josephthal (now known as Josephthal, Lyon & Ross) in Morristown, New Jersey. One of their clients was Daiwa Securities, a Japanese firm. Every morning, Goss says, some traders at Daiwa would call to request a summary of the day's research comments from firms like <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> and PaineWebber. Goss and his friends at Josephthal would call around to their buddies and get the comments to oblige the Japanese firm. But one day it dawned on them that if Daiwa was willing to pay thousands of dollars a month for the information, others might, too. "We bought a book with money managers' names and phone numbers in it," Goss says. "We started cold-calling people from the book and offering a free trial." They recruited informants with offers of free subscriptions. The first issues were really low-rent: handwritten and faxed to one subscriber at a time.<p>Today, claiming more than 500 subscribers, the partners run JAG Notes as a separate business, though they continue to work during the day as brokers at tiny Westfalia Investments. Subscribers range from big brokerage houses to small investors. For many individual investors, the appeal of JAG Notes is limited, because it isn't detailed enough to assess a stock's long-term prospects. But for those willing to play the risky game of day trading, it can be a helpful tool.<p>"It's the best thing that I've found for what I do," says Robin Karian, a mother of two who trades stocks from her home in rural Massachusetts. Karian checks JAG Notes each morning to see if her favorite brokerages have recommended any blue-chip stocks. Her goal: Buy shares from the list at the opening and sell them later the same day at a higher price.<p>For some, a subscription to JAG Notes is simply insurance (at $1,850 for a year's subscription) against being caught off guard by the competition. Says Chris McLellan, a managing director at Robertson, Stephens & Co., a San Francisco brokerage: "We take it just to be sure that we don't get blindsided."<p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
