	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Il Testamento</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Il Testamento</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>IL TESTAMENTO
("Ill Will")<p>By Judith Harris<p>CAST
Giacomo Puccini: the once rich but now deceased composer
Antonio Puccini: the deceased son of the composer
Baron Livio Dell'Anna: the deceased brother-in-law of Antonio
Pasquale Belladonna: the butler who inherited Puccini's wealth
Simonetta Puccini: the illegitimate granddaughter of Puccini
Aldo Giarrizzo: court-appointed curator of the composer's estate<p>ACT I
The drama opens in 1986 with Pasquale Belladonna, an aged butler, inheriting an estimated $13 million estate from his newly deceased lover and employer, the self-styled baron Livio Dell'Anna. The money and the properties once belonged to Italian composer Giacomo Puccini, of Madama Butterfly and La Bohme fame. When Puccini died in 1924, his son Antonio inherited the estate. Antonio's widow passed the wealth to her brother, Livio.<p>ACT II, SCENE I
Enter Aldo Giarrizzo, the Puccini estate curator with an appetite for justice. Giarrizzo sues Belladonna in 1990, alleging that the butler seized Puccini's riches without right. "He's short, fat, uneducated, and lacking in any cultural sense," Giarrizzo sings of Belladonna in the opera's most celebrated aria, "O, Uomo Grasso." The Italian court dismisses Giarrizzo's suit, deciding that the butler and the "baron" had a "para-matrimonial relationship." The butler, however, is not the only player in Giarrizzo's court duel.<p>ACT II, SCENE II
In the distance, we hear a lone soprano: Simonetta Puccini, the illegitimate daughter of Antonio. In February 1995, the 68-year-old Simonetta is recognized as a Puccini and awarded one third of the estate. "For 20 years, I've fought to have my rights respected and to look after the moral and cultural heritage of Puccini," she sings in the aria "Un Bel Anno." Living in a modest apartment in Milan, Simonetta seeks to wrest control of the maestro's legacy. <p>ACT III
With Simonetta's approval, Giarrizzo attempts to create a foundation that will protect Puccini's residences. Torre del Lago, the lakeside retreat in Tuscany where the composer is buried, would become a proper museum. "Everyone agreed, from the Milan mayor to Simonetta," sings Giarrizzo. Suddenly, Simonetta demands to be named president of the foundation. But Giarrizzo refuses; he doesn't think she's up to the task. Alas, as future court skirmishes loom, the properties continue to decay. In the background, thieves loot Torre del Lago.<p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

