	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-All in a Goonda's Work</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>All in a Goonda's Work</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-All in a Goonda's Work</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>ALL IN A GOONDA'S WORK<p>By Manjeet Kripalani<p>On a bright evening last winter, social activist Madhu Mehta was enjoying the sunset from his home on Napean Sea Road in Bombay, India, when a visitor was ushered in.<p>"He was a young man in his early 30s," Mehta recalls. "He was scared."<p>The visitor, a midlevel employee of a multinational company, told an astonishing tale. He was a Citibank credit card holder who, due to financial difficulties, had defaulted on payments toward his credit card balance of 36,000 rupees (about $1,140). He said his card had been impounded by the bank, and an independent collection agent had been sent to settle the account.<p>When the young man, Deepak Gandhi, requested an extension of the time limit to repay his debts, he said the collection agent, one A. Qadir Shukri of Bombay Credit & Company, told him he must either settle within 48 hours or have one of his organs removed to repay the amount to the bank. The cardholder claimed he had been first offered the choice of giving up an eye, his liver, a lung, or a kidney. But the collector then decided he wanted a kidney and asked for his blood type. The young man fled.<p>Mehta lent a sympathetic ear. He is the head of the Hindustani Andolan, a 21-year-old group that he describes as a "nonpower-seeking renaissance political, social, and cultural movement." The 65-year-old Mehta says the need for the group is easily explained:"India is run by thugs and charlatans. So we have to take action."<p>Mehta quickly took up the young man's cause, charging that he had been subjected to "Chicago mafia-type tactics." He demanded an investigation into the matter and Shukri's suspension as a collection agent.<p>In a country that thrives on drama (India produces more films each year than Hollywood), the story was irresistible. The press had a field day: CITIBANK AGENT THREATENS TO PLUCK KIDNEYS OUT FOR RECOVERING CREDIT DUES read a headline in the Indian Express, one of the nation's leading dailies.<p>It wasn't long before bizarre legends about defaulters and credit cards began circulating. An old lady who was behind in her loan payments was said to have had her car repossessed on the streets of Delhi--while she was driving her granddaughter to school. Then there was the story of a collection agent who threatened to take possession of a defaulter's wife. Given the already shady reputations of the collection agencies, the stories spread like wildfire.<p>"The collection agencies are mostly mom-and-pop shops," says Rajiv Luthra, a consumer-finance consultant in New Delhi. "It's a 'goonda-gardi' business." That is to say, a thug's work.<p>Mehta says that description certainly fits the persistent Shukri. "A very uncouth person," sniffs Mehta, who met the man on Gandhi's behalf. "He certainly doesn't look well-educated."<p>For his part, Shukri denies the strong-arm tactics. "It was a small amount, so why should I do this?" he says. And Citibank--the No. 1 player in India's fledgling consumer-finance market--dismisses Gandhi's tale as pure fabrication, perhaps inspired by stories in the local press detailing the organ trade in India. Indeed, police closed their investigation after a month, citing a lack of evidence. Now Gandhi is working with Citibank on a repayment schedule for his outstanding debts.<p>Still, Shukri--goonda, or victim of rumor?--is no longer in the bank's employ. He strikes a philosophical note about the ups and downs of the collection business. "Things like this happen," he says. <p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
