	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Philip Diehl:  Creme de la Mint</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Philip Diehl:  Creme de la Mint</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Philip Diehl:  Creme de la Mint</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>PHILIP DIEHL: CREME DE LA MINT<p>By Louis Jacobson<p>Since taking office as director of the U.S. Mint last year, Philip Diehl has found himself arguing for fewer coins instead of more__not necessarily the most obvious position for the nation's czar of spare change. But Diehl is trying to keep pace with a Congress that's seemingly coin-crazed. <p>First, the House Republican budget plan contains a proposal to scrap the dollar bill in favor of a new dollar coin. That pushed Diehl to side with advocates of folding money.<p>Sure, replacing the dollar bill with a longer-lasting coin might produce budget savings (anywhere from $20 million to $800 million a year, depending on which estimate you believe). But Diehl argued that a new coin, no matter how well designed, might not be able to overcome the public's distrust of dollar coins__the legacy of the Susan B. Anthony debacle. "There's real resistance to the government telling people what's good for them," Diehl says.<p>Call it a customer-service approach to currency. Diehl, 44, is accustomed to worrying about customers__or constituents, as the case may be. He started out in the service sector, logging nights as manager of a La Quinta motel while earning a master's degree in government at the University of Texas in Austin. Later he joined the staff of Lloyd Bentsen__first as a top aide in his Senate office, then as his chief of staff at the Treasury. It was then a short jump over to the Mint.<p>Once there, the former senate aide soon found himself lobbying Congress to stem a glut of commemorative coins. Legislators regularly push for special-issue coins to honor pet causes; recent suggestions have included the Navy's Blue Angels precision-flying squad and Congress's Botanic Gardens.<p>Again, it comes down to the customer__in this case, collectors reeling from a flood of commemoratives. At the same time, surcharges that benefit the organizations featured on the coins are jacking up prices. The latest example: a set of 16 Olympic coins Congress foisted on the Mint as a way to raise $100 million for the Atlanta games. Right now, sales are expected to snare only half that amount. Diehl fears the coin deluge will turn off even die-hard numismatists; it's better to cut back. "The less you sell," he says, "the more appeal it has."<p>If and when Diehl reins in the commemoratives, there are other policy questions for the Mint to tackle__whether to get rid of the penny, for example. But Diehl's long-term vision sounds positively Gingrichian: replacing coins with "digital" cash. "Coins are at best a second-wave technology," he says. "Barter was first, then coins. The third-wave technology, it's absolutely clear, is debit cards and smart cards."<p>For now, though, Diehl gets rid of his coins the way a lot of us do: He tosses them into a jar and leaves them for his kids. Then the next time they hit him up for money, he'll hand them the jar and say, "If you roll them, they're yours." 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

