<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/09-Chrysler's Fabulous Bailout Boys</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Chrysler's Fabulous Bailout Boys</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Gary Hector<p>Paul Volcker had to ask for an invitation. Jim Wolfensohn, president of the World Bank, swung by on his way back from Africa. Roger Altman, friend of Bill Clinton and former deputy Treasury secretary, stopped in for a few minutes to schmooze. And Doug Fraser, retired president of the United Auto Workers, stayed until well after midnight. <p>Fifteen years ago these men played pivotal roles in one of the biggest--and most successful--political gambles in U.S. history. In a swirl of headlines, drop-dead dates, and arm-twisting, they persuaded the U.S. government to guarantee up to $1.5 billion in debt for Chrysler. The agreement saved the automaker from bankruptcy. But this night they were all together atop the former Pan Am building in New York City to party--knock back a few drinks, munch on a gargantuan wheel of cheese, and talk shop.<p>A big topic, of course, was Kirk Kerkorian's offer to acquire Chrysler. Steve Miller, the former Chrysler executive who organized the reunion, found the bid astounding. "Who could have imagined that we'd see a smart Wall Street type offering $22 billion for something that was worth $200 million when we were working on it?" he said.<p>Miller is now chairman of Morrison Knudsen. And glancing around the reunion, it was easy to spot other alumni who have risen to prominent positions. David Schulte, who was then at Salomon Brothers, has since started Chilmark Partners. Brian Freeman, a key staff member at Treasury, became an investment advisor to labor unions. Freeman ended up advising UAL workers in their buyout effort and introduced them to Gerald Greenwald, former Chrysler vice chairman. Greenwald is now CEO of UAL.<p>The only conspicuous no-show was Chrysler's leader during the bailout: Lee Iacocca didn't make it. Neither did the giant cheese wheel; by the end of the evening, the bailout alumni had gnawed it to crumbs. 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
