	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Burping Their Way to the Top</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/09-Burping Their Way to the Top</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						September 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>BURPING THEIR WAY TO THE TOP<p>By Jane Birnbaum<p>They came for tips on selling RemarkaBowls and dinnerware separates from the Tabletop Collection, but for 500 of the nation's top Tupperware salespeople, the spring seminar in Dallas was also a great chance to scope out the competition.<p>Considering some of the prizes awarded to Tupperware's best hawkers, scouting one's opponents might seem like a smart idea. Top-ranked salespeople (actually, they're called "managers" in Tupperspeak) vie for such incentives as minivans and Caribbean cruises.<p>But veterans insist that they're rooting each other on, not looking over their shoulders. Nickie Malouf of Burbank, California, a Tupperware manager for 17 years and No. 2 nationally last year, admits that wanting to be first would be "a natural, normal thought," but says, "it doesn't go through my head." <p>With all those warm feelings, you can almost believe that the salespeople in shooting range of No. 1 wish nothing but the best for Judi Daugherty of Morgantown, West Virginia, the top manager nationwide last year after just 18 months in the Tupperware game. Needless to say, other managers were curious to meet her. "She had set a new standard of excellence, and I was dying to know what she was doing that was different," says San Diego's Alana Klepper.<p>Daugherty didn't keep attendees of the Dallas conference in suspense. In her talk on how she had earned $20,000 in one month and personally sold an astounding $40,000 worth of Tupperware in that time, she disclosed one of her key strategies: Demonstrate the Modular Mates system, a basic part of the Tupperware line intended to instantly organize a cupboard. "If I can sell women a set, when they get home they can start to see the bigger picture more quickly," Daugherty says. Yes, sets do indeed cost more than single pieces.<p>Even though Daugherty won a Dodge Intrepid, $10,000 cash, and some jewelry last year for winning the national sales competition, she didn't mind sharing her secrets. "Teaching 499 people to earn $20,000 a month can't hurt me," she says. "I might not be No. 1 again for 1995, but that's not my goal. I'm No. 1 because I work hard."<p>For many of the top contenders, the Dallas seminar was their first chance to get acquainted. "When I met [No. 2 ranked] Nickie Malouf, I felt like I was meeting a queen," Daugherty says. "Tears came to my eyes. She's been in the top year after year, and here's me, the new kid on the block, meeting the best of the best." In fact, Daugherty's status was in flux in Dallas because manager Patty Wilson of Mason, Ohio, was $5,000 ahead at the end of the first quarter of 1995. "I sat right next to Patty on stage, and I said, 'Let's try to get together for a phone call,' " Daugherty says. "She was excited, too."<p>Wilson, who has been selling Tupperware for six and a half years, doesn't begrudge Daugherty her rapid ascent to the top. She doesn't plan to change her strategy, either: She'll simply continue "dating" as many parties as she can--that is, persuading friends and acquaintances to host sales demonstrations. Like her grocer father before her, Wilson makes monthly sales charts. And, for inspiration, she listens to the Tupperware awards-ceremony theme song--Whitney Houston's "One Moment in Time"--at least twice every day. 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
