	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-They Don't Give Out Samples, Either</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-They Don't Give Out Samples, Either</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Lauren Goldstein  <p> As economists ponder the price of gold these days, some Americansare heading their cars toward Fort Knox, Kentucky, with a hearty "There's gold in them hills!" Hoping for a chance to spend their rapidly plunging dollars on gold souvenirs and to catch a glimpse of the 147 million ounces of gold brick stored there, about 3,600 visitors a year show up on the doorstep of the U.S. Bullion Depository. <p> Disappointment awaits them. "There are no tours," says Bill Daddio, the man in charge of Fort Knox's security. In truth, Fort Knox remains harder to get into than ... Fort Knox. When U.S. Treasurer Mary Ellen Withrow visited last January, she was allowed in, but her staff had to wait outside. Even the regularshipments of <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a> are left at the gate to be searched. Tourists will probably get a better idea of what Fort Knox looks like if they stay home and rent the James Bond movie Goldfinger. The movie wasn't actually filmed at the depository, but Daddio says the sets were good replicas.  <p> Secrecy is a key element in Fort Knox's security. When pressed for details, the response is "enough." How many people work there? Enough to do the job, Daddio says. How much money is spent on security? "We're given what we need to do the job," he says. <p> Don Nichols, public affairs officer for the U.S. Mint, sums it up: "Fort Knox is a facility we're very neurotic about."  <p>  <hr> <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
