		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Re-Engineering India</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Re-Engineering India</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jack Egan  <p> Not so long ago India was dismissed out of hand in financial circles as the "sick man of Asia" and the last place to think of investing. Today, despite jitters about emerging economies after Mexico's meltdown, India is considered one of the more promising places in the world to put money.  <p> Behind that stunning shift in perception stands Manmohan Singh, India's owlish finance minister, known for his stylish sky-blue turbans and wily pragmatism. He has been the chief architect of an ambitious program to thoroughly overhaul India's red-taperiddled economy. "Finance Minister Singh and the current government's reform agenda are not only inextricably intertwined," says Douglas Johnson, senior international investment strategist for <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a>, "he's been the key for maintaining the confidence of foreign investors."  <p> Oxford-educated and a former economics professor, the self-effacing Singh, now 62, seemed a bit of an odd choice when Prime Minister P.V. Narasimha Rao picked him in 1991 to bring India's stagnant economy back from the brink of collapse. Yet in the past four years he has succeeded in restoring India's international credit rating to investment grade while supervising the sweeping change from a Soviet-style command economy toward a more competitive, market-oriented system. The country's official foreign reserves, negligible when he took office, now stand at more than $20 billion. <p> These days, however, Singh is getting singed from all sides, putting his notable poise to the test. Within India, where the ruling Congress party appears weak going into next year's elections, naysayers worry that Singh is handing over the country to foreign investors while neglecting India's multitudes. Michel Camdessus<p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
