<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-Dogged Pursuit of a Better IRA</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>In Dogged Pursuit of a Better IRA</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Dogged Pursuit of a Better IRA</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> IN DOGGED PURSUIT OF A BETTER IRA  <p> By Louis Jacobson  <p> America's savers may get a pleasant surprise this year. Congress is mulling three proposals intended to make Individual Retirement Accounts more attractive, and it appears likely that one of them will pass.  <p> If that happens, credit Senator William V. Roth Jr., the perennial champion of the IRA, for refusing to give up on the idea that we should all save more. The Delaware Republican has been advocating incentives for savings for more than two decades, with a tenacity that hasn't gone unnoticed by his Senate colleagues. "He's a bulldog, I tell you," says Rhode Island's John Chafee. "He gets that bone in his teeth and hangs right on to it."  <p> The dog metaphor suits Roth well. When he first ran for a seat in the House of Representatives, he won by crisscrossing the state with his trusty pet Saint Bernard. The dog was a magnet for kids, and while the tykes were occupied, Roth slipped their parents his campaign literature.  <p> Roth, now 73 and in his fifth term as senator, still loves big dogs. Photographs of several generations of Saint Bernard pets dot his Senate office. He also still can't understand why his efforts to expand IRAs have met with so much resistance. The mention of past failed attempts to pass IRA legislation throws the ordinarily low-key senator into a fit of frustration.  <p> "I'm still shocked in disbelief that individuals don't see the worthiness of the idea," Roth says. And why is it that not everyone likes IRAs? "Stupidity. People don't like to think about fiscal matters. But it's rare when you can promote a concept that helps both the government and the people at the same time."  <p> The concept of the IRA dates back to the mid-1950s, when Senator Carl T. Curtis, a Republican from Nebraska, began crusading for them. The idea, then as now, was to encourage Americans of average means to increase their savings by granting them some combination of up-front tax deductions and a deferral of tax on accumulated interest income until the savings were withdrawn. Supporters saw it as a way to increase the rates of both personal savings and national savings, giving businesses access to more capital and thus promoting economic growth.  <p> But it was a tough sell. Congressional leaders sensed no urgent desire from the public, and they were fearful of forgoing tax revenue by offering deductions and deferments for savings. It wasn't until 1974 that the aging Senator Curtis succeeded in getting the first true IRA passed into law. When IRAs were expanded again in 1976, Curtis passed the torch to Roth.  <p> It was an appropriate move. As a young man serving in military intelligence, Roth had come to admire the high rates of saving in postwar Germany and Japan. Roth's big break came early in Ronald Reagan's first term, when he and then-Representative Jack Kemp successfully sold Congress on what have become known as the Kemp-Roth tax cuts (and what alumni of Roth's office refer to, a bit defensively, as the Roth-Kemp tax cuts). Among other things, the legislation eased limits on who could qualify for an IRA and how much could be deducted.  <p> That bill's passage kicked off the golden age of IRAs, a time when rising numbers of Americans opened accounts and kept adding to them. But that era ended in 1986, when Democrats and Republican deficit hawks worked to tighten many tax loopholes, including permissive eligibility standards for IRA tax credits. Roth began trying, once again, to convert his Senate colleagues to the IRA gospel, but it hasn't been easy. Critics remained wary of giving up tax dollars, particularly when some economists suggested that many savers were simply shifting existing holdings into tax-favored IRAs. <p>The battle for IRAs hasn't made Roth a household name. Though the Almanac of American Politics acknowledges that Roth has made" some significant accomplishments" on Capitol Hill, it also says he is "not treated as a major player."   <p> Still, he persists in trying to sell fellow legislators on his current proposal. Called a back-loaded IRA, this new species of savings account would encourage depositors to switch to it after first paying the deferred taxes on their old IRA, which would actually boost the Treasury in the near term. After that initial tax hit on the transferred funds, earnings on the funds would be tax free. In addition, these IRAs would allow penalty-free early withdrawals for college tuition, first-time home purchases, and the like.  <p> Critics say the U.S. can't afford to offer such expensive tax incentives, but Roth believes IRAs create a habit of saving, helping people take care of themselves. "They're very shortsighted," says Roth, "the people who don't agree."  <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Taxation, Retirement

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
