		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>He Has a Fine Way with a Steinway</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Fine Way with a Steinway</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> HE HAS A FINE WAY WITH A STEINWAY  <p> By Carol Schatz  <p> Franz Mohr doesn't really play the piano, but he knows how to improvise. During a lifetime spent around concert grands, his not-so-classical movements have included applying hair spray to Artur Rubinstein's keyboard to make it "grippy" (the way Rubinstein liked it), removing broken strings mid concert for Vladimir Horowitz, and telling conductor Eugene Ormandy, "Maestro, if this piano is flat to you, then you've got no ears!"  <p> So when the 68-year-old retired chief concert technician for Steinway & Sons hosted a free public seminar on how to buy a used piano, a standing-room-only crowd of more than 120 filled New York City's Steinway Hall. They came to hear him speak about his passion and perhaps to reassure themselves that it was business as usual at Steinway, which was bought by Selmer in April for $100 million.  <p> As a Steinway (playerless and retrofitted with the digital equivalent of piano rolls) played Bach in the balcony, enthusiasts ogled the hall's massive marble columns and ornate domed ceiling while sharing musical anecdotes. "I had a kitty who played the keyboard," giggled one well-dressed woman. "Unfortunately she wasn't very good." A bookish-looking telecommunications professor sitting near her confessed that he couldn't quite afford a $30,500 Steinway medium grand. "I don't own one yet," he said. "But I will." <p> When Mohr, a small peppy man with a white mustache and an engaging grin, began to speak, the audience leaned forward and listened with the same rapt intensity they might give to, say, Chopin's E Flat Nocturne.   <p> "I am a Steinway nut, and I can't help it," said Mohr. An experton the 12,000 parts in a Steinway, Mohr joined the company in1962 after emigrating from Germany and was Horowitz's personal piano technician for almost 30 years. "Today the world is being flooded with mass-manufactured pianos that deteriorate when they leave the factory," he said. "It takes a year to build and assemble a Steinway, there are no two alike, and they get better as they are broken in."  <p> Used pianos in good condition cost a quarter to half as much as new ones, but Mohr warned bargain-seekers that an instrument in bad condition can become a money pit. Reconditioning an old Steinway, for example, can cost from $10,000 to $17,000.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
