		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/08-"Everybody Wants to Get Sauced"</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-"Everybody Wants to Get Sauced"</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>As backyard barbecuers bore friends this summer with their sauce recipes, Karen Putman will be whipping up another batch of her Flower of the Flames Raspberry Bar-B-Q Sauce, a rich, slightly sweet elixir that, as she boasts, "just makes your tongue slap your head silly, it's so good!"<p>The difference is, Putman sells her sauce--shipping 400 cases a month at $22.80 a case. With that business, and some notoriety in barbecue circles under her belt (she did, after all, win a Piggy award from the Kansas City Barbecue Society), she has started consulting to would-be sauce wizards, providing advice on recipes for a fee of $45 to $50 an hour.<p>Putman finds plenty of demand for her services; Kansas City has spawned more than its share of BBQ entrepreneurs. "There's a big epidemic of sauce," Putman says. "Everybody wants to get sauced."<p>For those who want to give the sauce business a try, Putman rents out (at $115 a day) her 1,200-square-foot commercial kitchen in Lenexa, Kansas. But she offers a word of caution. "These people all have that expectation that they're going to go straight to the top," she says. "It's hard to tell them that success is just not going to happen overnight." But for Putman, creating a sauce comes more easily. "It's like going and sittin' on a fish bank, I guess," she says. "It's work, but relaxing work." <p>Some recipes even seem to write themselves, such as the one for her new mustard-based sauce. The recipe came to her in a dream, and she perfected it just 45 minutes after waking up. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
