	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Elaine to Wall Street:  3Think Pink2</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/08-Elaine to Wall Street: Think Pink</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						July/August 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> ELAINE TO WALL STREET:  "THINK PINK"  <p> By Elizabeth Macdonald  <p> Why is Elaine Garzarelli thinking pink? In the pink-covered debut edition of Sector Analysis Monthly Monitor, her first stab at dissecting the market since <a name="NYSE:LEH"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41936"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lehman Brothers</b></a> let her go last October, she concludes 44 pages of notes, equations, and charts with a newspaper clip asserting, "Pink is fashion's new power." To wit: "Why pink now? We've rediscovered the female figure, and pink is a color that represents good health.' "  <p> Sitting in a casual restaurant off the main drag in East Hampton, Long Island, one of Wall Street's most famous analysts certainly looks in good health. Tanned and rested, Garzarelli says that at 43 she's never been better. "I finally feel free," she says, knocking back a glass of tomato juice.   <p> This spring, she flung open the doors to her new firm, Garzarelli Capital, Inc., in Boca Raton, Florida. She says she has lined up 400 clients who will pay a minimum of $8,400 a year to receive monthly reports and quarterly conference calls. She'll also be working with stock picker Mario Gabelli and her old friend Leonard Zacks, who runs an investment research firm in Chicago. She'll do all this while dividing time between Florida and East Hampton."I want to reconnect to people," she says. "I'm interested in human relationships now."  <p> But some of those who know her wonder if this veteran of 12-hour work days can learn to relax. After graduating from Drexel University, she headed to Wall Street in 1971 and began a remarkable career. She predicted the October 1987 market crash, then later became a complete optimist. Soon her predictions became self-fulfilling, when she talked, the market moved. Institutional Investor named Garzarelli as Wall Street's top quantitative research analyst for 11 years straight.   <p> In her short skirts and peek-a-boo blouses, Garzarelli stood out among the investment world's starched white collars. Few Wall Street economists can list the accomplishment of appearing in a No-Nonsense pantyhose commercial. But her flamboyance didn't necessarily work to her advantage at Lehman. She became expensive her annual compensation was reportedly more than $1.5 million and she began working more at home. "Working in the office was like being at a party all of the time," she says. "People throwing darts, talking. I couldn't get anything done." In October 1994, Lehman forced her out. Lehman officially declined to discussthe reasons for her departure.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
