<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-The Unsinkable Velma Morrison</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>The Unsinkable Velma Morrison</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-The Unsinkable Velma Morrison</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront <p> THE UNSINKABLE VELMA MORRISON  <p> By Jesse Kornbluth  <p> When the news came, Velma Morrison was at her winter home in Palm Desert, California, hundreds of miles and a warm sun away from the beleaguered headquarters of Morrison Knudsen in Boise, Idaho. For years, the widow of MK's founder had been praying for the ouster of William J. Agee, the sixth chief executive officer in the firm's 83-year history and the one with the most disastrous record. Now her wish had come true, but she was still unhappy.  <p> If Velma Morrison had owned a vast chunk of stock, it would have been easy to understand her outrage: MK shares that traded at close to 30 last year had dropped below 9 by the time Agee was axed. But she sold almost all her shares in 1990, the same year she turned 70 and was forced to resign as MK's first female director.  <p> What enraged Velma? Namely, from her point of view, that Bill Agee, who once described himself as "born, bred, and buttered" in Boise, seemed not to have grasped MK's vibrant sense of family. She felt he did not understand that MK was, at bottom, an engineering and construction firm. Nor, finally, did Agee abide by the memory and traditions of founder Harry Morrison.  <p> Morrison died in 1971, and Velma is remarried now. But she has kept her legendary surname. "They do that these days, don't they?" she coyly asks.  <p> Along with potato king Jack Simplot and grocer Joe Albertson, the master builder Harry Morrison established both a fortune and a way of doings things in Boise. Albertson walked his grocery stores, greeting acquaintances by name. Simplot moved to a bighouse on the hill, but his home phone number has always been listed, and he drops off his own dry cleaning. And Morrison? Affectionately called that "damn dam builder" by his widow, he built the Hoover Dam and was once described in a Time magazine cover story as the man who had most changed the face of the earth. Morrison liked nothing better than to grab a guitar at gatherings of MK employees and croon the songs of the day. Although he was rarely photographed without his vest, Morrison had no airs. <p> Velma had no trouble fitting in when she moved to Boise as Harry's second wife in the late 1950s. The two had met at her restaurant, the Broiler, in Bakersfield, California. He was 73, suffering from diabetes, his wife recently deceased. She was a perky blond 38-year-old divorcee with three children. A few months after they met, Velma recalls, he told her, "You've trained as a nurse. Come and work for me. You can give me my insulin shots as I travel." Velma sold her restaurant and took the job. They married in 1959. <p> Velma says he told her they could live anywhere the company had an office. She chose Harry's old house in Boise, where the people are, she says, "really friendly." There, she embraced community causes with gusto, which is no small thing in a city where good citizenship is like a second religion.  <p> After Harry's death, Velma could have settled into a comfortable, undemanding life, like some widows of wealthy men. Instead, she took over the Harry W. Morrison Foundation which her late husband had started in 1952 to support local institutions and created the Harry W. Morrison Performing Arts Center. In 1984, the $18 million, 2,066-seat theater was inaugurated with a production of My Fair Lady, Harry's favorite musical. In 1988, Velma married rancher and fruit grower John Hockberger and started building her dream house. She also continued serving on MK's board of directors as one of the company's largest shareholders. According to James McClary, chairman of the board from 1972 to 1978, Velma grasped the essential nature of the business of construction; she had traveled with Harry and understood that every job has to stand on its own feet.  <p>  <p>in the summer of 1988, William Agee had been an MK director for seven years. But that wasn't what some Boiseans thought of when his name came up. They remembered his unsatisfactory stint at Boise Cascade. They recalled how he had become, at 38, the CEO of Bendix only to be at the center of a personal controversy at that Fortune 500 company when he made young Mary Cunningham his chief strategist. And they remembered Bendix being gobbled up in a takeover battle Agee himself had launched, with Agee riding a golden parachute to safety. But Agee had gone on towed Cunningham, father two children, and settle into a quiet series of consultancies from Cape Cod.  <p> The summer of 1988 wasn't the best of times for MK. The company was unwinding its ill-timed excursion into the real estate business, and the charges to the bottom line were enormous. At a board meeting, sources say, Agee expressed deep concern; before the session ended, the directors had asked him to become both CEO and chairman.  <p> Velma now swears she was never completely sold on Agee. Others say she was an Agee enthusiast. After all, he had grown up on the same street where Harry and his first wife, Ann, lived. Velma is said to have been charmed by Agee's charisma and his contacts. And, because he was as native as potatoes, she thought he was likely to continue Harry's mission.  <p> Velma gave the Agees a reception that fall. But during the remainder of their relationship, friendship never developed. "They were just too high falutin for us," Velma says. (The Agees did not respond to requests for an interview.)  <p> More troublesome to Velma, however, was that Agee began changing the company in ways she didn't like. First, Agee drove out many of MK's most experienced "construction stiffs," people who were her friends. He turned the company away from its core business to new enterprises, mostly railroad and subway-car manufacturing, that were risky and unprofitable, which hurt her stock. But for Velma Morrison, the "meanest, cruelest" act was symbolic: Harry's portrait was moved from the boardroom to the storage room.  <p> Velma herself was soon moved out. In 1990, when she turned 70, she says Agee reminded her that she'd have to leave the board. The official acknowledgment of her three decades of service to MK? "You won't believe this," she says, "but Mr. Agee gave me a little farewell dinner after a meeting of directors at a restaurantat O'Hare Airport.... He did present me with a gift: a very nice piece of Steuben crystal made from the design of my new house. Frankly, I thought I deserved a little more."  <p> Had she been allowed to continue on the board, she says, "Agee would have had me to fight all the way." That year she sold all but 100 of her shares.  <p> Though Velma was off the board and no longer one of the company's largest shareholders, the tension between her and Agee continued. In 1991, rumor had it that Agee was headed out. Velma was then in London, visiting with two former MK executives who were working on the Chunnel project. Agee apparently believed that Velma went to London to ask these men to come home and run the company. He threatened to sue her.   <p> "These lawyers came all the way over, first class, to talk to me," Velma says. "I had to hire lawyers myself." Eventually, she says, "It went away."   <p> As Agee's compensation rose, the fortunes of many of his employees fell. He changed the retirement benefits, which encouraged some senior managers to take early retirement. Agee who liked to say that MK was "a place where tradition lives" also canceled the retirees' picnic. By this point, Velma saw no reason to be discreet; she decided to become one of the event's sponsors. "Last year, almost 350 people came," she boasts, "and I think I knew just about everyone's name."  <p>  <p>Agee's rule at MK began to unravel in November of 1994, when he completed the transfer of his office to his home in Pebble Beach, California. In a rare corporate revolt, an anonymous band of upper-echelon employees who called themselves the Committee for Excellence bombarded the board with documents showing MK's precarious finances.  <p> Because the directors (including Worth senior contributing editor Peter Lynch) have kept a low profile since dispensing with Agee, Velma's voice has been heard loud and often in recent months. Some Agee partisans have, therefore, marked her as a meddler who lobbied former California Supreme Court Justice William Clark the board member who would later serve as an interim chairman to dump Agee. Her motive, according to some sources in a Time magazine story: Agee had cut off her perks.  <p> Velma finds such charges laughable. "What perks?" she hoots. "I had none. This is Boise; the only people who cared about perks here were Bill and Mary Agee. As for Mr. Clark, I didn't know him from Adam. He called me when he took over. But I never met him until after he resigned." Clark confirms this.  <p> In recent weeks, Velma Morrison has found reason to celebrate. That process began when Harry Morrison's portrait was rehungin the conference room. But she didn't achieve full-bore elation until MK tapped Robert S. Miller Jr., who had been instrumental in <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler's</b></a> 1980 turnaround, to be its new chairman, a choice that she finally likes. In the days after Miller's appointment, trading of MK shares was very heavy, and the stock price rose.  <p> And how did Velma Morrison, with her piddling token amount of MK stock, feel about the run-up?  <p> "Very good," she said that week. "I had called my broker over the weekend. And as soon as the market opened on Monday, he bought me 5,000 shares." <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Small Business Ownership, Family Business

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/6pages.gif"><br>About 6 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
