	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/06-Points Off for Extra Credit</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Points Off for Extra Credit</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-Points Off for Extra Credit</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> POINTS OFF FOR EXTRA CREDIT  <p> By Jane Birnbaum  <p> This month, many of Chuck Malouf's 12th-grade students will trade in their school days for low-wage jobs. Many will find themselves on their own financially for the first time.   <p> But if Malouf has fulfilled his mission, these 17- and 18-year-olds now have some tools to cope with what lies ahead. As part of his senior economics class at John Muir High School in Pasadena, California, Malouf labors to explain to these young adults the difficult decisions they will face concerning money.  <p> He delivers his lectures with the timing of a stand-up comic."Most Americans have a tough choice," he told the class on a recent rainy morning. "You either buy a fancy new car or you feed your children." He pauses a beat before delivering the punchline: "It's obvious you buy the car, right? Because when your children suffer from malnutrition and you cruise to the hospital, you've got to look good." Once the laughter subsides, Malouf offers up the moral: "The question is, Do you want to look good or be good?"  <p> The son of Lebanese immigrants, Malouf, 53, grew up in nearby Glendale and started working at the age of eight, selling doughnuts door to door. A graduate of local schools and holder of an M.B.A., he's taught personal finance to Pasadena high school and community-college students for 28 years. He's also written a textbook, Consumer Education and Economics, which is currently scheduled for a fourth edition.  <p> Security at Muir is heavy, and the buildings look run-down. No matter. Malouf makes his classroom stimulating and fun. (A sign on the wall poses the question "Can I pay my MasterCard with my Visa card?")  <p> This afternoon, Malouf delves into the realities of personal budgets. But before handing out worksheets and asking his students to prepare a household budget based on a monthly income of $1,200 (and then redo it based on $1,000 a month), Malouf talks casually with the class, trying to squeeze a lifetime's worth of insights into a few hours. He explains how to keep track of spending, warns of the temptations of credit cards, and even briefly discourses on the meaning of money.  <p> "What can you do with money?" Malouf asks. You spend it, of course, the class replies. "What else?" Save it. "What else can you do with it?"  <p> "Can you lay in bed with it?" wonders one girl. Laughter all around.   <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
