				<font size=5><b>A Patient Rebel at IBM</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/06-A Patient Rebel at IBM</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> A PATIENT REBEL AT <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM </b></a> <p> By Steven Gaines  <p> Of all the gay-rights activists in America, the least rebellious may be Ed McCanless. For the past five years, he has patiently lobbied IBM for domestic-partner rights, the same benefits provided to employees' live-in lovers at <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple</b></a>, Lotus, <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>, and other high-tech companies. And for the past five years, IBM's response has been perfectly consistent: Not no, not yes. Just "We'll think about it."  <p> Those five years of rebuffs haven't discouraged McCanless. And who knows? In a strange way, perhaps he has come up with the only approach capable of moving so large a force as IBM. Be nice. Be patient. After all, it took years for the Big Blue suits to try out a casual dress code, a benefit that doesn't even cost the company money.  <p> In any case, the strategy seems to come naturally to McCanless, an optimistic employee who is convinced that IBM will, as he puts it, "do the right thing." And in his cardigan sweater, khaki pants, and penny loafers, McCanless looks like he's comfortable enough to wait it out. The 38-year-old engineer at IBM's manufacturing and development facility in San Jose, California, has networked tirelessly, however, to put together a list of gay and lesbian IBMers in the U.S. a critical resource for organizing.<p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance, Technology Industry<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
