<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Who Called This a Penny-Ante Town?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Who Called This a Penny-Ante Town?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Elizabeth Royte<p>While Hollywood gets ready to release a film version of Robert James Waller's sentimental Bridges of Madison County in June, the real inhabitants of Winterset, Iowa, here are engaged in a drama of a more mercenary sort: a low-stakes game called three coins, played downtown at the Montross Pharmacy since 1987.<p>Here's how it works: As many as 15 players ante up a nickel each. After each player takes zero to three coins into his hand, the contestants each predict the total number of coins hidden in the group. The players then open their hands, count the coins, send whoever guessed correctly out of the game, and start a new round. The last one out buys everyone coffee; the ante goes into a fund.<p>Last year, the nickels added up to $150.15, enough to buy beer and pizza at the annual awards ceremony. But players don't need to wait that long for recognition. Each week, the most skilled player gets to wear a badge signifying the feat. The loser gets a badge as well, emblazoned DAL, for "Dead Ass Last." <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  
