		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Show Boat to China?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Show Boat to China?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Show Boat to China?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>SHOW BOAT TO CHINA?<p>By Paul Alexander<p>For a man perhaps best known for a remarkable failure--his departure in disgrace from the Cineplex Odeon movie-theater chain--Garth Drabinsky is relentlessly optimistic about his latest venture. To hear him talk, his theater-production company, Live Entertainment of Canada, or Livent, is poised to democratize the nature of investing in live theater.<p>Sometime this summer, Drabinsky plans to list shares of his company on Nasdaq, meaning that rather than leaving patronage in the hands of the well-heeled--the traditional method of financing theatrical productions--he will offer stock to anyone who can afford to buy in. Maybe this will just give the American middle classes a glamorous new way to lose money--theater is notoriously fickle as an investment--or maybe Drabinsky really has vision. <p>One thing the Canadian doesn't lack is a healthy ego. His new autobiography, Garth Drabinsky: Closer to the Sun, could be read by future investors as a kind of prospectus, giving in 520 pages all the ups and downs of this 45-year-old's life. <p>A definite low point was his exit from Cineplex Odeon, which he cofounded in 1979 and built into one of the largest cinema chains in North America. When he was kicked out as chairman in 1989, the company was $590 million in debt.<p>So far, Livent's experiences on Broadway have been mixed. Its first venture, Kiss of the Spider Woman, didn't earn back its start-up costs, prompting Livent to write off $6 million on the show in January. But Drabinsky believes Show Boat, Livent's second Broadway effort, will recoup its start-up costs this year.<p>Livent investors will be buying into Drabinsky's overall concept: Take a show that started in a big city like New York, Toronto, or London, then spin off as many versions of the show as possible in smaller markets where there's less competition for the entertainment dollar. For other producers, that non-Broadway income is usually ancillary, but for Drabinsky it's a critical part of the business model. For instance, a Chicago production of Joseph and the Amazing Technicolor Dreamcoat grossed a staggering $50 million over 16 months--enough to cover $1.8 million in start-up costs and weekly operations with plenty left over.<p>The returns haven't materialized lately for investors in Livent, which trades on the Toronto Stock Exchange. (Livent isn't related to U.S.based Live Entertainment, a film and video production concern.) Livent's shares had dipped to around $10 (Canadian) in mid-March from highs around $16 to $17 a little over a year ago. (The stock went public at $8.75 in May 1993.) But the company received a vote of confidence in February when Thomas H. Lee, a Boston-based takeover specialist who focuses on turning small companies into big successful ones (like Snapple), bought 13 percent of Livent.<p>Drabinsky's latest production hints at things to come. He has opened Phantom of the Opera in Singapore and intends to tour it in the Far East. If he has his way, the latest hit Broadway musical will be playing soon in a theater near you.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

