	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-One Man's Arabian Nightmare</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-One Man's Arabian Nightmare</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Christopher Byron<p>On a warm and cloudless night in Paris in the summer of 1993, an elegantly dressed banker named Jamal Radwan emerged from a restaurant on the Avenue Duquesne with a female companion. Radwan was a key player in the high-stakes world of Arab finance, but on this particular night his thoughts were focused on the romantic stroll he planned to take. He didn't notice the tall man lurking a few steps away.<p>As Radwan stepped forward, the stalker emerged from the darkness and closed in from behind. Evil was in the moment. Drawing forth a knife big enough to skin a bear, he attempted, in a single, violent stroke, to sever Radwan's head. Then the attacker began to dissect Radwan's face, working relentlessly, methodically. Blood gushed to the pavement and Radwan collapsed. The attacker crouched and crudely sliced Radwan's mouth and tongue. Vous allez' pas dire, he said in a measured tone. Vous allez pas ecrire. You will not speak. You will not write.<p>With that, the assailant raised the knife, plunged it twice into Radwan's chest, stood up, and disappeared into the dark of Paris's side streets. French police never identified any suspects in the brutal knifing. <p>Jamal Radwan survived the attack. After seven hours on an operating table, he began a slow but steady recovery--one that has included more than a dozen operations to reconstruct his face. <p>Radwan's tongue also healed. And despite his attacker's gruesome warning--or perhaps because of it--the banker is using it to talk about the lawsuit he filed in federal court in New York only weeks before the attack.<p>In the suit, Radwan, the former head of the once-powerful Saudi European Bank, accuses some fellow Arab financiers of a vast web of schemes that bears an eerie resemblance to the scandal that brought down the Bank of Credit & Commerce International. One startling aspect of Radwan's suit: Among the individuals he names are major shareholders and even directors of a Bahrainian firm called Investcorp--a company that has purchased stakes in such marquee properties as <a name="NYSE:SKS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=40406"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Saks Fifth Avenue</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:GUC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=46896"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gucci</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:TIF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11481"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Tiffany</b></a>.<p>Syrian by birth, Radwan became a U.S. citizen after graduating from Southern Methodist University in Dallas in 1964. He then joined <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan Bank</b></a>, which eventually assigned him to Riyadh, the capital of Saudi Arabia. There, Radwan helped establish Chase's presence in the Arab kingdom.<p>This feat was enough to bring him to the attention of Ahmed Zaki Yamani, Saudi Arabia's powerful petroleum minister. In 1979, when Yamani was setting up Saudi European, he hired Radwan to run the bank. With Yamani's clout behind it, Saudi European was soon reaping profits from lucrative oil-financing contracts--at least for a time. <p>In the mid-1980s, oil prices collapsed and Yamani was fired as petroleum minister. In a bid to raise capital, Radwan says in his lawsuit he made a big mistake: He sold Saudi European stock to a bunch of what he says were renegade financiers--many with ties to Investcorp. Also among the new investors was Charles Keating, later a villain in the U.S. savings-and-loan debacle.<p>The new shareholders, Radwan alleges began demanding sweetheart loans as if the bank were their personal cash drawer. Radwan claims he spent the last half of the 1980s trying to thwart nefarious schemes. One especially tantalizing charge is that several Saudi European shareholders tried to drag the bank into a greenmail attack on Houston-based Gulf Broadcasting Co.--that is, they sought to force Gulf to buy back its own shares at inflated prices.<p>Though Keating was eventually implicated in a greenmail plot against Gulf, no evidence has ever come to light that Radwan's bank or any of its other shareholders were involved. As Radwan's lawyer, Mark Cymrot says, "It's really Radwan's word against theirs. A lot of this case is like that." Radwan's enemies have fired back with lawsuits of their own, claiming that Radwan himself is a looter and that he has stashed as much as $30 million to $40 million in Swiss bank accounts. <p>Little attention has been paid so far to this legal battle. But the links and similarities between Radwan's claims and the BCCI scandal--including common characters like moneyman Ghaith Pharaon and the Gokal shipping family of Pakistan--suggest revelations to come. To date, Radwan says he has spent more than $10 million on legal fees. He has prevailed in every case so far, and his most recent victory--the first to produce an important ruling on substantive issues--came just before Christmas, when a French criminal tribunal declared him innocent of any wrongdoing in the bank's management.<p>At the time he was attacked on the streets of Paris, Radwan himself was acting as an informant for Manhattan District Attorney Robert Morgenthau, passing along information on BCCI--and Saudi European. Radwan believes that may be the reason for the assault. "They wanted to silence me from blowing the whistle," he says. That, of course, is speculation, and so far no evidence has surfaced pointing to any suspect in the attack, let alone one of Radwan's business adversaries. <p>Radwan's claims about schemes to loot Saudi European are being treated seriously--if cautiously--by U.S. authorities. Says a top official in Morgenthau's office: "You'd want to take some of his assertions with a grain of salt. After all, he was part of the very world he insists is so corrupt. But I'd say he knew what he was talking about."<p>Attempted murder would be an extreme way of doing business, to be sure. But in the Middle East it's often hard to tell where business ends--and where the Arabian nights begin.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: International Investing<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
