	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Making Allowances for Kids</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Making Allowances for Kids</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Making Allowances for Kids</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>MAKING ALLOWANCES FOR KIDS<p>By Ralph Gardner<p>Finding common-sense solutions to the everyday problems between parents and children is how Cary Normile Sellers and Dr. Mary Foote spend their days. Normile is director of guidance at the Spence School, a private girls' school in New York City; Foote is a psychologist who lectures at Spence and other schools. <p>Unsurprisingly, a lot of the answers center on money. "The parents have more money than the children, so the parents have more power than the children," Foote says. The way parents share that power with their children is through an allowance. It teaches them responsibility, offers them a taste of independence, and, not insignificantly, gives parents an answer to the question "Can I have that?"--"Buy it with your own money."<p>Foote believes many parents are forking over too much allowance, sometimes up to $10 a week for young children and $80 for older kids living on New York's Upper East Side. "Guilt is often a motivating factor," she says. "Parents work all the time and think, 'If I'm not going to be with you, money makes up the difference.' "<p>So, then: How much to give? Foote suggests that first graders receive a dollar or two a week. A recently released national survey by Nickelodeon/Yankelovich Partners shows six- to eight-year-olds get an average of $2.77 each week. Older elementary schoolers should get around five dollars, says Foote, also about in line with the survey.<p>A few dollars may not sound like much to some kids or their parents, but it is enough to encourage children to save and teach them the value of money. Some families even earmark portions of children's allowances for saving, charity, and spending. Foote agrees that's a noble idea but knows from personal experience that its success hinges not just on the resolve of the parents but the disposition of the child.<p>"Parents are asking for trouble if they try to make their child save," she says. "I tried that with my kids. It didn't work with any of them. I got into a power struggle with each child. They said, 'It's my money--I can do whatever I want with it.' I had to eat my words."<p>An allowance becomes especially important to a child beginning in the third, fourth, or fifth grade, when he or she wants to buy things that are "private" and, perhaps, objectionable--makeup or compact discs with graphic lyrics, Normile says. She recalls a middle-school student who recently came to her for consolation after her mother balked at letting her buy an off-color T-shirt. <p>Foote's solution to this dilemma is to split up the problem: Tell the child that how she spends her money is her business but that T-shirts with expletives printed on them aren't allowed in the home or the school. "You need to sit down and see if you can't develop some dialogue," Foote says, "instead of getting into a power struggle over money."<p>The experts disagree over one of the most frequently asked questions: whether kids should be paid to do chores. Normile points out that once you start paying somebody to do something, whether a first grader or a member of a corporate board, you'll have a tough time getting work for free in the future. Here's the scenario: "If you link it to doing work, a child can say, 'Fine. I won't make my bed, and I don't care about that dollar.'" To Normile, an allowance's most important role is to teach children to set their eyes on a distant prize and work to win it. "You have to plan for what you want," she says.<p>But Foote likes aligning an allowance with a task so the child is introduced early on to the idea that money doesn't come easy. "It trains us that we're going to have to earn our keep in the world," she says. "There is no free lunch." <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
