<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/05-Lessons From a Big Loser</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Lessons From a Big Loser</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Lessons From a Big Loser</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth Magazine/Outfront<p>LESSONS FROM A BIG LOSER<p>By Gretchen Reynolds<p>While Nicholas Leeson languished in a Frankfurt jail in March, the next wave of young financial wizards gathered in a University of Chicago business-school classroom for the year's final lecture in A Guide to Business Ethics, taught by Nobel laureate Robert W. Fogel. After class, students debated whether Leeson--the 28-year-old trader who destroyed Barings PLC--was or wasn't an unprincipled fink.<p>"He was not," said a 29-year-old M.B.A. student who's starting an investment banking job next year. "He was just doing his job. There was a serious management failure by Barings, but that's not his fault--it's the bank's."<p>Another student immediately disagreed, faulting Leeson instead. "He shouldn't have assumed risks to that level. If he loses, he brings the entire bank down with him."<p>"First thing I did was check where he got his M.B.A.," a 27-year-old student chipped in. "I figured if it was Chicago, we were in trouble." (Leeson didn't get an M.B.A. at Chicago, or anywhere else for that matter.)<p>The Leeson-basher kept pressing the issue. "I still say he should've let his bosses know what level of risk they were assuming," he said. "I can't believe any sane CEO would willingly risk the entire future of his company on one trader's calls."<p>"Come on," another future M.B.A. replied. "You've been interviewing for jobs for a month and you can still say that?"<p>"What I don't understand is why people were so surprised at the amount he lost," a 27-year-old student said. His theory: "If you lose a certain amount, you lose your job. Say it's $100 million--or $400 million. Once you've lost that much, the floodgates open. You have to keep trading. If you don't, you've lost your job. If you lose another $400 million, you've already lost your job, so who cares? But if you win back that first $400 million, you're a hero." 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


