	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Everyone Needs a Nag Like This</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/05-Everyone Needs a Nag Like This</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						May 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>EVERYONE NEEDS A NAG LIKE THIS<p>By William Green<p>Grumbling about taxes over supper one night, Martha Bagby challenged her daughter Meredith to write a book explaining what the government was doing with the money.<p>That motherly advice paid off to the tune of a $110,000 book contract for 21-year-old Meredith Bagby. Her First Annual Report of the United States of America is hitting stores. And, the Harvard senior acknowledges, Mom's help was invaluable. "I don't think it ever would have gotten completed had she not nagged me so much about it," she says. <p>Bagby, who spent a year gathering data, didn't even tell friends about the not-for-credit project "because they would think I was strange." Using a desktop-publishing program and $2,500 of her own money, she ran off 250 copies of the book. While her parents sold mail-order copies out of their garage in West Palm Beach, Florida, Meredith drove around Boston distributing copies to newspapers and television stations.<p>Nobody showed much interest until Ross Perot got a copy and touted it to Bob Dole, Newt Gingrich, and others. When word got around, HarperCollins bought the book. Bagby plans to revise it annually.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Small Business Ownership, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
