				<img src="">	
				<p>
				<font size=5><b>The Oop-tima Card</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-The Oop-tima Card</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 
<p>
Worth magazine/Outfront  
<p>
 THE OOP-TIMA CARD  
<p>
 Call it a graceless gaffe for American Express and its Optima
True Grace card. To pitch this newest piece of plastic, Amex
aggressively touted the card's namesake attraction: a grace period
that allows customers with an outstanding balance to avoid paying
interest on new purchases. Then some Optima cardholders discovered
a glitch on their statements. Thanks to a computer mix-up, they
had been robbed of the grace period and charged for the interest.
Amex says the problem is small change--"The average incorrect
charge was only 21 cents," says a spokeswoman. Besides, the error
affected only about one account in ten and has since been corrected.
But that response may not placate every Optima customer. "They
advertise this true grace period,' but I didn't get any," grouses
Andrew Shaw, 29, a New Yorker who fell victim to the snafu. Still,
Shaw decided not to cancel his card once Amex removed the charge.<p>
<p>
  <hr>  
