	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Plays at the Plate</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Plays at the Plate</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Plays at the Plate</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> PLAYS AT THE PLATE <p>When it's time to pump up church donations, ministers flock to consultant Herb Miller  <p> By Ellen Simon  <p> Upon graduating from Drake University's seminary in Des Moines, Iowa, in 1966, Herb Miller had a goal: "I planned to never mention money at any church I preached at." Nearly three decades later, Miller, 58, stands before 20 ministers and church leaders at a Louisiana hotel, ready to preach a gospel of "stewardship"--in church circles, the polite term for fund-raising. Simply put, this group of ministers is looking for advice on how to increase the take in the collection plate.  <p> Miller's own career as a pastor is behind him now. As executive director of Net Results Resource Center, a Lubbock, Texas, consulting group, he takes to the pulpit these days to teach ways of pumping up church donations. His personal conversion came after ten years of leading congregations in Arkansas, Iowa, and New Mexico. "I noticed I was baptizing people by total immersion, but their wallets were coming out powder dry," he recalls.  <p> At a time when members of mainline Protestant denominations are giving less of their income to churches than at any time in the past 25 years, Miller has found his calling. He spends 250 days a year on the road, traveling around to offer workshops. He has written a number of books, including Money Is Everything:What Jesus Said About the Spiritual Power of Money. Miller, in a sense, is God's management consultant.  <p> Today's crowd at the Radisson Hotel in Kenner, Louisiana, is typical--Catholics and Southern Baptists, New Yorkers and Texans. One attendee listens to Rush Limbaugh on headphones during a break. Each has paid $95.  <p> And as usual, not everyone in the room is comfortable with the subject. As Rev. Robert Hess, who made the trip to Louisiana from his Delmar Reformed Church parish in Delmar, New York, says,"Too many congregants already say, All you ever do is ask for money.' "  <p> Flipping transparencies on an overhead projector, a few pens sticking out of his shirt pocket, Miller offers his audience some basic tips. For fund-raising letters: "Do a good job of printing or photocopying. Let the quality of the letters speak of the importance of God's work!" He also recommends holding a special event he calls "Consecration Sunday." By calling in a guest speaker and offering a free lunch, the event serves as a "synthetic Easter"--that is, a one-time event with an Easter-size turnout.  <p> By the end of the six-hour workshop, some of the pastors have overcome their discomfort. Rev. Ron McKay of Taylorville United Methodist in Tuscaloosa, Alabama, says he is no longer afraid to ask parishioners for money. "It was what I was looking for," he says.  <p> And for those who are still averse to Miller's tactics, one of his not-so-spiritual insights may provide inspiration: "There's nothing more basic in human life than the phrase 'Put me down for the same amount as last year.' "  <p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
