<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/03-Road to Kerouac's Riches</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Road to Kerouac's Riches</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Did the author's daughter get beat out of her rightful inheritance? <p> By Monica Corcoran  <p> Jan Kerouac recalls the second and last time she saw her father, Jack, the author of On the Road. "He was drinking whiskey and watching The Beverly Hillbillies, but I knew he was happy to see me."   <p> Jan, then 15 years old, told her father she was going to Mexico to write a book. Kerouac, who had left his second wife before Jan was born and rarely acknowledged his daughter, offered her this parting gift: "You can use my name."  <p> That was all the man who coined the term "Beat Generation" ever gave his only child. Two years later, in 1969, Jack Kerouac died of alcoholism in Florida and left his estate to his mother, Gabrielle. A local court valued his belongings and property at the time at $35,559. When Gabrielle died in 1973, her will named Kerouac's third wife, Stella Sampas, as the sole heir.  <p> Or did it? "I've always been suspicious of the way the Sampas family got everything," says Jan Kerouac. At 43, having penned two semiautobiographical books of her own, she lives in New Mexico, coping with kidney problems that require her to undergo daily dialysis. Last year, after showing a copy of Gabrielle's will to a handwriting expert, Jan quickly filed a motion to have the will reexamined, claiming it had been forged. That triggered a court battle pitting her against Stella Sampas's relatives, who inherited the Kerouac estate when Sampas died five years ago. (Jan Kerouac does receive some copyright royalties from her father's written works.) Jan Kerouac's lawyer, Thomas Brill, expects the case to go to trial by the end of this year.  <p> The Sampas family dismisses Jan Kerouac's charges. "There's no question that the will is authentic," says Skip Dalton, attorney for the Sampas family. "We're just going to slay this dragon and move on."  <p> Now valued at up to $10 million, the estate includes Jack Kerouac's journals, manuscripts, some paintings by the author, and letters. The original manuscript of On the Road, typed out on one longscroll of paper, is worth more than $1 million, according to literary collector and dealer Richard Marcel. "My lifelong goal is to get back my father's things so I can put them in a museum or a library," says Jan Kerouac.  <p> In the meantime, the Sampases have been selling off Kerouac's belongings piecemeal. A trench coat, for example, fetched $15,000 from actor Johnny Depp. "I've heard from dealers that the Sampases are selling pieces hand over fist," says Gerald Nicosia, author of the 1983 Kerouac biography Memory Babe. "They're destroying a national treasure."  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Estate Planning, Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

