	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Jake and the Taxman</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Jake and the Taxman</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> JAKE AND THE TAXMAN <p>For 46 years, Jacob Freidus has thumbed his nose at the IRS. His tab stands at $20 million.  <p> By Thomas Maier  <p> In American history, Jacob Freidus holds a special place, but it's not a distinction that pleases his government. What this frail 79-year-old man from Cold Spring Harbor, New York, has managed to achieve is the secret envy of many Americans, especially as April 15 rolls around: Freidus may be the greatest tax dodger in history.  <p> His tax bill--estimated at close to $20 million--dates to 1949. Still going strong in its fifth decade, the battle of U.S. vs. Jacob Freidus is the longest-running case known to the IRS. As a spokesman for the U.S. attorney in New York says, "He's been fighting the government for a very long time."  <p> A half century ago, the press heralded Freidus as the boy wonder of Manhattan's real estate market--a man who had amassed a $15 million fortune. Then, in 1949, he was charged with evading more than $200,000 in income taxes and eventually sentenced to four years in prison.  <p> He was hardly repentant. While in prison, according to the government, Freidus concocted a new tax dodge--allegedly funneling millions from his real estate empire to another dummy company he controlled.When the government discovered the plan, it ordered Freidus to pay $9 million in back taxes.  <p> The moment of reckoning never came. Freidus appealed the decision and, for the next two decades, used virtually every imaginable excuse to drag out the case. The government won the trial in1973, though legal complications kept it in U.S. Tax Court until1982.  <p> A U.S. appeals court eventually ordered Freidus to pay up, but he managed to stall once again. After the government launched a legal effort to sort through Freidus's business files and figure out what could be used to pay the back taxes, Freidus delivered his master stroke. In 1991, with authorities closing in, he filed for bankruptcy. Among his debts: a $17 million tax bill (the original debt, plus three decades of penalties and interest) and $458,000 in outstanding New York State taxes.  <p> Last year, a federal bankruptcy judge ruled that Freidus can't use the law to avoid the debt. He contested that ruling in front of another federal judge; once more, his appeal was dismissed. <p> The government is again ready to start sorting through Freidus's finances--looking for a way to collect his debt of nearly $20million. No one expects a quick resolution.  <p>  <p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency, Taxation 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
