		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Fast-Track Taxes</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Fast-Track Taxes</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> FAST-TRACK TAXES  <p> When it comes to taxes, time is money. During the yearly flood of last-minute tax returns, it can take the IRS anywhere from two to five weeks to cash your tax-payment check--giving you extra time to earn interest on the funds. Of course, Uncle Sam would prefer getting his hands on your money right away. To that end, the IRS has created 1040-V, a new tax form being sent this year to nearly 10 million taxpayers who owed money on last year's returns. Under this system, taxpayers are asked to send their normal 1040 return to one location and then mail their payment, along with the 1040-V, to a special IRS lockbox address where checks will be cashed promptly. Why help out the tax man? The1040-V "will help us process your payment more accurately and efficiently," says the IRS. On the other hand, that additional envelope will also cost you an extra stamp. The good news: 1040-V is voluntary--for now.  <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
