	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Betting on the Chips</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Betting on the Chips</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> BETTING ON THE CHIPS <p><a name="NASD:INTC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13787"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Intel's</b></a> Pentium problems opened a window on to our technological souls--but few looked  <p> By Dean Robinson  <p> For Intel, the flap over its Pentium computer chip's long-division errors concluded in mid-January with a massive subtraction. The company set aside $475 million to replace all those brain-damaged microprocessors, closing (it hoped) the books on the subject. <p> There may be a lingering cost for the rest of us, though: a missed opportunity to delete some technological navet from the hard drive of our psyches. For a moment, the media was talking about the fallibility of technology--though it quickly passed. "Once Intel did the right thing, the public went back to thinking about O.J. Simpson," says Paul Saffo, a director at the Institute for the Future, a think tank in Menlo Park, California.  <p> If you're thinking all this doesn't matter because you never used a Pentium yourself, think again. Got an account at <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan Bank</b></a>? Make your investments through Prudential Securities? Both companies were among those that used Pentiums before the flaw was publicized and corrected. Hundreds more key institutions may have depended on the chip. Math-deficient machines even found their way into the Federal Reserve Bank of St. Louis.  <p> Intel's gurus tell us the chances of a Pentium error were one in 9 billion calculations; others say it was riskier. Either way, the potential for harm was limited--this time. But with so much of our lives dependent on computers, this should have been a wake-up call about the danger of believing that technology can be flawless. Too bad no one was listening. "There's a touching faith in the accuracy of computers," says Saffo.  <p> Technology folks, at least, harbor no illusions. In a public message on the Internet, Thomas Nicely, the Lynchburg College math professor who first publicized the Pentium bug, argued that today's complex computer chips have outpaced human ken: "It is no longer possible to completely debug them, or even to determine every bug that exists," he wrote. Surely this is a sobering idea--if anyone stops to think about it.  <p> Problem is, there's not much we can do about our chip habit; it's too late to reboot. "You can't go backward," says Eugene Glazer, a Wall Street analyst who covers the industry. If that means more flaws and, as a result, more problems--well, so be it. "There's a certain price society pays for progress," says Glazer. "The increase in productivity is dramatically greater than the additional problems."  <p> Of course, no one's claiming that a Pentium problem could have caused society to crash. The chip's one known flaw kicks in only for arcane division problems. Still, it would have been nice to admit that, even with Intel's move to replace the chips, our brave new microprocessed world won't be bug-free. "People put too much trust in computers," says Saffo. "I worry that someday, when something goes wrong, they'll overreact the other way." <p>
<p>KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
