	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Adventures in Baby-Sitting</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/03-Adventures in Baby-Sitting</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						March 1995 <p>Worth magazine/Outfront  <p> ADVENTURES IN BABY-SITTING  <p> Late last fall, Wall Street trading behemoth Salomon Brothers gave vice president Robert M. Stavis the biggest one-year pay package in the firm's history: $35 million in salary, bonus, and compensation. The news catapulted Stavis, now a managing director, into the spotlight as the Street's newest and biggest bonus baby.  <p> It turns out that Stavis was more like a bonus baby-sitter. The trade that earned him most of his pay--a monster arbitrage involving government securities and mortgages--was actually orchestrated by Lawrence Hilibrand, a famed Salomon trader who defected in late 1993 for a hedge fund. Insiders say Stavis and six colleagues in the bond arbitrage group inherited the position and sat with it after Hilibrand left. The trade eventually earned $500 million for Salomon. Neither Stavis nor Salomon will comment.  <p> There was a method behind this bonus madness. People familiar with the payouts say Hilibrand's defection had Salomon brass so worried that the firm made a sweetheart deal with Stavis and his colleagues: Stick around and we'll pay you 20 percent of the group's profits. It worked; they stuck.  <p>  

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
