	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Special Dispensation</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Special Dispensation</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Special Dispensation</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>SPECIAL DISPENSATION
For banks, deciding how to push customers' buttons at ATMs is anything but automatic<p>By Dean Robinson<p>When you stop off for cash at the corner ATM, the machine may not talk back, but it is watching--and learning.<p>Every transaction you make becomes fodder for banks and ATM networks that are constantly studying questions such as: How much money do you want? And how do you want it? The answers can be used to tailor ATM offerings for different markets and customers.<p>One example: Big bills for big spenders. At some Las Vegas casinos and at select Citibank sites in New York City, ATMs now dispense $100 bills. <p>"All those tens and twenties are too bulky, too much to handle," says Citibank spokeswoman Maria Mendler. Too much, that is, for customers in the habit of withdrawing stacks of cash: Citibank is spitting out the C-notes only at a dozen test spots chosen for their high withdrawals. "It wouldn't be useful if we put them in locations where people take out an average of $50," says Mendler.<p>Banks are also working to speed customers on their way by fine-tuning the "quick cash" setting, the ATM shortcut to a designated cash amount. Most machines around the country--when they offer such an option--are set to deliver $40 or $50. But economists (or sociologists) should take note: In New York two of the city's largest ATM networks now dispense a quick $100. <p>On the laid-back West Coast, even a one-touch setting must seem too constricting. Most <a name="NYSE:WFC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11619"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wells Fargo</b></a> ATMs provide at least two fast-cash choices: $40 and $100. Bank of America's system is even more accommodating--cardholders can customize the feature to their own most frequently selected amount.<p>For thoughtfulness, who can knock the Portland, Oregon based <a name="NASD:USBC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14968"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>U.S. Bancorp</b></a>? Its ATMs may provide an unvarying $50 in fast cash, but that last $10 makes all the difference: It comes as two fives. "It's cheaper to use just one denomination, as most banks do," says John Kresge, head of ATM and debit-card marketing at U.S. Bancorp. "But this way, if you want to get a cup of coffee at <a name="NASD:SBUX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15745"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Starbucks</b></a>, you don't have to use a twenty." Not for a small, anyway.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
