		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Presumed Solvent</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Presumed Solvent</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Outfronts<p>PRESUMED SOLVENT<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Tired of long lines at the bank? Weary of endless service fees? Don't get mad. Get a law degree.<p>When it comes to banking, the scales of justice definitely tip in favor of attorneys. Though it's not widely known outside law offices, banks frequently offer the legal set special treatment unheard of by folks who don't bill by the hour.<p>"We're here to help the 'time is money' crowd," says David Skinner, vice president of personal banking at <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan</b></a>. Perks can include a personal banking account executive, unsecured lines of credit, and jumbo mortgages. Standing in a bank line is out of the question, since the account executive handles all transactions.<p>Such niceties are usually extended to a bank's wealthiest depositors as a matter of course. But if your business card reads "attorney at law," many banks will roll out the red carpet regardless of your current income or assets--even to associates fresh out of law school.<p>"I pay no checking or ATM fees," chirps Anupam Chander, a 27-year-old associate at Cleary, Gottlieb, Steen & Hamilton, of his perk-ridden account with Citibank. "When I call my personal banker, she gets back to me the same day. It's a great setup." Indeed. But what do they do with all those free toasters? <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
