	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Lee's Big Ad Venture</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Lee's Big Ad Venture</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>LEE'S BIG AD VENTURE<p>By Stacie Stukin<p>Susan Powter beware: Lee Iacocca is about to join the insanity with his own infomercial. The retired <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a> chairman will take to the airwaves this spring to pitch a videotape series, Iacocca on Success: It Can Happen to You. Granted, the quintessential "rags to riches" son of immigrants has earned the right to opine on success. But must Iacocca rub shoulders with Jay the Juiceman, Cher, and Vanna White to spread his motivational message? "He really wants to give something back to society," says his agent, Rick Bradley. Give and you shall receive is more like it: Iacocca plans to peddle his tapes at around $25 each. That should help augment the $500,000 annual stipend he gets as a consultant to Chrysler and the $60,000 he commands for individual speaking engagements. In addition, Iacocca sits on the board of Ronald Perelman's <a name="NASD:NWCG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=17177"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>New World Communications</b></a>, which owns more than one third of the outfit producing his power pitch. Rest assured, though, the production will be tasteful. Rather than gesticulate madly and roam a studio audience, Iacocca plans to segue from chats with guests to inspirational soliloquies--perhaps next to a cozy blazing fireplace. But even if the spectacle helps channel-surfing insomniacs tally the price of success, they may still wonder: What price dignity?<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
