	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Is That Seat Taken?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Is That Seat Taken?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Is That Seat Taken?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>IS THAT SEAT TAKEN?
Forget season tickets: "Permanent" seating plans let you stake out your turf for good<p>By Bob Woods<p>Think that season ticket proves your loyalty to the hometown sports team? Maybe you should consider buying a seat for life.<p>That's the idea behind permanent seat licenses, a new scheme that lets die-hard fans purchase lifetime rights to designated seats. It's also the latest tactic for financing the construction of new sports facilities.<p>The idea has been pioneered by the Carolina Panthers, a new National Football League franchise in Charlotte, North Carolina, that will begin league play this fall. More than 52,000 Panther fans have signed up for permanent seat licenses costing from $600 to $6,400 each.<p>That's not as great a deal as it sounds. The seat licenses aren't actually season tickets. Instead, fans own the rights to their seats but must still purchase a season ticket each year.<p>The idea came about when Jerry Richardson, the owner of the Panthers, hired sports marketing whiz Max Muhleman to devise a plan to raise $100 million for construction of a Charlotte stadium. Without a facility, the NFL wouldn't grant the city a franchise.<p>Betting on the appetite of the hungry fan, the Panthers offered seat ownership in Carolinas Stadium, now under construction. Charlotte banks got into the act, too, offering special four-year fixed-rate loans at 8 percent. Some companies even extended financing to employees.<p>Not surprisingly, some other cities--including Tampa and Seattle--have begun eyeing permanent seating plans. And Muhleman is working on a similar program in St. Louis to help lure the Los Angeles Rams to town.<p>Speculators in stadium real estate are already talking about resale value, but for now, it's too early in the game. Owners are barred from selling the seats until 1997. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Sports Industry, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

