<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-He Said, She Sued, He Lost</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>He Said, She Sued, He Lost</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-He Said, She Sued, He Lost</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>HE SAID, SHE SUED, HE LOST
A court appeal may soon set the price of a broken engagement<p>By Gretchen Reynolds<p>The blissful engagement of Richard Austin Springs III and his love Sharon Wildey endured for exactly seven weeks in 1992. Then Springs, a wealthy 50-year-old Oregon cattle rancher, got cold feet, wrote his affianced--a 49-year-old Chicago lawyer--a Dear Sharon letter, and attempted, rather gracelessly, to fade from her life.<p>He was about to discover what real courting means.<p>In October 1992, Sharon Wildey sued Springs for breach of promise, an offense so antiquated that 18 states have stricken it from the books. To the astonishment of most legal scholars, Wildey won, and won big: In November 1993, a jury awarded her $178,000 for the financial costs--and pain and suffering--of having been jilted.<p>The case immediately became a minor cause celebre, with everyone from the Chicago Tribune to Dateline NBC focusing on its seeming absurdity. When the frenzy subsided, the idea of suing over a broken engagement seemed like yet another legal oddity.<p>But the real legacy of Wildey v. Springs is just now being shaped. Today the case sits before Chicago's Seventh Circuit Court of Appeals. A decision on whether to overturn is expected this month, just in time for Valentine's Day. And if the award to Wildey is upheld, the case may well be transformed from an oddity to a precedent.<p>Even now, the circumstances sound absurd. Wildey and Springs had known each other barely four months. And when Springs bolted, he left behind a $19,000 engagement ring and $10,000 in his Chicago checking account. Wildey kept both. Then she sued.<p>But there's more to the case than money (or even romantic reprisal). "Our legal system is slowly moving toward the notion that it has a significant role to play in regulating intimate relationships," says Jane Larson, a law professor at Northwestern University. "The Sharon Wildey case is a major milestone in that respect."<p>If it is a milestone, we may be on the wrong road, argues Katha Pollitt, a feminist scholar and writer. "People should be able to change their minds in questions of romance without penalty," she says. "Pain and suffering are part of life."<p>Many lawyers expect to see a rash of similar lawsuits if the award is upheld--possibly even the development of a new subset of family-practice law. "You once had to have a lawyer handle your divorce," says Barry Schatz, a prominent divorce attorney in Chicago. "Then you started to need one to draw up your prenuptial agreement. Will you need one now to handle the terms of your engagement?<p>"Call your friends when you are brokenhearted," Schatz advises. "But leave your lawyer out of it."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
