	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Don1t Blame Society. Blame the Accountants</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Not Society. Blame Accountants</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>DON'T BLAME SOCIETY. BLAME THE ACCOUNTANTS.<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>This time, the IRS isn't just mad. It's very disappointed.<p>"It's bad," says Leslie Shapiro, the director of the office of practice at the IRS. "They have failed to meet their commitments as role models in society."<p>Violent criminals? Professional athletes? No, just more than 400 professional tax preparers, most of them certified public accountants, who've recently been nailed as nonfilers. And to no one's surprise, the IRS doesn't show a sense of humor when it comes to the pros.<p>Since March of 1993, Shapiro's department, which governs CPAs, attorneys, and enrolled agents who prepare taxes, has been sniffing through tax preparers' returns. Or lack thereof.<p>Shapiro concedes that "it's strange" that those who prepare taxes for a living would neglect to file their own. So what's their excuse? <p>They're only human, says Gerald Padwe, vice president of taxation at the American Institute of CPAs. "Sometimes a life-cycle event occurs that prevents a taxpayer from filing," Padwe says. For instance? "The death of a spouse would be one." Or maybe they've just been too busy with their clients' returns.<p>One excuse that definitely won't fly: I didn't have the right forms.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
