	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 95/02-Darwin's Portfolio</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Darwin's Portfolio</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>95/02-Darwin's Portfolio</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						February 1995
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>DARWIN'S PORTFOLIO
Want to breed a better investment strategy? Try a computer model of evolution theory.<p>By Jim Melloan<p>In a quest to find the perfect investment strategy, some money-management firms have turned to a method with a track record of four billion years: evolution.<p>Using a science called artificial life, these firms subject potential investment approaches to stringent computer simulations. Different investment strategies are used to make simulated investment decisions based on historical market data. A financial struggle for survival ensues, with the winning strategies being those that make the most simulated money.<p>So far that sounds like standard Wall Street number-crunching. But rather than just sticking with those winners, the artificial-life approach takes the best strategies, "mutates" them slightly to produce a new generation, and runs them through the simulation again and again. Sophisticated genetic algorithms guide the strategies' evolution through countless repetitions.<p>"The number of possible strategies you can explore with this stuff is absolutely mind-boggling," says Richard J. Bauer, author of Genetic Algorithms and Investment Strategies, the first book on this fledgling field. "The other night I was at my PC exploring foreign-exchange trading rules, and I was sifting through about 35 billion possible rules."<p>For Redfire Capital Management Group, a tiny start-up investment firm in Cambridge, Massachusetts, the articifical-life approach has paid off. The company boasts of an 88 percent return for the first 11 months of 1994 using artificial-life strategies to trade stock-index options.<p>Redfire, with less than $100,000 under management, is small, but the approach has also captured the attention of First Quadrant Corp. in Pasadena, California, with about $16 billion in assets. First Quadrant now uses genetic algorithms to manage about $5 billion of that total.<p>For now, few others have tumbled to the method, and even fewer are willing to go public about it. Devotees are hoping artificial life remains their secret. As Redfire partner Michael de la Maza says, "We're very happy to keep it quiet."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

