		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>So Much for the Bear Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-So Much for the Bear Market</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>SO MUCH FOR THE BEAR MARKET
When traders slug it out in the pits, things can get ugly.<p>By Ted C. Fishman<p>Bulls and bears have always slugged it out at the Chicago Board of Trade. So when the Brookfield Zoo's polar bear mascot came prancing around the pits, naturally a trader belted him -- it was practically a conditioned response. <p>Under the fur, however, was an actor playing bear to promote an Endangered Species Fund picnic. The mascot was rushed to a first-aid station, where he was treated briefly. <p>The ursiphobic trader, J. Allen Jorjorian, popped the bear on a $25 bet and now may face sanctions from the CBOT's conduct committee. Jorjorian, who didn't return our calls, was working in the CBOT's financial-futures room -- home of the infamous U.S. Treasury bond pit. Members often complain that the overcrowded pit makes them ornery, and there have been previous cases of violence. <p>Zoo workers can be a tad ornery, too: They've suggested promoting next year's picnic by sending Arki, their real polar bear, into the T bond pit -- dressed like a trader. <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

