<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Rough Sailing</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Rough Sailing</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Rough Sailing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>ROUGH SAILING
A young American says he's buying Aristotle Onassis's former yacht. The owner disagrees.<p>By James Gorant<p>In February, Alexander Blastos's ship seemed to have come in. The little-known Greek-American businessman had agreed to pay $2.2 million for the mothballed yacht once owned by billionaire Aristotle Onassis -- and promised to spend a further $40 million fixing it up for charter cruising.<p>But now Blastos's deal appears to have been scuttled and the 29-year-old has headed for Europe, leaving anger and questions in his wake. Several people involved in the transaction believe Blastos grossly exaggerated his wealth, duping everyone along the way -- including the Greek government, which has owned the boat since receiving it as a gift from Onassis's daughter Christina.<p>Blastos is hard to find. His relatives in Keene, New Hampshire, say they don't know where he is. But in a telephone interview peppered with grandiose boasts, the putative millionaire insists his deal hasn't fallen through: It's just awaiting some "paperwork." He gamely pledges to boost his budget for restoring the Argo, which Onassis called the Christina, to a stunning $80 million.<p>Blastos won't be cruising on the Argo anytime soon, however. "The sale is off," confirms a spokesman at the Greek embassy in Washington, D.C. "There were questions that Blastos didn't have the finances." As a result, German shipyard Blohm & Voss presumably won't get to refit the yacht for Blastos, a lucrative job that would have included fixing the hydraulics that transform the mosaic-tiled dance floor into a swimming pool. And famed yacht designer Luigi Sturchio won't oversee the restoration project as planned. Neither the shipyard nor Sturchio would comment.<p>It's the latest humiliation for a boat with a glorious past. The Argo is one of the world's largest and most famous yachts. Originally a Canadian navy frigate, the vessel was bought by Onassis and remade in opulent style with gold faucets and original art works by El Greco and Gauguin. The Greek tycoon used the Christina to entertain guests such as Greta Garbo, Frank Sinatra, and Winston Churchill; in 1968, he honeymooned aboard the yacht with Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis.<p>After the billionaire's death in 1975, Onassis's daughter donated the Christina to his home country, which dubbed it the Argo and used it for official purposes. But high operating costs made such outings infrequent. The boat hasn't been used since 1987 and is now in serious disrepair.<p>Blastos's interest, therefore, came as a welcome development. Styling himself a money manager who had thrived on hot stocks and other investments, the Greek-American talked a good game. But trouble surfaced in June, when Greek news reports quoted a lawyer in the deal claiming that Blastos's deposit check had bounced. Blastos says there was never such a check. The Greek government won't comment on any of this or give details about how the deal unraveled.<p>Blastos's true financial status is hard to assess. He says he built his wealth starting as a preteen, got "phenomenally lucky" in the stock market, and branched into other areas. But according to the editor of his hometown newspaper, the Keene Sentinel, many of these stories simply don't hang together. "There's always some truth to what he says," says James Rousmaniere Jr. "But as to what percentage, you're left hanging."<p>Rousmaniere says he tracked down a number of the projects on which Blastos claims to have gotten rich, including auto sales to Japan and a fruit-processing plant in Mexico. "By his account he was very high up in these projects," says the editor. "But when you talk to others who were involved, you discover that sometimes he's not even clearly remembered."<p>Untroubled by such comments -- or by Greece's insistence that the Argo deal is dead -- Blastos says he's now moving on to the next stage of his career: shipping. "I'm on my way to Greece tomorrow to finalize the purchase of two ships." <p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

