	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Ford's New Star Vehicle</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Ford's New Star Vehicle</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						November 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p><a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>FORD</b></a>'S NEW STAR VEHICLE
In the wake of O.J.'s freeway ride, buyers aren't bucking Broncos.<p>By Abby Ellin<p>Entrepreneurs hawking O.J. t-shirts aren't the only ones making money off the sordid Simpson saga. Count in Ford dealers on the West Coast, who report a rush on "O.J. Simpson Broncos." <p>Nationwide, Bronco sales surged 24 percent from June to August, but a Ford spokesman says it's because the company began offering rebates two weeks before Simpson fled police in a Bronco on June 17. "It has nothing to do with O.J. Simpson," he says testily. <p>In Southern California, however, the link is unmistakable. Bronco sales are up almost 65 percent from last year, and dealers say it has plenty to do with the accused murderer. "That car looked good going down the freeway," says Scott Strotz, sales manager at Kemp Ford in Thousand Oaks. <p>While all types of Bronco are flying off dealers' lots, the biggest prize is the white XLT with tan interior. That's about $29,000 to emulate the Juice -- not counting mobile phone. It seems some dealers even have offered "O.J. specials." Predictably, that trend started on the West Coast too. "People in the East have better taste," says a California dealer who's almost out of Broncos.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
