<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/11-Feeling the Heat</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Feeling the Heat</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/11-Feeling the Heat</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						April 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>FEELING THE HEAT
Fire walker and self-help guru Tony Robbins finds himself dragged across the legal coals.<p>By Christopher Byron<p>In the world of infomercials, no one delivers a message with more punch than Anthony Robbins. The personal-improvement pitchman is perhaps the most successful television guru ever, generating about $30 million a year from products sold on his Personal Power shows -- and at least as much again from seminars.<p>Robbins's schtick is familiar enough, a warmed-over but powerful mix of techniques from Dale Carnegie to Werner Erhard. In a California twist, he earned his superstar rep in part by herding hundreds of pumped-up, barefoot disciples across beds of burning coals.<p>Beyond all the motivational talk, Robbins mostly sells his own image to fans. A handsome, six-foot-seven-inch man who lives in a castle overlooking the Pacific and oversees a Fantasy Island-type resort in Fiji, Robbins portrays himself as the embodiment of all that follows when people use his "technology" -- a series of lectures offered via audiocassette, on videotape, or in person.<p>But in fact, Tony Robbins has had some trouble winning friends and influencing people lately. He continues to settle lawsuits from franchisees who accuse him of deception. An effort to build a financial-planning business has ended. And most recently, Robbins was accused of fraud in legal action by Guthy-Renker, the company that helped craft the Robbins image.<p>That fight centered on Robbins's infomercials. Guthy-Renker, which produces the shows, claimed Robbins tried to extort money by blocking its latest release. It sought $3.3 million in actual damages, plus $5 million as punishment for Robbins. Brad Hunsaker, Robbins's top lawyer, says the holdup came after a disgruntled Guthy-Renker employee told Robbins he was being mistreated by the production company. The resulting spat could have made for juicy revelations about both parties' finances, but at press time it seemed headed for a hush-hush settlement.<p>Meanwhile, Hunsaker himself plays a key role in another of Robbins's financial headaches: a continuing flow of damaging lawsuits from peeved franchisees. In a scheme devised around 1989, the guru's organization charged entrepreneurs for the right to show taped Robbins seminars to large crowds. That largely proved a bust. But instead of shutting down the operation, Robbins merely changed its concept slightly and flogged franchises all over again. The new system wasn't a roaring success either.<p>In lawsuits, licensees have charged that Robbins deceived them about their ventures' prospects and exclusivity. Ironically, among their best weapons is a blistering internal memo written by Hunsaker. In that 1990 document, known to some lawyers but disclosed widely for the first time here, Hunsaker mentions "obvious misrepresentations that were made during the early part of our history."<p>The smoking-gun memo became evidence in a franchisee suit filed against Robbins in Georgia, where a judge ordered sanctions against the Robbins organization for lying in court papers. The case was settled out of court -- and other settlements have followed as Robbins's network has dwindled to 20 licensees from more than 50. The most recent payoff came late this summer after a Texas franchisee named Cindy Chambers sued, saying she was duped and that Robbins himself unfairly poached on her territory.<p>Meanwhile, Robbins continues to suffer setbacks in other areas. Destiny Financial Services, an effort to manage his disciples' money, quietly fell apart last year after a three-year joint effort with San Diego stockbroker David D'Arcangelo. This summer Destiny's remnants were swallowed by Rodman & Renshaw, a Chicago brokerage firm. D'Arcangelo now pitches his new employer's services from Robbins's office building in San Diego.<p><p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
