	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Sharon's Stones</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Sharon's Stones</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>SHARON'S STONES
Tales from Harry Winston, where the stars go to borrow jewels.<p>In truth, we're tired of actress Sharon Stone and her jewels. After getting grief for wanting to keep a $400,000 "loaner" necklace from Beverly Hills jeweler Harry Winston, Stone now is suing the store for $12 million, claiming breach of contract. Tacky.<p>Still, we're weirdly fascinated by Winston's jewelry-lending practice. Turns out the store has handed over (and gotten back) diamonds worth as much as $3 million at a time. That was for Elizabeth Taylor, but lesser stars such as Patti LaBelle have paraded in $2 million sapphire-diamond combos lent by Winston.<p>Like many tony stores, Winston likes loaners because its name gets dropped in those gushing descriptions (hair! dress! shoes!) of guests at gala events. A Winston shopping list from the 1994 Academy Awards -- all safely returned:<p>-> Dolly Parton: Diamond necklace and earrings ($750,000)<p>-> Rosie O'Donnell: Sapphire-and-diamond necklace, diamond cluster earrings ($550,000)<p>-> Marisa Tomei: Diamond earring-and-bracelet set ($400,000)<p>-> Laura Dern: Diamond drop earrings, bracelet, and ring ($250,000)<p>-> Winona Ryder: Diamond necklace and cluster earrings ($100,000)<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
