<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Plastic Soldier</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Plastic Soldier</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Plastic Soldier</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>PLASTIC SOLDIER
One man's credit-card crusade.<p>Forget those frequent-buyer deals on credit cards. George Brennan has found a better way to get money back: He hauls stores into small-claims court after using his credit card. <p>The Californian retiree has made more than $7,000 since early 1993 by suing stores that ask for personal info -- such as his address -- when he pays with plastic. Gathering such data is illegal in 12 states, since it might be used by fraudsters. <p>Brennan was once ripped off this way; now he styles himself an avenger, prevailing over retailers including <a name="NYSE:S"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11338"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sears</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:SME"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11342"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Service Merchandise</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:CC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10343"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Circuit City</b></a>. He's not alone in his crusade: Several stores have settled class-action suits. <p>Still, Brennan's litigious shtick may be wearing thin. "He just goes around making purchases, suing the stores, then returning the items," says an exasperated James Brooks, an Orange County judge who recently tossed out such a case. Brennan remains unbowed. His next shopping destination: <a name="NASD:BKST"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16052"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Brookstone</b></a>.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

