<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Live Fast, Die Young - Pay Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Live Fast, Die Young - Pay Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Live Fast, Die Young - Pay Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>LIVE FAST, DIE YOUNG - PAU UP
Two insurers challenge River Phoenix's estate -- and a Hollywood tradition:  Actors who try to hide their drug and health problems.<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>When River Phoenix died of a drug overdose last year, the young actor was mourned as a lost talent -- the James Dean of his generation. But Phoenix's true legacy in Hollywood may have more to do with movie economics than with tragic romanticism. In part because of two little-noticed lawsuits against Phoenix's estate, actors with drug and health problems may soon find it harder to get work.<p>As usual in Tinseltown, it all comes down to money. When Phoenix died, two insurance companies paid nearly $5.7 million to the producers of two movies he was acting in at the time, "Dark Blood" and "Interview With the Vampire." Phoenix was replaced in his "Interview" role by Christian Slater, but "Dark Blood" had to be scrapped entirely.<p>Now the insurance companies are suing Phoenix's estate to get their money back. CNA International and American Casualty claim Phoenix violated his contracts for the movies by lying when he said he didn't do drugs. That's an unusually tough stand, but it has won support from other insurers. And it's souring the clubby atmosphere on movie sets, where many stars routinely file false medical reports.<p>Post-Phoenix, insurers are insisting that movie producers prove that actors are truly drug-free and healthy -- or face sky-high premiums. One industry official estimates that cast-insurance costs have swollen tenfold since Phoenix's death and won't settle down until insurers' demands are met.<p>In addition to a physical examination, many insurers now want major stars to submit to blood and urine tests, an electrocardiogram, and a chest exam. The old procedure merely called for a bill of health from each actor's personal physician. "Demi Moore, Bruce Willis, and Sylvester Stallone just went through all that [testing] for a picture," says Marty Fink, president of Complete Film, a unit of Carolco Pictures. "They didn't like it one bit."<p>But a look at the Phoenix case shows why such measures might be wise. Phoenix's medical certificate for both films, signed by the star and his doctor, Michael Klaper, states that Phoenix never used "LSD, heroin, cocaine, alcohol in excess, or any other narcotic, depressant, stimulant, or psychedelic." That was in August 1993, when Phoenix was deeply into the drug scene, according to many reports. Only two months later, the 23-year-old Phoenix collapsed and died with a cocktail of drugs including cocaine in his blood.<p>It isn't known whether Phoenix's estate could afford to reimburse the insurers -- his will has been sealed -- but the companies' claims are "groundless" in any case, says a lawyer for Arlyn Phoenix, the actor's mother and executor of his estate.<p>Phoenix's death isn't the only force behind insurers' newly tough attitude. Another huge claim, about $14.5 million, was paid by Fireman's Fund after actor John Candy died of heart failure while filming Wagons East in March. Candy apparently wasn't formally examined before he was insured for the role. If a doctor had seen him, say several experts, he likely would have received only limited coverage -- saving Fireman's a bundle.<p>Besides being famously obese, Candy smoked and had gained about 40 pounds just before filming began. Heart disease ran in his family. Actors with such obvious problems may soon be just as hard to employ as stars with heroin habits.<p>The insurance crackdown will likely cause some confrontations in an industry where unhealthy living and inflated egos are the norm. "Some big stars won't even see a physician," says Carolyn Norton, of insurance broker Hogg Robinson. Compliance could become a union issue: "We'd be concerned if insurance companies started making outrageous demands," says a spokesman for the Screen Actors Guild.<p>But most observers think the insurers will get their way -- and that actors who don't comply will find themselves banished to infomercialville. Says Scott Taylor, a showbiz-insurance broker: "This sends a message to stars who think they're untouchable."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
