	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Last Call?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Last Call?</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Last Call?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>LAST CALL?
One man fights to get beer commercials canned -- as deceptive advertising.<p>By Dean Robinson<p>Television beer commercials have never been big on realism -- their dumb bikini fantasies are the last bastion of unreconstructed manhood. But if a former policeman has his way, those ads full of babes and stunts will soon be ruled illegal.<p>Richard Overton is suing beer giant <a name="NYSE:BUD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10116"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Anheuser-Busch</b></a> for deceptive advertising. At first glance his argument seems simple-minded: Beer drinking isn't just babes and stunts, says Overton, so it's illegal to portray it as such.<p>But Overton, a college recruiter, is no frustrated party animal. He's just worried about the lopsided effect all these glamorous ads have on kids -- including his own. His case is now before Michigan's Supreme Court.<p>Overton saw his share of drunken fights and car wrecks as a state trooper. He thinks beer ads would be better if they carried a disclaimer -- "The people depicted are not under the influence of alcohol," for instance. But mostly he wants them ruled deceptive as a matter of law. "I have yet to find a good legal mind that disagrees with me," he says.<p>Well, actually, a few judges have disagreed with him: Overton has lost every round in court so far. Still, he vows to press on. "This is a bombshell waiting to explode" under the beer industry, he says. Unsurprisingly, Anheuser-Busch says the case has no merit.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

