<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-This Deal's a Turkey</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>This Deal's a Turkey</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-This Deal's a Turkey</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>This Deal's a Turkey
Or maybe not -- if you believe we'll be eating McOstrich burgers anytime soon, that is.<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Ostrich farming is taking off: Some 75,000 of the flightless birds are now being raised on 4,000 ranches nationwide, roughly a threefold increase since 1991. Ostriches are being touted all over as the next hot investment opportunity.<p>But if a big marketer of ostrich partnerships is any example, this business is strictly for the birds. Beecroft Young Interest Ltd., a Dallas-based firm, cold-calls many investors at home. Its story is alluring: "On a $10,000 investment, you'll easily get $100,000 back."<p>Small wonder BYI has sold out its first three ostrich ventures. But while BYI and its rancher make money, others are likely to be disappointed. Ostrich investing looks like a pyramid that's due for collapse. Already this year the Securities and Exchange Commission has shut down one Florida ostrich partnership; in California, state officials halted another venture.<p>The idea behind the current boom is that Americans will eat all these birds -- ostrich is touted as a low-fat, low-cholesterol red meat. But experts say a change in U.S. eating habits is doubtful at best. "It's more likely the Messiah will come," says Steven Kaplan, editor of Food and Food Ways magazine. Last year, 6,000 pounds of ostrich meat were sold in the U.S. At 80 pounds of meat per ostrich, that's a measly 75 birds.<p>What's more, ostrich meat is five times as expensive as beef. And U.S. investors buy birds for far more than they cost in South Africa, where ostrich meat is accepted as food. "Ostriches are being bred here mostly so they can be sold to other breeders," says Mitchell Hurwitz, a Dallas financial consultant who studied one BYI deal for Worth. "The whole thing appears based on the greater-fool theory -- like tulip mania," a Dutch investment fad that blossomed and withered in the 17th century.<p>Even without such caveats, though, many partnerships are unlikely to pan out. BYI's North Bend Ostrich Venture II deal is fairly typical. NBOV II raised $500,000 to buy 11 pairs of ostriches. Investors paid $10,000 for a 1.5 percent share of any income the birds produced. <p>Among the deal's problems:<p>-> In its brochure, BYI fails to mention that 25 percent of all new chicks are given free to the rancher, reducing returns. This fact is buried in a deal memo that BYI provided only grudgingly, after repeated requests.<p>-> BYI projects that its breeders will produce 28 or so chicks a year. A quarter go to the ranch; half of the remainder will be sold, the rest kept to raise the number of breeders. But an expert at North Carolina State University says ostriches have only 10 to 15 healthy chicks a year.<p>-> In its telephone sales pitch, BYI says it deals in "insured investments." But investors' stakes in NBOV II aren't insured -- just the ostriches are.<p>Mike Young, a principal in BYI, defends the deal and doesn't back off BYI's "conservative" projections. He concedes the ostrich market is "similar to a pyramid." But by the time prices fall, he says, his investors will likely have made a bundle. <p>Hurwitz, by contrast, says BYI investors may break even in two or three years -- if greater fools keep buying overpriced ostriches. That seems quite a gamble, but for now ostrich mania continues unabated. At press time, BYI was pushing a fourth partnership.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


