	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Chipped Teeth</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Chipped Teeth</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Chipped Teeth</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>CHIPPED TEETH
Yet another reason to hate going to the dentist.<p>By David A. Andelman<p>It may be inevitable, but it's still creepy: the move to implant microchips in people's bodies as identification devices. Dentists like the idea; near-indestructible teeth are the perfect location for a high-tech dog tag. Now the Food and Drug Administration may take up the issue -- there's a study to see if chips might be included in breast implants, for example. <p>The technology was pioneered to identify animals. Vets charge about $30 to inject a rice-grain-size microchip between an animal's shoulders. When a special reader is held close, the chip emits a code that matches an entry in a database. <p>Almost 1 million pets now can be identified this way if they're lost or stolen. The first Chiclet-size chip was implanted in a horse 15 years ago; shrinking electronics have created a healthy market for ID companies such as Avid and InfoPet. <p>InfoPet's chip has already been tested in human bridgework, according to vice president Jay Culberth. Culberth says implants could alert doctors to vital medical conditions, as well as identify dead bodies. One snag: Unlike dog tags, removing a chip requires surgery. <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
