<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-Cheap Thrills</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>Cheap Thrills</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-Cheap Thrills</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>CHEAP THRILLS
A literary novelist shouts down his muse and listens instead to the siren song of lucre.<p>By D.T. Max<p>What's an acclaimed literary novelist doing writing a brutal, trashy thriller called "Father's Day"?<p>Selling out, of course. And he's not ashamed to admit it.<p>At age 34, John Calvin Batchelor saw his second book reviewed on the front page of the New York Times Book Review. But after four more well-received novels, he was still barely making a living. So Batchelor, now 46, began planning a huge payday.<p>His strategy was as closely plotted as the bravura opening of Father's Day, in which the U.S. Army launches an assault on Air Force One. First Batchelor studied the plots of classic political thrillers: "Fail-safe," "Advise and Consent," "Six Days of the Condor." For a model, he finally settled on "Seven Days in May" -- the 1963 movie version, in which a paranoid Burt Lancaster plots against the president. With a slight spin, Batchelor devised a "high concept" any Hollywood player would love: " 'Seven Days in May,' only this time the president dies."<p>Then he set out to dumb down his style to thrive in Tom Clancy territory. His tactics:<p>-> Use short paragraphs, short scenes with cutaway endings, and lots of acronyms.<p>-> Include many ambiguous, testosterone-laced conversations.<p>-> Call sympathetic characters by their first names, unsympathetic ones by their last names.<p>-> Always have characters think in italics.<p>Is Batchelor abashed at such crass calculation? Not even slightly. "This book made me rich," he says, reached in Maine as he surveys some oceanfront property he may buy with the $1.25 million he says he got from Cinergi for film rights.<p>Besides, Batchelor is rather pleased with the craft in "Father's Day," which will be released this month. "You have to be a highly trained professional to even attempt such a novel," he says. Take the battle for Air Force One. "In Hollywood, they call that the 'money scene,' " he says. "I dare you to find a better one."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Publishing Industry, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

