		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/10-100 Grand</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b>100 Grand</b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/10-100 Grand</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						October 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>
100 GRAND<p>
The challenge: Blow a tax-free windfall of $100,000 -- imaginary, we're afraid -- on five items. This month we tapped three writers who find their romance in nightmares. Clive Barker's latest horror novel, "Everville," is out this month; he's also directing a movie, "The Lord of Illusions." Up-and-comer Poppy Z. Brite writes erotic horror from her home in New Orleans; her "Drawing Blood" was just released in paperback. Peter Straub, the best-selling author of "Koko," is at work on a psychosexual thriller called "American Nights."
---------------<p>
CLIVE BARKER<p>
-> $25,000 to anybody who can locate the Marquis de Sade's bones.<p>
-> $20,000 to the Samhain Society, which wants to make Halloween -- not Christmas -- the most important festival of the year. "A worthy cause."<p>
-> $20,000 to anybody who can provide diagrams for a genuinely new sexual perversion.<p>
-> $10,000 to erect a monument at his old school in Liverpool. "It'd say: To all the teachers who said I'd never get by without a working knowledge of mathematics."<p>
-> $25,000 to anyone who can raise the devil.<p>
POPPY Z. BRITE<p>
-> $50,000 to travel abroad with a couple of friends, eating weird things, buying a new wardrobe, and shipping lots of books home.<p>
-> $2,000 to work out post-travel kinks with a black-leather massage chair from the Sharper Image.<p>
-> $7,500 for three caviar blowouts -- chilled vodka and tip included, of course.<p>
-> $5,000 for a complete CD-ROM computer system. "Just so I can never get any work done."<p>
-> $35,500 to install a padded dungeon in her home, fully equipped "for those important muscle-toning exercises."<p>
PETER STRAUB<p>
-> $30,000 for a first edition of Ernest Hemingway's first book, "Three Stories and Ten Poems." "That's for myself."<p>
-> $30,000 for an Elizabeth Murray painting -- a gift for his wife, Susan.<p>
-> $19,000 for "inspirational fuel" that'll help him work better, a category that includes compact discs and fresh-cut flowers.<p>
-> $600 for lunch with his wife and three good friends at Lespinasse, a classy restaurant in New York City.<p>
-> $20,400 as a donation to the Gay Men's Health Crisis, to help fight AIDS.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
