	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Your Ad Here</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Monica Corcoran<p>Next up: The human billboard? <p>Basketball bruiser Anthony Mason set minds ticking at the NBA finals when his coif drew almost as much interest as the action. For different games, Mason had his team's name--Knicks--and "In God's hands" neatly shaved into his locks. Ad folks' natural response: Why not the distinctive logo of his sponsor, Adidas? One wag even suggested that Mason just ditch a few letters from Knicks and sell the space to Nickelodeon, the cable channel known as "Nick." Would Mason sculpt his scalp for profit? "We haven't rented out Anthony's head yet," says his agent. "But we'd consider it." Unfortunately, the NBA says that would violate the rules. Still, the idea of body ads has huge potential. Tennis has no restrictions on anatomical adornment: Can we expect Andre Agassi to lease his stubble to <a name="NASD:CANNY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41862"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Canon</b></a>--or Pete Sampras to flex his marketing muscle by tattooing a <a name="NYSE:NKE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14254"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Nike</b></a> swoosh on his bicep? "It wouldn't be favorably received," sniffs a tour supervisor for the Association of Tennis Professionals. Still, says Brian Murphy, editor of The Sports Marketing Letter, such ads may be the wave of the future. "Think about beach volleyball," he says. "Those broad vistas of unadorned flesh." <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Sports Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
