	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-The Supreme Court Justices</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-The Supreme Court Justices</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						It's tough being a Supreme: decisions, decisions. Still, who knew that one of the choices would be whether to take freebies that'll later show up on financial disclosure forms? Luckily, our justices weren't intimidated. And we were intrigued by some  of the gifts and donations they accepted: items of clothing, for example. (No pelican briefs, alas.) Yes, we asked David Souter to tell us more about Patricia Andrews. He declined to comment.
---------------<p>THE JUSTICE: Anthony Kennedy
THE GIFT: $400 worth of shirts.<p>
THE JUSTICE: Sandra Day O'Connor
THE GIFT: Bust of General Omar Bradley.<p>
THE JUSTICE: Clarence Thomas
THE GIFT: Bust of Churchill; $150 worth of cigars; $125 worth of suspenders.<p>
THE JUSTICE: David Souter
THE GIFT: Two paintings from Patricia Andrews.<p>
THE JUSTICE: John Paul Stevens
THE GIFT: Lots of honorary memberships. This is one popular guy.<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
