<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Painting by Numbers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Painting by Numbers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
An economist draws on financial arcana for clues on making money in art.<p>Bu Jim Melloan<p>After the great art crash of 1990, many people would prefer never to see the words art and investment in the same sentence again. But a few hardy souls still see potential profit in Picassos.<p>The latest pitch comes from Roger Stiles, a London art-market economist who takes his cue from the world of derivatives and other financial instruments. Stiles, 33, has designed several products that allow high rollers to invest in art without ever  having to store a canvas.<p>Already an American brokerage house has participated in Stiles's idea for a complex "art swap." In essence, the brokerage took ownership of a big art collection but agreed to pay a fee based on the art's current value to the previous owner, a  strapped English celebrity. (Stiles won't name names.) In return, the celebrity agreed to maintain the works -- which include a Rembrandt, a Matisse, and a Picasso -- and gradually sell them to third parties, with the U.S. brokerage getting any  profit if the art's value appreciates. Stiles's firm, Fine Art Investments, gets a cut from the celebrity.<p>By taking the swap, the U.S. company is betting that the collection will benefit as the art market improves. Also, the art may fetch more than its assessed value if the works are sold one by one, rather than in a single auction. Some experts  ridicule the idea. "An outrageous concept," says Chicago dealer Paul Gray. Huffs William Grampp, author of Pricing the Priceless: "Anyone who tries to buy and sell art for profit should have his head examined."<p>But Stiles, who boasts a degree in econometrics and forecasting, is undaunted. Indeed, the former official for Christie's in London continues to develop a related investment idea -- his Art Securities Index, a sort of Dow Jones Industrial Average  for the art world.<p>The ASI, based on the share values of publicly traded art dealers and auction houses, is supposed to be a proxy for the health of the top 10 percent of the fine-art market. There have been other art-market indexes; Sotheby's published one from 1975  to 1992, for instance. But Stiles apparently is the first to encourage investors to bet on the direction of his index. Privately offered ASI options would help investors hedge big purchases, he says, or play the art market without getting paint on  their fingers.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Art Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
		<center>
