<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Package Dealer</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Package Dealer</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Seth Godin is an idea man, both on-line and off.<p>By Dean Robinson<p>WHO HE IS: Seth Godin, idea packager.<p>HIS OUTLETS: Books and on-line computer games.<p>WHAT IS IDEA PACKAGING, ANYWAY? Figuring out what people will buy, then persuading someone to sell it. "It's similar to producing movies."<p>WELL, MAYBE NOT HOLLYWOOD MOVIES: Examples of Godin's handiwork include "Professor Barndt's On-the-Spot Stain Removal Guide"; a popular on-line trivia game called Guts; and "The Postcard Activist", booklets of ready-to-mail postcards.<p>WHY HE BECAME AN IDEA PACKAGER: "Fifty thousand times a year, book publishers buy an idea from someone." Why not from him?<p>HIS FIRST BOOK DEAL: "Business Rules of Thumb."<p>SAMPLE RULE FROM "BUSINESS RULES OF THUMB": Never pick up the check if your lunch date outranks you. -- Pavloo Loupakis, Greek shipping magnate.<p>GODIN'S BIGGEST SUCCESS SO FAR: A series of novels based on popular Nintendo games.<p>HOW WELL THEY DID: The best seller, "Ninja Gaiden," sold more than 300,000 copies at $3 each.<p>HOW TO NOVELIZE A VIDEO GAME: Pay neighborhood kids to figure out everything that happens in a game. Pay someone else to write a book from kids' discoveries. Collect royalties.<p>A RECENT COUP: "E-Mail Addresses of the Rich and Famous."<p>BIGGEST PROBLEM ON THAT PROJECT: Impostors and fakes. "We found three people who said they were Jerry Garcia."<p>OTHER GODIN BOOKS IN THE WORKS: "The Beardstown Ladies' Common-Sense Investment Guide," "The People Magazine Celebrity Almanac," "The Guerrilla Marketing Handbook."<p>AND IN THE ON-LINE WORLD: Ace in the Hole, a trivia game played via electronic mail. The winner gets a three-year lease on a Mazda Miata.<p>WHY HE PREFERS OLD-FASHIONED BOOKS, DESPITE FORAYS INTO COMPUTERDOM: They last longer, and "if you want to change the way America thinks about something, you do it in a book." <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Publishing Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
