	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Going, Going ...</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Threats of a baseball strike affect another national pastime -- rotisserie leagues.<p>By Kevin Caliendo<p>Ball teams and broadcasters aren't the only ones who spent summer scrambling to deal with the threat of a strike by Major League Baseball players. Well-known names from billionaire Bill Gates to rock star Meat Loaf were also maneuvering to avoid getting caught in the squeeze play.<p>That's because a strike, which at press time seemed likely to hit in late August or early September, could rock the $150 million industry that has grown up around "fantasy baseball." Over the past decade, the addictive pastime has spawned statistical services, magazines, a weekly newspaper -- even a pay-per-view television show.<p>In fantasy baseball, also called rotisserie-league baseball, participants match talent-scouting abilities by assembling imaginary teams made up of real major-league players. The concept was dreamed up in 1980 by a group of journalists hanging out at  New York's now-defunct Le Rotisserie Francaise.<p>Now that there's big money to be had, major companies such as <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a> are getting into the game. Gates's huge software concern began offering its Complete Baseball service with much fanfare in June. A mixture of history, stats, and daily updates  from an on-line service, Complete Baseball is nifty enough. But it came to market late -- halfway through the current season, when most rotisserie leagues were already well under way. Sales may be damped by the prospect of a truncated season, and  "if there were an extended strike, losses [on Complete Baseball] could be heavy," says product manager David Malcolm. <p>That would be an unusual defeat for Gates, hardly known for striking out.<p>Another big name with plenty on the line is Meat Loaf. Meat, as he's known, is a rotisserie-league junkie: He has participated in 30 leagues in the past three years, winning 20 of them. He's also been negotiating to buy a fantasy-baseball service to  which he has subscribed for four years -- Baseball Manager, offered on the Prodigy on-line service.<p>"I don't have a clue about what I'll do" if the players go out on strike, says Meat. "Fantasy leagues are my escape."<p>Also affected would be New York governor Mario Cuomo, a talented rotisserie player who would face an unaccustomed loss if the strike proceeds. By July, Cuomo's team was well out of contention in his fantasy league, says team co-owner Marty Steadman.  Cuomo and Steadman probably need a complete season if they're to catch up. But Cuomo has been "so busy with legislation and his reelection effort that he may not be too upset" by a poor showing, Steadman says.<p>Meanwhile, many small businesses -- particularly those that supply the statistics that fuel fantasy baseball -- may go belly-up in a strike. "Millons and millions of dollars could be lost in this industry," says Lew Fidler, president of the  Rotisserie League Baseball Association.<p>Fantasy-league customers are expected to ask for refunds in droves, fouling up stat companies' finances. John Kavanagh, a San Francisco lawyer who has written extensively on rotisserie baseball, says he'd advise small stats services to file for  bankruptcy so they don't get wiped out by litigation.<p>To be sure, some companies have emergency plans. The service Meat Loaf wants to buy, for example, will reuse stats from earlier in the season if there's a strike. STATS Inc., a big statistics provider that's part-owned by billionaire Paul Allen,  Gates's fellow Microsoft founder, plans to conduct make-believe games using stats from previous years. "The games will have everything from injuries to home runs," says director of marketing Ross Schaufelberger. TV's ESPN may even run highlights  that have been spliced together from old footage.<p>Other coping strategies range from the sensible -- asking rotisserie leaguers to "draft" players from the minor leagues -- to the unusual. One league, for instance, will ask participants to draft TV shows and follow the Nielsen ratings in lieu of  batting averages. "I bet Seinfeld goes in the first round," says John Hunt, who writes a Baseball Weekly column for rotisserie-league junkies.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Technology Industry, Sports Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

