<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Fixed-Income Investing</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Fixed-Income Investing</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Why the Bond Market is Breaking the Rules<p>By Gregory Millman<p>When the Federal Reserve raises short-term interest rates, as it began doing in February, long-term rates should come down. Why? Because such a move indicates the Fed is on the job fighting inflation -- a signal to investors that they can stop worrying about the value of their long-term investments.<p>Recently, however, investors haven't been following this script,. In the spring, when the Fed nudged up short-term interest rates, long-term rates surged and prices plunged.<p>An analysis at the Fed suggests a troubling explanation: Widespread use of derivatives may have made the bond market less likely to follow the rules of the past. If true, this is bad news for investors trying to gauge the direction of rates.<p>The Fed acknowledges that fears of inflation weren't entirely extinguished by its efforts to boost short-term rates earlier this year. But it also implicates investors who bought mortgage-backed securities -- often through mutual funds.<p>On the surface, mortgage-backed securities seem fairly innocuous. They are derivatives created by Wall Street firms by repackaging household mortgages. An investor buys the flow of interest and principal payments on a group of mortgages.<p>So how did these securities end up distorting bond prices? The Fed study notes that when interest rates began rising, homeowners stopped refinancing. This, in turn, meant that investors in mortgage-backed securities could count on a longer flow of interest and principal payments, which, in effect, turned these securities into longer-term instruments.<p>Money managers try to insure their investments against the risk created by rising interest rates. They do this by shorting bonds of a similar maturity. In this case, that meant that fund managers had to short longer-term Treasurys to balance the government-backed securities. That drove down the price of ten-year bonds and drove up long rates.<p>Patricia Mosser, the Fed economist who led the study, was surprised by the findings. If this one kind of derivative could have unexpectedly changed the shape of interest rates, what other surprises might lurk in the market? <p><p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Retirement Investing, Bond Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

