	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/09-Brand New Heavies</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/09-Brand New Heavies</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
For a corps of professional strikebreakers, it's not just a job -- it's an adventure.<p>By Vincent Coppola<p>Corporate cutbacks and activist unions have helped fuel a rise in labor disputes -- and a healthy business for Zipper Allen. That's too bad, because when Allen works, he's often a target for curses, rocks, and worse.<p>Allen is a sign of the times: a professional strikebreaker. The retired Green Beret sergeant major -- once known to labor leaders as Colonel Klink, real first name Howard -- is founder of Falcon Global, a Pennsylvania security firm that companies  use when things get rough. Falcon bases its business on Allen's talent for raising small armies from the 150 former Special Forces soldiers he says he keeps on call, not to mention numerous weight lifters, bouncers, and sundry other muscleheads -- including a 450-pound Samoan. "We're the outsiders everybody hates," Allen says. "You know what? We're willing to take it."<p>Allen and two other Vietnam vets founded Falcon in 1991; credit cards funded its first year. After handling a brutal coal-miners' strike in 1993, however, its business boomed. Since then, clients have included major corporations such as <a name="NYSE:TXT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11466"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Textron</b></a>,  Koppers Industries, and <a name="NYSE:K"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10841"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kellogg</b></a>.<p>Military discipline is crucial: Falcon employees are told not to break heads -- even if mightily provoked -- as they ensure scabs' safe passage through picket lines. Not that it'd be wrong, mind you; it'd just be bad publicity. "If you can't stand  to have some Teamster call your mama everything imaginable," says Allen, "don't get on that line."<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:TXT">Textron Inc.</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:K">Kellogg Company</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
