<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Yesterday's News</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Yesterday's News</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Used merchandise moves upmarket as stores promote a new take on old stuff.<p>By David Hochman<p>In stores all over the country, what's old is new again. Recycling has merged with retailing, and suddenly the used-goods market is growing like -- well, like there's no yesterday.<p>The new trend isn't about thrift shops or the established trade in things like old computers or compact discs. Instead, big-ticket items including office furniture, posh exercise equipment, children's toys and clothes, and wedding gowns are appearing in stores that look more like the <a name="NYSE:GPS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11469"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gap</b></a> than Goodwill.<p>Atop the wave is <a name="NASD:GBIZ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16366"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Grow Biz International</b></a>, which operates 540 used-merchandise stores under names including Play It Again Sports and Once Upon a Child. Grow Biz started in 1983 after founder Martha Morris couldn't find a place to sell her good-as-new backpack. "People love (this type of store) because you get great value without feeling you've stepped into a garage sale or a pawnshop," says Douglas Raymond, president of the Retail Advertising & Marketing Association.<p>"Recycling's no longer underground," agrees Mark Werts, a pioneer in the recent movement toward vintage clothing as high fashion. Werts's superchic American Rag now has seven locations around California and is planning to move east.<p>One word of warning with used goods, however. Some older models of cribs, exercise equipment, toys, and other products don't live up to the latest safety standards. If in doubt, call the Consumer Product Safety Commission at 800-638-2772. Old news isn't always good news.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

