<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Making a Name</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Making a Name</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Mario Gabelli's Couch Potato Fund adds some zip to mutual funds' staid image<p>By Dean Robinson<p>What's in a name? If it's the name of a mutual fund, usually not much: Most fund companies stick with boring combos of words such as growth and equity when naming their products. Let's praise Mario Gabelli, then, for livening things up with his <a name="FUND:CICPX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/CICPX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gabelli Global Interactive Couch Potato Fund</b></a>, a fund name that's both accurate and attention-getting.<p>The veteran money manager has a history of being daring with fund names. Last year the Securities and Exchange Commission forced Gabelli to change the name of his Six Plus Fund because it seemed to guarantee a rate of return. That's a mutual fund no-no. Undaunted, Gabelli tried to call his offering the Little Guy Fund. But the SEC nixed that too. "We're not very good on humor," says SEC spokesman John Heine. The former Six Plus is now called <a name="FUND:GABCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/GABCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gabelli ABC Fund</b></a>.<p>The SEC doesn't have many firm rules on fund names; regulations mostly concern things like mentioning United States or U.S. government in conjunction with words like insured and guaranteed. But the agency is uptight about false advertising. "Our concern is whether people are misled," says Heine. "If a name indicates something other than what's in a prospectus, it's a pretty serious problem."<p>Perhaps wary of such issues, Gabelli soft-pedals his new fund's humorous name. "We're not marketing people, we're investment people," he harrumphs defensively. The stand is a bit disingenuous: There's more than a little marketing to Gabelli's Couch Potato Fund, which invests in "information superhighway" companies. And Gabelli himself grabs plenty of customers just by dint of his name, so he knows the power of image.<p>Still, most financial types aren't convinced that outre names are good for business. "There's a maxim in marketing," says Jack Trout of Trout & Ries, a marketing-strategy firm. "Don't get cute with money and drugs. People don't want to play around when it comes to money or their health." Gabelli has a stronger fan in Hrach Alexanian, research director at Morningstar, the mutual fund-watching company. "It's nice to see something funny," says Alexanian. Nonetheless, he frets that Gabelli customers might not see the humor: "People are very conservative when it comes to money. What's the probability that someone's going to invest in the I'm Going to Jump Off a Cliff Fund?"<p>Well, that depends: Is everyone else doing it?<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:CICPX">Gabelli Global Interactive Couch Potato Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:GABCX">Gabelli ABC Fund</a><br>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
