<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Happier Returns</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Happier Returns</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The IRS is targeted by lawmakers who want it to be -- gasp! -- nicer to taxpayers.<p>By David A. Andelman<p>The Internal Revenue Service may soon be getting friendlier to taxpayers -- whether it wants to or not.<p>Momentum is building for a proposed law officially known as Taxpayer Bill of Rights 2 but commonly called T2, in reference to the popular Arnold Schwarzenegger movie Terminator 2. Like that movie, T2 is a sequel: Six years ago, T1 gave taxpayers some fundamental rights that had never been recognized by the IRS -- paid ombudsmen to stand up for them, for example, and the right to sue the agency.<p>The IRS opposes T2, which would establish yet more basic rights the agency doesn't want written into law. The measure, sponsored by T1 author Senator David Pryor (D-Arkansas), would clear up some glitches in its predecessor. It would make T1's ombudsmen more powerful, for example, and have them report to a Taxpayer Advocate in Washington, D.C., instead of to the local IRS offices they police.<p>T2 also would require the IRS to reduce interest charges if it takes too long to find tax mistakes, and to pay taxpayers' legal fees whenever it loses a dispute in court. Pryor says he sees the changes as a kind of payback "at a time when we are asking the American taxpayer for contributions to reduce the deficit."<p>In the House, Representative James Traficant (D-Ohio) is pushing an even tougher bill that would force the IRS to consider taxpayers innocent until proven guilty. That's hardly a radical notion in criminal prosecutions, but the opposite is basically true in the IRS's civil prosecutions: Right now, the agency can seize property on its sole authority from taxpayers it judges have acted illegally. Then it's up to taxpayers to get their stuff back in court if they feel they've been wronged.<p>"Jeffrey Dahmer and the Son of Sam have more rights under the law than those accused of fraud under the IRS," says Traficant. Still, even supporters of the Traficant bill say the innocent-until-proven-guilty standard probably won't make it into law. "The tax courts are already pretty clogged up," says David Keating, executive vice president of the 250,000-member National Taxpayers Union. "Imagine if every audit case were made criminal." More likely, say most observers, a watered-down version of Traficant's bill may be melded with T2.<p>T2 is set to start moving forward this summer. It was vetoed two years ago by President Bush, but President Clinton is believed to be more sympathetic to the cause.<p>The IRS, meanwhile, doesn't think it needs any more legislation to do its job right. "We do believe in rights -- we're taxpayers, too," says a spokeswoman for the agency. "But quality customer service doesn't always mean getting what you want."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Taxation, Government Adgency, Politics

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
