<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/08-Byers Beware</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/08-Byers Beware</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
A telemarketing scammer shows why states want new powers.<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Roger Byers should be a popular guy: He loves to give people Hawaiian vacations and $5,000 credit lines. Instead, his activities in at least seven states are a prime example of why law officials are anxious for new legislation to combat telemarketing abuse.<p>Short, slim, fifty-something Byers is a felon and a serial scammer. He has been fined millions of dollars for deceptive schemes and has run afoul of the law since at least 1974, when he was convicted in Nevada for transporting stolen stock certificates. But Byers may still be telemarketing in dozens of states: Despite his record of rip-offs, authorities can't seem to shut him down.<p>The problem is simple. Individual states can bar Byers from doing business in their territory if he acts improperly there, but only a federal action would stop him nationwide. The FBI and other federal authorities, however, don't deal much with telemarketing scams. Such cases are usually small-scale and tough to prosecute. When toted up, however, these small cases cost consumers up to $40 billion a year -- and cause huge headaches for local law enforcers.<p>Dealing with telemarketers state by state isn't very efficient. Some schemes operate all over the country, but there's no system to tell local officials if a telemarketer has been banned in other places. Even if there were such a system, states couldn't use the information to bar known scammers unless local complaints started coming in.<p>In Roger Byers's case, the dilemma is plain. Companies controlled by Byers have been banned from certain activities in states from California to Nebraska to New Jersey. State officials say his standard telemarketing scheme involves offering a preapproved $5,000 credit line, even for folks with bad credit or no credit history. To learn more or to claim an award, consumers are told to call a phone number within 48 hours. According to judgments filed in numerous states, consumers end up paying for what they believe to be a widely accepted credit card, such as MasterCard or Visa. But the credit Byers provides can be used only to buy overpriced goods from a special catalog.<p>Through a Phoenix-based company dubbed North American Credit Card, Byers raked in nearly $1.4 million this way in 1991. His come-ons featured a Hawaiian vacation that turned out to be no luau. "You had to buy an incredibly expensive airline ticket to get it," says Hugh Hegyi, an assistant attorney general in Arizona. "Plus, you had to shell out money just to find that out. Byers is just a real jerk." Earlier this year, Arizona barred Byers and his son Donald from telemarketing there.<p>In Oklahoma, Byers recently was told to stop illegally soliciting business as North American Credit Card, USA Promotions, Continental Credit Card, and Dialing for Dollars. All four operations offered awards and preapproved credit lines. Says Jane Wheeler, chief of consumer protection in the state attorney general's office: "We hope he never comes back." So do California, Nebraska, and New Jersey, not to mention Maryland and Idaho -- all places Byers's companies have been barred from making misleading offers.<p>Byers's phone has been disconnected, and he couldn't be located for comment. His attorney in Arizona, where Byers owes more than $3 million for his most recent con, says he has no idea where his client went. Byers didn't pay fully for his defense, the lawyer adds. Byers's son Donald, who was also named in the Arizona scam but denies any wrongdoing, is even terser: "I don't know where my father is. Don't ever call here again."<p>If the past is any guide, Byers may now be setting up yet another telemarketing business in a state where he hasn't been banned. Such a move would be perfectly legal -- until President Clinton signs some legislation that state officials think could stop people like Roger Byers.<p>Versions of the proposed law have been passed by both houses of Congress; a final draft is being hashed out and stands a good chance of reaching the president's desk before the end of the year, says Emmitt Carlton, a spokesman for the National Association of Attorneys General. The measure would allow states to ban offending telemarketers nationwide, instead of just in their own territory. Meanwhile, a major crime bill would provide more federal funds to combat telemarketing scams.<p>"We definitely need tougher remedies," says James Jeffries, director of Wisconsin's Consumer Protection Agency. "You can't keep up with telemarketers like Byers if they can always just move on."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing, Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
