<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Power Player</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Power Player</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
As the blues become red hot, Joliet Joe's custom harmonicas are instrumental<p>By David Hochman<p>WHO HE IS: "Joliet Joe" Filisko, 27, whose brass- and gold-plated harmonicas are used by savvy harmonicists from the South Side of Chicago to the West Wing of the White House.<p>WHO HE'S UP AGAINST: Hohner USA, which pumps out more than 650 harmonicas an hour.<p>HOW JOE COMPARES: He turns out just one "harp" a day, charging from $125 to $165 apiece.<p>HOW MANY HE'S SOLD: About 800 in the past four years. He's so busy now that he takes orders only from professional musicians.<p>HOW JOE MAKES A HARP: He combines standard parts with custom-made parts to produce his souped-up product. "I think of it as transforming a Pontiac into a hot rod," he says.<p>ARE THERE MORE EXPENSIVE HARMONICAS? Yup -- Hohner sells a two-foot-long orchestral model for $1,295.<p>OWNERS OF JOE'S HARPS: President Clinton has a gold-plated model, complete with presidential seal. Then there's Kenny Loggins, Dan Aykroyd, and Chicago blues greats Charlie Musselwhite and Junior Wells. David Flack, a self-described "harmonopath" from Portland, Oregon, has bought 30.<p>WHY SUCH DEVOTION? Pucker-friendly round air holes, as opposed to Hohner's square ones. Handmade cover plates prevent air leakage. And Joe will custom-tune for anything from delicate jazz to raw blues to full-bodied country.<p>ANY DOWNSIDE? Filisko harps are three times as heavy as their competitors. But the pros actually like this heft: "It gives me a much bigger, warmer, fatter, fuller sound," says jazz harmonicist Howard Levy.<p>WHY THAT'S AN UNUSUAL COMPLIMENT: Levy has an endorsement deal with Hohner.<p>WHAT'S BEHIND THE BOOM IN HARMONICA PLAYING: "The more music is overrun by synthesized sounds, the more people hunger for authentic roots music," says Kim Field, author of Harmonicas, Harps, and Heavy Breathers. "Nothing's more authentic than harmonica playing."<p>A WORD OF WARNING: Playing too long can lead to harmonica player's hemoptysis, first cited in the case of an Australian harmonicist who coughed up blood after playing six hours straight.<p>HOW LONG JOLIET JOE PLAYS: "Eight hours straight many times, sometimes longer."<p>WHAT HE'S GOTTEN AS A RESULT: So far, just the blues.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

