<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Petty Cash</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Petty Cash</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
When it comes to inheritances, being treated like a dog may not be so bad.<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Be nice to rich old Aunt Edna's Pekingese: That pooch may soon have his paws on the family fortune.<p>The New York Bar Association is making it easier for every dog to have his day, offering guidelines for including animals in a will. Such authoritative advice hasn't been published before, says William Thomashower, who led the bar's effort. "A lawyer who never had a pet might not understand -- or might even laugh," he warns.<p>But the issue is serious. More than half the U.S. population owns a pet, and many people simply don't think ahead. The ASPCA in New York, for example, gets about 500 animals a year that have outlived their owners. "You don't have to leave your pet everything," says Kim Thornton, editor of Dog Fancy magazine, "but owners should make some provision."<p>In fact, nearly 27 percent of dog owners and 21 percent of cat owners already name their pet in a will, according to one survey. Bequests usually range from $20 a week to $10,000 a year -- although a few pets make out much better. Back in 1968, for example, oil heiress Eleanor Ritchey left $4.3 million to Auburn University for the care of her 150 dogs.<p>Pet bequests aren't simple matters. "You can't just leave a chunk of money to your dog," warns Thomashower. The number-one issue: Naming a caretaker. Then comes guesswork about appropriate amounts for feeding, grooming, medical care, and so on. Too confusing? Pet owners can also leave animals to Texas A&M University. For a $25,000 donation, the university will take care of any pet in a new building built just for the purpose. Only one cat and two dogs live there now, but director Sally Knight says 57 animals with still-living owners have been signed up.<p>Some other examples of well-provided-for pets:<p>-> Tinker, a Turkish Angora cat from Seattle, inherited about $500,000 from owner Anna Morgan last year. A trust pays for her $385-a-month apartment and a $10-a-day caretaker.<p>-> Mr. Pig and Calamity Jane, a hog and a German shepherd, were in the clover when their owner, Margo Lamp of Davenport, Iowa, left a 320-acre farm to support them in 1990. "Cammy" died soon after, but Mr. Pig thrived until last July. The property will eventually be sold to help fund a local humane society.<p>-> Lady, Lucky, and Princess needn't beg for bones. The mutts inherited about $300,000 from their owner, Floridian Raymond Falkenstein. All three have been adopted by different caretakers, but a thorny legal issue has yet to be resolved: Should the estate pay for care of Lucky's daughter, Beauty?<p>-> Damon and Pythias, long-haired Burmese cats, had reason to purr when New York millionaire Terry Krumholz left them her $750,000 Fifth Avenue apartment in 1991. But the siblings were evicted when the building enforced a no-pets policy. The cats resettled elsewhere, but fur is still flying as family members contest Krumholz's will. "We're not looking to cut the cats out," insists an attorney for the challengers.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Estate Planning

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
