<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Moe Money</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Moe Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Heirs of the Three Stooges slap each other with lawsuits but find little to nyuk about.<p>By Dean Robinson<p>The Three Stooges poked, punched, slapped, and nyukked their way into the pop-culture pantheon. Now, in the group's 60th anniversary year, the actors' descendants are putting on their own show: a nasty courtroom fight over who controls the Stooges' comic inheritance.<p>Even after death, Moe Howard is the Stooge with the upper hand. His grandson now controls all Stooge merchandising rights. But the heirs of Larry Fine and Joe DeRita -- who played Curly-Joe, successor to both Curly and Shemp Howard as "third Stooge" -- are trying to elbow into the picture, and Curly's heirs may also get involved. The stakes are high: If Columbia Pictures goes ahead with a planned Three Stooges movie, the disputed rights could mean millions for whoever is declared the winner.<p>This isn't the first time Stooge heirs have tangled, but it'll likely be the first case to go to trial. Earlier challenges pitted the estates of Curly and Shemp against their brother Moe but were settled out of court. The latest fracas involves claims by the heirs of Larry and Curly-Joe against Moe's daughter and grandson. In essence, Curly-Joe's widow and four of Larry's grandchildren say they've been shafted and want damages of "at least" $10 million from Moe's kin.<p>Jeffrey Scott, Moe's grandson and the linchpin of current Stooge licensing efforts, agrees the other Stooge heirs deserve some of the proceeds. But he says he's made the right payments to them all along, and angrily rejects the idea that he still owes big money to anyone. "It was a dead property" until recently, he says of Stooge licensing. "It wasn't generating a lot of money each year -- maybe $200,000."<p>That's possible. But the real payout will likely come from future licensing deals, not small-scale efforts such as the air fresheners and pillow cases now sold by Frank Reighter's mail-order Stoogestore or the limited-edition plate recently offered by the Franklin Mint. The true plums in Stoogedom are tie-ins with a new movie, which Scott has been helping develop since 1988.<p>"A Columbia movie would greatly increase the visibility of the Stooges," says Harry Ross, who operates Soitenly Stooges, another mail-order business. If the movie is a hit, Ross envisions Stoogemania sweeping stores and fast-food chains nationwide. "The best thing that could happen," he says, "is if McDonald's introduced Curly fries tomorrow." Scott agrees: "The movie is the Saturn V rocket that blasts the payload into space."<p>Scott, a prolific television writer who has won several Emmy awards, feels he's entitled to a healthy share of any rewards from a resurgence of Stooge popularity -- and for more than legal reasons. "I've been working my tail off for six years to turn the Stooges into something that could generate millions and millions of dollars," he says. "It hasn't happened yet, but I've made a movie deal. I've put together most of an animated-series deal. I sold a live stage show and a merchandising deal to the MGM Grand hotel in Las Vegas. I put together a deal to do new commercials." He believes the Larry/Curly-Joe camp is trying to cut him out of an industry he helped build.<p>But opposing attorney Bela Lugosi -- son of the horror-movie star and a celebrity licensing expert himself -- counters with a portrait of Moe Howard's legal maneuvers that's as full of slapstick as a Stooges routine. A prime example: Old letters and contracts that Scott says give him control of all Stooge rights. The documents actually grant Moe those rights; later contracts hand them to Scott's company.<p>In fact, Lugosi says, Moe wrote the earliest contracts himself -- and signed Curly's name himself, too. A later contract also has a questionable Curly signature, he adds; yet another isn't signed at all. In any case, Lugosi argues, the papers were supposed to make it easy for Moe, the lead Stooge on-screen and off, to negotiate for everyone -- not to sign away the other Stooges' rights forever.<p>Stooge watchers say the spat may have no real winners. For one thing, the Stooges movie isn't yet a sure thing -- especially since Scott sued Columbia last year over some development money that apparently is missing. News reports have talked of a possible link to the Heidi Fleiss affair, and Stooge infighting has further complicated matters for the star-crossed movie.<p>Scott says he's talking to Columbia about settling the missing-money suit but won't give details. Columbia also has no comment. Still, Scott insists that a Stooges movie will soitenly get made, "probably within the next year."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Estate Planning, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

