	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Investing:  My First Time</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Investing:  My First Time</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>INVESTING: MY FIRST TIME
Robert Lutz, 62, president of <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a><p>"In the early 1950s, with some money I got from my grandmother at the time of her death, I bought some shares of North American Aviation, which was later taken over by <a name="NYSE:ROK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11283"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Rockwell International</b></a>. I bought it because the Korean War was on and I was an airplane fanatic. NAA was selling F-86 Sabres -- jets that competed against the MiG-15. After I bought, the stock went up considerably. But as the war progressed, my father advised me to get out of NAA. I never knew why for sure, but I assumed he was right because he read every business and news publication. I sold, and I remember the price fell very shortly thereafter. My father isn't infallible, however. In 1968, when I was at <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors</b></a>, I bought a 1952 Citroen for $150 in France. My dad told me I should grow up -- that I should be buying GM shares instead. He said GM was the world's best corporation and that one share, which went for around $90, would soon be worth $200. Well, you know where GM stock has gone since then. My Citroen, on the other hand, is worth around $20,000."<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:C">Chrysler Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:ROK">Rockwell International Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:GM">General Motors Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

