<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-Explosive Charges</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-Explosive Charges</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
For fighting Pan Am 103 lawsuits, an insurer now faces a worse kind of claim <p>By Christopher Byron<p>After five and a half years, the terrorist bombing of Pan Am 103 may still have casualties to claim. Latest to feel pain from the disaster that killed 270 people: Insurance giant General Re, charged by a grand-jury witness with tolerating as much as $500 million in possible bombing-related fraud.<p>A lawyer for General Re says the company has no comment on the federal probe, about which few details are publicly known. So what's the inside scoop? A former employee has claimed that a General Re unit used false detective work to avoid paying the relatives of those who died on Flight 103 when it exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland.<p>In fact, in what may turn into a big headache for General Re, the whistleblower has implicated chairman Ronald Ferguson in the affair. This is bad news for a company that, for now at least, is one of the few bright spots in an industry battered by natural disasters such as the Midwestern floods and the Los Angeles earthquake.<p>Often referred to as the Tiffany of reinsurance, General Re underwrites the risks of other insurance companies. Despite a bleak 1994 for most insurers, with stock prices off by 10 percent so far, General Re has been rated a buy by analysts including Michael Frinquelli of Salomon Brothers. The company's profit is expected to rise healthily this year, Frinquelli says. But that's assuming management can stick to its knitting, which could be difficult if Ferguson and other General Re executives are distracted by a scandal.<p>The whistleblower story begins on a January day three years ago, at an extraordinary meeting in a General Re conference room. Among the attendees were Ferguson and the company's top in-house lawyer, Edmond Rondepierre, according to someone familiar with the events. The men came to hear from a former official at one of the firm's subsidiaries -- Robert Alpert, who had earlier resigned as head of claims for United States Aviation Underwriters. U.S. Aviation manages a pool of top insurance companies that provide coverage to the airline industry.<p>Alpert had asked for the meeting to inform top brass that he had quit because of what he thought was illegal behavior by U.S. Aviation in defending itself against more than 200 lawsuits related to Pan Am 103. As "lead" of more than 100 insurance companies at risk in the crash, U.S. Aviation could decide for everyone whether to pay the claims of the victims' relatives.<p>U.S. Aviation had been fighting these lawsuits in part because a private investigator had shown the Central Intelligence Agency to be involved in the bombing, something that might not be covered by its policies. But Alpert himself had hired the investigator in question -- and he believed the resulting report was worthless and false. (That conclusion has since been substantiated in the media and verified by the U.S government.) The claims chief became convinced that his higher-ups were using the false report as a convenient way to escape a liability that some news reports had said could go as high as $7 billion. Taking the advice of his lawyer, Alpert resigned in disgust.<p>The January showdown that resulted was no ordinary meeting. To ensure there would be no misunderstanding, Alpert prepared an astonishing method of presentation. As the meeting began, says someone familiar with what followed, Alpert sat stone silent in the boardroom and pressed the play button on a tape recorder. Amazed, Ferguson and Rondepierre listened as a prerecorded speech unspooled. Later, Alpert handed over transcripts of the tape.<p>But days turned into months, and U.S. Aviation continued to defend itself on what Alpert saw as highly questionable grounds -- even after a federal civil trial found that the company should pay what's now estimated will be $500 million in settlements. Eventually, Alpert was contacted by federal prosecutors. A grand jury was impaneled in New York and has been hearing evidence in the case for roughly a year. U.S. Aviation tried desperately to stop Alpert from testifying.<p>It failed. Earlier this year, a judge overseeing the grand jury rejected U.S. Aviation's argument that its communications with Alpert, a lawyer by training, were protected by attorney-client privilege. Now Alpert is a key witness in a probe that's the talk of the aviation-insurance industry.<p>Alpert and federal officials refuse to comment on his testimony, which isn't public. The grand jury already has indicted someone who helped U.S. Aviation develop its "the CIA did it" defense. A source familiar with the investigation says further indictments are likely in the autumn.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry, Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
