<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/06-100 Grand</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/06-100 Grand</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						June 1994
Worth magazine/Outfront<p>100 GRAND<p>The challenge: Blow a tax-free windfall of $100,000 -- imaginary, we're afraid -- on five items. This month we tapped three people famous for their love of being quoted. As we had hoped, all three returned our calls promptly. Larry Sabato is the author of Feeding Frenzy, a critique of journalism. Norman Ornstein is a resident scholar at the American Enterprise Institute and has been a commentator on Comedy Central. Besides getting Claus von Bulow off the hook, lawyer Alan Dershowitz has appeared on every talk show in existence.
---------------<p>LARRY SABATO<p>-> $15,000 to hire a part-time cook "to make me one really good, healthy meal a day. All I eat now is junk food."<p>-> $40,000 as seed money for a foundation that would fight cynicism about politics.<p>-> $25,000 to establish a scholarship fund, named for his parents, at the University of Virginia, where he teaches.<p>-> $19,000 to publish a third edition of his book, Feeding Frenzy. "It makes a great holiday gift."<p>-> $1,000 to put in cattle futures so he'll have another $100,000 to blow.<p><p>NORMAN ORNSTEIN<p>-> $20,000 to buy Prozac for Rush Limbaugh, Ralph Nader, and other excitable types in the media.<p>-> $30,000 to provide civics texts to every reporter and editor involved in covering Washington, D.C.<p>-> $30,000 to help create a visitors' education center in Congress.<p>-> $10,000 to buy great season tickets at Baltimore's Camden Yards so he and his sons can watch the O's win the pennant.<p>-> $10,000 to Brian Lamb, president of C-SPAN, "just for being Brian Lamb."<p><p>ALAN DERSHOWITZ<p>-> $25,000 as a reward for anybody with evidence that would save the life of an inmate on death row.<p>-> $20,000 to start a censorship watch on college campuses that would "expose the absurd excesses of the politically correct."<p>-> $10,000 to attend a fantasy camp for basketball players under six feet tall.<p>-> $20,000 to a program that would buy back guns from young kids.<p>-> $25,000 to help finance his son Elon's next movie. (Elon coproduced Reversal of Fortune.) <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

