	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-The Golden Girl</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-The Golden Girl</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
After losing a bundle, Frances Lear tries again--as a financial advisor, naturally on video<p>By Dana Dickey<p>Frances lear has hardly proved herself an astute investor: Lear's, the women's magazine she founded with her $100 million divorce settlement from sitcom magnate Norman Lear, closed in March after anemic ad sales, a staff exodus, and losses estimated at up to $50 million.<p>So what's the Chanel-suited 70-year-old doing hawking her financial tips in a new videotape aimed at women? Well, she describes the effort as a "magical collaboration" with Peter Foley, 35, her former chauffeur and current lover--a sandy-haired would-be filmmaker who has kept a picture of actor Mickey Rourke on the wall of his office. ("I just admire his talents," he says.)<p>Although Lear is spending $500,000 on the videotape, called Take Control of Your Money, the venture is largely a family affair. Foley, the tape's producer, spent a summer studying film but has scant experience as a senior producer. Foley's line producer is his sister Elizabeth Foley, a Columbia University film student, and his aunt, Mary Scanlan, is a project publicist.<p>On the financial-advice side, Lear is depending on Harry Browne, an iconoclastic newsletter publisher she's admired for 20 years. But according to Hulbert Financial Digest, Browne's recommendations have underperformed the Standard & Poor's 500 index by more than 50 percent over the last eight years--albeit at a relatively low level of risk. At least Lear has kept her sense of humor: She also hired Anne Elder, a comedy writer from Los Angeles, to add a witty edge to the video.<p>In the 90-minute tape, expect to see Lear leading a discussion group of seven women, aged from their mid-20s to late 50s. Talk about finances will be intercut with segments that follow these women in their workaday lives. "I talked to lots of women--professionals and women entering the work force--and no one had any idea what to do with their money," Lear says. "Everybody said, 'Please help.' "
Thus guru Browne will pop up throughout the tape, outlining his cautious philosophy. Without using a stockbroker, women are counseled to shoot for a 10 percent annual return from a "permanent portfolio" of equal parts gold, mutual funds, money market funds, and long-term bonds. "They will always carry you through," says producer Foley, who admits ignorance in money matters and says he hasn't had savings until recently.<p>Browne's own version of the strategy, meanwhile, has yielded an 8.2 percent annualized return over the past five years. Some experts criticize his advice--particularly the idea of keeping a quarter of your portfolio tied up in gold, no matter what the market's doing or how old an investor is. "Certainly not a position that Wall Street would traditionally embrace," says James Stack, president of InvesTech Research, a financial-research firm.<p>Until it failed, Lear had said she intended to turn Lear's, where this reporter worked until 1991, into a women's financial journal. But her interest in the magazine was waning, many staffers say, and its demise was expected. She'll be touting her new project in TV infomercials and ads in women's magazines. But not, alas, in the magazine that carried her name.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

