	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Selling the Cellar</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Selling the Cellar</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
An oenophile sours on the grape and gives his life over to Jesus instead.<p>By John Anderson<p>Who he is:  Marvin C. Overton III, part-time neurosurgeon, full-time gospel evangelist--and, until recently, star of the fine-wine circuit.<p>What he's like:  A classic Texas cowboy, tall and garrulous, raised on ranches and oil rigs. His outsize character comes through even in his wine jottings: "This wine is a suave devil!"<p>What he's famous for:  His collection, especially his Bordeaux wines. "One of the largest, most eclectic, and best-assembled private collections anywhere," says Clive Coates, a noted wine writer.
and of course: The celebrated Overton Tastings, at which fellow oenophiles would quaff hundreds of his precious vintages.<p>What's in his cellar now:  Nothing. He sold the lot in recent auctions at Christie's and Butterfield & Butterfield.<p>Why he abandoned wine:  "I didn't need it anymore."<p>What prompted all this:  In 1992, Overton was told he had cancer and might have only months to live.<p>His response:  He demanded new tests, telling doctors: "Those tests are lying. The Lord is not ready for me to go--I'm a fighter for Jesus."<p>The new results:  No cancer. "I told 'em so."<p>How he reacted:  "I needed to weed out all the inessential things in my life, and wine was one of them."<p>His farewell tour:  A five-city series of blowout tastings. "A masterpiece," raves wine consultant Dennis Foley.<p>His take on wine now: "Oh, I'll have a glass now and then. I still love wine, but I love Jesus more."<p>What he does with the extra time: "Preach the healing, cleansing message of Jesus' love. Say, have you pardnered up with Jesus?"<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
