		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Idea Man</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Devon Jackson<p>Who he is:  Carl Person, 57, the attorney behind a wave of theft-of-idea suits against Hollywood studios.<p>His background:  High school dropout and 1962 Harvard Law grad. Holds patent on a gizmo designed to catch flies alive.<p>Claims to fame:  First lawyer to sue for right to advertise. Helped develop the paralegal profession by founding the Paralegal Institute. Created a private court system that never took off. Won the right to sell shares in lawsuits, another fizzled idea.<p>Other notable facts:  Is suing the pope for $120 million on behalf of an ex-priest seeking restitution for his years of service.<p>His self-image:  An economist who acts on convictions.<p>His latest conviction:  That theft-of-idea litigation can catch on if it's marketed well. "That's what we're selling."<p>Why he's targeting Hollywood:  He hates monopolies. In fact, he's even sued the maker of the Monopoly board game.<p>How theft-of-idea works:  Client claims a studio developed a movie from an idea the client submitted but was never paid for.<p>Movies he's suing over:  New Jack City, Regarding Henry, Coming to America, Sister Act, and Philadelphia.<p>What he's suing for:  From $48 million (New Jack City) to $420 million (Coming to America). He gets 50 percent if he wins.<p>What Hollywood thinks of all this:  "Meritless," says Paramount (Coming to America, Regarding Henry). "No substance," says Disney (Sister Act).<p>How he's getting into movies:  He produced an unreleased film, Ramblin' Gal, directed by his wife, Lu Ann.<p>How you should get into movies:  "Submit your idea to a thief, hope they steal it, then call me." <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
