<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/05-Final Notice</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-Final Notice</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
John Jordan stole to keep his dream alive. When it died anyway, he got drastic.<p>By Vincent Coppola<p>If you've ever bought merchandise via those glossy inserts stuffed into credit-card statements, you've helped fund a $300 million industry that's got more in common with blackjack than with catalog shopping.<p>Industry leader John Jordan, however, turned "merchandise syndication" into another, deadlier gambler's game: Russian roulette.<p>A silky-smooth Atlanta entrepreneur, Jordan sent out more than 100 million solicitations a year, building his import operation into a $50 million house of cards called Jordan Concepts. Slender and engagingly polite, he made his money flogging electronics, jewelry, and other gewgaws in credit-card mailings from Montgomery Ward and other issuers.<p>Even in good times, statement stuffing is a loser's game. A hefty 15 to 20 percent of revenue goes to the card issuer, while the stuffer must carry huge upfront costs for printing and shipping. Cash may not start flowing until three months after orders are placed. And all the while another warehouse full of steak knives sits waiting to be moved.<p>But these are not good times for stuffers. Since the late 1980s, sales have slumped while costs and competition have risen. And response rates keep tumbling--from a heady 6 percent back in the 1960s to just a fraction of 1 percent today. Says E. James Kearney of Chicago-based Eire Partners, one of the players that now control the industry:"The heyday is over. The business is dying."<p>Jordan Concepts, meanwhile, is already dead, quietly liquidated by Chase Manhattan, its main financier, after the embarrassed bankers realized Jordan had defrauded them out of nearly $24 million. But the tale behind that fraud, so convoluted it took investigators three years to unravel, lingers as a reminder of the high-pressure world behind every cheesy opal-ring solicitation.<p>Curiously, the evidence suggests Jordan possessed a perverse integrity. He didn't take any money for himself; everything he stole seems to have gone into Jordan Concepts and, eventually, down the drain. "He was brilliant,"says Miami accountant Stanley Foodman, who lost $140,000 he put into a separate Jordan venture. "Too bad he didn't use his brains for a better purpose."<p>Because of their lousy cash flow, merchandise syndicators live on credit lines that are secured by their receivables--the money they've already earned but haven't yet gotten. As Jordan's sales tumbled along with the industry in 1987, he was caught in a massive credit crunch.<p>His solution was that of an addicted gambler:Invent $12 million in receivables to keep the credit flowing from <a name="NYSE:CMB"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10322"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chase Manhattan</b></a>, then plow the borrowed money into more mailings. "Sales cures all" became Jordan's mantra, then his prayer. "This was a man who could not separate himself from his business," says Bryan Farrell, the assistant U.S. attorney who prosecuted Jordan.<p>Jordan's high rolling unnerved both colleagues and competitors. "I was cutting back, and this guy is placing business all over the place," recalls Kearney. It also rang alarm bells. In March 1990, Chase Manhattan finally became suspicious and sent a team of auditors to Atlanta.<p>Jordan was ready:With a household intercom he bought at Radio Shack, he bugged the conference room the auditors used so he could learn what documents would be examined. Then he set about creating a false paper trail, preparing fake cancelled checks, banks statements, and dozens of other business forms. Jordan even made call-forwarding arrangements in other cities, just in case the auditors phoned his partners and vendors--the calls would have bounced back to Atlanta, where his assistant Donna Crabtree waited with a prepared script. (Crabtree pleaded guilty to one count of bank fraud for her role in the scheme.)<p>"For 16 days the auditors grill him," says Donald Samuel, Jordan's attorney. "He fools everyone." Satisfied, Chase advanced another $1 million. But Jordan's dreams kept withering in mailboxes around America. After another few months and no miraculous sales boom, two of his senior financial officials cut a deal with the government, agreeing to testify against their boss in return for immunity.<p>The game drew to a close three years later. After investigators laid bare his scheme in federal court, Jordan was convicted this February on nine counts of fraud and conspiracy. When he failed to show for the verdict, his lawyers figured he'd fled the country.<p>Instead, facing eight to ten years in prison, Jordan had chosen a far harsher penalty. On a red clay field behind a local Holiday Inn, he put a pistol in his mouth and a .38-caliber bullet in his head. A maintenance man found a written apology next to his body. Even the prosecution was shocked.<p>"This was a guy who thought he could overcome anything," says Farrell. "We take no pleasure in this. We're here to achieve some kind of justice. Nothing more."<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/3pages.gif"><br>About 3 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:CMB">The Chase Manhattan Corporation</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
