	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/05-100 Grand</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>The challenge: Blow a tax-free windfall of $100,000--imaginary, we're afraid--on five items. Our players this month are from the world of cartooning. Ben Katchor's weekly strip, Julius Knipl, Real Estate Photographer, now runs in the Village Voice and is syndicated in ten cities. Robert L. Washington III and John Paul Leon are the team behind Static, the newest superhero title from Milestone Comics. Bill Plympton's work has appeared in many magazines; he's currently working on MTV's Liquid Television.<p>BEN KATCHOR
$50,000 for round-the-world cruise with wife Susan aboard an Italian container ship. 
$10,000 on account at Noodle Town in Chinatown, New York.
$10,000 to attend a convention of the British Matchbox Label Society in London.
$25,000 to help start a kosher dairy restaurant across from New York's Public Library. "One was there years ago."
$5,000 to the Association for the Improvement of Newspaper Comic Strips--or to help revive it if it's defunct. "They tried to make strips better for kids in the 1920s."<p>ROBERT L. WASHINGTON III and JOHN PAUL LEON
$50,000 for a pre-Gutenberg edition of Dante's Inferno (RLW) and a painting by 19th-century illustrator N.C. Wyatt. (JPL)
$20,000 to visit pivotal historic sites--"Egypt, Greece, the Middle East, China, West Africa, Mayan sites, and Disneyland." (RLW)
$10,000 on a historical wardrobe for use by studio models. (JPL)
    $10,000 to rent Shea Stadium and a pitching machine for an afternoon. (JPL)
$10,000 to support a social center for the homeless. (RLW)<p>BILL PLYMPTON
$50,000 to buy a cable channel called PlympTV. "Everyone will have their own channel soon--but I'll be ahead of the game."
$29,500 to hire two sumo wrestlers to smash into each other at the end of each cartoon on the new channel--"a human applause machine of sorts."
    $10,000 for Hillary Rodham Clinton to do a hula dance on PlympTV.
$10,000 for Tipper Gore to sing "that rap classic, 'Big Butt, Yeah.' "
$500 to hire Chevy Chase as emcee for PlympTV.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

