<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Shoot the Moon</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Shoot the Moon</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Coming soon to a virtual-reality theater near you: The original vast wasteland<p>By Jim Melloan<p>Like to pilot a lunar rover around the site where Neil Armstrong first set foot on the moon? In 1997 you could get a chance, if the first commercial moon landing goes as planned.<p>Indeed, such just-for-fun gimmicks may fuel the next great space mission, which will likely show up on pay-per-view television. A new company, International Space Enterprises, has hooked up for the task with Russia's Lavochkin Association, which built most of the former Soviet Union's spacecraft. The team's implausible goal: To make seven unmanned lunar landings by 2000, helped by agreements with film studios and a major theme park.<p>ISE envisions mapping and filming the lunar surface to enable virtual-reality simulations of the moon for games and theater attractions. The company won't name most of its partners, which makes its chances hard to assess. But experts agree with John Pike, a space-policy analyst with the Federation of American Scientists who was initially dubious but now says there's no "giggle factor."<p>Adding credibility is the involvement of robot guru Red Whittaker, who's designing a lunar rover for a company called LunaCorp that plans to hitch a ride on ISE's first outing to the moon. (First stop: The Apollo 11 site.) A mission into an Alaskan volcano this summer will showcase Whittaker's progress, and LunaCorp will be trying to tempt sponsors with the notion of a contest offering the chance to drive the rover around the moon for an hour--by remote control, natch.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry, Technology Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
