				<font size=6><b>94/04-Real Estate Shake-Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>
Real estate markets in other western cities are cashing in on the Los Angeles earthquake, as Angelenos flee riots and recession in search of cheap homes and firmer ground. "The first weekend after the quake we had 60 visitors from Southern California--and 15 sales," says Anne Mariucci, president of a housing community near Phoenix. "Before that we had no sales to Californians." The pattern was repeated in Denver, Las Vegas, Salt Lake City, and Portland, Oregon.  "I've joked that whenever there's a disaster in California, business goes through the roof," says Steve Slabaugh, a real estate executive in Lake Oswego, near Portland. "But the day after the quake, our phone rang off the hook."<p>

					</font>
