	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Old Teams Go an Extra Inning</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Kevin Caliendo<p>Now that members of the 1969 Miracle Mets baseball team have licensed a line of diapers, among other gewgaws, the marketing of bygone teams is poised to become big business. Already, members of other legendary lineups have asked the '69 Mets for advice. Among them: Pitcher Vida Blue of baseball's 1972--1974 Oakland A's and linebacker Harry Carson of football's 1986 New York Giants. With so many old-timers touting memorabilia, team-level promotion was inevitable, says Stephen Hisler, president of the marketing firm National Pastime. His pick for the dream team of yore: The 1980 U.S. Olympic hockey squad. Mike Eruzione, who was the captain of the fateful team, says the Olympians "would love to" market themselves. Brian Murphy, publisher of Sports Marketing Letter, says many old teams could do well, including the 1985 Chicago Bears football team and the Cincinnati Reds of the 1970s, baseball's Big Red Machine. Cal Levy, an agent for several old Cincinnati players, including Johnny Bench, Pete Rose, and Joe Morgan, agrees. But he notes a major snag: "We can't do anything until Pete Rose [who's banned from all baseball-related activity] is reinstated."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Sports Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
