<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-No Peeking Please</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-No Peeking Please</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
A proposed law on privacy is riling big business, which wants the right to watch<p>By David A. Andelman<p>Big business grabbed headlines recently by opposing the government's plan to mandate "trap doors" in many electronic devices so the feds could eavesdrop on communications. But what of business's own penchant for electronic spying?<p>Ironically, corporate lobbyists are fighting fiercely to protect companies' right to monitor their own employees and, in some cases, their customers. Battle lines are forming over a bill sponsored by Senator Paul Simon of Illinois that attempts to set limits on electronic snooping in the workplace. The main concern: Technology that allows employers to watch over every move made by a worker--from listening in on phone calls to counting the number of keystrokes by typists.<p>"In some industries, employees are tied to their desks via their computer and phone system," says Kristina Zahorik, a Simon aide. "Everything they do is recorded. They can't even get up from their computers to go to the bathroom --if they do, they can get docked pay or lose their jobs."<p>But opponents see the Simon bill as another ill-advised attempt by Congress to micromanage business. "If I'm paying people to get a job done, I should have the right to know what they're doing," says Larry Fineran, a top lobbyist for the National Association of Manufacturers.<p>The proposed legislation wouldn't ban electronic monitoring completely. But it would require employers to warn workers when snooping will take place--or to be able to prove "reasonable suspicion" for unannounced spying. Big companies say that's overkill: Monitoring is simply a high-tech version of the old-fashioned supervisor, they argue.<p>The securities industry gets special treatment in Simon's measure, since most of its electronic and voice interactions are policed by Securities and Exchange Commission rules--allowing for a record of trades, for example. Still, the Securities Industry Association opposes key provisions of the bill.<p>"It's too sweeping," says Kristin Hofeditz, manager of securities legislation for the SIA. "If electronic monitoring is a tool of harassment, that's a problem. But in our industry, it's used to protect our customers, our investors." Hofeditz says the measure would stop the SEC from using electronic records to investigate market irregularities unless it got a warrant--"a step backward," she claims.<p>But the bill's advocates, including the American Civil Liberties Union, say the proposed protection for workers, as well as for consumers whose conversations may be monitored without their knowledge, is invaluable.<p>The measure's sponsor in the House of Representatives is Montana congressman Pat Williams, who previously shepherded into law an anti-polygraph bill that limits the use of lie detectors at work.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
