	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-His New Vehicle</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>Lee Iacocca brings Broadway to Branson, a town that's country music to his ears <p>By Jonathan Burton<p>Lee Iacocca has finally found the stage he's sought since stepping down as chairman of <a name="NYSE:C"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10334"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Chrysler</b></a> in December 1992. And it's right in the heartland that embraced his trademark folksy pitches and no-nonsense prose.<p>After fielding dozens of business proposals, the 69-year-old Iacocca is betting that the next great American industry will be country music and that Branson, Missouri, will be its Detroit. Once again, Iacocca will have the spotlight he loves--but this time, he'll pay for it to shine on a Branson production of The Will Rogers Follies, the hit Broadway musical.<p>Iacocca is a major partner in the new staging of the Rogers show, which is slated to open this month. And he's investing in a Branson real estate project that will include a convention center and shopping mall. The town also has attracted Iacocca's new investment company, Iacocca Capital Partners. The firm has consulted with Iacocca about Branson--and is scoping out opportunities for itself there. Iacocca predicts his interest in the town won't be "a flash in the pan."<p>That goes double for Branson itself. The small Ozarks town, full of country-music theaters, has tapped a potent mix of glitz and family values to become the nation's number-two destination for driving vacations. Iacocca was originally just one of five million tourists who pour into Branson each year. He was awed by a five-mile traffic jam and originally agreed to head Branson Airlines, a proposed solution to the area's traffic woes.<p>But then the business icon took in a Wayne Newton show and realized that if Vegas could be reborn in the Ozarks, so could Broadway. He rounded up partners and soon was back in business with a homespun spectacle that echoes the values he sold in Chrysler ads and in his bestselling books. Will Rogers himself, another showman-cum-capitalist, would approve.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Enterntainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
