	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Getting Shelved</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Getting Shelved</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>After losing control of Paramount, Davis also fails to snag a writer for his book<p>By Robert S. Boynton<p>Martin Davis, Paramount's ill-tempered chairman, dreamed of publishing a blockbuster book about his career and its crowning achievement--the smooth merger of Paramount and Viacom. But when rival Barry Diller and his QVC Network appeared as spoilers, Davis's literary ambitions, like so many of his plans, became a footnote.<p>The Paramount boss didn't just lose control of his own fate in the much-publicized takeover spat that followed. He also failed to corral the famous writer he had targeted as his Boswell: Bryan Burrough, coauthor of Barbarians at the Gate, the best-selling account of the battle over <a name="NYSE:RN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13122"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>RJR-Nabisco</b></a>.<p>Davis, 67, had figured to spin history by cooperating with Burrough on a definitive book. To woo the writer, he gave Burrough extraordinary behind-the-scenes access--only to discover that the story became a morass soon after Diller's QVC launched its unwelcome bid for Paramount. Burrough emptied his notebook into a none-too-flattering Vanity Fair piece but ultimately decided not to write a book. (Davis, in turn, says he decided not to cooperate after all.)<p>Burrough says he had been fascinated by the cast of oversize egos. But when lawyers and mutual fund managers started dominating the fight, he lost interest: "I've done that already." Another factor was that Burrough and his agent, Andrew Wylie, failed in their attempt to sell publishers on a $1 million package of book and movie rights. Burrough had reportedly received that sum for his last book, Vendetta--a resounding dud.<p>Meanwhile, Davis had lost his early edge in the best-seller stakes. Other prospective authors were eyeing the Paramount-Viacom-QVC fight: Ken Auletta, media critic for The New Yorker; a Wall Street Journal team led by Laura Landro; a Variety team; and Geraldine Fabrikant and Bernard Weinraub at the New York Times.<p>Most of these eventually dropped out as even hardened business buffs got sick of hearing about Paramount. Nonetheless, a Davis spokesman says his boss is still interested in writing a book. With someone else running his company, he'll certainly have enough free time.<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
