<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/04-Feds Nix Flix Tax Trix</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/04-Feds Nix Flix Tax Trix</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>A tough IRS task force will be the next disaster to shake up Hollywood stars<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Should a starlet be allowed to deduct her designer threads on her tax return this month? Can a box-office hunk justify his daily massages as a professional expense? <p>Not much longer: The Internal Revenue Service has lost patience with such Tinsel Town tax dodges. This tax season marks the first outing for an IRS task force that spent 18 months preparing to take on Hollywood--in part, by having agents take movie-accounting seminars and even film classes at UCLA. "We're ready to put our book smarts to use," says agent Randy Perrin.<p>Of the 30,000 returns expected from the entertainment industry this month, 3,000 will be screened for possible audits; usually only 1 percent of returns get such attention. Entertainers are worried. "If the IRS were going after Sylvester Stallone for deducting a personal trainer, that'd be unfair," says Bruce Stiglitz of the law firm Loeb & Loeb, which represents stars such as Frank Sinatra and Diana Ross. "For someone like Danny DeVito, maybe they'd be right."<p>But IRS agents say many tax evaders think anything can be deducted as a business expense in La La Land. Face-lifts, hair appointments, even cocaine purchases--all are deductions the IRS has seen and won't tolerate. The task force also hopes to kill a longtime bugbear: "loan-out corporations," set up by stars to collect fees, handle contracts, and receive salaries. The task force believes many loan-outs exist solely to avoid taxes or establish tax-favored pension plans and shouldn't be allowed. "They know that's where the pot of gold lies," says tax lawyer Eugene Veenhuis of Mitchell, Silberberg & Knupp, whose clients include Jack Nicholson and Paul Newman.<p>Veenhuis and others think banning loan-outs would boost IRS revenue a lot--hundreds of millions of dollars, by some estimates. That'll take years to happen, but individual players will feel the pinch sooner: The task force already is sending out 300 audit notices a month.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government Adgency, Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
