<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Seize and Desist</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Seize and Desist</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
The Securities industry cracks down on bad brokers by targeting their property.<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>After victimizing their clients, many crooked stock brokers proceed to stiff the securities industry too--by failing to pay fines levied against them by the National Association of Securities Dealers.<p>But that may change as the NASD, the self-policing body for the over-the-counter brokerage business, experiments with hardball tactics more familiar to villains who cross the Internal Revenue Service or the Drug Enforcement Agency. In a pilot program, the NASDhas been trying to seize the cars and boats of brokers who won't pay up.<p>NASD hired a credit-rating service to check into the personal finances of brokers and brokerage executives. By zeroing in on deadbeats with substantial assets and asking that their property be seized, the NASD is hoping to win legal precedents for its approach--and gain a measure of revenge for ripped-off customers.<p>NASD compliance chief John Pinto says it's too early to judge whether the program has been a success, but he's hoping the action sends a get-tough message. "If bad brokers are fined, that's an obligation that will follow them wherever they go," he promises.<p>Perhaps, but that's hardly true at the moment. As little as a tenth of bad-broker fines have been collected in recent years, partly because brokers have little incentive to pay up if they've already been barred from the business. Last year's performance was a bit better--but only because of two blockbuster cases against Equitable Life and Prudential Securities, both of which paid their fines promptly.<p>And despite the new enforcement push, collections aren't expected to skyrocket in 1994. The majority of deadbeat brokers "just disappear," Pinto admits.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Ethical Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
