<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Numbers Game</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Numbers Game</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Most telethon tote boards count a lot more than viewers' phone pledges<p>By Carla Koehl<p>Will pat boone be misleading us again on March 5 and 6? Well, yes.<p>Trusting telethon viewers may think the crooner's Easter Seals tote board merely tallies phone pledges as they roll in. Not so: Most of the total is safe in the charity's coffers long before the show begins. A whopping 84 percent of last year's $47.7 million came from corporate contributions and fund-raising events held over the entire previous year, concedes Easter Seals president James Williams. Those funds were gradually added to the tote.<p>Watchers of the heartrending telethon, however, are encouraged to believe something else. Hosts such as Robb Weller hardly ever mention that the rising numbers have little to do with the viewers they beseech to make that pledge. A true tote would start at $40 million and rise far more slowly--or start at zero and struggle to reach $8 million. Curiously, last year's board debuted at $33,236 and jumped quickly to $1.7 million. Over applause Boone hastily explained that "so much of that is the corporate sponsorship."<p>But if you missed that mention, too bad. It was just about the only caveat in the 21-hour show, says an Easter Seals spokeswoman. "We don't want to discourage people from giving $5 and $10 pledges," she explains.<p>The practice is commonly used to build excitement at telethons. The United Cerebral Palsy telethon does it, for example: Only an estimated one third of last year's total of $24 million came from phone pledges. The United Negro College Fund also includes other fund-raising in its telethon tallies but declines to give details on the $11 million raised this January.<p>Experts on charity don't object. Says a spokesman for the National Charities Information Bureau: "If you start off by saying, 'We've already achieved half our goal, but stick around for the entertainment,' you wouldn't get too many viewers." So the pumped-up tote boards are now legion. Take the Children's Miracle Network, which trumpeted a huge $116.9 million total on its 1993 telethon tote board. A spokesman says the number was "a culmination of the year's efforts" but declines to break down the total exactly.<p>Jerry Lewis doesn't do much better: Of the $46 million tally from his last Labor Day telethon for the Muscular Dystrophy Association, just 35 percent came from phone pledges. The remainder was from direct-mail appeals and fund-raisers held that weekend.<p>"It's true, the perception is that all telethon money is coming in from pledges," says Kay Hollings, associate executive director of the national United Cerebral Palsy group. "That's partly because the hosts mention it only once in a great while. They think the audience is a standing army; it's really just a passing parade."<p><p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
