<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Impure Plays</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Impure Plays</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Mutual funds lose their apple-pie image as scandals hit Invesco and Fidelity<p>By Jonathan Burton<p>While scandals have rocked Wall Street and the banking industry, the mutual fund industry has remained largely crisis-free. Until now.
Internal probes at two big fund companies have suddenly brought the business face-to-face with its worst nightmare--a muddy scandal that could scare away small investors. Regulators are nosing through reports that portfolio managers at both Invesco Funds Group and Fidelity Investments made dubious deals for themselves in stocks they were also buying for fund shareholders.<p>A venture-capital unit of Fidelity owns Capital Publishing, Worth's parent.<p>Besides hurting both firms, the charges are a reminder that this fast-growing business hasn't yet developed widely accepted ethics guidelines. And they're a black mark for an industry that portrays itself as better than its shark-like counterparts in brokerages, banks, and insurance companies.<p>Investment professionals say the mutual fund troubles may be partly explained by the industry's explosive growth. Fund assets swelled to $1.4 trillion last November, from $568 million at the end of 1990, leaving little time to focus on ethical niceties. "It's amazing how lenient [mutual] funds are," says a longtime Wall Street trader.
That should change as attention centers on conflicts of interest that plague the fund business. The trick will be ensuring that managers can't easily put their own trading accounts ahead of shareholders' welfare--easier said than done right now. Fidelity, for instance, sees stock trading as a good way for employees to learn about markets. Some companies see it as a tool to keep hot portfolio managers aboard.<p>Still, a few fund firms acknowledge potential conflicts. Martin Whitman, who runs the $140 million Third Avenue Value Fund, says fund managers should buy their own fund's shares if they want to invest: "That's what I do. I eat my own cooking." <p>Managers don't benefit just by trading for themselves, of course. A lesser-known conflict has to do with buying the same stock for different funds. Hedge funds are more lucrative for managers than vanilla funds, for example: 20 percent of a hedge fund's profits might go to its manager, compared to 1 percent for a mutual fund. So managers have a big incentive to trade first for their hedge fund, then at the resulting higher price for the mutual fund.<p>Few fund holders are aware of such conflicts; the Securities and Exchange Commission doesn't even require mutual fund managers to disclose whether they also run hedged money. But the fallout from the Invesco and Fidelity investigations may lead to tighter rules. High time.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
