<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Eternal Rewards</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Eternal Rewards</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
For inept insurance scammers, death be not profitable. A guide to doing it right.<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Dying to make a million bucks? Some folks are--dying, that is. Or at least that's what they want insurers to believe when they have a spouse or relative file big phony death claims.<p>But there's a definite art to dying for dollars. While no industry-wide statistics exist on bogus death claims, the nation's biggest insurer, Prudential Life Insurance, says it catches up to 40 defrauders each year. Only the truly cunning, it seems, can play dead.<p>How to die, then? A primer:<p>Don't act on impulse. Being dead isn't a whim, and it's not for everyone. Loneliness helped drive James Lang, a baker from Washington State, to resurrect himself after only six weeks. Upon returning contrite to his distraught family, Lang went into counseling.<p>Consider drowning. There's no need to provide a body. The downside: "Whenever somebody with a big policy disappears on the high seas, we're suspicious," says William Rodgers, vice president of investigation at Prudential.<p>Plan discreetly. Robert Granberg, a retired New York State investigator, offered a man in a bar $10,000 to assist in his fake-drowning plot. The man declined, then helped convince investigators that Granberg hadn't gone to a watery grave. Granberg was later caught at a motel with his wife.<p>Ditch the address book. "It's not easy to completely give up your past," says insurance-fraud investigator Robert Federspiel. Most defrauders get nabbed when they contact friends or family. Carroll Wayne Baumgarner, for example, was collared at his kin's home in Maryland two years after he faked his death in a Canadian boating accident.<p>Get a new identity. A dead person can't drive, work, or vote. Surprisingly, this trips some people up: California embalmer Melvin Lee Lincoln faked his and his wife's deaths, then tried to renew his driver's license. He ended up repaying $150,600 he'd collected from insurance companies--and he lost his embalmer's license.<p>Lie low. In particular, don't break the law. Phillip Champagne, thought to be dead for ten years, was snagged last year for counterfeiting $100 bills after his restaurant in Washington State went under. Investigators quickly identified him as "the man who could walk on water without getting his feet wet," a reference to his supposed drowning death. Now in prison, Champagne is being sued by Federal Kemper Life Assurance for the $700,000 it paid on his policy.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Insurance Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
