<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Essay Questions</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Essay Questions</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Last spring, Susie and Bill Mosca sparked a trend by unloading their Maine bed-and-breakfast for $500,000 through an essay contest. Since then, property owners have been holding contests to peddle everything from trailer homes to 22-room mansions. But check carefully before launching such a scheme yourself: Some states are declaring the competitions illegal.<p>Here's how the contests work. Let's say you want to sell a house for $1 million in a weak market. Just charge a $100 fee to each of 10,000 essay writers and pick a single winner. Easy--unless you don't get 10,000 entries, a common snag as the contests multiply. Canceling a contest because of low response may violate consumer-protection laws, even if all the money is returned. Says Edgar Dworsky, assistant attorney general of Massachusetts, "What if Publisher's Clearinghouse said, 'We're not giving away a million bucks because we didn't sell enough magazines?'"<p>Massachusetts also regards the contests as thinly veiled lotteries, which can be held only by the state or a charity. Rhode Island takes the same stance; the contests are now outlawed in both states. In California, two civil suits have already been filed, and criminal charges could follow. Herschel Elkins, the state's senior assistant attorney general, says he's seen essay competitions that misrepresent the value of the prize or hand over a property just before the bank arrives to foreclose. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
