<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-Drawing New Fault Lines</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-Drawing New Fault Lines</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Two proposed laws would make it harder to win big judgments in liability lawsuits<p>
By David A. Andelman<p>
If some lawmakers have their way, consumers will soon have a harder time hitting the jackpot in two types of liability lawsuits. While neither proposed change has drawn much attention so far, both will be major legislative battlegrounds this spring.<p>
The first measure targets product-liability suits and stands a good chance of passage despite vehement opposition from organized labor and consumer advocates such as Ralph Nader. Aimed at freeing the courts of many suits filed by contingency-fee lawyers, it would be the first federal statute to deal with product defects and liability. Its key provisions propose to limit the enormous awards for punitive damages that are often assessed by juries in state courts.<p>
Companies would be protected, for example, in the case of harmful drugs or medical devices that have been approved by the Food and Drug Administration. But the bill, introduced by Senator Jay Rockefeller of West Virginia, also establishes a mediation process so that suits involving real economic loss can continue. And in a measure intended to speed the end of cases, companies could be fined up to $50,000 if they turn down a settlement that's less than the amount a plaintiff is ultimately awarded.<p>
The second measure is a securities-fraud bill. Introduced by Representative Billy Tauzin of Louisiana, it would amend the Securities Exchange Act of 1934, which was aimed at protecting investors. In pushing his measure, Tauzin argues that the original law has become "the tool used by speculators to recoup losses from risky investments."<p>
In particular, the new bill is aimed at limiting the kind of class-action suit that is filed whenever a company's stock suffers an unexpected dip. Many people think these suits enrich only lawyers, who collect a hefty reward when the company decides it's cheaper to settle than to fight. Tauzin has lined up some 55 cosponsors in the House and has strong support from oft-sued accounting firms and from Silicon Valley, a frequent target of class-action attorneys because high-tech stocks are known for their sharp price swings.<p>
But the bill's opponents worry that it could simply let guilty companies off the hook. Daniel Schulder of the National Council of Senior Citizens says the proposed changes "would shield thousands of companies...from legitimate private suits brought by individuals injured by financial mismanagement and scams." The elderly, he says, are frequent victims of such schemes.<p>
Both liability-limiting bills are especially galling to consumer groups because they've been proposed by Democrats--not Republicans, the traditional supporters of big business. "For consumers, it's already hard enough," says Linda Lipsen, legislative director of Consumers Union. "Congress should not be making it even harder."<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
