		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-The Color of Money</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>When Ted Turner decided to colorize his library of black-and-white films in the 1980s, he sent the stocks of his two contractors soaring. But Turner called it quits at 225 movies, and the two colorizing companies, CST Entertainment Imaging and American Film Technologies, have struggled ever since. Now, after lame efforts to diversify, both CST and AFT insist that--skeptics be damned--they're coming back. CST is working on "featurization": colorizing old TV-series episodes and stitching them into new TV movies. The first is a Wyatt Earp movie that features an aged Hugh O'Brian, the original TV Earp, recalling the old days. AFT, which went into bankruptcy last October, is banking on emerging TV systems overseas. CEO Gerald Wetzler claims foreign demand for cheap color product can be met only by colorizing. "Colorization was a fad," he says. "Now it's an economic imperative."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Entertainment Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
