	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-A World of Their Own</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Dean Robinson<p>By the end of this summer's soccer World Cup, at least nine names will be etched into the minds of the tournament's U.S. television viewers. Diego Maradona isn't one--but Snickers is. In a rare coup, every television commercial surrounding the cup's 52 broadcasts was sold two years ago to a cartel of the tournament's sponsors without being offered to other advertisers. The estimated $20 million deal was engineered by the networks that will carry the games, ABC and ESPN. Even before securing broadcast rights, ABC approached official cup sponsors and "marketing partners," which had paid up to $20 million each for the designation. Four companies quickly agreed to buy all the commercial air time available. That bolstered the networks' bid and blocked competing advertisers from riding World Cup hype. But the initial pact turned out to be a little too effective for the World Cup organizers, who asked ABC and ESPN to admit additional sponsors and partners. After some juggling, the networks ended up with five gold advertisers, each with two minutes of ads per broadcast, and four silver advertisers, each with 30 seconds. The brand names: <a name="NYSE:KO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10359"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, MasterCard, Snickers, <a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors </b></a>, Canon, Adidas, <a name="NYSE:FON"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11560"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sprint</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:G"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10655"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gillette</b></a>, and Fuji. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Sports Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

