	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/03-A Sweetheart Deal</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/03-A Sweetheart Deal</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Trash that Pez dispenser when you were five? The Sternfelds will sell it back - for $3,000<p>By David Hochman<p>Who they are: Sue and Richie Sternfeld, key players in the sweet market for Pez candy dispensers, collectible of the moment. <p>How they met: Richie, 50, sold vintage Pez dispensers through hobby magazines; Sue, 36, was a big customer. After two years of telephone transactions, they decided to merge their collections--and their lives. Now they dominate the market.<p>Where they honeymooned: The first day, the newlyweds visited the Pez factory in Orange, Connecticut. The next day, they flew to the first-ever Pez convention.<p>Why they're so pez-obsessed: "Pez has so much personality," says Sue. "If you had a whole house full of Picassos and just one little rack of Pez, people would run up to the Pez and say, 'Wow, these are so cute!'"<p>Another possible reason: They earned more than $10,000 from two Christie's auctions last year.<p>How many dispensers: They own more than 700, including every type ever issued by Pez Candy. They also have some bootleg models, such as the moss-covered Chia Pez and a one-of-a-kind Pee-wee Herman.<p>Most valuable dispenser: Tops in their collection is Make-a-Face, a cross between a regular model and Mr. Potato Head. Fewer than 25 exist; one was sold recently to a Colorado collector for $3,000.<p>Their role in pezmania: "First, they promote Pez in the trade magazines," explains Harry Rinker, a collectibles analyst. "That gets the auction houses interested, which in turn gets the media excited. Pez gets trendy, prices go up--and nobody's happier than the Sternfelds."<p>How hot the market is: Several dispensers, including Muselix, a rare German model, command nearly $2,000 apiece. <p>Who else is playing: As many as 2,000 Pez buffs, says Richard Geary, who runs the annual Pez convention in Cleveland. A decade ago, he adds, there were fewer than 50 Pezmaniacs.<p>What the company thinks: "I don't really understand it," says Pez president Scott McWhinnie.<p>Pez trivia: Dispensers never feature real people. "We've received thousands of letters asking for a Michael Jackson dispenser," says McWhinnie. "Need I say more?"<p>When the fad will fade: "In five years, it's not going to be half as big," says analyst Rinker. "Ultimately, there's a limit to how much someone will pay for something like this, and we're pretty near that point."<p>What they'll do after that: Also stashed in the Sternfelds' tiny apartment in Queens, New York, are hoards of <a name="NYSE:DIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11603"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Disney</b></a> items, Pillsbury Doughboy collectibles, and Colonel Sanders doodads.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Business

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:DIS">The Walt Disney Company</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
