<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Uncle Sam's Free Library</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Uncle Sam's Free Library</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						  <p>By Emanuel Howard<p>When the government writes a book, anyone can reprint it without paying royalties. Publishers don't need permission--just a gut feeling that people will pay for turgid prose. And people do. No Clinton tome yet rivals the Warren Commission report: Published by Bantam only 80 hours after it was released, it sold 1.6 million copies. But some Clintonian works have hit the best-seller list, enriching publishers but not the taxpayers who funded the reports.<p>
--The President's Health Security Plan (Times Books, $9)<p>Copies were on bookstore shelves the night President Clinton presented his health plan to the country. Almost 250,000 copies in print.<p>
--Health Security (Touchstone Books, $7)<p>An editor stood in line to buy a copy of the health plan for $34. The publisher had 100,000 copies on sale within five days and has since printed 20,000 more.<p>
--The Gore Report on Reinventing Government (Times Books, $9)<p>After reading a newspaper story on the report, Times Books asked for a copy. Within five days, 75,000 books were on sale. Total copies now at 100,000.<p>
-- Creating a Government That Works Better and Costs Less (Plume Books, $9)<p>Plume took 17 days to get 60,000 copies out. Why so long? Tom Peters, author of the foreword, was in Japan.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Publishing Industry, Government

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

