				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Carla Koehl<p>Think the '80s are over? Think again. Good times on Wall Street have sparked a comeback of the hubris that marked the Masters of the Universe era: Execs are once more asking tailors to visit them at work. Says a Salomon grandee, "I see a lot of people getting measured again--while they're on conference calls." Bergdorf Goodman notes a buildup of Wall Street calls for its door-to-door tailors. And custom clothier Richard Contratti just had his best season since 1987. "It's not that I stopped ordering after the crash," says Bear Stearns pooh-bah Alan Schwartz, barking orders to his assistant as Contratti fits him for two new suits. "Now I just feel better about ordering a few more." Sherman McCoy would be proud.  
