<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Shrinking Returns</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Shrinking Returns</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
So you're confused about zero-coupon bonds? Tell me about your mother.<p>By Laurence R. Stains<p>As we all know, the markets are driven by psychology as much as fundamentals. So how come journalists always quote economists instead of psychologists? To redress this problem, we interviewed Dr. Michael Ascher, a fellow of the American Psychological Association. A professor at Temple University in Philadelphia, he specializes in anxiety-related disorders. We asked Ascher: Why do investors keep making the same crazy mistakes? Here's his diagnosis; the bill is in the mail.<p>Symptom: You sell too low.
Diagnosis: You're swayed by negative scan--you dwell on past losing moves and dismiss previous successes. In a futile attempt to reverse the pattern, you panic and sell in downturns.<p>Symptom: You buy too high.
Diagnosis: Uh-oh. Sounds like a case of emotional reasoning. Though you may know you're paying too much, you talk yourself into it because you fear missing out on further gains.<p>Symptom: You hang on too long.
Diagnosis: The cognitive glitch with your name on it is superstitious thinking. You think the stock will shoot straight up as soon as you sell it.<p>Symptom: You pin all your hopes on one stock.
Diagnosis: The stock has become an object of security--an unproductive emotional attachment has developed, much like Linus and his blanket in the Peanuts cartoons. Well-adjusted adults reserve such infantile behavior for their cars.<p>Symptom: You avoid risk.
Diagnosis: You may have depressive tendencies. Take two Prozacs and call a manic money manager in the morning.<p>Symptom: You take too many unreasonable risks.
Diagnosis: You may be manic --perpetually euphoric. Find yourself a money manager with depressive tendencies.<p>Symptom: You have a weakness for hot stocks.
Diagnosis: A classic case of low self-esteem--you'll trust anyone's opinion about a stock, as long as it's not your own.<p>Symptom: You have a weakness for concept stocks.
Diagnosis: You're susceptible to grandiose thinking--you exaggerate the stock's prospects and, of course, your soon-to-be-heralded brilliance in realizing its massive untapped potential.<p>Symptom: You buy a stock at 17 and ride it up to 85. Then, when it dips to 83, you spaz out at your broker and insist he eat your trading costs.
Diagnosis: You're a pig.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
