<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Not in My Backyard</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Not in My Backyard</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						  
New York City's elite apartment dwellers stop a barbarian from storming the gate<p>By Carla Koehl<p>Billionaire Ronald Perelman went hunting for an apartment after his separation from celebrity gossip Claudia Cohen, but discovered a place where his money didn't work: New York's stuffy co-op market.<p>Despite his wealth, Perelman was rejected as a resident by not one, not two, but three prestigious co-operative apartment buildings in Manhattan. Why? "I have nothing to say to you," says Betsy Green, the real estate broker who presided over Perelman's search. "I don't speak to the press." Can't say we blame her. Such rejections are a black mark that every broker seeks to avoid.<p>Not that Revlon Ron isn't in good company--sort of. Richard Nixon, landing in New York after his resignation, also was turned away by three high-class buildings, including the one where Henry Kissinger lives. More recent famous rejects include Rush Limbaugh, designer Carolyne Roehm (the ex-wife of Henry Kravis), and Madonna.<p>In Perelman's case, the rejections must have been especially galling. By the time he got approved at his new place at 73rd Street and Park Avenue--where he already wants a bigger apartment--Perelman had been shooed away from buildings where his peers are ensconced: John Gutfreund at 834 Fifth Avenue, Gordon Getty at 820 Fifth Avenue, and Sid Bass at 4 East 66th Street.<p>According to tenant advocates in New York City, the only legitimate reason to turn away someone respectable is financial instability--hardly Perelman's problem. But few victims care to tout their reject status, so the board of a co-op--where tenants own shares in a corporation that owns the building--can be picky with impunity. Often, that consists of treating celebrities and the nouveau riche as pariahs. Says broker C.B. Whyte about famous tenants: "It's either a hassle or it costs money [for extra security measures]. That's what boards are supposed to avoid. Who needs it?"<p>However unfair, such snobbery pales in comparison to the horror stories of racism and prejudice that brokers say are common in New York co-opdom. They suspect, however, that Perelman fell victim to a different form of discrimination. "Have you ever met this guy?" says one leading broker. "He's rude, he's newly single, and he's got some very tacky visitors. Trust me, you don't want him in your building."
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Homeowner, Real Estate Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
