<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-High Stakes</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-High Stakes</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Led by Virgin, airlines bet that gamblers will take a flier in new casino-class seats<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>
Virgin airways flights, with their on-board magicians, musicians, and massages, already resemble a night in Las Vegas. The experience should get even more realistic this month, as the upstart British airline launches its gambling service on flights from London to Hong Kong. If all goes as planned, the first outing will usher in a high-tech age of airborne wagering.<p>Virgin's gambit, hatched by flamboyant entrepreneur Richard Branson, is the latest twist on the worldwide gaming craze--and a logical follow-up to the growth of riverboat gambling in the U.S. Already, Singapore Airlines, Mexicana Airlines, and other international carriers are thinking of following Virgin. U.S. airlines would like to play, too, but must clear some legal hurdles first.<p>Gaming is a natural for the troubled airline industry. As fares remain stubbornly low, carriers are scrambling for extra income and new gimmicks. So far, this has meant a lot of talk about live stock quotes, video games, and the like. Since many such services will be offered via a small seat-back screen--often equipped with a credit-card reader--it's a small leap to electronic gambling. "It wouldn't be very hard to do," says a spokesman for Northwest Airlines, which has readied six planes for the move.<p>Gambling in the air isn't completely new. In the early 1980s, for example, Singapore Airlines briefly installed full-size slot machines in the back of some planes. But as seat-back screens become more common and gaming continues to explode, the match now makes perfect economic sense. "I think it will take a lot of money from passengers," says Anthony Curtis of Las Vegas Advisor, a newsletter about gambling.<p>Virgin is spending $17 million to fit 6 of its 13 jumbo jets with interactive systems that will allow fliers to win--or lose--small stakes on their credit cards while playing games including blackjack, poker, and roulette. The airline is concentrating on its Pacific routes at first, but transatlantic gaming flights are possible this year too.<p>Before getting its casino flights off the ground, Virgin must get approval from British authorities. That'll be easy compared to the task faced by U.S. airlines, which are prohibited from offering gambling--even in international airspace--by the 1951 Johnson Act. That law was amended in 1992 to exempt U.S. flagged cruise ships in international waters; U.S. airlines have been lobbying for similar treatment. According to one industry study, U.S. carriers will sacrifice $680 million in annual revenue if in-flight gambling isn't allowed.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
