	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Human Dartboard</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Human Dartboard</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						  
Now Burton Malkiel is picking stocks. But will he ever get that monkey off his back?<p>By Jim Melloan<p>Burton Malkiel is the patron saint of anyone who hates money managers. His most famous theory--that a blindfolded monkey throwing darts at the financial pages can pick stocks as well as any expert--remains as compelling today as it was 20 years ago. But if his theory is true, why is he running his own investment firm? And did he raid any zoos to build his staff?<p>Well, no. In fact, he's not even using darts to pick his investments. But Malkiel is beating market indexes anyway, casting a big shadow on his own book, the classic A Random Walk Down Wall Street.<p>In Random Walk, Malkiel essentially says stock prices are impossible to predict. But his own results suggest otherwise: Since June 1991, his Princeton Scientific Capital Management has produced an average annual return of 25 percent, compared with 13 percent for the S&P 500--a showing Malkiel immodestly calls "pretty amazing." PSCM manages $40 million, mostly from partner Norton Garfinkle.<p>The Princeton professor sheepishly insists that Random Walk, which has sold more than 500,000 copies, remains valid. But he adds a few caveats to his much-quoted advice that investors should simply assemble a diverse portfolio and watch it move with the market over the long term. For example, Malkiel talks up measurements he once pooh-poohed, such as price-to-earnings ratios.<p>"You can make some money on some of these things some of the time," he says. "The question is, can you assemble a portfolio of investing styles to beat the market over the long pull?" Malkiel now believes he can do just that. Indeed, he'll soon start marketing his talents to institutional investors and rich folks.<p>"I'm surprised my system is doing as well as it is," he says. "I'm a skeptic, even as far as my own theories are concerned."
 <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

