	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/02-Making the Grade</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/02-Making the Grade</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Clinton's first year gets a grudging B from our panel of top economists<p>By Kevin Caliendo<p>An informal survey of award-winning econo-mists shows only lukewarm regard for President Clinton's economic skills. Clinton's grade for his first year in office, a gentleman's B, was bolstered significantly by his victory on the North American Free Trade Agreement, which overwhelmed the economists' serious doubts about deficit reduction and health care.<p>"The grade may reflect how easily we grade our presidents, rather than how well he really did," says Paul Krugman, a 1991 winner of the John Bates Clark Medal for outstanding young economists.<p>Despite such caveats, each economist hailed NAFTA as a big step toward free trade and praised the president's lobbying ability. "A Republican president wouldn't have been able to get NAFTA through Congress, and most Democrats would've ignored it," says Laurence Meyer, current holder of the Blue Chip Economic Forecasting Award. "He pushed hard to get it. That alone deserves an A."<p>But most economists dock Clinton a grade or two for his other first-year initiatives. "The deficit-reduction bill puts too much reliance on tax increases," gripes William Hummer, the 1990 Blue Chip winner. "Small business is going to bear the brunt of this." Charles Reeder, recipient of the the 1982 Blue Chip, adds: "It's like some sort of punishment for those who made it big in the '80s rather than a sound economic plan."<p>Clinton has his advocates, such as Paul Samuelson, the 1970 Nobel Prize winner. "America is ahead of all the advanced nations in economic recovery," he says. "And Clinton has tried to do something about the baleful Reagan legacy of a bingeing, low- investing society." Says Peter Bernstein, the 1983 Blue Chip winner: "I'm not a deficit-cutting freak, but that's what the markets wanted."<p>Still, the president draws little but scorn from free-market absolutists such as Milton Friedman, a Nobel winner in 1976. "The health plan that Clinton has proposed would be an utter disaster for whomever adopts it," Friedman warns. "It is a straightforward regulated plan, a la Russia in the 1950s."<p>The president's B grade--hardly Rhodes scholar material--was inflated by two grades of incomplete from economists who felt that his policies would ultimately fail but wanted to see more evidence before sending Clinton off to detention. <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Politics
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
