<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Withholding Pattern</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Withholding Pattern</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Travel agencies may be reluctant to tell fliers about deals on smaller airlines advisory<p>By Tom Nawrocki<p>Emboldened by upheavals in the airline industry, small carriers have been extending their flexible, low-cost services to bigger markets. The only problem is, some travel agents are unwilling to tell fliers about the small-carrier options.<p>One of the upstarts is Alaska's MarkAir, a former cargo-only airline that has been carrying passengers since 1984. After launching an Anchorage-to-Seattle route two years ago, it recently expanded to serve 14 cities in the lower 48. MarkAir never requires a round-trip purchase and asks as little as $180 for a round trip between San Francisco and Denver.<p>Unlike major carriers that swathe cheap fares in restrictions, many small airlines allow fliers to show up at the gate with a couple hundred bucks. Kiwi International, for instance, offers a round trip between New York and Atlanta on literally a moment's notice for only $169. Here's the catch: Kiwi serves just six U.S. cities and San Juan, Puerto Rico. Other off-brand airlines include Horizon Air and Morris Air.<p>Even frequent fliers may not know about such alternatives, and some travel agents don't volunteer the information to clients. When asked recently for the cheapest rate from the New York area to Denver, for example, Thomas Cook said that "all the carriers" were charging $527 for a round trip. Only a specific query about MarkAir prompted a better quote: $298 round trip. Another agency, Travel Network, said it couldn't find any fares for MarkAir flights from New York to Denver.<p>Why is it so hard to find these cheap fares? Perhaps because travel agents work for commissions, and the larger airlines usually pay higher commissions. Ticket buyers can protect themselves, however. One easy tactic: Always ask an agent directly if there's a cheaper flight available.<p>Fliers should also seek a second opinion on the lowest fare; some agents are more sympathetic to budget concerns. With a bit of homework, December travelers may find that an airline they've never heard of is just what they need: a nice holiday bonus.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Travel Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

