	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Vinyl Resting Place</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Karen Benfield<p>Steven Spielberg isn't the only one making money off dinosaurs. As vinyl albums turn into fossils, rare-record dealers are cashing in.<p>Gryphon Record Shop in New York is one of a flourishing breed of vinyl-only outlets, most of which specialize in old classical discs. "Many recordings will never be transferred to CD," says manager Raymond Donnell. And audiophiles pay plenty for hard-to-find pressings: Gryphon charges $100 for a ten-inch album of violinist Mischa Elman playing Mendelssohn, for example.<p>A storefront isn't needed to corral this lucrative market. When Lawrence O'Toole had financial woes last year, he used vinyl to turn things around. "I loved classical music,"he says, explaining how his New York apartment became a clearinghouse for obscure discs. "But mostly it was desperation. I was in hock."<p>He isn't anymore: In the first nine months of 1993, the 42-year-old writer sold more than $50,000 worth of rare classical records, and his business is growing fast. O'Toole now publishes regular mail-order catalogs, and 80 percent of his sales come from overseas--a majority from Japan. Another rare-recording peddler claims an international clientele of 15,000. <p>It's possible to make stellar returns in the vinyl market. Savvy dealers snap up discs for a song at flea markets, record stores, and yard sales; O'Toole once plunked down 99 cents for a recording of pianist Marcelle Meyer playing Mozart and sold it for $501. Value is determined by the rarity of the disc, along with the level of the performance. Interesting jacket art also boosts value. Wondering if there's hidden gold in your record collection? Here are a few highly coveted albums:<p> Wilhelm Furtwangler conducts Beethoven's Fourth (VOX)<p> Ernest Ansermet conducts the Royal Ballet--Great Performances (RCA Living Stereo)<p> Famous Duets from French Opera, with Pierrette Alarie and Lopold Simoneau (Ducretet-Thomson)<p> Any recording by the Barylli Quartet (Westminster) <p> D.E. Inghelbrecht conducts Faure's Requiem (Ducretet-Thomson)<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Music Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

