		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Trouble in Fantasyland</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Trouble in Fantasyland</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>
Rotisserie players should weigh the risks of a league that's based in the workplace<p>By Kevin Caliendo<p>Office workers who take part in popular sports-fantasy leagues--also known as rotisserie leagues--may be gambling for higher stakes than they imagine.<p>Two federal employees recently were suspended and four others were reprimanded for the pastime, in which competitors construct imaginary teams made up of real players from multiple teams in a sport. The employees' sin: Using government computers to swap messages about their league. Meanwhile, in North Lauderdale, Florida, a firefighter lost his job after being arrested for running a league. Attorneys say millions more could be at risk because most fantasy leagues and office pools, while part of corporate life, are actually illegal gambling--except in Montana, where gambling laws exclude fantasy leagues.<p>A crackdown is unlikely, but workers with crabby managers should keep their league out of the workplace. "The people who have to worry are those whose bosses have no life," says Lew Fidler, a New York lawyer who also provides statistics for fantasy leagues.<p>Like most attorneys, Fidler thinks rotisserie players are safe if the boss plays too--and he notes that most authorities are in no position to enforce the law. "I run leagues for the legislature of New York, and another with Mario Cuomo," he says. "The U.S. Congress has one. And Tony Lake, the national security advisor, who can wake Bill Clinton up at any time, is in one as well."<p>Still, the legal situation remains murky. The Fort Lauderdale case didn't set a precedent because it was dropped on a technicality; the firefighter returned to work. In the federal workers' case, no criminal charges were filed and the workers continue to play in fantasy leagues. "But they don't even talk about it at work anymore," says their lawyer. "It takes all the fun out of it." 
 <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
