<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-The CIA's Trade Secret</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-The CIA's Trade Secret</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p> <p>
Spying turns from guns to butter, and spooks start lobbying for NAFTA<p>By David A. Andelman<p>The central intelligence Agency has quietly switched from the cold war to the trade war. And in its first major outing, the new-look CIA is emerging as an unexpected and persuasive lobbyist in the battle to ratify the North American Free Trade Agreement.<p>Intelligence sources say key voters on Capitol Hill--including senators David Boren and Alfonse D'Amato, and House members Bill Richardson and Robert Torricelli--have received classified briefings on NAFTA from senior CIA analysts. The CIA station in Mexico City also has bolstered the pact by hosting lobbyists, politicians, and aides as they pass through on fact-finding visits.<p>The agency's support for NAFTA heralds an era in which spies mainly serve their countries' economic aims, not political or military goals. It's also a crucial test for the CIA itself, as director James Woolsey tries to justify his budget by throwing manpower at issues close to boss Bill Clinton's heart: In addition to two political experts and a couple of military analysts, six economists now work at the agency's Mexico desk.<p>The CIA's briefings to members of Congress hammer on a simple theme: NAFTA will strengthen the Mexican government. People who have attended these sessions say the spooks bring along volumes of agency statistics to support their case. The pitch is focused on politicians who Woolsey thinks can make a difference. Boren, for example, is a swing vote on many economic issues. But the cagey Democrat is also an intelligence junkie; colleagues believe he can be swayed by the CIA.<p>Another important target is Richardson, the powerful New Mexico Democrat. Richardson is already a NAFTA believer, but he's expected to convince others who are sitting on the fence. Democrat Torricelli of New Jersey gets the nod as a maven on hemispheric trade, while spy-friendly Republicans such as John Warner of Virginia and D'Amato of New York are also on the hit list.<p>The CIA doesn't specifically acknowledge its briefings of members of Congress. A spokesman says only that "when we talk about policy issues, it's for the advantage of policy makers." But that's not the whole truth. Supporting NAFTA is good for the CIA too: It needs to keep Mexico's spies on its side as U.S. companies head south and become magnets for industrial espionage.<p>Mexico City is a legendary battleground for spooks. For years the city provided the only regular air route into Cuba, and it's a launching pad for agents being smuggled into the U.S. Small wonder that the CIA works closely with Mexico's spy agency and is currying favor with Mexican power brokers by supporting NAFTA.<p>CIA chief Woolsey is well suited to play Capitol Hill politics. He comes from Oklahoma, the same state as Boren and Democrat Dave McCurdy, former chairmen of the House and Senate intelligence committees, respectively. His hometown is also near the district of Kansas Democrat Dan Glickman, current chairman of the House committee. Ever a good neighbor, Woolsey keeps all three informed on CIA trade concerns. <p>Woolsey, who was expected to testify himself during NAFTA hearings, also may be angling for a closer relationship with Dennis DeConcini, current head of the Senate Intelligence Committee. The Arizona Democrat has pushed for cuts and major changes at the CIA. But he's also a strong supporter of NAFTA and may count Woolsey's help as a favor.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Politics, Government Adgency

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
