<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Scare Tactics</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Scare Tactics</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p> 
Mutual funds try to dampen investors' optimism by predicting lower returns<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Mutual fund companies haven't had to worry about luring new customers for a while now; the bull market has done that work for them. Instead, many companies are trying to ensure that all their new recruits don't bolt at the first sign of trouble. Curiously, their main tactic is to predict worsening performance.<p>"Have recent returns caused your expectations to become too high?" Scudder president Edmond Villani asks in a letter that braces his shareholders for disappointment. Even glummer is the latest missive to Vanguard customers from Chairman John Bogle: "It is clearly not out of the realm of possibility for stock prices to fall precipitously," he warns. Meanwhile, T. Rowe Price adds its own dark note with a $1 million advertising campaign focusing on risk. "People's sense of history is very short," says a spokesman.<p>Why all the doom and gloom? In part, it's out of fear that a market crash will scare away novice fund buyers--just as novices were scared away from stock buying by the 1987 crash.<p>"The specter of '87 is very much on people's minds," says Michael Lipper of Lipper Analytical Services. "They know the good times can't last forever."<p>But a bigger worry is that the bull market may simply be petering out just as mutual fund companies are on the verge of changing American investing habits for good. With mutual funds now at the core of many people's portfolios, the argument goes, a bad period could turn the public against funds forever--unless expectations are carefully managed. And that would be devastating for an industry that until recently has attracted $1 billion a day in new investments.<p>"The funds have a tremendous amount of risk on their hands," says Don Phillips of Morningstar, a mutual fund-tracking agency. "If they disappoint, new investors may flee and never come back."<p>This concern makes sense for a few reasons. Many mutual-fund customers are spoiled because they've never seen a major market correction: According to a study by Investment Company Institute, one in ten didn't even own a fund before 1991.<p>Also, first-time fund buyers, as a group, have a median household income of just $40,000. That doesn't leave room for disappointment on Wall Street: It won't take much to send these investors scurrying back to the safety of CDs.<p>But all the caution flags may be counterproductive. T. Rowe Price now advises investors to expect 8 percent to 10 percent annual growth on stocks for the next several years. Vanguard predicts 7 percent to 10 percent for the next decade. That's galling when the Standard & Poor's 500 index returned 14.6 percent annually over the past decade--and 10 percent since 1926. Who wants to underperform the historic average, especially when some outside experts predict a 13 percent return on stocks? <p>The ironic result may simply be to drive investors away from the more downbeat fund companies--which happen to offer many of the best-established, safest, and most reliable funds. "Funds keep saying, 'Don't be so optimistic,' but investors see great returns,"says Phillips of Morningstar. "It may seem like they're crying wolf."<p>Beneficiaries of the scare tactics could include fund companies such as Invesco or Janus, neither of which intends to give customers any extra warnings. Or more money could flow to banks and other newly established fund hawkers with no track record.  <p> <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

