	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Instant Irish Pubs Are Hot in Europe</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Instant Irish Pubs Are Hot in Europe</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Jolee Edmondson<p>Instant Irish pubs are hot in Europe, and they're due here soon. Some assembly is required, but the effort is usually worth it--for Guinness, at least.<p>Where in europe can you get a pint of Guinness and retreat to an Irish-made oak snug to enjoy Irish food and music? Well, lots of places actually--France, Denmark, and Russia, to name a few. It's all part of a two-year-old scheme hatched by Guinness to sell more stout. The "Irish pub" concept, which will be exported to the U.S. in early 1994, involves selling aspiring bar owners a prefab kit complete with classic fixtures such as beamed ceilings and high "elbow tables." The kits are made by a group of Irish craftsmen. There are five models, ranging from a $90,000 rural cottage pub to a $400,000 Dublin Victorian pub with mosaic floor and stained-glass windows. Also on tap are services such as business advice and recruitment of Irish workers. So far, 150 entrepreneurs have bought from the County Wicklow-based Irish Pub Co., which got funding from Guinness but is owned by a top Irish architect. The brewer doesn't profit from pub-kit sales but does get extra revenue: The 20 Irish pubs that have sprouted in Italy each sell about 11,000 gallons of Guinness a year--ten times the beer sales of an Italian bar. In the U.S., Guinness will target middle-class urban areas and gentrifying historic sections of cities. The company hopes its brainchild will challenge local taverns and beery hangouts such as Bennigan's and Houlihan's.  <p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/1page.gif"><br>About 1 page

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
