	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Investment Buffs</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Investment Buffs</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p> <p>
Nudist investors prepare for a bare market <p>By Andrew Gluck<p>The next time your investment-conscious neighbors talk excitedly about a "naked put," be careful how you answer. They may not be using the Wall Street term for selling a stock they don't own.<p>Introducing Bullish Bares, an investment club for nudists. Under its banner, 15 men and women--about half of them retirees--gather monthly in a retired college professor's living room in Cape Coral, Florida, to discuss stock-picking strategies in the buff. "We don't see ourselves as naked," says one member. "When you're talking about buying <a name="NYSE:BMY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10232"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Bristol-Myers Squibb</b></a>, you're not saying to yourself, 'My, that woman has big breasts.'"<p>Bullish Bares is made up of five married couples and five single people; most belong to the local naturist society. "Nudists have to manage their money, too," says a member. Indeed, the club's founders insist it's nothing special. "We're all straitlaced people," says the retired professor's wife. "A boring group."<p>While the dress code at Bullish Bares is risquE, its portfolio is far from risky. Six of its nine holdings are blue-chip stocks, including <a name="NYSE:MCD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10974"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonald's</b></a> and Quaker Oats--though its largest position is a more daring bet on AFLAC, a small insurance company.<p>After the investment decisions have been made, everyone hops into the pool. But frolicking doesn't get in the way of business: Bullish Bares has trounced market averages, showing a 29 percent return in its first 18 months.  -<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
