<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Inflation Is Down, But Never Out</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Inflation Is Down, But Never Out</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
 <p>By Jim Jubak<p>A 1994 <a name="NYSE:F"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10597"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ford</b></a> Taurus loaded with the usual options costs only 0.5 percent more than last year's model. But a <a name="NASD:TOYOY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41889"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Toyota</b></a> Corolla costs 5.7 percent more. Personal computers are still dropping in price, but cereal is soaring: <a name="NYSE:K"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10841"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kellogg</b></a> has raised prices three times this year. <p>What's the real inflation rate? And is it headed up or down next? The truth is, no one knows. But lately the markets sure have been acting as if they know. Falling interest rates and rising bond prices show that investors think inflation is sound asleep.<p>RISKY BUSINESS<p>The short-term trend is on their side. for the third quarter of 1993, one measure showed prices climbing at just 2.5 percent on an annual basis, well below 1992's 2.9 percent. But buying bonds on this trend is risky: Inflation must stay at current levels, or go lower, for investors to feel good about earning just 6 percent on ten-year bonds. Even if inflation hits the forecast of just nine months ago--3 percent or more in 1994--bonds could take a tumble.<p>Realizing they're treading the edge of a cliff, smart bond managers are prying apart standard indicators for signs that inflation might wake up. For such worriers, the commonly cited consumer price index is just a starting point.<p>BEHIND THE FIGURES<p>The cpi reflects the price of a "basket" of consumer goods and services, including transportation, food, and housing. By this measure, inflation seems under control. There's also the producer price index, which tracks prices of products before they get to consumers. The PPI rose in September for the first time since April, and seems to be climbing at about a 2 percent annual rate. Still no danger.<p>But some veteran inflation watchers feel the CPI and PPI numbers are misleading. Why? Because many of the trends that pushed prices lower in 1993 may not continue. Tobacco companies aren't likely to slash prices so deeply again, for example. Oil prices look like they've reversed their decline, and the new gasoline tax will also push up consumer energy prices.<p>GOING TO THE SOURCE<p>If the inflation trend is going to change direction in 1994, it will likely show up first in commodity prices. And here the news is disquieting, says Jim Grant, editor of Grant's Interest Rate Observer. The production of basic materials from silver to gypsum has fallen behind demand. With silver, copper, nickel, and aluminum near the bottom of their historic price ranges--and with stocks and bonds near historic highs--the current cycle may be near its end. That makes the stocks of commodity-producing companies a better investment than bonds right now.<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Company Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#NYSE:F">Ford Motor Company</a><br>

						<a href="#NASD:TOYOY">Toyota Motor Corporation</a><br>

						<a href="#NYSE:K">Kellogg Company</a><br>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
	<tr><td width=390>
	
