	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Follow-Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
 <p>The man out to topple the Internal Revenue Service by welshing on his debts ("Crazed Like a Fox,"Outfront, October) continues on his unique course. Alex S. Gabor, author of Confessions of a Sex-Crazed Money Man, and his soon-to-be-ex-wife, Aerial Tiger, have filed for bankruptcy protection--claiming $750,000 in debt and $1.9 billion in assets. Gabor argues that the assets are tied to the defunct Marcos regime in the Philippines and can't be used to pay creditors. Gabor and Tiger also still owe much of their bankruptcy-filing fee. "Cases like this are why I stay on the panel," says the court trustee on the case.<p><p>The feds have won a victory in their crackdown against big unreported cash sales, which are often used to launder drug money ("A New Meaning for 'Car Wash,' " Outfront, June). One giant Washington, D.C.-area auto dealer, the Rosenthal group, not only settled federal charges after a sting operation, forfeiting $2.6 million in cash and more than 50 luxury cars; it also agreed to educate other local dealers about cash-sale reporting rules. The harsh terms were a surprise, since the feds didn't show that Rosenthal's owners or top managers were involved in any alleged violations.<p> <p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
