	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-Financial Aid</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Financial Aid</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
A university hopes its students can make good grades in the mutual fund industry<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Now that there are more than 4,000 mutual funds, fund managers often use gimmicks to help stand out in the crowd. Even jaded investors may be startled by a new fund's claim to uniqueness, however: It boasts of being run by an unpredictable cast of university students.<p>The SBI Fund isn't merely a school project; it's a real fund that will invest real money. It's sponsored by the School of Business and Industry at Florida A&M University as part of its on-the-job approach to learning. In the past, SBI has sponsored other student-run enterprises--owning and managing a strip mall and an insurance agency, for example.<p>SBI students will be involved in all aspects of the SBI Fund, according to the fund's registration statement. Undergraduates will mostly do clerical work, while M.B.A. students will conduct research and pick stocks. The fund's cheap labor force and not-for-profit structure make for fees that are among the lowest of any stock fund.<p>The students will have plenty of guidance. Final say on investments rests with a professional fund manager--and looking over his shoulder is a star-studded advisory committee, including Dale Frey, president of GE Investments, and Leon Cooperman, a former top Goldman Sachs executive.<p>The SBI Fund, which was expected to open for business in mid-November, will offer two separate investment pools. With minimum investments of $250,000, both are aimed at institutional investors.<p>"It's curriculum for the students and a source of funds for the university," says Sybil Mobley, dean of SBI. Any profits from the SBI Fund will flow back to the school's coffers--an amount that Mobley predicts will be "more than chump change."<p> <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

