	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 94/01-But Is It Prudent?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-But Is It Prudent?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>At $82 million, Bush's library complex is the costliest presidential shrine yet in progress<p>By Kevin Caliendo<p>For George Bush, the next few years could be just as challenging as his term in the White House.<p>Groundbreaking on his ambitious Presidential Library and Center at Texas A&M University is set for early 1994; soon Bush supporters will receive their first mail shot asking for donations. At a cost of $82 million, the project is by far the most expensive presidential shrine ever, eclipsing by some $25 million the previous record set by Ronald Reagan's library.<p>The massive undertaking--which includes a conference center and a government school--has its doubters, even though Texas A&M already has agreed to donate $40 million for snagging the complex. But fund-raisers remain chipper. The Bush Foundation has solicited "lead gifts" since July and has racked up more than $10 million so far. The largest donation is from former media mogul Walter Annenberg, who gave $2 million. "We foresee no problems" raising the entire amount, says Don Wilson, executive director of the future library and center.<p>When the library is opened in early 1997, its operations will be funded for two years out of the original $82 million. Then the National Archives will operate it at taxpayer expense, as it does nine other presidential libraries. (The privately funded Nixon library isn't among them: A campaign to keep it afloat has just been launched.) In all, the government spent $27 million in 1992 on the facilities. Vital statistics on the libraries of living ex-presidents:<p>GEORGE BUSH<p>Where: College Station, TX
Opening: 1997 (planned)
Cost to build: $82 million for entire complex
Operating cost: $1.2 million a year
Admission: Undecided
On display: Piece of the Berlin Wall, his Yale baseball glove, Desert Storm exhibit
His involvement: Part-time resident, guest lecturer at affiliated George Bush School <p>
RONALD REAGAN<p>Where: Simi Valley, CA
Opened: November 4, 1991
Cost to build: $57 million
Operating cost: $2.6 million
Admission: $4
On display: Bonzo movie posters, chunk of destroyed Soviet missile, George Gipp letter sweater
His involvement: Hosts world leaders, attends library events<p><p>JIMMY CARTER<p>Where: Atlanta
Opened: October 1, 1986
Cost to build: $26 million
Operating cost: $1.7 million
Admission: $2.50
On display: Peanut room, notes from Camp David accord meetings, computer station where Carter's image answers questions
His involvement: Works at nearby Carter Center on inner-city and foreign problems<p><p>GERALD FORD
Where: Grand Rapids, MI
Opened: September 18, 1981
Cost to build: $11.4 million
Operating cost: $2 million
Admission: $2
On display: Nixon's resignation letter, contract offer to play for Green Bay Packers
His involvement: Attends many programs, invites notable speakers<p><p>RICHARD NIXON
Where: Yorba Linda, CA
Opened: July 19, 1990
Cost to build: $25 million
Operating cost: $963,000
Admission: $4.95
On display: Photo of Nixon and Elvis together, life-size statues of world leaders, Watergate exhibit
His involvement: Speaks at policy conferences<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Government, Politics
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
