	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>94/01-Bank Statement</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>For years now, some gay activists have stamped the dollars they spend with pink triangles, slogans, or other signs, hoping to remind people that the homosexual community has, by some estimates, more than $500 billion in annual spending power. The tactic surfaced most recently in Cobb County, Georgia, where officials halted all public support of the arts so that no taxpayer money would go to gay artists. Although defaced currency is still legal tender, stamping money is a crime. Now activists who want to make a statement without breaking the law have an alternative: Pink Inc. of Bethesda, Maryland, has begun offering "gay-pride message checks," complete with pink triangle and microscopic writing that says, "Gay money," "No, she's not my sister," and other phrases. The checks can be printed for any bank account; so far, customers in 33 states have ordered them.<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
