<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Return to Sender</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Return to Sender</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Don't answer these "political" surveys<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>The Association for Investor Awareness says it wants to "make your voice heard" inWashington, D.C. But answer its mailing and you'll do the listening--to cold calls from investment pitchmen.<p>AIA sends out mass mailings that challenge government policy on taxes and investing, asking recipients to help prod legislators. The patriotic-sounding patter ends by inviting investors to respond to an "Information Research Survey" about three basic tax rules.<p>So far, so good. But then AIA asks for investment preferences and personal information, including telephone numbers. "The results of this survey will be forwarded to Washington,"it promises.<p>It's true that AIAsent the tally from nearly 19,000 replies to the presidential campaigns of both Bill Clinton and George Bush last year. But that's the only contact AIAsays it has had with politicians. Despite the Washington address on its stationery, AIA has no listed telephone or staff there. Its "executive suite" in D.C. is manned by a service firm that simply collects the mail. AIAisn't among the 40,000 groups registered to lobby Congress, and other shareholder-rights organizations have never heard of it.<p>That's no surprise:AIA Director Mike Casson isn't an activist but a direct marketer by profession, and AIA's main business seems to consist of gathering and selling information. Actually based in Dallas, the group shares an office with American Direct Marketing Services, which sends out brochures as Marketing Investors Group. According to papers filed with the Texas secretary of state, Casson is president of ADMS.<p>ADMS/MIGis a classic name-selling shop,delivering lists of cold-call prospects in categories such as "master investors" and "older money." Reached at ADMS, Casson insists that AIAisn't a front for his direct-marketing business, describing it instead as "a conduit between concerned investors and their elected officials." But he can't cite any such work except mailing the rival presidential campaigns--once. (And all he has to show for that effort is a form letter from a Clinton aide.) Casson says AIA"would like to" start a library for investors, and that "plans are underway" for anewsletter.<p>He adamantly defends selling the names of investors who respond to AIAsurveys. "What we do isn't any different from any other publication or association," he says, noting that Worth sells the names of its subscribers. But AIA doesn't do much except sell names. Says Richard Barton of the Direct Marketing Association:"It has an obligation to tell people. It's not legally required, but. . . we consider it unethical." Casson says he doesn't see any need to disclose AIA's practices in its mailings.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Politics, Telecommunications Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
