<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Money in the Bank</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Money in the Bank</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Speculators make deposits in hundreds of thrifts, hoping to gain more than a toaster.<p>By Emanuel Howard<p>This year will be the most profitable for the troubled mutual-bank industry since its heyday in 1987--and that's great news for a little-known bunch of speculators dubbed "flippers."<p>But thrift bankers have become peeved by the easy-to-copy tactics of these opportunists and are fighting a rising wave of flippers.<p>Flipping is a sure way to make a buck from the trend for mutual banks--banks owned by their customers--to convert to stock ownership by offering shares to the public. When a thrift converts, its depositors get an insider price on the new shares, which can then be resold at a profit.<p>Obviously, reselling is easier if the offering is a big success. But with thrift stocks, that's hardly a gamble:Mutual-bank offerings have been hot ever since 1990. Share prices may pop as much as 50 percent in initial trading.<p>Flippers have turned this fact into a strategy. Now estimated to number a few hundred nationwide, these speculators deposit tiny sums of money in as many as 500 of the 1,300 or so remaining U.S. thrifts. They may wait five years for a thrift to become healthy enough to offer stock. Then they scoop up shares at a steep discount--paying, say, $10 a share--and can take profits as soon as the stock opens at, say, $15.<p>Today's most active flippers have been lying in wait since 1987, knowing that the savings-and-loan crisis eventually would spur a move toward more-stable stock ownership among thrifts. Another force promoting stock offerings:Thrift managers who survived the crisis are eager to cash in--they get the insider price on shares, too.<p>On top of this, a year of solid profits for thrifts means that shares are in demand among investors. Ninety-one thrifts converted last year, making it the first billion-dollar year since 1987. This year will be even bigger, analysts say. SNL Securities, an industry information clearing house, pegs 765 candidates as ripe for conversion. <p>There's nothing wrong or illegal about flipping, but thrift officials hate it because it makes for volatile stocks. When there's a heavy flipper presence, as many as 50 percent of all issued shares change hands shortly after a conversion. Prices may rise in the short term but often retreat soon after, leaving an aura of disappointment.<p>So thrift managers have begun to shut out the flippers--or at least flippers who operate on a nationwide basis. Most mutuals no longer accept out-of-state or mail-in deposits. Insider prices for shares may be restricted to depositors with accounts that have been open for six months or a year.<p>But this is just damage control: "The smart investors have already got their accounts set up," says Eric Luse, a partner at Luse Lehman Pomerenk & Schick, a law firm involved with many mutual-bank conversions.<p>There may still be opportunities for flippers--perhaps even in your neighborhood. Analysts say the Northeast is poised for a conversion boom in 1994, and speculators are scrambling to make deposits in time. States with especially healthy thrifts include New York, Ohio, Illinois, Pennsylvania, Indiana, and North Carolina.<p>"Some of these institutions are the strongest in the country," says Mark B. Cohen of Adams Cohen Securities. "In fact, if you've still got a mutual bank in 1993, it's probably a good one."<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Banking Industry
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
