<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Hip Hop Honchos</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Hip Hop Honchos</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Rap's new moguls prove that capitalism can come straight outta Compton<p>By Michael Small<p>No rap song pays tribute to spreadsheets and depreciation--yet. But the lexicon of finance is fast appearing in the private lives of many top rappers. As owners and chief executives of their own record labels, they aim to become leaders of a new moneyed class.<p>"I'm an assets person," says Luther (Luke) Campbell, leader of sex-rap group 2 Live Crew, which triggered a First Amendment firestorm in 1990 with songs such as "Me So Horny." "I'm into concrete investments, and I always wanted to work for myself."<p>Insisting on low overhead and plowing profits back into his company, Campbell already has produced about 35 artists on his Luke Records label. He's pulled in acts from genres other than rap--including H-Town, a rhythm-and-blues group that hit platinum sales this year.<p>Campbell isn't the only one using capitalism to expand beyond rap's usual boundaries. Eazy-E, former head of the vicious "gangsta" rap outfit N.W.A (Niggaz With Attitude) and boss of his own Ruthless Records, is banking on his new Jewish duo, Blood of Abraham. Seattle's Sir Mix-a-Lot is releasing the jazz-backed poetry readings of Jazz Lee Alston.<p>Indeed, in 1993 a corporate logo has become rap's ultimate status symbol. New Jersey's Queen Latifah and Long Island's Parrish Smith started their own labels this year, while MC Lyte and others recently formed artist-management companies.<p>"Rappers used to invest in cars, jewelry, and Moet," says Michael Gonzales, coauthor of rap guide Bring the Noise. "But Eazy-E and Luke showed that you can make some money if you get an office, buy a Xerox machine, and run a company."<p>Other rock and pop stars have launched successful labels--Prince heads Paisley Park, Herb Alpert created A&M --but the new rap moguls surpass most artists when it comes to signing hit acts year after year. Campbell's Poison Clan hit the Billboard Top 100 chart recently, for example. Eazy-E's biggest earners include Michel'le and MCRen, whose 1992 EPwent platinum.<p>By contrast, none of the new artists on Madonna's Maverick label have gone gold.<p>Many of rap's new entrepreneurs are backed by large distributors, but Campbell and Eazy-E have kept surprising independence. Campbell released his first 2 Live Crew single in 1985 with $10,000 he earned as a Miami DJ and party promoter. He kept costs low and could afford to cut out the middleman by distributing and manufacturing his own records.<p>Eazy-E, who grew up as Eric Wright in impoverished Compton near Los Angeles, started Ruthless with $25,000 he earned from illegal activities. He sold his records from the back of a car at swap meets. "Eric learned his sense of business from the streets," says former rock promoter Jerry Heller, a 50-year-old M.B.A. who has been Eazy-E's top employee since 1986. "He has a very Machiavellian sense of power and control."<p>After releasing several local hit singles, Eazy-E signed a distribution deal with Atco, followed by similar deals. He recently shifted most business to Relativity Records, where he negotiated for more control. "I ain't into up-front money," he says. "A deal is about getting the right percentage at the back end."<p>Campbell and Eazy-E spend between $175,000 and $275,000 of their own cash to make a record, video, and marketing plan for each new artist. In such a money-conscious atmosphere, even the finances of new proteges come under scrutiny. Parrish Smith asks the rappers on his PMD(Parrish Making Dollars) label to save 40 percent of their income: "We try to get them to put off buying the Benz and buy a cheap house instead."<p>The stars themselves also dabble in investments outside the industry. Eazy-E is a major shareholder in a bank and a software company, for example. Smith rents out homes on Long Island, while Campbell plays in blue-chip stocks and made a bundle as an early investor in ClearlyCanadian drinks.<p>Running a label, however, is the only form of capitalism that's as much fun as rapping. "It's a gamble," says Eazy-E of business. "But you might as well take the chance. If I make $500, I'll either turn it into $1,000 or I'll leave with nothing."<p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Small Business Ownership

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

