				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-He Said, She Said</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Andrew Feinberg<p>Among today's politically aware baby boomers, it's a rare couple that doesn't manage its investments as a team:The macho money man is a dying breed. But while they may agree on investment goals--well, sometimes, anyway--men and women still speak different languages when it comes to money, according to financial planners, brokers, and psychologists. Here's a brief guide to the comments these professionals hear from couples every day.<p>
On their lousy track record:<p>She:We've never been very good with money.<p>He:I've been too busy working.<p>On their investment skills<p>She: I'm not sure we're on the right track.<p>He:We've done okay.<p>
On risK:<p>She:I don't want to lose this.<p>He: How fast can we make this grow?<p>On indecipherable jargon<p>She:I don't understand what you just said.<p>He:I've been reading up on that. Could you go through it again?<p>
On losers:<p>She:We should never have bought that stock. That was stupid.<p>He:We should never have listened to that broker. He was a jerk.<p>On winners<p>She:I was lucky.<p>He:I've always had a feel for technology stocks.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Family Finance

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
