<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Celestial Reasonings</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Celestial Reasonings</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Is the market a Taurus or Ursa Major? Financial seers seek answers in the stars.<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Heaven knows whether the economy will falter or whether stocks will reach dizzying new heights. That's why we asked four noted financial astrologers what the stars have been saying lately:<p>Henry Weingarten, who says he manages about $9 million in assets, thinks a "Clinton crash" could hit this month or next--and that economic catastrophe is coming. Although the Dow Jones Industrial Average topped 3600 recently, Weingarten predicts a plunge to 2800 by December and a 1994 low of 2000. On the bright side, the conjunction of Uranus and Neptune, which brings chaos and confusion, will ultimately result in "a new vision," whatever that means. The new year will be good to real estate, he says, and gold will top $500 an ounce.<p>Cambridge grad Graham Bates was expecting a sharp dip in stock prices on September 30. After a brief recovery, he augured, a 300-point drop in the Dow would likely happen in late October or early November. Bates, a London-based astrologer who's a former pension-fund manager and a mathematician by training, tracks correlations between planetary and economic patterns. The opposition of Jupiter and Saturn that accompanied the Depression is happening again, he says, and a buildup of planets in Capricorn indicates great volatility for stocks in 1994. But by the end of 1994, sustained economic growth will lift the market back to all-time highs.<p>"I'm expecting a continued bull market in stocks, because [low] interest rates will continue until November 1998," says Grace Morris, an Oak Lawn, Illinois, astrologer and psychotherapist. Neptune is now in the earth sign of Capricorn, which tends to bring low rates. Morris expects that Virgo companies such as Coca-Cola and Texaco will have tough times in 1994 and 1995, when Saturn goes into Pisces and opposes their sun. But based on the 11-year nodal cycle of the moon, real estate is now reversing a low and won't top out until 2000.<p>Arch Crawford, perhaps the best-known of the celestial seers, has been expecting a big drop in the stock market since April; he says now it might come as late as February 1994. The Uranus-Neptune conjunction, which happens just once every 171 years, is unfolding as Saturn stands at a 90-degree angle to Pluto, itself a 33-year cycle. "If you like the status quo, that's bad," says Crawford. "But if you like change, it's good."He sees fear and political uncertainty knocking the Dow as low as 1200 by 1996 and was planning to sell gold in October so he could buy it back cheap in July 1994. That way, he'll ride out a bout of hyperinflation later in 1994--and be fully prepared when the U.S. is placed under martial law.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Investing Strategies

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
