<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-Blue Highways</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6007.html?worth+PCFN25.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN25.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-Blue Highways</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
Getting a car across the country is no joyride if you pick the wrong shipper<p>By Carla Koehl<p>Aileen gersing was told a $600 deposit and a one-page contract would get her Olds Cutlass trucked from Florida to Seattle in two weeks. Instead, she says, A. Aaron's Auto Shippers sent her car to California, leaving it in a lot where it racked up parking fees until she agreed to pay her $600 balance--which hadn't been due until the car reached Seattle. <p>"They held it hostage," she says of an ordeal that cost her $750 more than planned. (She had to hire another trucker to finish the job.) A. Aaron's president Mitchell Winik declines to comment on Gersing's charges, contained in a complaint filed with the Interstate Commerce Commission, but he previously has blamed a subcontractor for the delay.<p>Gersing is one of hundreds of people each year who run into trouble with car shippers. "It's a big problem, and it's only going to get worse," says Gregory Morrow, senior trial attorney for the ICC, which regulates the trucking industry. "There's no repeat business in car shipping. Why should they care if they screw you over?" Complaints this year describe cars that arrive with 2,000 extra joyride miles on them, cars that arrive damaged beyond repair, and cars left in lots while the company vanishes with customer deposits.<p>Nearly 400 complaints like Gersing's recently prompted the California attorney general to sue Palm Springs-based A. Aaron's, seeking more than $3 million in penalties for alleged nationwide deception of consumers. Resulting injunctions have kept the company out of action since June. Now A. Aaron's is striking back--starting with a suit against <a name="NYSE:T"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10103"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>AT&T</b></a> for cutting off its toll-free telephone number. <p>To protect yourself:
-  Sign a contract with the company actually transporting the car, not just a company brokering the job. (A. Aarons is a broker.)<p>-  If the contract contains a "benefit of insurance" clause, don't sign. Such clauses require customers to claim car damage or loss on their own policies before demanding repayment from the carrier. <p>-  Check with the ICC that the company's insurance is paid and its record is clean--and send along a copy of the contract. Officials there don't give legal advice, but they'll warn about a bad deal.<p><p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

