	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/11-After the Fall, Bonds Hit a Wall</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/11-After the Fall, Bonds Hit a Wall</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Jim Jubak<p>It's been a spectacular downhill run for interest rates. In 1981 short-term rates hit 20 percent, while long-term rates clocked in at 13 percent. Today, 30-day Treasury bills pay just about 3 percent, and the 30-year "long bond" returns a little more than 6 percent.<p>Is this the end of the ride?<p>Probably, even though rates may drift a mite lower in the next six months. That's important for investors to know. Anyone who bought the long bond ten years ago would have earned, on average, almost 15 percent a year-only slightly worse than the S&P 500's performance during the period. (Existing bonds, with their higher interest payments locked in, rise in price when interest rates fall.)To match that showing for another year, however, long-term rates would have to drop another whole point, an unlikely prospect.<p>further declines aren't impossible, of course. after all, rates fell for 27 years from 1873 to 1900:The yield on railroad bonds, the benchmark of that era, sank to 3.18 percent from 6.5 percent. The greatest decline of this century sent rates even lower, to 2.45 percent on high-quality corporate issues in 1946, from 5.98 percent 26 years earlier. But while those bond rallies lasted a quarter century each, this one has matched their declines in half the time.<p>By this measure, the bottom is surely near.<p>The same conclusion comes from looking at real interest rates, rather than nominal rates. Nominal rates are what bonds, CDs, and bank accounts pay out-the number touted in your bank's window or in your broker's memos. To figure real rates, just subtract inflation.<p>Nominal rates jump all over the lot, following inflation, but real long-term rates remain remarkably stable at 3 percent, says David Munro, chief U.S. economist at High Frequency Economics in New York. With inflation now hovering at about 3 percent, nominal interest rates near 6 percent are in line with the historic norm.<p>betting on significantly lower rates, then, amounts to a risky guess that the 1990s will prove a historical anomaly. Such periods do exist:In the mid-1930s, for example, nominal rates ranged from 4 percent to 7 percent while inflation was essentially zero-a boon for investors. In the 1970s, rampant inflation meant that real rates were negative 1 or 2 percent for much of the decade.<p>The 1990s could also buck history, but Munro doesn't think it's likely. "Those were boom and bust periods," he says. "This economy is singularly neither a boom nor a bust."<p>That said, the current inflation number may overstate the health of the economy. The true figure, maintains Munro, is closer to 2.5 percent, giving rates a bit of room to fall yet. Investors can expect a few blips in rates, but "we're wobbling down" to a target of about 5.5 percent on the long bond, he predicts. <p>whether that's positive depends on your point of view. Paltry economic growth paired with modest inflation is good for economists and the bankers at the Federal Reserve, who despised the boom-and-bust economy of the 1980s. But for investors, it's come time to squeeze the last drops from the bond market and look elsewhere for double-digit returns.<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Bond Investing, Economy

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
