		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Wrong Again About Citicorp?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Wrong Again About Citicorp?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						<p>By Monica Corcoran<p>Well, the rehabilitation of <a name="NYSE:CCI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10345"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Citicorp</b></a> (CCI) is complete. In July, Fortune put its stamp of approval on the company's new seriousness. The bank, it seems, will be generating profits instead of red ink from now on.<p>Most of Wall Street agrees. The megabank has shed 14,000 jobs and pared $1.3 billion in costs over the past two years. All that, the herd says, should now drop to the bottom line. As of midsummer, 15 of the 27 analysts tracked by Research Holdings Limited have buys or buy/holds on the stock.<p>But wait. We hear skeptics crying in the wilderness__at least the wilderness not tracked by RHL. The bank, the skeptics say, has again only papered over its problems. Frankly, given Citicorp's history, we think the outnumbered bears deserve a listen.<p>
BUY: "I think that a powerful earnings recovery is in the making, and you have a very cheap stock on your hands. Citicorp is trading at 1.3 times book average while most regional banks are trading at 1.8. It's more investable today than at any other time in the past 20 years."
Projected earnings: $2.85 for this fiscal year, $4.25 for '94.<p>Arthur Soter, Morgan Stanley<p>
BUY: "In the long term, I think CCI has a unique franchise, with substantial stakes in high-growth areas of the world."
Projected earnings: $2.85 for this year, $4.75 for '94.<p>David Berry, Bruyette & Woods <p>
MAY SELL: "Citicorp is the least well-capitalized of the banks we follow. We think their capital needs will be greater than they've been saying. Citicorp has to raise $4 billion or $5 billion of common equity, and they've already done a lot of the easy things. Also, management at Citicorp is unknown at this point. Why should shareholders have to put up with that when there are better options out there?"
Projected earnings: $2.30 for this year, $2.75 for '94.<p>Raphael Soifer,
Brown Brothers Harriman<p>
SELL: "I advocate shutting the bank down. Look at their reserves for bad loans. The Feds are basically carrying Citicorp by not requiring them to take write-offs. It's going to be a disaster. Unless you believe in the miraculous real estate recovery, these guys are doomed. The numbers they're publishing are ridiculous."<p>Projected earnings: $2.50 for this year, $3.00 for '94.
Michael Murphy, Overpriced Stock Service<p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing, Banking Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
