<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-What Goes Down Must Come Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-What Goes Down Must Come Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						
<a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip Morris</b></a> show different prospects for recovery<p>By Derrick Neiderman<p>It's no secret that some highly visible companies have had an extremely difficult year in the stock market. Wal-Mart, Merck, and Philip Morris, to name three, are all trading between 25 percent and 40 percent lower than they did earlier in the year. Do any of these stocks have a chance of rebounding soon? Unfortunately, stocks don't rebound simply because they declined in the first place. Yes, the stock market is capable of overreacting to short-term problems, and yes, the essence of long-term investing is, in part, to hold on and weather the hard times. However, the plain truth is that downtrodden stocks tend to need a true catalyst to reverse direction.<p>Wal-Mart (WMT) may not get the catalyst it needs. Until this year, the sales growth at stores open at least one year exceeded 10 percent, far above the rates reported by other discount retailers. When the company announced same-store sales-growth expectations of 7 to 8 percent__good, but apparently not good enough__earlier this year, Wal-Mart stock slid and has yet to recover.<p>The decline in same-store growth is only part of the story. Wal-Mart, although still the class of the retail industry, cannot possibly maintain its historic growth levels: Earnings per share grew at a compound annual rate of 29 percent over the last eight years, fueled by the company's rapid expansion into new territory. <p>Wal-Mart stock will come back, but not because it is a bargain. Even today, Wal-Mart trades at 26 times its expected 1993 earnings, a decided premium to the overall market. The expected comeback is therefore likely to be a protracted one, coming from steady, somewhat lower growth.<p>Merck & Co. (MRK) shares have been weak, along with virtually everything else in the pharmaceutical sector. What the stock needs in the short term is for investor psychology to improve, which presumably would happen if the Clinton administration's health-care sanctions turn out to be less damaging to these companies than is expected.<p>Not all drug companies, however, are created equal. Although Merck is better positioned than such companies as <a name="NYSE:LLY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10509"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Eli Lilly</b></a>, Syntex, and Upjohn__which are all facing similar periods of declining earnings__disappointing sales of Merck's Proscar prostate treatment and the company's apparent overdependence on pricing power have chipped away at its traditional industry leadership position. By contrast, shares of <a name="NYSE:SGP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11326"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Schering-Plough</b></a> have almost fully made up the ground they lost in the first half of 1993 on the strength of the company's existing products and its new drug pipeline. Industry leadership appears to be changing, and a rebound for Merck cannot be assumed.<p>That leaves Philip Morris Cos. (MO). Pricing power had for years been the company's main strength, so when it announced sharp price cuts for its Marlboro cigarette brand earlier this year, the $77 stock crashed to $45 almost immediately. Yet now, with the stock trading under $50 a share, the $2.60 dividend gives Philip Morris a yield of more than 5 percent, the highest among the 30 Dow industrials. The dividend is sustainable on the company's non-tobacco earnings alone. <p>What this means is that Philip Morris shares have a new basis for valuation, one that provides downside support as investors await signs that the domestic tobacco business is improving. When these signs appear__or when the dividend is raised__the stock should react favorably and begin to move off the bottom.<p> <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Stock Investing Strategies, Stock Market Trends

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

