	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-The Tax Revolt: A Bunch of Ingrates?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-The Tax Revolt: A Bunch of Ingrates?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Activists rebuff a politician who voted their way on the budget<p>By Emanuel Howard<p>In no state has the tax revolt of the 1990s run hotter than in New Jersey. It almost cost Bill Bradley his senate seat in 1990. It made "Dump Florio" bumper stickers the automotive accessory of choice. (Governor Jim Florio became the bte noire of the movement after he raised taxes in 1990.) And in 1991 it was pivotal in ending 17 years of Democratic dominance in the state legislature when it handed Republicans a lopsided majority.<p>But the beast still isn't satisfied. Just ask Frank Lautenberg, New Jersey's other Democratic senator. Lautenberg's vote on the budget against his own party's president is clear evidence that the tax revolt has not spent its energy __ even if the movement is increasingly vague on exactly what concrete measures it wants.<p>In the first round of voting in June on Clinton's tax plan, Lautenberg was one of six Senate Democrats who turned their backs on the president and voted with Republicans against the budget bill. "It's rather like supporting Franklin Roosevelt in 1932 and then not voting for the New Deal in 1933," says Republican New Jersey State Assemblyman Leonard Lance.<p>To hear Lautenberg tell it, he took a great political risk to protect the interests of the poor, elderly, and middle-class people of New Jersey. Lautenberg's spokesman, Steve Schlein, insists that the senator's vote was "fairly consistent" with his record and that the 40,000 postcards delivered to his office in a wheelbarrow by the Coalition Against Higher Taxes did not influence him.<p>"Bull," says Dick Zimmer, Republican congressman from New Jersey's 12th District and contender for the senator's seat in 1994. "Frank Lautenberg's vote was expedient." Prior to the Senate vote Zimmer harnessed the energies of New Jersey's anti-tax forces and led the charge against the state's senators. Bradley, who is halfway into his six-year term, wasn't swayed.<p>So what did Lautenberg get for his trouble?<p>"I think that absent the tax revolt of 1990, [Lautenberg's vote against the bill] would have never happened," muses Bobbie Horowitz, co-chair of Hands Across New Jersey, a key member of the anti-tax coalition in the state. "So I do think it's significant. But is it sincere? Probably not. And if it really mattered, if the party really depended on Lautenberg's vote, I'm not sure that it would not have been there." Says Patricia Ralston, the group's other chair, "I know that if Lautenberg wasn't up for reelection he would have voted yes. And I'm going to do everything in my power to have him knocked out of office." <p>Laments Schlein, "You can't win."<p>In fact, the tax revolt in New Jersey may be entering a new phase in which no politician wins. In 1992, when the movement peaked, rivers of blood ran down the Democratic side of the state legislature. Since then, the Republican-controlled body has done little to reverse Governor Jim Florio's tax package, save repeal a penny of the state's sales tax. Elected ears are burning in both parties. "We know the Republicans aren't pure because Bob Dole is a big tax man himself," says Tom Pearson, president of Bergen County-based Tax Revolt North. "The last biggest tax bill in history was his, in 1984." The anti-tax coalition recently met with Ross Perot's tactician, Orson Swindle.<p>The next test of the clout and strategy of the revolt comes this fall when Florio runs for reelection. After falling to single-digit approval ratings, Florio has rebounded. The polls in July were showing a virtual dead heat, with both Florio and his expected Republican challenger Christine Todd Whitman at 38 percent.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Politics, Taxation, Government Legislation

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

