		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Labor Marches On</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Labor Marches On</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 <p>By Pam Earing<p>Although Labor Day parades continue to shrink and union membership shrivels, we all continue to labor. All the trends suggest that by 2000 we'll be members of a very different workforce, spending our days in a very different workplace. One comforting fact about work in America, though: It could be worse. In a poll of U.S. office workers, 43 percent said they were satisfied with their jobs. In Japan, only 17 percent said they were. <p>Number of workers expected to enter the U.S. labor force between 1985 and 2000: 25 million<p>Percentage that will be white males: 15<p>Percentage of companies that electronically monitor their employees: 22<p>Percentage of companies conducting electronic surveillance that don't warn their employees: 66<p>Percentage of U.S. workers who say they do not receive an annual performance review: 45<p>Percentage of major companies that provide or plan to provide some sort of diversity training for managers: 60<p>Percentage of black executives who say they do not think they will ever be considered for a top-level job in their company: 56<p>Percentage of office workers who feel that making a significant contribution at work is important: 72<p>Percentage of top management who feel that making such a contribution is important: 39<p>Percentage of new jobs in the year 2000 that will require at least a high school education: 60<p>Percentage of people currently entering the labor force with less than a high school education: 70<p>Fastest-growing category of worker compensation claims: job stress (now 22 percent of all claims)<p>Fastest-growing category of workplace illness: cumulative trauma disorders (61 percent of all illnesses reported)<p>Leading cause of workplace fatalities in New York City: homicide<p> <p><p><p>
KEYWORDS: Employment

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
