<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Is It High Yield or a Mirage?</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Is It High Yield or a Mirage?</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
Some money-market funds want investors so badly they'll cut their fees__at first<p>By Tim Middleton<p>Money-market yields have been cut to the bone. Taxable funds, which make up three-quarters of the market, currently net just 2.6 percent, and tax-frees a paltry 1.8 percent, according to IBC/Donoghue.<p>But those are just average yields. Some funds are doing much better by their investors, and others much worse. Pretty much all of the difference is due to the amount that a money-market manager charges investors to run the fund. Some managers in the $574 billion industry charge four times as much in fees as others. And every cent of that comes out of the interest an investor could be earning.<p>In this environment, it makes sense to search for a money-market fund with low expenses and better-than-average returns. But before investors switch, they should read a bit of fine print. Some funds run genuinely tight ships, with expenses lower than the industry average of 60 basis points. (Fund-management expenses are measured in basis points, 100 of which make one percentage point.) But other funds look good only because the fund company has decided to waive all or part of its expense charges, a practice called undertaking. Half the nation's 930 funds, up from one-quarter just two years ago, are undertaking. Eight of the ten least-expensive funds as ranked by Donoghue, including Strong U.S. Treasury, First Union Treasury, and INVESCO Treasurer's, are atop the list only because they undertake. <p>What's so bad about this? A fund can decide to stop undertaking at any time. These funds are betting that eating expenses now will pull in investors who either won't notice when the fund stops undertaking or will be too lazy to move their money even if they do notice. Investors, therefore, have two good choices. They can avoid the undertakers and stick with funds that really have their expenses under control, or they can go with the deal now and be ready to move when the expense-waiver is rescinded.<p>For example, the exceptional 3.3 percent return offered on the Aetna Money Market Fund is possible only because the $72 million portfolio has been absorbing fees and expenses since the fund's inception in January 1992. Aetna reckons its actual fees and expenses total 70 points; imposing them would make it just another face in the crowd. Some 40 percent of customers are new to the insurer-cum-mutual fund complex. "Yield shoppers will switch funds to pick up 20 or 30 basis points," notes Christian Thwaites, an Aetna marketing aide. Aetna hopes they'll tarry to sample other wares such as annuities.<p>On the other hand, some money-market funds are run by genuine skinflints. One of the few true low-cost operators, Vanguard Group, has annual charges that reduce gross yields on its money funds by 30 points or less, and actual returns therefore run well above average. And Vanguard keeps expenses low despite offering all the bangles offered by more expensive funds, such as unlimited check writing ($250 minimum). "When you look at our expense ratios, you're looking at what it costs for all the bells and whistles," says Ian MacKinnon, boss of the group's $48 billion fixed-income portfolio.<p>Exactly what do those higher expense ratios go for at other funds? Profit for the fund manager is the simple answer. One of the highest-cost operators, Shearson Money Market Portfolio, deducted 130 basis points from a gross yield of 3.39 percent in the first quarter. That left just 2.09 percent for investors. Shearson also limits use of the cash to its own family of mutual funds; outright withdrawals can result in a back-end load of up to 5 percent.<p>It isn't that hard to escape the high-fee graveyard. High rollers can seek out funds with huge minimums: Vanguard's Admiral requires a balance of $50,000, but charges are a rock-bottom 15 points. Low-cost offerings with above-average net yields and the more conventional minimum of $3,000 include the U.S. Treasury Fund from Gabelli, another true skinflint.<p>Anyone who still insists on paying top dollar, incidentally, has plenty of choices. Oppenheimer Cash Reserves, SunAmerica Money Market Securities, and Mutual of Omaha Money Market Account each recently charged 129 points or more and reported net yields in the low 2 percent range.<p>A readily available benchmark on yields, published daily in the "Money Rates" table in newspapers, is the net return on <a name="NYSE:MER"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10990"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merrill Lynch</b></a> Ready Assets Trust. It's a top performer and its charges are about average.
 <p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

