<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-Headed for the Rough</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-Headed for the Rough</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
The mania for REITs makes a bad deal possible<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>Golf is more popular than ever. So are real estate investment trusts. Putting the two together in National Golf Properties, a real estate investment trust (REIT) that will own golf courses, would appear to be a stroke of genius. Savvy investors instead score this a bogey that illustrates how the popularity of REITs is making it possible to sell some questionable deals.<p>National Golf is part of a drive by <a name="NYSE:MS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11018"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Morgan Stanley & Co.</b></a> to capitalize on the REIT craze now sweeping Wall Street. The blue-chip Wall Street firm, which has limited experience with REITs, is expected to rake in $15 million in fees for raising about $200 million from investors in an initial public offering that was in the works in mid-July. But National Golf is a REIT that, as it was structured at press time, scores better for the investment bankers than for investors.<p>"This is a deal that probably shouldn't get done at just a 7 percent yield," says Ken Campbell, an Upper Saddle River, New Jersey, money manager who specializes in real-estate securities. "But because it's got golf in the name and it's a REIT, it just may do well."<p>Golf is hot on the street right now. The only other pure plays on golf are both smashing successes: <a name="NYSE:ELY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15521"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Callaway Golf Co.</b></a>, which makes the Big Bertha club, has nearly doubled in price since its February 1992 initial public offering; <a name="NASD:ALDA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16236"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Aldila Inc.</b></a>, which makes graphite tubing used in golf clubs, went public in June at $14 a share and within weeks soared to $26.<p>Because National Golf isn't just a golf play, it's raking in the green. A heavy calendar of upcoming public offerings ensures that 1993 will be by far the biggest year yet for REITs. And REIT stocks have risen smartly since real estate bottomed in 1990, showing a total return of 36 percent in 1991, 12 percent in 1992, and 16 percent in the first half of 1993, according to the National Association of Real Estate Investment Trusts in Washington, D.C.<p>But real estate pros say they wouldn't touch National Golf's initial public offering with a ten-foot nine iron. The company is fraught with conflicts of interest, and its unusual corporate structure could jeopardize its special tax status as a REIT.<p>REITs, which are formed to buy properties, mortgages, and other real estate assets, were created by a 1960 federal law that exempts real estate companies from taxation if they pay out at least 95 percent of their income as dividends. Typically, the special tax status accorded a REIT sails past the IRS without a question. But National Golf isn't a typical REIT.<p>"We think there's a real risk of the IRS stripping the company of its REIT status, and that would be a catastrophe for the stock," says Robert Steers, chairman of Cohen & Steers, which manages a top-performing real estate mutual fund.<p>National Golf is an untested kind of REIT, one of just a half-dozen "umbrella partnership" REITs, or UPREITs. The first UPREIT went public less than a year ago__and the IRS hasn't yet ruled on its tax status. The agency may eventually find that UPREITs don't qualify for the favorable tax treatment accorded REITs.<p>Unlike traditional REITs, shareholders in UPREITs don't own real estate directly. The property is owned by a limited partnership, and the REIT owns the partnership. Investors in National Golf will own 53 percent of the units in the partnership; the rest will be owned almost entirely by David G. Price, who heads one of the premier golf-course management companies in the nation.<p>Price chose the UPREIT vehicle because it allowed him to transfer 47 golf courses he owned to the partnership without actually selling them, thus avoiding any capital gains taxes. That too could hurt National Golf, says Steers, if the IRS rules that Price's transfer of the golf courses was actually a sale for tax purposes.<p>While National Golf's status with the IRS may be in doubt, the conflicts of interest posed by the deal are clear. The worst is an unusual clause in the prospectus that permits Price to sell all his units in the limited partnership back to the company for cash. "Price might decide to sell his units back to the REIT when golf-course prices are peaking, and the company might be forced to sell new shares of stock or leverage up in order to pay him off," warns William Ackman of Gotham Partners, a hedge fund in New York that invests in REITs.<p>None of this means the deal won't go down, however. With interest rates lower than they've been in decades and investors dissatisfied with a return of less than 3 percent on a money market fund, National Golf's 7 percent annual dividend may seem an irresistible attraction. Ackman urges discretion. "Investors are being yield pigs," he says. "They don't understand that return of capital is more important than return on capital."<p> <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Real Estate Investing, Taxation, Sports Industry

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

