<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 93/09-A Mutual Fund for Daredevils</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Archives>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b> </b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>93/09-A Mutual Fund for Daredevils</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						 
He's number one, but should any investor bet on Thieme?<p>By Andrew Gluck<p>"I don't have a strategy," says mutual fund manager Heiko Thieme. "I just do whatever's necessary to shoot for returns of 15 to 25 percent a year." Lately, he's delivered. But should any investor be willing to follow this daredevil, even for that kind of return?<p>The stage for Thieme's high-wire act was set in February 1990, when the German-born lawyer left his job as a stock strategist for the American subsidiary of Deutsche Bank to take over the <a name="FUND:AHERX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/AHERX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>American Heritage Fund</b></a>, a battered 40-year-old stock fund. Thieme paid just $10,000 for the fund-management company. Paying more than a pittance would have been crazy, because American Heritage wasn't just a bad fund: It was the worst mutual fund in the nation over the preceding five years. Ever the showman, Thieme viewed that as a strength. "I thought, if I own the worst- performing fund, that will be newsworthy," he says.<p>But 1990 was almost a disaster. Thieme sank about $200,000 of his own money into the venture, for overhaul and administration. Despite 90-hour workweeks, Thieme showed a dismal 30 percent loss that first year.<p>The next year, Thieme turned things around. Between the beginning of 1991 and the end of last June, American Heritage has been number one, according to Lipper Analytical Services Inc., up nearly 200 percent__more than four times the gain of the average stock fund. American Heritage gained 96 percent in 1991 and 18.9 percent in 1992, and was up 30 percent in the first six months of 1993.<p>Thieme's technique seems to be frenetic activity, and lots of it. He has turned over his portfolio in the last three years five times more often than the average fund manager has. He's also served up a smorgasbord of unusual tactics that includes shorting stocks, day trading, making dividend plays, and a touch of market timing. "I have ten years' experience running a trading desk at Deutsche Bank," he says. "Why shouldn't I use it?" It's not uncommon for Thieme's $100 million fund to trade in and out of $10 million of stock in a single day.<p>Such techniques are rare for a mutual fund manager, and Thieme's main profit-making tactics are more mainstream. But they are equally aggressive. He times the market (he has maintained a 25 to 35 percent cash position in recent months, for fear of a market pullback) and he makes big bets on beaten-down blue chips and small growth companies no one has ever heard of.<p>For a blue chip to qualify, it must be hated by most other investors. Three of the fund's five largest positions were contrarian plays on America's most out-of-favor, well-known brand names: <a name="NYSE:MO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11179"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Philip MorrisL</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:MRK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10986"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Merck</b></a>, and <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>.<p>The rest of the fund's stock position is in scantily covered midsize and small-company stocks that are often too small or too risky for institutional investors. For instance, Senetek (ADR OTC), a British biotech company with a market capitalization of about $25 million when Thieme bought it in September 1992, is the fund's largest position, accounting for 7 percent of assets in early July. No other fund tracked by Morningstar owned even a single share of Senetek, according to analyst Amy Arnott.<p>"I am a risk taker," says Thieme, who studied law in Hamburg, Edinburgh, and Berkeley before moving to the United States for good in the late 1970s. "But I take only calculated risks." Thieme's leisure-time activities belie that claim. He flies planes and skydives, and he claims to have eaten razor blades. In 1972, he bluffed his way up the Matterhorn, telling an instructor he had climbed Mount Whitney in California. "He asked me which side I climbed," recalls Thieme. "I said, 'Not the easy side.'"<p>Thieme, an intensely public man, has assiduously courted the press, averaging at least one appearance a week on financial TV talk shows, where he unabashedly hypes his record. Time will tell whether Thieme's turnaround of American Heritage is a fluke or the first outing of a masterful investor. Either way, the show should be a great one.<p>Investors with weak hearts, however, might be better off just watching.
 <p><p>
KEYWORDS: Mutual Funds Investing

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
