	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Need To Know: Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Need To Know: Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Don't Cry for Argentina<p>
Madonna's star turn as Evita has stirred up the pride of the Peronists in Argentina. Perhaps she will inadvertently stir up the Argentine market, too, by reminding U.S. investors that more than Mexico and Telmex stock lie south of Texas. Argentina's Merval stock index could be ready for a nice run. After all, with so many markets flying high in 1996, Argentina's looked mediocre with only a 16 percent gain.<p>
Yet economic conditions are good in Argentina. The toughest challenge of the past three years has arisen not internally but from Mexico. All of Latin America has suffered from the devaluation of the Mexican peso in late 1994, an experience known in the markets as the Tequila Effect: Investors caught in Mexico's stock-market crash felt as if they had swallowed the worm at the bottom of the tequila bottle. They concluded that finances elsewhere in Latin America must be much worse than official reports claimed and assumed that governments couldn't be trusted not to devalue their currencies.<p>
Argentina, however, has been pushing real economic measures and public-relations policies to demonstrate its commitment to a solid currency, a responsible fiscal budget, and economic reforms. The key to Argentina's economic credibility is its Convertibility Plan, which prevents the government from artificially pumping up the money supply and inciting inflation, which averaged a whopping 6,800 percent in 1990. Essentially, the government has pegged the Argentine peso to the U.S. dollar and promised that anyone can exchange pesos for an equivalent number of dollars. It guarantees this trade-in value by printing only as many pesos as it has dollars. At the height of the Mexican crisis, Argentine officials pledged to buy back every single peso if they had to. That's a strong commitment -- so strong that comforted investors didn't take them up on it.<p>
While the plan saved Argentina's credibility, it pinched the economy. In order to continue attracting foreign investors and keep those dollars in its vaults, Argentina had to jack up interest rates, which in turn slowed the economy. Peso CD rates jumped from average returns of 8 percent in 1994 to 11.67 percent in 1995. The gross domestic product, which grew at 7.4 percent in 1994, shrank to 4.4 percent in 1995. Unemployment leaped from 11.5 percent in 1994 to 17.4 percent in 1995. Last year, it hardly improved, drifting down to 17 percent.<p>
Such wrenching changes in the economy put tremendous pressure on President Carlos Menem's government. But Menem had a convenient fall guy: then economy minister Domingo Cavallo. Since Cavallo was widely known -- and hailed -- as the father of the Convertibility Plan, he was blamed for its painful side effects. Once the economy started growing again in 1996, Menem removed Cavallo, a future political rival.<p>
Like Evita's life, Argentina's economy has drama and captivating personalities. Right now, that story is in a good phase. The economy has been pulling out of the recession for a few quarters, racking up a 6.6 percent GDP gain in the third quarter of 1996, paced by a 17 percent jump in fixed investments -- a sign of renewed confidence. Cavallo's replacement enjoys a reputation for fiscal toughness and has the stature to resist political attacks on the Convertibility Plan. Like all emerging markets, Latin America's are allergic to higher U.S. interest rates, which tend to keep speculative money at home. But barring Federal Reserve Board tightening, 1997 may be the most relaxing time in Latin America since Mexico exploded in December 1994.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
