	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Need To Know: Best Buys: Fixed Income</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Need To Know: Best Buys: Fixed Income</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The 30-year bond may yet rally enough to drive its yield decisively below the magical 6 percent mark, but investors will have to wait until later in 1997. The bond fell 3.2 percent in value during the first three weeks of December, cruelly disappointing the many buyers who had expected a rally through the Christmas holiday. Only a weaker-than-expected Christmas retail season is likely to move interest rates lower quickly and give investors who are speculating on rates the reward they seek. This page displays the results of our search for high-yielding investments that offer different levels of safety and liquidity, depending on an investor's goals and investment horizon. Our top picks below represent the best choice for the investor who (1) needs cash, (2) wants near-term yield, or (3) seeks long-term returns.    <p>
**As Safe and Liquid as Cash**
Our picks with an emphasis on safety<p>
We look at Treasury bills, money-market funds, bank money funds, and short-term CDs -- instruments that lock up money for no more than three months -- for this category. Safety is paramount here. The competition for savers' dollars has heated up: Many banks are now offering high promo rates, while many top-ranked taxable money funds are waiving at least a portion of their fees. Fund managers continue to maintain longer-than-average maturities as they lock in rates in anticipation of declines in short-term rates. The average maturity for taxable money funds is now 54 days (out of a maximum 90 days), while the typical tax-free fund averages 50 days. <p>
TAXABLE<BR>
Fund, Telephone Number, Yield<BR>
OLDE Premium Plus Money Market Fund, 800-872-6533, 5.70%<BR>
Strong Heritage Money Fund, 800-368-1030, 5.70<BR>
Southern Pacific Thrift & Loan (CA), 3-mth. CD, 800-428-5056, 5.65<BR>
Bluebonnet Savings (TX), 3-mth. CD, 800-343-5874, 5.56<BR>
Abbotsford Bank (WI), Money Market Account, 800-288-2229, 5.55<BR>
<BR>
TAX-FREE<BR>
