	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Need To Know: What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The four top financial-newsletter writers below identify their favorite domestic stocks. The price listed with each writer's stock pick is the maximum at which he considers the recommended stock attractive. Remember that the newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages, and may have changed his opinion after the December 20 publishing deadline.<p>
Al Frank
The Prudent Speculator
Looks for undervalued stocks with the potential for long-term appreciation.
<a name="NASD:DFLX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13173"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>DATAFLEX </b></a> (Nasdaq: DFLX)  Up to $3.15
Dataflex (Clearwater, Florida) sells, services, and supports desktop-computer equipment, primarily through contracts with large companies. (Its lines include the likes of <a name="NYSE:IBM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10796"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>IBM</b></a>, <a name="NYSE:CPQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10381"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Compaq</b></a>, and <a name="NASD:AAPL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12644"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Apple</b></a>.) In 1994 and 1995, Dataflex undertook a series of acquisitions that left it saddled with heavy debt. In 1996, however, the company embarked on a major consolidation, shedding nearly two-thirds of its businesses and pruning its debt to $22 million from $65 million. I expect profitability to return quickly. The stock now trades near an eight-year low and considerably below its book value of $4.96 a share. My three- to five-year target price is six dollars.<p>
Jim McCamant
Medical Technology Stock Letter 
Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies.
GENEMEDICINE Up to $6
GeneMedicine (the Woodlands, Texas) is at the forefront of the biotech industry in developing gene-therapy products that will be used more like traditional drugs -- a breakthrough that will allow physicians to control the dose and length of treatment. GeneMedicine has strategic partnerships with Roche Bioscience to develop treatments for severe asthma and with Boehringer Ingelheim  to develop cancer treatments. The company has ample cash reserves, and I expect the stock to react positively to the impending announcements of additional corporate partnerships and the initiation of clinical trials. My 18- to 24-month target for the stock is $10 a share.<p>
Michael Murphy
California Technology Stock Letter
Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.
<a name="NASD:OCTL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14306"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>OCTEL COMMUNICATIONS</b></a> (Nasdaq: OCTL)  Up to $25
Octel (Milpitas, California) is the leading maker of equipment for voice-messaging systems. The company has solid underlying financials, and sales have grown an average of 21 percent a year since 1992. Six months ago, the stock was trading as high as $31 a share, but when Octel delayed a product release, the market came down hard -- shares plummeted to $14. But the company has won three large new contracts with cellular companies in South America and Asia and has recently bought back 1.5 million shares. I predict Octel will still earn $1.15 a share for the fiscal year that ends June 1997 and $1.35 a share for fiscal year 1998. My year-end target price is $40.<p>
Louis Navellier
MPT Review
Uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks.
<a name="NYSE:SFY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12354"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>SWIFT ENERGY</b></a>(NYSE: SFY)  Up to $38
Swift Energy (Houston, Texas) is a 17-year-old oil-and-gas company that focuses on exploration and development in 15 states and around the world. For the nine months ended September 1996, Swift's revenues were up 97 percent, and earnings were up 172 percent. The company's oil production increased 17 percent during the period, and its natural-gas production jumped an astounding 98 percent -- in part because of the successful completion of a project in Texas, where the company more than doubled its position in 1996. With continued growth from partnerships and joint ventures, earnings should reach $1.15 a share in 1996 and $1.45 a share in 1997.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

