	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Need To Know: What They're Buying Now</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Eight acclaimed mutual-fund managers tell Worth readers about their current favorite stocks. Assume that the manager has bought the stock for his fund at a price lower than the one mentioned here -- the maximum at which he considers it attractive. The manager also may have sold the stock after December 20, the publishing deadline. The approaches of these managers are meant to illustrate a range of successful investing styles. Before readers buy stock, Worth recommends they conduct their own due diligence.<p>
Preston Athey
<a name="FUND:PRSVX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PRSVX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>T. Rowe Price Small Cap Value</b></a>
Invests in value stocks with market capitalizations under $500 million.
<a name="NASD:RIVL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12649"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>RIVAL</b></a>  (Nasdaq: RIVL)   Up to $27
If you agree with Peter Lynch's idea that investors should consider companies whose products and services they use, then Rival (Kansas City, Missouri) is a good candidate. Who has never used a Rival Crock-Pot or can opener, a Pollenex showerhead, or a Patton fan? Rival is emerging from a period of flat earnings triggered by recent acquisitions -- last year, for example, the company bought Bionaire and Fasco Consumer Products. As these and other acquisitions begin to pay off over the next two years, Rival should enjoy robust earnings. At about 11 times my 1997 earnings estimate of $2.10 a share, the stock is undervalued and underappreciated.<p>
James P. Craig
<a name="FUND:JANSX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/JANSX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Janus Fund</b></a>
Invests primarily in large growth companies with the idea of preserving capital over the long term.
<a name="NYSE:FMS"></a><b>FRESENIUS MEDICAL CARE</b>  (NYSE: FMS)   Up to $32  
Fresenius Medical CareNorth America (Lexington, Massachusetts), the nation's largest provider of dialysis services and products, was created by the merger of National Medical Care and the German manufacturer Fresenius. The result is a dominant and highly efficient company whose 21 percent market share is three times that of its nearest competitor. I expect revenue to grow more than 20 percent a year over the next three to five years, in large part because kidney failure is one of the fastest-growing disease classes in terms of patient numbers. The stock should earn $1.37 a share in 1997 and $1.83 in 1998. My six- to nine-month target for FMC is $40.<p>
Shelby M. C. Davis
New York Venture Fund
Invests in large companies using a value-oriented style.
<a name="NYSE:BAC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10178"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>BANKAMERICA</b></a> (NYSE: BAC)   Up to $100 
BankAmerica (San Francisco) is one of the country's largest holding companies, with holdings that include Bank of America, the biggest bank in California, and banks in seven other states. BankAmerica has ridden out the tough times in California, and now, with the state's economy continuing to gain strength, it should prosper. Cash earnings, including goodwill, have progressed nicely and should be over $9 a share in 1997 and $10 a share in 1998. New chairman David Coulter is bent on raising return on equity as much as 20 percent by pursuing growth initiatives, cutting costs, and repurchasing shares. My two- to three-year target price for the stock is $140. <p>
Daniel B. Leonard
Invesco Strategic Portfolios Technology
Seeks growth stocks in technology and related fields.
<a name="NYSE:TXN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11462"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TEXAS INSTRUMENTS</b></a> (NYSE: TXN)   Up to $70  
Texas Instruments (Dallas) is one of the world's largest manufacturers of semiconductors, electronics, and software. Because of the sharp decline in the price of dynamic random-access-memory (DRAM) chips, 1996 was a down year for the company. However, the company recently reached an agreement with Samsung Electronics whereby Texas Instruments will receive more than $1 billion in royalty payments over the next ten years. In addition, TI is expected to announce its intention to sell its defense division. These events should provide the company with enough cash flow to lower debt and buy back stock. My 12-month target is $90 a share. <p>
William J. Nasgovitz
Heartland Small-CapContrarian Fund 
Buys stocks of small domestic companies believed to be undervalued.
<a name="NASD:TPMI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16754"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PERSONNEL MANAGEMENT</b></a> (Nasdaq: TPMI)   Up to $9  
Personnel Management (Greenwood, Indiana) provides temporary services, a business in which revenue should grow at least 12 percent annually for the next five years. The company had a difficult 1995. While it was busy acquiring mom-and-pop temp operations, it lost sight of its financials. Costs ran out of control, and growth slowed in the company's core Indiana market, where it holds a dominant position. Today, however, Personnel Management has a new CFO and a new COO, and they're turning around the business. I expect the company to post earnings gains of 50 cents a share in 1996 and 75 cents a share in 1997. My 12- to 18-month target price is $13 to $15.<p>
Eric E. Ryback
Lindner Dividend Fund
<a name="NASD:TESC"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=46295"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>TESCORP</b></a> (Nasdaq: TESC)  Up to $6  
Tescorp (Austin, Texas) owns and operates cable systems in rural Argentina, where 90 percent of the population owns a TV set and 55 percent receives cable. Tescorp's strategy, in a time of significant merger activity within the industry, is to buy subscribers at favorable prices and boost cash flow by consolidating overlapping systems and eliminating duplicate costs. The company plans to increase its subscriber base from 58,000 to 150,000 over the next few years. By then, Tescorp will be buying subscribers at a higher rate, so I wouldn't be surprised to see it acquired by a large telecommunications company. My 18-month target price is $11 a share.<p>
Ralph Wanger
Chuck McQuaid
Acorn Fund
Holds stocks of small companies that may benefit from favorable economic trends.
<a name="NYSE:ADZ"></a><b>APPLIED INDUSTRIAL TECHNOLOGIES</b> (NYSE: ADZ)  Up to $30
Applied Industrial Technologies (Cleveland), formerly known as Bearings, changed its name in January (at press date the ticker symbol hadn't been set) to better reflect its product mix. The company distributes mechanical and electrical drive systems, specialty maintenance products, industrial rubber products, and bearings. It is centralizing its inventory into state-of-the-art warehouses to provide better service and has signed several new supply contracts. Both of these moves should boost revenues. The stock is cheap at less than 13 times estimated June 1997 earnings of $2.20 a share and should do well when sales accelerate. My two-year target price is $44.<p>
Donald A. Yacktman
Yacktman Fund
Seeks long-term growth in companies with market capitalization of at least $1 billion.
<a name="NYSE:DFS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16233"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>DEPARTMENT 56</b></a> (NYSE: DFS)  Up to $25
Department 56 (Eden Prairie, Minnesota) designs and distributes a variety of collectibles and giftware, such as porcelain houses and figurines. Since I recommended the stock in June 1996, earnings have rested slightly, in part because some of the company's manufacturers relocated. That's resulting in more-efficient production, which has helped Department 56 bring its successful Heritage Village and Original Snow Village series to the retail shelves much more quickly to meet the growing demand. Orders for the third quarter of 1996 increased 3 percent versus the same quarter in 1995. I expect Department 56 to earn $2.45 a share in 1996, with goodwill included. 

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
