				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Need To Know: 10 Stocks to Avoid/Consider</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						10 to Avoid:
Steven Romick, a portfolio manager for Los Angelesbased First Pacific Advisors, manages the UAM FPA Crescent Fund. The fund is the fourth-best performer over the past three years among the 190 balanced funds tracked by Morningstar. Romick plays a defensive game, looking for stocks with limited downside risk that are either undiscovered or misunderstood by Wall Street -- which explains why he has not had a down quarter during the past three years, a period when the major stock and bond indexes have suffered. His portfolio consists of high-yield bonds and stocks that sell for lower book values and lower multiples of earnings than the market. Romick finds the current market full of overvalued stocks, including U.S. Filter, which sells for 54 times its 12-month earnings despite producing a meager 10 percent return on investors equity. Many competitors of bar-code-scanner manufacturer Symbol Technologies have reported falling margins -- telling Romick that these products are becoming commodities. Software developer and distributor GT Interactive Software has warned investors to expect disappointing sales, and Wal-Mart, its biggest customer, is rumored to be considering dropping the company.<p>
Company (Exchange: Ticker) Fair Value<br>
<br>
<a name="NASD:ADVNA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=12489"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>11Advanta</b></a> (Nasdaq: ADVNA) $33<br>
* Aggressively growing loans<br>
* Delinquencies are increasing <br>
* Recent non-recurring gains <br>
<a name="NYSE:AOL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15558"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>America Online</b></a> (NYSE: AOL) $25<br>
* Loses money on heavy users   <br>
* Ad revenue far below plan<br>
* Cash flow is deeply negative<br>
<a name="NASD:BOST"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16244"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boston Chicken</b></a> (Nasdaq: BOST) $20<br>
* Negative cash from investing <br>
* Overstated earnings, book value <br>
* Low return on investment<br>
<a name="NASD:GTIS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47396"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>GT Interactive Software</b></a> (Nasdaq: GTIS) $4<br>
* Slowing sales<br>
* Heavy reliance on Wal-Mart<br>
* Insider selling<br>
<a name="NASD:MDRX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15556"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Medicis Pharmaceutical</b></a> (Nasdaq: MDRX) $20<br>
* Tax-loss carryforwards hide low level of earnings and growth<br>
* Priced at 15 times book value<br>
<a name="NYSE:OLM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11760"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Olympic Financial</b></a> (NYSE: OLM) $10<br>
* Falling cash flow<br>
* Declining quality of loans<br>
* Under-reserved for loan losses	<br>
<a name="NYSE:SRM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14697"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sensormatic Electronics</b></a>(NYSE: SRM) $12<br>
* Negative cash flow	<br>
* Large accounts receivable<br>
* Falling operating margins<br>
<a name="NASD:STRY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14815"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Stryker</b></a>Stryker (Nasdaq: STRY) (NYSE: SBL) $20<br>
* Negligible growth in revenues<br>
* Lack of new products<br>
* Priced at 28 times earnings<br>
<a name="NYSE:SBL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11420"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Symbol Technologies</b></a> (NYSE: SBL) $30<br>
* Increased competition<br>
* Rise in expenses<br>
* Dependent on overseas growth<br>
<a name="NYSE:USF"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13524"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>U.S. Filter</b></a> (NYSE: USF) $16<br>
* Priced at 54 times earnings<br>
* Low 10 percent return on equity<br>
* Overpaying for acquisitions<br>
<br><p>
10 To Consider: 
Christine Baxter co-manages the $1.4 billion PBHG Emerging Growth Fund, the top-performing small-company growth fund for the past three years, according to Morningstar. (She is also the lead manager of the new PBHG Limited Fund, which opened in July.) Baxter, who joined Wayne, Pennsylvaniabased Pilgrim, Baxter & Associates as a research analyst in 1991, is a disciple of famed momentum investor and Emerging Growth Fund co-manager Gary Pilgrim. Baxter looks for small companies that produce outstanding sales and earnings growth. Because these companies are increasing sales and earnings at 40 to 60 percent a year, their stocks often trade at 60 to 90 times earnings. Her current favorites include Sitel, which has boosted earnings more than 45 percent a year by providing companies with toll-free telephone-service facilities. Inso, a spin-off from Houghton Mifflin, sells software that allows users to view complex documents over the Internet; around one-third of its sales are to Microsoft. Baxter expects Target Therapeutics, a maker of micro-catheters for minimally invasive brain surgery, to increase earnings by 40 percent now that it has received FDA approval of its GDC micro-catheter product. 
<br><p>
Company (Exchange: Ticker) Fair Value<br><p>
<br><p>
<a name="NASD:COGI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=20099"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Consolidated Graphics</b></a> (Nasdaq: COGI) $50<br>
* Aggressive acquisition strategy<br>
* High operating margins<br>
* Earnings grew 41 percent <br>
<a name="NASD:INSO"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=42049"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Inso</b></a>Inso (Nasdaq: INSO) $44<br>
* Fast-growing Internet software<br>
* Innovative distribution strategy <br>
* Strong balance sheet<br>
<a name="NASD:LCRY"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44534"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>LeCroy</b></a>LeCroy (Nasdaq: LCRY) $38<br>
* Strong sales of new product<br>
* New LAN product due in 1997<br>
* Improved operating margins<br>
<a name="NASD:NCSS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=47933"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>NCS HealthCare</b></a> (Nasdaq: NCSS) $32<br>
* Operates pharmacies in fast-growing nursing-facility business  <br>
* Acquisition is boosting margins<br>
<a name="NASD:PSAI"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=20083"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Pediatric Svcs. of America</b></a> (Nasdaq: PSAI) $20<br>
* High margins in home care for chronically ill children <br>
* Hospital partnering strategy<br>
<a name="NASD:SITL"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43788"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Sitel</b></a> (Nasdaq: SITL) $22<br>
* Fast-growing outsourcer of toll-free telephone services <br>
* Active European business <br>
<a name="NASD:TGET"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14840"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Target Therapeutics</b></a> (Nasdaq: TGET) $40<br>
* Innovative brain-surgery product dramatically lowers costs<br>
* Product just approved in U.S.<br>
<a name="NASD:UNSN"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=44052"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Unison Software</b></a> (Nasdaq: UNSN) $30<br>
* Leading network-management software for NT, Oracle, Unix<br>
* Rapidly expanding margins <br>
<a name="NASD:VSVR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=43724"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>VideoServer</b></a> (Nasdaq: VSVR) $50<br>
* Increasing earnings 44 percent a year, with expanding margins <br>
* Partner with Cisco and Compaq<br>
<a name="NASD:WHIT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=51414"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Whittman-Hart</b></a> (Nasdaq: WHIT) $25<br>
* Aggressive regional expansion  <br>
* Serves slighted middle market<br>
* Expanding profit margins<br><p>
Update:
The February 1996 "10 Stocks to Consider" picks by John Wallace, manager of the Robertson Stephens Growth & Income Fund, gained 30.2 percent in the 52 weeks ended December 12, versus an 18 percent gain in the S&P 500. Wallaces biggest winner, Vans, jumped 75 percent, while Monsanto rose 62.5 percent. The "10 Stocks to Avoid" chosen by Potomac, Marylandbased hedge-fund manager Peter Frorer gained just 14.5 percent. General Acceptance dropped the most, falling 78 percent.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

