	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Need To Know: Winners & Losers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan's not-so-cryptic December warning about investors' "irrational exuberance" set the stage for a volatile final month of 1996 for stocks. Earnings surprises and the continued deluge of takeover activity added to the uncertainty. Some high-profile professional money managers profited from the volatility -- others wound up on the wrong end of trades.<p>
WINNER: George Long, Oppenheimer Capital
Oppenheimer chief investment officer Long has been buying up huge blocks of <a name="NYSE:MD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10975"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>McDonnell Douglas</b></a> stock for his institutional clients since 1994. Liftoff occurred on December 16, when <a name="NYSE:BA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10221"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Boeing</b></a> announced it would buy the rival aircraft maker for $13 billion. The one-day gain for Oppenheimer's 26-million-share position: a whopping $275 million.<p>
LOSER: Michael Price, Franklin Mutual Series Funds
Legendary value investor Price gave up on McDonnell Douglas a little too soon, selling 800,000 of his 1.7 million shares in the company just a few months before its takeover by Boeing was announced. His Mutual Series Funds missed out on a possible $8.4 million windfall when McDonnell's shares jumped $10.50 on news of the deal on December 16.<p>
WINNER: Jeffrey Vinik, Vinik Asset Management
Former Magellan Fund manager Vinik's new $800 million hedge fund got off to a quick start last fall, snapping up shares of small companies like electromagnetic-product maker <a name="NASD:INVX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13774"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Innovex</b></a>. Vinik bought 636,000 shares of Innovex in early November, at an average price of $27.25, then sold off more than a third of them as news of his stake drove the stock to nearly $50.<p>
LOSER: Robert Sanborn, Oakmark Fund 
The 3.8 million shares of <a name="NYSE:BDK"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10214"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Black & Decker</b></a>Black & Decker owned by Sanborn's Oakmark Fund fell more than $7 a share the second week of December after the power-tool company pre-announced disappointing earnings. "The market overreacted," says analyst Kevin Grant, who downplays the fund's $28 million loss because "the company's fundamentals are still good."<p>
LOSER: James Stowers III, American Century Investments   
Stowers's Twentieth Century Ultra Fund's 2.5 million shares of Oakley plunged 24 percent on December 5, when the sunglass maker warned investors to expect a sharp decline in fourth-quarter earnings. Ultra, which usually invests in companies with upward price momentum, bought almost 1.3 million shares in the third quarter, according to CDA/Spectrum.<p>
LOSER: Paul Wick, <a name="FUND:SLMCX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/SLMCX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Seligman Communications and Information Fund</b></a>
The stock of disk-drive-component maker <a name="NASD:KMAG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13912"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Komag</b></a>, one of longtime technology investor Wick's largest positions, got nailed the second week of December, when the company announced that manufacturing problems would lower earnings. The 1.9 million shares of Komag in Wick's fund dropped more than 11 points for the week -- a loss of nearly $22 million.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
