<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Need To Know: Keeping Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Need To Know: Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By John Fried<p>
The National Business Conduct Committee, a division of the National Association of Security Dealers regulatory arm, has permanently expelled the brokerage firm Stratton Oakmont from the securities industry. In addition, Stratton Oakmont's president, Daniel M. Porush, and head trader, Steven P. Sanders, were barred from the business as a result of the decision. Stratton had been operating under a Securities and Exchange Commission injunction and was the subject of disciplinary actions by the NASD, including charges of securities fraud, stock manipulation, and violations in connection with initial public offerings. Current Stratton Oakmont accounts will be handled by J. B. Oxford, a Los Angeles brokerage firm.<p>
The new inflation-indexed ten-year Treasury notes haven't generated much investor interest, according to a survey of 57 fixed-income investment firms by Capital Access, a data-research and information-services company in Murray Hill, New Jersey. Only 5 percent of the firms surveyed planned on investing in the notes. Those firms that did show interest said the notes would make up no more than 10 percent of their government portfolio. Uncertainty about the notes, especially in light of potential changes in the consumer price index -- the benchmark against which return on the bonds will be indexed quarterly -- was a reason for the caution.<p>
The board of directors at the New York Stock Exchange has agreed to raise the trigger mark for the "circuit breaker" on the Dow Jones Industrial Average. A drop of 350 points will now trigger a half-hour shutdown; a 550-point drop will result in an hour-long shutdown. Former circuit-breaker limits of 250 points for a half-hour shutdown and 400 points for an hour-long shutdown were set eight years ago, when the broad market was trading at a far lower level than it is today. At the current level , a 350-point drop would equal a decline of about 5 percent.<p>
A majority of high-net-worth individuals surveyed by Bankers Trust said that their financial and legal advisers don't encourage them to be philanthropic. The survey also found that the most often cited factors discouraging philanthropy were a lack of time and a lack of confidence that the money would be put to good use.<p>
The SEC expanded its suit against Charles Huttoe, former chairman and CEO of teleconference-equipment maker Systems of Excellence, who has been accused of writing false press releases about the company through an Internet newsletter -- SGA Goldstar Whisper Stocks -- and then selling the stock as the price grew. In a revised complaint, the SEC said that certain employees of SGA Goldstar Research, the firm that puts together and distributes the newsletter, were bribed with stock to recommend Systems of Excellence. The proposed amended complaint calls for the disgorgement of $12 million, the amount of illegal profits the SEC alleges was obtained through the sale of the security by Huttoe and the other defendants. This is the first case in which the SEC has examined specific use of the Internet in manipulation of a public security. Says SEC assistant director of enforcement Erich T. Schwartz: "It won't be the last." <p>
A new variety of bond fund, offered by fund families like Fidelity and Benham, may make investments in bonds look attractive again. These "target time-line" bond funds have a designated maturity date and offer an assumed yield, which, in Fidelity's case, may vary by plus or minus 50 basis points per year. Investors must keep their money in the fund until the maturity date in order to earn this yield. These bonds, however, are not guaranteed, and anything from a market shake-up to volatile interest rates could stir the fund further away from its quoted yield.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
