<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/02-Need To Know: Living Beyond Our Means</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/02-Need To Know: Living Beyond Our Means</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						Interest rates, trade deficits, and our place in the global Ponzi scheme<p>
By Jim Jubak<p>
December produced a parade of prophets predicting the end of this rally: first, Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan, then Goldman Sachs guru Robert Hormats, and finally Morgan Stanley heavyweight Barton Biggs. They took their best shots, and the market dissed them all.<p>
But as any reader of the Old Testament knows, the prophet who gets pelted with stones is the most worth studying. The comments of our latter-day prophets, even when wrong, clearly outline the shape of the market for the next three to six months.<p>
Greenspan was first out of the blocks. On December 5, he speculated that the stock market might be displaying signs of "irrational exuberance." A wave of selling initially rolled around the globe with the sun. The Dow Jones Industrial Average dropped nearly 145 points before a mid-morning rally cut the loss to 55 points. After thinking about it overnight, the market decided the Fed chairman's implicit threat to raise interest rates to rein in speculation was just hot air. The Dow climbed 82 points the next day.<p>
Greenspan was trying to jawbone himself some room to maneuver. The Fed can't raise interest rates to cut this market down a peg without taking the chance that higher rates will send this slow economy into a recession. Even worse, if the market stays at this level and the economy slows enough so that the Fed should lower rates to spur growth, the Fed will have to risk either doing nothing (recession) or cutting rates (hello, bubble market). For now, the Fed is a paper tiger.<p>
Let's consider Barton Biggs next. On December 16, Biggs, a managing director at Morgan Stanley, advised his clients -- and clients take seriously the advice of a man who manages $51 billion at one of the world's most powerful investment firms -- to cut their positions in stocks by almost 25 percent. The Dow, which had started the day strong, finished down 37 points. But Biggs's pessimism didn't stick. The Dow rose in the next three sessions by a total of 205 points.<p>
The reaction to Biggs's remark shows just how tightly investors in this market are wound. Everyone secretly fears that the market is overvalued and has one eye on the exit. But the indexes will once again outperform most money managers. No manager can afford to be in cash, no matter how pricey stocks are. Managing risk becomes little more than a matter of racing for the door when someone like Biggs hiccups.<p>
The last of our prophets, Robert Hormats, a vice-chairman at Goldman Sachs, let lose another market flurry when he was quoted in the December 11 Wall Street Journal speculating that the Japanese were losing their appetite for U.S. Treasurys. Mind you, there's no solid evidence that the Japanese, the mainstay of the U.S. bond market, are slowing the pace of their buying. At the moment, that's not something they can even consider.<p>
Why? First, the Bank of Japan is in the midst of re-capitalizing the loss-plagued Japanese banking system. The discount rate in Japan is now a meager 0.5 percent. Japanese banks can borrow at that rate in Japan, buy U.S. Treasurys that are paying 6 percent, and reap a low-risk 5.5 percent. This interest-rate differential pulled $8.8 billion from individual Japanese investors into U.S. Treasurys in October. That helps keep U.S. interest rates low and boost the stock market.<p>
Second, the enormous American trade deficit is one of the few friends the Japanese economy has. Same goes for the German economy. The money flows abroad as we buy German machinery and Japanese cars (and Italian shoes and Swiss watches...). That big a deficit would normally put pressure on the dollar -- foreigners are holding a lot more of them each month -- and the Fed would probably raise interest rates both to support the dollar (higher rates would entice foreign investors to hold on to dollar-denominated notes) and to cut domestic consumption by slowing the economy.<p>
But these aren't normal times. Economies around the world are in the doldrums. The Japanese and German governments need those sales to the U.S. To keep the U.S. humming, foreign central banks have been buying up dollars in their markets and then buying U.S. Treasurys. That keeps U.S. interest rates low and encourages U.S. consumers to buy more goods of all sorts -- including those made abroad.<p>
It isn't much more than a global Ponzi scheme, a crazy edifice constructed of mispriced currencies and low U.S. interest rates. It isn't sustainable indefinitely. We are consuming beyond our means, and foreign savings are subsidizing that consumption.<p>
So Hormats is wrong in the short run. Foreign money isn't going to flee the U.S. bond market any time in the next six months. Investors should not waste time worrying about that.<p>
What they should worry about is the inevitable revival of the German and Japanese economies. That's when investors in those countries will have good reasons to keep their money at home. When they do, the foreign money that propped up U.S. stock and bond prices will dry up. U.S. financial assets will go from overvalued in comparison to financial assets elsewhere in the world to fairly priced or perhaps eventually undervalued.<p>
That's the longer-range truth that all three of our prophets are preaching. Sometime in the future, investors in this country will have to learn to live with higher U.S. interest rates, a much weaker dollar, and slower growth. In the long run, U.S. financial assets are too expensive. In the long run, everything must balance. In the long run.<p>
KEYWORDS:
Street Wise, international, foreign, worldwide, economy
					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/4pages.gif"><br>About 4 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

					<p>
	
		
</td>
	</tr>
