<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Winners & Losers</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Winners & Losers</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						This summer's U.S. equity roller coaster put market gurus to the test, as this new feature shows. After reaching all-time highs in late May and early June, stocks began a slow descent that soon turned into a free fall. During just the first two weeks of July, the Dow Jones dropped more than 6 percent, and the Nasdaq composite index plummeted more than 11 percent. By August, however, both indexes had reversed course, eventually reaching new highs in October. That volatility created both big profits and big losses.<p>
WINNER: Foster Friess: <a name="FUND:BRWIX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/BRWIX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Brandywine Fund</b></a>
Friess responded to a 12 percent loss in June and July by buying technology, energy, and consumer cyclical stocks that fit his "high growth at low cost" criterion, says portfolio manager William D'Alonzo. Brandywine bounced back in August and September, gaining 15 percent.<p>
WINNER: Gary Pilgrim: <a name="FUND:PBHGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/PBHGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PBHG Growth Fund</b></a>
Pilgrim, usually fully invested, went into June with 15 percent in cash. By mid-July, he began to use that reserve to buy companies whose earnings were still on target, "especially those in technology," says colleague John Force. PBHG Growth gained almost 14 percent in August and September.<p>
WINNER: Garrett Van Wagoner: <a name="FUND:VWEGX"></a><a href="http://www.investools.com/cgi-bin/Library/t_page.pl/worth/VWEGX"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Van Wagoner Emerging Growth Fund</b></a>
By the end of May, Van Wagoner had built up a cash hoard equal to 20 percent of his portfolio. "I hadn't been able to find anything to buy," he says. In July, he used that cash to snap up his favorite technology stocks, helping his fund to rebound nearly 15 percent in August and September.<p>
LOSER: Garrett Van Wagoner: Van Wagoner Emerging Growth Fund
Van Wagoner was too quick to pull the trigger. He bought aggressively in early July as the market was still on the way down, and his fund took a beating, falling 17.5 percent for the month. "I just wish I had waited," he says. Still, on the year, his fund was up 37 percent through October 23.<p>
WINNER: Edward Yardeni: Deutsche Morgan Grenfell  
By Friday, July 19, chief economist Yardeni knew the market slump was over. "I saw it as one of these 10 percent quick and dirty corrections," he says. That day, Yardeni told clients to use the drop as a buying opportunity; he is now calling for the Dow to hit 10,000 by the year 2000.<p>
LOSER: Elaine Garzarelli: Garzarelli Capital   
Garzarelli's July 23 warning that stocks would fall 25 percent rattled markets for a day -- and then the Dow resumed its climb. The exLehman Brothers strategist stands by her call. "Sometimes [my model] is four to six months early," she says. She blames election-year euphoria for the delay.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
</center>
<pre>


</pre>
					<tt><font size=+1>
					<center>
						<img src="/imgs/2pages.gif"><br>About 2 pages

					</font>
					</tt>
					</center>

					<pre>
					</pre>


					</font>
					<p>

					<p>

<font size=+1><b>Mutual Fund Index</b><br>
</font>						<a href="#FUND:BRWIX">Brandywine Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:PBHGX">PBHG Growth Fund</a><br>

						<a href="#FUND:VWEGX">Van Wagoner Emerging Growth Fund</a><br>

