				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-What They're Recommending</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						The four top financial-newsletter writers below identify their favorite domestic stocks. The price listed with each writer's stock pick is the maximum at which he considers the recommended stock attractive. The newsletter writer may hold the stock either in a personal account or in a fund he manages, and may have changed his opinion after the October 25 publishing deadline.<p>
Al Frank
The Prudent Speculator
Looks for undervalued stocks with the potential for long-term appreciation.
<a name="NYSE:NAV"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11063"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Navistar International </b></a> (NYSE: NAV)  Up to $10.12
Navistar International (Chicago) manufactures trucks and truck engines and operates the largest truck-parts distribution network in the U.S. Navistar's 1996 earnings will pale in comparison with its 1995 earnings of $1.83 a share, but the company has remained solidly profitable during the trucking industry's current cyclical downturn. We think the slump has run its course and that cost-cutting measures will soon help the bottom line. The stock is currently trading at a 25-year low of $9.25 a share -- below book value. We believe Navistar is currently undervalued at seven times earnings and four times cash flow. Our three- to five-year target price is $20. <p>
Jim McCamant
Medical Technology Stock Letter 
Focuses primarily on small biotechnology companies.
<a name="NASD:CTII"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=15573"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>CytoTherapeutics</b></a>  (NASD: CTII)  Up to $15
CytoTherapeutics (Providence) develops implantable (and easily removed) systems that deliver therapeutic protein for the treatment of central-nervous-system disorders. The company has developed technology to implant encapsulated cells that have been genetically engineered to deliver necessary proteins across the blood-brain barrier for diseases such as Alzheimer's and Parkinson's. Clinical trials with the company's partner, Astra, have proved that the technology works. The stock is trading at around $9 a share; it should continue to respond positively to results in further trials and to additional corporate partnerships over the next year. <p>
Michael Murphy
California Technology Stock Letter
Looks for high-growth high-tech companies.
<a name="NASD:ROSS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11793"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Ross Systems</b></a>  (NASD: ROSS)  Up to $9
Ross Systems (Atlanta) distributes and manufactures client/server software and applications, focusing on the process-manufacturing, nonprofit, and health-care sectors. Ross took some losses during its shift from a proprietary operating system to open UNIX systems, but the company has been profitable every quarter in 1996. We expect it to earn 47 cents a share in the fiscal year ending next June. Ross is adding to its product line, and its systems will soon be able to operate on Windows NT. While most client/server software companies sell for two to five times sales per share, Ross's stock price is right at sales per share. My 12-month target price is $18. <p>
Louis Navellier
MPT Review
Uses modern portfolio theory to identify high-return, low-volatility stocks.
<a name="NYSE:COA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10356"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coachmen Industries</b></a>  (NYSE: COA)  Up to $35
Coachmen Industries (Elkhart, Indiana) manufactures and distributes recreational vehicles under a variety of brand names, including Travelmaster, Viking, and Saratoga. The company also builds modular homes, which accounted for 16 percent of sales in 1995. Revenue was up 18 percent for the third quarter of 1996 compared with the third quarter of 1995. Coachmen is a growth stock with a low price-to-earnings ratio; it's currently trading at just 13 times forecasted earnings. With manufacturing plants operating in seven states and the demand for recreational vehicles and modular housing continuing to grow, Coachmen looks very attractive.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
