<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Naughty or Nice</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6001.html?worth+PCFN18.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN18.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Naughty or Nice</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By Jim Jubak<p>
Want to know if the economy's headed for a slowdown that could send the market tumbling? Look around your local <a name="NYSE:WMT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11600"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Wal-Mart</b></a> or <a name="NYSE:GPS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11469"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Gap</b></a> this Christmas. Crowded stores? The feared slowdown isn't imminent. Big markdowns and desultory buying? Trouble sooner rather than later.<p>
The holiday-shopping season -- the period from November 15 to December 25 -- is always critical for U.S. retailers. Those few weeks account for about 25 percent of their annual sales. But in 1996, this end-of-the-year shopping frenzy is even more important than usual: Weak holiday sales will show that the consumer is too tapped out to keep the economy humming.<p>
The consumer certainly looks over-extended. Total payments on mortgages, credit cards, and auto leases climbed to 14.6 percent of disposable personal income in the third quarter of 1996, according to Economic Analysis Associates in Greenwich, Connecticut. A larger percentage of income is now going toward those monthly debt payments than at any time during the long market rally that began in Ronald Reagan's first term. Not surprisingly, retail sales in the third quarter of 1996 were basically flat compared with sales in the previous quarter.<p>
What would a bad Christmas mean for investors? In the short term, lousy fourth-quarter sales would kill corporate earnings in the first quarter of 1997. Retailers and their suppliers build up inventory to meet anticipated holiday demand. If that demand doesn't materialize, they are forced to cut prices to move aging stock, which hurts profits, and they don't make new buys until that old merchandise is off their shelves, which hurts sales. A slow Christmas would also generate downward pressure on prices. No one will ask consumers to pay more when unsold goods clog the sales channel.<p>
Not all companies are equally vulnerable to a Christmas slowdown. In the retail sector -- which is still contracting after a wave of overbuilding left the U.S. with too many stores -- watch out for companies that have been losing market share to competitors in relatively good times. In the home-improvement category, for example, <a name="NASD:HECHA"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13666"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hechinger</b></a> seems especially vulnerable; it has been steadily losing business to <a name="NYSE:LOW"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10920"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Lowe's Companies</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:HD"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11470"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Home Depot</b></a>.<p>
Technology companies are also facing big Christmas worries. Last year, <a name="NASD:MSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14120"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Microsoft</b></a>'s Windows 95 generated new sales across the computer industry as consumers bought faster and more powerful machines to take advantage of the heavily promoted new software. This year, in contrast, there's hardly a ripple of excitement to send even committed technophiles to the stores. Earlier this year, even well-run companies, such as <a name="NYSE:CPQ"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10381"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Compaq Computer</b></a> and <a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a>, had trouble managing their inventories to avoid stocking too much of the wrong product. With profit margins lower now, similar mistakes this Christmas could be painfully expensive for companies and investors.<p>
In the longer run, poor end-of-the-year sales could speed up an ongoing shift in market psychology. For most of the year, investors have essentially ignored slowing economic growth or seen it as a positive force -- since slow growth would prevent the Federal Reserve from raising interest rates. But in the third quarter of 1996, investors started to worry about how companies could keep delivering accelerating earnings growth while the economy slowed. In the reporting season that followed the September 30 close of the quarter, the market punished the stocks of companies that delivered predicted earnings but failed to increase sales.<p>
Take <a name="NASD:COKE"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=13014"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Coca-Cola</b></a>, for example. On October 15, the company reported earnings of 39 cents a share, up 22 percent from earnings in the third quarter of 1995. But still the stock dipped. Analysts pointed to troubling "top line" numbers in Coke's results. Worldwide sales volume grew just 6 percent, and operating revenue fell by 5 percent. If not for a $396 million drop in income-tax payments, earnings would have actually declined in 1996.<p>
Coke is not alone in facing the results of slowing sales. For example, shares of <a name="NYSE:EDS"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41915"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Electronic Data Systems</b></a> dropped more than $15, about 25 percent, when management noted that the number of new business contracts written in the fourth quarter looked "somewhat lower." The extreme reaction to the EDS announcement says something important about this market. Investors are worried that the long period in which cost cutting and downsizing produced increased profit margins may be over.<p>
They have good reason to worry. Currently, the return on equity (a measure of profitability that looks at how much a company earns on each dollar invested in it) of the companies in the Standard & Poor's 500 Stock Index is well above 20 percent. The average since 1947 falls between 10 and 15 percent. If profit margins fail to grow and sales stagnate, companies won't be able to deliver the earnings growth investors now demand. Even worse, return on equity could actually fall while sales are sinking. Earnings would dive.<p>
Impossible? It's already happening to some companies that operate in slow-growing and exceedingly competitive parts of the economy. On October 25, <a name="NYSE:K"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10841"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Kellogg</b></a> reported that sales fell 8.8 percent as both sales volume and prices in the U.S. declined. The company's earnings dropped 31 percent for the quarter compared with the third quarter of 1995.<p>
After years of focusing on the bottom line -- earnings -- investors must now pay attention to the top of the income statement, too. In 1997, think sales.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
