<html>
	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Keeping Up</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Keeping Up</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						By John Fried<p>
The Treasury Department's new "inflation indexed" bonds will be available in January. The notes, valued at a minimum of $1,000, will be targeted primarily at conservative investors -- they'll carry a lower interest rate than traditional ten-year Treasurys, but the principal value of the notes will be adjusted to the consumer price index. One advantage of the new instruments: They should offer better returns than cash instruments (such as money-market funds) without leaving bondholders vulnerable to inflation. The basic disadvantage: Any increase in principal will be taxed the year it is credited, even though the investor might not get the cash for years. Critics point to certain scenarios -- involving a low coupon rate combined with high inflation -- in which investors in the highest tax brackets could actually pay more in taxes on the principal than they earn in interest. <p>
News from the supermarket: Two more brokerages -- Quick & Reilly and Prudential Investments -- have unveiled plans to launch mutual-fund supermarkets, programs that offer customers an array of no-load mutual funds from different money managers. Merrill Lynch has initiated a rewards program to encourage investors to keep all their money with Merrill. For example, an investor who keeps $100,000 in eligible investments pays an annual fee of 1.5 percent of assets to cover all commissions on a dozen securities transactions, a 0.25 percent break on margin interest, and financial-planning advice. At higher asset levels, the benefits increase and the fee decreases. Finally, The Wall Street Journal reports that Charles Schwab plans to expand its mutual-fund business into banks and smaller brokerage firms. <p>
A KPMG Peat Marwick survey of 1,151 major employers has found that more workers are now enrolled in HMOs than in traditional health-care plans. The survey also reports that health-coverage premiums rose by a scant 0.5 percent from spring 1995 to spring 1996.<p>
Americans gave 16 percent more to charity in 1995 than they did in 1993, a survey conducted by the Gallup Organization shows. According to the survey, sponsored by the Independent Sector, an organization dedicated to the promotion of philanthropy, the average American household gave 2.2 percent of its income in 1995, up from 2.1 percent in 1993.<p>
The Securities and Exchange Commission has moved to curb abuses of Regulation S offerings of stocks and bonds. Under Regulation S, American companies sell securities to foreign buyers for less than they are worth on the American market. Foreign buyers have found it easy to violate the terms of the regulation by selling the securities back into the U.S. market before it is legal to do so. The new SEC rules require issuers to make more frequent and more timely disclosures of Regulation S sales.<p>
President Clinton has signed the National Securities Markets Improvement Act of 1996, which, in his words, will eliminate "regulatory overlap between the states and the federal government." While the act will primarily affect financial institutions, individual investors will see a difference as well. The act, Clinton said at a signing ceremony, "strengthens the SEC's hand in addressing fund names that use words such as government,' guaranteed,' or insured,' which can cause investors to conclude, incorrectly, that their investments are guaranteed by state or federal authorities."<p>
Corporations are providing employ ees more investment options in their 401(k) plans, according to a survey by the Profit Sharing/401(k) Council of America. The survey found that 74 percent of the 668 companies queried offered at least five investment options in 1995, up from only 16 percent in 1990.<p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

<center>
		
	<a href="/index.html">
	<IMG SRC="/imgs/datalineyellow.gif" border=0 alt="Worth"></a><p>
