	<head>
		<title> Worth OnLine - 97/01-Global Markets</title>
	</head>
	
	<body background="/imgs/goldbarsmooth.gif" bgcolor="#FFFFFF"
	      text="#000000" link="#FF0000" vlink="#BB0000"> 	
	<a name="#top">
	<table width=550 cellpadding=10 cellspacing=5>
	
	<tr>
		<td width=390 valign=top> 
		
		<a href=/cgi/ad-relay.cgi?http://www.pcfn.com/6015.html?worth+PCFN16.gif+Front%20Page>
<img src="/ads/PCFN16.gif" border=3 width=372 height=45 alt="PC Financial Network"></a>


		</td>
		<td  width=150>
		<!-- empty cell -->
		</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
	<td width=390 valign=top>
		
		<center>
		<p>
		<b><a href="/index.html">Home</a>  |  <a href="/departments/departments.html">Departments</a>  |  <a href="/search/query.html">Search</a>  |  <a href="/forums/index.html">Message Boards</a></b>
		<pre>
		</pre>
				<font size=5><b></b></font><br>
				<font size=6><b>97/01-Global Markets</b></font><br>
				<font size=4></font><p>
				</center>
				
				<blockquote>
					<center>
						<font size=4><b><i></i></b></font><p>
					</center>
					<font size=4>
						What's Up Down Under?<p>
By Todd G. Buccholz<p>
To place a bet on world economic growth, look down under. So many Australian stocks are wrapped up in commodities -- the building blocks of industrialized countries -- that as world prices of copper, minerals, wool, and natural gas go, so goes Australia's All Ordinaries Index. For example, demand for copper, which accounts for more than 5 percent of Australia's exports, tracks the global economy so well that it's called "the commodity with a Ph.D. in economics." In its heavy dependence on commodities, Australia is economically more like faraway Canada than like its Asian neighbors. Even the Australian and Canadian dollars tend to move in sync.<p>
The Australian economy has looked impressive in the past few years, with the gross domestic product averaging about 4 percent growth. True, the unemployment rate is problematic at 8.5 percent, but it's down from 9.7 percent in 1994. On the budget front, Liberal Party prime minister John Howard is prescribing the kind of tough medicine that has cheered the bond market and brought Australian interest rates much closer to U.S. rates. The spread between ten-year U.S. Treasury bonds and ten-year Australian government bonds has shrunk from about 250 basis points in January 1996 to 90 this past October. This means cheaper financing and more investment opportunities for Australian firms. And Howard's budget calls for reducing Australia's deficit-to-GDP ratio from 3.6 percent in 1994 to a small surplus in 1998.<p>
Before trading your suburban ranch for one in the outback and swapping Fido for a dingo, however, consider the potential pitfalls. Most importantly, Australia seems to be moving from strong and steady growth to the more sluggish pace that in recent years has spread over the world like a communicable disease. We used to call it "Eurosclerosis" until the Japanese caught it. Now even Asian Tigers like Thailand are suffering from slower growth and disappointing corporate performances. (The Thai stock market has plunged nearly 28 percent this year.) Australia has a limited number of weapons to battle such a slowdown. Since the government has already launched an ambitious and laudably tight fiscal policy, Australia won't be "priming the pump," or stimulating consumption through government spending. In fact, the government will be acting like a drag on the economy.<p>
So the Aussies may come to depend on either a sudden spurt in world economic growth, with the consequent rise in commodity prices, or lower interest rates. The Reserve Bank of Australia cut short-term interest rates by 50 basis points last July and will likely cut them again if the economy continues to soften. The RBA has an advantage over the Eurosclerotic central banks that have confronted slowdowns: It's free to slash rates without fear of a currency plunge. This is because the government is on the road to a balanced budget, making Australia less dependent on foreign investors, and because there is no effort to peg the nation's currency directly to that of another country -- as France, for example, is trying to nail the franc to the deutsche mark. Thus, if the RBA cuts rates and the Aussie dollar slides a bit, the RBA needn't sweat. Indeed, as you might expect in a land where trade with other countries usually makes the difference between prosperity and hard times, the RBA may even cheer if the cheaper currency gives Australian exports a kangaroo bounce.<p>
Contributing editor Todd G. Buchholz is a managing director of a New Yorkbased international investment fund and the author of From Here to Economy: A Shortcut to Economic Literacy.<p>
KEYWORDS: world, international, global, worldwide

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
</td><td width=150 valign=top>

