* Sells at 30 times earnings<br>
* Bankrupt competitor is discounting competing goods <br>
<a name="NASD:PSFT"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=14838"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PeopleSoft</b></a> (Nasdaq: PSFT) $40<br>
* Sells at 68 times 1997 earnings<br>
* Insider selling<br>
* High level of receivables<br>
<a name="NASD:PETM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=16273"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>PETsMART</b></a> (Nasdaq: PETM) $20<br>
* Sells at 45 times 1997 earnings<br>
* Inventory turnover slowing for past four quarters<br>
<a name="NASD:WMAR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=41993"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>West Marine</b></a> (Nasdaq: WMAR) $25<br>
* Sells at 35 times 1997 earnings<br>
* Insider selling<br>
* Inventory turnover slowing<br>
<br><p>
10 TO CONSIDER
David King is a value investor at heart. He and Anthony Kreisel, who co-manage Putnam Investments' $20 billion Fund for Growth & Income, scour their universe of 500 or so large U.S. companies with above-average yields or low price-to-book and price-to-sales ratios in search of undiscovered values. Since they took over the fund in 1993, its 16.1 percent annualized return has trounced the average growth-and-income fund by more than two percentage points. How do they know when they've spotted a winner? Says King, "We're looking for cheapness and change -- inexpensive out-of-favor companies that have had some change in leadership, incentives, or structure that alters their business." Kmart has been one of their favorites since new CEO Floyd Hall shored up the company's balance sheet and improved its merchandising. King says new management at USF&G and Pharmacia & Upjohn should help those companies turn around as well. Change, however, doesn't need to be so dramatic. King expects Hewlett-Packard to see accelerating growth as more of its revenue comes from disposable goods, such as printer cartridges. And wholesale bank J. P. Morgan is well on its way to becoming a premier financial franchise.<p>
Company (EXCHANGE: TICKER) Fair Value (Anything under this price is a bargain.<br>
* Reasons<br>
<br>
<a name="NYSE:FCX"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10606"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Freeport-McMoRan Copper</b></a> (NYSE: FCX) $40<br>
* High-grade gold reserves <br>
* Expanding production<br>
* Excellent management team<br>
<a name="NYSE:GM"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10640"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>General Motors </b></a>(NYSE: GM) $60<br>
* Potentially attractive labor deal<br>
* Valuable Hughes subsidiary<br>
* Improved financial condition<br>
<a name="NYSE:HWP"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=10723"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Hewlett-Packard</b></a> (NYSE: HWP) $48 <br>
