* Trading at discount to peers<br>
* Improved financial controls<br>
* Emphasis on fee income<br>
<a name="NYSE:FG"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11528"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>USF&G</b></a> (NYSE: FG) $20<br>
* 25 percent earnings growth<br>
* Balance sheet back in order<br>
* Boosted share repurchase<br>
<a name="NYSE:WHR"></a><a href="http://www.hoovers.com/cgi-bin/brand_worth_mlist.cgi?mode=full&index_code=11632"><img src="/imgs/graph.gif" border=0><b>Whirlpool</b></a> (NYSE: WHR) $65<br>
* Winner in global consolidation<br>
* Above-average yield<br>
* Cyclic buying opportunity<br><p>
UPDATE
The December/January 1996 "10 Stocks to Consider" picks by Elizabeth R. Bramwell, president of New Yorkbased Bramwell Capital Management, gained 30 percent in the 12 months ended October 21. Cutter & Buck, Bramwell's biggest winner, jumped 84 percent. The "10 Stocks to Avoid" selected by Jim Floyd, senior analyst at the Leuthold Group in Minneapolis, underperformed the market, gaining a meager 5.3 percent in the period. RJR Nabisco dropped the most of the ten, falling 16 percent. <p>

					</font>
					<p>
		
		
		
